<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA DIAMONDBACK JAY BELL'S HOMER BRINGS $1 MILLION TO LUCKY
WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By AL TOBY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Gylene Hoyle's eyes were closed when she made her $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Diamondbacks second baseman Jay Bell had nearly fouled
out on pop-ups on two previous pitches. And Hoyle, who saw her
chance slipping away, couldn't bear to watch.
</P>
<P>
   But on the next pitch came Bell's game-winning grand slam in the
bottom of the sixth inning against Oakland pitcher Jimmy Haynes.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyle, a 31-year old Chandler, Ariz., resident, had won $1
million in a grand-slam promotion sponsored by Shamrock Farms.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that ball went sailing I was just in a state of shock,''
Hoyle said of the home run into the left-field seats. ``I didn't
even actually see the ball go over the fence because I had my eyes
closed at that point. I only knew that he actually hit the run when
everybody around me started yelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoyle's post-home-run reaction of jumping up and down and
hugging her husband was shown on the stadium's big screen, which
added to the crowd's jubilation.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Hoyle had picked the correct inning and
grand-slam hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, who knew he was the designated hitter,
</P>
<P>
   said he had every intention of hitting a homer for Hoyle and
halting his hitless streak in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ended the series 1-for-14,'' Bell said. ``That one hit was
pretty special. I'm very, very pleased and happy for them.''
</P>
<P>
   What was bigger for Bell, winning a woman $1 million or winning
the game?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not even a good question,'' Bell answered. ``Winning
her $1 million was certainly (more) gratifying.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoyle automatically got the opportunity to participate in the
grand-slam contest when she won tickets to Sunday's game from the
``Tim and Willie Show'' on KNIX-FM (102.5).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just happy to get in the gate because we've never been
here before,'' Hoyle said.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario couldn't have been more gut-wrenching for Hoyle.
After the count was 3-1, Bell fouled off two pitches. The foul ball
before the home run just cleared the backstop's net.
</P>
<P>
   Until today, Hoyle said she wasn't a big fan of baseball.
Hoyle's family coached her on which player to pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest of my family are big Diamondbacks fans and they all
said Jay Bell was the best hitter,'' she said. ``He had the most
home runs at that point, so we picked Jay Bell because we figured
he could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Matt Williams said he could tell that Bell was
swinging for the fences after he swatted at three pitches that
would've been ball four.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyle, a child care provider, is married and has an 8-year old
daughter, Colleen, and a 7-year-old son, Clayton Jr. Her husband,
Clayton, works as a drill rig operator.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things that Clayton Hoyle said came to mind
after his wife won was the status of a 1986 truck he was thinking
of putting on the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not real interested in selling it now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shamrock Farms' director of marketing, Ann Puelz-Ocana, said she
didn't expect someone to win after less than two seasons of the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really didn't have any idea of how big the odds were in
winning,'' Puelz-Ocana said. ``We thought that it would take
longer. Either way, we're very excited for the winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Puelz-Ocana said Shamrock Farms had taken out an insurance
policy that would pay off the winnings.
</P>
<P>
   Other than taking a long-deserved vacation, Hoyle said she
doesn't know what she's going to do with the money. ``My stomach is
dry,'' she said. ``I'm all nervous and shaky. I haven't quite
comprehended all of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoyle's daughter picked her own vacation spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll probably be going to Disneyland,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 0024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
