<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6375 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ASTROS-ROYALS-HNS     07-12 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ASTROS-ROYALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Over the past two weeks, the Astros' bullpen has
resembled a collection of drowning men trying to stay afloat on
rough and choppy waters.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quite frankly, life rafts have been in short supply lately.
</P>
<P>
   But a rare rescue mission was launched Sunday when the Astros
scored five eighth-inning runs, providing a safe late-inning
cushion in a 7-3 victory over the Kansas City Royals at Kauffman
Stadium and securing a sweep of the three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Lima pitched 7 strong innings for his 13th win, and
reliever Jay Powell finished off the Royals with 1 perfect innings
to notch his second save in the Astros' final game before the
All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owed the bullpen this one,'' said Astros center fielder
Carl Everett, who had a two-run pinch double in the eighth.
``They've been pitching a lot lately, and these last few games have
been tough on them. I know they're tired. It was nice to remind
ourselves that we're capable of scoring some runs and giving those
guys some breathing room.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima (13-4) absolutely suffocated the Royals for most of the
day, holding the American League's fifth-ranked offense to five
hits through the first seven innings. The only Royals batter who
reached scoring position before the seventh _ first baseman Jeremy
Giambi _ advanced to second on an error after an infield single in
the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jose pitched a great game,'' Astros interim manager Matt
Galante said. ``He's been getting it done all season, so now we get
to hear his music, which is good, because that means we won.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros improved to 14-5 in games started by Lima, who along
with pitchers Mike Hampton and Billy Wagner and first baseman Jeff
Bagwell will represent the team in All-Star festivities in Boston
over the next three days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't complain about my first half,'' said Lima, who is
29-12 with a 3.53 ERA since the beginning of last season. ``I
thought maybe I'd win 10 games by the All-Star break but not 13.
That shows that Jose Lima is for real. My goal was to win 20 games
this year, and I've already got 13. Be careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, it seems the Astros have to be careful simply making
their way from the team bus to the clubhouse without suffering an
injury. Seven players missed time because of injuries on the
10-game road trip, including three who were placed on the disabled
list. Two others _ third baseman Bill Spiers and outfielder Matt
Mieske _ played Sunday despite sore hamstrings.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat amazingly, the Astros managed to win six of the 10
games on the trip, including the sweep of the Royals. The Astros
have swept four three-game series in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going 6-4 on this trip with a MASH unit is pretty good,''
Galante said. ``We knew these games were going to be a struggle
because of the injuries, but we battled through everything pretty
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's victory left the Astros in a virtual tie for first
place in the National League Central. Cincinnati will be percentage
points ahead of them when they open the second half Thursday night
at the Astrodome against the Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Royals starter Jeff Suppan (4-5) appeared to be on top of his
game in the early innings, retiring the first nine batters he
faced. But Craig Biggio led off the fourth inning with his
major-league-leading 38th double and scored on Bagwell's single up
the middle. Spiers also had an RBI single in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals didn't generate any scoring until the seventh inning,
when Jermaine Dye's seeing-eye double dropped between Bagwell and
right fielder Derek Bell, pushing Kansas City's first run across
the plate to make it a 2-1 game.
</P>
<P>
   After playing three consecutive one-run games, the last thing
the Astros needed was another squeaker. They took care of that with
a five-run eighth-inning outburst, highlighted by Everett's double
off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who was out of the starting lineup for the third
consecutive game because of a strained left hamstring, upped his
RBI total to 65 _ second on the team behind Bagwell's 78. Everett
drove in 76 runs in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pinch hitting is the toughest job in baseball, but I've been
playing regularly, so I'm already in the flow,'' said Everett, who
was 2-for-2 with four RBIs off the bench in the three-game series.
``I've said it before: I take pride in being up with runners in
scoring position.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros sent nine batters to the plate in the top of the
eighth, and the long half-inning took a toll on Lima, whom Galante
described as ``stale'' when he returned to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   An RBI double by rookie outfielder Carlos Beltran and a
run-scoring single by Johnny Damon pulled the Royals within four
runs, and after Lima allowed another base hit, Galante called on
Powell with runners on first and third and two out.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, who had allowed a pair of runs in each of his previous
two outings, struck out Dye to end the eighth and retired the side
in order in the ninth to secure the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to be as aggressive as I could,'' said Powell,
who has appeared in seven of the Astros' last 11 games. ``I knew I
didn't have anything (Friday night, when he allowed two runs in
one-third of an inning), but this time I was going to make them hit
the ball. I felt a lot better today.''
</P>
<P>
   And the battered Astros no doubt will feel a lot better after
the three-day All-Star break.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
