A6380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-FARMER-LEGACY-1S     07-12 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FARMER-LEGACY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WHAT JAMES FARMER LEAVES BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs last graf to change wording to read: x x x fairness, and
economic opportunity, etc. (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, July 12:
</P>
<P>
   James Farmer, the former head of the Congress of Racial
Equality, who died on Friday at 79, was the last of the major civil
rights leaders of his generation, and one of the first to begin the
struggle. Moved by what he had learned in college of Gandhi's use
of nonviolent disobedience, Farmer founded CORE as a local group in
Chicago in the early 1940s, and it was there that he first used
Gandhian tactics to integrate the White City Roller Skating Rink.
</P>
<P>
   It worked in Chicago, and chapters sprang up east and west, in
New York, Philadelphia, Los Angeles and Seattle. But it was
unthinkable to try to take the effort into the deep South in the
1940s.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until the late 1950s and early '60s that black and
white civil rights activists began to defy the laws and customs of
segregation in places like Alabama and Mississippi. To endure the
consequent broken skulls and jaws and legs, to suffer shootings,
burnings, bombings and lynchings, all without violent resistance,
so that the nation could learn from the example of what was done,
required a depth of courage and dignity and faith that has never
been surpassed in the history of this nation.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer was one of the principal leaders of that time. He
directed the daring Freedom Rides that began integrating interstate
bus service in the South in 1961. ``My father was a Freedom Rider,
I'm a Freedom Rider's son,'' he would sing out in jail. ``He was
one of the founding fathers not just of the New South, but of the
New America,'' said Rep. John Lewis, who was beaten unconscious and
jailed with Farmer on one of the bus rides.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer and CORE also formed an important bridge between the more
traditional, legalistic organizations, like A. Philip Randolph's
Brotherhood of Sleeping Car Porters, Roy Wilkins' National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People and Whitney
Young's Urban League, and the newer groups that grew in street
power as the 1960s progressed. Among these were the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
and the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee led by Lewis,
Julian Bond, James Foreman and others.
</P>
<P>
   Together, James Farmer and the others led the effort to overcome
a system of legal oppression that had endured, in one form or
another, from the beginning of the nation. That is achievement
enough for their generation. The effort to win greater fairness,
and economic opportunity, remains for ours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
