A6381 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DROP-SOUTH-POLE-SPI &LR;      07-12 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DROP-SOUTH-POLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCHORD AIRCREW ANSWERS CALL FOR EMERGENCY MISSION TO ANTARCTICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mission accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   An exhausted but jubilant C-141B Starlifter aircrew from McChord
Air Force Base near Tacoma reported success early Sunday after an
emergency mission to airdrop medical supplies at the South Pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went fantastically,'' said mission commander Lt. Col. John
Pray in a telephone interview from Christchurch, New Zealand,
shortly after his crew completed the 15-hour round trip to
Antarctica. Six containers of medical supplies were dropped during
a seven-minute pass over Amundsen-Scott South Pole Station
beginning at 10:35 p.m. PST Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The airdrop was ordered last week after the National Science
Foundation urgently requested medical screening equipment and
medicine to treat a 47-year-old American woman after a lump was
found in her breast.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, whose name was not disclosed, works as support staff
at the station. She had recently undergone a biopsy and a battery
of tests with the base physician and the results were shipped via
the Internet to doctors in the United States. The treatment they
directed was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its isolated location 800 miles inland from the main
U.S. research station at McMurdo Sound, and because of the extreme
weather conditions during the dark Antarctic winter, it was
impossible to land a plane at the polar camp, officials said. There
are 41 people wintering at the station until the Antarctic spring
arrives in late October.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other way of getting in there, so an airdrop (of
supplies) is the only option,'' Pray said last week.
</P>
<P>
   The cargo, wrapped in shock-absorbing foam and other materials,
included diagnostic equipment, medicines, fresh food and mail. The
six heavy cardboard crates were rigged with parachutes and marked
with strobes and chemical lights to mark their location, said Tech.
Sgt. Robert Brown, McChord cargo loadmaster on the mission.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the research camp radioed the McChord aircraft
that one of the bundles had broken open on impact and two others
sustained minor damage, but the contents were intact, Pray said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the word that everything survived, made it A-OK,''
Brown said. ``That makes us real happy _ especially the
loadmasters, since we packed the cargo ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The C-141B normally flies with a crew of six _ a pilot,
co-pilot, flight engineer and two cargo loadmasters. But the
extended mission over the Antarctic ice cap required three
additional pilots, two navigators, two flight engineers, six cargo
loadmasters, a parachute rigger and a flight surgeon, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The McChord transport plane was escorted to the South Pole by an
Air Force KC-10 Extender refueling tanker, which transferred 78,000
pounds of fuel to the C-141B in a single mid-air maneuver, said
Capt. Martin Oliver, a backup navigator from McChord who worked
with the Christchurch team.
</P>
<P>
   Pray said when the C-141B approached within 25 miles of the
pole, the lights illuminated parachute drop zone were easily
spotted, despite clouds that partially obscured the view.
</P>
<P>
   The air temperature outside the aircraft stood at 80 degrees
below zero, requiring the plane's crew to don arctic weather gear
as the aircraft neared the cargo drop zone, Pray said.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem on the flight occurred as the cargo loadmasters
readied the first two bundles for dropping, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, one of the loadmasters, said when Pray ordered the doors
in the rear of the aircraft opened about nine minutes from the drop
zone, the wind nearly sucked out one bundle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost got away from us,'' Brown said. ``It went about a
quarter of the way out the door.'' Brown and two other loadmasters
_ Staff Sgt. Geraldo Moore and Tech. Sgt. Mike Miller _ were able
to wrestle the bundle back inside. They then successfully threw out
the first two loads as the aircraft flew 700 feet above the ground,
and 10,000 feet above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft then made a second pass over the zone seven minutes
later and dropped four more bundles.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't much easier on the ground, where staff at the research
base had just seven minutes to collect the six bundles before the
minus-67 degree cold damaged or destroyed the drugs and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Pray said he and his crew were thrilled to receive the radio
transmission from the polar station that the parachute drop was
successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were really quite happy and said we looked beautiful,''
Pray said.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft and crew are scheduled to return to McChord on
Wednesday, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   This report includes information from The Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
