<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6382 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-MONARCHS-COMETS-H     07-12 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MONARCHS-COMETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The All-Star break in the WNBA is dawning with the Comets,
champions in each of the league's first two years, again holding
the upper hand on the competition.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the Sacramento Monarchs on Sunday night proved again they
are inching closer with every game. Down by 23 points in the first
half after the Comets' Cynthia Cooper scored 17 of her 31 points in
the first 17 minutes, the Monarchs (10-5) used the 3-point shooting
of Ruthie Bolton-Holifield to get back within two, ultimately
losing 68-63 before a crowd of 12,255 at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Comets enter the All-Star break 13-2, easily
the best in the WNBA. They're three games ahead of the Monarchs in
the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we blew some leads,'' Comets coach Van Chancellor said.
``But we did hold on to win. And that's the mark of a good team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sacramento's got a really good team. They've done a good job
with their team.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night in Sacramento, the Monarchs clamped down on
Cooper and Sheryl Swoopes and logged a 74-63 victory.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday night there was no containing Cooper, who said
afterward she had as much to prove as far as pride as did the
Comets, who were in search of revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find myself in the awkward position (that) I still have to
prove myself, and it's great because it's motivating,'' she said.
``I think as a team we came out tonight and established ourselves
early, especially on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got out there and held them to very few points and made
them work for every single play, every single basket they got. I
think we had a little letdown, but that's sometimes normal. We beat
a good team tonight and got it done, especially on defense and on
the rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebounding, literally and figuratively, was something the Comets
had to do constantly Sunday in spite of a 17-0 run over a stretch
of 5:10 in the opening half that carried them to a 38-15 lead.
Sacramento, meanwhile, was having little success on either end of
the court.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Thompson had Yolanda Griffith, the Monarchs' leading
scorer, under control. Near the end of the half, Griffith had more
fouls (two) than points (one) and finished with 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Monarchs were shooting only 25 percent (6-for-24). But
Bolton-Holifield hadn't begun to heat up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like they caught us off-guard,'' Griffith said.
``They were aggressive, and we weren't.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in the second half, we calmed down and started playing
Sacramento basketball and got back into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolton-Holifield took charge in the second half like the
Bolton-Holifield who had been so prolific before suffering a severe
knee injury that knocked her out of most of the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we had the big lead, they (the Comets) were really
patient in running our offense and moving the ball,'' Chancellor
said. ``We lost our patience after we got up 23, didn't move the
basketball. And they fell victim to Bolton-Holifield.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ruthie hit some big shots,'' Griffith said. ``But the first
half, we couldn't buy a basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be a team effort. One person's not going to do it.
It has to be a team effort to beat the Houston Comets. We didn't
get a whole team effort tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahead 40-25 at intermission, the Comets had begun to feel the
wrath of Griffith and Bolton-Holifield from the end of the first
half into the middle of the second. A 10-2 Monarchs run shaved the
margin at the break.
</P>
<P>
   The run grew to 19-4 over the first two minutes of the second
half as Bolton-Holifield drained her fourth 3-pointer during the
run.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets still held a comfortable 55-37 lead at the 15:02 mark
before the Monarchs outscored the WNBA defending champions 14-2. A
Cooper basket just as the 30-second clock sounded gave the Comets a
bit of breathing room at 59-51.
</P>
<P>
   A little later, Bolton-Holifield, who led the Monarchs with 20
points, stole a Cooper pass and hit reserve Tangela Smith streaking
upcourt. Smith completed the break with a layup that cut the
Comets' lead to 61-59.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper by that time had moved over to shut off the offense of
Bolton-Holifield. And after Griffith made one of two free throws,
putting Sacramento within 67-63, Polina Tzekova blocked a shot by
Monarchs guard Kedra Holland-Corn.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento then missed its final three field-goal attempts, and
the Comets had secured a rather shaky victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another one,'' said Thompson (14 points, nine rebounds).
``At this point in time, I don't know how much they mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try to win as many as we can and get to the
postseason. A lot of these games really don't have faces. It's the
fact that we need to win them. That's what we try to go out and
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Sunday, the Comets had to fend off a Monarchs team that
changed from pussycat to tiger to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw this game as a game of runs, and they had a big one,''
Thompson said. ``Sacramento is a good team. I don't think anyone
thought they weren't going to try and get back into this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was the effort they had. But we stood strong. We held
them off to win in the end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 0048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
