<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6391 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-12 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAWL OVERSHADOWS MARINER LOSS AS GIPSON, HUNTER HURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Frankie Rodriguez pitch was high and inside, a
meaningless offering in a lopsided game. It touched nothing but
nerves.
</P>
<P>
   But on a hot day at Dodger Stadium, the wayward baseball gave
grown men every reason to turn into hot-tempered sandlot kids, the
Mariners and Dodgers letting go of all pent-up frustrations and
joining in a riotous, 15-minute altercation.
</P>
<P>
   The fracas Sunday interrupted an inevitable 14-3 Los Angeles
rout and series sweep, with four Mariners and three Dodgers _ the
group including a player on the disabled list and a coach _ getting
ejected after the last punch was thrown.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the kind of game where we've got two teams
frustrated, with the way they were playing and the way we've been
playing all year, and it just got out of hand,'' said Dodgers
third-base coach Rick Demsey, one of those waved off the field by
the umpires. ``Way out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The repercussions could be disastrous for the Mariners, both in
suspensions and injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Tossed from the Seattle side were closer Jose Mesa, setup man
Jose Paniagua, reliever Damaso Marte and outfielder Jay Buhner.
That's half the bullpen and a key player close to coming off the
disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Those were prisoners of war. There were casualties, too.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners utilityman Charles Gipson was taken to a local hospital
with a separated right shoulder after having several players roll
on him as he tried to be peace-maker. He was in such pain, team
officials had to dress him in the clubhouse. His season likely is
over.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Brian Hunter hyperextended his left knee in the
same pileup and could barely walk. He was unsure when he might play
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something you don't want to glorify,'' Mariners
outfielder Butch Huskey said, watching his injured teammates move
through the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Lou Piniella declined to speak with reporters after the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, getting Ken Griffey Jr.'s 29th homer and little
else, lost their fifth straight game and fell to 42-45 at the
break.
</P>
<P>
   For the Dodgers, catcher Todd Hundley and reliever Pedro Borbon
were ejected with Dempsey. Catcher Angel Pena received a forearm
injury, while infielder Dave Hansen hurt a finger.
</P>
<P>
   To hear some of them tell it, the melee was worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This brings us closer together,'' Hundley said. ``We're not
going to put up with that kind of cheap, pathetic play. ... If
you're going to start that stuff, unfortunate consequences are
going to be paid. You're going to end up sacrificing stuff on your
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson had this to say: ``You don't ever
like to see this happen, but it's part of the game. It's part of
sport. Anyone who thought this team didn't have spirit and heart,
we dispelled that today.''
</P>
<P>
   Anger spilled in the bottom of the sixth inning, with the
Dodgers leading 12-3, three runs in, two runners on and one out.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez sailed a pitch close to Mark Grudzielanek's chin. Both
players started arguing and gesturing. The benches cleared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't start anything,'' the Mariners reliever said. ``It
was straight over the middle of the plate. I was trying to get it
outside. Other people had other issues and went at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez and Grudzielanek never got close to each other. But as
clusters of players started shoving each other near second base, a
punch was thrown, believed to be by the Mariners' Paniagua. That
set everyone off.
</P>
<P>
   Marte, a Mariners rookie, was spotted landing a punch on Hundley
alongside the third-base line, then receiving one near the
first-base line from Dempsey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marte sucker-punched a couple people,'' Hundley said. ``He'd
throw his punch and take off running and then hit someone else. I
saw him hit (Gary) Sheffield.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, being coy and not specifically naming Dempsey as the
perpetrator, said he went to the person who hit Marte and showed
his gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him after the game and I congratulated him,'' he
said ``I thought it was outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish-speaking Marte, using teammate Rafael Bournigal as
an interpreter, felt justified in taking action.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hit me first, from behind,'' Marte said. ``They hit me in
the head, the back. I said I wasn't going to take it anymore. One
of their coaches hit me from behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa's involvement was unclear; he declined to discuss such
matters. But Buhner was spotted putting Borbon in a headlock near
the Mariners dugout. Borbon, Buhner said, caused Gipson's injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was Steve Austin coming out of nowhere,'' Buhner cracked,
mentioning the popular pro wrestler before turning serious. ``I was
just trying to get Borbon off Chuckie. I knew his shoulder was
(bleeped) up because he was screaming. It's a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   After what appeared to be three rounds of blows, the teams were
separated and then ran out on the field once more with Mariners
first baseman David Segui yelling and gesturing. Earlier, Segui and
the Dodgers' Raul Mondesi had wrestled each other to the ground. No
more punches were thrown.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers outfielder Todd Hollandsworth, the Newport High grad,
thought there was good reason for the melee. Then he found out
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Grudzielanek got hit,'' he said. ``I didn't know
that he didn't until he got back in the box and hit again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
