<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6393 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK     07-12 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS PLANNING TO SHOP FOR MUCH-NEEDED BULLPEN HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Once the Mariners have taken their All-Star break
and opened Safeco Field, they finally can get comfortable and
settle into a routine, right?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. The end of the first series at Safeco will signal
the start of the two-week frenzy leading up to the July 31 trade
deadline. And as has been the case in recent seasons, the club
should be an active participant, according to manager Lou Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   With a disclaimer, of course. There likely won't be any
blockbuster deals now that Randy Johnson has his wish _ no runs,
lots of money. There won't be any quick fixes either, no Andy Benes
stopovers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mariners intend to do some shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``If players are available that could help us for the remainder
of the year and longer, we would look in that direction,'' Piniella
said. ``The rent-a-player, I don't see any need for that. But if
you can find a pitcher or position player that you can project will
help you for a couple years, we would be interested. You need to
keep improving. We're not exactly a powerhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, what then?
</P>
<P>
   ``We could use help in the bullpen, experienced help,'' Piniella
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the halfway point, the M's find themselves with five more
victories and fewer headaches than the year before.
</P>
<P>
   The defense is better and the hitting nearly as potent. The
pitching rotation overall has promise, if not this season, than
certainly next. There is a closer with 18 saves, two shy of the
most ever by a Mariner at the break, and Paul Abbott has promise as
a setup man.
</P>
<P>
   But, oh, the rest of that bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us could say we could pitch better, but some more so
than others,'' starter Jamie Moyer said.
</P>
<P>
   At the break, the M's find themselves with the second-worst
earned run average in the majors, 5.91, exceeded only by Colorado's
6.21.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella says arm injuries incurred in May by veterans Mark
Leiter and Butch Henry threw an already fragile pitching staff into
great disarray, creating the continual shuffle that has forced him
to use 23 pitchers, the most by any team in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Only two teams have walked more hitters than the Mariners (374):
Tampa Bay (382) and Colorado (394). Any progress has been greatly
overshadowed by the free pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the pitching has settled a little bit and gotten
better,'' pitching coach Stan Williams said. ``We've switched
people around to see what they could do. But I'm still disappointed
that walks have beaten us. (Saturday) night, we get two outs, then
give up a walk, walk and a single. In the second half, we have got
to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   The most pleasant Mariners surprise so far has been rookie
starter John Halama, 7-2 with a 2.89 earned run average. The lefty
is 5-0 as a starter, has the club's only complete game and shutout,
and has surrendered just four runs over 31 innings in his past four
outings.
</P>
<P>
   For everyday players, second baseman David Bell has surpassed
expectations as no other, hitting .270 with 15 home runs and 53
RBIs as a replacement for the injured Carlos Guillen.
</P>
<P>
   The player who has fallen off the most is pitcher Jeff Fassero,
headed for his worst season among nine in the big leagues unless he
undergoes a rapid turnaround. Counting Sunday's defeat, he is 4-9
with a 6.93 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Among everyday Mariners, third baseman Russ Davis has had his
average plummet more than 30 points (.227), but he has maintained
power (17 homers) and dramatically improved his defense (eight
errors so far to 32 last season). Everyone else has kept pace or
exceeded their offensive projections.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries have hurt the Mariners, robbing them of the two veteran
pitchers, shortstop Alex Rodriguez for a month, right fielder Jay
Buhner for two months and designated hitter Edgar Martinez for a
few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   With most of these bodies back in place and a new ballpark to
play in, the Mariners are hoping they're not looking at a lost
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we fix a few things here and there, we're in a perfect
attack position,'' outfielder Butch Huskey said. ``It's better to
peak after the break than before the break, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   BOXED IN: Piniella, after yanking Halama out of Saturday's game
and turning to his bullpen in the eighth inning, found his move
even questioned by Dodgers fans. One in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Adame Jr., a 27-year-old Whittier man and former junior
college football player, bounded from his box seat 15 rows up and,
hanging over the dugout, engaged in conversation with Piniella for
several moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Lou, leave him in there. He's a professional. He
knows what he's doing,''' said the 6-foot-1, 265 pound Adame.
</P>
<P>
   GOING, GOING, GONE: Fassero is just the fifth big league pitcher
to serve up 28 homers or more by the All-Star break. His
much-bruised companions are Minnesota's Bert Blyleven, 30 in 1986
and 1987; Atlanta's Phil Niekro, 29 in 1970; and the Chicago Cubs'
Ferguson Jenkins, 29 in 1973. Blyleven finished with 50 and 46,
Niekro 40 and Jenkins cut his losses to 35.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
