<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S SOCCER DESERVES A FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Walking out of the Rose Bowl Saturday after
the U.S. women won their World Cup, I heard a father turn to his
twentysomething son and tell him thanks for buying the tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a once-in-a-lifetime thing,'' the father said.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose the man could be right, but it sure seemed just as
likely that what happened during this captivating 1999 Women's
World Cup is a sign of times to come.
</P>
<P>
   Then, later that evening, I spoke with my mother, who is not a
big sports fan. She did, however, watch the game on television _
one of 40 million Americans to do so _ and she said tears came to
her eyes the moment U.S. goalkeeper Briana Scurry stopped the
penalty kick and the Rose Bowl erupted with ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought to myself: `She's going to be the hero. She's going
to be the one who wins this game,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe everybody had that same reaction during another
heart-stopping moment, when midfielder Kristine Lilly was in the
absolute right place to head that ball out of the U.S. net to save
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it made you shiver to see Michelle Akers challenge
goalkeeper Goa Hong or fly legs-first into the boards, sacrificing
her body one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it came when Brandi Chastain booted that final penalty
kick into the back of the net and ripped off her jersey in what she
claims was a flash of temporary insanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what point made me tear up?'' a friend asked me
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the jets were flying over the stadium before the game and
the girls were jumping up and down. They were just so excited.
They're so real and so giving, like when they thanked the crowd
after the game.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a lesson in there. The images and gestures and mood of
this World Cup were all gutsy and athletic, yet at the same time
they were revolutionary because it was all so feminine, or at least
female, especially in the willingness of the team to share the
moment with each other and anyone who watched them play.
</P>
<P>
   The impression that the '99 Women's World Cup players gave more
than they took is indelible, even when expectations about the
future of their game go unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, time and corporate sponsors will tell us whether there
is any chance for a professional women's soccer league. What comes
next will have to be invented _ and we can only hope in some
positive manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be so good for our players, but it is a major
challenge,'' World Cup president Marla Messing said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had time to think about the league, but I look at
baseball, basketball, hockey and I don't think we can put together
a league that looks anything like that. We need a new model,
although I don't know what that model would look like,'' Messing
said.
</P>
<P>
   If a women's league presents challenges about how it should be
organized, the women have earned the right to have U.S. Soccer and
its partners attempt to come up with something revolutionary,
something that can assure the women's game a secure place in our
sporting landscape, a business model and marketing relationship in
which it can succeed.
</P>
<P>
   That much the women have earned.
</P>
<P>
   In a time when the big business of sports has driven us into
ugly, sordid, untrusting relationships with so many athletes,
teams, owners and leagues, the women have been the perfect
counterpoint.
</P>
<P>
   One day after the World Cup's grand finale, it is abundantly
clear that what struck us most about the U.S. team was its unity,
desire, effort, generosity, commitment and hunger.
</P>
<P>
   No, it certainly did not hurt that the skilled, fit and driven
U.S. team is overwhelmingly attractive. Nor did it hurt that the
principle makeup of the team is smart, white, college educated and
_ just as important _ heterosexual. All this made marketing tickets
and TV that much easier.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 650,000 tickets and the overwhelming attention is quite
an achievement and the team felt successful for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been told we were carrying this tournament,''
midfielder Julie Foudy said after the rush of the U.S. victory
settled down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've answered every single one of the questions. That's what
we talked about in the locker room (after the win). We came in as
the favorites but there was a lot of pressure for us to do well.
That's what gives me such pride. It was such a team effort and this
just shows you women can compete. It can be exciting,'' Foudy said.
</P>
<P>
   Some will say this Women's World Cup was a three-week event that
picked up steam the closer the U.S. team got to the final. In
reality, this Women's World Cup was at least 27 years in the
making, since a stroke of a pen back in 1972 legislated gender
equity for women's sports in schools that receive public funding.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that is why the 90,185 people bought out the Rose Bowl _ a
non-traditional (or could it be a new tradition?) crowd of young
girls, boys, families and women.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken a long time to build up to this breakthrough point.
</P>
<P>
   For that, perhaps we should take Title IX and rename it Title
11, just as a way of recognizing how a soccer team took a run at
challenging history and helped brighten a new vision for what women
can do and what sports can look like.
</P>
<P>
   If some view the '99 Women's World Cup as a cult happening,
there are a few new American athletic stars and worthy role models
who won't settle for anything like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many things as players we want,'' Mia Hamm said
after the World Cup was done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want a professional league. I think this is going to help.
And hopefully the response (to this World Cup) will help not just
women's soccer but men's soccer as well. This can get a lot of
people excited,'' Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, our work isn't done yet.''
</P>
<P>
   If the effort and tenacity the women showed in making this World
Cup what it was, you would have to take Hamm and her teammates at
their word. They have an admiring audience at their feet now.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
