<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH SEASON MADE WORSE BY MARINERS OWNERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Watching the team stagger into the All-Star break like
some gray-muzzled, arthritic malamute, while observing the
financial scar on the face of the new ballyard, it finally dawned
on me what is most aggravating about the recent stewardship of the
Mariners franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The owners have made a hard season brutal.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the team and its public are beaten up _ by far more
than the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The beating is not necessarily fatal, because this week's debut
of the Guilty Pleasure will be cause for celebration and
inspiration. But given the damage already done _ 15 defeats in the
last 22 games, including a season-high five-game losing streak and
a mere half-game out of the AL West cellar _ the new park on its
own is hardly enough medicine for a recovery to playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a substantive influx of talent by the July 31 trading
deadline, the 1999 death spiral under way would mean that Ken
Griffey Jr., and Alex Rodriguez this off-season will have merely
promises and not a single bit of evidence from the shy tycoons
about building a winner in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey and A-Rod, along with the rest of the local sports
world, recently have seen what this ownership's promises are worth.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is by far the most difficult of the major spectator
sports to master. As a game as well as a business, baseball takes
the most patience, the most money and the most wisdom. Since the
Randy Johnson debacle of more than a year ago, the franchise has
evinced almost none of those virtues.
</P>
<P>
   The impact on the fans is obvious. Not only are the Mariners
second in baseball in attendance decline, the new field's string of
sellouts extends only through the first four games so far. Late
last week there were 15,000 seats available for the July 21 game
against Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Before the season, Mariners brass perkily said they would cut
off season-ticket sales at 24,000 in order to keep seats available
for the walk-up crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the walk-ups were never threatened. The pre-season sale,
including the half-year at the Guilty Pleasure, ended around
20,000, a grand more than the best season at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   The impact on the team is no less blatant. Pitching has been in
chaos from the opener, thanks to a salary cap imposed by no rule or
entity other than the owners' reluctance to cash in more Microsoft
stock.
</P>
<P>
   With eight rookie pitchers and 23 overall shuttling in and out
of the clubhouse, it's amazing the laundry gets sorted properly,
much less the signals between catcher and pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Much statistical evidence illuminates the debacle of the one of
the worst staffs in major league history, none more startling than
this: In nearly a quarter of the games in the season's first half,
including Sunday's Hollywood slapstick, Mariners pitching has given
up 10 or more runs.
</P>
<P>
   That's beyond embarrassing. It's debilitating, because a mostly
young, fragile staff burns up more quickly. Besides losing the
games, the flailing relievers waste innings and confidence in
hopelessness, and the hitters are free to indulge their worst
instincts _ fence-busting instead of runner-advancing.
</P>
<P>
   On top of it all, the heavy lifting required to come back from
one-touchdown deficits is emotionally and physically exhausting.
Even the welcome addition of Brian Hunter's base-stealing prowess
is too often useless in context with either big deficits or
late-game relief flops.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest of the season, a point made earlier here is
offered up again: To tell fans that three rookie starters (Freddy
Garcia, John Halama and Gil Meche) are the stuff of playoff
contention is absurd. When the rooks are backed in the bullpen by
waiver-wire warriors such as Jose Paniagua and Frankie Rodriguez,
it flirts with consumer fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The astonishing conclusion is that this 23-year-old team has
expansion- quality pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the prime reason for the desperate scramble has been a
self-imposed requirement to make a little money this season,
apparently no matter what the consequences to ticket sales, public
relations or the baseball futures of its stars and prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has always said the stadium cost overruns had no
impact on the player payroll, Mariners CEO John Ellis finally told
the truth about the club attitude in a Feb. 19 letter to the Public
Facilities District: ``If the owners had to bear the entirety of
the enormous increased costs, in addition to the substantial
operating losses sustained over the past seven years, it would have
an obvious impact on the club's flexibility in struggling to field
a highly competitive team ... ''
</P>
<P>
   In plain English, it's the long-dreaded extortion: Give us the
extra tax money or say goodbye to Griffey and A-Rod.
</P>
<P>
   While the threat was formally in play during spring training,
its public disclosure this month that Griffey is the prime pawn in
a negotiation not of his making comes at the same time management
has requested that he shut up about his obvious dismay with the
dimensions and heavy air in the new park.
</P>
<P>
   With the team in decline at the time of his least favorite part
of the baseball calendar, the All-Star Game, Griffey can't help but
be working on a fairly serious mad-on toward his bosses.
</P>
<P>
   His edginess was apparent last week before a game when he called
up unsolicited to complain to radio station KJR-AM, with whom he
has had no dealings since a host on an affiliated station mocked
his wife a couple of seasons ago. Griffey wanted to deny an Atlanta
newspaper report that he told the bosses he wouldn't re-sign with
the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   The report was prompted in part by widespread national belief,
further fueled by disclosure of Ellis' own written statements, that
the owners can't sign both stars despite _ and, amazingly, partly
because of _ the new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The collective upshot of these developments is that, in addition
to putting a team through a home field change at midseason _
baseball players are notorious creatures of habit who will quietly
nurse multiple complaints about the move _ the owners, instead of
creating an atmosphere of success, have ignited controversies and
distractions that have alienated some in the clubhouse and made
many fans resentful.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime baseball followers know that all clubs go through
changes and turmoil, particularly when a stadium issue is at hand.
The difference here is that Major League Baseball, the state of
Washington and the Puget Sound baseball community have over the
years combined to make a hard game about as easy as it can get for
one franchise.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, baseball backed away from its own policy against
foreign ownership to permit Japanese investment in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, baseball broke down the races in such small divisions
that the Mariners have to be better than only three other teams to
qualify for postseason play.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature in 1995 convened a special session to create
massive, controversial public funding for a ballpark. Then in
December 1996, the state, King County and the city capitulated to
further club extortion, creating one of the sweetest leases in the
major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three seasons, the public did its part by
forsaking Seattle summers and showing up 8.4 million strong to a
garage, as well as helping creating the highest local TV ratings in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The response to this overwhelming, spectacular show of support
is a floundering 42-45 team whose stars are edging toward the exit
while their bosses edge toward the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   As far as stewardship of quasi-public institution, it's been
brutal. Absolutely brutal.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
