u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-TEMPS-SPI &LR;      07-12 1844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-TEMPS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OTHERS WATCHING CLOSELY MICROSOFT'S SAGA WITH TEMP WORKERS,
LAWSUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Microsoft has improved benefits for the contract
workers who make up a third of its Puget Sound area work force.
</P>
<P>
   But the workers' ongoing discontent _ along with two potentially
expensive lawsuits _ may compel the Redmond software maker to
eliminate or restructure this labor source.
</P>
<P>
   The change could cause reverberations nationwide in the software
industry and other businesses needing a work force that can grow or
shrink to match product life cycles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The end of perma-temping at Microsoft could be very near,''
said Marcus Courtney, co-founder of the Washington Alliance of
Technical Workers (Washtech), a labor organization in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is a legal ruling in a federal lawsuit called
Vizcaino vs. Microsoft. In it, a federal judge ruled that as many
as 10,000 current and former temporary workers at Microsoft are
eligible for appreciation on stock they should have been allowed to
buy.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit ``could undermine the entire information economy,''
forcing companies using temps to find some alternative and
companies providing temps to restructure or fold, said Harris
Miller, president of the Information Technology Association of
America, a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   He's not the only one worried.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Irvine, president of the local chapter of the National
Technical Services Association, which represents 300 providers of
temporary technical workers nationwide, said members are concerned
their customers ``might be afraid of falling into the same
situation as Microsoft.'' Formerly reliable tests for determining
who should legally be considered a worker's employer ``might work
one day and not the next'' because of the Vizcaino suit, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal legislation is pending that may also affect the
temporary-worker industry, noted Toby Malara, the association's
director of government public affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The temporary agencies have come to the forefront'' in
Washington, D.C., he said.
</P>
<P>
   Precisely what form of employment would replace temping and what
would become of the 5,500 to 6,500 temporary workers now in place
at Microsoft, remain unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are evaluating our options, and we hope that we will always
have the option to engage individuals in a temporary capacity to
address the needs of a rapidly changing high-tech economy,'' said
Sharon Decker, Microsoft's director of contingent staffing.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Microsoft is trying to do right by its temps, agreed
five of the six temporary workers interviewed for this story. They
said their work lives have improved since early May, when newly
negotiated contracts went into effect between Microsoft and the 15
principal agencies that supply it with temporary workers.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest software company told agencies that if they
wanted to continue to do business with Microsoft after May, they
would need to offer benefits including:
</P>
<P>
   _13 paid days off a year, whether as sick leave, compensatory
time, paid vacation or some other form.
</P>
<P>
   _Medical and dental insurance, for which the agency pays half.
</P>
<P>
   _Vocational training worth at least $500 a year.
</P>
<P>
   _A retirement savings program with some matching by the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also reduced, to 15 from more than 100, the number of
agencies with which it contracts for temps, so it could more
closely supervise their benefits offerings. Agencies subcontracting
to those 15 principal agencies would be expected to offer the same
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Five agencies or subcontractors surveyed last week said their
benefits meet or beat Microsoft's requirements.
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;T Onsite, a Seattle supplier of designers and writers, said it
has increased its IRA contribution rate to 20 percent from 15
percent of pretax earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Volt Computer Services of Redmond, which furnishes software
testers, reported it offers an extra two days vacation annually.
</P>
<P>
   The Write Stuff Inc., a Seattle supplier of communications
workers, said it meets or exceeds Microsoft's requirements and
sends a masseuse to its employees twice a month.
</P>
<P>
   BENEFITS AT OR ABOVE the minimum levels were also reported by
Kelly Services Inc., a Troy, Mich., supplier of administrative
workers, and by H.L. Yoh Co. LLC, a Philadelphia supplier of
testers.
</P>
<P>
   But exactly how those benefits are implemented is left to the
agencies, and that means they can choose to offer only the bare
minimums. So some agencies may offer health insurance to
individuals, but not to their families. And the vocational training
offered by some agencies may not go beyond the skill area in which
each temp's job falls.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Lewis, who has worked under contracts at Microsoft for four
years, mostly as a lab engineer, said, ``I would say my personal
situation is not better now than it was on May 2. I get $82 toward
personal medical premiums but none for my daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who is 40 and the single mother of a 12-year-old, added,
``As a parent, I could use a lot more flex time than the 13 days
per year we get.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft-engineered competition among agencies was supposed to
result in even greater benefits to temps. But the workers are still
chafing under contracts forbidding them from switching from one
agency to another during an assignment. Washtech wants these
provisions eliminated, saying they reduce the choices workers have
among agencies and thereby diminish the agencies' incentives to
compete to offer better benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Volt and Yoh said they won't ax the provisions
because they are too important to the agencies' stability.
Microsoft said it can't force them to.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the improved benefits, many Microsoft temps say they
continue to feel like second-class citizens. Distinctions between
Microsoft employees and the temps, such as different colored ID
badges and e-mail addresses, add to that feeling, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does feel like I'm set apart because of subtle things,''
like being on separate distribution lists for important documents
and having to get a manager's permission to attend a briefing that
full-time, permanent employees can go to without a second thought,
said Ed Campodonico, who will have been a Microsoft temp for three
consecutive years in October.
</P>
<P>
   And whether they represent policy or are merely careless,
remarks like those by Chief Financial Officer Greg Maffei last
month create _ or reflect _ a stigma attached to temps.
</P>
<P>
   Maffei said at a meeting of accountants, ``The quality of the
temps is not as good as the quality of the full-time people. ... We
wouldn't necessarily have said we want them for full time.''
</P>
<P>
   He later apologized for and withdrew the statement.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that the benefits temps are getting aren't
even close to what Microsoft offers its own employees. On its Web
site, Microsoft brags it offers ``more perks than Seattle has
coffeehouses.''
</P>
<P>
   For employees and their families, including same-sex domestic
partners, Microsoft covers 100 percent of medical, dental and
vision insurance premiums. It offers optional life insurance of up
to $750,000, a group legal plan and pretax deductions for day care
and elder care expenses and health care expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The 401(k) plan allows deferring 15 percent of pre-tax salary,
plus an additional 7 percent after taxes. Contributions are matched
50 percent, up to 6 percent of the employee's salary.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also offers paid maternity and infant-care leave,
financial adoption assistance, personal and family counseling,
health club memberships, matching charitable deductions and
personalized ergonomics consultation.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether it's fair that Microsoft employees get
benefits so much richer than those of temporary workers, spokesman
Dan Leach said: ``If you're interested in Microsoft benefits, there
are 2,000 jobs that anyone qualified should apply for.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not that simple. Applying for staff jobs was eased by
Microsoft's May declaration that it would disregard non-compete
clauses forbidding agency employees from becoming Microsoft
employees. Still, it's not necessarily easy to ``convert'' from one
to the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get a full-time job was a grueling process,'' said one
worker who just converted. ``I practically fell into my contracting
job.''
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT AND THE temps seem to be forever at odds. The company
maintains that contract workers make more in wages than its
employees and have more flexible schedules. Temporary workers argue
that they don't make more in wages, that even if they do, their
expenses are higher and that their flexibility is limited by
Microsoft's mandatory one-month time-off periods and by their
agencies' non-compete clauses.
</P>
<P>
   It's a matter of fairness, said David Stobaugh, an attorney in
the Vizcaino suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are truly `temps,' working for a few weeks or
months, fine. But these people aren't temps,'' he said. ``It's easy
to justify treating people differently when you call them something
else.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the lawsuits will undoubtedly affect the
company's thinking.
</P>
<P>
   In Vizcaino, the full appellate court most recently refused
Microsoft's petition to rehear a decision in favor of the temps
rendered by a three-judge panel of the court. Now Microsoft will
likely either seek review in the U.S. Supreme Court or face the
music.
</P>
<P>
   Once Vizcaino is resolved, it may be unnecessary to litigate
Hughes vs. Microsoft, a related case seeking back insurance
benefits for the same plaintiffs, Stobaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Vizcaino court) basically told Microsoft they have to
stop pretending these people aren't employees,'' he said. ``And
once they are employees for one purpose, they're employees for
every purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   One solution Microsoft may be considering is expanding its own
work force to create a pool of employees who will move from one
project to another as needed.
</P>
<P>
   If that were cost-effective at current salary levels, it
probably would already have been done. So it may be significant
that in mid-May, Microsoft said it would increase the number of
non-executive job classification levels to 22 from 12. Perhaps it
is preparing to create a floating corps of differently compensated
workers, Washtech's Courtney suggested.
</P>
<P>
   A prototype corps member may be one woman who came to Microsoft
several months ago as a Grade 8. She's a Microsoft employee,
wearing a blue badge, getting full benefits and eligible to
participate in the discounted stock purchase plan, just like any
other Microsoft worker. But she's paid by the hour and hasn't yet
received any stock options, unlike most Microsoft employees, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an employee, but I'm not treated like all the other
employees,'' said the woman, who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   Though not a temp, she wonders whether she's being treated
fairly.
</P>
<P>
   Where will it end? asked worker Lisa Lewis. ``Something's got to
give,'' she said. ``What, I don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
