<SLUG> BC-SOC-AKERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE-WORN AKERS WEIGHING SOCCER RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ What will Michelle Akers do? What should she
do?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tough year physically. I have to weigh if I want
to go through this again,'' Akers said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Then, she posed the real question:
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I need to?'' Akers said.
</P>
<P>
   In a year when Michael Jordan decided he wanted to go out on
top; in a time when John Elway won his second Super Bowl and walked
away on top of the game; when Wayne Gretzky refused to slog through
another season too hurt to play the way the greatest hockey player
ever will be remembered for playing, Akers should give herself the
time and permission to answer that question.
</P>
<P>
   No one would fault her for wanting to hang up her cleats now. No
one will say she has to stick around and risk further injury
because women's soccer needs her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a better team with Michelle on the field,'' U.S. coach
Tony DiCicco said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the toughest ... player I've ever played with,'' Brandi
Chastain bellowed in the wake of the U.S. women's victory Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But Akers' presence comes at an increasingly painful cost.
</P>
<P>
   She was not on the field when the U.S. won the 1999 Women's
World Cup. After 90 minutes of giving every ounce of blood and
sweat, Akers was in the trainer's room, exhausted, dehydrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's out of it. I've never seen her like that,'' U.S. World
Cup team spokesman Aaron Heiffitz said after the game.
</P>
<P>
   That was really saying something.
</P>
<P>
   To understand how wiped out Akers was after a goal-line
collision with goalkeeper Briana Scurry during a China corner kick,
think about all the times Akers has been down during her stellar
career.
</P>
<P>
   For 14 years, Akers has battled chronic fatigue syndrome _ a
condition that requires daily management and postgame IV's to help
restore her fluids and energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have no idea what this woman goes through just to play the
game,'' one team official said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Chastain, Mia Hamm was nearly choking up just thinking
about Akers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's such a champion. I just wished she was on the field with
us at the end. But the fact that she wasn't on the field told me
she had given it her all. We are not the same team without her,''
Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   The toll has been heavy, though. Akers also has had a dozen knee
surgeries. She has broken three bones in her cheek and suffered
more brain-rattling concussions than Steve Young.
</P>
<P>
   But, despite her lagging health and injuries, Akers overall was
the best United States player during this World Cup. Her ability to
to control the ball and launch her rocket shot were on full
display.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the '99 World Cup, Akers still is the most
dominating player in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Akers' relentless effort shored up the U.S. defense and gave the
team its underlying offensive threat. She did the same thing during
a stalwart effort in the quarterfinals against Germany and against
Brazil in the semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Akers did not make the team's visit to Disneyland Sunday.
However, she did make one statement to The Associated Press,
uttering the question that everyone is asking: Can she do this
again?
</P>
<P>
   After two World Cup wins, an Olympic gold medal and all she has
done for the sport of soccer, Akers has earned the right to end her
career as champion, even if she can't forget the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Akers what she remembers about her first Women's World Cup,
though, and she will tell you it was Pele.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, when the U.S. Women's World Cup team took the field in
China, Pele met Akers with a hug and a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sign. An embrace from one champion to another. It was a
moment of mutual respect between a man who uplifted his sport and a
pioneering woman who was doing the same thing for hers.
</P>
<P>
   Now the pioneer has made her contributions to the women's sports
revolution. Her place in history is alive and kicking, even if she
decides this is the right time to walk away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
