<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORBON CONNECTS WITH PAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Dodgers left-hander Pedro Borbon
laughed Sunday when reminded that his father, former Reds reliever
Pedro Borbon, played a major role in one of the most famous fights
in major-league history _ the 1973 playoff brawl touched off by
Pete Rose and New York Mets shortstop Bud Harrelson.
</P>
<P>
   The husky Rose beat Harrelson badly, but the underdog Mets won
the series. Borbon's father was accused of taking a bite out of a
Mets cap during the brawl.
</P>
<P>
   Borbon was thrown out of Sunday's 14-3 victory over Seattle for
his part in a 15-minute fight. After the Mariners' Jay Buhner got
him in a headlock, Borbon hit him several times in the face. He
also struck reliever Jose Paniagua.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I see one of my teammates going down, I'm going to get in
there and defend him,'' Borbon said. ``That's the way my dad was. I
don't even know where my cap is now, but I wouldn't have bitten it.
I don't have strong teeth like my dad did. I had someone tell me,
`You look just like your dad,' when they mentioned that fight.''
</P>
<P>
   About his altercation with Paniagua, which died down, then
picked up twice, Borbon joked, ``We Latin guys, we never let it
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he turned serious, blaming Mariners manager Lou Piniella
for setting the tone for Sunday's brawl. Many think it began
Friday, when Seattle's Freddy Garcia retaliated twice after Ismael
Valdes hit Mariners hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Seattle baseball,'' Borbon said. ``That's the way they
play, that's the way Lou Piniella plays. If you hit my shortstop
I'm going to hit your shortstop. If you hit my third baseman, I'm
going to hit your third baseman. Sometimes, I feel that the league
should go after him instead of the players.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella refused to comment after Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Masaoka finishes: Darren Dreifort went five innings to end a
personal three-game losing streak, but the most impressive pitching
was done by rookie left-handed reliever Onan Masaoka. He pitched
the final four innings, allowing just one hit and one walk for his
first career save.
</P>
<P>
   Masaoka, a starter throughout his minor-league career, said he
is just happy to be here and doesn't think about whether the team
will make him a starter one day. ``The good part is being here and
contributing,'' he said. ``We have a good group out there. We'll
think about that stuff later.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez, two potential
free agents after the 2000 season, went a combined 1 for 18 in the
series. The only hit was Griffey's third-inning homer Sunday that
gave him 379 for his career, tied for 38th all-time with Orlando
Cepeda and Tony Perez.... Griffey's two-out homer came on a 3-2
pitch after Dreifort got ahead 0-2.... Eric Young, who has
struggled in the leadoff spot this season, went 3 for 4 with two
doubles, two runs and his 33rd stolen base.... Chan Ho Park,
suspended seven games in June for kicking the Angels Tim Belcher,
was a bystander during most of Sunday's fight: ``I was scared out
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
