<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6404 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BB-REDSOX-BRAVES-BOS &LR;      07-12 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX DROOP, ENTER BREAK OFF LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BRAVES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Those storm clouds that gathered overhead just as Lou
Merloni struck out to end Sunday's 8-1 loss to the Atlanta Braves
did not follow the Red Sox home.
</P>
<P>
   Once they boarded their charter flight to Boston, the Sox not
only left behind the dark skies but a 4-6 road trip, their last bit
of unpleasant business in a National League city, and the
figurative first half of a season in which they exceeded all
expectations, perhaps even their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't want to answer that question,'' said third
baseman John Valentin, when asked precisely that. ``All I can say
is this team played well in the first half and we weren't expected
to. I've got to give credit to our team. We played hard and won
games against good teams, and we have confidence that we can
compete against good teams.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Sox resume competing after the All-Star break against
the Phillies Thursday in Boston, they will be fortified not only by
the return of Valentin, who had two singles off Braves ace Greg
Maddux in his first game off the disabled list. They also are
anticipating the return of shortstop Nomar Garciaparra, who missed
the last nine games of this trip with a strained left groin, a
stretch in which the Red Sox scored two runs or fewer five times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a good ballclub,'' Valentin said. ``We're going to
play well. It's a long season with a lot of ups and downs. The
break is coming at the right time. We're struggling a little bit
right now physically, and mentally we haven't been playing all that
great.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this team comes to the ballpark and works hard and plays
hard. Obviously, when guys are out of the lineup, it's going to
affect your club. But I thought we've played well with guys out. I
have to hand it to the rest of the guys who've stepped up.
Hopefully, (Tom Gordon) will come back and other guys will get back
in the groove.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows the second half is important. It's a war. Guys
will be prepared to come back and show what we showed at times in
the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not one of those times. Not against Maddux, who gave
one of his virtuoso minimalist performances _ six hits (five
singles), one runner to third base after the first inning, 84
pitches in eight innings _ while rookie Jin Ho Cho absorbed a
lesson in textbook baseball from the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   --First Braves run: A double, ground ball to advance the runner
to third, sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   --Two more Braves runs: Double, a Maddux sacrifice bunt, RBI
single, hit-and-run single, sac fly.
</P>
<P>
   --Fourth Braves run: A home run by Ryan Klesko, who later
dropped a three-run bomb on Tim Wakefield, who pitched the eighth
inning just for the exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be better, but he's still learning,'' catcher Jason
Varitek said of Cho (2-2), who lasted just four innings and has not
made it past the fifth in his last three starts, which have
resulted in two losses and a no-decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot to learn. I do, too, but he's got a lot of game
situations to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan, asked how Cho fits in the team's
second-half plans, said: ``He fits in the fifth hole. And don't
read anything into that.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, the Sox had hoped Ramon Martinez would be joining the
rotation, but that won't happen. Martinez, who had to take three
weeks between rehabilitation starts, is as much an uncertainty now
as Gordon, the closer who is expected to begin testing his bad
elbow after the break. Meanwhile, Juan Pena, the rookie who pitched
so splendidly in two starts before his shoulder went south, has
just begun pitching again, at the lowest rung of the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, who have lost five of their last seven games,
scored just two runs in their last 24 innings here. Jose Offerman
went 0 for 9 on the weekend. Troy O'Leary had one hit in 11 at-bats
here. Merloni went 0 for 12, Varitek 0 for 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not swinging the bats as well now,'' Varitek said, ``but
against Tampa Bay we were swinging better than the results showed.
Guys lined into double plays, balls were bouncing over fences,
people were making diving catches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what this team is built on. We have to have those
balls fall in. We don't have nine guys in the lineup who are
hitting three bills (.300). But we'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are 3-9 in interleague play, with six games left against
National League opponents, the Phillies and Marlins in back-to-back
series after the break. Those games are all at home, so at least
the Sox will be able to employ a designated hitter, which they
weren't able to do in NL parks, where they went 2-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like interleague play, period,'' manager Jimy Williams
said. ``That's my opinion. It's there. We'll go by the rules. But
I'm not an advocate.''
</P>
<P>
   He is, however, a believer in his team, one that goes into the
break four games behind the Yankees in the AL East, and just three
games ahead of third-place Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``We compete,'' he said. ``I think our pitchers have done a
great job. I really do. Overall, offensively, I've gotten some big
hits from a lot of different people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep playing, don't we? That's all. No excuses. Just keep
playing. That's all we're trying to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
