<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-JIFFY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURTON IN THIRD GEAR AT NHIS 
</HEADLINE>
 LUBE 300-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ The third time around was a gas for Jeff Burton.
</P>
<P>
   After he qualified poorly and started 38th in Sunday's Jiffy
Lube 300 NASCAR Winston Cup race at New Hampshire International
Speedway, Burton knew he faced a monumental uphill struggle if he
intended to drive his No. 99 Ford Taurus from the back of the
43-car field to the front, let alone Victory Lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never say if we qualify bad, we can't win,'' Burton said,
``but I have to tell you, going into this race, we didn't think we
had a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   After his Roush Racing crew worked feverishly Sunday morning to
change the springs, swaybars, and track bars on his car, Burton
knew all the last-minute alterations made the chances for a
three-peat visit to Victory Lane at NHIS seem remote, at best.
</P>
<P>
   But, lo and behold, at the end of Sunday's race _ which got
underway when Ted Williams gave the command ``Gentleman, start your
engines!'' _ that's exactly where Burton stood: Victory Lane.
</P>
<P>
   For the third year in a row, Burton was the winner of the Jiffy
Lube 300, but this time the 32-year-old native of South Boston,
Va., did so at the expense of rookie driver Tony Stewart. Bidding
to record his first Winston Cup victory, Stewart, who led twice for
118 laps (including 103 of the last 105), wound up 10th when he
dropped out of the lead with two laps to go after his No. 20
Pontiac ran out of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were out to lunch,'' said Burton, whose victory from 38th
was the deepest in the field a winner has started since Bill
Elliott came from 38th to win the 1988 Firecracker 400. ``But Frank
Stoddard (his crew chief) did a hell of a job, this whole team did
a great job. They got this car in contention to win when nobody
else could have done that. It just wasn't good enough when we
unloaded, but the guys never quit, I never quit and nobody ever got
down. We just kept working.''
</P>
<P>
   So did runner-up Kenny Wallace, who started sixth and never ran
among the Top 10 but somehow managed to work his way up to the
front on the last lap to record his career-best Winston Cup finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy Elledge made some great adjustments,'' Wallace said,
saluting the crew chief of his No. 55 Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``I
messed up on the gears. We should have pulled more gear. We got
second out of it. The car was awesome. It was very fast at the end.
That's how we stayed on the lead; I was conserving fuel there at
the end.''
</P>
<P>
   After he pitted for the last time on Lap 195, Stewart and his
crew chief, Greg Zipadelli of Berlin, Conn., gambled and lost when
they tried to stretch their last tank of gas 105 laps. Stewart, who
was involved in a bumping incident with Ernie Irvan on the postrace
cool-down lap, departed the track fuming and without comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was probably going to be a half-a-lap gamble,''
said Zipadelli. ``It showed up to be bigger than that. We thought
we were conserving more fuel throughout the whole run than we had
previously. If we did, and were getting the same fuel mileage we
did earlier, we should have made it.''
</P>
<P>
   But they came up two laps short when Stewart crossed the finish
line on Lap 298 and radioed his crew, ``We're out of fuel.''
</P>
<P>
   When Stewart dropped off the pace, John Andretti entered the
pits in second place with a chance to emerge as the leader. All he
needed was a quick splash of fuel. However, Andretti's No. 43
Pontiac coughed and wheezed when the fuel pickup failed and,
finally, stalled as he attempted to exit the pits.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, who pitted one last time with 10 laps to go, roared by
and left Andretti's stalled car in the pits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was proud of our team,'' Andretti said. ``But if I couldn't
have won it, or (teammate) Kyle (Petty) couldn't have won it, then
I would have wanted Jeff to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton's fourth win of the season and ninth of his career (one
third at NHIS), vaulted him from fourth to second in the Winston
Cup points, 240 behind leader Dale Jarrett (2,839), who finished
fourth after he was bumped out of third by a last-lap altercation
with Jeff Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got that trophy and we got those points and I don't care
how we did it _ we did it,'' Burton said when asked if Stewart's
misfortune in any way tainted his $139,490 victory. ``You win races
a lot of ways and to win races you've gotta put yourself in
position. We put ourselves in position and we did a better job than
they did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
