<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-WRAPUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR U.S. TEAM, PARADE IS JUST THE BEGINNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The United States women's national team was
treated to a victory parade Sunday morning at Disneyland, then an
afternoon rally at the Los Angeles Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   The first stop included a parade down Main Street, bands,
dancers, fireworks, confetti showers and workers sticking little
American flags in every empty hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome,'' defender Lorrie Fair said. ``All those
little kids with USA shirts and hats. There wasn't much notice that
we were coming. I was surprised to see so many people in red, white
and blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll find out how many people we've reached in the
days ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Kate Sobrero, the gutty U.S. defender who shut down China's Sun
Wen, wondered when her legs would give after a Saturday night that
lasted long into Sunday morning after the postgame party at the
Ritz-Carlton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We partied and partied,'' Sobrero said. ``It's been crazy, out
of control and I've had about two hours of sleep, but who cares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want this to end. I don't want to go home and not have
these 19 people around me all the time. I like living on cloud
nine, I can always sleep later.''
</P>
<P>
   As the team walked past a crowd estimated at 2,000 at the
Convention Center, many of the young fans held up signs that read,
``I have two fillings,'' referring to the U.S. team's Nike
commercial theme that encourages team camaraderie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids are just amazing,'' Kristine Lilly said. ``I think
they're capturing what we're all about. That's what we want to do.
Whether it's male or female, they are amazed by what they see.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team, without captain Michelle Akers who collapsed at
the end of Saturday's game because of heat exhaustion, was treated
to an entertaining show by midfielder Julie Foudy, who introduced
the U.S. players to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll leave nothing in the closet,'' Foudy said. ``Give me the
microphone and it's trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   After a few introductions, she looked at Saturday's hero Brandi
Chastain. Chastain tossed her shirt to the sky after her
game-winning penalty kick secured the U.S. victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see, she's the woman who has an uncanny knack of taking
her clothes off,'' Foudy said. ``She calls it temporary insanity,
but who believes that?''
</P>
<P>
   The team stayed for only a few minutes. They had interviews
scheduled throughout the day and had to board a plane for New York
for more appearances and a spot on Late Night with David Letterman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just doing whatever we're told, and having a good
time,'' Danielle Fotopoulos said. ``We're supposed to be on the
cover of Newsweek, Time, Sports Illustrated and People.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamm, Chastain and Foudy will play in an LPGA pro-am this week
and many of the players will be back in training by summer's end.
</P>
<P>
   The team handed out an itinerary, detailing Team USA's victory
tour, which begins with the U.S. Women's Cup on Oct. 3, in
Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
