A6409 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-COLUMN-LADN     07-12 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S SOCCER IS OUR GIG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ I sneered at the thought of a women's professional
soccer league before this Women's World Cup tournament began.
</P>
<P>
   Why in the world would we want to make fun of this sport
anymore? Major League Soccer has enough naysayers and critics who
think its collapse is around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   But the women give us something the men can't.
</P>
<P>
   This is our game. It's not Brazil's, England's or Germany's _
women's soccer is our gig.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer may be a century old in most parts of the world, leaving
our men decades behind, but women's soccer is our new phenomenon.
Let the rest of the world follow us this time.
</P>
<P>
   Need proof, look at Saturday's television ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's World Cup final between the United States and China
produced the most-watched soccer game ever on U.S. network
television.
</P>
<P>
   The United States' dramatic 5-4 penalty kick win posted a 13.3
overnight rating and a 32 share on ABC, 4 percent more than the
previous record, a 12.8 for the 1994 men's World Cup final, also
played at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ABC estimated 40 million viewers watched the game.
</P>
<P>
   The highest rating for the U.S. men was a 10.4 overnight and 27
share during a 1-0 loss to Brazil during the 1994 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see these numbers unless you're watching the NFL,''
said ABC spokesman Mark Mandel. ``If this event were on a Sunday
afternoon, these numbers would be through the roof.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like professional baseball, basketball and football,
viewers support sports played at the highest level and American
teams that win championships -- and these women offer both.
</P>
<P>
   While it may take years, if it doesn't fold first, before the
WNBA reaches the doorstep of the NBA, that's not the case in
women's soccer.
</P>
<P>
   You think every television and newspaper editor in America
doesn't recognize that Mia Hamm, Brandi Chastain, Michelle Akers,
Julie Foudy and Briana Scurry are the most popular soccer players
in America? Or dare we say, the world?
</P>
<P>
   You think every television and newspaper editor wasn't touched
by the theatrics and gut-wrenching performances the women showed
during their 120-minute victory in searing heat?
</P>
<P>
   Our men will always face impossible battles. We don't have the
best players in the world and we can't afford to pay the best
players in the world to come here. And we aren't capable of
delivering men's soccer at the highest level, not unless we invite
Manchester United or a few others in for a friendly.
</P>
<P>
   But women's soccer is different. The best players in the world
and the best team in the world are here.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt we'll have a professional league after the
(2000) Olympics,'' said Alan Rothenberg, president and CEO of the
1994 World Cup and adviser to the 1999 Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, there are obviously two things that are very
inviting. We would start out clearly as the best league in the
world, whereas the men have a good league but a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the other, we've tapped into a fan base that is excited,
interested and we would love to continue to encourage that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks, I can't recall the number of times I've
heard little girls and women explain that the reason they love
women's soccer is because the American players are the role models
they never had.
</P>
<P>
   And surely the chauvinistic pigs will follow women's soccer for
the other reasons found in Gear Magazine. But who cares? It's a
combination that will work.
</P>
<P>
   After a few months off, the women will be at it again, training
for the U.S. Women's Cup in October and a victory tour leading to
the Olympics next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think soccer is strong in this country,'' said forward Mia
Hamm. ``And it scares me to think how really strong it's going to
be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 0116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
