<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6413 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-FUTURE-LADN     07-12 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-FUTURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S IN THE FUTURE FOR WOMEN'S SOCCER?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Now that the medals have been awarded and the 1999
FIFA Women's World Cup turned into the smashing success many behind
the effort predicted it would become, what will become of the
sport?
</P>
<P>
   For all the gains reaped the past three weeks in this country
and around the world, is women's soccer in America ready to take
the next logical step?
</P>
<P>
   That step, of course, would be the establishment of a women's
professional league, much the same way Major League Soccer grew out
of efforts from the 1994 men's World Cup held in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Although the advent of a pro league is the ultimate goal, the
future also includes a deeper cultivation of the sport at the
grassroots level, something Marla Messing, President and CEO of the
Women's World Cup Organizing Committee, is sure will happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still going to have a huge impact on women's soccer in
this country,'' Messing said. ``I think we will see hundreds and
thousands of girls register for soccer in the fall that wouldn't
have otherwise, but for this event. They want to be like Mia
(Hamm), they want to be like Julie (Foudy), they want to play in a
Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I think the impact on the sport is going to be very
significant.''
</P>
<P>
   But this impact won't happen simply because people want it to
happen. It will take much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take money like anything else,'' said U.S. team
veteran Joy Fawcett. ``People who love the sport, enjoy watching
it, they might end up having to lose money in the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   That might not be what corporate America and any potential
sponsors of the league want to hear, but Fawcett speaks the truth.
Historically, start-up pro leagues tend to fail -- financially at
least -- at first before developing a core audience, which
ultimately could lead to success.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. assistant coach Lauren Gregg said establishing a league is
critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not only a possibility, but it's a necessity for us to
stay successful in the world arena,'' Gregg said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Team USA's players are hopeful of the signs pointing
toward a new league.
</P>
<P>
   But part of that process includes sustaining some momentum from
the success of this World Cup leading up to the 2000 Olympic Games
in Sydney, which will be held in September of that year. The talk
now is to have a pro league in place by the spring of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Leading up to that point, the U.S. team might venture on a
victory tour of sorts across the country to keep that contact with
the public before Sydney, although nothing formally has been
determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of people who have been awakened to the
sport and have fallen in love with women's soccer,'' said U.S.
forward Tisha Venturini. ``We've got to try and keep the momentum
going this next year. We want to keep people involved and aware of
the sport, so after the Olympics we can start a league.''
</P>
<P>
   The parameters of the league, from the players' perspective, are
quite simple, relatively speaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, we definitely want to be able to make a living at it
so we don't have to play and then go and get a job,'' Fawcett said.
``But we're not looking for million-dollar salaries.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. midfielder Julie Foudy has her thoughts on what a women's
league would be like.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be something where everyone's getting paid, not a
semi-professional league,'' Foudy said. ``It's can't be something
where you only have national-team players getting paid. There would
be eight teams nationwide, in big markets, with a lot of names from
the national team to go behind it to draw for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference in favor of the women's game is that much
of the best soccer already is played here in the states. And
without the same support in other countries, a pro league here also
likely would attract many of the world's greatest stars, eager for
a chance to showcase their talents to an appreciative public.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg said a pro league also would enhance possibilities for the
players beyond the current 20-member roster of the national team,
ultimately resulting in a deeper player pool overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of other countries have much deeper player pools than we
do and I think a league will help us keep some of our elite players
that right now fall between our youth national team and our women's
team,'' Gregg said. ``Right now, they have to choose `Do I go into
another career or do I starve to stay a soccer player?' So a league
will serve a role.''
</P>
<P>
   But the players that figure to fuel the potential success of a
league know the road won't be an easy one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it's a hard road,'' Foudy said. ``A league is a much
different thing than a World Cup. We just hope we can get enough
interest out there. I think the fan base is there to put on a
first-class production.''
</P>
<P>
   Venturini agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you start something new, it's going to take awhile
and it's going to be a rocky road,'' Venturini said. ``It's not
going to be like we start this league and all of a sudden we're
fantastic and everybody comes. It's going to be a struggle and we
know that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be a success because of the players that we
have and there's a lot of great players out there coming out of
college that aren't on the national team that could help makes this
league. It's just a matter of keeping the people interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest was something that as recently as earlier this decade
couldn't be sustained. The contrast from even eight years ago is a
sharp one when the U.S. won the inaugural Women's World Cup in
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard to compare,'' U.S forward Mia Hamm said. ``In
'91, we played in anonymity and we won in anonymity. This year,
it's like ...''
</P>
<P>
   The attention, the crowds and the passion for this U.S. team
could be a sign that women's sports, in general, are ready to
explode in the next century. Or it just might mean that Americans
simply love big events, but will do little to sustain interest in a
fringe sport over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. coach Tony DiCicco said without looking to the future, one
thing is clear in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer is here whether you all as media think that it's an
American sport or not,'' DiCicco said. ``I can tell you that my
four sons grew up with it thinking it is an American sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only going to further ingrain itself into our culture and
into our society. And the women's side of the game is proving that
it is worthy of media attention, it's entertaining to watch, it's
skillful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women's soccer and women's athletics are here to stay. We're
just scratching the surface.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
