<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOX OFFICE THUMB PULLS PLUMB IN `PIE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``American Pie'' captured the biggest slice of
business at the nation's multiplexes with a solid $18.1 million at
2,508 theaters during the Friday-Sunday period as the coming-of-age
comedy edged ``Wild Wild West,'' studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The victory for ``American Pie'' came amid this summer's
continued strong pace of moviegoing, with eight entries taking in
at least $7 million. ``It's impressive for `American Pie' to win
the weekend because most of the top 10 films are also geared to
teen-agers,'' said Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source
forecasting service.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Pie,'' made for a bargain-basement $11 million
without major stars, benefited from strong reviews and a buzz of
anticipation that began several months ago. The movie, focusing on
a group of high school males who vow to lose their virginity, could
take in as much as $125 million for Universal by the end of its
run, according to Bucksbaum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not have asked for more from this tiny little
movie,'' said Universal distribution chief Nikki Rocco. ``Our exit
polls show huge across-the-board appeal and it should play well
throughout the rest of the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Audiences for ``American Pie'' were dominated by the target
customers, teens, who constituted 74 percent of all patrons for the
film. ``It's definitely going to cross over to date crowds and
older audiences,'' Bucksbaum said. ``The word of mouth on `American
Pie' is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry tracker Arthur Rockwell said Universal had been smart
to open ``Pie'' at a time when teen-age moviegoing is at its
heaviest. ``The studio has to be very happy to have performed this
well in such a strong marketplace,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of holdovers also aimed at teens and young adults
followed closely with Warner Bros.' second weekend of ``Wild Wild
West'' grossing $17.2 million at 3,342 theaters and Sony's third
weekend of ``Big Daddy'' with $16.3 million at 3,254 sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``West,'' as expected, lost 40 percent from the previous weekend
but is still performing solidly with nearly $77 million in a dozen
days while ``Big Daddy'' has topped $116 million in 17 days.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's fourth weekend of ``Tarzan'' finished fourth with $11.3
million at 3,131 theaters with business dropping just 19 percent as
it continued to dominate the family market and push its total past
$129 million. `` `Tarzan' is really showing tremendous legs,''
Disney distribution head Chuck Viane said.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's fourth weekend of ``The General's Daughter''
followed with $8.1 million at 2,710 locations to pass $79 million
overall. The mystery-thriller is likely to join the $100 million
club by the end of summer, underscoring the success of the studio's
strategy of counter-programming against the youth-heavy slate.
</P>
<P>
   20th Century Fox's eighth weekend of ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _
The Phantom Menace'' came in sixth with $7.7 million at 2,447
theaters, 181 fewer locations than last week, as the space saga
topped $385 million. ``Phantom Menace'' will probably pass ``E.T. _
The Extraterrestrial'' at $399.8 million for the No. 3 domestic
spot by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's opening of thriller ``Arlington Road,'' with Jeff Bridges
portraying a professor worried that his neighbors are terrorists,
performed in line with expectations in seventh with $7.4 million at
1,631 theaters, edging Paramount's second weekend of ``South Park:
Bigger, Longer and Uncut'' with $7.1 million at 2,128 sites and New
Line's fifth weekend of ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me''
with $6.5 million at 2,608 sites. The ``Austin Powers'' sequel has
topped $182 million, placing it 34th on the all-time list ahead of
``Liar, Liar.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney's second weekend of ``Summer of Sam'' faded quickly in
10th with $3.4 million at 1,536 theaters, edging Universal's
seventh weekend of ``Notting Hill'' with $3.2 million at 1,579
sites to push its total to $103.3 million. The Julia Roberts comedy
has become the 190th movie of all time and the eighth released this
year to top the $100 million mark.
</P>
<P>
   Although the slate took in a respectable $115 million during the
weekend, it still trailed the same weekend of 1998, which was one
of the heaviest ever with a $34 million opening for ``Lethal Weapon
4.'' The total for 1999 has now hit $3.3 billion and is about 6
percent ahead of last year at the same point. ``Overall business
has been very solid,'' Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Next weekend may also see strong traffic at multiplexes as
Warner Bros. opens the much-anticipated thriller ``Eyes Wide Shut''
with Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman in Stanley Kubrick's final film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very good timing to open `Eyes Wide Shut' now because
it's so different from everything else in the marketplace,'' said
Bucksbaum, who predicted an impressive opening weekend of $26
million to $28 million.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount will also open ``The Wood,'' a comedy-drama about
friends growing up in the Inglewood area, while Sony debuts
``Muppets From Space'' and Fox rolls out gator-on-the-loose
thriller ``Lake Placid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good diversity of new films, but `Lake Placid' is a
tough sell and it may get buried,'' Bucksbaum said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
