<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6415 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN--HERSKOWITZ-HNS &LR;      07-12 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--HERSKOWITZ-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE Astros, bless their ravaged anatomy, are thriving on the
miseries of life; or at least, not losing any serious ground. This
is consistent with the team's new war cry, ``Things can always get
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, injuries are part of the game. All teams have them.
You take the bad breaks with the good. (Fill in your favorite
cliche.) A few can get sick of hearing and reading about injuries,
except the Astros have had their share of guys get sick, too.
</P>
<P>
   They have been playing without two starting infielders, their
best outfielder, two catchers, one utility player, one starter and
three relief pitchers. Joe Slusarski, rushed from the minors to
fill one of their vacancies, lasted a total of nearly four innings
before pulling a groin muscle.
</P>
<P>
   So you can see that with only minor adjustments, the Astros
could field a team of disabled players, sponsored by their local
HMO. And for inspiration, they could call on manager Larry Dierker,
due back soon from brain surgery, and coaches Tom McCraw, battling
prostate cancer, and Jose Cruz, back after being sidelined with an
irregular heartbeat. The next addition to the coaching staff ought
to be a faith healer.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if the ailing Astros could throw away their crutches,
remove their casts and play, the season wouldn't seem nearly so
interesting. For sheer numbers, there has been nothing to compare
with it in Houston, and in the novelty category you have Moises
Alou, wrecking a knee by falling off a treadmill.
</P>
<P>
   The only development more puzzling than the Astros' epidemic of
injuries is how well they have coped with them. The Central
Division title is no longer theirs to win; it is theirs to throw
away, in sickness or in health.
</P>
<P>
   What do you suppose the odds would have been in April that the
Astros would reach the All-Star break in a virtual tie for first
place with a starting lineup that included Randy Knorr behind the
plate, Bill Spiers at third base, Tim Bogar at shortstop and Matt
Mieske in left? Forget it.
</P>
<P>
   But here they are, having swept the Kansas City Royals on Sunday
7-3, with the shy, low-key Jose Lima collecting his 13th win. The
Astros might have the best starting pitching in the National
League, and maybe the defense most likely to make the timely,
sensational play. In Bullet Billy Wagner, they have the closer who
is guaranteed to mess up the bio-magnetic rhythms of opposing
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   You get a sense of how the Astros' pitching staff has gained
respect when you note that three of them _ Lima, Wagner and Mike
Hampton _ are going to the All-Star Game for the first time,
joining the semi-automatic Jeff Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio's absence is a bummer, but he doesn't need another
silver punch bowl to convince his peers of his value.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros did not exactly step aside and let the Cincinnati
Reds climb unchallenged back into the pennant race. The Reds earned
their place by winning 10 in a row and performing better on the
road than at home. But the Reds rely on their middle relief to
carry them, and teams that can't trust their starters, and do not
finish well, do not tend to improve under September pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the division remains bunched, the closest team being
seven games back, but none shows any evidence of the right stuff.
What appears to be going on is a tense and shifting battle for the
last four spots in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros can beat teams in a variety of ways, and there is
always the prospect they will delight us with a new one. It is a
resourceful team, and a smart one.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting a 2-1 lead in the seventh, with one out and the
go-ahead runs at second and third, Lima struck out two batters
without throwing a strike. His pitches shimmy and shake so much, as
does Lima, that nervous hitters were swinging at pitches in the
dirt. As he crossed the foul line after the third out, Jose did a
graceful little leap, almost a pirouette.
</P>
<P>
   You could hear the grinding of molars in opposing dugouts all
over America. But Lima is clearly the Astros' most colorful pitcher
since the heyday of Good Time Charley Kerfeld, who once failed to
get the money he wanted from the Astros but consoled himself by
holding out for 12 cases of orange Jell-O.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Astros broke open the game with a five-run salvo
in the eighth. KC's Jermaine Dye misplayed Carl Everett's sinking
liner, made a desperate dive and saw the ball ricochet off the heel
of his glove and roll dead about 20 feet away. When the Royals
managed to get the ball back into the infield, they found two
Astros almost standing on second, a sight so confusing the second
baseman dropped the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Astros were making mad dashes everywhere, and with plays at
third base and home, the Royals threw late to third and everyone
was safe. This is part luck and part improvisation. This is how a
damaged team wins, the best cure invented for whatever ails you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
