<SLUG> BC-CAR-JIFFY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART'S LUCK (AND GAS) RUNS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
 LUBE 300-STEWART-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Tony Stewart's been here, done this. In just
slightly different fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, a fast-running Winston Cup rookie, raced several times
at New Hampshire International in the Indy Racing League. In 1996,
the IRL race was his to win. Less than 20 laps to go and he led by
a couple of laps. And then his engine broke.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Stewart had the field covered again in his first trip
here as a NASCAR Winston Cup driver. He came out of the pits in
front with just over 100 laps to go in the Jiffy Lube 300 and
clearly was the class of the field.
</P>
<P>
   He held off Dale Jarrett and then Jeff Burton and now there were
less than 20 laps to go.
</P>
<P>
   And then Stewart, with crew chief Greg Zipadelli calling the
shots, gambled. While Jeff Gordon, Jarrett, Burton and most of the
frontrunners slipped into the pits for a splash of gas, Stewart
stayed on the track.
</P>
<P>
   Zipadelli took the information he had from his fuel mileage
people and took a calculated risk.
</P>
<P>
   And lost.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart ran out of gas, sputtered down the backstretch on Lap
298, and had to limp into the pits to get enough fuel to finish.
Burton took full fuel advantage and zipped to his third straight
Jiffy Lube 300 win.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart finished 10th after a last-lap run-in with Ernie Irvan
and quickly departed the grounds without a word.
</P>
<P>
   Irvan said Stewart ran into him on the last lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he was mad at me or something, I don't know,'' Irvan
said. ``Tony's all right. I'd be pretty upset, too. He was going to
have his first Winston Cup win and it didn't happen. It's just part
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zipadelli, who is from Berlin, Conn., and cut his racing teeth
in New England, held court outside The Home Depot hauler.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great car,'' Zipadelli said. ``I feel like I let the
team down. We all make mistakes and we've made mistakes all year.
Today just feels like the biggest one.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news was the Joe Gibbs team had Stewart's car running
great and collected its 10th Top 10 finish of the year, maintained
its sixth spot in the points standings, and continued to run away
with the Rookie of the Year race.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's a Cup rookie driver with a Cup rookie crew chief, but
it's definitely a team on the way up.
</P>
<P>
   Which didn't make Sunday's end result sit any better.
</P>
<P>
   There was no second-guessing on the sidelines, said Gibbs, the
former National Football League coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision was made and everyone felt it was our best
shot,'' he said. ``We just didn't get it. It's hard to predict.
You're trying to guess what's going to happen with a mechanical
engine.''
</P>
<P>
   He never dared, Gibbs said, to think of what might be as the end
of the race neared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried the whole time,'' Gibbs said. ``Like everyone
else, I was holding my breath.''
</P>
<P>
   Compounding matters in the decision was that Kenny Wallace and
Bill Elliott and a couple of others had pitted at about Lap 208 and
thus were able to stretch their mileage and did not need to come in
for gas. Wallace managed to slip into second place and Elliott was
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart takes his 10th and moves on to Pocono in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was probably going to be a half-a-lap gamble,''
Zipadelli said. ``It showed up to be bigger than that. We thought
we were conserving more fuel throughout the whole run than we had
previously.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just one of those stumbling blocks,'' he said. ``I
guess we shouldn't take chances like that. We ended up with a Top
10 after going for it. We'll just have to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting at Pocono.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
