r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     07-12 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN ON WORSHIPFUL WAVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Maybe you bounded out of bed early enough Sunday
to catch U.S. defender Brandi Chastain on the television program
``Meet the Press.'' Your Women's World Cup hangover permitting, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain isn't the only member of the winning women's World Cup
team to go where politicians usually tread, merely the first. These
next few days you can count on seeing almost as much of the U.S.
team as you did of Chastain when she stripped down to her sports
bra after Saturday's glorious finish to the third Women's World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had Chastain's penalty kick settled in the back of
China's goal than the requests started pouring in. National news
weeklies needed access to the players for cover stories. So did at
least one national entertainment weekly.
</P>
<P>
   And every television talk show from morning to late night was
clamoring for the shiny, happy faces of U.S. soccer's summer
sisters.
</P>
<P>
   It is an awesome wave the U.S. players are riding right now.
Whether it tails off next week or continues building through the
Sydney Olympics next year, this much seems certain: there are more
waves gathering force behind them.
</P>
<P>
   If the thundering reception given the Women's World Cup in this
country proves anything it's that there never has been a better
time to be strong and athletic and female.
</P>
<P>
   In a society that has made no secret of its obsession with
people skinny and frail and female, the Venus worship of these
women of style AND substance is empowering, encouraging, ennobling.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the World Cup. Tomorrow, the White House? You'll have to
forgive women right now for feeling no goal is out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   Americans are a proud and patriotic people. We might not always
vote in numbers too great too ignore, but the roar that drowned out
the final bar of the U.S. anthem before Saturday's title match bore
testimony to our national spirit.
</P>
<P>
   We embraced the Women's World Cup out of love for our country.
It wasn't just our affection for soccer or the amiable U.S. players
that drew us in.
</P>
<P>
   If it had been only about the soccer, the enlightened crowd at
the Rose Bowl would have invested more emotion in Saturday's
third-place match between Brazil and Norway. The crowd of 90,185
looked on with interest but not much intensity as Brazil prevailed
on penalty kicks.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain, Briana Scurry, Mia Hamm and Company without the USA on
their chests would be like a penalty kick showdown to decide a
championship minus Michelle Akers. It's entertaining, but you can't
help feeling there's some spark missing.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the idea of a barnstorming tour between now and the
Sydney Olympics appeals to us. Why not pit the U.S. women against
foreign teams in friendlies in venues other than the ones they
brought to life during the World Cup?
</P>
<P>
   There's only one way to spread the gospel and that's by reaching
out to the masses. Which brings us to the recognized savior of the
sport, Hamm. The star striker was nailed to the cross during the
World Cup by a few people within U.S. Soccer for stubbornly putting
the tournament ahead of the hype.
</P>
<P>
   The nerve of her, forgoing opportunities to promote her recently
published book and declining invitations to appear on television
talk shows and magazine covers, just so she could concentrate on
beating Nigeria and Brazil and China!
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   In another era, people would have written songs lauding Hamm's
humility. Her reluctance to hog the spotlight would have been seen
as her greatest strength, not a glaring shortcoming.
</P>
<P>
   And now? It's all about athletes posing like it's 1999.
Self-effacement is nice, but self-promotion sells. It's nice if you
can undress the competition with your silky moves, but if you bare
your bra after a score or pose nude for a magazine, so much the
better.
</P>
<P>
   Before U.S. Soccer officials dare to come down on Hamm for not
properly promoting her sport, they should consider this: By
refusing to hog the spotlight she gave many of her teammates 15
minutes of fame.
</P>
<P>
   When Hamm wouldn't go on David Letterman, Chastain went in her
place and charmed the smug grin off the late-night talk-show host.
</P>
<P>
   When Hamm declined to talk to reporters, it gave us no choice
but to get to know her teammates better and share their stories
with the public.
</P>
<P>
   It's great when a sport's biggest star feels comfortable serving
as its lead ambassador, but not everybody is blessed with the
personality of a Wayne Gretzky or a Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The growing media throng has backed athletes today into an
impossibly tight corner. If they actively seek the spotlight, they
are criticized for putting themselves above the team. If they shun
the spotlight, they are called aloof and worse
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame, because there are far worse things than watching
Chastain parry with the pundits. Like China's goaltender Gao Hong
and the penalty kicks, they are seriously overmatched.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 0124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
