<SLUG> BC-CAR-JIFFY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACE A NEW BALLGAME FOR TEDDY 
</HEADLINE>
 LUBE 300-WILLIAMS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ He slipped out of the state trooper-green Chevy
and onto the start-finish line of the Jiffy Lube 300 to the cheers
of yet another crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stand tall, Ted Williams, stand tall,'' yelled one fan along
the fence at New Hampshire International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Williams, grand hitter of baseballs and grand marshal for
this NASCAR Winston Cup auto race, did just that.
</P>
<P>
   He puffed up his chest and with a big smile met his fans. He
took a breath and said into a microphone for 90,000 race watchers
to hear: ``Gentlemen, start your engines.''
</P>
<P>
   Several minutes earlier, Williams had been introduced to a loud
ovation, took a seat, and then shook hands with each of the 43
drivers as they were announced.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the gentlemen started their engines, Williams was
on the other side of the fence and high above trackside for a
television interview with racing announcer Eli Gold. But before
that, his son John Henry took him to the edge of the track for an
up-close-as-you-can-get racing experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was enough for me right there,'' Williams said. ``I was
starting to back up.''
</P>
<P>
   He only had seen racing on television, but he could, Williams
said, become a fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be right there, when they're going VROOOM,'' he said.
``Boy, it reminds me of when I saw John Glenn go up on his shot.
When you're there and you see that. I'd never seen anything like
this before today.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd impressed him as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder where all these people come from,'' he said. ``Boy,
oh boy.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he chatted briefly with Kyle Petty as they posed and
shook hands during the introductions and told him how overwhelming
the event was.
</P>
<P>
   And he talked of meeting young Busch North driver Kenny White
the day before. Through a connection made by longtime Williams
friend Dave McCarthy, a New Hampshire State Police major, White's
No. 9 race car is sponsored by the Ted Williams memorabilia
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about what I was going to say to that little
boy,'' Williams said. ``My first inclination was to say to be
careful. Then Ithought I'd tell him to do 10 races and I'd come
see the 11th.''
</P>
<P>
   He was, it seemed, a little nervous about the whole racing
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Williams came to New Hampshire Saturday, attended the grand
marshal's dinner that night, and Sunday was headed back to Boston
for All-Star Game festivities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
