<SLUG> BC-TEN-HALL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODRUFF GETS KICK BY BEATING CARLSEN 
</HEADLINE>
 OF FAME CHAMPIONSHIPS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ You can find any number of cleated scholars
majoring in field goal at the University of Tennessee, and earning
their keep that way. So why would Christopher ``Country'' Woodruff,
winner of the NCAA tennis title for his hometown college in 1993,
get the idea that he could do it, too?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just foolin' around,'' says Woodruff, who comes from Knoxville
and ended a two-year drought Sunday by seizing the Hall of Fame
title over Denmark's Kenneth Carlsen, 6-7 (5-7), 6-4, 6-4, on the
Casino lawn.
</P>
<P>
   He hadn't really pictured himself returning to campus as a
football hero a couple of years ago, but fooling around kicking
field goals with a pal nearly got him booted out of tennis for
good. ``My sneaker caught in the ground as I kicked and my left
knee got twisted,'' he says. ``I knew it was bad. Torn cartilage.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad enough to curtail a career that was getting hot in 1997 when
he beat Andre Agassi at the French, won the Canadian Open over Guga
Kuerten, and finished at No. 30. Surgery and a troubled,
longer-than-anticipated recovery dropped him to No. 1,559 in the
rankings as he began the long way back this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great to get back into the top 100,'' says the
willowy 6-foot-2-inch Tennessean. He arrived in town at No. 116 _
the low man on the champions' totem pole this season _ and departed
No. 90.
</P>
<P>
   Woodruff's forehand and long legs pulled him through a
serve-and-volleying duet with enough nimble shotmaking to keep a
sun-and-sea breeze-coddled crowd of 3,400 absorbed for 2:18.
</P>
<P>
   Among them a small platoon of Danes in viking-horned helmets and
flapping the country's white-crossed red flag was delighted as its
man, No. 109 Carlsen, progressed to a 4-3 lead in the second. As
the lone Dane to win a pro title (Hong Kong, last year), Carlsen, a
bony 6-4, was making his way nicely with net-skimming backhand
returns.
</P>
<P>
   Abruptly Woodruff's serve and forehand passers on the run began
to bite harder. The Tennessean, called ``Country'' by his fellows
because he's so down-home relaxed, went on a seven-game toot to 4-0
in the third, threatening to run the table as Carlsen wiggled out
of four breakers to 1-4.
</P>
<P>
   Then it got too tight and exciting _ temporarily _ for Woodruff.
With a service winner Carlsen averted a match point, got to 2-5,
broke Woodruff despite two more match points, and, at 5-4, clubbed
Country into almost another loss of serve: 0-40 and four break
points.
</P>
<P>
   However Woodruff calmed himself to serve big, make the volleys.
He whewed as the last shot of the match, Carlsen's passing backhand
was ``golly, long by a Tennesee inch, and that ain't big.''
</P>
</TEXT>
