<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUMBLE AT THE RAVINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There are two ways to view the The Rumble in the
Ravine on Sunday between the Dodgers and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   You could check the videotape of a fight that had more punches
than most Don King or Bob Arum promotions and surmise that the Los
Angeles Dodgers might have found a personality during its
15-minute, sixth-inning, wall-to-wall roll in the dirt with the
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it could wind up being nothing more than a spat at
recess between two frustrated flyweights.
</P>
<P>
   The tale of the tape supports the latter view. Seattle, armed
with two candidates for the first $20 million-a-year contract in
baseball, Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez, is three games under
.500 at the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have won four straight for the first time since a
five-game winning streak at the end of April, but they will pause
eight games under at 39-47, last in the NL West, and 10 games
behind the Giants. So it all could wind up being nothing more than
great SportsCenter video.
</P>
<P>
   But in a season short on good vibes, most of the Dodgers were
willing to consider the brawl a potential bonding agent, especially
since they also won the game 14-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' said Trenidad Hubbard, whose three-run double in
the sixth preceded the brawl and in turn led to his major-league
debut as a catcher. ``Something like this can definitely bring a
team together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You always stick up for your teammates,'' said Dodgers
reliever Pedro Borbon, one of three Dodgers ejected for his role in
the fight, ``especially when you see three guys ganging up on one
and so many sucker punches.''
</P>
<P>
   As brawls go, this one had stamina.
</P>
<P>
   After Hubbard's bases-loaded double made it 12-3, Seattle
reliever Francisco Rodriquez ran a fastball up and in to Mark
Grudzielanek. The Dodgers shortstop took a few steps to the mound
and extended his arms in a what's-up gesture. Rodriquez barked a
few epithets back, took two steps toward the plate, and everyone
ran for the dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   The players milled around for about 30 seconds, and it appeared
it might end there. But two Mariners relievers, Jose Paniagua and
Damaso Marte, late arrivals from the bullpen, jump-started the
fracas by jumping Dodgers catcher Angel Pena.
</P>
<P>
   That set off several brush fires. Todd Hundley took off after
Marte after seeing Gary Sheffield get sucker-punched. When two
Mariners grabbed Hundley, Marte then reached over and
sucker-punched Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Rick Dempsey finally wrestled Marte to the ground, where
Dodgers reliever Jamie Arnold righteously avenged the sucker
punches. ``I wasn't trying to escalate things,'' said Dempsey.
``But someone had to take Marte down.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Todd Hollandsworth was on the wrong end of a pile in
front of the Mariners dugout. Borbon pushed Paniagua out of the
fracas, only for Jay Buhner to jump in and throw a headlock on
Borbon. ``That wasn't me,'' Buhner told Seattle writers. ``It was
Steve Austin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have walked away,'' said Borbon. ``But when you get
hit, you hit back. And we're a family. Hit my teammate, it's like
hitting my brother or my children.''
</P>
<P>
   On the grass behind second base, Devon White and David Segui did
their best to keep the fight going. White eventually gave up the
chase, but after the field had been cleared, Sequi started running
his mouth again and players again ran onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like this can pull a team together,'' said Dempsey.
``We finally had a good series and I think this will have a
beneficial effect for us after the break.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson acknowledged some residual value, but he
was more concerned about the down side. Pena hurt his left forearm
in the fracas, Dave Hansen needed a stitch to close a cut in the
little finger of his right hand, and Hundley twisted a knee.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, Dempsey and Borbon were ejected, and suspensions are
likely to follow. The loss of Hundley and Pena forced Hubbard
behind the plate. Seattle infielder Charles Gipson also suffered a
separated shoulder, and Brian Hunter, who wore a footprint on the
back of his jersey, hyperextended his knee. Marte, Paniagua, Buhner
and Jose Mesa were the Mariners ejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had my druthers, this wouldn't have happened,'' said
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson. ``You don't want to see anyone get
hurt in a fight, and Pena may be hurt bad, at a time when he was
starting to take charge (defensively) and picking up at bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Pena had a full day. He was 3 for 3 with a walk,
including his second home run of the season, and he scored four
times, once when he tagged and rambled home on a popup to shortstop
Alex Rodriguez, who stumbled and fell backward making the catch.
</P>
<P>
   Pena's Cadillac trot and pelvic thrust after that home run,
according to some Mariners, was at least partially responsible for
the fracas.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the who, when and how, the Dodgers will at least
spend the next three days feeling they're on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends,'' said Eric Karros. ``If we go on and play well, I
think people will look back at this as a key moment. But we've been
in this position before, when things have happened and people said
`they're ready to take off.'''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, they're ready for the WWF.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
