<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 03:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6458 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     07-12 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE BIG GOAL FOR WOMANKIND
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  All over San Francisco on Saturday afternoon, exasperated men
who wanted to do some shopping were being dragged off the sidewalks
and into smoky bars so their wives and girlfriends could find a TV
and watch a damn ballgame.
<P>
   We guys will never understand why, on a perfectly beautiful
summer day, you gals would choose to be inside, eating junk food
and watching sports.
</P>
<P>
   This female bonding, frankly, we guys just watch it and shake
our heads at the silliness.
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened Saturday. Some of us manly men
noticed that the USA soccer girls are kind of cute, and we watched
and got sucked in to the whole spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of the kickoff, I was loudly criticizing the
strategy of the coaches and shouting instructions to the USA
players. Geezus, girlfriend, after you pass, break for the goal!''
</P>
<P>
   And this was the first soccer game I'd ever watched.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over _ and it ain't over 'til the fat man
(Pavarotti? Meat Loaf?) sings _ my newspaper instincts kicked in
and I wrote a headline:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hamm on Rye, &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Hold the Mao, &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; With a Shot of Brandi &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but the girls have a lot to learn. When Brandi Chastain was
interviewed on TV after her game-winning penalty kick, she froze up
and forgot to snarl and say, ``Everybody wrote us off. The fans and
media said we suck, but we proved everybody wrong!''
</P>
<P>
   That's what you're supposed to say. That's what guys always say
after they win a championship. They're pissed. Or they threaten to
boycott the medal presentation ceremony because they're not allowed
to wear their shoe company's logo. Or they threaten that they won't
be back next year unless they get a better contract.
</P>
<P>
   Brandi was way clueless. She didn't give us one decent winner's
cliche. She spewed out something spontaneous and happy and
inspiring, acknowledging her teammates, the fans, summing up all
the event's impact and cool-ness in a few sentences. I felt so damn
sorry for Brandi not knowing how to act like a boorish winner that
my eyes puddled up.
</P>
<P>
   I would say the entire event, the World Cup and the United
States beating China in front of a zillion fans, was a great moment
for women and athletics, but I know that can't be true, because
President Clinton said it was a great moment for women and
athletics.
</P>
<P>
   My wife was at a workout place, and the women gathered around a
locker-room TV to watch the finish. Kathy says all the women were
crying. Well, sure, they're not used to the cigar smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy heard one woman say, ``As a kid, I could never be anything
but a cheerleader. I've got two little girls . . .'' And there's
the scary part, folks: We're looking at a generation coming up
where it's going to be hard to put together a decent cheerleading
squad.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how far women have come: Before Saturday, the most
dramatic and inspiring moment in women's sports history was
probably the finish of the 1984 Olympics marathon in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time women were allowed to run the marathon in
the Olympics; it took them 88 years to convince Olympics officials
that women can run 26 miles without ruining their mascara. Twenty
minutes after the winner breezed into the Coliseum, a 39-year-old
runner staggered in as if she'd been shot.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriele Andersen-Scheiss, suffering from heat exhaustion,
seemingly near death, seriously, took almost six minutes to run
that last quarter-mile.
</P>
<P>
   She spun, lurched, momentarily passed out on her feet and
finally fell on her face across the finish line. Not exactly
poetry, but proof: Women athletes ain't no sissies.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, I swear, my favorite uncrowded jogging path was
stampeded by women runners.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, our girls kept getting knocked down and kicked around,
but they kept getting up, and did they look good? I mean athletic
good. They reminded me of a classic piece of sports commentary,
from the glory days of the basketball Lakers. Warriors center
Clifford Ray was asked what he thought of the wild-running Lakers.
He shook his head slowly and said, ``Legs, legs, legs.''
</P>
<P>
   I had a problem watching Saturday's game on TV. With no
commercials, I didn't know which beer to drink. And the announcers
were so straightforward and informative that I wondered why they
didn't prattle and overanalyze and ass-kiss and lame-joke like the
announcers do on men's sports events. It was disconcerting.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the game (is it called a game? match? tilt?), Mia Hamm
got loose and was flying toward the Chinese goal, and the announcer
screamed out a warning, ``Here's Mia!!!'' It was as chilling as
such calls as ``Here's Jordan to the hoop!'' or ``In the bullpen,
Eckersley is taking off his jacket!''
</P>
<P>
   As I drove over to pick up my wife at her workout place, I was
wondering if the big U.S. win would have any lasting impact. There
was some kind of road work blocking my way, a detour. Maybe I could
sneak through. Nope, a cop coldly turned me away. Man, I hate it
when I get Scurried.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 0334EDT &QL; 
