 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2556 -- July 12, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. INSTANT COMPANY Not so long ago, it seemed incredible that a
Web company could be born in a mere two years. But rather than
going back to normal, the pace of creation in Silicon Valley now
seems to be speeding up even more. Any Web company that starts out
today and takes two years to get up and running is likely to be
left in the dust. By Po Bronson. From The New York Times Magazine.
Full-length (3,500 words) + edited article available.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
THE LITTLE WHITE BOMBSHELL Manufactured in secret and taken in the
privacy of a doctor's office, RU-486 will leave the abortion war
without a battleground - and perhaps with a peace treaty in sight.
By Margaret Talbot. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length
(7,600 words) + edited article available.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
THE COLOUR OF SUSPICION The way cops perceive blacks - and how
those perceptions shape and misshape crime fighting - is now the
most charged racial issue in America. From the front seat of a
police cruiser, racial profiling is not racism, it is a tool, and
cops have no intention of giving it up. By Jeffrey Goldberg. From
The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (8,600 words) + edited
article available.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
EVEN I DIDN'T KNOW I COULD PITCH THAT GOOD Country music legend
Kenny Rogers, whose current hit is ``The Greatest,'' (a simple song
about a boy, a ball and a bat,) has written a special essay about
the lessons that baseball teaches young and old. ``The Greatest''
captures that moment in every kid's life when the game is more
important than the score. It goes beyond music and baseball. It's
about life.'' By Kenny Rogers. 1,000 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 5.
COLOMBIAN CRISES Colombia is worse off in many ways than it was a
decade ago. The country's violent forces - left-wing insurgents and
right-wing militias - have never been better armed and financed or
held more territory. Colombia's drug economy, with its pernicious
effects, is as pervasive as ever. And the government is running out
of options. By Michael Shifter. From Foreign Affairs Magazine.
1,500 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
MEXICAN NIGHTMARES As Mexico City sinks beneath a wave of crime,
the provinces smolder and drug lords send corruption creeping
through the establishment, Mexico's rulers seem more interested in
fighting one another than their common enemies. For the country to
survive as a democracy, this will have to change - and soon. By M.
Delal Baer. From Foreign Affairs Magazine. 1,800 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
FROM NATURE NEWS SERVICE (N/A France and Spain)
</P>
<P>
   A. New Tactic For Tuberculosis Treatment Tuberculosis continues
to infect a third to a half of the world's population. Whereas most
people who carry the bacterium do not get sick, three million
people still die from the disease each year. The current vaccine is
not very effective. Researchers have now found some success with an
experimental genetic vaccine against TB. By Hannah Wunsch. 600
words. (Embargo 19h00 BST Wednesday July 14.)
</P>
<P>
   B. Infertility Passed From Father To Son A specific cause of
male infertility - a small genetic deletion on the Y chromosome -
can apparently be passed from father to son when the child is
conceived by an assisted reproduction technique. By Hannah Wunsch.
500 words. (For immediate release.)
_____________________________________________________________ 8.
FROM NEW SCIENTIST MAGAZINE (N/A UK, Australia, New Zealand)
</P>
<P>
   A. Hot Iron, Cold Sea Exploding stars have left their signature
deep in the South Pacific. By Robert Adler. 500 words. B. Brain
Food Change your diet and it might just make you brighter. By
Philip Cohen. 500 words. C. Die, Boss Man Do you want to blast your
boss to oblivion? The ultimate revenge fantasy could soon be coming
to your computer. By Duncan Graham-Rowe. 400 words. D. Riddle Of
The Sands Deep in the Sahara lie vast deposits of incredibly pure
glass. Nothing on Earth could have created them. By Giles Wright.
2,000 words.
