<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, July 11, moved Saturday and are repeated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   (moved in the `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   LEFT-RIGHT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Liberals and conservatives as
strange bedfellows: Politics has long forged odd alliances but
there is clearly something significant happening to the national
debate when Vietnam doves morph into Kosovo hawks and presidential
front-runners rebuff traditional party militants to capture the
center when the nomination process has barely begun. Not long ago,
when people were described as ``left'' or ``right,'' liberal or
conservative, Democrat or Republican, their views on a range of
issues _ on religion and state, education, war and peace, taxation
_ could be inferred. That's no longer the case. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   FUGITIVE-FINANCIERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The tale of Martin
Frankel is already enhancing the lore of that most modern of
outlaws, the fugitive financier. There have been a surprising
number of them in the last three decades, with Robert Vesco being
perhaps the most notorious. And their stories serve as a reminder
that even millions of dollars of loot cannot happiness, at least
when you're on the lam. By Leslie Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   APPALACHIA-REVIEW (Undated) _ When President Clinton visited
Appalachia to call attention to poverty, his visit had a familiar
air. The Kennedys and LBJ had made the trip more than 3 decades
ago. But although some poverty persists, Appalachia is a very
different place with very different economic development needs than
it was in the '60s. What never seems to change is the mythology of
the place as the poster child for American poverty, an image that
persists, to the region's detriment and benefit, no matter how much
times change. By Peter Applebome. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVATE-SCHOOLS-REVIEW (New York) _ For many urban parents,
agonizing over whether to send their children to public or private
schools has become a ritual fraught with concerns about money and
fears that a public-school education is a sentence to a life of
second-class opportunities. But hard evidence comparing the
performance of public and nonpublic schools has proven elusive.
Now, though, New York state has released test scores that provide a
rare basis for side-by-side comparison, with surprising results:
There were only modest differences in the performance of private
schools _ mainly Catholic ones _ and public schools. By Anemona
Hartocollis.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-MILITARY-REVIEW (Washington) _ In the past decade, the U.S.
military has shrunk, both in size and weaponry. At the same time,
though, the number of peacekeeping missions, relief efforts and
other military operations has proliferated _ from the Persian Gulf
to the Caribbean, from Bosnia to Kosovo. Pentagon's commanders say
the U.S. military today is as consumed with ``operations other than
war'' as a much larger force was with fighting Cold War proxy
battles and preparing to stop a Soviet invasion of Western Europe.
The new assignments, they complain, are straining the downsized
military, perhaps to the breaking point. By Steven Lee Myers. WITH
GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-INSECTS-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ The last corner of L.A.
County's 4,000 square miles was recently declared officially
colonized by Africanized honeybees. Science has been powerless to
stop the bees' steady northward march from South America. But
Californians have reacted to this latest invader with equanimity
because their state has long been home to a rogues' gallery of
flying, crawling pestilence. By Todd S. Purdum. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-DRUGS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The suspicions also are
familiar. If an athlete does very well, or if an athlete develops
an injury of illness, charges of drug use spring up automatically.
This raises questions about the ethics of drug use in sports. What
is it, some ask, that is at the root of society's horror of
performance-enhancing drugs? By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   LAWYERS-CHARACTER-REVIEW (Undated) _ Character review is as much
a part of becoming a lawyer as passing a bar exam. The arcane
character-and-fitness process, unknown to most of the public but
hotly debated within the profession, is facing new scrutiny after a
drive-by shooting rampage last weekend by a disciple of Matthew
Hale, a white supremacist who had been rejected by Illinois bar
examiners on moral grounds. By Mike Allen.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-HYPE-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Ernest Hemingway
brilliantly cultivated his own elephantine public image during his
30-year reign as America's most famous writer. But the rough,
cantankerous Hemingway would probably have a difficult time
recognizing himself today in the hype overlicensed Hemingway
products, which reaches full-throttle this week in the buildup to
the centennial of his birth on July 21.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week, leading
with the pros and cons of swimming with dolphins, and the
possibility that George Washington fathered a child with a slave.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ALIBIS-REVIEW (Tokyo) _ Alibis for sale in Japan provide
bogus ``respectability.'' The alibi-ya are essentially conjurers
who help people at the margins of society. For instance, women in
the sex industry are frequent clients of the alibi-ya, which enable
them to tell relatives and even boyfriends about their fine jobs in
a trading company. The alibi-ya provide name cards, pay stubs and
an impressive position in a decent line of work _ all fictitious.
If a caller tries to reach the young woman while she is at her
nonexistent job, a polite receptionist will say she has stepped
out. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   TIBET-LOBBY-REVIEW (Washington) _ A behind-the-scenes look at
why the pro-Tibet lobby can be so effective in Washington. Tibet
sympathizers, who have included figures as diverse as right-wing
Sen. Jesse Helms and the Beastie Boys rock music group, caused the
U.S. to reverse its stance and come out against a World Bank loan
to China intended to help establish Chinese farmers on land the
Tibetans say is traditionally theirs. By David E. Sanger. WITH MAP.
</P>
<P>
