trip to New York at an upstate farm belonging to Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, a fellow Democrat who is retiring from the Senate next
year. He said he hoped she would succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   In her first outing in a state in which she has never lived, she
seemed to have nearly as many differences with her husband, the
president, as with her likely opponent, New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani. She declared Jerusalem the ``eternal and indivisible
capital of Israel,'' argued against proposed Medicare cuts for New
York's teaching hospitals and embraced a proposal that would help
dairy farmers but raise milk prices for downstate consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly she listened, though, and said more than once, ``Thank
you for explaining this to me!''
</P>
<P>
   Barak Takes Charge in Israel
</P>
<P>
   Ehud Barak, a highly decorated former general, took office as
prime minister of Israel with an absence of pomp. This is not
unusual for Israel, where there is something of an aversion to
standing on ceremony. But it seemed to reflect the long delay _
seven weeks _ between Barak's victory and his swearing-in.
</P>
<P>
   The elation of Election Day had deflated during the weeks of
political negotiations to form a wide, seven-party government.
Still, Barak gave an impassioned inaugural speech, in which he
re-inspired many with his pledge to march full speed ahead toward
forging a broad regional peace.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DEBORAH SONTAG
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt Drops a Nominee
</P>
<P>
   When Salam Al-Marayati was appointed in June to a congressional
terrorism commission, Jewish groups quickly protested. While
Al-Marayati is known as a moderate among American Muslim leaders,
and has built relationships with Jewish groups in Los Angeles,
where he lives, he also has made statements suggesting that
Palestinian terrorism arises from ``despair and suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt has withdrawn his
appointment, maintaining that Al-Marayati, who fled Iraq with his
family when he was 4 years old, could not pass a security clearance
in time.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAURIE GOODSTEIN
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Russia Gains Kosovo Role
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of wrangling, NATO and Russia agreed on a role for
Russian troops in the peacekeeping force in Kosovo. Paratroopers
who will make up most of Russia's 3,600 troops began arriving at
Kosovo's main airfield on Tuesday, following a tense weekend during
which NATO blocked Russian aircraft from landing.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have agreed to serve under NATO command, but they
can refuse to carry out orders, meaning disputes are almost sure to
arise. Still, NATO commanders believe they are the best hope for
convincing fearful Serbs, who have historic ties to Russia, to
remain in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVEN LEE MYERS
</P>
<P>
   Setback for Tobacco Industry
</P>
<P>
   A Florida jury ruled against the tobacco industry in the first
class-action smoking case to reach a verdict. Anti-smoking groups
said the ruling, which held that the nation's biggest tobacco
companies conspired to hide the dangers of cigarettes, could cost
the industry billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But the ruling is just the first step in a complex process that
could take years as more than 100,000 Florida smokers or their
survivors seek awards. Jurors will next decide how much in
compensatory and punitive damages to award a few representative
smokers.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARRY MEIER
</P>
<P>
   Capital-Gains Cut Is Sought
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans said they wanted to cut the top tax rate on
capital gains to 15 percent from 20 percent in the tax bill they
will take up this week. Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the
Ways and Means Committee, said the reduction would extend the
economic boom by stimulating more investment.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats objected, saying Republicans were cozying up to the
rich. Besides, they said, with stock prices having just hit another
new high, Wall Street hardly needs the stimulus a rate cut would
provide.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD W. STEVENSON
</P>
<P>
   Record Set in Mile
</P>
<P>
   For those who treasure the breaking of supposedly impenetrable
barriers, Roger Bannister will always be a hero. In 1954, the
Briton became the first to run a mile in less than 4 minutes, doing
so in 3 minutes 59.4 seconds. Now international track meets
generally bypass the mile in favor of the slightly shorter 1,500
meters. Still, the mile retains glamour, so there was excitement
when Hicham el-Guerrouj, a 24-year-old Moroccan, lowered the world
record to 3 minutes 43.13 seconds in Rome. Had he run that time in
Bannister's record race, he would have beaten Bannister by 120
yards.
</P>
<P>
   _ By FRANK LITSKY
</P>
<P>
   Summer in the City
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers were not happy. Too darn hot. So, being New Yorkers,
they thought: Let's sue someone! Then the idea wilted. But when the
lights went off in upper Manhattan _ among other things,
jeopardizing freezers full of Columbia University medical research
_ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani threatened just that, accusing Con Edison
of not doing its homework.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it did, maybe it didn't, but one indisputable culprit _
and it's Giuliani's pride and joy _ is the city's sizzling economy.
All those computers. All that information buzzing about. All those
air conditioners! Add a couple of 101-degree days, and it was too
much.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
