<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 08:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0782 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-INSECTS-REVIEW-     07-12 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-INSECTS-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALLING ALL SWAT TEAMS: THE LATEST BUZZ FROM CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the two decades since John Belushi bellowed,
``Your honey or your wife!'' as a corpulent killer bee on
``Saturday Night Live,'' those relentless, aggressive insects have
passed out of the realm of schlock movies and sketch comedy and
into the daily reality of life in states along the Mexican border,
beginning nine years ago in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, the last corner of Los Angeles County's 4,000
square miles was declared officially colonized by Africanized honey
bees, when a swarm was found lurking under the eves of a building
in the desolate desert suburb of Palmdale.
</P>
<P>
   Science has been powerless to stop the bees' steady northward
march from South America, and the sighting of a single swirling
swarm in a backyard tree can still prompt a brief mention on the
local television news.
</P>
<P>
   But there is nothing like the panic in the streets that
Hollywood's mid-1970s imagination predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Californians have reacted to this latest invader with
equanimity because their state has long been home to a rogues'
gallery of flying, crawling pestilence. This is, after all, the
place ``where bowers of flowers bloom in the sun,'' and that means
a motley chorus of pests the world over is always buzzing
``California, Here I Come!'' and posing new threats to the state's
$27 billion-a-year agricultural industry.
</P>
<P>
   There are thrips, tiny juice-sucking insects that prey on
avocados, scarring and discoloring the fruit so it looks like a
potato. There are olive fruit flies from the Mediterranean,
discovered here last fall, the first ever in California and perhaps
in all of North America, which leave black olives grayish-white and
rotting. There are red imported fire ants from South America, whose
mounds grow as big as basketballs and make it hard to move
harvesting equipment through orchards.
</P>
<P>
   And now come the Africanized bees, whose ancestors came from
South Africa and were released inadvertently from a Brazilian
breeding experiment 42 years ago. They have gradually moved north
and west, and recently were discovered for the first time east of
the Mississippi River, in Jacksonville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The bees are no more venomous than their calmer cousins but are
considerably more aggressive, capable of delivering 10 times as
many stings.
</P>
<P>
   In California, the bees stand poised to colonize the commercial
honey-bee hives that are vital to pollinating commercial crops,
principally almond groves. Because the Africanized bees are
unpredictable and harder to manage, they represent a threat to an
important industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do we have so many things blooming and growing together
here that don't belong together?'' asks Robert Page, an
entomologist at the University of California at Davis who has
helped isolate a gene that may make Africanized bees meaner.
``We've been a real cultural mixing bowl forever. Everybody who
comes wants to bring their favorite plant. And when they come, they
also bring their favorite plant's parasite or disease agent.''
</P>
<P>
   In this state, there is seldom a letup.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982 the state Department of Agriculture set up the Pest
Detection Emergency Protection division to combat an invasion of
the Mediterranean fruit fly, which attacks 250 types of crops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a long discussion about what we would do when there
wasn't an emergency project to keep people busy,'' Pat Minyard, the
division's manager, said ruefully, adding: ``We've never had that
situation. There is an extraordinary range of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Jennings, director of Pest Management Policy for the
Department of Agriculture in Washington, said he knew of no formal
ranking of pests by state, but that California and Florida, with
their warm climates, long growing seasons and diverse crops, would
be together at the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a pest unless it's doing something economically,''
Jennings said. ``What rises to be a pest is a direct function of
what you're growing.''
</P>
<P>
   For ordinary citizens, Africanized bees can be a severe
annoyance, and there have been a handful of fatalities, including a
72-year-old man who was attacked and killed two years ago in his
mobile home in Casa Grande, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Noise, like that from lawn mowers or leaf blowers, seems to
aggravate the bees. The Africanized variety will chase a human who
disturbs it up to a quarter mile, 12 times as far as the European
bee, and if you duck under water, it will simply outwait you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, everyone should just increase their awareness about
it,'' said Oscar Hidalgo, a spokesman for the state Agriculture
Department. ``There's not really much that we can do to stop its
flow. We live with a lot of pests that can harm you, sting you.
Awareness is the key.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, California works diligently to stop the flow of
pests that pose more immediate threats to agriculture, especially
the various fruit flies that love backyards and commercial
orchards.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, much of San Diego is under quarantine because of
Mexican fruit fly infestations, and big black and white signs
dotting the freeways warn residents not to move fruit from trees in
their own backyards.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, people don't realize the impact they could
have in bringing even a single piece of fruit,'' Hidalgo said.
``You shouldn't even take it off your property. If you take it a
mile, two miles to your office, now that's an infested area, too.
But it's something we have to basically use the honor system on.''
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, in the Westwood section of Los Angeles, 10 olive
fruit flies were found in a residential neighborhood, and about 400
have now been trapped in an effort to gauge the scale of the
problem over a 300-square mile area.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say it was the first-ever sighting of this pest in
California, though it is widespread in Europe and North Africa.
Unlike other fruit flies, it poses a threat only to olives, but
California is the nation's sole producer of commercially grown
olives, with a 1997 crop valued at nearly $70 million. Most of the
growing areas are well north of Los Angeles, but officials are
taking no chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' said Minyard of the state agriculture department,
``we're just trapping, trying to wait and see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
