<HEADER>
A6573 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-APPALACHIA-REVIEW-A     07-12 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-APPALACHIA-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPALACHIA: FOR BETTER AND WORSE, POVERTY'S POSTER CHILD 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl)  
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When President Clinton headed to the back roads of Appalachia
last week to call attention to those left out of the nation's
pageant of prosperity, his visit had a distinctly familiar air.
John F. Kennedy, Robert F. Kennedy and Lyndon B. Johnson had all
made the trip more than 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   You can still find many of the poorest Americans living in the
shadow of rickety coal tipples in Appalachian hollows, but
Clinton's visit, in fact, had as much to do with change as
constancy. Despite the poverty that persists, Appalachia is a very
different place with very different economic development needs than
it was in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   What never seems to change is the mythology of the place as the
poster child for American poverty, an image that persists, to the
region's detriment and benefit, no matter how much times change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always glad when we get any kind of attention, because
the region remains so misunderstood,'' said Jean Haskell, director
of the Center for Appalachian Studies and Services at East
Tennessee State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately,'' she said, ``what happens a lot of the time is
that images are so ingrained, we get, by definition, the same old
culture-of-poverty story. It's a very oversimplified view of the
region.''
</P>
<P>
   Images of Appalachian poverty go back to regional writing of the
19th century. But that image of a place ``below the bottom looking
up to see the bottom,'' as one local mayor put it in the 1960s,
took on particular resonance during that era, when the ills of
Appalachia became a prime spur for the War on Poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Appalachia still remains poorer than the nation as a whole, and
in forlorn coal mining communities far off the interstates, life
can seem every bit as dismal as it did 35 years ago. But, by most
measures, Appalachia is becoming less a place apart.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, 219 of the 406 counties in the region qualified as
distressed, meaning they had poverty and unemployment levels 150
percent of the national norm, and per capita income two-thirds or
more below the national norm. Today 108 counties are listed as
distressed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, 31 percent of the people in the region lived in poverty
compared with 22 percent nationally. Now the poverty rate is 15
percent, just two points above the national average. Once an
educational wasteland, the region now has a high school graduation
rate slightly above the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the region has not shared in the current prosperity. But
from the manufacturing hub of Tupelo, Miss., to the aerospace
center at Huntsville, Ala., to the glutted tourism scene in
Gatlinburg and Pigeon Forge, Tenn., or the booming retirement and
second-home meccas in Asheville, Cashiers or Highlands, N.C., much
of Appalachia is basking in the same economic glow as the rest of
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of the matter is the region has progressed
tremendously in the 34 years since Johnson went there,'' said Jesse
White, the federal co-chairman of the Appalachian Regional
Commission, which was established in 1965 to promote economic
development. It is headed each year by a federal appointee and by a
governor of one of the states.
</P>
<P>
   But the old images persist, and were probably reinforced by
Clinton's trip, a subject that people in the region view with very
mixed feelings.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, Appalachia has benefited enormously because of
its down-and-out image.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1965, the Appalachian Regional Commission has approved
spending $7.4 billion in the region, which covers parts of 13
states. Nearly two thirds of that has gone to build 2,400 of an
anticipated 3,000 miles of highway.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it is a short step or two from the image of
pervasive poverty to the stereotype of inbred, gap-toothed
hillbillies who, needy or not, are not necessarily the most likely
targets for corporate recruiters looking for attractive expansion
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to call attention to the problems to get the proper
kind of focus,'' said West Virginia Gov. Cecil Underwood, the other
commission co-chairman. ``But if you overplay it, then it just adds
to the morale problems and the loss of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   There was both praise for and skepticism about Clinton's talk of
new markets, investment and entrepreneurship.
</P>
<P>
   And a bleak analysis would say that, despite the progress, the
region faces enormous new hurdles because its traditional strengths
in natural resources do not go as far in an age defined by
microchips rather than coal mines.
</P>
<P>
   But both White and Ms. Haskell said that the trip reflected a
contemporary approach to the region's economic development _ more
focused on entrepreneurship and long-term investment than on
smokestack chasing or anti-poverty programs. In that sense, White
said, maybe the imagery of the region will finally begin to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very different trip than the one LBJ took in the
1960s,'' he said. ``If you remember, President Clinton's second
stop was to an electronics company started by a man who left the
region and then came back and created good-paying jobs. The last
thing we wanted was for the bad news of Appalachia to be the only
story that came out of this trip.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 0851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 08:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0788 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-PRIVATE-SCHOOLS-REV     07-12 0366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-PRIVATE-SCHOOLS-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
(Repeating) 
 UNDATED: private schools.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the high end, though, public schools did at least as well as
private ones. Statewide, 5 percent of private school students and
5.6 percent of public school students, excluding those in special
education, scored in the top category; in New York City, the
numbers are 3 percent for private and 3.5 percent for public.
</P>
<P>
   Some individual Catholic schools excelled. At St. Jerome's in
the South Bronx, 29 percent of the students passed the test, ahead
of all but one surrounding public school. Nearby Catholic schools
did much worse, with St. Pius V, for instance, having only 11
percent passing. St. Jerome's is one of New York City's poorest
parishes, where income averages $5,000 per person, said the Rev.
John O. Grange, the parish priest. Some students are the children
of poor, illiterate Mexican immigrants, on scholarship. But Father
Grange said most of the students are slightly better off than those
in nearby public schools. Tuition is $2,000 per child.
</P>
<P>
   But in middle-class neighborhoods, public schools tended to
outscore Catholic schools. In affluent Bayside, Queens, for
instance, 81 percent of public-school students passed the test,
compared with 60 percent in Catholic schools.
</P>
<P>
   Among the independent schools that took the test, variations in
performance discourage sweeping conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   The Trinity School on the Upper West Side was one of the top
performers in the state, with 98 percent passing, 30 percent in the
top level, and just 2 percent below standard.. At Manhattan Country
School on the East Side, more children scored in the middle, with
94 percent passing, but only 0.3 percent at the top and 6 percent
below standard. At the Cathedral School in Morningside Heights,
only six students took the test, indicating the danger of making
too much of statistics at all.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, said Diane Ravitch, a senior fellow at the
Brookings Institution, is that no one type of school is inherently
better or worse. ``You can't really make a blanket statement,'' Dr.
Ravitch said. ``A parent can only make a judgment about what's good
for their own child.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
