<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 08:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0791 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-LEFT-RIGHT-REVIEW-2     07-12 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LEFT-RIGHT-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN U.S. POLITICS, LEFT AND RIGHT ARE CROSSING PATHS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating) (The Week in Review) 
(bl) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bedfellows get stranger and stranger: Rep. Henry Hyde, the
anti-abortion, right-wing Republican, joins forces with Rep. Barney
Frank, the gay, left-wing Democrat, to curb federal power in
property forfeiture; Ron Unz, the conservative Republican who
helped end bilingual education in California, argues against school
vouchers in the pages of The Nation, a leftist magazine; the
Clinton administration fights its longtime allies, the trade
unions, over their support of steel import quotas.
</P>
<P>
   Politics has long forged odd alliances but there is clearly
something significant happening to the national debate when
give-peace-a-chance Vietnam doves morph into Kosovo hawks and the
front-runner for each party's presidential nomination slams the
door on traditional party militants to capture the political center
when the nomination process has barely begun.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, when people were described as ``on the left'' or
``on the right,'' liberal or conservative, Democrat or Republican,
their views on a range of issues _ on religion and state,
education, war and peace, taxation _ could be inferred. That's no
longer the case.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who tried for years to kill the federal Education
Department now want to be known as the education party. The
Democrats, whose long commitment to fighting poverty was evident
last week in President Clinton's tour of the nation's poor areas,
have effectively ended welfare. And the White House, sounding like
a group of Rockefeller Republicans, says a keystone of foreign
policy should be opening the world to U.S. exports and investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the big issues that used to divide the left and right _
the Cold War, inflation, crime, welfare _ have just collapsed as
partisan issues,'' said Francis Fukuyama, a professor of public
policy at George Mason University. Fukuyama predicted, in some
fashion, the current confusion a decade ago with a much-discussed
article in The National Interest magazine titled ``The End of
History?'' in which he argued that liberal democracy and a
market-oriented economy together form the only viable option for
modern societies.
</P>
<P>
   Fukuyama was dismissed by those who noted that history, far from
ending, quickly found other conflicts on which to focus: The era of
the angry white male in American politics, followed by the Clinton
impeachment fight, made reports of the death of ideology and the
end of the culture war seem premature.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some believe that the big conflicts are far from over,
that a vague and dangerous centrism has masked, not solved, them.
Republican conservatives, disenchanted by the party's abandonment
of the crusade against abortion and other matters they consider pro
family, said in June they might start a new party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relativism that is being so widely adopted may be the
dominant culture, but there is another culture that is very
uncomfortable with it and is resisting it,'' said conservative
historian Gertrude Himmelfarb, whose book ``One Nation, Two
Cultures'' is to be published this fall by Knopf. ``There are many
of us who are still resisting the '60s.''
</P>
<P>
   The traditional left is no less incensed by what it sees as the
nation's acquiescence to the Reaganism of the 1980s _ the end of
welfare, the growing resegregation of American schools, the wide
acceptance of the death penalty and the lack of availability of
health care for millions of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that the failure of communism has a lot
to do with the marginalization of the left,'' said Katha Pollitt, a
columnist for The Nation. ``But for me the central value of the
left is a commitment to equality, including economic equality, and
we have less of that today than we had 20 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, few in this country or abroad argue much any more
with Fukuyama's point about the centrality of markets to modern
societies.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Hue, national secretary of the French Communist Party,
which in the 1970s and '80s maintained a firm Marxist line, said
recently: ``The Communists are not adversaries of the market. The
Communists have broken with the statist vision of things.''
</P>
<P>
   The leftist governments in Britain and Germany are further
evidence of this change. When the Labor Party leader Tony Blair was
elected prime minister in Britain, a London tabloid ran a
caricature of him dressed in baby clothes as his Conservative
predecessor, Margaret Thatcher, cooed, ``It's a boy.''
</P>
<P>
   In Russia today, Communists are considered conservatives and
free-marketers liberals. In Israel, the group that most resembles
the founding socialist Zionists, with their frowzy clothes,
collectivist vision and unyielding dedication, are the right-wing
Jewish settlers in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   There is much talk among former leftists here and in Europe of
something they call the third way, or what may be seen as
capitalism with a conscience. But it is pretty hard to distinguish
it from the compassionate conservatism that serves as the rallying
cry of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential
front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while the eclipse of the left has clearly played a major
role in the shift, the demise of the right is equally significant.
Paul Weyrich, who coined the phrase ``moral majority'' in the 1970s
and was the godfather of what became a substantial political
movement, said recently that the effort had ended in failure. He
recently urged his adherents to ``tune out and drop out,'' sounding
rather like '60s-era liberals frustrated by the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he will not require judicial nominees to oppose
abortion, which had been a standard Republican position. Evangelist
Pat Robertson has said: ``There's no way that we are going to pass
a constitutional amendment banning abortion. It's just not going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, when Weyrich said, ``We lost the culture
war,'' he was referring to the fact that most Americans did not
view Clinton's extramarital sex and lies as the basis for
impeachment, but he was also casting the issue in larger terms:
efforts to expunge '60s-era personal morals had failed.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Wolfe, a professor of political science at Boston College,
agrees in some sense with Weyrich. He spent several years
interviewing middle-class Americans for his book ``One Nation,
After All'' (Viking, 1998) and found that most people are far more
tolerant of others and other ways of life than is often assumed.
</P>
<P>
   As Wolfe puts his findings now, ``The right won the economic
war, the left won the cultural war and the center won the political
war.''
</P>
<P>
   While most analysts agree that the nation seems to be entering
an uncharted era of consensual politics, they don't agree on why.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lind, a senior fellow at the New America Foundation in
Washington, has argued in a series of books and articles that what
is really going on is that a university-trained professional
``overclass'' has managed to suppress discussion of class conflicts
that are as powerful as ever.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the new ruling class, Lind argues, is increased
wealth and comfort for itself, and anything that interferes _ curbs
on immigration, labor or free trade, which would make it harder to
find domestic help and cheap employees and the purchase of products
it wants _ is opposed by all members of the class, whether they
call themselves Democrats or Republicans, liberals or
conservatives. Disagreements over so-called wedge issues, Lind
maintains, are a ruse aimed at making the rest of the nation
believe there is debate going on.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Postrel, editor of Reason magazine, a libertarian
monthly, has a different interpretation. In her book ``The Future
and Its Enemies'' (Free Press, 1998), she contends that the old
categories of left and right have lost their usefulness because the
world has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A defining question in one era _ whether to nationalize the
railroads, give women the vote, outlaw racial segregation or
abolish the draft _ may be settled and therefore meaningless in
another,'' she writes. ``Nowadays, `conservatives' may support
careers for women, and `liberals' may back the death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Postrel urges abandoning traditional political categories
and creating new ones, namely ``dynamists'' _ those who accept and
promote innovation _ and ``stasists,'' who favor a regulated,
engineered world. She clearly comes down on the side of the
dynamists, arguing that only through unregulated experimentation
will society advance materially and intellectually.
</P>
<P>
   With the explosion of information and technological innovation,
she argues, central planning bodies are impotent; only freedom,
even chaos, will do. By promoting such practices, she says,
societies will progress; by squelching them, they will go the way
of centrally planned governments.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a new idea but has come to a kind of fruition. Half
a century ago, conservative economist Friedrich Hayek argued that
socialism had no future because in a modern economy the vast
majority of information generated is local in character and
requires higher and higher degrees of sophistication to grasp. As a
result, distant managers or bureaucrats are unlikely to be
sufficiently nimble or informed to make good decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it is not only Soviet-style governments that have been
forced to undergo change but large corporations like IBM, which
nearly collapsed and has had to create more entrepreneurial styles
of work for its employees. With such a focus on individual
initiative and the accompanying access to vast quantities of
information, it is not surprising that broad ideological approaches
are losing out to a case-by-case, problem-solving one. Nor is it
surprising that with increased exposure to other people and ideas
has come increased tolerance and openness to other ways of life.
</P>
<P>
   Unz, the California activist who fought bilingual education,
says he opposes school vouchers because, while competition and
marketing may be good for selling sneakers or soft drinks, they are
bad for public education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call myself a Ronald Reagan Republican but I look at things
on a case-by-case basis,'' said Unz, a Silicon Valley entrepreneur
who is also pushing campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   It is entirely appropriate that Silicon Valley has become one of
the country's focal points because its arresting combination of
market economics and informal personal and social behavior _
Reaganesque politics of the 1980s and Clintonesque morals of the
'60s _ seems to define the nation today. Many had previously
thought the two incompatible. Sociologist Daniel Bell once wrote of
the inherent contradiction between the Protestant ethic of
capitalism and the hedonism it created. And Reagan Republicans
tended to think of their goal as reversing the trends of the '60s.
Yet many analysts argue today that the Reaganites accomplished
their own revolution without really shifting the society as they
had hoped; they may have curbed the extremes of the 1960s but much
of the rest has been absorbed into mainstream culture.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lilla, a political philosopher at New York University,
wrote in The New York Review of Books in May that the two
revolutions are coexisting nicely right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts are these,'' he wrote. ``The '60s happened, Reagan
happened and for the foreseeable future they will together define
our political horizon. As anyone who deals with young people today
knows, Americans find no difficulty in reconciling the two in their
daily lives. They see no contradiction in holding down day jobs in
the unfettered global marketplace _ the Reaganite dream, the left
nightmare _ and spending weekends immersed in a moral and cultural
universe shaped by the 60's.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 0854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
