<HEADER>
A6609 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN14-CO     07-12 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Scant repentance from Serb protesters
 &HT;    For release July 14, 1999.
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With each day comes new protests in Yugoslavian towns. The
protesters want Slobodan Milosovic removed from office. While that
may be comforting to the U.S. State Department and NATO, I find
something quite discomforting about it.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters seem to want Milosovic removed for the wrong
reason.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of one opposition leader at a Sunday rally in
Kikinda who told the crowd, ``So much evil has been done in our
name,'' the protests principally have to do with the destruction
Milosovic's ethnic-cleansing policy brought on his fellow Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Few, save the speaker in Kikinda, appear to be addressing the
real issue: contrition for what was done to the ethnic Albanians.
Rally after rally throughout the country calls for Milosovic's
removal because of the consequences of his policy.
</P>
<P>
   Among those joining the opposition are Serbian military
personnel, angry because they have not been paid. (Are these the
guys behind the gunsights in Kosovo?) Others are contentious
because of the economic collapse of the country and its
international isolation. Every once in a while, someone will utter
something about what brought all this about: ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take a rocket scientist to recognize that Milosovic,
while ordering the policy, was not the only person carrying it out.
Throughout Kosovo, thousands of ethnic Albanians were killed simply
for being ethnic Albanians. To do that _ to shoot or otherways kill
the Kosovars, to dig the mass graves and conceal them _ required
the hard work of a lot of ethnic Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   It took until 52 years after World War II for someone to write a
book about the role of ordinary German people in Hitler's
Holocaust, but one can be written right now about the role of
ordinary Serbian people in dealing with Milosovic's attempt to
clear Yugoslavia of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Goldhagen's 1997 ``Hitler's Willing Executioners'' would
be the model for ``Milosovic's Willing Executioners,'' because the
Serbs _ numbers unknown _ were just that.
</P>
<P>
   Serb troops and civilians turned ethnic Albanians out of their
homes, killed thousands, forced hundreds of thousands of others
across the border with just the clothes on their backs, and looted
or appropriated the property the Kosovars left behind.
</P>
<P>
   (Horribly, the ethnic Albanians, their country returned to them
by outside forces, have gone to revenge, duplicating some of the
atrocities committed by the Serbs _ this time under the very noses
of NATO. A confrontation between NATO and the Kosovar militants is
inevitable.)
</P>
<P>
   When Milan Protic, a popular anti-Milosovic leader, tells the
throng that as a result of so much evil being done in Serbia's
name, ``we have suffered a lot,'' he misses the point _ unless
Protic accepts some of the responsibility on behalf of the Serbian
people.
</P>
<P>
   Milosovic's Serbia has suffered from NATO planes, a consequence
of his policy but the ethnic Albanians suffered far greater
ruination at the hands of Serbian soldiers, volunteers and
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   It likely is impossible for Serb and Kosovar ever to kiss and
make up, and even if Kosovo achieves total independence, there
still will be a hostile border to share.
</P>
<P>
   But the Serbs, particularly those demonstrating on the streets,
need to come to grips with the fact that it was they, their sons
and daughters, who participated in what has been termed the most
horrible war crimes in Europe since the end of the World War II.
</P>
<P>
   They should be saying that Milosovic not only should be turned
out but that he must answer before a war crimes tribunal. Then they
should get on their hands and knees to seek forgiveness for
implementing his ghastly policy of ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   And they should be telling their protective Russian allies to
tone down the rhetoric against NATO because, after all, what NATO
fought against _ and Russia blindly supported _ was akin to what
happened to the Russian people at the hands of Germans in the 1940s
as well as via the blood binges of Joseph Stalin and some of his
successors.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
