<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Garage space: Real, rented, digital
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The first time I visited a self-storage
place, I was writing a story about auto theft. Someone had rented a
closet-sized storage locker and systematically disassembled a
stolen car to fit inside. It looked like an origami auto. A most
impressive sight.
</P>
<P>
   I think of that when I survey my own garage. If I could perform
a similar feat of compacting, I'd have room for everything.
</P>
<P>
   About half of it has been invaded by stuff. Random objects not
useful enough to keep inside, yet somehow not really garbage. Stuff
like my son's vintage computer-parts collection: a CGA monitor
similar to one I once saw on display at a museum, a casing for one
of the original IBM PC-clones _ like the ones the pioneers used to
pop buffalo-hide floppy disks into _ a docking station for a laptop
that hasn't been manufactured for half a decade, a Mac II ... . All
pretty much worthless. All so initially expensive I cannot bring
myself to toss them.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's the furniture that might just be repairable, or
refinishable or fine to use as soon as fashions change in some
breathtaking manner and avocado is rediscovered as a color scheme.
</P>
<P>
   And there are the boxes of stuff unpacked from past moves that
sit under other boxes like buried time capsules.
</P>
<P>
   And the old toys. Disposing of them is as good as admitting that
these teens will never be little kids again. Who is so heartless to
consign a My Little Pony to the landfill?
</P>
<P>
   And this is not mere sloppy living on my part. It is a trend.
</P>
<P>
   Garages and sheds around the country are overflowing into rented
storage places. These establishments are sprouting by the roadside
like mushrooms and gas stations.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than a billion square feet of store-it-yourself
storage space around the country, according to industry estimates.
That's a very round number, but seems plausible enough. There are a
lot of extra tires and promising furniture refinishing projects out
there.
</P>
<P>
   We have reached an amazing level of widespread affluence in this
nation if we are buying more stuff than our houses can hold. Either
that or grand theft, auto, is a far more widespread pastime than I
was raised to expect.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see this as simple greed. Not only do people buy
more things than they can possibly use, they buy more things than
they can possibly house.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the hoarding instinct goes beyond what you can buy or touch.
We now have the technology to be data hogs, virtual pack rats, the
digital equivalent of those old guys who die in houses stuffed with
old newspapers, copies of National Geographic and rolls of string
that ambulance crews must tunnel through with shovels on their way
in.
</P>
<P>
   Zip drives, Jaz drives, Clik! drive combine with monster hard
drives to allow us data storage of size once reserved for the space
program. To live a seemingly normal life yet squirrel stuff away
compulsively.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I look at this Zip disk, it's like going up into the
attic _ only without bumping my knee on a ladder or coughing
through dust.
</P>
<P>
   A Zip disk, the most-used kind, holds 100 megabytes of data in a
plastic square that looks like a slightly bloated floppy disk. It
holds about five times the data of a circa-1986 desktop PC.
</P>
<P>
   The disk lying here next to my computer holds my checkbooks and
credit cards activity for five years, six years worth of old
columns, three years of e-mails, drafts of letters and articles, a
genealogical program with data files, a few other useful programs,
a mysterious subdirectory marked ``Misc'' and about a dozen
photographs. These words will end up parked there as well. The disk
is not full yet and there's a blank one waiting nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Bit for bit, there is probably more primary source material
about my life on a disk or two than exists about Shakespeare, Jesus
and the Confederate Navy combined.
</P>
<P>
   This much data in the form of yellowing paper would take up a
good chunk of garage space. Knowing this, I'm not one to feel
superior to those who haul their stuff to some store-it yourself
compound. I'm their electronic equal.
</P>
<P>
   But at least I can still park the car.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
