<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small-town news beats the best politics has to offer
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ It's time for my take on last week's news _
however warped it may be.
</P>
<P>
   (SET ITAL)First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton(END ITAL) has just
wrapped up a three-day swing through upstate New York on what's
been termed a ``listening tour'' to learn about the issues and
interests of the voters, just in case she decides to make a bid for
the Senate seat being vacated next year by the retiring Democratic
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly dairy prices and upstate air transportation problems
loom large on the first lady's agenda. And what's with the pink
pantsuit and pearls? Dressing down for the proletariat?
</P>
<P>
   (SET ITAL)New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani(END ITAL), the
likely Republican candidate for the same Senate seat Clinton has
been eyeballing, in an effort to call to the New York voters'
attention the fact that the first lady has no roots in their fair
state, has announced he's going to go on a fund-raising trip, too.
Guess where? Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   This is getting funnier by the minute.
</P>
<P>
   (SET ITAL)Current first lady and possible Senate candidate
Hillary Rodham Clinton(END ITAL) is house hunting. Reports have her
looking at $5 million estates in Westchester and $2 million
Manhattan apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Say what? The lady is presently unemployed and even if she does
make it to the Senate, the job doesn't pay that kind of money. And
has she forgotten that her husband, who just happens to owe $20
million in legal fees, will be out of work in another year or so?
</P>
<P>
   May we assume land deals are out?
</P>
<P>
   (SET ITAL)Wronged first lady(END ITAL) seeks Senate seat as
therapy? New York women, occasionally referred to as a ``pivotal
voting bloc'' speak out on Clinton's possible candidacy. Most are
impressed with the way she handled Bill's bimbos and think the new
job would be ``good for her'' as well as an inspiration for all
women.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how I look at it, the idea of a trend toward our
country being run by a congress of wronged women scares the hell
out of me.
</P>
<P>
   (SET ITAL)The Clinton administration(END ITAL) has announced a
$6 trillion budget surplus over the next 15 years. Hooray! Now
they're busy trying to figure out how to spend it. Boo! Hiss!
</P>
<P>
   Why not send it back where it came from? To us _ the taxpayers?
And don't forget our interest.
</P>
<P>
   (SET ITAL)Al and Bill(END ITAL) are separating. Al's nervous
about having his image tarnished with the voters. Bill's fuming.
Tipper and Hillary are doing air kisses.
</P>
<P>
   Get used to watching everybody make nice in public but don't
expect to see them opening supermarkets together.
</P>
<P>
   And now for the rest of the news _ titillating but of lesser
consequence.
</P>
<P>
   Marv Albert and his rug are back in the NBC booth after being
fired for making naughty with a lady in a Virginia hotel room. (One
more role model in the sports world?)
</P>
<P>
   Michael Douglas is cavorting with yet another new girlfriend, an
actress by the name of Catherine Zeta-Jones. They're doing the
Continent and the British Isles. (Did he behave like this before he
played the lead in ``The American President''?)
</P>
<P>
   Alec Baldwin (another actor) has been spotted fat in the
Hamptons. (Apparently that's worse than overweight in Hoboken.)
</P>
<P>
   So there you have it, folks. A nutshell recap of last week's
late and breaking.
</P>
<P>
   There was a bit of good news, but it's all local. A neighbor
stopped on my porch to let me know that her granddaughter has
perfect attendance at school.
</P>
<P>
   Another stopped me in the grocery store to say she'd recently
lost her wallet uptown with a week's pay in it. Someone found it,
brought it to her, and refused a reward.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's the kind of news we all like to read. Why can't the
rest of the country be more like Gibsonburg?
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
