<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web destinations for vacation plans
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's hot, your nerves are shot because the kids are
home from school for the summer, you're broke and the air
conditioner is making a strange grinding noise ... it must be time
for a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   What could be better than piling the whole family in the car and
driving for hours or even days to a place that's even hotter and
that will make you more broke?
</P>
<P>
   Since so much fun awaits you, let's at least make the
preparation for the vacation as easy and inexpensive as possible.
That's where the World Wide Web comes in. You can take care of
almost everything while sitting at your computer.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start our journey at a terrific site called Travel Zone at
search
</P>
<P>
   .thetrip.com/. This site uses the AltaVista search engine so _
as you would expect _ the main advantage here is the ability to
ferret out almost any vacation-planning information you need.
</P>
<P>
   You can simply type in a word or a phrase, click the button and
get dozens of links to that information. You'll also find some
helpful links on the main page that can take care of chores like
figuring conversion rates for foreign currency, finding maps,
guides to cities and airports, and ways to find low-cost airfares.
You'll also want to check out the main page (www.trip.com/), where
you'll be able to rent a car, book a hotel room, and find airline
fares and schedules.
</P>
<P>
   There's also advice aplenty, including ways to find the lowest
airfare, the way to plan what the site's designers call a
``stress-free trip'' and how to decipher airline codes for various
cities.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe that's overkill ... perhaps all you really need is a
virtual road map to get you to your destination. The Web is crammed
with virtual map and travel route planning services. Here are two
good ones: MapQuest at www
</P>
<P>
   .mapquest.com/ and Yahoo!'s mapping site at
maps.yahoo.com/py/maps.py.
</P>
<P>
   Both of these sites work in much the same way. If you enter a
starting address and the address of your destination, you can get
both a map and printed turn-by-turn directions, complete with
mileage. In most cases, you'll find the directions good _ perhaps
not the route you would choose, but workable. However, as with any
other kind of directions, including the kind you'd get from a
friend, there is the fairly remote chance that you'd figure a
better way on your own. That's why it makes sense to take a peek at
the map for a common-sense check of the driving directions.
</P>
<P>
   So far, we've covered sites that offer most of the conventional
tools you'll need for planning a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   But for some people, vacations are true adventures ... instead
of lying on a Florida beach, they have hang gliding in South
America in mind. If you have the desire and the cash, there's a
nifty Web site that caters to unique vacations. It's called InfoHub
Specialty Travel Guide and can be found at www.infohub
</P>
<P>
   .com/travel.html.
</P>
<P>
   Simply use a pull-down menu to select a country or a separate
pull-down menu to pick an activity (ballooning, volcano tours,
mountain climbing ... if you can think of doing it, it's listed).
You'll also be able to specify a price range that you are willing
to pay by using another menu.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, keep in mind that for information about a specific
location or activity (whether you are planning a trip to
grandmother's or want to explore the Incan ruins), any of the major
search engines can be used. Simply type in the keywords of the city
you want to visit or the activity that interests you.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
