A6673 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAC-REPORT13-COX     07-12 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New TrueReality software allows full Nintendo 64 power
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Mac has always excelled at pretending it was
something other than a Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1990s, developers have written software that
lets Macs emulate the Windows operating system, Unix workstations
and the Sony PlayStation.
</P>
<P>
   Now a developer has come up with a program that emulates a
Nintendo 64 game player on a Mac. It's called Mac TrueReality, and
online reviewers are reporting that this emulator really works.
</P>
<P>
   True, the first versions of TrueReality were rough. They didn't
support 3-D graphics, for example.
</P>
<P>
   But now developer Niki Waibel has released the first new version
in four months. This version, 1.1.3, is a major improvement. It
runs faster, supports 3-D graphics and plays a greater selection of
games.
</P>
<P>
   A reviewer for the Web site Insanely Great Mac said he
successfully used TrueReality to play such popular N64 games as
``Mario Kart,'' ``Super Mario,'' ``Wave Race,'' ``Star Fox,''
``Bomberman'' and ``Bomberman Hero.''
</P>
<P>
   That developers are undertaking such difficult and risky
projects such as emulators is a good sign for both Apple and the
Mac. For one, it helps expand the Mac market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not long ago, people didn't even think it was possible to
emulate the N64 processor,'' notes Web site Mac OS Planet in a
recent review. ``But in almost a year the Mac OS and Apple have
made so many advancements that an N64 emulator is now possible.''
</P>
<P>
   While impressive, TrueReality is not as easy to use as Windows
emulators Virtual PC or SoftPC. The main problem is that N64
software is on cartridges and not computer-friendly disks or CDs.
</P>
<P>
   That means to play N64 games, you must first find computerized
versions of the software. Computerized versions are available _
they really are just the software sheared of the cartridge shell _
but they can be hard to find. The best place to look, of course, is
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you find, remember this: It's illegal to play on a Mac
an N64 game you don't already own.
</P>
<P>
   First, though, you have to get TrueReality. It's available as a
free download from the developer's site at mtr.dht.dk/.
</P>
<P>
   This site also has more information about TrueReality _ how it
works, the history of previous versions and what others have to say
about the program.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the site has some computerized versions of N64 game
demos to get you started.
</P>
<P>
   To run TrueReality, you'll need a Mac with a PowerPC processor.
The faster the better. You'll also need at least 32 megabytes of
RAM, Apple GameSprockets software and OpenGL drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
