<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    View of Atlanta's downtown available online
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of Atlanta's nicest views recently became a lot
more visible.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Dial restaurant, atop downtown's Westin Peachtree Plaza
hotel, has a 360-degree view of Atlanta. A while back, the hotel
started charging non-guests $5 to take the glass elevator ride to
the top of the 73-story hotel. The Web camera gives the same view
for free to anyone with a computer and Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   The camera is mounted on the revolving bar level of the Sun Dial
restaurant. You can see it at sundial.directsight.com/.
</P>
<P>
   To fix a faucet, go to how-to site
</P>
<P>
   If you're wired but don't know how to wire, Better Homes and
Gardens' Web site might be able to help.
</P>
<P>
   The site, www.bhglive.com/homeimp/index.html, is an encyclopedia
of home improvement and home repair tips, divided into five
categories: wiring, decks, plumbing, carpentry, and masonry and
concrete.
</P>
<P>
   The tips and instructions are adapted from the Better Homes and
Gardens how-to books. The Home Improvement Encyclopedia has more
than 2,000 pages of content and 53 animated demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   The site was ranked as one of the Internet's 50 most useful
sites by Yahoo! Internet Life.
</P>
<P>
   Bulk-buying discounts on brand names offered
</P>
<P>
   Small booksellers have found that size matters and have
struggled to compete with the big retailers that can buy in bulk
and sell for less. Now maybe you can get the same advantage.
</P>
<P>
   A Web site that launched last month, www.mercata.com, hopes to
bring bulk buying to individuals over the Internet. With Mercata's
``power buy,'' people can buy brand-name products _ JVC stereos,
Kodak cameras and Toshiba televisions _ for a limited time at group
discounts. Shipping is free, also for a limited time.
</P>
<P>
   Customers can recommend products for Mercata to offer. For now,
the site offers consumer electronics, sporting goods, power tools,
lawn and garden equipment, specialty gifts, and items for the home.
</P>
<P>
   Mercata's product line includes Baby Jogger, Braun, Bushnell,
Coleman, Cuisinart, General Electric, Top-Flite and Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Mercata, funded by Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen's Vulcan
Ventures, also offers customers a 30-day satisfaction guarantee on
products, customer service from 3 a.m. to 3 p.m. EDT Monday through
Friday and real-time delivery tracking.
</P>
<P>
   Explore our planet and all its many layers
</P>
<P>
   The Discovery Channel's Web site and the American Museum of
Natural History have collaborated on a site that explores the
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The site, www.discovery.com/exp
</P>
<P>
   /earthjourneys/earthjourneys.html, has features that let
visitors take a closer look at our planet. Peel the Planet lets
people look at the different layers of the Earth and find out how
each layer is formed and what function it serves. Click Through
Time lets people examine 5 billion years of the Earth's
development, focusing on high points such as the Ice Age and global
warming.
</P>
<P>
   Lovett or leave it: Finding right CD price
</P>
<P>
   The number of places on the Web where you can buy things is
getting almost too big to manage. And, unlike with the telephone,
there are few ways to make sure you are getting the best deal ahead
of time when you check the price of a CD or any other product
available online.
</P>
<P>
   One site, www
</P>
<P>
   .bottomdollar.com, works as a comparison shopper. Choose a
category, such as music, type in a singer, such as Lyle Lovett, and
in a few seconds the search engine produces several prices for Lyle
Lovett CDs and cassettes at several different Web sites, with
prices ranging from inexpensive to unimpressive.
</P>
<P>
   The site was chosen by Cool Site of the Day,
www.coolsiteoftheday
</P>
<P>
   .com, last week.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom Dollar's power shopper is described as a virtual Brillo
pad to scour the Web to get the best deal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
