<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SONY-PASSPORT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Photo system helps customers look their best
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Embarrassed when you're required to show your
passport or student ID because you despise that goofy photo? Here's
help.
</P>
<P>
   Sony has come up with a Digital Passport Photo System that lets
you preview and pick your preferred passport photo before it's
printed.
</P>
<P>
   Moto Photo Inc., headquartered in Dayton and America's largest
franchiser of one-hour photo processing and portrait stores, is the
first chain in the nation to install the new service. It's
available at five of the six area Moto Photo stores.
</P>
<P>
   According to executive vice president David Mason, the system
not only adds value for customers, but the storeowner benefits from
reduced paper waste and a lower media cost than chemical-based
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system also produces photo stickers _ a hot item with
younger audiences,'' Mason said. ``Photo postcards and multiple
reprints of all images can also be produced, creating a variety of
business possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Sony's digital photography marketing manager David Longendyke
says the traditional method involves taking a picture, pulling the
film out of the camera, waiting it to develop, peeling it apart and
then looking at the print.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point the store owner has already spent the money on
the film or the print and if the eyes are shut or there's a funny
expression, the store operator either has to take another shot _
which costs them money _ or the customers end up with a picture
they don't really like,'' he explained. ``If it's for a passport
they're going to have it for 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Sony's system allows customers to review and proof photos
electronically. The system allows the store operator to shoot up to
30 high-resolution images and preview them with the customer on the
camera's display. The desired photo is then printed on U.S. State
Department-accepted high performance laminated paper media in
approximately 90 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response has been great!'' said Scott Guyton, general
manager of Moto Photo at Washington Square. ``My crew loves it
because it's much easier to use than the Polaroid versions. The
customers love it because the color comes out much better and
because they can see it on the screen before we print it.''
</P>
<P>
   Price of the entire system is $2,500. Two passport photos are
approximately $19.95 at Moto Photo stores.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
