 ART ADV.: A photo with ALLST-FIDRYCH is being transmitted to NYT
Photo Service subscribers.  
 For IMMEDIATE Release   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following 1999 All-Star Game
feature stories Monday for use by NYTimes News Service clients. All
stories will bear the BOS designator and move under the Sports (s)
category code.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions, contact the NYTimes News Service desk at The
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-FIDRYCH (Boston) _ Since he'd thrown six no-hit
innings and wound up with a two-hitter in his first major league
start, Mark Fidrych metamorphosed from the kid from nowhere to
``The Bird,'' delightful alien from another baseball planet. By Bob
Duffy. (2 takes) &UR;  &LR; PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-WILIAMS (Boston) _ Ted Williams enjoyed the greatest
individual performance in All-Star Game history, bashing two homers
and going 4 for 4 with a walk and five RBIs in a 12-0 victory in
his hometown park in 1946. By Dan Shaughnessy. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-MOMENTS (Boston) _ Ted Williams provided the Red Sox'
most memorable All-Star moments, but it hasn't been all Ted since
the Sox first sent players in 1933. By Dan Shaughnessy. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-46GAME (Boston) _ Fifty-three years ago, when all the
players were white and most of the best ones were in the American
League, the All-Star Game came to Fenway Park for the first time.
By Dan Shaughnessy. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-36GAME (Boston) _ The 1936 game was the first National
League victory in the four-year-old competition, it was stained by
the strange sight of 17,000 empty seats, and it represented perhaps
the only time that Joe DiMaggio was ever humiliated on the ball
field. By Bob Ryan. 1800 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-DERBY (Boston) _ Home Run Derby, the TV show created
in 1959 that showcase the greatest long-ball hitters, is today a
full-blown happening, with crowds jumping, cameras covering every
angle, packed full of high-fives, chest-beatings, and triumphant
fist-clenchings. By Kevin Paul Dupont. 1365 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
