<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shopping online for auto insurance _ it's a good thing
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One Thursday night during the dreadful lull between
``Frasier'' and ``ER,'' I decided to see if I could do something
about my ridiculously high auto insurance. Back in the olden days,
I would have wandered out to wherever I kept my organizer and
scrawled ``call insurance companies about car.'' But given my
tendency to ignore most of the things I write in my organizer, I'd
still be paying many hundreds of dollars too much for car
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   That night I saw an ad for an insurance company flash on the TV
with an 800 number and an Internet address. I realize I could have
called the 800 number, which the company said was available 24
hours a day, but that just would have been another item on the
seemingly endless to-do list. However, my computer is conveniently
located in the same room as the TV, and I could log on and off in
time to catch the start of ``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet gurus say the Net is slowly but surely creating
more-informed consumers. With nearly every major carmaker online,
buyers are walking into dealerships more informed than they once
were. Some turn up at the dealer with printouts of the make and
model they want, complete with pricing for extras and estimated
delivery charges.
</P>
<P>
   When I sat down at my computer to shop for insurance, I didn't
head directly for the insurance company advertised on TV. Instead,
I decided to see if there was some sort of insurance evaluator that
would let me enter the types of coverage I wanted and provide me
with a list of companies that could provide it and at what cost. I
decided to go this route just to see whether the outrageously
expensive insurance company I had wasn't, in reality, one of the
more reasonable companies around.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance comparison shopping is available through the Yahoo!
insurance center, or you can eliminate the middleman and go
directly to www.insweb.com. Through a secure server, users enter
information about themselves, their cars and the amount of
insurance they want. The information is processed, and insurance
companies offering the lowest rates are shown.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about shopping online for insurance, a car, a
house, a mortgage or any big-ticket item is how much control the
user has over the information-gathering experience. When the site
asks you about your current policy, you can step away from your
computer and rummage through your papers for the document without
worrying about leaving an impatient customer service representative
waiting on hold.
</P>
<P>
   It's also possible to enter a user name and a password so you
can save the information you've entered. You can come back later
and not have to re-enter everything unless you need to.
</P>
<P>
   The other great thing about using the Web instead of the phone
is that the Web is available the second it occurs to you there's
something you'd like to do, whether it's checking out auto
insurance rates, buying a tie from Lands' End or reading that
newspaper article you've been meaning to get to. And if this is the
episode of ``ER'' where Carol is going to tell everyone she's
pregnant, you can just let the computer sit there and watch a
little TV before picking up exactly where you left off.
</P>
<P>
   Most Web sites offering insurance or loan quotes have this
feature, as well as a guarantee that your information is private
and secure. If you don't see a notice informing you that your
information is being sent via secure server and won't be sold to a
third party, go to another Web site or do it the old-fashioned way
and use the phone. The last thing you want is two hackers in Des
Moines knowing more about your financial situation than you do.
However, most reputable sites such as InsWeb, HomeAdvisor or the
bank mortgage calculators will have taken the appropriate security
precautions.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, I was indeed paying too much _ way too much, in
fact _ for my car insurance. Not only was I able to find much more
competitive rates, I could ask to be connected to a list of
insurance agents in my neighborhood who would contact me via
e-mail. In a few days, I received a note from the insurance agent
confirming the quote listed on the Web site. Now I have a brand-new
insurance company with reasonable rates and a friendly agent.
</P>
<P>
   I probably could have done the same research by calling
individual companies and asking for quotes, but that takes time,
the kind of time most people don't have. Lots of Web sites like to
say their goal is to help busy people manage their lives.
</P>
<P>
   To be honest, whenever people tell me this, I can't help but
wonder who these incredibly busy people are whose lives need all
this care and speed and hand-holding. But it's not really about
hand-holding time-crunched yuppies who want to check their stock
prices between power lunches, but rather about offering consumers
the option of getting things done in their own time on their own
schedule. As Martha Stewart would say, this is a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
