<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-SOCCER13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia girls gear up for next World Cup
 &HT;    By Keith Still
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you got a kick out of watching the U.S. women's
national soccer team play in the Women's World Cup last week, wait
until next time _ when some Georgia girls may have their shot at
the goal and the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The next Women's World Cup won't be played for another four
years. By then Alison Lovelace, 18, of Dallas, Ga., and twins Nancy
and Julie Augustyniak, 20, of Peachtree City could be vying for a
spot on the next national team. Alison and Nancy already play on
younger-level national teams, and Julie is an alternate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty exciting to think about,'' says Nancy, who admits
she's a little nervous when people say she or her sister could make
the next World Cup team. ``I never thought I would make it this
far.''
</P>
<P>
   The Augustyniak sisters started playing soccer when they were 5
years old. They have soccer scholarships at Clemson University and
hit the field for the United Soccer League's Atlanta Classics team
during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   They also travel all over the country to train. In February,
Nancy worked out in Florida, where she teamed up with some of the
U.S. Women's World Cup players.
</P>
<P>
   Alison spent the World Cup in Oklahoma City, where she was
competing with her Tophat Soccer Club team members in the Southern
Regional Championships.
</P>
<P>
   These girls aren't the only ones displaying fancy footwork in
Georgia. Girls' soccer has exploded here since the 1970s. Young
girls may start out on recreational teams, but many are moving on
to high-level competition within their leagues throughout the state
and even the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia has a lot of female players knocking on the door of
the national teams,'' says Jacob Daniel, state director of coaching
at the Georgia State Soccer Association.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the fields are overflowing with girls who could turn
out be the next Mia Hamm or Michelle Akers. About 850 girls don
shin guards and cleats during the fall and spring seasons in
Atlanta's Tophat Soccer Club alone. And Rick Skirvin of the Georgia
State Soccer Association says more than 350 teams of girls travel
all around Georgia competing in matches at the state's premiere
Athena level.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's recreational or fiercely competitive, many agree
soccer teaches leadership, teamwork and self-esteem _ and it has
great health benefits. It can also open the door to college
scholarships, where women's soccer programs are catching on like
wildfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all Tophatters that continue competing all the way
through high school get scholarships to college or use soccer to
help them get into schools that don't offer scholarships, like
Princeton,'' said Cy Strickler, founder of the girls-only Tophat
Soccer Club.
</P>
<P>
   But the important thing to remember, say Nancy and Julie, is to
play only if you're having fun. And don't forget about academics.
It's a fun sport, but ``soccer can only take you so far,'' Julie
says.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU WANT TO JOIN
</P>
<P>
   If you want to join a soccer team, now is the time to register.
Some clubs have already had tryouts, but others will be looking for
players throughout the summer. To find out about teams near you,
call the Georgia State Soccer Association at 770-452-0505 and ask
for a list of leagues in your area. You can also log on to the
Tophat site at www.tophatsoccerclub.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
