<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Students speak up on violence, videos, family
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ High school students participating in a recent
academic contest said they believe the family is the cause of _ and
the cure for _ violence in the United States, according to a
survey.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-nine percent of the students surveyed said bad parenting
is most responsible for violent acts in schools, and 36 percent
said the most important factor in reducing crime is the family.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty percent of the students said that violent games and movies
do not lead kids to imitate aggressive behavior. And one-third said
there was no need to shield kids from the games and movies.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two-thirds of respondents said the country's gun control
laws were too soft, but 61 percent felt handguns should not be
banned.
</P>
<P>
   Panasonic surveyed 171 high school students last month. The
students were competing in the company's 1999 Academic Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Landmark on the move
</P>
<P>
   The Cape Hatteras Lighthouse in North Carolina has moved from
its old perch on a badly eroded beach. It will take several more
weeks for it to settle in at its new home, 1,600 feet from the
rough Atlantic surf.
</P>
<P>
   Movers still must slide the 129-year-old lighthouse the final
108 feet of the 2,900-foot trip, then ease it onto rails over a
concrete pad. During the next two months, crews will build a new
foundation for the nation's tallest lighthouse. It's 208 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service decided to spend $10 million to move
the landmark before it tumbled into the sea. The move was expected
to take four to six weeks, but it took only three.
</P>
<P>
   China busts smugglers
</P>
<P>
   Investigators uncovered a smuggling ring that used China's
postal service to sell thousands of skins and other parts of
endangered tigers, leopards and cobras.
</P>
<P>
   Police seized a half-ton of animal parts, including monkey
skulls, elephant tusks and cobra and pit viper skins. It was the
largest such seizure in five decades, an official Chinese newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The smugglers used regular mail service to avoid border
controls, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Some Chinese use these endangered animal parts in traditional
medical cures. People in wealthy Chinese communities in Hong Kong,
Taiwan and Southeast Asia have bought many animal parts from
smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
