</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The scoop: News on Internet might not be fit to print
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Be suspicious of anything I say about newspapers and
technology.
</P>
<P>
   After all, I've been around both for a long time, and sometimes
a guy can spend so much time in his own back yard that he no longer
notices the trees there. But, given that warning, I'm going to stay
in my own back yard today.
</P>
<P>
   It's on my mind because a lot of smart people, even folks in my
own business whom I respect, worry that somehow the Web and all the
news sites there have turned the newspaper into some sort of a
dinosaur, doddering around on its last legs, dying slowly.
</P>
<P>
   The worry is simple and logical. In the old days, it was
difficult-to-impossible for individuals and poorly funded small
start-ups to create a competing newspaper. Marketing people would _
in their own jargon _ say that the barrier was cost of entry. In
plain English, it means that the cost of starting a conventional
print newspaper from scratch is so high that it creates a barrier
most people can't cross.
</P>
<P>
   Then along came the Web. All of a sudden, anyone could get a Web
site, put news on it and call that operation an electronic
newspaper. Instead of a big printing press and trucks to deliver
the paper and staffs of thousands, they needed an Internet
connection, the ability to type and some news to publish. And,
since defining news is like defining love (it is whatever it seems
to be to the person involved), that part was easy.
</P>
<P>
   So, understandably I think, bosses at newspapers started to
worry _ with that barrier down _ that the days of traditional
newspapers were gone.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, maybe you've noticed this yourself, but sometimes the
bosses are wrong. This is one of those times.
</P>
<P>
   When you buy a newspaper, you're paying for a lot more than the
printing press and all those trucks. What you are buying _ and I
know this sounds corny, but a lot of true things do sound that way
_ are the services of professionals with ethical standards. While
you may see newspapers as biased and often wrong (lots of people
do), you'd have to hang out at one for 30 years or so _ and I've
done that _ to see just how seriously most newspaper folks treat
their task of presenting the news accurately and fairly. They often
do it imperfectly, but the real marvel of a newspaper is how often
it is done right.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, as with airline pilots, lawyers and doctors, plenty of
mistakes are made, and there is the normal distribution of idiots
and jerks. But maybe that's a good comparison. While there are
undoubtedly physicians who are stump dumb and others who are evil,
you'd still rather take pot luck with a physician if you need
medical help than seeking out your neighbor who had just finished
the ``Brain Surgery for Dummies'' book.
</P>
<P>
   And now we're getting to one of my real fears about the Web.
I'll start by acknowledging that there are all sorts of wonderful
sites, filled with information you can access seven days a week, 24
hours a day. And newspapers aren't alone in seeing others step into
their traditional roles. You'll find information and advice for
law, medicine, fixing the drain in the kitchen sink and even coping
with your neurotic behavior.
</P>
<P>
   That scares me. Let's create a perfect world where every one of
these sites is manned by really smart and decent people who do
their best. Even then, if I had a serious need for legal, medical
or plumbing help, I'd call a professional. And, when you consider
that the world is not a perfect place, and that some of the bad
information on the Web is presented just as slickly as the good
information, well ... what a mess.
</P>
<P>
   The day may come when a computer can fix a leaky pipe, cover the
news professionally or create an airtight legal document. But that
day is not here. So, enjoy this new world of instant information
but also avoid the temptation to think that everything that looks
good is good.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
