<HEADER>
A6701 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A13-COX     07-12 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: The exterior of a black car parked in the sun
is hotter than a white car, but does it affect interior
temperature? Does the AC work harder in the black one, with a
noticeable difference in gas mileage? Is window tinting a factor?
</P>
<P>
   _ John Nemetz
</P>
<P>
   A: The air conditioner's effect on your gas mileage is minimal.
Purchase a light-colored car in hot states. Black holds heat; white
reflects it. Anything to help thighs unstick from the seat. Need a
big difference in car temperature? Buy one with a light interior,
says auto AC guru Eddie Creel of Nelson Automotive. Medium fan
speed (rather than high) lowers the air temperature quickly. Window
tinting also helps. Park in the shade and leave windows cracked
whenever possible. Car parked/cooking in the sun all day? Roll down
the windows for the first few driving minutes to let hot air
escape. What does this AC sage drive? White cars with light gray or
tan interiors. White hides scratches as well as dents better.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I ordered some Roger Bros. flatware in 1991. I built my
dining room and dishes around it. Many pieces have disappeared in
little hands. I recovered a few from the sandbox. It was ZIA
stainless steel. I can't find replacement pieces anywhere. _ Jule
Vigness
</P>
<P>
   A: This popular pattern is often in stock at Wilma Saxton,
stainless flatware replacement service. Call (800) 267-8029 and
leave your list of desired pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My father's brother, who no one has seen in more than 30
years, is the recipient of a part of my grandfather's (his
father's) estate. My father and uncle have been trying to find him
for months, but have been unsuccessful. The authorities need his
Social Security number to locate him, but the Social Security
Administration will not release it due to confidentiality
requirements. If he is not located, the money, now escrowed by the
court, will go to the State of Texas in seven years. Do you know
any means to get his Social Security number or another way to
locate a missing person? _ Bennett Brooke
</P>
<P>
   A: You can try a private detective, but you can also use a
little-known service from the Social Security Administration:
letter forwarding. Circumstances? It must involve a matter of great
importance, such as a death or serious illness in the missing
person's immediate family, or a sizable amount of money due the
missing person. Your situation fits. Forwarding letters with a
humanitarian purpose is free; a $3 fee is charged for others (check
payable to the Social Security Administration). Each letter is read
before forwarding _ so send it unsealed. Enclose nothing of value.
But do send identifying information: your uncle's date and place of
birth, his father's name and mother's full birth name. Requests are
sent to: Social Security Administration, OCRO, Division of
Certification and Coverage, 300 N. Greene St., Baltimore, MD 21201.
Q: I volunteer for a nonprofit organization and am involved with
hiring. We have just hired a new employee and used a service to do
a criminal background check. What are the guidelines on placing the
report in the employee's personnel file? If we cannot keep it
there, how do we prove a search was done? _ Doris M. Hug
</P>
<P>
   A: Oddly enough, the Fair Credit Reporting Act covers the use of
this information, and the Federal Trade Commission has authority. A
credit report is any consumer report used to screen eligibility for
a variety of things: to receive credit or to land a job. The
information you secured is for a specific purpose. An unauthorized
use _ such as selling it to another party _ is prohibited. I would
advise prudence and limit the access to such personal information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was outraged over the sentence of 20 years probation given
to the woman who pleaded guilty to smothering eight of her children
over a period of two decades. I'd like to write the Philadelphia
district attorney to protest. _ C.W.
</P>
<P>
   A: The prosecutor was Charles Gallagher; the district attorney,
Lynne Abraham. Both can be contacted at 1421 Arch St.,
Philadelphia, PA 19102. Part of Marie Noe's sentence is five years
of house arrest (with an electronic bracelet) as well as
psychiatric therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is a ``Cotton-eyed Joe''? I am not talking about the
dance or the song. In the song ``Harbor Lights,'' there are harbor
lights, in ``Harvest Moon'' there is a harvest moon, so what is a
``Cotton-eyed Joe''? _ Roy McCoy
</P>
<P>
   A: A person. The phrase cotton-eyed was used to describe folks
who had a condition that made their entire eye appear milky or
white, according to Dr. Francis Abernethy of the Texas Folklore
Society. Local retinal surgeon Dr. Armie Harper says the white
appearance may have been caused by cataracts or perhaps a corneal
scar. However, it was probably pterygium, a condition affecting
those who worked outside _ farmers, field hands, etc. Pterygium,
caused by overexposure to the sun and wind, covers the eyes in
reddish-white film.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to know the dimensions of the luggage allowed as
a carry-on. I know there is a certain limit at check-in. _ David S.
</P>
<P>
   A: The suggested size is 9 by 13 by 23 inches to fit under the
seat or in the overhead compartment, but the rule is a combined
size of 45 inches (height, width and length), says American
Airlines, whose weight limit is 70 pounds per bag. Weight limits
vary by carrier. (Hey, if you can't lift it, maybe you shouldn't be
carrying it on the plane). The limit of two carry-ons per passenger
does not include normal-size purses, coats or items that assist
those with disabilities. Grouse about passengers with carry-ons?
The practice allows baggage handlers to move checked luggage
quicker.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've finally found a solution for the mosquitoes that bother
us in our baby wading pool outside _ citronella tiki torches. But
now, I'm wondering if all the black smoke they put out is dangerous
for my baby. _ B. Rowan
</P>
<P>
   A: The Central Texas Poison Center says the smoke may irritate
eyes, but is not toxic. For safety, keep the center's number handy
_ (800) 764-7661.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My husband's source of wingtip dress shoes in a size 14 EEE
(black or cordovan) has been discontinued. After trying two big and
tall catalogs and several local sources I am at the end of my
shoestring! _ Laurie Stauffer
</P>
<P>
   A: Nothing worse than an unshod husband. Time to develop some
new mail order sources for wingtips: Reyers Shoe Store at (800)
245-1550 and E. T. Wright Executive Shoes at (800) 934-1022 (free
catalog). Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at
P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767 or e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
