EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, July 12, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Tuesday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HATE-CRIMES (Redding, Calif.) _ Jewish and gay communities are
facing new realities in the wake of the arrest of Benjamin Matthew
Williams, 31, and James Tyler Williams, 29, who authorities say are
the uncharged prime suspects in the July 1 slaying of a gay couple
in Shasta County and the June 18 firebombing of three
Sacramento-area synagogues. By MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   NASA-WOMEN (Elmira, N.Y.) _ Two women who grew up in Elmira,
N.Y., in the back yard of the National Soaring Museum, will take
their dreams to new heights with the next flight of the shuttle
Columbia, scheduled for launch on July 20. Eileen Collins, 42, will
become NASA's first female mission commander on the Columbia
mission while Dr. Heidi DeBlock, 37, is a visiting scientist at the
Kennedy Space Center. By PAUL GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MOSQUITO-BITES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Some people seem to attract
mosquitoes more readily than others, and health experts say the
attraction has to do with the amount of carbon dioxide that comes
through a person's skin. And that's bad news for active people. The
more you move around, the more carbon dioxide you produce. By
CELINA OTTAWAY.
</P>
<P>
   TEENMAGS (Undated) _ We have a proliferation of magazines for
teenage girls: Teen People, Latin Girl, Jump and, now, the newly
launched CosmoGirl, the little sister of Cosmopolitan. Guess what?
The themes haven't changed much since I was a teen. CosmoGirl's
pages are filled with advice on: how to get rid of pimples, why the
newest rock star is the coolest thing on wheels, how to avoid
geekdom by buying hip clothes and, once again, how to get a
boyfriend. By JANE GANAHL.
</P>
<P>
   PARK-DIG (San Francisco) _ Old harnesses, cartridges, insignia,
cracked regimental crockery, buckles, shoe polish cans, broken
tools, even peach pits, coconuts and soup bones _ they're all among
the artifacts turned up in excavating a century-old army dump now
being restored to its prehistoric condition of tidal marsh. By ERIC
BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH (San Francisco) _ A dramatic increase in reliance on
genetic engineering may be helping produce bumper crops, but it
also is raising concern that labeling laws are weak and that too
little is known about potential effects on humans and the
environment. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   CHEVRON (San Francisco) _ These are heady times in the oil
industry, what with the whiplash of merger, crude oil prices on a
rebound after bottoming out near $10 a barrel last year, and the
wail of consumers pierced by price spikes at the corner service
station. It's been a particularly wild ride at San Francisco-based
Chevron Corp. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-PIE (Undated) _ ``American Pie'' is a movie about
young male virgins who really, really, really, really want to have
sex. Really. This means its subject matter and pronounced
hubba-hubba content will strike the viewer in one of two ways: a)
dead accurate and insanely funny; or b) irrelevant to one's own
adolescent experience. But Boys will be boys, and then some. By AMY
BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL (Montreal) _ Though it's just a short distance from the
U.S. border, it doesn't take long to realize that Montreal is truly
a different world. Not only are there plenty of things to do in
this plucky city, the strength of the U.S. dollar makes this a very
affordable getaway spot. By TIM REYNOLDS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-HOMER-KING (Roswell, N.M.) _ In one special season with the
Roswell Rockets in 1954, Joe Bauman set the single-season record
for hitting home runs. Even after the assaults by Mark McGwire and
Sammy Sosa last year, Bauman's record remains a standard for any
professional baseball league. By TIM GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-GAMBLING (Berkeley, Calif.) _ Eric already had passed
through Gamblers Anonymous by the time he arrived at the University
of California at Berkeley. His parents placed him in the program
during his senior year of high school, after discovering he
frittered away a $5,000 savings account by placing sports bets with
a bookie. By MARK FAINARU-WADA.
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLING-BOOKIE (Berkeley, Calif.) _ For a bookie to set up shop
on a college campus is hardly an elaborate production. All it takes
is a phone line, word of mouth, access to the latest odds and,
perhaps more than anything, some organizational skills. By MARK
FAINARU-WADA.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ In the aftermath of last
week's revelation about the off-limits Crystal Springs Watershed _
that there are eight homes lived in nearly rent-free by employees
and supervisors of the San Francisco Water Department _ other
prominent water agencies around the Bay Area said such a thing
would never be permitted on their lands. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ What if Europeans had settled the
West Coast before the East Coast? That was the question raised by a
friend, and his guess was that they never would have left
California. No one would have crossed the desert to a land of
humidity and slush, just to find Guldens in them thar Coney dogs.
We'd never have learned what lousy pastrami we have here. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ When I first heard that
Louisiana will require kindergarten through fifth grade public
school students to call their teachers ``Sir'' or ``Ma'am'' _ and
put courtesy titles before the adults' names _ I thought it was an
OK idea but no big deal. Then I started thinking: The whole nation
really does have a respect problem. Not just with kids in public
schools, but with most people. In most places. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH (San Francisco) _ Death is making a remarkable comeback,
all things considered. Life should be doing half so well. Dying,
according to informed sources, has had a bum rap and isn't nearly
as negative an experience as previously imagined _ good news for
the middle-aged. There was a day, within my own time line, when
dying was something people avoided until the very last moment, but
things have taken a turn for the better, kick-the- bucket-wise. By
GERALD NACHMAN.
</P>
