<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6714 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV18-NY     07-12 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLECISMS, GAFFES AND BOO-BOOS GET THEIR AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 18)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics. Double parentheses
should be set as brackets.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The moment has arrived for our annual coveted Bloopie Awards.
Note how the adjective  &UR; coveted &LR;  (from  &UR; cupidus &LR; , ``desirable,''
its heart penetrated by Cupid's arrow) is wedded to the proper noun
 &UR; Bloopie &LR;  (from  &UR; blooper &LR; , an  &UR; oops &LR;  sound influenced by  &UR; blunder &LR; ,
originally a baseball term for a ball looped by the batter just
beyond the infield, and if not caught synonymous with  &UR; Texas
leaguer &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   Jamming words together, with the second word capitalized in lieu
of a space separation (you hear this,  &UR; TimeWarner &LR; ,
 &UR; DaimlerChrysler &LR;  and  &UR; PricewaterhouseCoopers &LR; ?), is the ultimate
symbol of merger used by giant corporations eager to get really
close. And because  &UR; coveted &LR;  is most often married to any award,
why not the covetedBloopie Awards for solecisms in advertising
copy?
</P>
<P>
   The envelopes, please.
</P>
<P>
   A triple Bloopie to Motorola, for its ``Digital DNA'' ad in
Newsweek and The New Yorker, showing an unhelpful repairman with
the name tag ``Earl'' sitting next to an unused phone. (No, not the
Maytag man; Motorola stole the idea.) The caption reads, `` &UR; Who'd
of thought that an electronic chip inside your car could help you
avoid curbs, other cars, and best of all, Earl in repair. &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Allen, the literate comedian, sent me a copy of a note he
shot off to Christopher Galvin, boss of Motorola. ``Question: At
the advertising agency that placed this ad for you was there
literally no one in a position of authority aware of the fact that
the phrase `would of' is grammatically unjustified and that the
correct version is `would have' or `would've'?''
</P>
<P>
   The pronunciation of contractions is called verbal reduction.
(Why? I dunno, but ommina find out.) If spoken in jest, a
dialectical  &UR; who'd a thunk &LR;  would have worked, and so woulda  &UR; who
woulda thought &LR;  (as in  &UR; woulda-coulda-shoulda &LR; ). But to write  &UR; of &LR; 
to express the contraction  &UR; 've &LR;  is a solecism.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the half of it. As Harvey Phillips of New York
points out, Motorola's sentence has three errors; its digital DNA
is all thumbs. The second is a misplaced comma: In  &UR; avoid curbs,
other cars, and best of all, Earl in repair &LR;  we have a series. As
the Times stylebook says, ``In general, do not use a comma before
 &UR; and &LR;  in a series.'' (Strunk and White disagree, citing  &UR; red,
white, and blue &LR; , but theirs is a little book.)
</P>
<P>
   Even if you accept as correct a serial comma after the
next-to-last item in a series, I think it is a mistake to write
 &UR; curbs, other cars, and best of all, Earl in repair. &LR;  The
interjected  &UR; best of all &LR;  should stand alone, separated from the
rest of the sentence by commas, dashes or parentheses. Thus, the
punctuation should be  &UR; curbs, other cars and, best of all, Earl in
repair &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in this triple-helixed DNA of error, let's look at the
Motorola  &UR; Who'd of thought &LR;  sentence in its totality, as Grace
Thaler of Boston suggests. It's a question. How do you punctuate a
question? With a question mark, not with a period.
</P>
<P>
   The chagrined but good-humored CEO, Galvin (let's face it, what
happened to Coke in Belgium was worse), wrote back to Steve Allen,
who caught only one of the errors: ``Couldn't agree more! It was
stupid. We pulled the ad series.''
</P>
<P>
   And now to the ``There's No  &UR; Their &LR;  There'' Bloopie, named after
the Oakland Mayor Jerry Brown's campaign against Gertrude Stein's
municipal slur. (Brown is a brown is a brown.)
</P>
<P>
   In an ad by Crystal Cruises in The New Yorker, we read, `` &UR; A
different writer, editor, or cartoonist from The New Yorker will
join us for each segment, offering their thoughts and observations
through on-board discussions. &LR; '' ``Alas,'' writes Sharon King Hoge
of New York, ``where are the fact checkers?'' (She means copy
editors; fact checkers are in a lower pay grade.)
</P>
<P>
   A horror of seeming sexist forces some writers into the
improperly disagreeing use of the nonspecific plural pronoun. `` &UR; A
different writer, editor, or cartoonist &LR;  ((they go for the Strunk
advice on serial commas, not mine)) ...  &UR; offering their thoughts &LR; ''
is a mistake. The subject is singular ( &UR; a different writer &LR; , not
 &UR; different writers &LR; ), and the agreeing pronoun should be  &UR; his, her &LR; 
or the tedious  &UR; his or her &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   One solution is to make the subject plural:  &UR; Different writers, &LR; 
etc. ...  &UR; offering their thoughts &LR; , but that would commit the
cruise line to dragging more than one writer out of the ship's bar
to each segment. The best formulation: Get rid of the  &UR; their &LR; 
there. Thus: ``A different writer ... will join us ... offering
thoughts and observations.''
</P>
<P>
   Runner-up in this category is Chivas Regal Scotch whisky (Chivas
comes from the old Gaelic  &UR; seimh as, &LR;  ``a narrow place,'' and is
the name of the distillery's founders), for `` &UR; Some are born with a
silver spoon in their mouth &LR; .'' As Michael Stronger of Brooklyn
notes,  &UR; Some &LR; , construed as plural (``Some are''), agrees with
 &UR; their &LR; , but leaves one spoon in one mouth. To the sound of
``oom-pah-pah,'' say ``Some are born with silver  &UR; spoons &LR;  in their
 &UR; mouths &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   The Veddy Veddy Wrong Use of Latin covetedBloopie to
Bloomingdale's for advertising `` &UR; Veni-Vedi-Vici &LR; '' (``I Came, I
Saw, I Conquered'') cuff links.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe the historian Suetonius, Julius Caesar succinctly
summed up his Pontic triumph with the alliterative `` &UR; Veni, vidi,
vici &LR; ,'' with the  &UR; V &LR;  pronounced as  &UR; W &LR; . That middle V-word is the
Latin  &UR; vidi &LR; , from the root  &UR; videre &LR; , ``to see,'' and is not
 &UR; vedi &LR; , from the Bloomingdale's copy department, rooted in error.
(I never took Latin, but am told that  &UR; vidi &LR;  is in the first-person
singular perfect active indicative, and sounds like one flake of
the Breakfast of Champions.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a covetedBloopie to Columbia House, the Squad Squad's
favorite home video mail-order company: ``Each video contains two
1-hour episodes on each video.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 1120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
