<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6749 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-PIE-HNS &LR;      07-12 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-PIE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOYS GO FOR THEIR SLICE IN `AMERICAN PIE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apple pie will never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   Why, we can't say. It would ruin the surprise. It would ruin
your appetite. More to the point, it would strain the bounds of
good taste in a family newspaper, which is loathe to describe in
detail any unorthodox sex act performed by hormonally over-equipped
teen-age boys.
</P>
<P>
   So you'd better use your imagination, because ``American Pie''
does not. Nothing in this gleeful ode to testosterone is underdrawn
_ no primal urge of the pubescent male, no graphic description, no
powerfully revolting joke. Besides Mom's apple pie, other mundane
objects newly minted as nauseating plot devices (or sex tools, or
both) include tube socks, laxatives, beer and a flute. The flute
incident is only alluded to, but the beer, laxatives and tube socks
all take turns holding the spotlight. Among other things. Ahem.
</P>
<P>
   All throat-clearing aside, ``American Pie'' is a movie about
young male virgins who really, really, really, really want to have
sex. Really. This means its subject matter and pronounced
hubba-hubba content will strike the viewer in one of two ways: a)
dead accurate and insanely funny; or b) irrelevant to one's own
adolescent experience.
</P>
<P>
   This particular critic, having never been a teen-age boy, must
confess to falling into the second category of reactions. This
particular critic must also confess to laughing anyway. Sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of ``American Pie'' are four desperate high school
seniors: Jim (Jason Biggs), a good-natured kid with no love life;
Finch (Eddie Kaye Thomas), a brandy-snifting sophisticate with no
love life; Oz (Chris Klein), a lacrosse star who looks and sounds
like Keanu Reeves but still has no love life; and Kevin (Thomas Ian
Nicholas), who has a love life but thus far hasn't persuaded his
girlfriend, Vicky (Tara Reid), to have sex. (In truth, they have
plenty of sex they just don't have intercourse. Apparently Kevin
and Vicky watched the impeachment trial.)
</P>
<P>
   Together, this foursome of frustrated masculinity makes a solemn
pact: They vow to lose their virginity before they graduate. ``This
is our very manhood at stake!'' quoth Kevin, in an impassioned bit
of speechifying. ``Yes, we will make a stand! We will succeed!''
</P>
<P>
   Thus inspired, each member of the quartet chooses a strategy.
Kevin turns up the heat on Vicky. Jim sets his sights on Nadia
(Shannon Elizabeth), a Czech exchange student. Finch pays a friend
(the ever-worldly Natasha Lyonne) to spread rumors about his
manhood. Oz, going ``sensitive,'' joins a choral group, where he
meets a Heather Graham lookalike named, umm, Heather (Mena Suvari).
The ensuing mishaps unfold with unwavering crudity and mostly good
humor, although an episode involving Internet voyeurism goes way
past the point of innocent fun; peeping Toms have gone techno.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Pie'' is the brainchild of brothers Chris and Paul
Weitz, a first-time producer and director who together wrote the
screenplays for ``Antz'' and the less-than-hormonal ``Madeline.''
The screenplay is by another relative newcomer, Adam Herz, whose
previous writing credits consist of unsold sitcom scripts and here
springs fully formed from the brow of the Farrelly Brothers.
Whether the barf-inducing gross-outs in ``American Pie'' are meant
as a subtle homage to the Farrellys' ``There's Something About
Mary'' is unclear, but probably not: They're probably just
barf-inducing gross-outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Pie'' is cute. The four lunks are cute, their
girlfriends are cute, their friends are cute, even their parents
are cute. Jennifer Coolidge has a short but sultry bit as a
classmate's hot mom, and Eugene Levy brings his Groucho eyebrows
and deadpan timing to a brilliantly dorky turn as Jim's dad; their
birds-and-the-bees discussions are the best scenes in the film.
</P>
<P>
   And it is, in its own, sophomoric way, sincere. Though it never
looks at the serious side to sex (pregnancy? AIDS? morality?
naaaah), it does take a few spare nanoseconds to question the
wisdom of chasing sex for sex's sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never even had sex, and I'm already sick of it!'' gripes
Jim near the end of the movie. But then the moment ends, and before
long the young man has resumed his quest with renewed dedication.
Boys will be boys, and then some.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
