<HEADER>
A6753 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROUND-COVERS-LIFEBEA     07-12 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROUND-COVERS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUND COVERS: A CARPET MADE OF LEAVES
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photo of two ground covers 
 By SUSAN McCLURE 
 c.1999 Susan McClure 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a plush carpet made of gleaming leaves instead of fibers,
ground covers can stretch beneath trees and shrubs, beside fences,
around rocks, mailboxes, and lamp posts. They can edge a mixed
garden or shrub border or cover a hard-to-mow slope _ an
impressively large range of jobs performed by a versatile group of
plants.
</P>
<P>
   The ubiquitous lawn, which consumes the most ground in the
majority of landscapes, can qualify as a ground cover. But the term
usually refers to decorative perennials, vines, and low-growing
shrubs that will spread across beds carved into the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Ground covers are plants on the move. They may creep over the
soil surface like ivy, sprout from underground stems like
bugleweed, spread with plantlet-bearing runners like strawberries,
or have an expanding waistline of upright stems called suckers like
dwarf bush honeysuckle.
</P>
<P>
   The mobility of ground covers can be a boon to low-budget
gardeners. You can start with a clump from a friend's yard. By
making cuttings or divisions, you can propagate it into several or
dozens of new plants to spread across beds large and small.
</P>
<P>
   Aggressive growers such as sedums, ivies, wintercreeper, and
periwinkle provide maximum beauty for amazingly little effort. When
used in a new ground cover bed, they must be weeded regularly, like
when growing flowers or vegetables. But once ground covers fill in,
they can monopolize the space, smothering weeds and needing nothing
more than a little watering during an extended drought.
</P>
<P>
   The most common ground covers are shade-tolerant evergreen vines
such as English and Boston ivy, pachysandra, and periwinkle. These
brighten the winter landscape and make ideal companions for
evergreens or deciduous trees and shrubs with bright bark or
berries.
</P>
<P>
   During the growing season, these popular evergreen ground covers
tolerate shade beneath deciduous trees and thrive where lawns grow
anemic from solar-deprivation.
 &UR; Mix and Match &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can plant masses of a single type of ivy, pachysandra or
periwinkle to make a uniform expanse of greenery and striking sweep
of color. When used over a large area, the size and the shape of
the bed becomes a bold, visually powerful landscape element.
</P>
<P>
   But in smaller or more complex gardens, you may prefer
interesting blends of ground cover plants. As in a perennial
garden, you could mix taller with shorter, bold-leaved with
fine-leaved, or flowering with evergreen or variegated-leaved
ground covers. Here are some of the less common choices you might
want to use in your yard.
</P>
<P>
   --Sedges (Carex spp.): These are grass-like plants that form
expanding clumps. While some species _ like ornamental grasses _
grow well in sun, many sedges prefer moist shade. This makes them
particularly useful beneath mature shade trees or in gardens on the
shady north side of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Among the best sedges for ground covers are the wood sedge and
the Bowles Golden variety. The latter has arching golden-centered
leaves that reach 18 to 24 inches high. It bears willowy flower
spikes from late spring to early summer.
</P>
<P>
   Not all sedges are well behaved enough for mixed ground cover
plantings. Gray's sedge, for instance, spreads aggressively and may
overwhelm nearby plants.
</P>
<P>
   --Stonecrops (Sedum spp.): These small but mighty creepers have
petite and beautiful succulent leaves and clusters of bright
star-shaped flowers. The leaves on varieties such as ruby Dragon's
Blood and green, cream, and pink Tricolor stonecrop can be as
attractive as the flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Ground-covering sedums, including species such as Sedum spurium
and Sedum acre, hug the ground, reaching only a few inches high. If
given full sun and well-drained soil they require, a single plant
can spread to several feet across.
</P>
<P>
   --Hardy Geraniums (Geranium spp.): If provided with full or
partial sun and good garden soil, hardy geraniums are likely to
live for decades. Most are clump formers with sprawling stems that
can cover some ground. Geranium ibericum, with 20-inch high,
blue-violet flowers, works well as a mid-garden ground cover.
</P>
<P>
   A few hardy geraniums are true creepers. Bigroot geranium (G.
macrorrhizum), which bears pink or white flowers in early summer,
can grow to 24 inches wide, or even wider.
</P>
<P>
   For the front edge of a ground cover garden, try 4- to 6-inch
tall Geranium sanguineum var. striatum, a long bloomer with pale
pink flowers, and Geranium x cantabrigiense Ballerina with
attractive gray leaves and red-veined pink flowers.
</P>
<P>
   --Sages (Salvia officinalis): For a sunny garden of well-drained
soil, try mixing silver and golden-variegated sages, aromatic herbs
that can be used in cooking. When planted 18 inches apart, they
sucker and fill in to make a solid planting about 2 1/2 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   This ground cover may need regular replanting in northern
climates because golden-variegated sages, such as Icterina, are not
reliably hardy.
</P>
<P>
   --Junipers (Juniperus spp.): These evergreen shrubs come in
prostrate forms that can spread 2 to 6 feet across a sunny garden
with well-drained soil. The feathery branches are particularly
attractive when grown beside a sidewalk which they will lap over,
softening the edges.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Susan McClure is a Chicago-area free-lance writer.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
