<HEADER>
A6759 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESEND-YOUNG-COLUMN12     07-12 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESEND-YOUNG-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas created these schools with `let 'em picnic' attitude
 &HT;    EDS: RESEND. CHANGE IN FIFTH GRAF
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The way Texas has administered charter schools in
their infancy, it's easy to get the notion that public education is
a clambake. You just heat up the coals and hand out the clams.
</P>
<P>
   The Emma L. Harrison Charter School was handed roughly $850,000
_ that's some shells. The costly disaster now stands as a monument
to the ``educational entrepreneurship'' touted by Gov. George W.
Bush on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison is the first operating charter to have its charter
revoked. Bush is correct that Texas has success stories to tell
about charter schools, but this success appears to be more by
happenstance than design. Texas sauntered into this arena with
precious little design.
</P>
<P>
   Observers without rose-colored shades say that lack of state
oversight has other charter schools tiptoeing on insolvency's ridge
while doing some of the same things that got Harrison shut down.
</P>
<P>
   A postscript to last week's decision on Harrison was that the
Texas Education Agency announced it would hire six additional
staffers to monitor the 168 charter schools authorized in this
Texas boot scoot.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the blame is not the state's alone. Harrison
officials' attempts to shed blame are pathetic. They flagrantly
abused the public trust and the intent of charter dollars, which
weren't to be used on building needs but on students. Teachers
missed paychecks. Unemployment and retirement system funds weren't
paid. Funds were co-mingled with those of the East Waco Community
Center. The school ran up a debt approaching $400,000. The charter
board operated below radar. The school refused to let the public
see records, ask questions, observe official actions.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of this charter school, we are left to reflect on
some of the destructive bromides of those who wonder aloud about
blowing up our public schools and starting all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Let's create charters. Let's remove all those bureaucratic
controls. Accountability? They'll take TAAS. That'll do it. And,
while we're at it, why not invite private and church schools to the
clambake through vouchers? At least Texas has refrained from the
latter for another legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, let's all decry bureaucracy and state oversight. Who
campaigns as pro-bureaucracy? Off with bureaucrats' heads, we say.
</P>
<P>
   Well, you know what the Emma L. Harrison Charter School was? A
school without bureaucracy or state oversight.
</P>
<P>
   The experience of the Harrison charter school tracks some of
those with privatized state services _ privatization being just
about as easy a sell these days as shaved ice.
</P>
<P>
   So we privatize. And when the private company carrying out the
public bidding fields questions about doing something questionable
with public dollars, it says, ``None of your business. That's
proprietary.''
</P>
<P>
   Adventures in charters and privatization both should remind us
of the necessity to have checks and balances, and public oversight,
and, arghhh, bureaucracy. Because you know what? The most clumsy,
burdensome bureaucracy is us.
</P>
<P>
   Every session of the legislature we have people elected by the
public who try to do their best to keep the public out of its own
business, trying to blot out the light, trying to make things more
``efficient'' _ meaning less encumbered by the messy business of
public accountability.
</P>
<P>
   The unfortunate chapter that was Emma L. Harrison Charter School
should make us all a little more respectful of things like public
oversight, ``burdensome'' regulations, prying media types and all
those things that make democracy messy.
</P>
<P>
   Take them away, and look at the mess you cause.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
