<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6767 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EYES-DIRECTOR-KANSAS-     07-12 1796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYES-DIRECTOR-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEING FOR THE BENEFIT OF THE GREAT STANLEY K. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stanley Kubrick, ever the control freak when it came to his
films, is pulling strings from the grave as the world prepares for
his final cinematic statement, ``Eyes Wide Shut.''
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick finished editing the film shortly before his death in
March at age 70 and had already made sure the marketing elements
were in place. He approved the movie poster (designed by his wife,
Christiana Kubrick), outlined the content of previews and
television ads and formulated a detailed plan for selling the
picture to a public already saturated with movie hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stanley had laid most of this out before he died,'' said
Warner Bros. senior vice president for publicity Nancy Kirkpatrick.
``He was a meticulous planner. He was the architect of all of his
marketing campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick's well-known mania for secrecy has been defied in recent
weeks with an unauthorized review of the film that appeared last
month in a London newspaper and a just-published memoir by the
screenwriter who worked with him on ``Eyes Wide Shut.''
</P>
<P>
   But he still seems to be in control.
</P>
<P>
   For the last 30 years _ since ``2001: A Space Odyssey'' in 1968
_ Kubrick exercised near-total command of all aspects of his films
as director, producer, editor and sometimes cinematographer and
co-writer. He oversaw everything from production design to the
dubbing of foreign-language trailers. Apparently no aspect of the
film was too inconsequential for him to weigh in.
</P>
<P>
   And he was infamous for demanding that actors perform a scene
30, 50 or even 100 times until the great director deemed it
perfect.
</P>
<P>
   He was indulged in all this because of his reputation as a
cinematic genius who brought us unique films that told stories in
unusual ways. ``Dr. Strangelove,'' ``Paths of Glory,'' ``2001'' and
``A Clockwork Orange'' are considered landmark movies, each with a
distinct look and tone. Kubrick's reputation afforded him an
autonomy enjoyed by virtually no other American director.
</P>
<P>
   And with that autonomy came an obsessive secretiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Warner Bros., curious about the Kubrick films they
were financing, could read his screenplays only by flying to
London. (Kubrick had moved to England in the '60s and, phobic about
air travel, never returned to his native United States.) There they
were allowed to peruse the script in a hotel room with a Kubrick
associate hovering nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The director's cast and crew members were sworn to secrecy _ and
invariably toed the line. The privilege of working with Kubrick was
considered compensation enough for keeping a lid on information
about the production.
</P>
<P>
   Even Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman, the husband-and-wife stars of
``Eyes Wide Shut,'' have clung to Kubrick's master plan. They've
granted interviews to several national magazines but have declined
to give any specifics about the film's content.
</P>
<P>
   On occasion Kubrick's secretiveness seemed beyond all reason. In
the just-published Eyes Wide Open, screenwriter Frederic Raphael
describes how Kubrick sent him photocopied pages from ``a gray and
dated-looking text'' and asked for his ideas on adapting the book
into a screenplay. All references to the author's name and the
novel's title had been removed.
</P>
<P>
   Raphael almost immediately recognized the writing style as that
of turn-of-the-century Viennese author Arthur Schnitzler. In fact,
the book was Schnitzler's Traumnovelle (published in English as
Rhapsody: A Dream Novel. But Kubrick stubbornly refused to confirm
that fact until he was certain he was going to hire Raphael to
write the screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a year later the two men barely weathered a crisis over
the secrecy issue. Working with Kubrick, Raphael shifted to
contemporary New York Schnitzler's story of a marriage threatened
when a husband and wife begin to exchange their sexual fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   Raphael sent a copy of the first draft to his longtime agent as
proof that he had met his contractual obligations and now should be
paid for his efforts. This routine business practice horrified
Kubrick, who demanded that Raphael produce a list of anyone who may
have read the screenplay, how many copies had been made and who
received them.
</P>
<P>
   Raphael reports that he was bemused by this paranoia,
particularly since Kubrick regarded a screenplay merely as a
skeletal framework. The real substance of a Kubrick film sprang
from on-the-set variations and improvisations created by the
director and players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is morbidly afraid of giving away any of his secrets,''
Raphael writes, ``the best of which may be that he has none.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeding the rumor mill
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick's secretiveness may have originated in his psyche, but
it had a very pragmatic effect. The very lack of information makes
``Eyes Wide Shut'' all the more intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick hadn't released a film since 1987, which alone was
enough to crank up the rumor mill. But there were reports that this
film would push on-screen sexuality to a new level.
</P>
<P>
   There's no record of Kubrick or anyone on his staff saying that
he wanted to make a pornographic movie. But he was happy to let
filmgoers believe it.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview shortly before his death in 1995, writer Terry
Southern (Kubrick's collaborator on ``Dr. Strangelove'') said
Kubrick had entertained the notion of making a sexually explicit
movie for years.
</P>
<P>
   According to Southern, some 30 years ago the two men had been
screening porn movies when Kubrick commented, ``Wouldn't it be
interesting if one day someone who was an artist would do that _
using really beautiful actors and first-rate equipment?''
</P>
<P>
   Southern turned that idea into a novel, Blue Movie, which was
dedicated to ``the great Stanley K.'' In the book a world-class
movie director tackles pornography, saying: ``I've got to find out
how far you can take the aesthetically erotic _ at what point, if
any, it gets to be such a personal thing that it becomes
meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   It's now pretty clear that whatever else it is, ``Eyes Wide
Shut'' is not pornographic _ at least in the view of the ratings
board of the Motion Picture Association of America, which has given
the movie an R rating.
</P>
<P>
   But just the lurid suggestion that Kubrick was making a sexually
explicit film was enough to raise ``Eyes Wide Shut's'' currency.
</P>
<P>
   The big tease
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe the advertising approach Kubrick envisioned
for ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' Warners' Kirkpatrick called it ``a tease
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He never used those words directly with me,'' she said in a
recent telephone interview from Los Angeles, ``but that's exactly
what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick's manipulation of the media reached its zenith at the
ShoWest convention held in Las Vegas in March. There an eager
audience of movie exhibitors got a first glimpse of footage from
Kubrick's film.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-second clip, edited by Kubrick, showed Kidman slowly
removing her earrings while looking into a mirror that reflected
her nude body. A naked Cruise approaches and begins fondling and
kissing her.
</P>
<P>
   There was no dialogue, just a bluesy chant on the soundtrack
that repeated the words ``Baby did a bad, bad thing; baby did a
bad, bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Warners' Kirkpatrick says: ``Stanley had actually instructed his
production team to have it distributed worldwide within a couple of
hours of the Las Vegas showing.''
</P>
<P>
   So within hours of its debut, the clip was on TV (in edited
form) and all over the Internet in all its naked glory.
</P>
<P>
   In the days before his death, Kubrick also instructed his
associates on how to cut 30-, 60- and 90-second trailers for the
film. The earliest of these showed scenes from the movie _ again
with no dialogue and against the ``bad, bad thing'' chant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there's no dialogue, you can put any story you like in
there,'' Kirkpatrick said. ``It was brilliant because it allowed
audiences to impose their own ideas on the material.''
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick left detailed instructions about how and when
promotional items for the film were to be distributed and when
critics would see ``Eyes Wide Shut.'' (Reviewers in some cities saw
it Thursday; Kansas City writers will see it Wednesday.) Kubrick
even specified which stills could be used to promote the film.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the control of Kubrick, though, is Raphael's
just-published memoir. According to Kirkpatrick, Kubrick's
survivors are ``upset that he breached that confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Raphael (whose screenwriting credits include ``Two for
the Road,'' ``Darling'' and ``Far From the Madding Crowd'')
contributes to the tease campaign by declining to give away too
much about the project. His book is mostly about his encounters
with Kubrick, whom he describes as ``a movie director who happens
to be a genius rather than a genius who happens to be a movie
director.''
</P>
<P>
   A far greater betrayal, in the view of Kubrick's people, was the
review of ``Eyes Wide Shut'' written by Alexander Walker and
published June 22 in the London Evening Standard. Walker, a Kubrick
friend and biographer, saw the film at a private screening arranged
by the family.
</P>
<P>
   In his review, he described the movie as ``a story of how an
apparently happily married couple, rich, successful New Yorkers,
the sort we call the `Beautiful People,' are set at odds with each
other by their dreams and fantasies.''
</P>
<P>
   The title, Walker wrote, ``connotes a spellbound state _ the
mood of a waking dream,'' and the revelation by Kidman's character
of an infidelity ``sends her husband rebounding into a world of
sexual possibilities, including a posh masquerade ball that quickly
turns into a huge orgy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately Walker delivered a rave: ``Even at its most baffling,
it is an astonishing work made with masterly control and at the
same time a humanity that this director's detractors have insisted
he did not possess. ... This valedictory production is a victory
for its maker's unending quest to make his reach exceed his
grasp.''
</P>
<P>
   But his liking the film did not excuse running the review early,
Kirkpatrick said. ``That review was, to me, the most shocking
betrayal. Raphael's book seems to me to be a case of a writer with
an experience he felt compelled to write about. But Walker was a
family friend. They showed the movie to him, and he betrayed their
trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker has declined comment except to issue a statement through
the Evening Standard that he ``was not under any embargo.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, on Friday, Americans finally will get to see what
all the furor is about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what people think it is,'' Kirkpatrick said. ``But
then were any of his movies ever what people thought they were
going to be?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 1217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
