r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PETS-CATBOOK-KANSAS-K     07-12 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETS-CATBOOK-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S STRICTLY CATS RULE IN THIS HOUSEHOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARJEAN BUSBY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Living with nine cats and one Siberian husky sounds crazy
enough, but then you read on. Author//photographer Bob Walker and
his wife, Frances Mooney, have redesigned their San Diego home so
it's like a feline playground with offbeat perches.
</P>
<P>
   A hundred feet of elevated walkways, for example, satisfy the
cats' preference for heights and bird's-eye views. A ceiling-high,
rope-covered post caters to their scratching instinct.
</P>
<P>
   No pussyfooters, they can scurry down a spiral staircase to the
television room or descend a 16-foot carpeted ramp in the owners'
bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   For his second illustrated book, Cats Into Everything (Andrews
McMeel Publishing, $18.95), Walker takes readers through routine
activities, including shaving with a curious fat cat on his
shoulder. When Mooney makes an afghan from recycled sweater yarn,
furry thieves run off with the colored wool she needs.
</P>
<P>
   For chapters called ``Fur in Our Food'' and ``Not a Creature Was
Stirring,'' Walker achieved novel photo shots through
unconventional approaches.
</P>
<P>
   - He placed a camera underneath a glass-top table to record
house pets lapping milk with scratchy tongues, getting combative on
catnip and devouring a well-balanced people meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always act as if they are one meal away from
starvation,'' he writes. ``Unfortunately for them, their ample
girth betrays their plaintive meows.''
</P>
<P>
   - By mounting a motorized camera on the bedroom ceiling, Walker
recorded various sleeping positions of the cats and couple for more
than a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``A powerful flash illuminated our bed every 13 minutes,'' he
explains, but after a couple of nights ``everybody slept
comfortably.''
</P>
<P>
   The warm reception of Walker's 1996 book, The Cat's House,
prompted Kansas City-based Andrews McMeel Publishing to tap
Walker's skills as photographer, writer and designer once again.
His wife, a colorist and do-it-yourself decorator, shares his sense
of whimsy. Their original interest involved a gallery operation and
framing pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Walker comments on their set-up:
</P>
<P>
   ``Living and working with a household full of felines has
demonstrated what all cat lovers know: Cats will purr and play and
carouse their way into all aspects of their feeders' lives. Whether
we're working, eating, sleeping or socializing _ our cats are into
everything we do.''
</P>
<P>
   The public's most frequent questions deal with his ``least
favorite cat task.'' Do you use clumping or regular cat litter?
Answer: clumping. How often do you clean your cat boxes and how
many do you have? Every other day, five boxes, he replies.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, he's the one in the house who does it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
