</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSQUITO-BITES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING MOSQUITOES AT BAY NO SIMPLE CHORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CELINA OTTAWAY  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Some people seem to attract mosquitoes more
readily than others, and experts say the attraction has mostly to
do with the amount of carbon dioxide that comes through a person's
skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not blood type,'' said Dr. Jonathan Day, a medical
entomologist at the University of Florida. Day has spent 20 years
studying diseases that are transmitted by insects. ``It's not what
you eat or what you don't eat. It has to do with the amount of
carbon dioxide you produce.''
</P>
<P>
   The body emits carbon dioxide through the breath and through the
skin. Mosquitoes are attracted to the carbon dioxide that comes
through the skin, said Day. The more you produce, the more
mosquitoes are drawn to you.
</P>
<P>
   That's bad news for active people. The more you move around, the
more carbon dioxide you produce. Also, when the muscles work they
produce a waste product called lactic acid. This comes through the
skin and attracts mosquitoes, Day said.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors that draw the bugs in are body temperature and
size. The larger and warmer you are, the more likely you are to
attract mosquitoes, Day said.
</P>
<P>
   Dark colors also make you an easy target.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mosquitoes tend to fly pretty close to the ground,'' Day said.
``They look at you against the horizon, so dark colors stand out.''
The best color to wear is yellow, Day said.
</P>
<P>
   Alligator trapper Tony Hunter grew up hunting in the Florida
Everglades, where the mosquitoes would surround the boats in a
faint black fog.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried everything,'' he said, ``eating garlic and vitamin
B1, but personally I never really noticed a difference. I think we
just gave them a little more flavor in their meal.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst, he said, was when he and his friends heard that
parsley might help and they sprinkled everything they ate with the
flakes. ``Nasty stuff,'' he said. And it didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kenneth Boch of the Center for Progressive Medicine in
Albany uses nutritional supplements and herbs in his practice, but
he hasn't found anything that works well to repel mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Some people have luck with high doses of vitamin B1 (100
milligrams, two or three times a day), he said. ``But it doesn't
work for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Boch said he isn't overly impressed with garlic as a repellent
either.
</P>
<P>
   Chemical insect repellent is the best thing to keep mosquitoes
away, according to both Hunter and Day. Both said repellents with
the ingredient DEET work well.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter uses the strongest DEET spray he can find when he goes
out on his job as an alligator nuisance trapper for the state of
Florida. But, he said, mosquitoes have their favorites.
</P>
<P>
   On the hunts, some people spend the trip smacking at bugs and
getting bothered and bitten, while others like himself get away
with a few welts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are some tips for reducing mosquito populations around your
home:
</P>
<P>
   Lawn: Mow at least once a week during spring and summer.
Mosquitoes like to hide in tall grass.
</P>
<P>
   Hedges/bushes: Keep them trimmed. The more shade you have, the
more mosquitoes will be attracted to your yard.
</P>
<P>
   Tire swing: Drill drainage holes in the bottom to avoid stagnant
water, a mosquito breeding ground.
</P>
<P>
   Kiddie pool: Empty out water once or twice a week. Standing
water can become stagnant and produce optimum mosquito breeding
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Sand box: Make sure toys are not left for long periods of time
with standing water in them. A sand pail full of water is a
potential breeding ground for mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Barbecue: Shelter it during rainfall.
</P>
<P>
   Bird bath: Empty water at least once a week to avoid stagnant
water.
</P>
<P>
   Trellis: It can block the wind, which keeps mosquitoes away. Try
not to have too many objects in your yard that will block the
breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Rain gutters: Don't forget to clean them out: Debris can block
water from flowing, creating a mosquito haven.
</P>
<P>
   Garden/ornamental pond: Stock goldfish, which will eat mosquito
larvae that float on top of the water.
</P>
<P>
   Pool: Be sure to skim regularly because mosquitoes lay their
eggs on the water's surface.
</P>
<P>
   Poolside bushes: Keep them trimmed. The shade of the bushes
combined with the humidity of the pool provides mosquitoes with an
ideal haven.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Off! Biting Insect Center
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
