<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6777 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTREAL-HNS &LR;      07-12 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTREAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FESTIVAL CAPITAL' IS A BARGAIN FOR AMERICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM REYNOLDS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Though it's just a short distance from the U.S.
border, it doesn't take long to realize that Montreal is truly a
different world.
</P>
<P>
   From the barrage of questions at the Customs patrol station on
the border to the intimidating French highway signs, and right down
to having to deal with Canada's $2 coin, Montreal feels unique from
the moment you cross the Pont Jacques Cartier or the Pont Champlain
to reach the island city.
</P>
<P>
   But once you're actually in the city, whether you're fluent in
French, know only two phrases or are completely baffled by the
language, it's easy to be swept away by how simple it is to find,
not only your way around, but to find a plethora of things to do as
well.
</P>
<P>
   First, take notice of the fact that Montreal is turning into a
fine day, weekend or longer getaway spot for several reasons, the
best of which is the exchange rate of the strong U.S. dollar into
Canadian currency. Right now, you can get about $1.40 Canadian for
$1 American, and even though things tend to be priced a tad higher
than in the States, the exchange rate pretty much assures you of
getting more bang for your buck.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do tend to get many visits from Americans, and as you know,
that's likely attributed to the exchange rate right now,'' said
Sylvie Bouchand, a waitress at a club on Crescent Street, a
must-stop for the party set. ``The rate is bad for us because of
the taxes, but with the tourism, it is good.''
</P>
<P>
   For the sports fan, there's Montreal Expos baseball. And since
the club only draws an average of 8,800 fans per night to cavernous
Olympic Stadium, tickets are readily available not to mention
cheap. The best seats in the house go for the equivalent of about
$20 U.S. ($33 Canadian), and even the bleacher seats ($7 Canadian,
or about $4.50 U.S.) provide a good view of the on-field action.
</P>
<P>
   There's more to Olympic Stadium than Expos baseball. The
building was constructed in 1976 to host the Olympic Summer Games,
and can be seen on clear days from more than five miles away,
thanks in large part to the 552-foot curved tower atop the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Cable car rides to the top of the tower are available, and the
view _ even, believe it or not, on cloudy days _ is spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Not into sports? Near the stadium sits the Biodome, a must-stop
for those with interests in science and a particularly popular spot
on either very hot or very rainy days. The building usually offers
exhibits of four ecosystems _ tropical and Laurentian forests, the
marine environment of the St. Lawrence River and the polar world.
All displays are in English and French, and the staff, like many
workers in Montreal, are bilingual, so communication isn't a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   But even the Biodome doesn't compare with the ecological
experience downtown, as Montreal's Botanical Garden is the second
largest in the world, behind only Kew Gardens in London. The
Botanical Garden keeps a minimum of 28,000 species on display and
plans on offering more during the summer months.
</P>
<P>
   One of the popular tourist stops in Montreal is St. Joseph's
Oratory, which sits atop Mount Royal. It was founded by the Blessed
Andre Bresette, who died in 1937 and was beatified in 1982. The
Brother of the Holy Cross, who was better known as ``Frere Andre,''
was credited with thousands of cures, drew more than 1 million
people to his funeral there, and more than 100,000 people still
visit the shrine annually, many still looking for cures.
</P>
<P>
   The downtown and night life scenes are filled with opportunity,
from dance clubs to restaurants, coffeehouses and the Hard Rock
Cafe, which teems with tourists on a nightly basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too crowded,'' Bouchand said. ``We (meaning the locals)
like to stay away from the crowds sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Although natives sometimes prefer to stay away from the crowds,
the city's tourism board welcomes the activity, and proclaims
Montreal as ``the festival capital of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers, take delight. Not only are Peel and St. Catharine
streets lined with shops, but a 29-kilometer-long underground
section of the city is devoted to shoppers and tourists.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Underground City'' has 1,700 boutiques, department stores,
restaurants, movie houses, theaters and exhibition halls, as well
as seven major hotels, 1,615 housing units, thousands of offices,
the central train station and so on. Plus, like the rest of the
city, use of the Metro system is readily available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
