<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LETTERFROMMUSSOORIE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA'S CONFLICT WITH PAKISTAN BRINGS OUT FLAG-WAVERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUSSOORIE, India _ The searing heat of summer normally drives
thousands of Indians up to Mussoorie and other colonial-era resorts
that the British called ``hill stations.'' But this year, far fewer
are fleeing the baked plains for the cool mountain air.
</P>
<P>
   The Cricket World Cup competition, played at venues in the
Netherlands, Ireland and Britain and culminating with the June 20
final at Lord's Cricket Ground in London, kept tens of millions of
Indians glued to satellite-fed transmissions of the slow-paced
sport, yet another legacy of the British Raj.
</P>
<P>
   Also, people are uneasy over the fighting at Kargil, a village
near the truce line that divides Indian and Pakistani sectors of
disputed Kashmir, explained the owner of Padmini Niwas, a
turn-of-the-century, tin-roofed inn known in pre-independence days
as Rushbrooke.
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, the clashes have united this sprawling
nation and unleashed a torrent of frothy patriotism. Indian
officers in media interviews speak of ``gallant'' action by their
men, giving a quaint, almost World War I flavor to the conflict and
its coverage. Enlistment reportedly has skyrocketed. Newspapers and
corporations compete to raise money for families of those slain at
Kargil.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Indian troops have been engaged in hand-to-hand
combat, recapturing bunkers atop mountain peaks that 700
``intruders'' quietly had seized without a fight at the end of a
milder than usual winter. India says the occupiers are regular
Pakistani troops and Muslim ``mercenaries''; Pakistan says they are
Kashmiri freedom fighters and ``mujahideen'' (holy warriors), who
receive only its moral and political support.
</P>
<P>
   When Indians are not exuberantly waving flags, they are quietly
seething over what many see as an intelligence failure. The
intruders were spotted not by army patrols or the border security
force but by a goat herder who chanced upon the strangers in March.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict's first casualty was the unprecedented outpouring
of goodwill for Pakistan engendered by the simple act of starting
regular bus service between New Delhi, the Indian capital, and
Lahore, Pakistan's second-largest city.
</P>
<P>
   In March, as Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee made the
inaugural run that many saw as heralding an era of friendly
relations, infiltrators were digging in on peaks overlooking a
strategic road near Kargil. After their discovery, they mowed down
row upon row of Indian troops inching up to entrenched positions.
</P>
<P>
   It was seen as a betrayal by Pakistan, and such a startling stab
in the back that many Indians believed that Pakistan's new army
chief had ordered the Kargil infiltration _ strategically clever,
but diplomatically short-sighted _ without the knowledge of
Pakistan Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif. Pakistani statements later
indicated there was no independent army move.
</P>
<P>
   But what is clear is that the subcontinent lost yet another
opportunity to overcome old animosities and finally build bilateral
cooperation for the benefit of the two peoples. Though traditional
military rivals, Muslim Pakistan and Hindu-dominated India were
part of British India before independence in 1947 and are extremely
close culturally.
</P>
<P>
   So why did Pakistan do it?
</P>
<P>
   Since it officially doesn't concede its troops are even involved
_ except in tit-for-tat artillery duels _ there is no official
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   At times of domestic political turmoil, both sides have cited a
perceived, or fabricated, threat from the other to divert public
attention. But at this time, Sharif holds a solid parliamentary
majority and has neutralized most political rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking among some in New Delhi is that it was Pakistan's
last chance to seize any advantage in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   The drawn-out guerrilla campaign to win Kashmir's independence
from India had lost much support in the predominantly Muslim
region. Indeed, attacks had dropped off so precipitously that in
the past year tourists were returning to the region's
breathtakingly beautiful lakes and mountains after more than a
decade. Moreover, Pakistan's successful nuclear test last year, in
answer to an earlier one by India, gave the country an intense
feeling of invulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   Although the neighbors had twice come to blows over Kashmir,
never before had both been armed with nuclear weapons. Yet the
threat of a nuclear holocaust, while discussed in India's energetic
press, curiously has not created much of a stir.
</P>
<P>
   A story given more prominence quoted Indian cricket star Kapil
Dev as demanding that matches with Pakistan be canceled until its
troops withdraw from Kargil. In Pakistan, the story bigger than the
risk of nuclear annihilation was the disclosure that its top
cricket players publicly boozed in London nightclubs before the
Australians trounced them in the World Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   But the conflict is deadly serious business.
</P>
<P>
   Both Pakistanis and Indians are convinced that casualties are
far higher than what their respective governments officially say.
Indian troops have not been outfitted with high-altitude gear and
Pakistanis, frequently short of supplies, at times have been
reduced to eating ice sprinkled with sugar. And fighting has been
so intense at times that the wounded have been left on
mountainsides 28 hours before seeing a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the two adversaries have in common is the word to
describe their battle fallen _ ``martyrs.''
</P>
<P>
   (Barry Shlachter was based in both India and Pakistan as an
Associated Press correspondent. He recently returned from a brief
trip to India. You can contact him via e-mail at:
barrs(at)star-telegram.com or phone at (817) 390-7718. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 1232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
