<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6785 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-12 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAVE BERKELEY IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ What if Europeans had settled the West Coast
before the East Coast? That was the question raised by a friend,
and his guess was that they never would have left California.
</P>
<P>
   No one would have crossed the desert to a land of humidity and
slush, just to find Guldens in them thar Coney dogs. We'd never
have learned what lousy pastrami we have here.
</P>
<P>
   The descendants of the Pilgrims would have stayed by the pool in
their basic black Speedos, dipping sourdough into extra virgin
olive oil, while sipping a dry but impertinent chardonnay. You'd
never catch them washing down dry turkey on white bread with
cranberry juice. Never mind how sexy, beautiful and temperate
California is.
</P>
<P>
   The food alone is enough to make a Puritan have a nice day.
</P>
<P>
   This all came to me after going to New York City and dining in a
new restaurant called the Berkeley Bar &AMP; Grill, which was conceived
as a tribute to Alice Waters and the California food revolution
that started at Chez Panisse almost 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the only California revolution recognized in New York
was the right turn on red. Never mind such advances as Silicon
Valley, extreme games or pizza with blue potatoes on it.
</P>
<P>
   California always has been a Woody Allen joke.
</P>
<P>
   I was eager to see what a New York restaurant based on exotic
California would be like. The Berkeley Bar &AMP; Grill's owner, Drew
Nieporent, who co-owns New York's famous Tribeca Grill with Robert
De Niro, once said that restaurants in New York always look east to
Europe, and never look west to California.
</P>
<P>
   When I called to make a reservation, the woman who answered the
phone knew who I was. It turned out she had just moved to New York
from Nieporent's restaurant in San Francisco, Rubicon. I imagined
Jimmy Breslin and Mayor Rudlolph Giuliani having to wait in line,
while San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown and I got a table.
</P>
<P>
   I should have suspected the Berkeley Bar &AMP; Grill wouldn't be
authentic, because no one in Berkeley knows who I am.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant is trapped in the glass of the Sony Plaza on
Madison Avenue, so it's sleekly un-Chez Panissey. That's excusable,
but the sound system was playing Crosby, Stills and Nash.
</P>
<P>
   What was this, a theme restaurant? TGI Berkeley's? The menu,
though, was as Berkeley as a Birkenstock, with a ``Berkeley Bar &AMP;
Grill'' logo that looked just like the work of Alice Waters' friend
David Goines. Maybe he even designed it.
</P>
<P>
   The menu featured Shattuck Avenue comfort food like goat cheese
salad, pot-au-feu and osso bucco with toasted couscous, along with
the required references to sources of ingredients, like ``Chatham
Bay cod.''
</P>
<P>
   I used to live in Chatham, Mass., and didn't want to be
disappointed with tributes to two towns I know, so I ordered the
turbot. The fish was excellent, but the plate was too organized to
be authentically Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   The potatoes and zucchini were carved like little pieces of
soap, the way they do in culinary academies, not the Chez Panisse
kitchen, where vegetables are meant to look as naive and natural as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   And how come the ``Spring Soupe au Pistou'' was made with winter
root vegetables? Forget the dinner roll. New Yorkers know pastrami,
but they still don't get bread and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   The verbiage was as self-congratulatory as anything in the Bay
Area, though. The wine list said selections were made with Berkeley
in mind, ``the idealized Berkeley that has inspired two generations
of American chefs.''
</P>
<P>
   The idealized Berkeley also inspired free speech, and the menu
freely spoke too much. The name of the artist in the kitchen was
even listed as ``Patricia Williams, Loving Chef.''
</P>
<P>
   And get this. One of the desserts was called ``Hash Brownies
with Cherry Garcia.'' It was a brownie topped with Ben &AMP; Jerry's
ice cream, and for $9 you didn't even get high. Instead you got a
sprinkling of oregano.
</P>
<P>
   We paid about $150 for an idealized Berkeley meal that ended in
a rip-off dope joke even Woody Allen would edit out.
</P>
<P>
   But I must say, the place was comfortable, the staff pleasant,
and the food was better than the $300 meal we had at the pompous
four-star restaurant Jean- Georges, a perfectly executed New York
theme restaurant, appropriately located in one of Donald Trump's
towers.
</P>
<P>
   At this joint, which features stiff waiters bearing sickly sweet
sweetbreads under silver domes, the bread looked oddly like Acme
bread from downloose Berkeley. The waiter made a big show of
bringing two kinds of butter, salted and unsalted, with a leaf
pressed into the latter for identification.
</P>
<P>
   Both kinds of butter were terrible. Butter, bread, salad _ those
are the kinds of things Northern Californians notice while New
Yorkers are looking around to see who else is there.
</P>
<P>
   You can eat well cheaply in New York. Start spending money, and
you're a fool.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know why they don't understand the food revolution in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   What they seem to have missed is that it's about food.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
