<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
July 13. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   PROTEST: About 250 protesters shut down I-70 near St. Louis
Monday morning, disrupting rush hour traffic for about an hour. The
Rev. Al Sharpton was among dozens arrested. Protesters want more
minority contracts for Missouri highway construction. Last minute
efforts by the governor's office failed to halt the protest. Will
Sentell. 20.
</P>
<P>
   SUPER: Foloing developments in the KC schools superintendent
saga. Board members expected to meet privately Monday to discuss
their next move and whether to go to Oklahoma City to check out
Benjamin Demps. Phillip O'Connor. 15.
</P>
<P>
   MAYOR: The mayor of a small town near Branson, Mo., is arraigned
Wednesday in federal court in Kansas City on charges of paying to
have sex with a 15-year-old girl and witness tampering. Mark
Morris. 12.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   POZNANSKI. Column on British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ALLSTAR. Juan Gonzalez besmirched the All-Star Game this year
with his antics, and ratings for the annual event have been in a
steady decline, but the '99 game may draw the best audience in
years. Why? Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa appreciation, the last
All-Star gathering at Fenway Park, and no Gonzalez sightings. Steve
Rock. 18-20.
</P>
<P>
   ROSY. Jose Rosado is a two-time All-Star, folks. Is he that good
or are the Royals that bad? Dick Kaegal. 16-18.
</P>
<P>
   LPGA. LPGA exhibition at Iron Horse, featuring three pros,
including Michelle McGann. Howard Richman. 12-15.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   SPEED _ If there's a Johnny Appleseed for economic development
projects it might be a state of the art motor speedway. Just ask
Pat Svacina, a spokesman for city hall in Fort Worth, Texas. If
Fort Worth's experience is any guide, Kansas City, Kan., for
decades the region's most economically depressed community, could
enjoy a breathtaking revival. By Rick Alm
</P>
<P>
   KCSI _ Kansas City Southern Industries receives a favorable
ruling from the IRS on the company's tax-free spin-off of its
financial services companies. By Mark Davis
</P>
<P>
   INSURE _ Kansas Insurance Commissioner Kathryn Sebelius holds a
news conference to talk about a new law that requires insurers in
the state to cover costs of reconstructive surgery following
mastectomy. By Julius Karash
</P>
<P>
   ELK _ 12,000 Elks in Kansas City for national convention. Who
are these guys? Rick Alm.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   PETS-CATBOOK (undated) _ For his second illustrated book, Cats
Into Everything (Andrews McMeel Publishing, $18.95), Bob Walker
takes readers through routine activities, including shaving with a
curious fat cat on his shoulder. When Walker's wife, Frances
Mooney, makes an afghan from recycled sweater yarn, furry thieves
run off with the colored wool she needs. By MARJEAN BUSBY. 280
words. Story will move in the ``l'' category.
</P>
<P>
   EYES-DIRECTOR (undated) _ Stanley Kubrick, ever the control
freak when it came to his films, is pulling strings from the grave
as the world prepares for his final cinematic statement, ``Eyes
Wide Shut.'' By ROBERT W. BUTLER. 1,744 words. Story will move in
the ``e'' category.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-BEDWET (Kansas City, Mo.) _ It's commonly estimated that
5 million to 7 million children and adolescents (girls 5 and older
and boys 6 and older) wet their beds, including 15 percent of
5-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   In the vast majority of those cases, bedwetting is a symptom of
an immature ``brain-bladder connection,'' according to Bradley
Warady, a pediatrician who specializes in kidney-related ailments
at Children's Mercy Hospital. And in many cases it's just a matter
of time until it clears up. By KAREN UHLENHUTH. 983 words. Story
will move in the ``l'' category.
</P>
