<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6797 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN13-CO     07-12 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: It's Paris, my love
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The hotel where I almost always stay is small and
comfortable and, though not air-conditioned, has something that
other Paris hotels lack _ a staff that knows me by name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, Mr. Murray,'' the manager announces as I enter the small
lobby. ``Welcome back.''
</P>
<P>
   A long way from home, I like the recognition. I like, too, that
in Paris my name is pronounced mur-RAY. I wish now I'd have brought
my beret.
</P>
<P>
   I love this part of Paris, a street of bistros, bakeries and
flower shops.
</P>
<P>
   The Pantheon is only around the corner. The Sorbonne, at the
center of the Latin Quarter on St. Germain, is a five-minute walk.
A bit farther is the Seine, Notre Dame and the American bookstore
with the fabled name of Shakespeare and Co.
</P>
<P>
   Sidewalk cafes, of course, are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   I have to re-educate myself as to the art of lingering at a
table long after the glass is empty. It's an un-American kind of
leisure, to simply sit and do nothing, but I am working hard to
persevere in my restraint.
</P>
<P>
   A cigar helps. So does a copy of the International Herald
Tribune. So does the weather, hardly 80 degrees and tempered with a
light breeze.
</P>
<P>
   I feel very much at home, and for good reason.
</P>
<P>
   I like to think everyone has two hometowns: the one where you
are born and the second where your heart is. Paris quickly becomes
everyone's other hometown.
</P>
<P>
   If you've never been to Paris, you should come and find out for
yourself, as it is to be walking down a tree-lined boulevard and
suddenly _ Voila! _ you have found your heart.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, there is a love story being written here at every
turn. But it is not simply lovers embraced on park benches. It is
more than that. All of Paris is in love.
</P>
<P>
   All of Paris is in love with Paris.
</P>
<P>
   It is a difference found nowhere in America, perhaps nowhere
else in the world.
</P>
<P>
   _ The people of New York claim that they (heart) New York. But
theirs is a love-hate relationship at best.
</P>
<P>
   _ In thriving cities such as Atlanta or Houston, the feeling
often may take the form of civic pride. But pride is not love.
</P>
<P>
   _ In small-town America like where I live, it is more a sense of
kinship, a place where you grew up, where your parents and
grandparents grew up before you, and your children since. Family
may be love, but it is not a love story.
</P>
<P>
   But Paris! It is a city dedicated to art and beauty. Its street
scenes are like vistas. Gorgeous monuments or grand fountains await
at one corner or the next. The City of Light is a city of life.
</P>
<P>
   It's for good reason that all of Paris is in love with Paris.
But it's more than that. Paris, it would seem, loves its people in
return.
</P>
<P>
   That's something I can only guess at. To visit Paris is not
enough. You would have to live in Paris. Such is the commitment of
love.
</P>
<P>
   What is the difference between visiting Paris and living in
Paris?
</P>
<P>
   Sadly this:
</P>
<P>
   It is the difference between love and unrequited love.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of The Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. His address is P.O. Box
151108l, Lufkin, Texas, 75915; e-mail, jmurray(at)coxnews.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
