<HEADER>
A6798 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES1     07-12 0237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: The national debt explained
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This goes back to the Reagan administration. Ronald Reagan and
his fellow Republicans had crabbed for decades about the federal
deficit. Nothing, not even motherhood, came close to zapping waste,
fraud and abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Then Reagan got into office, slashed taxes, built up the
military, and ran up the biggest deficit in the history of the
universe. Deficits, Republicans explained, were only bad if you
looked at them in some dumb, outmoded way.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush, who said he wouldn't, raised taxes, complaining
tax-and-spend Democrats made him do it. Bill Clinton raised taxes,
and now, riding an economic boom, says we're drowning in cash.
Enough, he says, to patch up Social Security, Medicare and the
defense budget. Along about 2015 we wipe out the national debt, a
nifty 3,000 kazillion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say yeah sure okay that's fine we can do some good
stuff for the old folks, but what we really need is to cut taxes.
And anyhow Bill Clinton dammit is stealing our best ideas, which,
by the way, we now oppose.
</P>
<P>
   I'll miss the national debt. It was something you could count
on.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
