<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6802 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SEX-LADN     07-12 1417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SEX-LADN </SLUG>
 
(For use by SLANG partners) 
By MARLA MATZER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Most of the movies hyped as ``must-sees'' in
recent years have been of the sci-fi, special effects genre: movies
like ``Godzilla'' and ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace.'' Despite a general sense among viewers that we're seeing
more sex on screen than ever, such movies feature virtually no sex.
Those big movies that do feature sex today tend to turn it into a
raunchy joke (``There's Something About Mary'') or an act of
violence (``The General's Daughter'').
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the late Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut'' on the
horizon, we once again have a film that is creating enormous
pre-release ``buzz'' for its reported exploration of the psychology
of sexual desire, rather than its violence or fancy visual tricks.
Though the movie doesn't open until Friday, the trailer _ featuring
Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman, nude and fondling each other _ has
been causing a stir for months.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, a TV ad for the movie has debuted, showing Kidman
in her underwear and hinting at some kinky goings-on. And last
week, Time magazine devoted its cover and eight pages inside to
``Stanley Kubrick's haunting final masterpiece,'' calling it a
``Freudian interpretation of jealousy and sexual obsession.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there has always been sex on celluloid, from the
earliest, silent short subjects that depicted scandalously long
kisses and love triangles. By the early sound era, movies were
routinely trading on racy subject matter to lure viewers. Illicit
sexual affairs and scantily clad starlets were staples of a number
of movies in the early '30s.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as more recently, the industry was pressured to clean up
its act. To stave off government regulation, the Motion Picture
Producers and Distributors of America (MPPDA) set forth a strict,
voluntary set of standards. Often referred to as the Hays Code
(after MPPDA head Will H. Hays), the production code went into
effect in July 1934. It read like a Ten Commandments of ``thou
shalt nots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No picture shall be produced which will lower the standards of
those who see it,'' read one of the document's general principles.
``Indecent or undue exposure is forbidden .... Scenes of passion
should not be introduced when not essential to the plot ....
Excessive and lustful kissing, lustful embracing, suggestive
postures and gestures, are not to be shown,'' read some of the
code's other mandates.
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye ``It Girl'' Clara Bow and the lustful Mae West; hello
Donna Reed and Doris Day. According to ``Becoming Mae West'' by
Emily Wortis Leider (Farrar, Straus and Giroux, 1997) West's first
post-code picture, ``Goin' to Town,'' ``was put through the
wringer'' to clean up any possibly objectionable scenes, dialogue
and song lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, in 1936, William Randolph Hearst's papers
launched an all-out attack on the ``lewdness'' of West's ``Klondike
Annie.'' Soon after, Mae West parted ways with her studio.
Paramount couldn't stand the heat anymore, and Mae West without sex
just wasn't Mae West.
</P>
<P>
   There were occasional challenges to the absolute authority of
the production code during the next several decades (the code
remained in force until 1966). Movies such as Howard Hughes' 1943
film ``The Outlaw'' went right up to the edge of what was
acceptable. ``The Outlaw,'' remembered for the enduring image of a
ripe-and-ready Jane Russell reclining in hay, pushed code
boundaries with its very apparent obsession with Russell's ample
chest.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there remained a thriving industry that pumped out
low-budget, non-studio exploitation pictures, which were outside
the MPPDA's jurisdiction. This helps explain, for example, such
staples of the drive-in as women-in-prison movies.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the 1960s that vivid portrayals of sex
resurfaced in mainstream films. This was largely thanks to an
influx of young filmmakers who worshipped sexual liberation and
European cinema, which had always been much more open to sexual
content.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Hosoda, who has made it his life's mission to catalog
``where to find your favorite actresses and actors nude on
videotape'' through his self-published ``Bare Facts Video Guide,''
pegs the wave of nudity and sex that began to hit American cinema
in the '60s to such European films as ``I Am Curious (Yellow),'' a
1967 Swedish picture about the sexual adventures of a female
sociologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europeans are much more blase about sex and nudity ... . We're
kind of a puritanical country,'' said Hosoda, who is based in the
Silicon Valley area. ``These European films definitely influenced
American films ... (major actors such as) Jane Fonda and Jon Voight
started doing nudity.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Hollywood suddenly moved beyond the mild nudity and
double entendres of the previous couple of decades to frank
depictions of sexual perversity and fantasy: Mrs. Robinson (Anne
Bancroft) seducing Ben Braddock (Dustin Hoffman) in ``The
Graduate.'' Jane Fonda romping in next to nothing in
``Barbarella.'' Jon Voight playing a hustler in ``Midnight
Cowboy.'' European director Bernardo Bertolucci pushing the
envelope with ``Last Tango in Paris,'' starring Marlon Brando.
</P>
<P>
   This trend continued into the early '80s, when such pictures as
``American Gigolo'' were released. Richard Gere, the star of that
film, recently recalled, ``Everyone that was making that movie
(which came out in 1980) loved European films. It was perfectly
natural to us (to depict sex in a frank way). We thought it was
more aberrant to be like Doris Day and Rock Hudson. I mean, that
was weird.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the body-baring work of such actors as Gere, Voight and
Brando, Hosoda notes that most male nudity in American movies has
been for humor. ``Male nudity tends to be done for laughs: Almost
every comedian, starting wtih Gene Wilder and Marty Feldman, did
some nudity,'' Hosoda said.
</P>
<P>
   If male nudity from the beginning was kept a joke due to
Americans' discomfort with anything that could be construed as
homoerotic, most nudity and depictions of sex were soon to follow
into the ``for laughs'' vein. In its time, ``Tango'' wasn't just
explicit and kinky; according to its champions, it shattered social
conventions in its portrayal of two strangers who seek an
understanding of themselves through rather anonymous sex with one
another. Some cineastes even heralded such movies as ``Tango'' as
part of a new wave of pictures that would liberate American cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in search of the broad and predominantly young audience
that fueled the astounding box office for such pictures as ``Star
Wars,'' American films took a turn back in the other direction.
While nudity and sex stayed, it was played in a totally different
way. It was sex from an adolescent boy's perspective: naughty and
funny.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the multibillion-dollar porn film industry proves
that there is a big audience for pure, raw sex _ disproving any
notion that the more conservative tack in many of today's movies is
due to any such change in public taste. If anything, porn,
especially its easy availability in the home through video, may
have drained off some of the audience that attended sexy movies a
couple of decades ago just to ogle.
</P>
<P>
   More recent attempts to sell sex in mainstream movies such as
``Striptease'' and ``Showgirls'' have fared poorly at theaters,
though they've often made back their money on video.
</P>
<P>
   If it's box office the studios are after, it's doubtful we'll
see any significant return to '70s-style movies following the
opening of ``Eyes Wide Shut.'' Kubrick's films have not generally
been top-grossing hits, and ``Eyes'' will surely not outperform
such puerile summer films as ``Big Daddy.'' Will it be, as one
publication asked, ``the sexiest movie ever''? Maybe not. But it
may prove an interesting gauge for Americans' level of comfort with
real sexual issues, circa 1999. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. Though the late Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut'' doesn't
open until Friday, the trailer, featuring Nicole Kidman and Tom
Cruise nude, has been causing a stir for months. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
2. In the 1960s, Hollywood suddenly moved beyond mild nudity and
double entendres to such depictions as Mrs. Robinson (Anne
Bancroft) seducing Ben Braddock (Dustin Hoffman) in ``The
Graduate.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
3. In 1973, European director Bernardo Bertolucci pushed the
envelope with ``Last Tango in Paris,'' starring Marlon Brando and
Maria Schneider. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6813 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATH-HNS &LR;      07-12 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I'LL TAKE LIFE, THANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GERALD NACHMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Death is making a remarkable comeback, all
things considered. Life should be doing half so well.
</P>
<P>
   Dying, according to informed sources, has had a bum rap and
isn't nearly as negative an experience as previously imagined _
good news for the middle-aged.
</P>
<P>
   There was a day, within my own time line, when dying was
something people avoided until the very last moment, but things
have taken a turn for the better, kick-the-bucket-wise.
</P>
<P>
   Death is suddenly fashionable, like some kind of ultimate
weight-loss program. Grief counseling is a booming industry and
seminars on death and dying are popping up like '80s self-esteem
courses. An affirmative attitude toward dying is self-esteem's
final triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from recurring books on the subject, such as the
best-selling ``How We Die,'' wherein Dr. Sherwin Nuland describes
the down-and-dirty facts of death, we've been treated to two major
PBS series _ one on the big D itself, another on near-death
experiences. It made dying sound like such movies as ``Ghost,''
``Always,'' ``Heaven Can Wait,'' ``Truly, Madly, Deeply'' and
``Inventing Your Life.''
</P>
<P>
   They all portray dying as an experience not to be missed, where
a good time is had by all. There is much talk of dying as a
``journey'' _ not the familiar depressing trip whence no traveler
returns but, rather, as a neat ride at some terminal Tomorrowland.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, you're no longer alive, but death is likely to be far
more interesting than life. Or so it's been painted lately by
writers, movie directors and TV producers who know a good thing
when they see it and have begun to, well, beat the subject to
death.
</P>
<P>
   Dying, insist death's new public relations people, is just ``a
part of life,'' a transition, like graduation day, and shouldn't be
feared but graciously welcomed, like an uninvited wedding guest.
</P>
<P>
   I've read some of the pop death literature but, scaredy cat that
I am, I still tiptoe around the topic.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a big sissy about dying. If only I could learn to relax
about death, I might enjoy the sensation, yet I'm an old-fashioned
guy when it comes to my own demise. Frankly, the more happy talk I
hear about death, the more I worry. When it comes to goodbyes, I
still tend to get all teary-eyed, especially when it's me that's
heading off for eternity.
</P>
<P>
   Even death's jolly spin doctors _ Nuland, Kubler-Ross and Jack
Kevorkian _ confess that dying has its down side, but even ``Dr.
Death'' somehow has made the subject newsworthy, almost
titillating.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, all those poor souls eventually died, but what matters is
that they ``died with dignity,'' which always sounds as if they lay
on their death beds in tuxes and cocktail dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Dying with dignity _ that's the ticket for the enlightened
Nineties. Grab your coat and get your hat, leave your worries on
the doorstep, just traverse your feet, to the shady side of the
street!
</P>
<P>
   Dying with dignity, maintains the pro-death faction, is less
painful than regulation croaking. Instead of gasping those final
breaths, one now has the option of going out with head held high,
laughing at the Grim Reaper all the way to the graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   Much was said of how Jacqueline Kennedy and Richard Nixon
``taught us how to die.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm probably just a slow learner but I haven't quite got the
knack of it yet. I haven't learned to ``come to terms with death.''
Yet death, says Nuland, ``is not the enemy, disease is.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry to split hairs here, Doc, but I say death is the ultimate
heavy.
</P>
<P>
   While it would be lovely to say ``au revoir'' in style and give
the deceased a proper sendoff (``Champagne for the entire intensive
care unit!''), death does tend to make a man cranky.
</P>
<P>
   It is bad enough to watch the nightly news update of people
being killed in ingenious new ways without having to endure talk
shows that want you to feel cheerier about expiring, advising us to
think of death as a sort of apres-Golden Years. The premise seems
to be that, since death gets us all sooner or later, let's make
death our little friend, so as to demystify it.
</P>
<P>
   Me, I'm all for mystifying death as much as possible. I don't
care to know the details of my final days, nor do I plan to go
smiling into that good night.
</P>
<P>
   I'll worry about all that when the final knock comes. It will
give me something to do while I wait, instead of thumbing old
copies of Today's Health.
</P>
<P>
   I have made out both a dying will and a living will. But that's
all the will I can muster right now about the actual ``dying
process'' _ as the neo-deadheads call it, as if discussing the fine
points of making cheddar cheese.
</P>
<P>
   I much prefer death to remain a nice big fat surprise, just like
good old life itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6816 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SEX-LADN     07-12 1425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SEX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX AND CINEMA GO HAND IN HAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARLA MATZER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Most of the movies hyped as ``must-sees'' in
recent years have been of the sci-fi, special effects genre: movies
like ``Godzilla'' and ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
