into the ``for laughs'' vein. In its time, ``Tango'' wasn't just
explicit and kinky; according to its champions, it shattered social
conventions in its portrayal of two strangers who seek an
understanding of themselves through rather anonymous sex with one
another. Some cineastes even heralded such movies as ``Tango'' as
part of a new wave of pictures that would liberate American cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in search of the broad and predominantly young audience
that fueled the astounding box office for such pictures as ``Star
Wars,'' American films took a turn back in the other direction.
While nudity and sex stayed, it was played in a totally different
way. It was sex from an adolescent boy's perspective: naughty and
funny.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the multibillion-dollar porn film industry proves
that there is a big audience for pure, raw sex _ disproving any
notion that the more conservative tack in many of today's movies is
due to any such change in public taste. If anything, porn,
especially its easy availability in the home through video, may
have drained off some of the audience that attended sexy movies a
couple of decades ago just to ogle.
</P>
<P>
   More recent attempts to sell sex in mainstream movies such as
``Striptease'' and ``Showgirls'' have fared poorly at theaters,
though they've often made back their money on video.
</P>
<P>
   If it's box office the studios are after, it's doubtful we'll
see any significant return to '70s-style movies following the
opening of ``Eyes Wide Shut.'' Kubrick's films have not generally
been top-grossing hits, and ``Eyes'' will surely not outperform
such puerile summer films as ``Big Daddy.'' Will it be, as one
publication asked, ``the sexiest movie ever''? Maybe not. But it
may prove an interesting gauge for Americans' level of comfort with
real sexual issues, circa 1999. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. Though the late Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut'' doesn't
open until Friday, the trailer, featuring Nicole Kidman and Tom
Cruise nude, has been causing a stir for months. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
2. In the 1960s, Hollywood suddenly moved beyond mild nudity and
double entendres to such depictions as Mrs. Robinson (Anne
Bancroft) seducing Ben Braddock (Dustin Hoffman) in ``The
Graduate.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
3. In 1973, European director Bernardo Bertolucci pushed the
envelope with ``Last Tango in Paris,'' starring Marlon Brando and
Maria Schneider. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6837 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVIS-COURIER-2ND     07-12 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-COURIER-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... the Aussies, too.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tangibly obvious is the way he has grown into the role of the
American Mr. Davis Cup, once occupied (much more hysterically) by
John McEnroe. McEnroe anointed Courier the other day as ``The guy
who's making Americans interested in the Cup again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever anxious to answer the call of country, and nearly always
successful, McEnroe, however, often carried combativeness too far
and was a walking international incident. That's one reason Courier
is the best choice for the captaincy when the time arrives for
Gullikson to step down.
</P>
<P>
   An example: McEnroe antagonized the French by calling them
``frogs'' and less complimentary names. Courier charmed them by a
singular act of an American champion in Paris, giving his trophy
acceptance speeches in French. It helped that he had a French
girlfriend at the time _ the preferred method for learning any
language _ but it was also an indication that this high school
dropout has made far more of his travels than virtually all of his
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   A cosmopolite, he seeks out the essence of the countries he
visits. Not easy, even for a curious James. An athlete, naturally
concerned with being ready to work, will understandably confine
himself to hotel, rest, practice, the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is too interesting to limit yourself to tennis,'' says
un-tunnelized Courier, an avid reader, musician _ ``of sorts,
guitar and drums'' _ listener to all music, rock to Rachmaninoff,
and explorer of foreign lands.
</P>
<P>
   That his tympanic Backside Boogie _ shuffle left to drill an
inside-out forehand diagonally to the right corner _ is functioning
forcefully once more is ``gratifying.'' He terrorized the world
with that shot for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be back in good health again is very gratifying,'' he says.
``I'm not concerned about being No. 1 again, but I sure didn't like
going down so far. It was mostly injuries that did it. The worst
was the sore right bicep that plagued me for a couple of years.
Doctors couldn't figure it out. It was really frustrating. I
decided it was up to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Courier _ heal thyself. And he did, ``by reforming myself
and my rackets. Balls we use have gotten generally heavier. I had
to catch up with the trend. I did more weight-lifting to increase
my strength. Then Jay Schweid, the master stringer, and I started
tweaking my rackets. What were the variables? It was trial and
error, but after a lot of tweaking we came up with a heavier
racket, 4-5 grams, and looser stringing, and the pain went away. We
design them and Jay gets them custom-made at a factory in Asia. I
haven't endorsed a racket since '89. These are distinctive, right
out of the Schweid-Courier book.''
</P>
<P>
   Courier's bookish habit earned him a few knocks in 1993 at the
ATP Championships in Frankfurt. He brought a novel onto court and
perused it during a changeover while losing to Andrei Medvedev. It
was his 90 seconds of leisure, wasn't it? Karsten Braasch, the
iconoclastic German, used to smoke an occasional cigarette between
games. No rules govern that brief sojourn. But literature and
nicotine are discouraged pastimes at play.
</P>
<P>
   At Birmingham, Courier was reading (not on court) ``The Perfect
Storm,'' and he lived up to that title. Currently he's deep into
the Japanese novelist Murakami's ``Hard Boiled Wonderland and the
End of the World'' (the English version; his Japanese vocabulary
doesn't go much beyond sushi). Surely Courier intends to transform
Longwood into a hard-boiled wonderland run by the homebodies and a
world's end for the Aussies' '99 shot at a 27th Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't read too much into these titles,'' he advises.
</P>
<P>
   OK, but Davis Cup has been on his mind since boyhood (something
that never afflicted Sampras until, the tardy volunteer says,
``Birmingham inspired me'').
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 11 when I went to Harry Hopman's tennis camp at Bardmore
(Fla.), and that's where I was first aware of the Cup,'' Courier
says. ``Of course, Mr. Hopman was the all-time captain of those
great Australian teams of the '50s and '60s, and he told us it was
the greatest thing in tennis to play for your country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later, when I moved in at Nick's (the Bollettieri boot camp at
Bradenton) we all would watch Cup matches on TV when two of Nick's
kids, Aaron Krickstein and Jimmy Arias, were playing for the US. It
seemed terrific, a different, more exciting atmosphere than a
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got my first live taste when I went to Peru as a team
sparring partner in 1988, Andre's (Agassi) debut. Latin America was
something else, very nationalistic, loud. They put me on to play an
exhibition the second day against one of their guys, Alejandro
Aramburo. It was an (exhibition), no pressure on me. But they were
his home folks in Lima, and he choked badly. I won quick, and felt
sorry for him.''
</P>
<P>
   He felt sorry for himself in the din of Mexico City, glad that
Gilbert took him, the rook, off the hook. But by 1997 Courier was
blooded. He savored the drums and clamor of Brazil, the fervently
patriotic crowds at Ribeirao Preto, where he responded by sticking
out that husky, try-and-beat-me chest and carried the weekend by
stopping the boys from that hood, Fernando Meligeni in five, and
French Open champ-to-be Guga Kuerten in a long four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that kind of atmosphere, and I hope it's that way at
Longwood _ for us. Though Courier doesn't approach McEnroe's US Cup
singles record (16-9 to 41-8), he has been Crunch Man big time,
scoring the decisive win in five of those 13 victories during his
team streak. Thrice, more than any other American, he has succeeded
in the super pressure cooker of an ultimate fifth match with the
score 2-2: over Jacco Eltingh at Rotterdam in 1994; Russian Marat
Safin at Atlanta last year; Rusedski at Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   The incomparable imbroglio with Australia very well could come
down to a fifth match Sunday, Courier facing off with the kid,
Hewitt. Courier would salivate. So would all the bag boys across
the US because this unassuming, small-town kamikaze guy is the
people's choice as a tennis player.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
