<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6838 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-12 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WARNING ON THE COMING BUDGET-PRIORITY TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- For the most part, news that the president and
congressional leaders are about to start serious talks about
national priorities for the next decade is reason to cheer.
</P>
<P>
   By definition, serious talk leading to serious action on the
basic shape of a force as huge as the $1.5 trillion federal
government has almost always had to be bipartisan and collegial.
And that tends to be for the better.
</P>
<P>
   But not now, and certainly not this week. In fact, a grand
budget deal between President Clinton and the Republican Congress,
giving each side the core of what it wants, would run a large risk
of being the worst imaginable outcome for the country, threatening
one of the main pillars of the current prosperity _ a responsible
fiscal policy.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at the first topic that each side wants to bring up if
both indeed start talking this week as planned. The Republicans
want to talk about tax cuts, and the president wants to discuss
changing and expanding Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   One side has priorities that, whatever their merits, reduce
revenues substantially; the other has priorities that, whatever
their merits, increase expenditures substantially. The most common
GOP tax-cut dream is worth at least $800 billion over the next
decade; the net cost of the Clinton Medicare package is $374
billion over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   They are reconcilable, even if pared back, only if the two sides
decide to use a projected operating budget ``surplus'' that
currently exists only as a projection by each side, based on some
of the most crackpot assumptions in the history of federal
budgeting. The current shorthand in politics and journalism, that
they have $1 trillion to fool around with, is nuts.
</P>
<P>
   I can't believe this will happen. I particularly can't believe
that Clinton would place at risk one of his most significant
accomplishments _ a fiscal policy that has directly liberated a
trillion dollars or so for investment by the private sector, and a
lowering of interest rates that has freed up even more.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more than enough deal-making talk to raise a red
flag.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the news is alarming. Within the Social Security system,
revenues continue to outpace benefits payments, and will continue
to do so for many years, given a decent economy. And there is
almost a bipartisan agreement to use all of whatever surplus there
is only within the system to pay down federal debt.
</P>
<P>
   That's fantastic. It is no substitute for inevitable change, but
down the road this responsible act of walling off Social Security
surpluses will make change vastly less wrenching for future
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The red flag needs to be raised about blank ink beginning to
show up outside Social Security. To say there is roughly $1
trillion to play with over the next 10 years is madness. Here's
why.
</P>
<P>
   When the last, relatively small steps were taken two years ago
to balance the overall budget, Congress and Clinton also agreed to
increase spending on some agreed on priorities like education and
to cut income taxes primarily for working families with children.
</P>
<P>
   To make the numbers work, however, they reintroduced two
dangerous concepts from the crazy, triple-digit-deficit 1980s _ the
rosy scenario and the magic asterisk.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, the deal makers severely tightened the spending
caps that regulate spending that is subject to annual
appropriations. They then assumed that these ``savings'' they had
made on paper would continue into the future.
</P>
<P>
   This is a slight variation on the fictions used by Ronald Reagan
and Congress starting in 1981. Back then, budgets were ``balanced''
on the assumption of economic performance that everyone knew would
not occur (the rosy scenario) as well as by a spending category
usually marked with an asterisk (savings to be proposed later).
</P>
<P>
   This time around, the rosy scenario involves spending, and the
magic asterisk is the same. That's because not one dime from the
tighter caps has in fact been saved; all the action since the 1997
deal has been in the other direction _ for the military, for
highways, for airports, for farmers. Some $21 billion in add-ons
last year were called ``emergencies'' to dodge the rules, and
another $20 billion-plus has already been approved this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``surplus'' outside Social Security assumes cutting
overall appropriations below this year's level for the upcoming
fiscal year, making further cuts in non-inflated terms for each of
the next two years, and then keeping the caps at no more than the
inflation rate after 2002.
</P>
<P>
   For the year 2000, there isn't a Republican or a Democrat who
believes congressional majorities exist or should exist to pass
bills specifically establishing these caps in the coming weeks. And
yet the ``surplus'' not only assumes it, it assumes caps all the
way through the year 2009 that are lower in uninflated dollars than
the ceilings for the year 2002 that everyone treats as a joke.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has at least proposed adjusting the caps
realistically, adding a higher cigarette tax and other changes that
at least constitute an idea. But he has made his proposals to a
dysfunctional Congress under Republican control. The Republican
direction, which both assumes the ``surplus'' for a decade and
seeks nearly a trillion dollars in tax cuts, makes the 1980s look
responsible by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   That's why a deal that tries to accommodate the two political
parties could be so dangerous. The alternative _ doing as little as
possible beyond protecting Social Security _ is minimalist, but
preferable.
</P>
<P>
   And that would leave the question of national priorities for the
next decade to the presidential campaign, in the admittedly
quixotic hope that the candidates might discuss the future
specifically and responsibly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
