<HEADER>
A6839 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVIS-SAMPRAS-2TA     07-12 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-SAMPRAS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO. 1 IS NO LONGER TOP PRIORITY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They'd finished their private practice session at the Harry
Hopman Tennis Academy in Tampa, winding down a week of leisurely
preparation for the clay-court season, and now Pete Sampras and his
coach, Paul Annacone, were killing time in their condominium at the
Saddlebrook resort.
</P>
<P>
   As they lounged on the couch, Annacone picked up the remote and
started channel-surfing. Horse racing. Click. Baseball. Click.
Hockey. Click. Tennis. Cli . . . Wait a minute. This might be
interesting. Or lethal.
</P>
<P>
   Annacone waited to see whether Sampras would grab the control
and hurl it through the screen. There was no reaction, violent or
otherwise. So Annacone kept the station tuned to the United States'
first-round Davis Cup series in Birmingham, England.
</P>
<P>
   The series Jim Courier, Todd Martin, and Alex O'Brien were
playing for the Americans. The series they were supposed to lose.
The series Sampras had been asked to play by captain Tom Gullikson
and US Tennis Association president Julia Levering, who both had
made visits to his Los Angeles home _ an unusual gesture for a
captain, an unprecedented one for a USTA head _ three months ago at
the start of the year. The series Sampras had refused to play,
publicly proclaiming that Davis Cup was not a priority for him, not
compared to winning Grand Slam events and preserving his world No.
1 ranking; then he'd skipped the year's first major, the Australian
Open, citing fatigue, only to show up on national television
convalescing by playing 90 holes of golf in the Bob Hope Desert
Classic. The series that had prompted Gullikson to say upon
arriving in Birmingham, ``You'd think he'd look at me and see my
brother'' _ making the snub personal by invoking the ghost of his
twin, Tim Gullikson, who had been Sampras's coach, mentor, and
spiritual guide before dying of brain cancer in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The series that had made Pete Sampras a pariah in American
tennis circles, denounced for selfishness, disloyalty, and being
downright unpatriotic.
</P>
<P>
   Annacone had not really expected Sampras to go ballistic; he
wasn't one to betray his emotions one way or another. But he
noticed that Sampras was as focused on the screen as he was,
sensing the same things he did. That the excitement and tension in
Birmingham fairly burst through the tube. That the Americans were
waging a positively heroic battle against Britain's best, Tim
Henman and Greg Rusedski, and darn it if they might not win this
thing somehow. That the nationalism and teamwork, so contrary to
the nature of singles tennis, were real and significant, at least
on selected weekends like this first one in April.
</P>
<P>
   So Annacone figured this might be the proper time to lay out
some career options for his player. Gently, of course, for he had
noticed some subtle changes in Sampras's demeanor toward the end of
1998. That's when Sampras did something he'd never done: played six
weeks in a row, slummed through the European indoor circuit in Lyon
and Vienna and Stuttgart and Paris, all to satisfy an objective
that had come to consume him _ surpassing Jimmy Connors's record
and ending up as No. 1 in the world for a sixth straight year. It
had been a singular opportunity, Annacone realized, and Sampras had
made it, had seized his place in history. But at what expense? He'd
grown more irritable over little things, more impatient about
inevitable travel inconveniences that he used to shrug off, and he
wasn't eating well. So God only knew how he'd react to this pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't you like to be there, with that type of intensity and
atmosphere,'' Annacone said to Sampras as he pointed to the
captivating drama in Birmingham playing out before them, ``instead
of in some first-rounder in San Jose or Scottsdale?''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't even sure Sampras had heard him. His condo mate was
transfixed by the screen. ``Listen to that noise,'' was all Sampras
said.
</P>
<P>
   So Annacone kept prodding. ``Wouldn't you like to be part of
that?'' he asked. ``You've got a choice, Pete. You can play in
matches that really matter to you and maybe risk the No. 1 ranking.
Or you can grind it out at all those little tournaments to protect
your ranking and maybe shorten your career by a year or two. It's
up to you.''
</P>
<P>
   They parted that weekend without anything being settled.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gullikson picked up his phone at home a week later. He was
still feeling the exhilaration of the Birmingham bombshell, the
palpitating 3-2 US upset that had gone extra innings, as it were,
coming down to an 8-6 Courier win over Rusedski in the fifth set of
the deciding match. Next up for the United States was a
quarterfinal against Australia at Longwood Cricket Club in
Brookline in July to commemorate the centennial of the year
Bostonian Dwight Davis donated the cup symbolizing international
team tennis supremacy. But Gullikson wasn't thinking about that
just yet. He was still savoring the unlikely triumph, still
accepting kudos _ none unlikelier than this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations,'' Pete Sampras said on the other end of the
phone. ``That was terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson thanked him and figured that was that. It never had
been personal, anyway, despite his reference to Tim. Tennis was one
thing, friendship another, and he and Sampras always would be
friends _ and this certainly was a nice gesture. He prepared to
hang up.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and one other thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to play Davis Cup,'' Sampras said. ``Just doubles. If
it's OK with you and Jim and Todd.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Was it OK? Sampras will be in Brookline next weekend, alongside
his American teammates _ Courier, Martin, and O'Brien _ to face the
Australian side of Patrick Rafter, Lleyton Hewitt, and the Mark
Woodforde-Todd Woodbridge doubles duo.
</P>
<P>
   Was it OK?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great for Pete,'' says Gullikson. ``I think it's
great for the US Davis Cup team. I think it's great for tennis.
We've got the No. 1 player in the world of the last six years.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, that again. It turns out that Sampras's obsessive
achievement will dilute his gallantry. He insisted on playing
exclusively doubles because he didn't want to step on the toes of
Courier and Martin, who got the Americans this far. ``Those guys
are the reason we're playing in Boston,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He even called Courier and Martin to seek their blessing. ``I'm
willing to play for the year and I'm willing to play doubles,'' he
told them, ``and if you're not comfortable with that, I won't be a
party of it. I don't want to ruffle anyone's feathers.''
</P>
<P>
   But enough of this noble nonsense. Gullikson never accepted
Sampras's proviso; he only granted permission _ in about a
nanosecond after the offer was made _ for Sampras to join the team.
Anyway, after losing in the Wimbledon quarterfinals, Martin
volunteered to defer to Sampras in singles, saying he'd felt all
along Sampras should be used in that role. And Gullikson has
maintained from the start that the decision on how he deploys his
lineup will be his alone. So Sampras probably will play doubles
Saturday. And he'll definitely play singles Friday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
