<HEADER>
A6840 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMITH-COLUMN-TEX     07-12 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IS REALLY COOL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK Z. SMITH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was roughly 35 years ago, as a teen-ager, that I became
strongly aware of the perils of tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a freshman in high school in 1964, the U.S. surgeon
general released a headline-making report that cited cigarette
smoking as the leading cause of death from lung cancer and as a
major contributor to emphysema and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, I read an article in Reader's Digest titled
``I Am Joe's Lungs.'' It somberly detailed how cigarette smoking
destroys alveoli, tiny air sacs in the lungs that are critical to
breathing. If I had any lingering doubts about the dangers of
smoking, that article vanquished them.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy of smoking would later be brought home to me in a
much more personal way. Both my father and an aunt died in their
late 50s. Longtime smoking habits contributed to their
unnecessarily premature deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Even with those experiences in my background, I had mixed
emotions about a courtroom verdict in Miami on Wednesday that could
prove a big-time headache for Big Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   A jury concluded that the nation's five largest tobacco
companies showed ``extreme and outrageous conduct'' by selling
cigarettes and other products that they knew caused fatal illnesses
such as lung cancer and emphysema.
</P>
<P>
   In upcoming phases of the trial, the jury potentially could
decide to award billions of dollars in damages to hundreds of
thousands of current and former Florida smokers whose health has
been damaged by tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are being sued for $200 billion. The case is
especially significant because it is the first class-action lawsuit
by smokers ever to go to trial. If the plaintiffs win, it could
trigger a wave of new class-action litigation by smokers in other
states and put renewed pressure on government officials to clamp
down on tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
   I must admit that, for the most part, I reveled in the Miami
jury verdict. I have little respect for the tobacco industry. I
could not in good conscience work in such an industry.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it's hard to be wholly sympathetic to the
smokers suing the tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe that most people who grew up in the United
States in the last several decades could have been totally unaware
of the dangers of smoking when they took up the habit _ even if
they were only young teen-agers when they did so.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the surgeon general's report in 1964, there was
substantial research indicating that smoking was a no-no for those
who wanted to live a long, healthy life. Logic would dictate that
the tobacco industry would die a natural death from a lack of
customers even if cigarettes were a penny a pack.
</P>
<P>
   In the Miami lawsuit, the plaintiffs contend that the tobacco
industry conspired to hide the danger and addictiveness of
cigarettes. Indeed, there is little doubt in my mind that the
industry has sought for decades to distort the truth and conceal
damaging information about tobacco's ill effects.
</P>
<P>
   But let's face it, for the tobacco industry to attempt to hide
the dangers of smoking is like an elephant trying to hide the fact
that it's big. It's been painfully obvious for decades that tobacco
is a killer.
</P>
<P>
   So when I see on an American Lung Association Web site that the
number of American teen-age smokers is estimated at 4 million or
more, I shudder.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, I posed this question to my 20-year-old, non-smoking
daughter: What possesses so many young people to take up smoking,
when they almost inevitably must know that it is a nasty,
expensive, life-shortening habit?
</P>
<P>
   ``They just think it looks cool,'' she informed me.
</P>
<P>
   That brought my dad to mind. A star athlete in high school who
was very physically fit in his younger years, he told me he started
smoking at age 18 because... he thought it looked cool. By the time
he had a major heart attack at age 51, and a cardiologist insisted
he stop smoking immediately, he didn't think tobacco was quite so
cool anymore. He quit smoking that very day and never puffed
another cigarette. But the ravages of a sustained 33-year nicotine
habit already had taken their toll and almost certainly contributed
to the massive heart attack that killed him seven years later.
</P>
<P>
   Once you start smoking, it's hard to stop. The American Lung
Association estimates that, of the 47 million Americans who smoke,
31 million would like to stop.
</P>
<P>
   But the good news is that an estimated 44 million adults are
ex-smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's cool.
</P>
<P>
   (Jack Z. Smith is an editorial writer and columnist for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. He can be reached at (817) 390-7724 or
jzsmith(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
