<HEADER>
A6843 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-WOOD-BOS &LR;      07-12 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAIGHT FROM `THE WOOD' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It &UR;  &LR; all started with a student film called ``Blacktop Lingo.''
Executives at Sundance Institute had gotten an eyeful of Rick
Famuyiwa's short at the 1996 Sundance film festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It explores the connection between basketball and jazz music
in a very original way,'' remembers Michelle Satter, director of
Sundance Institute's feature-film program. ``It made us very
excited about him.''
</P>
<P>
   They were so excited that a year later the 1996 graduate of the
University of Southern California's film school was still on
Sundance executives' minds as they tried to fill about 10 slots in
its summer filmmaking lab. (Sundance gets about 3,000 applications
a year for the program.)
</P>
<P>
   Sundance representatives tried calling Famuyiwa, but the
telephone numbers were always disconnected. They tracked him down
to different addresses, but no luck. Famuyiwa had moved two or
three times that past year.
</P>
<P>
   Famuyiwa and Sundance finally came together when a college
friend of Famuyiwa's sent the organization an application. A
tenacious Sundance associate recognized the friend's name from the
credits in ``Blacktop Lingo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were like, `Oh, do you still keep in contact with Rick?'
'' recalls Famuyiwa, during a recent telephone conversation from
Los Angeles. ``He was like, `Yeah, I work with him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Both were salesmen at a Los Angeles Niketown, a popular stop for
recent USC and UCLA graduates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was selling shoes,'' says Famuyiwa, who recently turned 26,
laughing. ``I needed to pay the bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Famuyiwa sent Sundance a copy of his coming-of-age screenplay
``The Wood,'' which he had co-written with USC professor Todd Boyd.
Over the next two years, Famuyiwa fine-tuned the script at
Sundance, got MTV Films interested in producing the movie, and
hired young actors Omar Epps, Taye Diggs, and Sean Nelson for key
roles. All that work finally pays off when the film opens this
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Famuyiwa still seems surprised by his relatively fast rise from
talented USC student to first-time director of a studio film. The
trajectory has landed him on a short list of young black Hollywood
filmmakers that includes John Singleton, the Hughes brothers, and
Kasi Lemmons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought I would maybe raise the money'' to make ``The
Wood'' himself, says Famuyiwa, ``or go to an independent company
like Working Title or Good Machine and get my litle budget and
no-name actors and make my film. For it to happen this way is
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Satter links Famuyiwa's success to his ``grounded'' personality.
On the phone, he speaks slowly and deliberately, laughing easily
and often. But he's a talker who doesn't need much urging to chat
about details in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a great energy,'' says Satter. ``He's a big guy, but
he has a real kindnes. You can see it in the film. It has great
heart and humor to it. You feel that you're seeing his vision and
his self on the screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Boyd, who's morphed from Famuyiwa's professor to friend to
writing partner and producer since meeting him in 1992, ``I think
Rick has a very unique perspective. His parents immigrated to
America from Nigeria _ I always call him the true African-American.
I think because of that he has a unique view on life. What makes
good filmmakers is people who have a view that's outside of the
mainstream, or outside of the norm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wood'' tells the tale of three twentysomething buddies who
summon up memories of their friendship hours before one of them is
scheduled to traipse down the aisle. Like many first-time
filmmakers, Famuyiwa wrote about what he knew.
</P>
<P>
   The story is set n ``the Wood,'' the black, middle-class
neighborhood in Inglewood, Calif., where Famuyiwa grew up. And yes,
it's based on the reaction Famuyiwa had when one of his two best
friends from his teenage years announced he was getting married.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until that point you're just going full steam ahead,'' he
explains. ``It was the first time I looked back and said `Wow, you
know, we've been through a lot in the time we've known each other.'
''
</P>
<P>
   During those formative years, Famuyima didn't dream of having a
film career. He loved movies growing up, but ``I never saw
filmmaking as a viable option. . . . I had no idea you could go to
school for film. The concept was, like, foreign to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to Famuyiwa's mom, Florence, to remember the movie
camera she had purchased for her 11-year-old son. He used it to
make silent films with his younger brother. But when Famuyiwa
entered USC, he was a basketball-playing political-science major
with an eye on law school.
</P>
<P>
   That changed when Famuyiwa discovered that he was attending a
college with what he modestly calls a ``pretty good'' film school.
He took some classes, saw some films _ he remembers ``JFK'' in
particular _ and was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just remember all the controversy and discussion and debate
surrounding'' Oliver Stone's movie about the Kennedy assassination,
says Famuyiwa. ``I felt that would be a great thing to do, to kind
of affect people in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   Famuyiwa found his mother surprisingly supportive of his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it comforted her that there was an actual degree you
could get in it,'' says Famuyiwa. He'd slip his mother USC
pamphlets bragging that 80 percent of the film school graduates
wound up working in the business. ``I don't know where they got
that figure from,'' he adds dubiously. ``But, you know, I guess
even if you're a PA (production assistant, a low-level support
staffer), they consider that work.''
</P>
<P>
   There were some tough times, however. Famuyiwa spent two years
after school writing and pitching stories to the studios. That
period included his infamous Niketown stint. The memory now makes
Florence Famuyiwa chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were like sad days,'' she says. ``I was like, `God,
what's going on? This kid went to a very reputable school. He did
very well.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Famuyiwa wasn't always impressed with the Hollywood he
encountered during that time. While he acknowledges that the
industry has become more open to African-American talent, he
believes many executives are willing to showcase blacks only in B
movies with comedic or violent ghetto content.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was one producer in particular who produced one of these
hip-hop comedies,'' said Famuyiwa. ``His whole idea was black
audiences are sophisticated, but I guess not sophisticated enough
to embrace things other than `Booty Call' and `How to Be a Player.'
''
</P>
<P>
   The recent failures of ``Beloved'' and ``Why Do Fools Fall in
Love'' have only made things worse, says Famuyiwa: ``The kind of
roles and scripts and stories that are being sold and are being
embraced are quite often not really of high quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Famuyiwa had a different vision, so he eagerly grabbed the
opportunity to develop ``The Wood'' through Sundance's rigorous
filmmaker's lab. For four weeks in the summer of 1997, a group of
creative advisers _ it included directors Jon Amiel and Michael
Apted, casting director Mali Finn, and actors Kathy Bates and
Denzel Washington _ aided Famuyiwa in casting, shooting, editing a
few scenes from the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say USC was my undergraduate experience and Sundance
was my graduate school,'' says Famuyiwa. ``You make films at USC
but (Sundance) is the first time you get a chance to make films in
the process that you do professionally.''
</P>
<P>
   The smooth ``lab'' experience carried over to the set when ``The
Wood'' was finally shot. (Producers Ron Yerxa and Albert Berger
brought the script to MTV after seeing it performed at an LA
screenplay reading sponsored by Sundance.) The only difference,
Famuyiwa says, was the addition of politics as he dealt with the
studio and a gaggle of agents and managers for the actors.
</P>
<P>
   As Famuyiwa awaits reaction to ``The Wood,'' he's keeping busy.
He's already working on a new romantic comedy. And there's some
interest in transforming ``The Wood'' into a television show.
Famuyiwa and Boyd are now writing a pilot for the project.
</P>
<P>
   But the ever-humble Famuyiwa isn't getting too excited about his
blossoming television career. At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``After looking at this past fall's schedule, this might just be
an exercise,'' he says, laughing. ``You know, I thought it was bad
in films, but television is like completely white. . . . There are
no ethnic characters, stories or anything. It's kind of amazing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
