<HEADER>
A6845 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-OZ-2TAKES-BOS &LR;      07-12 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-OZ-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER SEASON IN OZ 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Augustus Hill, a dreadlocked young black inmate in a wheelchair,
is being bound with rope by some white men. Augustus is angry _
perennially seething _ but he sits impassively, stoically. Behind
him hangs a large Confederate flag. His hands are tied, then his
feet, with the kind of thick rope someone might use for a lynching.
The knots are pulled tight. It's a disconcerting scene _ even if
Augustus Hill is a fictional character played by actor Harold
Perrineau, and even if this is all taking place on a television
soundstage.
</P>
<P>
   And . . . action. Hill looks the camera in the eye, telling a
story directly to the viewer: It seems this truck full of ``Aryan''
males, the driver being the son of a neo-Nazi fellow inmate in
Hill's prison, Oz, has roped a black man to a truck and dragged him
to his death.
</P>
<P>
   Guess who's coming to Oz?
</P>
<P>
   ``Prisoner number 99S333, Andrew Peter Schillinger,'' intones
Hill of the driver. ``Convicted February 16th, '99, murder in the
second degree, possession of narcotics. Sentence, 50 years. Up for
parole in 20.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the way every episode of the HBO series ``Oz'' begins:
with Hill, the narrator, introducing us to a new prisoner or the
current conflict in the prison. The ``Oz'' folks call this bit
``the box.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ugly,'' says the director, Keith Samples, sitting 30 feet
in front of Parrineau, as another take of ``the box'' is shot.
</P>
<P>
   The show's creator and co-executive producer, Tom Fontana,
smiles and says, ``That's the `Oz' motto: `Simple, but sick.' ''
The dragging scene was shot earlier the day, near dawn, in
Brooklyn. Everyone knew they were creating a raw echo of a
horrifying real-life crime, the one that last summer took the lilfe
of James Byrd Jr. in Texas. Cast members said everyone wanted to
get it done as quickly as they could, with as few takes as
possible. There's a good deal of humor flying around the set where
``the box'' is shot, but there wasn't out there on the Brooklyn
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to ``Oz.'' The name is short for Oswald State
Correctional Facility: Level Four, and inside Oz is a special
community of prisoners who live in an innovative zone called
Emerald City. It is bright and clean, with no cell decorations
permitted and doors made with unbreakable glass, not bars. (Fontana
modeled it after a New Jersey facility.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Oz,'' which starts its third season on HBO this week
(Wednesday, 10 p.m., with repeats on Thursday, Saturday, and next
Monday), is the best-written, hardest-edged drama on TV these days,
network or cable. (Due to its harsh content, of course, it could
only be made for cable.) It has also become a showcase for
actor-directors such as Matt Dillon and Chazz Palminteri. It's one
of the best ensemble dramas ever written for the medium. And it is
the most brutal. The violence shown in previous seasons has
included a bloody riot, a crucifixion, brandings, rapes, a naked
man strung up with carvings in his chest. You may or may not see
the full act of violence, but ``Oz'' never flinches from
dramatizing its consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Moreno, who plays one of the show's kind characters, Sister
Peter Marie Reimondo, says her mother has seen the show just once _
out of respect for her daughter _ but that's it. ``Oz'' is a
hellish place to be.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it as a drama that has the magnified impact of ``Scared
Straight.'' This place is no fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right,'' agrees Fontana. He's seen other prison movies,
but says the famous documentary starring inmates ``is the movie I
remember seeing and being very impressed by.''
</P>
<P>
   The fictional land of ``Oz'' is located in an unspecified state
prison. All the interior scenes are shot on the 60,000-square-foot
sixth floor of the Chelsea Market building on Ninth Avenue in
Manhattan. When they're not on the set, the main actors hunker down
in tiny cell-like dressing rooms. ``You don't see daylight,'' says
Eammon Walker, who plays prisoner Kareem Said. ``It's like living
in prison. We see each other all the time, we breathe each other
in.'' They film about 8 to 12 minutes of footage a day. Each
episode costs about $1 million. About 50 actors pass through in a
season; another 100 may be hired as extra prisoners or guards.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Oz,'' everyone _ prisoners, guards, visitors _ is on edge.
It's a world of competing cliques and warring ethnic factions,
tribe against tribe. Black thugs, black Muslims, neo-Nazis, the
Italians, the Latinos, a couple of Irish, a couple of old-guy
lifers. This season _ which will focus on the inmates and their
families outside _ a Russian mobster joins them. There's one woman,
a beguiling nymphomaniac/killer mom who's on death row. Liaisons
are struck, deals are made, drugs are snorted, alliances are
formed. Between the prisoners, with the guards, who are far from
scrupulous. Those relationships _ always contracts in mutual
interests _ are often shattered. Betrayal is just around the
corner. Everyone's a con man. Today's victim is tomorrow's
victimizer. It's one endless vicious cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The life expectancy in `Oz' is not all that great,'' deadpans
actor J. K. Simmons, who plays the neo-Nazi Vern Schillinger,
father of the hate killer who will be joining the population.
</P>
<P>
   The show is not easy to watch, especially when the violence
escalates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have a responsibility,'' says Fontana, ``that if I
am going to do violence, then that violence should be terrifying
and everybody watching that goes, `Oh my God, I don't ever want to
be close to that.' I want to be shocking, but I don't want it to
have a half-life. I want it to be something. Repulsive.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
