<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHORS-CELEBRITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG NAMES, LITTLE READERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's Della and Maria and Dr. Laura and Jamie Lee. These
pop-culture icons earn their suppers in different ways _ Reese and
Shriver on television, Schlessinger on radio, and Curtis in films.
But they've all hopped on the same trendy bandwagon. A wagon that
shows no signs of slowing down in our media-driven society.
</P>
<P>
   These celebrities are children's book authors.
</P>
<P>
   Book industry purists may have reservations about calling them
``authors.'' But the literati can't dispute the fact that
well-known names on picture books for wee folks have proven strong
sellers. Often, celebrity equals talk-show appearances equals
front-of-the-bookstore placement equals big bucks.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Shriver's recent book, ``What's Heaven?,'' appeared
on the New York Times bestseller list for seven weeks, sharing the
spotlight with such established fiction writers as Mary Higgins
Clark, Stephen King, and John Grisham. And the book's sales figures
have shot above $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Roback, children's book editor of Publishers Weekly, says
few writers can pen a solid children's book, even authors who
successfully write adult books. Danielle Steel's children's books
were ``awful,'' she says, and Patricia Cornwell's recent book for
kids is ``dreadful.'' Maria Shriver's book, which concerns dealing
with death, ``has sold well because of who she is, the subject
matter, but also because she tells her story in an honest and
straightforward way. But, of course, her ability to generate media
coverage has been a driving force behind sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite some teeth-gnashing by thoroughbred children's book
editors and shop owners over celebrity books, they do agree on one
thing _ Jamie Lee Curtis's books are popular not because she's a
likable actress and a member of Hollywood royalty but because she's
a talented author working with an imaginative illustrator, Laura
Cornell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamie Lee has a voice,'' says Roback. ``And she's proven
herself with not one but three books (``Tell Me Again About the
Night I Was Born,'' ``When I Was Little: A Four-Year-Old's Memoir
of Her Youth,'' and ``Today I Feel Silly'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids liked her first book and therefore looked forward to her
second and third. Kids are very discerning. They don't care about
celebrity. They don't even know who some of these people are. They
only care about the story,'' says Roback.
</P>
<P>
   Shriver _ an NBC TV journalist, mother of four, wife of actor
Arnold Schwarzenegger, and member of the Kennedy clan _ says she
started noting the concerns and worries of her children, especially
her oldest daughter, Katherine, following the death of family
matriarch Rose Fitzgerald Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began jotting down their questions on little pieces of
paper, and also their answers,'' says Shriver, during a telephone
interview from her home in Santa Monica, Calif. ``I had no
intention of writing a book. But what made me first think about a
book was that I didn't find anything out there for kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Shriver was 9 when her uncle John was assassinated and 12 when
her uncle Robert was murdered. She remembers how shattered family
members were at the time and how alone and confused she felt with
her feelings and grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to tell kids that it's OK to cry, that it's OK to
feel all the emotions a death can stir up,'' says Shriver. ``And
the response to my book has been so satisfying to me. It seems to
have unearthed a whole lot of things for a lot of people _ of all
ages. It's still such an uncomfortable subject for people to talk
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought this was just a children's book,'' says
Shriver. ``I also thought it was a book that could be right up
there with Grisham and Stephen King. My publisher thought I was
crazy. But I'm very driven and goal-oriented, and my book's done
very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Betsey Detwiler, owner of Buttonwoods Book Store in Cohasset,
says the Shriver book sold well in her store because of the
publicity as well as the topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she did a good job, although my own religious
persuasion is different,'' says Detwiler. ``The book can be useful
for family discussions. But my own favorite on the same subject is
`When Someone Dies' by Sharon Greenlee, an elementary school
teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   Terri Schmitz, owner of the Children's Book Store in Brookline,
says she finds most celebrity books appalling, although she
concedes Shriver's book is the most useful and the least offensive
of the latest trio _ Shriver, Reese, and Dr. Laura. But she thinks
the illustrations in Shriver's book are amateurish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even stock Dr. Laura's book (`Why Do You Love Me?'),''
says Schmitz. ``It's badly done, like most celebrity books. They
are didactic and seem to be done to satisfy the ego of the person
writing, instead of the intended audience. These celebrities don't
really know anything about children's literature and how it works.
Della Reese's book (`God Inside of Me') is well meaning but not the
kind of book a child would want to hear a second time. Plus the
illustrations and text don't work together.''
</P>
<P>
   Reese, star of the top-rated television series ``Touched by an
Angel,'' says she wanted to write a book that would help children
understand that there is a piece of God in all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem in the schools and with these kids shooting each
other is all because they have no basis in God,'' says Reese by
phone from California. ``If they had God in their lives, they'd
have no reason to stick a needle in their arm or carry a pistol.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laura, host of a radio advice talk show that is syndicated
on more than 400 radio stations nationally, says she remembers her
son Deryk, now 13, asking her one day in the kitchen, when he was
6: ``Mom, why do you love me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stunned,'' she says, during an interview from her home
in southern California. ``At the time, I wasn't into God and tried
to explain to my son that I loved him because he came from me and
his daddy. Now I'd say to him what God says _ I love you because
you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlessinger says it took her years to get her children's book
published, until she tapped the publisher of her successful adult
books, HarperCollins. She says she plans a series of books to
promote a dialogue between parent and child.
</P>
<P>
   The celebrity phenomenon began, most observers agree, when
singer-songwriter Carly Simon hooked up with her Vineyard neighbor,
Doubleday editor Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, a decade ago and
published ``Amy the Dancing Bear.'' It didn't hurt, some say, that
Simon was also ``umbilically connected'' to the publishing world
via Simon &AMP; Schuster, a house founded by her father. The same year,
1989, Britain's Duchess of York, Sarah Ferguson, came out with her
first ``Budgie the Helicopter'' book.
</P>
<P>
   Preempting these authors was singer and actress Julie Andrews,
who wrote a book called ``Mandy'' in the 1960s. But she published
it under her married name, Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wasn't trying to cash in on her celebrity,'' says Roger
Sutton, editor of Horn Book Magazine. ``Jamie Lee's books aren't
bad, but Maria Shriver's and Della Reese's books are too preachy,''
he says. ``What's missing from most of these celebrity books is a
good story. A sermon is no substitute for a story. Plus there are
so many other good books out there. Would Maria Shriver's book have
been published without Maria Shriver as the author? The answer is
no.''
</P>
<P>
   But publishers are increasingly focused on making money, says
Sutton. For years, ``children's books were segregated from this
behavior, but that's not true anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus there's a lot of people out there who think it's easy to
write a children's book because children are so cute and sweet. But
that's not true. Children are just like the rest of us _ they're
very complicated. When parents are buying books, they shouldn't
think about what kind of message it might bring to a child but
their own reaction to the book. Take a book like `Where the Wild
Things Are.' You can't help but have a response to it. And that's
true of all the other classics. Kids don't want to be preached to
and don't want to be talked down to.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity books are stocked mainly by the large chain stores and
outlets that buy in bulk and then rapidly move books on and off the
highly visible sales tables. Many such books don't even reach the
shelves of small, independent children's bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We handle these kinds of books on a very token level,'' says
Carol Chittenden, owner of Eight Cousins bookstore in Falmouth.
``We never feature them prominently. I don't think they hamper good
books from being published. What they can do, however, is reduce a
person's sense of just how wonderful a good children's book can
be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
