<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW DO TREES STAY GREEN WHEN IT DOESN'T RAIN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How do trees stay so green during drought, while grass goes
dormant and flowers wilt?
</P>
<P>
   D.B. Newton, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It's every root for himself out there when water gets scarce.
</P>
<P>
   The deeper, wider roots of a tree can find water in places where
the shallower, narrower roots of grass and other small plants can't
reach. Trees are powerful engines at drawing water out of the soil,
which gives them advantages when things get dry. A decent size tree
can move as much as 1,000 gallons of water a day from the soil, all
the way up the trunk and out the leaves. To do this heavy H2O
lifting, they use a sophisticated suction system that works much
like a straw. On the bottom of the leaves of all green plants,
including trees, are little pores called stomata. These tiny holes,
which you can see with just a magnifying glass, breath in carbon
dioxide to use in photosynthesis. But they give off water vapor. In
other words, they sweat. When a water molecule escapes from a stoma
on a tree leaf, it pulls on the next water molecule inside the leaf
that it's attached to. That molecule pulls the H2O further inside
the leaf . . . and on and on, creating a giant suction system that
stretches down the trunk and into the roots and literally out into
the soil. Trees actually draw water up like a straw.
</P>
<P>
   Trees also get help in extending their reach from another whole
organism, called mycorrhizae, which weave their fine fibers in and
among the fine tips of the tree roots. The tree supplies the fungus
with carbon, and the fungus spreads way beyond the roots to collect
water and bring it back to the tree. Other plants get fungal help,
but not as much.
</P>
<P>
   Roots grow preferentially, depending on where they find water. A
tree will grow more roots where it finds moisture, than it will in
places where the first exploratory roots find things too dry. In
soil where tree and grass roots intermingle, tree roots usually
win.
</P>
<P>
   In dry conditions you might even see yellow or brown lines in
your grass. That's where tree roots are outcompeting grass roots
for the available water. In some places, like golf courses or those
maniacally manicured suburban lawns, the grass is so healthy, with
roots so thick, that it can actually outcompete tree roots for
water.
</P>
<P>
   During droughts, many plants close their stomata by directing
more water into guard cells that circle the pores. The guard cells
swell, squeezing the stomata closed. Some plants can do this in
just a few minutes when things get dry.
</P>
<P>
   But that comes at a price. Remember, the stomata are the way the
trees take in the CO2 they need to photosynthesize and provide the
plant with energy. If they close their pores to avoid water loss,
they shut off their ability to feed themselves and growth is
slowed.
</P>
<P>
   When grass has to close its stomata for a long stretch, it
responds by going dormant, sending its nutrients to the roots to
wait for water.
</P>
<P>
   Closing stomata also makes plants less able to produce the
defensive molecules that fight disease or insects.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
