<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE COURTESY, PLEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When I first heard about Louisiana's plan to
require kindergarten through fifth grade public school students to
call their teachers ``Sir'' or ``Ma'am'' _ and put courtesy titles
before the adults' names _ I thought it was an OK idea but no big
deal. I agreed with the bill's sponsor, Democratic state Sen. Don
Cravins, who figured: ``We're not trying to say this is the answer
to discipline, but what do we have to lose?''
</P>
<P>
   Then I started thinking: The whole nation really does have a
respect problem. Not just with kids in public schools, but with
most people. In most places.
</P>
<P>
   Given that California is the most populous state _ and the
leader in lifestyle legislation _ what good might come from a
mandated injection of that uncommon practice, ``common courtesy''?
How far might a law (or five) similar to Louisiana's move us toward
being a kinder, gentler, more respectful California?
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few ideas for the California Legislature to consider:
</P>
<P>
   _ Expanding on the Louisiana law, every person who works in or
comes to a public building _ not just school kids _ would be
required to address everybody else as ``Sir'' or ``Ma'am'' and by
the appropriate courtesy title: Mr., Ms. or, if requested, Miss or
Mrs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Because California already requires smokers to step outside
restaurants and bars if they want to light up, how about a
companion law that treats cell phones the same as cigarettes? You
want to blab on one _ you gotta take it outside.
</P>
<P>
   No one (yet) has proved that cell phones cause cancer, but their
use at a nearby table definitely interferes with proper digestion.
Because most people who use cell phones seem compelled to shout
into them, they also raise anxiety and stress levels.
</P>
<P>
   More important, from their loud tweetering ringers to the way
they leave the companions of their users ignored and staring
blankly into space, cell phones are rude.
</P>
<P>
   _ Even though sport utility vehicles are gas guzzlers and
hazardous to the safety of people who drive ordinary-size cars,
SUVs proliferate on California freeways, country roads and urban
streets. One of the rudest aspects of them is that they block the
view of traffic (and changing traffic lights) from smaller cars.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be nice to have a law requiring SUV drivers to roll
down their windows and give periodic traffic reports to the people
behind them? The Department of Motor Vehicles might even work out a
simple hand signal code covering the five most common traffic
conditions. (A raised middle finger would not be included.)
</P>
<P>
   _ In a related matter, imagine how far it might go toward
restoring civility if we passed a law that made it illegal not to
let at least one waiting vehicle into street traffic or a freeway
on-ramp line.
</P>
<P>
   The mean, insulting practice of gazing dead ahead, pretending
you don't see a pleading driver, is not only disrespectful, it
contributes to road rage. To paraphrase the California almond
growers, all we ask is one car a commute.
</P>
<P>
   (As an appendix, I suggest jail for drivers who ``forget'' to
signal for a left turn or who blast a horn at someone who _ signal
twinking _ is making a legal left.)
</P>
<P>
   _ My last proposal is to put teeth (and money for cops) into a
law that's already on the books of California's cities and towns.
Everyday it is broken; everyday civilization gets dissed in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   Make it a three-strikes felony not to pick up after your dog.
</P>
<P>
   You want disrespect? There is no more pungent an example than a
pile of what used to be Kibbles'n'Bits on your doorstep, in your
driveway or at the base of your struggling sapling amongst the
impatiens and pansies.
</P>
<P>
   Any other suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6852 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-FOOD-REVOLUTION-2     07-12 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FOOD-REVOLUTION-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 ISLAND FALLS, Maine: ... even scientists.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rising backlash has prompted some food processors, who buy
most of the genetically modified crops, to distance themselves from
the new products. McCain Foods USA, the world's biggest buyer of
potatoes, requires growers to declare if they are using genetically
modified potatoes, effectively discouraging them from using
Monsanto's products.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear at all where this will shake out in terms of
consumer reaction, so, from a business perspective, you have to be
able to respond,'' said Frank Van Schaayck, head of the potato
group at McCain Foods USA.
</P>
<P>
   Stuck in the middle are the farmers who flocked to the new seeds
in the first place. ``We're getting beaten to death on this,'' said
Shur, who grows almost exclusively for Monsanto's potato-growing
subsidiary, NatureMark.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the rise of genetically modified foods simply applies
the tools of modern genetics to something farmers have done for
centuries: cross-breeding produce and animals to create better
products. Centuries of cross-breeding have turned the pint-sized,
coarse Mexican wild corn into the big, juicy ears popular at
cookouts.
</P>
<P>
   But the high-powered computers and other tools that allow
geneticists to move genes from one organism to another speed the
process ten-fold or more. They also dramatically enlarge breeding
possibilities by allowing lab technicians to ``cross'' almost any
two species. Scientists have even inserted flounder genes into
tomatoes to prevent freezing.
</P>
<P>
   The initial search for commercially viable foods was frustrating
and costly. The first effort, Calgene's Flavr Savr tomato, flopped,
largely because consumers were unwilling to pay more for it. And
the overwhelming majority of experiments never got to the
commercial stage; Shur grew thousands of lines of potatoes on his
Maine farm for Monsanto to develop a handful of promising
varieties.
</P>
<P>
   ``As precise as the science sounds, a lot of what gets produced
. . . is not of the right quality. It's junk,'' said Robert
Bernatzky, plant geneticist at the University of Massachusetts at
Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers finally came up with two hit genes, both taken
from bacteria. One caused plants to secrete the natural pesticide
Bt. The other made plants immune to products such as Monsanto's
Round Up herbicide, allowing farmers to spray for weeds without
killing their crop.
</P>
<P>
   These two genes, inserted into corn and soybeans, triggered what
Clive James, head of the nonprofit International Service for the
Acquisition of Agribiotech Applications, calls ``one of the fastest
adoptions of technology I've ever seen.'' An estimated 60 percent
of the soy acres, 50 percent of the cotton, and 35 percent of the
corn are planted in genetically altered seeds.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough encouraged authorities in developing nations,
who see the new crops as a way to feed a world population expected
to top 6 billion this year. Former president Carter, whose
nonprofit foundation helps small farmers in Africa, was especially
pleased at the Round Up-resistant soy and cotton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it nice to have a broad leaf plant . . . that you can
put in a row, and after it comes up, spray the field and kill the
weeds, but not the plants?'' he asked in a 1998 speech.
</P>
<P>
   But Europeans, whose faith in food safety was shaken by the
``mad cow disease'' outbreak in 1997 and other scandals, never went
along with the euphoria. Many perceived the new crops as dangerous
and unnecessary, and the British tabloid press took to calling them
``Frankenfoods.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue burst into the American conscience in a big way this
spring when the science journal Nature published a Cornell
University study showing that almost half the monarch butterflies
who fed on the pollen from Bt corn died. Monsanto criticized the
study as unrealistic, but researchers at Iowa State University got
similar results using different methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Bt crops kill monarch butterflies is an
unintended consequence,'' Iowa State bioethicist Gary Comstock told
the local newspaper. ``People want to know what the full
consequences to the environment will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, reports have increasingly focused on scientific
misgivings about genetically engineered crops. For example:
</P>
<P>
   --University of Chicago researchers are concerned that
genetically engineered crops could cross-breed with weeds, creating
``super weeds'' that have genes making them immune to Round Up or
other chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   --The EPA is hosting workshops around the United States on how
to prevent the Bt crops from creating strains of insects that are
immune to the toxic effects of Bt. Such mutants would then be free
to munch on any crops that count on Bt for protection.
</P>
<P>
   --Surprisingly, researchers have found that key genetically
altered crops do not increase yields. Round Up-resistant soybeans
may reduce chemical use, costs, and difficulties to the farmers,
but Edward Oplinger of the University of Wisconsin at Madison found
that they produced 4 percent smaller yields than conventional
seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Industry defenders say the concerns are legitimate, but not
cause for alarm. They represent problems of the early days of an
industry that is refining its products. Potato farmer Shur admits
that the genetically altered potatoes sold now are only modest
improvements, but he hopes that some experimental crops on his land
may represent a bigger breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just hopeful that we don't throw the baby out with the
bathwater,'' said Everett Thomas, director of the New York-based
Miner Institute, which field tests genetically altered products.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the 1990s may be remembered as the start of
something terrible. Said Ellen Taggart of the grass-roots group
Rural Vermont, ``We're manipulating the basis for life and creating
a new form of pollution, biological pollution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6855 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVIS-SAMPRAS-2ND     07-12 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-SAMPRAS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... Friday annd Sunday.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After all, it would be a bit difficult to defend a strategy that
doesn't include the man who is fresh off his sixth Wimbledon
triumph in seven years, a 20th-century record that enabled Sampras
to tie Australian Roy Emerson's all-time mark of 12 singles
championships in Grand Slam events. You don't sit out a guy who has
spent 270 weeks of his life ranked as the No. 1 player in the
world, a feat equaled only by Ivan Lendl.
</P>
<P>
   Even if that guy is no longer No. 1. One of the great ironies of
the year _ and one of the most emphatic statements about Sampras's
newfound priorities _ is that his Wimbledon watershed also marked
the end of his reign atop the computer rankings. Because of his
indifferent performance in 1999 _ nary a title before his
grass-court triumphs at Queen's Club and the All England Club _ and
because the resurrected Andre Agassi has been on a roll highlighted
by his French Open victory, Sampras has fallen to No. 3, behind
Agassi and Rafter, despite beating his longtime American nemesis in
the Wimbledon final.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't seem to bother Sampras in the least.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I'm letting the ranking go this year,'' he
says. ``But I'm not willing to play 20 tournaments or 25. So
playing Davis Cup is a huge occasion. I think I realized that it is
going to be tough for me to finish No. 1 this year, and not playing
much this year, especially the first four or five months, gave me
some time to step back and look at what I wanted to do the next
three or four years. I mean, it's hard to do both, to stay No. 1
and play Davis Cup. I've done it before, and it's very taxing, and
I've dug myself a very big hole to finish No. 1 this year. I feel
like the year to really do it was last year, to try to break the
record, and this year if it happens, it happens. I'm not going to
play six straight weeks again for my ranking and really go through
the misery I went through.''
</P>
<P>
   That point was reinforced in Birmingham, via Tampa TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely inspired me,'' says Sampras. ``You look at the
atmosphere. Those are the type of situations I want to be in for
the next three or four years. I mean, that's motivation right
there, versus playing some of those other events. It's not about
ranking; it's about handling the pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Gullikson believes Sampras's Davis Cup decision lifted
a burden from him by silencing those who questioned his motives,
thus indirectly reviving his individual career as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like he's in a very good place,'' says the captain.
``I think it takes some of the pressure off.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras maintains otherwise, saying his prodigal return to the
Davis Cup had no bearing on his Wimbledon mastery. Besides, he
points out with some justification, he's gotten a bum rap in terms
of his national commitment _ he's played five years of Cup
competition, starting in 1991, and has helped the Americans to two
titles and two runner-up finishes. And while he'd taken a pass
since 1997, he never said it was forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought my Davis Cup career was going to be over,'' he
says. ``I've always said I that I see myself playing some more
Davis Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges that Birmingham expedited his timetable, and
despite his claims to the contrary, something has settled him down
since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's at the stage of his career where he wants to play at the
right times, be out there when he wants to be,'' says Annacone.
``He's falling prey less to chasing No. 1. In the long run, that's
healthier for him. He's got an even more even-balanced
perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   That's saying something for a player who, until late last year,
always was known for his serenity as much as his superiority.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Palos Verdes, Calif., the son of Sam, an
aeronautical engineer, and Georgia Sampras, Pete never was pushed
into tennis. But he was prodigious at it. He began playing at age
7, and he used to watch tapes of Rod Laver, the only man ever to
sweep the Grand Slam events _ the US, Australian, and French opens
and Wimbledon _ in two different years. His most influential early
teacher was Dr. Pete Fisher, a Los Angeles pediatrician and tennis
guru.
</P>
<P>
   ``He taught me how to play,'' says Sampras. ``From a baseliner
with a two-handed backhand, he basically changed my game to a
one-handed serve-and-volleyer.''
</P>
<P>
   That association culminated in the first of Sampras's four US
Open crowns in 1990, when he was barely 19, but it wasn't until Tim
Gullikson came along that Sampras became a consistent champion. The
components were in place _ the unparalleled serve, especially the
second; the devastating forehand; the pure athleticism; the
evolving serve-and-volley game; the savvy defensive tactics. Tim
Gullikson gave him something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``He helped him become a better competitor,'' says Tom
Gullikson. ``He was a great ball striker, but every day you're
going to strike the ball differently. Great ball strikers tend to
rely on how they hit the ball. If it's not going well, they expect
to lose. Tim taught him how to win without his best stuff. He
taught him that when the shots aren't falling in, you've got to put
your blue collar on and go to work.''
</P>
<P>
   The partnership yielded Sampras's first two Wimbledon titles,
another US Open, and the first of his two Australians. When Tim
took ill at the 1995 Australian Open and was diagnosed with four
inoperable brain tumors, Sampras wept openly on the court in
Melbourne; he now sits on the board of the Tim and Tom Gullikson
Foundation, which assists brain cancer patients and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nothing seemed to rattle him for the long term. ``He has
tremendous self-belief, a quiet confidence,'' says Tom Gullikson.
``He's very calm and cool. He doesn't go around bragging about how
great he is.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the things that most impresses Annacone, with whom
Sampras hasn't missed a beat since they teamed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a pretty even-balanced mental approach,'' says
Annacone. ``Pete never does cartwheels down the hall. If he wins,
he doesn't get overly excited. If he loses, he doesn't slit his
wrists. That's why he's able to be so consistent. He's able to look
at things in terms of the long-term picture.''
</P>
<P>
   He lost sight of it for a while, but the Davis Cup helped bring
it back in focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he still wants more (Grand Slam titles),'' says Tom
Gullikson. ``He's an unfinished painting. There are still a few
more strokes to be put on the canvas. Davis Cup can help. It's four
weeks (a year) of being on a team, eating together, hanging out
together.''
</P>
<P>
   And playing because you want to. That's No. 1 now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
