A6857 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVIS-COURIER-2TA     07-12 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-COURIER-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURIER IS CARRIER OF GOOD NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Courier walks into his neighborhood grocery in Orlando,
Fla., one day in April, and something is different _ ``a big
surprise,'' he says. ``The bag boy looks at me and says, `You're
that Davis Cup guy!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Is this the same Courier who has banked four major titles _
matched pairs of French and Australian opens _ stood atop his world
at No. 1, and is a cinch someday for a niche at the International
Tennis Hall of Fame?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' he says, ``but nobody ever took any notice of me in
that store until after Birmingham. The bag boy. I don't think he
knew my name, but that recognition was great.''
</P>
<P>
   Not for himself. Courier gets enough of that. But for the game
he loves, and that he senses has slipped in the public
consciousness in his country over recent years. ``Birmingham, the
Davis Cup, had a crossover effect to touch people beyond the usual
tennis fans. That bag boy made me feel really good,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   An April weekend in Birmingham, England, unexpectedly was the
springboard for the rugged redheaded Courier to alight as an
American sporting hero, via ESPN, surpassing in his own trade even
Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi. They had carried their wallets,
disdaining invitations. Courier had lugged the USA. Jingoism still
counted.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the derisively regarded scrubs, Courier and Todd
Martin, was choice. Not lost in lamentation (like everybody else)
over the absence of the elite Sampras and Agassi, Martin and
Courier were underdogs with a rabid bite, gnashing the British
bubble, 3-2. Martin whipped Greg Rusedski in four, and Courier hung
on tenaciously through roller coaster rides of five sets over Tim
Henman and Rusedski. The excruciating closer over Rusedski _ 6-4,
6-7 (3-7), 6-3, 1-6, 8-6 _ kept couchies rapt and wrapped into it
for almost four hours.
</P>
<P>
   Australia awaited the victor, and Courier made sure the US was
on the way to Boston to keep that semifinal date with its most
esteemed and ferocious adversary. This is Bean Summer for Courier,
booked to play a Longwood encore at the US Pro the last week of
next month.
</P>
<P>
   James Spencer Courier, of the Dade City, Fla., Couriers, is a
very rare starboard-wing flapping bird in the Davis Cup aviary that
dates back to 1900 and Longwood Cricket Club in Brookline, Mass. He
returns like a swallow to Capistrano to the business of making
Americans feel good about their team Friday afternoon when he takes
on Australia in the person of Patrick Rafter. The scene is
historically sweet: Longwood again where a trust-funded Harvard lad
named Dwight Davis anteed his $1,000 pot _ a grandiosely crafted
silver basin _ into the international sporting game.
</P>
<P>
   Davis himself, whose impetus started it all, played and won the
opening match of the newly begun team competition in which the US
beat Britain, 3-0, and has spread like cell phones across the
globe, from the original two entries to 129 this year. He played in
one more series, the 3-2 victory over Britain in 1902. Then the
gentleman amateur moved on at 23 to the rest of his life as
philanthropist and civic-minded citizen, continuing to take an
interest in the Cup's ramblings.
</P>
<P>
   Courier, 29 Aug. 17, isn't ready for the rest of his life yet,
although it seemed he might be as his output shrank and ranking
expanded in the wrong direction from No. 1 in 1992 to a low of No.
117 nine months ago. He continues to take an interest in the
roaming Cup, too, an undertaking where his heartbeat beats whatever
Blinky, the ATP computer, has to say about him, No. 54 at
Birmingham, No. 41 today and rising.
</P>
<P>
   Having campaigned since 1991, fought to possess the prize at
home, and abroad in such locales as Mexico, The Netherlands,
Russia, India, England, Brazil, Courier has become a good luck
charm par excellence, more highly valued by US captain Tom
Gullikson and his predecessor, Tom Gorman, than a genie.
</P>
<P>
   This is his amazing, high-flying distinction setting Courier
apart from the crowd of Americans before him: A team with Courier
in the starting lineup never has lost. Thirteen engagements, 13
won, including two Cups. He's a two-legged talisman, a rabbit's
foot in sneakers, a forehanding four-leaf clover, an aggressive
amulet.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately there isn't a racket of wood to knock on when this
is discussed, and certainly the two Aussies he'll face, Rafter and
the Boy Buzzbomb, 18-year-old Lleyton Hewitt, are determined to
make 13 a very unlucky number.
</P>
<P>
   No other compatriot has come close to that kind of winning
streak. The last notable was the illustrious Aussie, Rod Laver,
whose five-year presence between 1959 and 1973 covered 11 team
victories and five Cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' Courier says with a smile, ``we'd better give Brad
Gilbert a lot of credit here for the 3-2 win in my debut. Mexico
City in 1991. Otherwise it was a nightmare. I couldn't handle the
altitude, the way the balls flew, and the rookie pressure. Luis
Herrera and Leonardo Lavalle both beat me. But Gilbert beat Lavalle
to make it 1-1 and Robert (Seguso) and Ken (Flach) were automatics
in the doubles in those days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were up, 2-1, and there I was, choking in the dressing
room, as Brad struggled against Herrera. He came through, finally,
in five sets. I was a nervous wreck. Lavalle beat me in the last
match, but it didn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say maybe Courier was an intangible force in that
one.
</P>
<P>
   He is an intangible force, says Gullikson. ``The team can feel
Jim's energy and competitiveness,'' he says. But a very tangible
one, too. ``He told me we'd beat the Brits and made us believers,''
adds Gullikson. ``Naturally he says we'll beat the Aussies, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
