<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING JOURNALISTS TO THE MAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is becoming increasingly clear that changes must be made in
this space. No, this is not my long-awaited (in some quarters)
resignation, but an announcement that henceforth this will be a
wrestling column.
</P>
<P>
   My aim is to be the first newspaper columnist who actually
wrestles the people she writes about. My ultimate goal is to
challenge Martha Stewart to a match. Soon I will be enrolling at
the Killer Kowalski Institute of Professional Wrestling to learn
the basics _ the leg lock, the monkey flip, the drop kick, the
brain buster, the chicken wing, the neckbreaker, etc. _ to prepare
for the day when I will be fit enough to challenge the woman known
in wrestling circles as Martha, Mistress of All She Purveys.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling is the hottest thing around. Every week millions of
viewers watch the The World Wide Wrestling Federation matches on
USA Network. Millions more tune in to World Championship Wrestling
on TNT. Last week both networks announced plans to expand their
wrestling programming this fall. Another network, TNN, will be
getting into the act, broadcasting Extreme Championship Wrestling
starting in September.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling is permeating the culture. Wrestlers are breaking into
politics. Jesse Ventura is governor of Minnesota. Jerry Lawler, the
professional wrestler who pioneered mixed-media wrestling by nearly
breaking comedian Andy Kaufman's neck, last week announced he'll be
running for mayor of Memphis. Clearly it's only a matter of time
before veteran politicians get into professional wrestling.
Journalists can't be left behind. That's why I'm changing the whole
concept of this column.
</P>
<P>
   People are clamoring for wrestling. They can't get enough.
Recent surveys reveal that wrestling is drawing a new breed of fan:
young, affluent, predominantly male but, increasingly, female. This
is much the same ``dream'' demographic newspapers seek to attract.
So why not a News Wrestling Federation (NWF)?
</P>
<P>
   The NWF could give the public a physical manifestation of the
intellectual debates that are always raging in journalistic
circles. Serious wrestling about serious issues. Well, mostly
serious issues. But real issues nonetheless, as opposed to the
phony, trumped-up feuds that are the heart of professional
wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   News can be a pretty cotentious business, so wrestling is a
logical step. Editors could put a lofty spin on it, style it as a
kind of noble, gladiatorial combat, as columnists and other
opinion-makers, so-called, square off in the ring against their
subjects, and occasionally against each other. WNF wrestling would
be informative as well as entertaining, with ringside play-by-play
commentary about the match along with expert analysis of the issues
involved. Kind of like CNN's war coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine ``Big Bad'' Maureen Dowd of the New York Times hammering
``Nature Boy'' Bill Clinton in print for his wicked ways, then
meeting him in the ring and punishing him with a power slam and a
flying head butt. NWF matches would give media targets a welcome
opportunity to take revenge. Wrestling and the news being what they
are, there'd be re-matches, grudge matches, hate matches that would
go on for years. Bob ``The Hulk'' Ryan against Antoine ``The Punk''
Walker. Alex ``Butter'' Beam vs. John ``The Terminator'' Silber.
And Martha and me, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   I must work hard at my wrestling studies. The Master, Kowalski,
points out that Martha is in fabulous shape from years of tossing
around compost. In his opinion, she is wasting her time being a
corporate phenomenon when she could be the Queen of the Ring.
Meanwhile I am trying to develop a wrestling persona (good guy? bad
guy?) and designing an appropriate costume. How much span is there
in Spandex? I fear I am about to find out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
