<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTEN UP ON COMPANY STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 47 and earn an annual salary of $52,000. My company's
401(k) plan is managed by Fidelity, and I have $150,000 in the
plan. Of this, $25,000 is in a stable value fund, $7,000 in
Fidelity Puritan, $15,000 in Fidelity U.S. Equity Index, $17,000 in
Fidelity Blue Chip Stock, $20,000 in Fidelity Low-Priced Stock,
$11,000 in Fidelity Diversified International, $30,000 in Sequoia
fund and $25,000 in my company's stock. Other options available
which I do not use are Clipper and Mutual Qualified Z funds. My
contributions amount to $225 a month, all of it going into my
company's stock where the contributions are matched by my employer.
Is my money properly invested and diversified?
</P>
<P>
   G.F., Stephenville, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A. Two things tend to bother me. The major one is the fact that
all of your contributions are going into your company's stock. I
very much like the idea of a person owning a piece of his employer,
but when there's a strong incentive to build a sizable position in
a single stock, such as your employer's matching program
represents, there's also a real danger that over time you will find
that stock dominating the portfolio. For most people, that can
represent a real problem of overconcentrating risk. On the other
hand, employer matching programs are usually so attractive that the
intelligent thing to do is amass the stock and calculate that the
value of the employer match outweighs the risk.
</P>
<P>
   Most such plans have provisions that stock thus acquired must be
held for a certain period of time before it can be sold, I suggest
you monitor these rules and your accumulation of your employer's
stock carefully. At the current level, representing only 16 percent
of the total portfolio, there is no problem. But this portion of
the portfolio is getting all of the contributions, and it will soon
enough get out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   My general suggestion for such a situation is to try to hold
your position in your company's stock to 30 to 35 percent of your
total portfolio. I suggest this without reference to the prospects
of your particular company, about which you are fairly certain to
know more than me. (And, of course, if you have an opinion that
makes you especially leery of accumulating the stock, you would
probably want to trim your holdings to the minimum allowed while
still retaining the company matching funds.)
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest of the portfolio, I have only one major
argument, which I'll bet you can predict. It's that $25,000 loafing
along in the stable value fund. In my opinion, you're simply too
young to have such a position. Even at times such s now, when the
stock market looks fairly scary to me, a person of your age should
simply decide that with your very long period of accumulation and
growth _ perhaps 13 to 18 years _ you will end up well behind in
the long run if you stick with a fixed-income option such as this.
Besides, you already have a toe in the fixed-income market through
your holding in Fidelity Puritan, which maintains about a third of
its portfolio in bonds.
</P>
<P>
   My preference for this money would be in Mutual Qualified Z
fund, which holds a mid-cap value-oriented portfolio. But if you
are uncomfortable with that move, at a minimum I suggest you sell
the stable value position and combine that money with your holdings
in Puritan.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't ask, but if you continue saving at your current level
and if you achieve average annual portfolio growth of 10 percent,
you will amass $587,133 by age 60 and $962,721 by age 65. These
calculations don't include the effect of your employer matches,
which I left out since I wasn't sure from your wording whether it
is a dollar-for-dollar match. If it is dollar-for-dollar, the
accumulations would be $656,372 at age 60 and $1,091,455 at age 65,
using the same assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Many years ago you advised me to get into Benham Trust GNMA
fund and I have done so, and am adding a small amount periodically.
I am now 80 years old. However, it now seems to me that as it is
now American Century Benham GNMA it is not doing so well. Would you
advise me to drop this and get into another fund?
</P>
<P>
   E.C., Centerville, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Usually when I recommend a Ginnie Mae fund, I warn investors
that they need to take a long-term view of their investment, that
there will invariable be seasons when the net asset value of the
fund falls, reflecting either increases in interest rates or
sometimes only fears that they will rise. The first half of this
year has been one of those times, with almost all GNMA funds in the
red on a year-to-date basis.
</P>
<P>
   American Century Benham GNMA has in fact done better than most,
posting a year-to-date loss of .06 percent. It is true that 1998
was a sub-par year for the fund, but its 6.32 percent total return
for the year wasn't all that far behind the 7.14 percent total
return for Vanguard GNMA, which is widely regarded as the leader in
the category. That slight underperformance wasn't enough to charge
the rating from Monringstar Mutual Funds, which continues to accord
its top five-star rating to American Century Benham GNMA.
</P>
<P>
   In short, I'd stick with it, taking the view that this is simply
one of those predictable bumps, and in the long run you'll get what
attracted you to the fund in the first place _ a solid yield and a
stable principal value.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I are desperate for guidance. We are trying to
save for a new house that we'd like to purchase in about six years.
We have saved $6,000, now divided between Vanguard's Balanced Index
and its LifeStrategy Moderate Growth funds. We are adding $150 to
each fund every month to accumulate our down payment. I am very
concerned about our relatively short time frame given the current
instability of the stock market. Have we made a wise choice? Do you
have other suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   L.W., Franklin, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, in theory these two balanced funds are appropriate,
since your time frame is in the intermediate term, although it's
near the bottom of the five-to-10-year intermediate term time
frame. But I'd be just as nervous as you are, and I'd hedge my
bets. I would do it by swapping the LifeStrategy Moderate Growth
position for Vanguard's Short-Term Bond fund, and then directing
all of your monthly contributions to the bond fund. I suggested
swapping the LifeStrategy fund rather than the very similar
Balanced Index offering solely based on the fact that LifeStrategy
Moderate Growth holds about 65 percent stocks, compared to about 58
percent for Balanced Index.
</P>
<P>
   Further, in about three years, when your goal is only about 36
months away, I'd then swap the Balanced Index holding for a
position in Vanguard's Prime Money Market fund, and at that point I
would switch all of the ongoing contributions to the money market
fund. Finally, about one year beforeb your anticipated purpose, I'd
move all the holdings to the money market fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have read your recommendations about putting a child's
college money in the parents' names as opposed to the child's. What
do you recommend if we have not done this in the past? Is it
possible to change? If so, what procedures must be followed, and is
there a penalty for this change?
</P>
<P>
   C.B., Southlake, Texas &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. While you're not allowed to take back funds given to a child,
there are a few strategies that perhaps can be used to effect the
same purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Under the typical uniform gift to minors act, the trustee can
use the funds in such an account for a number of expenses other
than education _ medical bills, pre-college education such as
summer schools, tutoring, and so forth. Therefore one tactic which
is sometimes used by parents who have set themselves up as trustees
under a uniform gift to minors act is to use the funds in the UGMA
account to pay for such expenses _ and then to put an identical
amount of money into an account in their own names but earmarked
for the child's education. Other than that, there's not much you
can do _ the gift was a gift and it can't be taken back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
