<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6882 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-GARDNER-ART-B     07-12 1673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-GARDNER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOWARD GARDNER: THE MASTER OF UNARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Howard Gardner is like the American Civil Liberties
Union: You may disagree with him, but you want him around.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner, a Harvard University psychologist and educator, throws
bombs in a field cluttered with bomb throwers. Most of his
colleagues' projectiles flare and sputter without notice. A few
gain intellectual purchase. But the one Gardner tossed 16 years ago
_ his theory of multiple intelligences _ left a crater that is
still changing the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Quite simply, Gardner trashed the way we measure smarts. He
identified seven different kinds of intelligence rather than the
narrow spectrum of verbal and logical/mathematical skills measured
in standardized tests. In doing so, he sought to unlock the myriad
abilities of children that went unrecognized by the old gauges.
Teachers and parents frustrated by the one-size-fits-all paradigm
showered him with hosannas. Multiple intelligence curriculums
blossomed in schools across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the debate over Howard Gardner and his ideas continues
unabated, even as he refines and expands the controversial
definition of intelligence that first put him on the map.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the buzz in very important circles,'' says James O.
Freedman, former president of Dartmouth College. ``He has moved the
debate on his terms. He has preempted the field intellectually. It
is against him that you argue now.''
</P>
<P>
   David Riesman, the dean of American sociologists, calls
Gardner's contribution ``extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Gardner _ who turned 56 July 11 _ drew near universal
support for opening the door to other ways of thinking about
intelligence, the consensus in his favor stopped there. Some
dismissed his ideas as a warm and fuzzy scheme skewed toward
self-esteem rather than the cold, adamantine general intelligence
quotient. Yale psychologist Robert Sternberg dismissed the theory
of multiple intelligences as ``a theory of talents, not one of
intelligences.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of his supporters liked the idea of Howard Gardner
more than the details of his theory. Riesman, for example, buys
virtually none of what Gardner is selling. ``I don't share that
view at all,'' says Riesman about Gardner's theory. ``I have a very
traditional view of intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner added five intelligences to the traditional pair of
linguistic and logical/mathematic: musical, spatial, interpersonal,
intrapersonal, and bodily-kinesthetic. He has since added
naturalist, and is considering a ninth, existential.
</P>
<P>
   The composition of this list is, and should be, subject to
endless argument. ``Bodily-kinesthetic,'' which identifies physical
and athletic ability, brings sharp challenges. Granted, Wayne
Gretsky is a great athlete, for example, but does that make him
intelligent?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, responds Gardner: ``Gretsky uses his body to solve
problems in ways that are valued.'' Horsefeathers, counters Jeffrey
Arnett, a developmental psychologist doing research this year at
the University of Maryland. ``Why call it intelligence? Is there
really a hockey intelligence?''
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Kagan, a Harvard psychologist and author who supports
Gardner's fundamental message, cautions that societies focus on
their own subsets of skills to determine success. ``In this
culture, our best jobs go to people with strong verbal and math
skills,'' he says. ``Therefore, we can say that it's too bad that
they are not in your preferred set of skills, but you're going to
have to master them if you want a secure future.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner agrees. He also stresses that his theory in no way
should lead to a reduction in academic standards.
</P>
<P>
   But psychologists and educators who believe in the efficacy of
the traditional tests claim nonetheless that Gardner's message
subtly undermines standards. ``People wanted to hear this because
it appeals to a certain American sentimentality that everyone is
intelligent,'' says Arnett. ``It's like in Lake Wobegon, where all
the kids are above average.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner is unfazed by such criticism. ``I reject that there is
any such thing as an unmodified intelligence,'' he says. ``There is
no general intelligence that shines no matter where people are or
what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course no one knows if Gardner's list of intelligences will
look right a century from now. It certainly is not the last word on
the subject. Freedman calls it Gardner's ``first draft at saying,
`Here's how to outline people's capacities.' '' The point is,
Gardner came up with a list in the first place. He confronts
questions that daunt others.
</P>
<P>
   His theories flow from his humaneness. Gardner is a mensch. He
formed his theory as a developmental psychologist studying gifted
children and people with learning disabilities. James Traub, a
journalist who specializes in education issues and a Gardner
critic, is not far off of the mark when he writes, ``Gardner is, at
bottom, a moral philosopher; he wants to change the way we measure
human worth.''
</P>
<P>
   He is also a rumpled, color-blind polymath who can talk
seamlessly about the politics of Bill Clinton, the art of Mark
Rothko, the music of Mozart, the dubbing of Italian movies and the
mores of corporate America in a 15-minute riff. And he writes well.
This breadth leavens his scholarship and makes him a dream of a
dinner partner.
</P>
<P>
   Shirttails out, his hair mussed, Gardner moves at warp speed
among the warrens of academia, cognitive psychology and,
increasingly, corporate America, where he consults on subjects like
leadership and creativity. He continues teaching at Harvard's
Graduate School of Education, where he holds an endowed chair in
cognition and education. He remains co-director of Project Zero, a
research group at the graduate school that plumbs how children and
adults learn. He has more books in the works. (All 17 are in print
and many translated into nine languages, according to Ike Williams,
his literary agent.)
</P>
<P>
   In his latest book, ``The Disciplined Mind,'' Gardner argues for
a curriculum of in-depth learning in a limited set of disciplines
rather than what he calls ``the Vanna White'' curriculum pervasive
today where students dash through thickets of untethered facts
without any coherent sense of learning.
</P>
<P>
   Together with psychologists Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi of the
University of Chicago and William Damon of Stanford University,
Gardner is also pursuing a long-term project called ``Good Work''
that will examine values, creativity, and leadership in six fields:
journalism, genetics, jazz, drama, law, and medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner grew up the son of Jewish immigrants in a comfortable
home in Scranton, Pa. He was a serious piano student as a youngster
and went to Harvard, where he graduated summa cum laude. Williams
tells how Gardner was shocked as an undergraduate to receive a
B-plus on a history test. He was so troubled by the score that he
asked a grader to reread his exam. Gardner had replaced the essay
question with one of his own. He wrote: ``A better question is . .
.'' and went on to answer that one. The reader gave him an A.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner's interest in better questions led to his recent forays
into corporate America. During his meetings at places like Fidelity
and Pfizer, he prods executives to reexamine their precepts about
how they do their jobs. These appearances speak as much about the
growing corporate interest in him as it does about his unflagging
curiosity in new fields.
</P>
<P>
   At a daylong affair with Fidelity in Boston earlier this year,
for example, Gardner communed with some 40 executives within the
company's Operations and Technology Group of its Personal
Investments and Brokerage arm.
</P>
<P>
   Picture this: Gardner watches ``Twelve O'Clock High,'' the World
War II movie starring Gregory Peck about a troubled bomber
squadron, with a room full of suits. He discusses with them the
lessons from the film about leadership, and he limns the varying
styles of Churchill, Gandhi, and Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner holds that successfull leaders tell stories about
themselves and the institutions they run in ways that employees can
understand. These stories often must compete with preexisting
stories at those organizations. Leadership, he reminds us, occurs
in the human mind, but leaders must also live the stories they
tell.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity liked what it heard. ``We were struck by how practical
it was for him to give historical examples of various kinds of
leadership,'' says William Costello, a Fidelity vice president and
clinical psychologist who organized the event. ``Howard talks to
the heart of what others have said before. He says, `Let me think
of this a bit differently.' That's his contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Her politics aside, Gardner considers Margaret Thatcher, the
former British prime minister, to have been one of the most
successful leaders in our time. He says that, like her
contemporary, former President Reagan, she had a simple message to
tell: ``Britain has lost its way, and I know a new and better
way.'' She told a compelling story to the British people that
worked.
</P>
<P>
   His two heros are Mahatama Gandhi and Jean Monnet, father of the
European Union, because both tried to enlarge the sense of ``we.''
Both remained flexible on the means but ironclad in the pursuit of
goals. Both walked the walk.
</P>
<P>
   But, Gardner cautions, a leader's story must not be so inclusive
that it alienates his or her core support. This is tricky. It was
no accident, he argues, that Gandhi was assassinated by a fellow
Hindu rather than a Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner concludes about leadership: ``So long as human beings
have any desire to change their situation, we will cherish those
individuals who can point us in a new direction and show us how to
get there.''
</P>
<P>
   The man points rather well himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
