<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6883 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-OZ-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-BOS &LR;      07-12 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-OZ-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... something. Repulsive.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fontana, 47, came to fame writing and directing ``St.
Elsewhere.'' He is partners with director Barry Levinson in ``Oz,''
as he has been in other productions, including the gritty,
critically acclaimed ``Homicide'' (recently canceled by NBC) and
the new ``The Hoop Life'' on Showtime. Levinson, says Fontana, may
not be much of a presence on the ``Oz'' set but ``he's always there
when I need him.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of strong personalities at work on ``Oz,'' a lot
of actors whom you might expect to fight for space. But, Walker
says, ``we're like a family and we're all here to work. Nobody's
really got time for the ego thing. I'm not saying there aren't
egos, but everyone puts it on the back shelf.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some muscling going on on set,'' says Winters, ``but
when you trust the people you are working with you can be as bad as
you want. There's poking, there's posturing, but for a show that is
chockful of reality and violence and a lot of sex, I think this
show . . . has so much love in the cast. It's a lovefest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's very little ego,'' agrees Lee Tergesen, who plays
convict/lawyer Tobias Beecher, ``which is great and sort of
uncommon. We all have a great respect for one another and part of
that is the material: If you're going to get naked in the showers,
it is just a very vulnerable feeling even if it's about a bunch of
tough guys.'' It is, he says, with a slight laugh, like a workplace
drama: ``You feel threatened and you have to position yourself in a
certain way. Everybody is fighting for survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a good friend of mine who is in prison right now,''
says Dean Winters, who plays convicted killer Ryan O'Reily. ``It's
one of the few prisons that actually shows `Oz.' He has written me
that it's pretty much on the money as far as the stereotypes go.''
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of each episode, the cast is introduced in a
montage, and you also see a tattoo of ``Oz'' being inked onto a
man's shoulder. That's Fontana's shoulder. ``I said I wanted to do
a thing with prison art,'' he says, ``and when I got closer to
doing it nobody was stupid enough to want the tattoo _ especially
if it was only going to be eight episodes _ so I said `(Expletive)
it, I have a number of tattoos. It'll be way cool.' '' Fontana says
three others connected with the show have since gotten their own
``Oz'' tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for the series, Fontana spent parts of two years
visiting prisons, mostly maximum-security facilities. ``I talked to
a lot of inmates, I talked to a lot of COs (corrections officers),
talked to a lot of former inmates. I didn't want to exploit them. I
wasn't allowed to bring in a lot of writing utensils or tape
recorders which, actually, ended up being great. What I would do is
talk to people and when I got outside, whatever I remembered was
what I was supposed to remember. I took it as a metaphysical
exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   What he wanted, Fontata continues, was less of prisoners' life
stories and more ``the feel of the place, the loneliness, the fear,
those elements such as no one ever smiling because smiling equals
vulnerability and if your goal is to survive this experience
vulnerability is the thing you push furthest away.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the research I did, what was intrinsic to the experience
was one could never relax, one must always be aware of everyone and
everything around them in order to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Does the show have a political agenda?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' says Walker. ``I just think that it throws
(prison life) out to the people watching.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's success with critics, and its importance to the
network (along with ``The Sopranos'' and ``Sex and the City,'' it's
a centerpiece of HBO's original programming) comes as America's
fixation with building new prisons and incarcerating ever-larger
numbers of people continues unabated, despite the debates about
that policy's wisdom. ``I never like to get too political,'' says
Fontana, ``because I feel the work should say it, not me. But I
find that you build these prisons and _ given the fact that some of
these people are getting out _ they're not going to be better,
they're going to be worse, we're just delaying the problem. But I
don't have the answers, and I never pretend to on any of the shows
I do. What I have is a lot of questions. And if people watching the
show, the next time they read something about prisons, don't just
go `Oh those (expletive) guys are such low-lifes!' but say `I
wonder if that's close to' '' the situation in ``Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   Of ``Oz,'' how much is realistic? How much is exaggerated? How
much is fantasy?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my job is to approximate the three in an entertaining
way,'' says Fontana. ``Approximate reality in an entertaining way
and hopefully find the truth buried in there. I want it to feel
real.'' What he asks of an audience ``is to sit there for 58
minutes and have their heads punched in.'' The reality of prison
life might break down into 99 percent tedium and 1 percent
heightened anxiety and/or potential violence. What Fontana has done
is emphasize and dramatize that one percent. Most of prison life,
says Walker, ``is about order and coping with order, and we all
have different ways of doing that, but when it gets ignited, that's
where `Oz' comes in and strings the heightened points together.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, the prisoners on ``Oz'' are a more clever, more articulate
lot than you might expect to find behind real-life bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of the dramatic license,'' says Simmons. ``The
average guys doing hard time in maximum security _ well, you know,
most of those guys are in there partly because of their lack of
options, and that includes growing up without any of the
advantages, including, in a lot of cases, smarts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very multi-layered show,'' says Walker. ``No matter
what your class, culture, color, or level of intelligence. If you
just want pure escapism, you can get that out of `Oz.' If you need
to be pushed cerebrally, you can get that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
