<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Eleanor Roosevelt: Vol 2, 1933-1938'' by Blanche Wiesen Cook
(Viking, $34.95). The greatest of presidents' wives, in the early
White House years. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Caravaggio: A Life'' by Helen Langdon (Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, $30). The dazzling Renaissance painter, warts and all. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The First World War'' by John Keegan (Knopf, $35). The
peerless military historian on Europe's great calamity. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Lorca: A Dream of Life'' by Leslie Stainton (Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, $35). A comprehensive biography of Federico Garcia Lorca,
the best-known Spanish writer of the century. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ladies' Man'' by Elinor Lipman (Random House, $23.95). A
comedy of errors (and manners) set in motion when a 55-year-old
roue visits three middle-aged sisters. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Jonathan Swift: A Portrait'' by Victoria Glendinning (Holt,
$35). Casual and chatty, literate and discriminating, this is a
civilized biography of the savage master of satire.
</P>
</TEXT>
