<HEADER>
A6893 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-SEX-BOS &LR;      07-12 1664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SEX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX TAKEN SERIOUSLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A strap slips, a shoulder dips, the evening gown slides away _
and instantly the short preview has you hooked.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, part of it is that ``Eyes Wide Shut'' is the last movie by
legendary filmmaker Stanley Kubrick, creator of such masterpieces
as ``Clockwork Orange,'' ``Full Metal Jacket,'' and ``2001: A Space
Odyssey,'' and is already rumored to be his chef-d'oeuvre.
</P>
<P>
   But let's be honest. The preview's promise is more elemental
than that, a direct-current jolt of desire that runs from the eyes
to the libido and back again.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal is as basic as the falling gown: ``Eyes Wide Shut''
is said to be a serious film about sexual relations. That alone
makes it an alluring oasis in a Hollywood wasteland.
</P>
<P>
   For 25 years, serious sex has been missing from the big screen.
Either pornography has hijacked it for movies that are merely
bouncing bodies, or the centripetal forces of market and culture
have conspired to spin out mass-market motion-picture products that
are unceasingly sophomoric or the cinematic equivalent of cafeteria
chow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are fewer and fewer movies dealing with adult
relations,'' laments Vivian Sobchack, a professor of film and
television at UCLA. ``If we are dealing with bodies now, the bodies
are being blown away, wasted, or involved in various kinds of
bathroom functions. It is a real infantilization of American
film.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Kubrick's final work, which premiers Friday, is the
repository for so many hopes. As the last work of an iconic
filmmaker, and a picture that stars two of Hollywood's most popular
actors, it simply can't be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who is not part of the `Austin Powers,' `StarWars,'
`Big Daddy' core audience _ which is everybody over 30 _ is waiting
for this film because it is the only thing out this summer that
looks at all engaging and mature,'' says Thomas Doherty, chairman
of Brandeis University's film studies program.
</P>
<P>
   Serious film aficionados hope that with his last picture,
Kubrick, who died just after its completion, may bequeath not just
a much-talked-about final work, but a new appreciation for serious
treatment of sexuality in cinema.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is high time we recaptured the adult movie category . . .
and actually have a movie that is by, for, and about adults
concerns,'' said Ray Carney, a professor of film at Boston
University. ``I can think of no other art that is so insistently
juvenile in subject and audience appeal than film.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always so. Sexually mature films enjoyed a brief
efflorescence in the late 1960s and early 1970s, just after actual
movie censorship ended and before cultural and commercial pressures
imposed themselves like a sodden superego over Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   That era produced six frank adult-themed movies that are still
talked about today: ``The Graduate'' (R, 1967); ``Midnight Cowboy''
(initally X, 1969); ``Bob &AMP; Carol &AMP; Ted &AMP; Alice'' (R, 1969); ``The
Last Picture Show'' (R, 1971); ``Carnal Knowledge'' (R, 1971); and
``Last Tango in Paris'' (X, 1973), an Italian-French coproduction,
but financed by United Artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came along very quickly after the end of censorship,''
says Gregory Black, professor of communication studies at the
University of Missouri at Kansas City and the author of two books
about censorship and film. ``Filmmakers and audiences were both
experimenting.''
</P>
<P>
   A quarter century, and thousands of movies, later, those
pictures still stand out as unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a frank, sophisticated approach to sexuality in the
cinema,'' said Rick Jewell, associate dean of the University of
Southern California's School of Cinema-Television. ``It has never
been quite the same since.''
</P>
<P>
   How much has the sexual climate changed?
</P>
<P>
   Well, ``Midnight Cowboy,'' the story of a street-stupid would-be
gigolo who ends up caring for a scrofulous street friend, won
Oscars for best picture, director, and screenplay for 1969, despite
its X rating, which was changed to R in 1971. ``Last Tango,''
featured on the cover of both Time and Newsweek, hailed by The New
Yorker's Pauline Kael, was nominated for two.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost inconceivable that that could happen today. These
days, says Jewell, most major studios demand in their contract that
directors bring their movies in at no more than an R rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``You literally can't make an NC-17,'' he said. ``You have to
keep cutting until you get to R.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of that is fear of backlash in a country that has steadily
backed away from the sexual revolution. Mankind, Mark Twain once
joked, ``has imagined a heaven and has left entirely out of it the
supremest of all his delights _ sexual intercourse.''
</P>
<P>
   Today ``sex and violence'' have become such a singular term of
denunciation that few seem to question why the erotic should be
condemned along with the destructive.
</P>
<P>
   But the change is as much market as moral. The pig in the python
of audience demographics is teenagers, who have both time and money
to be regular moviegoers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do something of a serious nature, exploring sexual
liaisons or relationships and you get an NC-17, that is much too
controversial,'' said Black. ``NC-17 is just death at the box
office. The mall theaters don't like to play it and the public
won't go see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Take ``Henry &AMP; June,'' Philip Kaufman's 1990 film about the
lovers' triangle among writers Henry Miller, his wife, June, and
Anais Nin. This was the film whose depiction of lesbian sex led the
Motion Picture Association of America to abandon the X rating and
create the NC-17 category.
</P>
<P>
   The hope was that the new rating would stand apart from the X,
which pornographers had appropriated as a lurid advertisement for
their product.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work out that way. Critically well-received, the film
made it into less than 150 theaters, and was a commercial flop. (In
its latest incarnation, ``Lolita,'' tame visually but controversial
for the adult-child relationship, spent years as a celluloid
zombie, wandering America in search of release.)
</P>
<P>
   Experiences like that have made R-ratings the golden mean, a
mark that promises enough spice to lure adults to the theater, but
not enough heat to make them leave their teenagers at home.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the regular news of procrustean cuts as a director reworks
his film to meet objections from the MPAA's ratings board,
Hollywood's voluntary system of censorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started out as a neutral objective measure just to inform
people, but it has become a shaping device that dictates the
content of the work,'' said Carney, who blames the search for an R
for the ``blandification of cinematic art.''
</P>
<P>
   Franker foreign films like Jean-Jacques Annaud's ``The Lover''
or Louis Malle's ``Damage'' are almost inevitably recut for the
American market.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are some exceptions _ ``sex, lies, &AMP; videotape,''
say, or the occasional Woody Allen film _ what the major Hollywood
studios produce for sexual fare is mostly silly teen movies like
``Risky Business'' or ``American Pie'' or cloying cute romances
like ``About Last Night'' and ``Reality Bites.'' Or we get noir
mysteries like ``Body Heat'' or thrillers like ``Fatal
Attraction,'' ``Basic Instinct,'' or ``Jade.'' Sex plays a role,
certainly, but it's a formulaic supporting part.
</P>
<P>
   Even ``9 1/2 Weeks,'' Adrian Lyne's high-gloss charade about
sexual control, turns out to be a movie about . . . obsession.
Indeed, obsession has become Hollywood's way of marketing any
vaguely erotic film, as though sex itself _ a topic that sweeps
like a second hand across the average person's mind, psychological
studies show _ wasn't itself a worthy subject of cinematic
exploration.
</P>
<P>
   That pitch says to the cautious middle-class, `You can see this
film without worrying that it might speak to you, that it might
touch a chord, that it might reveal something of yourself'; it is
about someone different, someone sexually obsessed.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick's film is hardly immune from those pressures, of course.
He, too, reportedly was under a studio obligation to deliver an
R-rated product, which has led to digital obscuring of body parts
in one group scene of the film. And yes, the marketing pitches the
movie as a ``thriller of jealousy and sexual obsession.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least at first blush, ``Eyes Wide Shut'' seems to promise
an exploration of common sexual temptations. The story of a
Manhattan doctor and his wife, beautiful people grown restless in
their marriage and ready to explore their sexual fantasies, part of
its appeal lies in that shadowed realm where passion lures reason
in search of stimulation.
</P>
<P>
   When you have sex, D.H. Lawrence said, you go to the dark gods.
There Cruise and Kidman seem to have gone _ and you want to follow,
vicariously, into the chthonian realm, to see, to experience, to
learn how they have changed upon their return.
</P>
<P>
   Could the film help reestablish the erotic film as a serious
Hollywood product? Drama, after all, has taken the first tentative
steps, with David Hare's ``Blue Room'' _ which also starred Kidman
_ and Patrick Marber's ``Closer,'' both treating sexual themes on
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get your hopes up. ``The country is too conservative and
the demographics that drive the industry are too young,'' avers
Black.
</P>
<P>
   USC's Jewell is a bit more optimistic. If ``Eyes Wide Shut''
meets with both critical and box office success, it might start a
trend, he says. But even then the impetus would have to come from
the adventurous actors or directors whose past success has given
them power to defy convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only a limited number of people who can get
financing for anything they want to do,'' said Jewell. ``These kind
of films are only going to get made if people who have the kind of
power that Stanley Kubrick and Tom Cruise do agree to make them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Scot Lehigh is The Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
