<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOVE LESSONS' TAKES PAGE FROM VOWS COLUMN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE DANIEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
LOVE LESSONS 
Twelve Real-Life Love Stories 
By Lois Smith Brady 
Simon &AMP; Schuster, $20, 236 pp. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For seven years, Lois Smith Brady has written the Vows column in
the Style section of The Sunday New York Times. Her slice-of-life
stories about brides and grooms have attracted a faithful, mostly
female readership _ even as the marriage rate falls and the divorce
rate soars. Early on in the life of the column, Brady writes in her
book ``Love Lessons: Twelve Real-Life Love Stories,'' she started
to realize that ``people do not really care about cake frosting and
petticoats. What truly captures their interest _ and what has held
mine for all these years _ are the love stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady's book, comprising 11 expanded Vows columns, along with
one chapter about her own parents' love story, is a bit like a
wedding cake. It's attractive, very sweet, and irresistible. But
after a few bites you need to put it aside.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, the sugar is diluted with Brady's warmth and wisdom,
which are what make ``Love Lessons'' worth reading. In the
emotional introduction, she shares details about her awkward
adolescence and her oft-bruised heart. Perhaps her love of love
stories is due to the fact that she has been living one with her
husband of more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   She imparts bits of wisdom from her aisle-hopping career: ``I
learned that true love has some universal qualities and telltale
signs. For one thing, most couples I've interviewed said they felt
incredibly lucky, even giddy, after meeting. . . . Whenever anyone
asks me about love now, I always say wait for that feeling, wait,
wait, wait.''
</P>
<P>
   And I liked this analogy: ``One woman I interviewed compared the
experience of falling in love to finding a gilded ballroom on the
other side of your small, dingy studio apartment. It's something
you never imagined existed, something magical, a little scary when
you think about it, and bigger than you ever dreamed.''
</P>
<P>
   As different as the couples in ``Love Lessons'' are, most hail
from New York City, or live there now, so many of the stories have
a decidedly Manhattan feel. Their ages and situations speak to the
variety of life: an older couple, newly widowed people, a man and
woman who meet briefly while traveling overseas, people who rush to
the altar and those who wait for years and years, the disabled, the
daredevils, people who fall in love, then out, then back in, such
as Brady's parents.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the couples, however, border on storybook caricature.
There's the quintessential rumpled bachelor who falls for the very
wealthy single mom, the two perfectly sweet earthy-crunchies who
walk down the aisle barefoot and exchange silver pendants instead
of rings, the couple who meet in a version of ``You've Got Mail.''
But these people do live. Their names, and even their photos (a
nice touch) are published.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Harlequin Romance effect probably is a product of
Brady's dramatic writing style, which at times makes everyone seem
a bit too perfect, or a bit too easy to analyze. And just as pastry
chefs sometimes load a cake with too many frosted flowers, Brady
too often weighs down her sentences with needless similes. ``When
my parents visited them, they would all sit out on the porch,
surrounded by weeping willow trees, and talk about literature while
the trees shook in the wind, rustling like wedding dresses.'' Not
being a ``Vows'' follower, I kept wondering, does she always write
this way? And if she does, does it come naturally or does she go
back and fill in the metaphors later?
</P>
<P>
   But despite this tendency to over-adorn, Brady is
conversational, quite fuuny, and clearly respects her subjects. If
she's ever cynical, she doesn't show it. Her warm feelings extend
to ex-partners, as well. As she so wonderfully puts it, ``Love is
not a eraser,'' suggesting that new relationships don't have to
wipe out former ones.
</P>
<P>
   Brady wrote an interesting New York Times column in May. Called
``Vows: An Update,'' it was headlined, ``The Seven-Year Itch: Where
are They Now?'' and looked up some of the first couples she'd
written about. Not surprisingly, half of them had divorced. Of
course the cynic in me couldn't help wondering how many of the
perfect pairings in ``Love Lessons'' would last, but perhaps that's
not really the point. For if you ever wanted (needed?) proof
positive that hope _ and love _ springs eternal, this book is it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
