<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 
! ``American Pie'' An entry in the bonehead-movie-of-the-summer
stakes, this high-school romp is gross, tasteless, and stupidly
sentimental in its desperate attempt to be this year's ``There's
Something About Mary.'' It's also humor-impaired, peopled by horny
boys who want to shed the yoke of loserdom and go for the winner's
circle. (R) (Jim Sullivan) 
 
!!! ``Arlington Road'' This manipulative but effective
conspiracy-theory film smartly taps into fears of another Oklahoma
City or another World Trade Center bombing. It pits Jeff Bridges's
anxious high-school teacher against neighbors (Tim Robbins and Joan
Cusack, both compellingly cast against type) he's convinced are
right-wing terrorists. (R) 
 
!!! ``Edge of Seventeen'' This poignant, touching film perfectly
and painfully captures the awkwardness of adolescence as a gay
high-school senior (winningly played by Chris Stafford) bumbles and
fumbles his way through the minefield of young romance in 1980s
Ohio. (Unrated) (Renee Graham) 
 
!! 1/2 ``Windhorse'' The most impressive thing about this
pro-Tibetan, anti-Chinese film, shot in Nepal and (clandestinely)
in Tibet, is that it got made at all. Apart from novelty value,
striking settings, and movingly heartfelt performances, the film is
undermined by simplistic construction. (Unrated)
