<SLUG> BC-SCI-HEALTH-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUTURE FOODS MAY CURE WHAT AILS YOU 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's genetically-modified foods are altered for pest
resistance, but tomorrow's will be engineered for disease
prevention and nutrient content.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists envision potatoes that will carry vaccines and
broccoli that will be packed with antioxidant vitamins. These
so-called ``functional foods'' will blur the line between
pharmaceuticals and food, researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   Val Giddings, vice president of food and agriculture at the
Biotechnology Industry Council, said he believes that one day
people will go to the doctor and get a prescription of ``so many
grams of this strain of broccoli and this variety of corn.''
</P>
<P>
   Life science companies like Monsanto and Dupont already have a
number of products in the pipeline. The first designer foods to hit
the market will probably be bananas with delayed ripening
qualities, tomatoes with a higher antioxidant content, higher-
protein rice (using genes transferred from pea plants), and
strawberries with increased levels of ellagic acid, a natural
cancer-fighting agent.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the US Food and Drug Administration has approved a
margarine called Benecol, which is supposed to lower cholesterol
levels. Iowa-based Pioneer Hi-Bred International and Dupont have a
joint venture, called Optimum Quality Grains, that has produced
LoSatSoy oil made from beans that have half the saturated fat as
others.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also working on making the soybean taste less
``beany,'' said Optimum president and CEO Carrol Bolen, so it can
be used by people who want the health benefits of soy but don't
like the taste.
</P>
<P>
   But Bolen, who is also a vice president at Pioneer, said the
next five years are critical. ``It will tell us a lot more about
whether agriculture biotechnology can really deliver,'' he said.
``We believe the opportunity is real. We are investing very heavily
in the area.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Monsanto is working on a high-solids potato that
doesn't soak up as much oil during frying, as well as canola that
is rich in beta-catotene to combat vitamin A deficiency, a problem
in many developing countries, said spokeman Jay Byrne.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot more research is needed to determine how to maximize
different nutrients, said Jeffrey Blumberg, a professor of
nutrition at Tufts University.
</P>
<P>
   Blumberg said scientists have only focused on phytochemicals, or
plant compounds, for the last 10 years and have just started to see
results in the last five. Beyond 52 known vitamins, minerals, amino
acids, sugars, and fatty acids essential to life, scientists are
just beginning to document a wide range of other substances in
foods that may be important for warding off disease and maintaining
good health.
</P>
<P>
   For example, nutrients such as flavonoids are antioxidants found
naturally in tea and in many fruits and vegetables such as broccoli
and onions. Blumberg said that such nutrients can either be
enhanced in foods that already have them or be added to those that
don't normally produce them, ``so if you don't like the tomato''
you could eat an engineered food with a similar profile, Blumberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   But this is easier said than done. ``If I want to reengineer a
tea to contain more flavonoid, which one of the more than 400 do I
pick? I am not suggesting there are adverse effects, but we don't
know enough about which ones provide the best benefit,'' Blumberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   Once modified fruits and vegetables come out of the pipeline,
labeling will become an issue. James Maryanski, biotechnology
coordinator for foods at the FDA, said that the agency has not yet
established specific guidelines on how to label such foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not engaged in the process at the moment,'' Maryanski
said, because these foods are not yet commercially available. ``We
are evaluating them on a case by case basis.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a new high oleic soybean oil, which has more
``good'' monounsaturated fat than regular soybean oil, will be
labeled as such, Maryanski said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
