<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENMAGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GENERATION, SAME OLD STORIES FOR TEEN GIRLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE GANAHL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was 16, there was ``16.''
</P>
<P>
   The glossy magazine was packed with information for adolescent
girls on how to get rid of pimples, why the newest rock star was
the coolest thing on wheels, how to avoid geekdom by buying hip
clothes and, especially, how to get a boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   And now, 30 years later, with the Age of Aquarius allegedly in
full swing, we have a proliferation of magazines for teen-age
girls: Teen People, Latin Girl, Jump and, now, the newly launched
CosmoGirl, the little sister of Cosmopolitan.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? CosmoGirl's pages are filled with advice on: how to
get rid of pimples, why the newest rock star is the coolest thing
on wheels, how to avoid geekdom by buying hip clothes and, once
again, how to get a boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Call it ``Cosmo with Training Wheels.'' It's equally glossy,
with blaring colors and even louder headlines promising remarkable
life reversals. (``Turn Your Crush Into Your Boyfriend!'') And
perhaps it will do for the next generation of women what ``Cosmo''
did for mine: nudge it down the slippery slope of self-loathing.
</P>
<P>
   When I was in my 20s, Cosmopolitan was Goddess among my gullible
friends. It dictated our fashion, our hairstyles, our social mores
_ making us feel miserably inadequate in the process. (``Jeez, why
doesn't my butt look that good?'') Eventually we wised up, one by
one, and started buying Ms. instead.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, I've had a firsthand look at the impact on young
girls of a society obsessed with physical perfection _ first as a
counselor in a psychiatric hospital that specialized in teen-age
girls with eating disorders (the walls of their rooms were covered
with photos of size-2 models!) and then as the mother of a teen-age
girl. She never went through a major geek stage, but frequently was
knocked sideways by the messages in magazines.
</P>
<P>
   One morning, I found her wailing in front of the mirror: ``I
hate my nose! It's so big!''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, it's not. It was time to dump the YM's
cluttering her room. (I wish we'd been on line then, so I could
have fed her a healthy antidote of ChickClick and Riotgrrl; the
most counter-Cosmo media around is on the Net.)
</P>
<P>
   You hardly can blame Hearst Magazines _ the publisher of 37
international editions of Cosmopolitan _ for running a product up
the flagpole. Apparently the national economy depends on the
allowance money spent by girls between the ages of 12 and 17.
</P>
<P>
   There are roughly 15 million of 'em, spending _ or getting their
parents to spend _ an incredible $96 a week average. That's some
kind of allowance. And ad money waiting to be spent.
</P>
<P>
   In response, magazines have popped up right and left to compete
with the super-successful triumvirate of Seventeen, Teen and YM.
Some are narrower in their focus: by ethnicity (Honey, Latin Girl
and Latina), by interest (a magazine for young New Age
spiritualists called New Moon), even by body type (Girl, founded by
Mode, the magazine for plus-size women.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite some of these magazines' attempts to hire models who
look like real people, those with huge circulations _ of which
CosmoGirl surely will be one _ still project a rail-thin, Calista
Flockhart vision of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Most troubling of all, Helen Gurley Brown's Cosmo-girl
philosophy lurks beneath the cheery cover of its junior version.
</P>
<P>
   Check the subject matter. ``Horoscope Booklet! 365 Days of Love
and Life Tips!'' ``Back to School Fashion Blitz: The 10 Items You
Can't Start School Without!'' And there is even a page each month
of stickers: this month, Ben Affleck. (And to think in my youth I
spent all those hours cutting out Peter Tork photos by hand!)
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it would be absurd to expect stories about ``What you can
do to save the rain forest'' or ``How to love your body just the
way it is.'' And to CosmoGirl's credit, there is a section called
Inner Girl that includes advice and self-help. But aside from a
piece on how to improve your grades, the advice deals mostly with
dating, eschewing a larger world view.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to see a piece on ``what to do if your parents are on
welfare and you can't afford any of the stuff we're hawking.''
</P>
<P>
   These magazines have been hammered in recent years _
specifically by psychologist Mary Pipher, who wrote 1994's
``Reviving Ophelia'' _ for turning teen girls into early slaves to
consumerism. One particularly egregious example in CosmoGirl is an
article on ``How to Turn Your Parents' No's to Yes's.'' The
problem: ``I want those jeans! So what if they're $100? All my
friends have them! I need them!''
</P>
<P>
   The writer suggests that teens ``change your voice to
`pleasant,''' and notes that if you ``make your mom feel like her
opinion counts, she'll be flattered and happy. Happy people buy
more stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   No fewer than 17 articles in CosmoGirl are about fashion and
beauty products _ each marked with brand names and values, things
you can buy. There's something troubling about a magazine with a
target audience starting at 12 years of age expending dozens of
pages on makeup looks. (Almost amusing is the painstaking,
step-by-step guide to applying makeup in order to affect the
``nature girl'' look.)
</P>
<P>
   I guess it's all part and parcel of ``Girl Power,'' the
adolescent stab at feminism launched when the Spice Girls began
their dubious tenure as role models. It's been troubling since the
get-go. The mantra seems to be: Be strong, be yourself, but get a
guy and buy, buy, buy. What ``power'' is there in slavery to that
ideal?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
