<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6929 &Cx1f; sci-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-     07-12 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, July 13:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PHYSICAL (Undated) _ Medical educators worry that a
generation of young doctors dazzled by sophisticated tests and
computer printouts is turning away from the hands-on skills for the
physical examination that, once forgotten, may never be retrieved
again. By Abigail Zuger.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CHINA-SPACE (Undated) _ China is striving to become only the
third nation in history to launch humans into space, a feat that
could come as early as next year, say international space experts.
By Warren Leary.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PROBLEMSOLVING (Undated) _ Satisfiability problems, called
SAT problems for short, arise in thousands of situations, from
staffing companies and scheduling airline flights to planning
wedding dinners that won't devolve into food fights. Researchers
embrace satisfiability problems as a tool for studying a phenomenon
called computational complexity. By George Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-UNETHICAL-EXPERIMENTS (Undated) _ In our time we have seen
the growth of systematic, state-sponsored programs of unethical
experimentation, and they have occurred in nations as diverse as
the United States, Nazi Germany, China, Japan and Iraq and South
Africa, a California researcher has concluded. By Philip J. Hilts.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPACE-XRAY (Undated) _ NASA is in final stages of
preparation to send a giant new X-ray telescope into space, on a
mission led by the Eileen Collings, first woman ever command a
flight. With images from distant galaxies, the telescope, called
the Chandra, inform scientists about the earliest days of the
universe. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRAIN (Undated) _ Researchers at the California Institute of
Technology have now mapped part of the process of the brain, one
step in the path from image to action. Their work holds promise
that some day people will be able to put limb-related brain
activity to use. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DOCTORS-WORLD (Undated) _ Political leaders in African are
finally beginning to take seriously the AIDS epidemic, which has
infected millions. Now, the U.N.'s top AIDS official says enough
leaders are taking action to curb the rapid transmission rate. By
Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WOMEN-SEX (Undated) _ By A host of pharmaceutical companies
are working to do for women what Viagra does for men. To do this
effectively, they need far more scientific data on female sexual
response than is presently available. By Anne Eisenberg.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CASES (Undated) _ An examination of a rare case of amnesia
that also involved a loss of perception of time. A man disappeared
from his job, traveled to Florida and was found on I-95, believing
he was a 23-year-old soldier struggling to get back to Fort Bragg.
The cause was found to be a cyst in the brain. By Marcia Sherman,
M.D.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SOUTHPOLE (Undated) _ This weekend the National Science
Foundation airdropped medical supplies for a woman wintering at the
South Pole who has developed a lump in her breast. What did they
send and what can she do down there? By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Items about flight patterns of bumblebees,
dating sedimentary rocks, and a star discovery. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH ( Undated) _ Personal Health: Few doctors are
trained to deliver bad news, and many _ in haste, anxiety, guilt or
sheer ignorance of the impact of their words _ say things to
patients and families that cause needless emotional pain and may
even compromise the effectiveness of treatment. By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Health notes and news: Over the past
few years there has been much debate over whether people who quit
smoking are more likely to get into traffic accidents. Now
scientists writing in the journal Nature say they have found no
connection; Researchers who studied low-birth-weight infants have
found that doses of vitamin A can significantly lower their risk of
chronic lung disease and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-QNA (Undated) _ On sleep paralysis, compounding, herbs and
anesthesia, and dangerous dolphins. By C. Claiborne Ray.
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   Some ScienceTimes stories are available to international clients
only by special arrangement, and are so marked. Asian and European
points: contact Karl Horwitz in Paris for details and prices
(Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX: 47-42-80-44). Latin American points:
contact Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX:
310-996-0089).
</P>
