<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7047 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROLLERHOCKEY-TEX     07-12 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROLLERHOCKEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLLER HOCKEY: THE BEST NEW SPECTATOR SPORT YOU'VE NEVER HEARD OF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Four nights after Game Six, that three-overtime
showdown that clinched the Stanley Cup for the Dallas Stars,
another Dallas hockey team had reason to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Stallions, the new roller hockey team, beat the
Anaheim Bullfrogs at Reunion Arena. It was the Stallions' first
victory of the season, finally changing that first number in its
embarrassing 0-7-0 record.
</P>
<P>
   What? You say you've never heard of the Stallions?
</P>
<P>
   Join the club. There hasn't been much of a spotlight on the
in-line skating brand of hockey, even though it's one of the fast
growing sports in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, more people are involved in non-ice hockey than ice
hockey. There are more little- and rec-league roller teams than
ever. The latest report from Roller Hockey International says there
are 6 million registered roller hockey players in the United
States, compared with ice hockey's 2.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier to learn and it's cheaper to get involved with
than ice hockey,'' said Charles Billera of Slapshots, home to many
of Arlington's recreational league roller hockey players. ``Plus
there's no checking in (amateur) roller hockey, so (players) learn
the skills of handling the stick and shooting and don't have to
worry if someone's going to take (their) head off.''
</P>
<P>
   In RHI, the major leagues of roller hockey, you'll see the same
hard checking and solid body contact found in ice hockey, though
there is usually less fighting. Not to say that doesn't happen. At
a recent Stallions vs. Chicago Bluesmen game, Dallas' Yanick Evola
ended up in the penalty box for a fight over a ref's call.
</P>
<P>
   Because hockey moves a little faster on in-line wheels, there
are typically double the shots-on-goal and points in an ice hockey
game. It's more about offense. Players take more risks when
shooting, sometimes going for the occasional luck shot from what
would be a three-point zone in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The puck isn't hard rubber but plastic, and it has eight small,
dome-shaped runners to help it glide easily across the plastic
Sport Court surface. Almost as much as it stays flat, the puck
rolls on its side or flies through the air. With the same relative
frequency as in a baseball game, it ventures into the stands where
fans await, and occasionally fight, over it. And you don't even
need a glove to catch it.
</P>
<P>
   Another difference between Stallions and Stars games: tickets
are cheaper ($7-$25) and parking is much more accessible. Reunion
Arena closes off its upper level and only sells tickets for the
lower and floor levels.
</P>
<P>
   USA Hockey InLine, the roller division of USA Hockey, boasts
more than 82,000 registered players, coaches and volunteers,
usually participating through venues such as Slapshots (in
Arlington and Richardson, Texas), the Arlington Skatium and North
Richland Hills' Mountasia. This year, the Fort Worth Brahmas began
a Surge Blacktop summer tour in which players make weekly stops
throughout the Metroplex and offer free skills clinics for youths.
</P>
<P>
   Still, RHI has struggled since its inception in 1993. By 1994,
the league boasted 24 teams, but that number quickly declined. In
1998, the league took a hiatus to restructure and evaluate.
</P>
<P>
   Many thought it wouldn't return. But USA Hockey InLine and RHI
joined forces and announced more programs and expanded Web sites.
Now professional roller hockey is back.
</P>
<P>
   The Stallions team is one of four new RHI members. Joining
Dallas in the Western Conference are the Bullfrogs, the San Jose
Rhinos and the Las Vegas Coyotes. The Eastern Conference consists
of new teams Chicago Bluesman and Minnesota Blue Ox, plus the
Buffalo Wings and St. Louis Vipers.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds are small, but growing. The Stallions typically garner
upwards of 800 fans at Reunion, mostly those who play in
recreational leagues or parents of children in little leagues.
</P>
<P>
   George and Linda Aponte of nearby Plano have made six of the
seven home games. Their sons, Matt, 11, and Leo, 12, play for the
Slapshots All-Stars in Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing for the kids is getting to see the game up
close,'' Linda said. ``And also that they get a chance to catch the
puck.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Stallions-Bluesmen game, despite the fact that the
Stallions were ahead the entire game, coach Alan May kept that
concerned coach look on his face. But the players, most of whom are
on summer downtime from Western Professional and Central Hockey
league teams, looked like they were actually having fun _ of
course, they were winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost look at them as guys who would play for free in a rec
league somewhere,'' George Aponte said.
</P>
<P>
   They practically are playing for free. All RHI players receive
the same compensation from the league: $300 per player per victory,
$200 per loss. Compare that with the Western Professional Hockey
League's salary cap of $10,000 per week and the National Hockey
League's pay, which averages $3 million per season.
</P>
<P>
   The future of major league roller hockey is uncertain. The
crowds at Reunion are growing, and even though they don't come
close to those in California _ San Jose and Anaheim each typically
see 4,000 patrons per game _ they're not as dismal as the crowds in
Minnesota, which number around 300. (Poor Minnesota must have given
up on any version of professional hockey.)
</P>
<P>
   And in the wake of the Stanley Cup, things look bright. ``We'll
reap the benefits of everything in the fall,'' says Billera. ``It's
too early to gauge the effects of the Stars, but it can only get
better.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
