<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7048 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNPRIVATEHOMES-TEX     07-12 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNPRIVATEHOMES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME OF THE FUTURE BORROWS FUNCTIONS FROM PAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New homes designed by internationally recognized architects
include features common to thousand-year-old dwellings where work,
storehouses, relatives, employees, servants and guests were all
sheltered under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   The connection and evolution between new technological marvels
and their medieval antecedents is the subject of an exhibit at New
York's Museum of Modern Art, ``The Un-Private House,'' through Oct.
5.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Riley, chief curator of MoMA's architecture and design
department, selected 26 homes recently built or under construction
to illustrate his hypothesis that the changing demographics of the
family, the proliferation of a variety of media and new concepts of
work and leisure are responsible for the architectural response
that borrows function from the past while exploiting new materials
and resources.
</P>
<P>
   Riley sees homes of the future as a fluid membrane within which
to stage our lives. Houses will need to be adaptable; spaces will
need to be transitory. Barrier walls will need to be translucent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The private house today has become a permeable structure,
receiving and transmitting images, sounds, text and data,'' Riley
says.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Herzog and Pierre de Meuron's house for a California
couple, to be completed in 2000, will have numerous screens on
which to display their extensive collection of electronic art. In
another instance, the owners of a Manhattan apartment, two Wall
Street traders, have seven display screens scattered throughout
their home. The screens constantly display information about the
international currency markets.
</P>
<P>
   Gisue and Mojgan Hariri's Digital House has interior and
exterior glass walls composed of liquid crystal display (LCD)
blocks that can assist and enhance daily living. A Julia Child-like
character pops up over the kitchen counter and dispenses food
preparation information, while virtual guests appear for a virtual
visit in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   Architects Elizabeth Diller and Ricardo Scofidio play with the
duality of virtual and real. In their Long Island weekend house, a
camera is positioned to capture the best view of the landscape.
This image is played back and competes with the actual view. ``The
view may be recorded and deferred ... day played back at night,
fair weather played back in foul,'' say the designers.
</P>
<P>
   While some architects exploit communication devices, others are
shifting the boundaries between public and private, work and
leisure. This is exemplified in Rem Koolhaas' House in Bordeaux. A
moving platform in the center of the house can be raised or lowered
among the three floors. This arrangement not only gives mobility to
the owner, who uses a wheelchair, but it also creates different
spatial arrangements with each move.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic public/private intercourse can be seen in
Shigeru Ban's Curtain Wall House. Located in a densely populated
Toyko neighborhood, it has glass walls and dramatic 2-story fabric
curtains that can be closed to obtain privacy or opened to create a
stage as public as any outdoor amphitheater.
</P>
<P>
   A new domestic architecture has been developed in response to
the radical transformation of the nuclear family: more couples
without children, same-sex couples, people living alone and
families with children from previous marriages. Many couples
without children have adopted loft living. Families with children
from previous marriages have constructed separate spaces adjacent
to the main house to afford the children as well as the parents a
sense of autonomy and privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The social conditions and structures that drove the development
of the private house _ the need for privacy, the separation of
living and work, the family, domesticity _ have all changed
drastically, perhaps more so in the past 50 years than in the
preceding four centuries, Riley says.
</P>
<P>
   The houses he chose to document these changes form the first of
five thematic exhibitions made possible by the Lily Auchincloss
Fund for Contemporary Architecture. The architects who designed
them are not only reconfiguring the domestic landscape, Riley says,
they are also ``laying the groundwork for the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
