<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MANAGED-CARE (Washington) _ As the Senate begins debate on
legislation to provide a ``bill of rights'' for patients,
Republicans warn that Democratic plans to regulate managed care
would jack up health care costs and lead to more uninsured people.
The Democrats, meanwhile, contend that the GOP proposals would
benefit only insurance companies. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TAXES (Washington) _ President Clinton's threat to veto
the tax cuts being proposed by Republicans in the House and Senate.
In addition to shoring up Social Security and Medicare, the White
House says the surplus should be used to avoid cuts in funding as
envisioned when the Congress adopted caps on government spending in
1997. By BENNETT ROTH
</P>
<P>
   GORE-GUNS (Washington) _ Vice President Al Gore is proposing an
anti-crime agenda that includes photo licenses for all new handgun
owners, a ban on cheap handguns, increased spending on police
training and a constitutional amendment for victims' rights.
Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush has far less
restrictive policies, while Gore's primary opponent, former Sen.
Bill Bradley, has policies that are even more restrictive. By ALAN
BERNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   CISNEROS-HEARING (Washington) _ U.S. District Judge Stanley
Sporkin separates the conspiracy cases of former Housing Secretary
Henry and those of two onetime aides, and federal prosecutors agree
to eventually drop charges against the pair. Cisneros, along with
John Rosales and Sylvia Arce-Garcia, have pleaded not guilty to
conspiracy charges in a 21-count federal indictment. By GARY
MARTIN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FRIVOLOUS-LAWSUITS (San Antonio) _ An inmate at the Bexar County
Jail in San Antonio pays $744 to the district attorney after a
judge ruled that the lawsuit the inmate filed was without merit.
The payment is a result of the law aimed at preventing prisoners
from filing frivolous lawsuits. The plaintiff had claimed jail
employees failed to protect him from another inmate who tried to
attack him with a pen. By THADDEUS HERRICK.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The U.S. women's soccer World Cup
victory may result in a timely save for Title IX, which is under
assault from House Speaker Dennis Hastert, who believes it has been
unfair to male athletes. The 1972 law has been a prime force in
providing women new athletic opportunities similar to those of men.
For politicians eager to woo the female vote, kicking around Title
IX would not seem to be a big winner, particularly now. By MARIANNE
MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush could
chip in a little more money to pay for state-paid security guards
as he travels the country running for president. Bush should also
give up his state salary _ about $316 a day _ when he's campaigning
out of state, too. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   UNITY-OUTRAGE (Houston) _ I am outraged at the coverage of Texas
Gov. George W. Bush at the Unity convention in Seattle. I am
outraged because those quoted consider themselves journalists, and
in most instances the kind of journalists whose jobs call for them
to handle any assignment, political or otherwise, fairly and
objectively. Suggesting that members of groups with ``journalists''
in the name can and do influence the news angers me, frightens me,
makes me want to bash my head against a wall because of the
oppression of having my trade turn on me. By JANE ELY.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALL-STAR (Boston) _ In this era where 12-11 slugfests are
becoming almost routine, Boston's Pedro Martinez is on a pace to
become the first pitcher to win 30 games in more than 30 years. And
Martinez, who carries a 15-3 record into his All-Star starting
assignment Tuesday night, is doing it at Fenway Park, of all
places. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Boston) _ For first-time All-Stars Billy Wagner,
Mike Hampton and Jose Lima of the Houston Astros, this is a pretty
special day. Just being in Boston for the 1999 All-Star Game. Just
getting to play at Fenway Park. And just being in the clubhouse
with the Barry Bonds and Ken Griffeys of the world. By JOSEPH
DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   GLF-BRITISH (Carnoustie, Scotland) _ Tranplanted Texan Steve
Elkington may be among the many contenders for this week's British
Open at Carnoustie, but even he believes the course is going to be
the real victor. By EDDIE SEFKO.
</P>
