<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GRANNY D': PATRIOT OF THE YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, we examined the roots of American patriotism. Today,
I hold up a sprightly 89-year-old woman from New Hampshire as
walking proof that patriotism, idealism and citizen activism still
live, despite the widespread cynicism that invades our political
processes.
</P>
<P>
   My nominee for Patriot of the Year is Doris Haddock, known
affectionately to 11 great grandchildren as ``Granny D.'' She is
walking across America, from Los Angeles to the nation's capital,
in an effort to awaken Americans to the insidious dangers of big
campaign contributions which, she is convinced, are corrupting our
electoral system and threaten to destroy the very soul of our
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Last week I talked with this slightly built woman in Fort Worth,
which she calls the ``halfway point'' in her journey. Thinking of
her New England roots, I could not help comparing her mission with
that of Paul Revere. Asked why she treks across American on a
mission some have called a fool's errand, she says: ``Let me tell
you about impossible causes. There are none on this Earth if they
are good causes.''
</P>
<P>
   The journey by foot, from one end of our country to the other,
has not been without hardship. Mrs. Haddock suffered dehydration
crossing the Mojave Desert in Arizona and had to be hospitalized
for four days.
</P>
<P>
   She has emphysema, acquired before she quit smoking some 20
years ago. Arthritis requires her to wear a steel-ribbed corset as
she walks. A hearing aid helps her to identify the sounds of
traffic. ``Aside from emphysema, arthritis and poor hearing,'' she
jokes, ``I'm in great shape!''
</P>
<P>
   Followed by a van staffed by volunteers, the determined reformer
wears a broad straw hat and sensible shoes while walking a measured
10 miles daily, starting before sun-up to avoid the midday heat.
She has walked Mondays through Saturdays, beginning New Year's Day
in the Rose Bowl, and calculates that she'll reach Washington,
D.C., on her 90th birthday Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, she will deliver to House Speaker Dennis Hastert and
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott a truckload of petitions she has
gathered along the way. The messages, signed by many thousands of
private citizens, demand that congressional leaders schedule votes
on bills to tighten election laws. She wants to stem the growing
tide of outrageously big campaign contributions from corporate
interests with legislative axes to grind, which increasingly
dominate American political life.
</P>
<P>
   This remarkable woman's coast-to-coast pilgrimage began on a
shoestring and a mountain of faith. It has been abetted by friends
and volunteers who carefully measure each day's 10-mile journey and
line up speaking appearances and hospitable lodging for each
night's rest.
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth, for example, she stayed at the home of attorney
Harold Hammet, who first became acquainted with Mrs. Haddock's
family four decades ago when he was a student at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   Widowed a few years back, her children and grandchildren grown,
Granny D depends for most of her livelihood on Social Security.
Last year, when her best friend died, the hopeful reformer says:
``I looked at my life and my lifelong beliefs and said to myself,
`How can I turn my pain into something beautiful or at least useful
in the world? What work can I do as a memorial to those I miss?' ''
</P>
<P>
   In a July Fourth speech to a Unitarian church in Dallas, Mrs.
Haddock explained, ``I do this for my great-grandchildren and all
the many boys and girls who may someday want to run for office.''
And for the hundreds of people she knows ``who love this country
and are deeply worried.'' Reflecting upon the almost 1,800 miles of
her journey thus far, she added: ``I do it for the truck drivers,
the engineers of the trains who blow their horns for me, and the
schoolchildren who yell, `Go, Granny, go!' ''
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth, Mayor Kenneth Barr and the Fort Worth City
Council officially proclaimed July 6 Doris ``Granny D'' Haddock
day. She shared her honor with newly crowned World Bantamweight
Boxing Champion Paulie Ayala, who hugged her joyfully.
</P>
<P>
   Her self-appointed mission to shame Congress into reforming
campaign practices is not Mrs. Haddock's first Quixotic venture.
Her daughter, Betty Lawrenz, remembers with a chuckle when her
mother encouraged the churches of their city to sponsor dances for
teen-agers, to assure a wholesome environment. One church broke the
ice, and others soon followed.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1960, Mrs. Haddock and her husband, along with
their local Episcopal priest, traveled to Alaska to protect a
village of native Alaskans from being uprooted by the government
for an underground nuclear bomb test. They prevailed, and the
eviction order was never carried out.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout her life, the determined lady says, she has refused
to ask whether a cause is achievable. She asks, instead, if it's
right. If it passes that test, she asks what she can do as one
person to help it come about.
</P>
<P>
   It was this reasoning, and this faith, that began her
coast-to-coast journey last New Year's Day. At first largely
ignored, she now has the attention of national TV networks.
Considering her track record, I wouldn't bet against her.
</P>
<P>
   Patriotism takes many forms, as varied as the shapes of
snowflakes under a microscope. From Nathan Hale's regret that he
had but one life to give for his country, to poet Ernest Crosby's
belief that it's even more heroic to live for one's country, our
democracy has been sustained by the faith of patriots who, like
Mrs. Haddock, see a need and give themselves to it.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
