<HEADLINE>
TALKING TACKY TO SOME FOLK WHO DESERVE IT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Sub to include (at) symbol in e-mail address) 
 
By JANE ELY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although I readily admit I occasionally have experienced some
pretty high-level indignation with an individual or two in my line
of work, never can I recall feeling pure, total outrage with a
great band of folk in the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Well, let the record reflect: I am purely, totally outraged.
</P>
<P>
   I am outraged at most of the sentiment reported out of the Unity
convention in Seattle about Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumed
leader in the race for the Republican presidential nomination in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   First came reports that many of the participants were quite
unhappy because Bush, though he was to be in Seattle last week, was
not planning an appearance at the meeting of the group called
Unity: Journalists of Color Inc., a coalition of four associations
of minority journalists _ blacks, Hispanics, Native Americans and
Asian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign decided the candidate's Seattle schedule was
too full for an appearance at the convention _ which reportedly
drew about 6,000, and many of the conventioneers decided that was a
snub by him and didn't like it worth a damn.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, it should be noted, did any who were quoted after Bush did
a hurried walk-through like that worth a damn.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, you might say that as far as the Unity convention was
concerned, Bush was damned if he did and damned if he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   But this doesn't have anything to do with Bush or his candidacy.
Nor does my outrage have anything to do with the fact those quoted
as being angry and/or disappointed with Bush are members of the
minority groups represented at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   My outrage is because those quoted consider themselves
journalists, and in most instances the kind of journalists whose
jobs call for them to handle any assignment, political or
otherwise, fairly and objectively.
</P>
<P>
   Suggesting that members of groups with ``journalists'' in the
name can and do influence the news angers me, frightens me, makes
me want to bash my head against a wall because of the oppression of
having my trade turn on me.
</P>
<P>
   Those who spoke in scorn because Bush wasn't coming and then
spoke in contempt as they viewed the brevity of his visit an insult
happened to insult me and, I fervently hope, about a jillion others
in the business.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a Seattle-based magazine photographer and a member
of the Hispanic journalists association most decidedly was not
speaking from his Hispanic standpoint when he claimed
disappointment on hearing the original report Bush would not
appear. What he reportedly said of the Texas governor was: ``He
should take advantage of this and bring his word to the people who
will cover his campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, good grief.
</P>
<P>
   I consider it outright horrifying that someone who calls himself
a journalist even thought that, much less said it. That is a
thought that should not even occur to someone in the news end of
this business. Indeed, it's really pushing the proverbial envelope
for writers of editorials or columns to suggest such a thing _
except, perhaps, in disassociating themselves from any who do think
it.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I disassociate myself from such as the Chicago television
anchorman and member of the black journalists group who actually
had the atrocious gall to contend: ``This is a community that can
make or break most candidates. He Bush should be here. He should
not overlook us.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, woe is me.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of overlooking, I am in agony that the leaders of these
four groups and this convention not only overlooked an idiotic
statement such as that, they contributed to the appalling notion
Bush should have heeded their bidding not because they represent
minorities but because they call themselves journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Well, if they truly are journalists, then they shame us all with
this professional heresy. No wonder the public is coming to have
little faith in and virtually no regard for this trade.
</P>
<P>
   I'm in it. I've spent my entire adult life working on
newspapers, and now I'm wondering. I cherish the people's right to
know and absolutely believe it is an almost sacred obligation to
strive to ensure the reporting of as many facts of worth as can be
gathered honestly.
</P>
<P>
   No genuine journalist or group of journalists ever would think
otherwise. And, for the record, let it be noted a colleague at the
convention stressed there were many _ maybe, in his words, an
``unscientific half'' _ who had no strong feelings one way or the
other about Bush's presence and maybe didn't even join in the later
standing ovations for Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   To be honest, while I certainly think others have the right to
belong to organizations and go to meetings and conventions, I'm
rather of the school that maintains journalists really shouldn't
meet in largish groups _ except maybe to drink or talk tacky about
others in the so-called media, be it their own branch or another.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure not remotely interested in drinking with any who claim
they as journalists can influence the news, can make or break
political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   I am, however, fully prepared _ indeed enormously motivated _ to
talk tacky about them. Which I just did _ because I think they were
tacky.
</P>
<P>
   They demeaned the news business _ something I cherish and honor
and stand ready to defend. I just wish I didn't have to defend it
from some who are in it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ely is a Houston Chronicle columnist. (jane.ely(at)chron.com) &QL; 
