<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH COULD CHIP IN A LITTLE FOR SECURITY TAB 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Although he spends much of his time away from
home now, George W. Bush didn't stop being governor of Texas when
he started running for president.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it was a good idea for him to give up his state
salary _ about $316 a day _ when he is campaigning out of state.
That will keep Texas taxpayers from having to pay that amount to
both him and Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, who becomes acting governor and
draws the governor's higher pay when Bush is away.
</P>
<P>
   It also was a good idea, from a public relations standpoint, for
Bush to announce that decision a few hours after the publication of
a newspaper report that questioned another campaign-related public
expense _ how much it was costing Texas taxpayers for Bush's
state-paid bodyguards to tour the country with the presidential
race's champion fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin American-Statesman, which carried the story, didn't
get an answer to that question because the Department of Public
Safety, for whom the governor's security guards work, doesn't
discuss security arrangements or costs.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Secret Service agents, whose salaries and travel
costs are shared by all the nation's taxpayers, will take over
Bush's security. But, for now, the governor will continue to be
accompanied on each trip by an undisclosed number of plainclothes
DPS officers.
</P>
<P>
   Officers traveling with the governor fly on planes furnished by
the Bush campaign, which also pays for their hotel rooms. But some
officers fly on commercial planes, for which the taxpayers
eventually are billed. And the state also pays their salaries,
including overtime pay.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign says it doesn't plan to cover those extra
expenses, even though Bush has raised more than $36 million for his
campaign, almost twice as much as the other candidates for the
Republican presidential nomination combined.
</P>
<P>
   It is the DPS' job to protect the governor, Bush campaign
staffers say, and they are correct. Bush is entitled to the extra
protection. Security obviously can't end when the governor leaves
the state Capitol _ or even the state. Security is an
around-the-clock job, more demanding than ever now that Bush is a
national figure.
</P>
<P>
   A governor is entitled to some sort of private life, the pursuit
of happiness away from the office, and security must be there also.
</P>
<P>
   Some activities, of course, pose more extensive or specialized
security demands than others. One of these days, Texas may even
have a governor who aspires to be a world champion skydiver. Well,
it could happen.
</P>
<P>
   DPS troopers have accompanied Texas governors _ at taxpayer
expense _ to social and political events around the country for
years. This governor's extracurricular pursuit just happens to be a
very public race for high national office.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Hillary Rodham Clinton is prompting similar
questions about taxpayer-paid security costs for her exploratory
travels around New York state, where she is considering running for
the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his campaign staffers may be betting that most Texas
taxpayers don't mind the extra expense of protecting the governor.
If so, they probably are, once again, correct.
</P>
<P>
   Most people recognize security as a necessity for high-profile
officeholders and candidates, and most Texas voters expected Bush
to run for president when they overwhelmingly re-elected him last
year.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a front-burner issue. But, nevertheless, most of the
governor's Texas supporters wouldn't object if Bush were to
voluntarily decide to spare a few thousand dollars a month to
partially repay the taxpayers for his security costs.
</P>
<P>
   With his fund-raising operation raking in campaign dollars at a
record pace, he should be able to afford the extra expense.
</P>
<P>
   And, like his decision to cut his salary, it would be a positive
political gesture. He may want to think about that _ if he has the
time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Robison is chief of the Chronicle's Austin Bureau.
(clay.robison(at)chron.com) &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
