<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Tuesday, July 13. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-PROTESTS (Tehran) _ President Khatami calls for a peaceful
end to demonstrations as witnesses say fresh violence erupted as
club-wielding police clashed with students in Tehran. By Elaine
Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN (Beijing) _ Taiwan declared Monday that it will no
longer follow a long-held political formula that China and Taiwan
are two parts of the same country, provoking an immediate and
furious response from Beijing. Abandoning the `one-China' stance
that has been a basic condition of all its talks with China, Taiwan
President Lee Teng-hui has chosen to take a step away from the
conceptual umbrella of eventual reunification between China and
Taiwan. It is a risky move that badly sours ties with China, and
could also tear at the strains in an already-troubled relationship
between China and the United States. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-NEWSPAPER-SALE (Moscow) _ Someone not familiar with the
average Russian's bent for intrigue might find it strange that one
of Moscow's most influential newspapers was sold last week to an
offshore investment fund run by two Iranians from a nearly empty
Manhattan office. But a lot is going on with the country's raucous
press these days, much of it unsettling, and Russians who have been
fitting the pieces together do not find such a sale strange at all.
By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-CARE (Washington) _ For the first time since a
health-care revolution began moving patients into managed care, the
Senate on Monday opened a high-stakes struggle over how to protect
the rights of patients and regulate the companies that provide
health insurance for most Americans. The legislation, dubbed the
Patients' Bill of Rights, is the first of several politically
potent health care issues _ ranging from overhaul of Medicare to
holding down the cost of prescription drugs _ to come to the fore
in Congress this session. It would regulate health maintenance
organizations and has broad implications for doctors, employers and
patients, as well as the HMOs. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOOMED-STADIUMS (Seattle) _ These are dark and difficult days
for many of America's domed stadiums, which were once hailed as
climate-controlled, multi-purpose technological marvels but, after
barely a generation, are increasingly considered obsolete by fans
and owners alike. In several cases, in places that might be
described as a bit climatically challenged, owners have been able
to entice or strongarm their cities into adopting the vastly more
expensive, have-it-all philosophy embodied in outdoor stadiums with
retractable roofs and bolstered by the go-go economy of the '90s.
These splashy convertible models are already in use Toronto and
Phoenix; Seattle is set this week to open Safeco Field, with a
retractable steel-rail canopy; and Houston and Milwaukee will open
retractable-roof stadiums next year. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
