<HEADER>
A7074 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STRETCHING-MACHINES-A     07-12 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRETCHING-MACHINES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRETCHING MACHINES GAINING A FOLLOWING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Ore.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By LIZ NEPORENT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a 5,000-square-foot gym in Rio Grande, N.J., a half dozen
members cluster around a large metal frame with various handles,
ropes, bars and built-in benches to help its users bend, stretch
and twist themselves into an array of positions.
</P>
<P>
   Dottie Drake, a registered nurse and the gym owner, is there to
help them master those moves.
</P>
<P>
   The gym, Fitness First for Women and Seniors, is one of a
growing number of fitness centers that are beginning to replace
stretching mats with more elaborate equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Drake bought the Stretch Zone stretching station, made by
Keiser Corp., about a year ago. The semicircular frame can be used
to perform 17 different stretches and can accommodate up to eight
people at once. Ms. Drake says the machine provides support and
structure for those who would normally have trouble stretching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of my clients are 95 years old,'' Ms. Drake said. ``They
have trouble getting down onto the floor and getting up again.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Groves, a spokeswoman for Keiser, based in Fresno,
Calif., said that sales were initially slow for the Stretch Zone
when it was introduced about two and a half years ago, but have
picked up in the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Groves speculates that this new demand is due in part to the
release of the American College of Sports Medicine's 1998 exercise
guidelines which, for the first time ever, recommended that people
who exercise regularly should stretch at least twice a week to
preserve flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   The sports medicine report definitely increased awareness of the
importance of stretching, Ms. Groves said. More than 250 fitness
centers have bought a Stretch Zone or the smaller Stretch Corner
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Precor U.S.A. also has succeeded with its Stretch Trainer, a
machine with a seat designed to tilt backward as the user leans
forward. A combination of body weight and gravity help control the
intensity of the stretch and by switching hand and leg positions,
the user can stretch nearly every muscle in the body without
getting out of the seat. Since its introduction in late 1997, more
than 4,500 of the $399 units have been sold to home users. About
3,000 of the larger, more substantial gym models have been sold
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Stretch Zone and Stretch Trainer are among the various
stretching apparatus that are being marketed to consumers and gyms.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Miller, owner of the Gym Source, an exercise equipment
supplier in New York, speculates that manufacturers are attempting
to create a new category of fitness machines because sales of
cardiovascular and strength training equipment have been flat in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure that the trend will last,'' Miller said,
``because stretching with apparatus is less natural than stretching
without. Machines isolate one part of the body at a time which is
less effective than incorporating additional muscles into the
stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller suggests that smaller stretching devices like the Pro
Stretch, a small half moon shaped piece of plastic engineered to
stretch the ankle and foot, have the most staying power because
this area is difficult to stretch otherwise. It sells for about
$30.
</P>
<P>
   Others also question the necessity of using an expensive device
to increase flexibility. In a study, not yet published, Dr. Barry
Bates, a professor of biomechanics and human performance at the
University of Oregon at Eugene, had 40 subjects ages 20 to 60
perform regular stretching routines for eight weeks. Half of the
subjects used a device similar to the Precor Stretch Trainer and
half stretched without using any equipment. At the end of the
study, Bates found virtually identical flexibility gains among both
groups.
</P>
<P>
   But Bates added that those who used machines liked them and got
more incentive to stretch. They reported that the machines made
stretching physically and psychologically easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is merit to the fact that some people may be more
inclined to stretch if they have a thing that helps them do it,''
Bates said. ``Having something to interact with can make a big
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Bates also said he believed there might be some advantage to
having a piece of equipment to help control body positioning and
the extent of the stretch. ``This may help prevent overstretching
and injury,'' he added.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
