<HEADER>
A7079 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUDE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      07-12 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUDE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A SHORT HISTORY OF RUDENESS:' MINDING MANNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a man with an indeterminate face, growing a mustache can be
a solution: the face may not look much like him, but the mustache
will. The subtitle of Mark Caldwell's book gives a better idea of
it than the title does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudeness'' is announced but only cursorily treated in
Caldwell's sociocultural dissertation. This is a pity since, apart
from ritual warnings that Americans are lapsing into terminal
boorishness, the subject has been little explored since the
mid-19th century, when a procession of British writers came over to
tell us about it. Paradoxical, to a degree, since the only person
capable of greater offense than a bad-mannered American is a
well-mannered Brit.
</P>
<P>
   Rudeness might have been more interesting to read about than the
subtitle's ``Manners, Morals and Misbehavior.'' (Rudeness is not
the same as misbehavior, being at once more elusive and quite
unmistakable. We may not be sure how the dart was shot; we know it
hit us.)
</P>
<P>
   These broader subjects are regularly treated in books and
magazines and in the slow sections of newspapers. Caldwell ranges
wide, writing about class, workplace etiquette, the mobility of
Americans, children, sexual mores, Internet manners and much else,
but a good deal of his material and thinking inevitably seem
familiar.
</P>
<P>
   There are picturesque details and asides, though many seem to
fit better in a general social history than a particular history of
manners. Early in the century, the profitable and much-read weekly
scandal sheet Town Topics regularly singed New York's upper crust
by printing accounts of its members' indiscretions. Their
identities were withheld, though they weren't hard for insiders to
guess; and you didn't have to be an insider to notice the
systematic placement of innocuous items _ complete with names _
just after the anonymous ones.
</P>
<P>
   According to Caldwell, William d'Alton Mann, the proprietor, was
moved by genuine indignation over his wastrel socialite
acquaintances. Indignation was allayed if they invested in
``Topics.'' Since no favor ever goes unpunished, the flattering
pieces that ensued signaled to the world that their subjects
obviously had something to hide.
</P>
<P>
   Another section concerns the etiquette among factory workers
turned up by a 1920s study of a telephone factory. Management
thought to increase productivity by giving bonuses for output above
the bogey, or fixed quota. In fact, suspicious that this would lead
to raising the quota, the workers used an elaborate protocol to
keep their output a little below it. This included craps games,
gossip and resting and was enforced by a ``bing'' (a painful
arm-poke) to anybody who worked too fast.
</P>
<P>
   The binged one was allowed a bing in return (in those days the
notion of punishment did not exclude the notion of dignity), but
the lesson was taken.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Caldwell's subjects are tired and tiring. We don't
really need pages and pages about the growth of expenditure on
weddings and funerals, or American mobility, or the changes in
dating mores over the decades. The author soil-sifts where others
have broken ground: much of his diligent research seems to have
been in primary-sourced and fresher books, and in newspapers and
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The cultural-studies field draws a lot from such material, as
well as from advertising and television programs. It is in keeping
with the academic trend to seek authenticity, as Marie Antoinette
sought it in milkmaid and shepherdess games, in what it deems
popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand _ junk food in, junk food out _ it doesn't do
much for the reader. Anyway, the point of junk-food studies is not
to sling the evidence but to use it for interesting ideas. Only
some of Caldwell's ideas are interesting; many are decidedly fuzzy
or wander off in different directions at once.
</P>
<P>
   After writing of the lavish growth in American spending on
weddings and funerals _ consumerism replacing ritual, he nicely
calls it _ he argues that it is a kind of democratizing. You don't
need to be well born or educated to achieve status; all you need is
money. Ingenious up to a point, but what do you get in a
Depression: a bread line armed with ``Brides'' magazines?
</P>
<P>
   He writes of Internet flaming and asks, reasonably, how real
this ``virtual'' viciousness is. He makes an interesting comparison
with the ritualized melodrama of grand opera and the verbal
slanging in 1930s film comedies. Yet here as elsewhere he misses an
obvious distinction. On Internet chat rooms (voyeurism reversed:
the user is Godiva looking for Peeping Toms), we are not just
spectators but actors, even if virtual.
</P>
<P>
   A chapter on children notes that the nurturing and expansive
approaches of Dr. Spock and Robert Coles have been eroded by
harsher institutional attitudes; the move, for example, to
criminalize youthful misbehavior. Without exactly condoning this,
he suggests that society fails to allow for parents stressed out by
their children's misconduct. He does his point no favor by citing
``the hysterical eruption of public hatred'' against Susan Smith,
who strapped her two children into her car and drowned them.
</P>
<P>
   He is not always so wrong-footed. Rebutting conservative
doomsayers, he points out that manners and morals are not the same
thing. Diogenes, for instance, was rude and right. He argues
usefully that manners are a frail and uncertain instrument for
solving profound social questions. Language codes _ here he goes
against a part of the left _ are counterproductive when too
rigorously relied upon to fight the battles of gender and race.
</P>
<P>
   A vein of good sense runs through the book, but its fatty layer
of potted research and sluggish thinking make it hard to get to. At
the end, inconclusively concluding that he cannot judge whether
civility or rudeness is winning out, Caldwell writes that the
incidences are ``so protean as to vex the analyst, frustrate the
historian and elude the scientist.''
</P>
<P>
   He might try a writer. Together, these 274 pages lack a 10th of
the candlepower of a single phrase on the same subject by the
English novelist Elizabeth Bowen.
</P>
<P>
   Manners, she wrote, are ``the exercise of the imagination on
behalf of others.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: `A SHORT HISTORY OF RUDENESS
</P>
<P>
   Manners, Morals and Misbehavior in Modern America'
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Caldwell
</P>
<P>
   274 pages. Picador. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
