<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7081 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SPACE-XRAY-850&AMP;AD     07-12 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SPACE-XRAY-850&AMP;ADDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 THE SHUTTLE UNDERTAKES A MISSION FOR X-RAY ASTRONOMY  (The Science
Times)  By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first woman ever to command a space shuttle or
any other spacecraft, Col. Eileen M. Collins of the Air Force, is
to take that step soon while hauling into orbit one of the largest
and most costly science payloads of all time and then guiding her
winged spaceship back to Earth for a tricky night landing.
</P>
<P>
   On July 20, Colonel Collins and four crew mates on the shuttle
Columbia are to carry into space the Chandra X-ray Observatory.
</P>
<P>
   The Chandra, a $2.7-billion giant, is to open a large new window
on cosmic extremes of violence and power, including exploding stars
and baffling objects at the heart of galaxies.
</P>
<P>
   As a pioneering woman, Colonel Collins is familiar with the
public-affairs rigors of the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration and has had the opportunity to meet President and
Hillary Rodham Clinton, telling the first lady in detail about her
forthcoming mission.
</P>
<P>
   In the cool, laconic style of astronauts, Colonel Collins, the
first woman in NASA's 40-year history to command a space flight,
plays down the attention and danger and says that all the technical
and the political pressures have put her under no unusual stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``You focus on your job and do the best you can,'' she told
reporters last week. ``I don't really think about whether I'm
comfortable in this role or not.''
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, her flight is challenging and important.
</P>
<P>
   The Chandra observatory and its rocket engine, weighing more
than 20 tons and measuring 57 feet in length, are the largest and
heaviest shuttle payload ever to fly.
</P>
<P>
   As such, they pose a potential hazard for Colonel Collins if
Columbia has to make an emergency return to Earth shortly after
blastoff. The shuttle glides to a landing, and the presence of the
huge observatory would make the orbiter unusually speedy and tail
heavy.
</P>
<P>
   If the observatory is put into orbit successfully, Colonel
Collins on return to Earth will still face night-landing risks. The
landing is scheduled for July 24 at the Kennedy Space Center in
Florida, close to midnight, the 12th night landing in shuttle
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much different'' from a daylight touchdown because the
pilot has fewer visual cues, Colonel Collins, 42, said. She added
that she and her backup pilot, using a laptop computer, would
practice landings even while in orbit.
</P>
<P>
   But mission dangers, she said, pale in comparison to the
benefits of the new observatory, which NASA has envisioned for
decades. ``We're very excited about this flight,'' she said. ``This
is a dream come true for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The observatory, named after Subrahmanyan Chandrasekhar, a
Nobel-winning astrophysicist who worked at the University of
Chicago, is meant to chart new worlds of X-rays emitted by cosmic
objects like quasars, exploding stars and possibly black holes _
stars so dense that light cannot escape their gravitational grip.
</P>
<P>
   Black holes are suspected of lying at the heart of many galaxies
and helping hold the dense aggregations of stars together.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists believe that, as the giant holes devour everything in
sight, matter rushes inward and bursts of X-rays fly outward.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have discovered that nearly all cosmic objects _
stars, galaxies, supernovae, gas clouds _ give off X-rays. But the
exact causes are often unclear, in part because telescopic
snapshots are usually so fuzzy.
</P>
<P>
   The eye and optical telescopes are blind to X-rays, which have
wavelengths too short for humans to see or for ordinary optics to
focus. Moreover, the Earth's thick atmosphere blocks X-rays from
ever reaching the ground.
</P>
<P>
   So cosmic X-rays, usually generated by the tremendous heat and
energy of cataclysmic events, can be viewed only by special
instruments in space.
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials say the Chandra observatory is up to 100 times
more sensitive than any other X-ray telescope lofted into space
since such studies began 34 years ago, making significant progress
likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be much, much, much better than science
fiction,'' Harvey D. Tananbaum, head of the Chandra X-ray Center in
Cambridge, Mass., which will run the observatory, told reporters
last week at the NASA pre-mission briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth W. Ledbetter, head of payload development at NASA
headquarters, added, ``We can make Superman jealous with our X-ray
vision.''
</P>
<P>
   The last big American X-ray telescope, the High Energy Astronomy
Observatory-2, known as Einstein, operated 350 miles above Earth
from 1978 to 1981. By contrast, Chandra is to speed through space
in a highly elliptical orbit that takes the observatory up to
one-third of the way to the Moon, as high as 86,992 miles. The
distant orbit, far above the Earth's radiation belts, which can fog
sensitive detectors seeking very faint X-rays, will allow much
longer exposures and thus greatly improve the telescope's
performance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like a time machine, Chandra should be able to peer back 10
billion years ago, when the universe was very young. It has taken
that long for powerful bursts of X-rays from quasars, moving at the
speed of light, to reach the Earth's neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers believe the heart of such ``quasi-stellar'' objects
hold black holes so powerful that their radiations outshine their
galactic hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists around the globe filed 800 proposals to use Chandra _
four times as many as could be accommodated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited,'' said Kimberly Weaver, an astrophysicist
at NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center in Greenbelt, Md., who is one
of the scientists set to use the X-ray observatory.
</P>
<P>
   Some distant galaxies fire jets of X-rays in opposite directions
from revolving disks. Among other things, Dr. Weaver plans to study
such jets with Chandra, hoping to track them in closer to galactic
cores, possibly tying their origin to black holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chandra will help us a lot,'' she told reporters. ``I think of
jets as a marker that helps us understand what's going on inside.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Astronomers, astronauts and NASA officials are doubly excited
about Chandra because the giant observatory has been a long time
coming.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Congress slowed the work because it was skeptical that
the observatory's tricky mirrors could be made readily. Then, some
of the project's computer software was found to have failings.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, NASA delayed its launching after discovering
that some of its circuit boards were possibly flawed. Most
recently, in April, the agency again postponed the flight after an
unmanned rocket using the same kind of attached booster rocket
meant to push the observatory into its final orbit malfunctioned,
forcing new inspections and repairs.
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials say that the great observatory is now ready to
open a new chapter in scientific discovery, and that its deployment
should go smoothly since Colonel Collins and her astronaut
crewmates have had extra time to prepare for ferrying it into
orbit.
</P>
<P>
   As Ledbetter of NASA headquarters said last week, ``Everybody's
done a marvelous job in overcoming the difficulties.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
