<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7096 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CASES-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      07-12 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CASES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN WHO VANISHED INTO HIS PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By MARCIA SHERMAN, M.D.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just over a year ago, Terry Dibert got up from his
desk in the school district headquarters in Bedford, Pa., and
vanished into his past.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds like an opening line to a thriller. But for Dibert,
who left his computer running and his jacket on the back of his
chair, it was literally true.
</P>
<P>
   Six days later and 800 miles away, Dibert, the district's
business manager, reappeared near dawn in the midst of a natural
disaster. Police officers from Daytona Beach, Fla., found him early
on July 6, wandering on Interstate 95 through the blinding smoke
from wildfires that had shut the highway and forced the evacuation
of much of the area.
</P>
<P>
   Dibert told the police he was a 23-year-old sergeant trying to
rejoin his Army unit at Fort Bragg. He was worried about being
separated from his wife, who was pregnant with their first child.
</P>
<P>
   What he said was accurate, but 11 years out of date, as the
police discovered when they called Fort Bragg and found that
Dibert's unit had been gone for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   For neurologists, amnesia is a fascinating if generally familiar
subject. The most common form is retrograde amnesia, in which some
or all recollections seem to have been misplaced, leaving the
patient stranded in the present. There is also anterograde amnesia,
in which old memories remain intact but new ones can no longer be
formed. Some traumas wipe out the events that led up to them. And
some patients lose only stored images and not words.
</P>
<P>
   But Dibert's case was different, more like ``a bad Twilight Zone
episode,'' as he put it in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mistaking the present for the past is not typical of most
cases of memory disorder,'' said Dr. Scott Small, a
neurobehaviorist at New York Presbyterian Medical Center in
Manhattan. ``Most amnesiacs can register the present. What makes
this case so curious is its resemblance to a fugue state, and those
are generally psychogenic in nature.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, a neurologist encountering Dibert would have
diagnosed his time traveling as the product of emotional stress
rather than a brain disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Daytona Beach was full of people under emotional
stress last summer. So the police took him to the logical place: a
psychiatric hospital. Still convinced it was 1987, Dibert
eventually mentioned family living in Bedford, Pa., and on July 8,
his frantic wife, Julie, received a call from a nurse who had
tracked her down.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Dibert arrived at the hospital, her husband recognized
her but had trouble recalling her name. He asked how ``Bunky'' was
doing, using the nickname they had invented for the child she was
expecting 11 years before. ``It was kind of fun for a while, but
also scary,'' Mrs. Dibert said.
</P>
<P>
   She was told that her husband was suffering from stress, and she
couldn't disagree. He had been complaining of pressure at his job,
and she had seen him taking aspirin for uncharacteristically
frequent headaches.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until Dibert was transferred from the Florida
hospital to his local hospital in Altoona, where he was unable to
recognize his children, that the diagnosis began to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   The clinical picture did not make sense to Dibert's psychiatric
team in Altoona. He had no previous history of mental illness, and
normal people, no matter how stressed, do not suddenly just lose
their bearing in time. The Altoona doctors, wondering whether he
might have injured his head during his wanderings, ordered a CAT
scan.
</P>
<P>
   When Dr. Michael-Gerard Moncman first came to examine Dibert, he
found a patient who had returned to reality enough to be frightened
and confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty much in the present,'' Moncman said. ``By that
time, he was aware of gaps in his memory. He could tell me very
clearly about his job doing parts inventory at Fort Bragg, but the
last four to six weeks were simply gone.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Dibert describes the time as an ``uncomfortable'' mix of past
and present. The more people talked to him about his life since
1987, the more he could remember, but with an effort. ``Things
would be said that didn't click at first,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The brain scan revealed that Dibert had a large cyst pushing
apart the nerve tissue surrounding it and pressing on a nerve
tract, called the fornix, known to play a role in memory retrieval
and storage. In one area, called the columns of the fornix, tissue
had split apart under pressure. There was also brain swelling,
explaining the headaches. ``There were some parts of the brain that
were literally bent around this thing,'' Moncman said.
</P>
<P>
   Brain cysts are not unusual. Some never produce symptoms; others
cause problems as they grow and push on adjacent structures.
Headaches, seizures, weakness, sensory disturbances, or dementia
may result.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeon who eventually drained Dibert's cyst, Dr. L. Dade
Lunsford, the chairman of the neurologic surgery department at
Pittsburgh University, said the cyst had probably been there since
birth, growing as spinal fluid seeped in from the base of the brain
and never escaped.
</P>
<P>
   As brain cysts go, Dibert's was not particularly large. But it
was in one of the deepest and oldest parts of the brain, where
memory, primitive drives and emotions are generated. Fear,
aggression, sexuality, eating and drinking all originate from this
area, called the limbic system.
</P>
<P>
   It may be hard to think of the self as something so mechanistic
that a touch in the right spot can turn the past on or off. But in
Dibert's case, Lunsford said, his cyst was ``perfectly placed'' to
do just that.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even the most strangely placed cyst with the strangest
effects is just a cyst _ a sac of fluid that can be drained
surgically. On July 16, about a week after nurses in Florida found
his family, Dibert traveled to Pittsburgh, where Lunsford made a
tiny hole in his skull. Guided by a three-dimensional image,
Lunsford drained 10 to 12 cubic centimeters of spinal fluid.
</P>
<P>
   It was not certain that the surgery would guarantee a happy
ending. The nerve tissue that had been bent around the cyst did not
simply spring back into place. Scans showed that a large space
remained where the cyst had been.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nerves don't like to be stretched,'' Moncman said. ``The
situation for this gentleman was that we tried to restore as much
normal anatomy as we could. But it's up to his brain to restore
normal function.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just pat the brain on the head and say `OK, you're
done.' You've got to stand back and hope for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   The scans, of course, gave no clue as to what happened in the
period leading up to June 30, when Dibert suddenly traveled into
his past. Lunsford speculated that up to that point, Dibert's brain
had been able to compensate for the increased pressure exerted by
the growing cyst. Perhaps a short-term increase in pressure cut off
the flow of memory information along the fornix, or perhaps the
compensating mechanisms protecting him until then simply broke
down.
</P>
<P>
   For Dibert, recovering from the brain surgery was the easy part.
He was most worried about was how the episode would affect his
three children.
</P>
<P>
   ``They handled it better than most adults did,'' he said. ``They
got out the photo albums and went through them, saying `Hey,
remember this? It was at my birthday party.'''
</P>
<P>
   During his initial post-operative checkups with Lunsford, the
surgeon noted a ``quizzical'' look in his patient, as if he still
could not understand or believe what had happened to him. But his
exam last spring, was essentially normal. ``I haven't heard from
him since,'' Lunsford said. ``And in my business, that's a good
sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Dibert, who returned to work in the fall, said last week that he
felt fine. His missing memories gradually filled in, except for a
gap of about 10 days starting ``three or four'' days before his
disappearance, he said. For a while, he and his wife worked to jar
loose the missing recollections. Eventually they gave up. In
Lunsford's opinion, there were probably no memories being made
during that period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened,'' said Dibert, ``and it's probably
best that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 1649EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7098 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAMPARSONS-TEX     07-12 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMPARSONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN `ANGEL' RETURNS, BEARING GRAM PARSONS' LEGACY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gram Parsons was never meant to grow old. He felt too deeply, he
dove too far into his psyche, fears and guilt. He lived too hard,
hanging around the Rolling Stones at the height of their dark
power, doing drugs as if they were going out of style.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons was a rich Southern kid, a trust-fund pretty boy who
briefly attended Harvard, moved first to New York and then Los
Angeles and wrote a bunch of songs that cut as close to the bone as
any penned by Steve Earle or Hank Williams. He was with the Byrds
when they recorded what was almost certainly their best album,
``Sweetheart of the Rodeo,'' and he cut at least one unassailable
masterpiece, ``Grievous Angel.'' And he cut a swath through Los
Angeles, a floppy-haired lady-killer in a white suit emblazoned
with marijuana leaves and a red cross on the back. But by the time
``Angel'' was released, Parsons was long dead, having overdosed on
a combo platter of cocaine, morphine and speed in a cheap hotel
room at age 26 in September 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons left this world largely unknown to most rock or country
fans, but he had become a hero to a coterie of musicians, including
Emmylou Harris and the Rolling Stones' Keith Richards. More
important, Gram Parsons practically invented what would come to be
known as alternative-country: Wilco, Son Volt, Whiskeytown, Golden
Smog _ and the Eagles and the Stones' ``Wild Horses,'' too _
probably wouldn't have existed without Parsons' trailblazing work.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, some of the debt will be repaid with the release of
``Return of the Grievous Angel: A Tribute to Gram Parsons,'' a
13-song valentine that shows just how far his shadow reached. Alone
and in pairs, the Pretenders, Cowboy Junkies, Beck, Evan Dando, the
Mavericks, Sheryl Crow, Elvis Costello and several more step
forward to interpret such classic Parsons songs as ``She,'' ``Ooh
Las Vegas,'' ``Sin City,'' ``$1,000 Wedding'' and ``Sleepless
Nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching over the entire project is Emmylou Harris, who credits
Parsons with teaching her how to sing harmony and appreciate rock
'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took me to a place I never would have gotten to on my
own,'' Harris says.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons' pedal-to-the-metal life inspired imitation in his
admirers _ even after his overdose. In fact, there was a final,
perfectly macabre touch to his death: Honoring a request Parsons
had made at the funeral of guitarist Clarence White, a couple of
Parsons' friends took his body off the baggage ramp at the Van Nuys
Airport when it was being transported for burial. They packed his
body in their car and took it to the Joshua Tree National Forest,
where they burned it. The spot (and the hotel room where he died)
have seen pilgrimages by musicians and music lovers for years.
</P>
<P>
   Such adulation is attributable to his reputation for greatness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything he put out was totally heart and soul,'' Harris
says. ``He brought rock attitude and the poetry of his generation
to country. His stuff was totally washed in the blood. It really
cut to the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   All songwriters aspire to this, but few hit the mark as
consistently _ and in so little time _ as Parsons. His character
portraits, such as ``She,'' are always strong, but it's when
Parsons turns the light back on himself that his real artistry
shines. On ``Ooh Las Vegas'' (covered on ``Return'' by Cowboy
Junkies) he goes to the big city and is seduced and overwhelmed. On
``Juanita'' (which Harris and Crow perform as a duet) he wakes up
dazed and ashamed in a drug-littered hotel room, hoping to have his
mind eased by a young woman with a ``conscience so clean.'' But it
is ``Sin City'' (covered by Harris and Beck) that is Parsons'
essence: He portrays Los Angeles as a sort of sunny, modern-day
Sodom, and himself as a lost soul unable to resist its deadly
charms.
</P>
<P>
   There is a sense of fatalism, endless regret and guilt, that
cuts through to the heart of bands such as Wilco and Whiskeytown.
This echoes Parsons, who always sounded unsettled, on the run from
nameless demons, lost in a world too mean and fast for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people more interested in his honky-tonk side and
people more interested in his ballads,'' says Peter Blackstock,
editor of No Depression, the monthly magazine that focuses on the
alt-country scene. ``But in either case, there's a direct emotional
honesty people connect with. I think it's too emotionally direct
for some people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, he also knew the importance of holding something
back, revealing ``just enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The restraint and economy of motion inherent in country
singing _ he taught me that,'' Harris says. ``And he taught me how
to rock. I was a folk purist, and I thought drummers killed music.
With Gram, I understood how you could have great lyrics and the
power of rock.''
</P>
<P>
   Listening to the songs on the tribute CD _ or ``Rodeo,'' or
``Grievous Angel'' _ is to hear an enormously talented but troubled
man who finally could not outrun his demons. The poignancy of
Parsons' work is the music itself, but it's also realizing that he
really was the man in his songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people compare Gram to Robert Johnson and Hank
Williams,'' Blackstock says. ``As much as they did, you have to
wonder what they could have done in another 30 years. It's
genuinely sad to think of what never was heard.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers pop music for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
