<SLUG> BC-COOLCLARINETIST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLOIST MARTIN FROST MAKES THE GEEKY CLARINET COOL
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by BC-COOL-MUSICIANS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Swedish clarinetist Martin Frost is a renowned touring soloist
in Europe and Japan, where he makes his living playing with
orchestras and in recitals.
</P>
<P>
   But in America, Frost is almost unknown.
</P>
<P>
   When Frost performs with the Mimir Chamber Music Festival at
Texas Christian University this week, it will be his second visit
to the United States. His first performance in this country came
during the same festival last year.
</P>
<P>
   So why has he been so slow to catch on here?
</P>
<P>
   ``The great clarinetists in America are in the orchestras,''
Frost said during a telephone interview from his home in Stockholm.
``In the U.S., if the conductor wants to program the Mozart
Clarinet Concerto, he uses a clarinetist from the orchestra.''
</P>
<P>
   Much the same can be said for other instrumentalists, except for
the piano, violin and cello. Numerous pianists and violinists
crisscross the continent as guest artists. Within the past two
decades, guitarists have made inroads into the recital and concert
scene, often developing a relatively large following along the way.
A few cellists have achieved widespread recognition as well.
</P>
<P>
   But for 50 years, the violin and the piano have dominated the
orchestral solo slots and the solo recital scene. Few solo spots
are available for other instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Frost, 28, began playing the violin at 6. He later switched to
clarinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 14 or 15, I started to think of being a professional
musician,'' Frost said. ``I started thinking of being a soloist a
little later. I didn't realize how difficult it was.''
</P>
<P>
   To a large extent, the situation is a self-perpetuating cycle,
based on the characteristics of the violin and piano.
</P>
<P>
   ``The violin and piano have great flexibility,'' says Fort Worth
Symphony music director John Giordano. ``The violin has an enormous
range. And the keyboard, of course, is the foundation of
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Giordano, who began his career as a saxophone soloist, says
there are reasons that the violin and piano continue to dominate.
Indeed, as long-standing chairman of the Cliburn Competition jury,
he is closely associated with the ongoing prominence of the piano
on the concert scene.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is much good repertoire for other instruments,
the piano and violin possess an infinite literature of
masterpieces, Giordano says.
</P>
<P>
   New York-based manager Thomas Parker, whose 28 clients include
1997 Cliburn gold medalist Jon Nakamatsu, manages one concert
clarinetist, Jon Manasse. And although Parker recognizes the
continuing predominance of piano and violin, he says there has been
some change in the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-five years ago, you couldn't give Jean-Pierre Rampal
away,'' he says, referring to the world-renowned flutist. ``Then he
had some breakthroughs, and that opened things up for all wind
instruments.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker believes that the major orchestras are not a promising
area for the independent wind soloist because the principals'
contracts often specify that they be given first refusal when a
concerto for a wind instrument is programmed. The opportunity for a
solo performance is greater with a smaller orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   And Parker sees a mixed outlook for the solo recital scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recitals work on a trickle-down basis,'' he says. ``People
will go hear someone who has been on television or on an orchestra
concert.''
</P>
<P>
   Most solo performances for lesser-known soloists, such as
clarinetist Manasse, are on smaller college guest-artist recital
series, Parker says.
</P>
<P>
   About 95 percent of Frost's engagements are as a traditional
recitalist or soloist with orchestras. The other 5 percent _ new
and ``avant-garde'' works that require dramatic motion and
choreography from the clarinetist _ are what have made him famous
in Europe and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   His breakthrough came with his performances of German composer
Karlheinz Stockhausen's ``Der Kleine Harlekin'' (''The Little
Harlequin''), Opus 42 1/2. An even more prominent break came when
Frost appeared in the title role _ a nonspeaking, nonsinging part
for clarinet soloist _ in German composer Wilfried Hiller's ``The
Pied Piper.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked on stage, acting for several hours a day for six
weeks,'' Frost said.
</P>
<P>
   He won considerable recognition in Europe for the role, and
developed his interest and skills as an actor. He has since
commissioned and appeared in a number of works for solo clarinet
that require choreography and special lighting.
</P>
<P>
   Last year in Fort Worth, Frost performed choreographed works by
contemporary Swedish composers, including Niklas Sivelov's ``Twist
and Shout,'' Fredrik Hogberg's ``Plast Musik'' (''Plastic Music'')
and Anders Hillborg's ``Peacock Music.'' This year, in his second
bid to move onto the American soloist scene, he'll perform the
American premiere of Hillborg's Concerto for Clarinet and Tape,
along with standard chamber works including clarinet. Performances
are Tuesday, Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   (Wayne Lee Gay covers classical music for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
