<HEADER>
A7102 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CHINA-SPACE-NYT &LR;      07-12 1318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CHINA-SPACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA PREPARES FOR HUMAN SPACEFLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(kd) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ China is closer to becoming only the third nation
in history to launch humans into space, a feat that could come as
early as next year, say international space experts.
</P>
<P>
   After years of saying it would ``one day'' or ``soon'' put
people into space, and initiating and postponing efforts to do so,
the Chinese government has finally embarked on a serious program to
make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think evidence of a manned space program in China is very
real and that they are serious,'' said Charles Vick, a space issues
expert with the Federation of American Scientists, a Washington
policy group.
</P>
<P>
   According to specialists following Chinese space developments,
Chinese officials had hoped to put two astronauts into space by
October to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the Communist takeover
of China. However, they said, delays in developing a new rocket for
lifting heavy payloads, and problems with other equipment, make
such a crewed flight unlikely until at least next year.
</P>
<P>
   The first flight in the program, an unmanned test of the new
rocket and spacecraft, still could come in October as part of
celebrations marking the founding of the People's Republic of
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming there is no major failure during the first unmanned
flight of the system, I would expect a Chinese manned flight a year
to 15 months afterwards,'' said Phillip S. Clark, a British space
consultant who closely follows the Chinese program. ``Only the
United States and Russia have the capability to send people into
space and China seems ready to become only the third nation to join
this exclusive club.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Cline, the official in charge of external affairs at the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration, said the space
agency had no detailed knowledge of China's plans. ``For many
years, they have set as a goal building a manned spacecraft, and
earlier said they wanted to make a manned flight this year,'' Ms.
Cline said. However, she said, the agency has heard that this
flight has been delayed for unknown reasons and that there will be
an unmanned mission instead this year.
</P>
<P>
   Renewed interest in human spaceflight by China flared last month
when pictures said to show the Chinese spacecraft and rocket
suddenly appeared on the Internet from an anonymous source. The
pictures depict a spacecraft based on the Russian Soyuz design atop
a large rocket with four booster motors attached to the sides.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, in an article to appear next month in the British
magazine Jane's Intelligence Review, describes the rocket as the
Chang Zheng 2F, an upgraded version of one of China's largest
satellite launchers, the Long March CZ-3E. The new version is
capable of placing a 10 metric-ton payload into low Earth orbit, he
said, while the Chinese manned spacecraft weighs about 8.4 metric
tons.
</P>
<P>
   The spacecraft itself resembles the Russian Soyuz, which is
built in three sections _ a propulsion section, an orbital section
and a return module _ but it is larger and carries two pairs of
solar-power panels instead of one set as the Russian craft does,
Clark said. The central orbital module, instead of being spheroidal
like the Soyuz, is more cylindrical, he said. The Chinese version
is designed to make docking with other craft and transferring crew
members easy.
</P>
<P>
   The detailed color photographs were supposedly taken by a
construction worker at the Jiuquan launching site near the Gobi
desert. They show a completed rocket and spacecraft being rolled
out of an assembly building to a gantry and firing pad.
</P>
<P>
   The new building looks a lot like NASA's giant Vehicle Assembly
Building at Cape Canaveral, Fla., where Apollo moon rockets, and
now space shuttles, are put together for missions. The rocket is on
a mechanical crawler with tank-like treads that slowly move it to a
launching pad, as American shuttles are transported. Until now, all
Chinese space rockets were assembled from components on the pad
before launchings and not transported there ready to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Initial discussion about the pictures focused on whether they
were real or clever fakes. Some spacecraft experts questioned
whether the pictures were of small-scale models or images put
together with computer-aided drawing and photo manipulation
software. After carefully examining details in the pictures and
calculating the size and positions of elements in the images, most
experts now believe they are authentic, for the most part.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too much detail there to be faked,'' Vick said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clark and other experts said the image of the large
assembly and integration building where the rockets are prepared
may have been enhanced in some way. The pictures are supposed to be
from a promotional brochure created for the construction company
that put up the building, and the firm may have been trying to
emphasize its work in the images, Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Some also question the relatively close proximity of the
assembly building to the launching pad, compared with the
arrangement at Cape Canaveral, as evidence of possible photo
manipulation. But Vick noted that the launching arrangement for the
new European Ariane 5 rocket also has the service building and
launching pad similarly close together.
</P>
<P>
   China launched its first satellite in 1970 and has maintained an
active space program, including entering the business of launching
commercial satellites for clients in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials began discussing sending humans into space in
the late 1970s and reports of astronaut training began emerging in
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The push toward the current manned flight effort, dubbed Project
921, began in March 1995, when China made a deal with Russia to
acquire space technology, including information on life-support
systems, docking mechanisms for spacecraft and spacesuits. In
October 1996, two Chinese astronauts and more than a dozen trainers
and support people arrived at the Russian cosmonaut training center
outside Moscow and stayed for about a year, experts said. At about
the same time, Beijing announced plans to fly a manned spacecraft
for the nation's anniversary celebration, but has said little about
the program since.
</P>
<P>
   Officials and scientists questioned about the program in China
give conflicting answers, with many declining to comment on
possible dates for manned flights until the government announces
them. But one thing Chinese scientists and outside experts agree on
is that most of the technology being developed is Chinese, even
though some is an adaptation of Russian ideas and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joan Johnson-Freese, an instructor at the Asia Pacific
Center for Security Studies in Honolulu, and author of the book,
``The Chinese Space Program: A Mystery Within a Maze'' (Krieger
Publishing, 1998), said the Chinese always have multiple agendas.
China wants to prove that it is a technically sophisticated nation
and a great power that doesn't need outside help, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Recent investigations by Congress and the Pentagon that accuse
China of stealing secrets, and benefiting from U.S. companies
illegally transferring rocket and satellite information to China,
have embarrassed the Chinese and given them something to prove, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no economic payback for a manned space program,'' Dr.
Johnson-Freese said. ``The manned space club is very exclusive.
It's all for the prestige.''
</P>
<P>
   China is willing to spend part of its limited funds to develop
technology that is distinctly its own for sending humans into
space, she said. ``This way, China can say: `This is not U.S.
technology. This is not Russian Technology. This is very much
Chinese technology,' '' she said. ``It's saying, `We don't need to
steal your secrets and expertise _ We have our own.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
