<HEADLINE>
KILLINGS SHATTER A TOLERANT TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDDING, Calif. _ The Jewish and gay communities in this
Northern California city are facing new realities in the wake of
the arrest of two men the authorities say prime suspects in the
July 1 slaying of a gay couple in Shasta County and the June 18
firebombing of three Sacramento-area synagogues.
</P>
<P>
   The Shasta County sheriff's office said investigators also are
exploring whether the men might be linked to the June 20 slaying of
James ``Mark'' Amos, a 66-year-old man found in his bed dead of
gunshot wounds about 3 miles from the home shared by the slain gay
couple, Gary Matson and Winfield Scott Mowder.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Matthew Williams, 31, and James Tyler Williams, 29, the
suspects in the killings, were arrested last week but have not been
charged.
</P>
<P>
   Allegedly tied to radical white power organizations and vocal in
their Christian fundamentalist beliefs, the Williams brothers are
an aberration among the population of some 150,000 people living in
and around this largely white and Christian town just south of
Mount Shasta, according to local Jewish and gay residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't have a lot of problems here,'' said Shorty
Papineaux, an antiques dealer and regular at the Rainbow Lounge,
one of two gay bars in Redding.
</P>
<P>
   The Congregation Beth Emanuel, the only synagogue between Chico
and Ashland, Ore., serves some 200 members in a brown building of
about 3,200 square feet on 2 1/2 acres or so of grass and weeds
just west of town.
</P>
<P>
   In April, after swastikas appeared at Foothill High School in
Redding and anti-Semitic brochures were distributed in the area,
the FBI evaluated synagogue security. Some of the bureau's
suggestions, such as better lighting, were followed, but others,
such as fences, were not _ in part because of the expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a strong community value of tolerance, that's
overwhelmingly what Redding is all about,'' said Mike Cogan, a
Redding lawyer and member of the Beth Emanuel synagogue. ``I think
we're all pretty clear about what's good and what's bad, and (the
killings are) really bad. ... We don't want this in our town.''
</P>
<P>
   Matson, 50, a lifelong resident of the Redding area, helped
establish an arboretum as well as the museum and farmers market in
Redding. Mowder, 40, his companion of 16 years, worked in the plant
department in a local hardware store.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the Williams brothers had been involved in a
landscaping business.
</P>
</TEXT>
