<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ROAD RISK TIED TO THOSE WHO QUIT SMOKING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain)  ( The Science Times)  By ANAHAD S. O'CONNOR  
 &HT;    (DW) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the last few years, there has been much debate over whether
people who quit smoking are more likely to get into traffic
accidents. Now, scientists writing in the journal Nature say they
have found no connection.
</P>
<P>
   People suffering from nicotine withdrawal can experience
physical agitation, visual hallucinations and anxiety, and it has
long been suggested that they become more accident-prone. To test
the theory, Jackie Knowles, a scientist with the Safety and
Environment Resource Center, conducted a study of the rate of
accidents occurring on ``No Smoking Day'' in Britain over a 10-year
period.
</P>
<P>
   Knowles theorized that if automobile accidents were truly
related to nicotine withdrawal, the number of accidents occurring
on that day would increase. Using data from a national accident
reporting system in Britain, Knowles compared the average number of
road accidents over 10 years occurring on the Wednesday before the
day, on the Wednesday after and on the day itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Wednesday before showed an average of 583 road accidents; on
the Wednesday after, the figure was 628.
</P>
<P>
   On No Smoking Day, the figure was 620, showing no unusual
deviation in the rate. Ultimately, Knowles concluded that there was
no relation between nicotine withdrawal and the average number of
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   A VITAMIN BOOST FOR THE TINIEST BABIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Researchers who studied infants with low birth weights have
found that doses of vitamin A can significantly lower their risk of
chronic lung disease and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   Newborns, weighing less than two and a half pounds have low
concentrations of vitamin A in plasma and body tissue at birth.
They are unable to digest a sufficient amount of vitamin A during
the first few weeks of feeding and thus suffer from poor absorption
of the vitamin into the small intestine.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, they are more susceptible to infection and have
fewer alveoli, or air cells, in their lungs. Those conditions can
lead to chronic lung disease.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors wondered if these ailments could be eliminated by large
dosages of vitamin A administered on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the National Institute of Child Health and Human
Development Neonatal Research Network used two groups of infants
with low birth weights. The first group, 405 infants, received the
recommended daily allowance of vitamin A (5,000 international
units) administered three times a week for four weeks. The 402
infants in the control group received the traditional treatment
given to tiny infants. The average birth weight was 1.7 pounds in
the vitamin A group and 1.69 pounds in the control group.
</P>
<P>
   After 36 weeks, it was found that chronic lung disease occurred
in fewer infants in the group receiving vitamin A than in the other
group. In the control group, 62 percent of the infants died or
developed chronic lung disease, while 55 percent of the infants in
the vitamin A group died or developed the disease. The study found
that, in addition to reducing the risk of chronic lung disease, the
vitamin A supplement for infants with extremely low birth weights
reduced the risk of infections, hemorrhages in the brain and
certain heart conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers concluded that infants with very low weights
should receive vitamin A injections regularly. They added that
vitamin A was not only effective in reducing the risk of chronic
lung disease and other infections, but was also inexpensive. No
side effects were detected.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
