<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRITICS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARIO AND SPIKE: A TALE OF ETHNIC SENSITIVITIES
</HEADLINE>
  (Critic's Notebook)  
(kd) 
 By   WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If art truly imitated life or the other way around,
the conjunction of Mario Puzo's death, a record-breaking heat spell
and the new Spike Lee movie should have caused a combustion this
month on the sidewalks of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Puzo, the poet of the Mafia (a word that sensitivity forbade him
to use), gave us, in collusion with Francis Ford Coppola, a show of
ethnic violence that offended some champions of the
Italian-American character. And Italian-American violence figures
in both Lee's new, furious ``Summer of Sam'' and his steamy and
more accomplished ``Do the Right Thing,'' in which tensions between
the Italian-Americans and the blacks of Bedford-Stuyvesant erupt in
murderous emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Lee's work has been subjected to close inspection for
the signals it has transmitted about ethnic tensions and identity,
in the decades of Puzo's prodigious success as novelist and movie
maker, ``The Godfather'' and its two sequels managed to defy even
the mildest rebuke. Criticism among Italian-Americans was pretty
well stilled by the collaborative skills of the
Puzo-Coppola-Brando-Pacino-De Niro team and their work's subsequent
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   That may be taken as a rebuff to the sensitivity squadron. By
the local rules of tolerance, fairness and other exhibitions of
public virtue, the Corleone family's record of ruthlessness
demanded protest, but the storytelling was so evocative, and the
characters were so pungent, that niceties like civil rules of
behavior came to seem prissy. ``The Godfather'' represented popular
entertainment at a high level of professionalism that approached
art and elicited respect on its own terms.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the ``Godfather'' series was a largely
made-by-Italian-Americans production that radiated old-country
warmth and color even while the slaughter was under way. The
feelings of both Puzo and Coppola for the folk quality of their
tale came through honestly enough to distance their work from the
mafioso genre on which it drew. And anyway they were proudly,
creatively Italian.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Baker reflected in The New York Times: ``Puzo escapes an
insensitivity indictment under the rule that any member of a group
thought to need sensitivity is, nevertheless, permitted to be
insensitive, but only to his own group. If a Puzo show referred to
a black character as `a spade,' as Raymond Chandler, the Anglo
master of crime fiction, did in the pre-sensitivity era, well _
`The sensitivity boys are going to take you for a little ride,
Mario.''' In fairness, Baker might have mentioned what an enjoyable
ride audiences had.
</P>
<P>
   Spike Lee's ``Do the Right Thing,'' the 1989 work that explored,
or some will say exploited, racial violence on a burning hot day in
Bedford-Stuyvesant, could not so readily avoid charges of
insensitivity. Here the conflict, between blacks and
Italian-Americans, was based on a 1986 incident that wound up with
the killing of a young black man, Michael Griffith, who was trying
to run away from a white gang.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's approach to his story was ambitious. The characters were
borrowed from both black and Italian-American stereotypes that went
beyond the stereotypical. The movie was respectfully received, yet
left an intriguing disquiet about his message.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, by contrast, Lee's ``Mo' Better Blues,'' his
parodic movie featuring two white jazz club owners who exploit
black music talent, opened under charges of anti-Semitism. If the
vaudeville accents of this detestable pair were not sufficient to
make Lee's point, his own off-the-cuff comments about Jews' running
Hollywood would have done the job.
</P>
<P>
   The Anti-Defamation League expressed its disappointment that in
this movie Lee ``employed the same kind of tactics that he
supposedly deplored.'' Such is the common response of an advocacy
group, be it Jewish or Italian-American or black, for whom the
merit of a movie lies essentially in its good intentions.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with ``Mo' Better Blues,'' however, was not only bad
intention but also bad movie making. Lee allowed his animus to
conquer his skills. His latest work, ``Summer of Sam,'' a
phantasmagoria of Italo-America, is not likely to win friends in
Italian-American neighborhoods and cannot match his achievement in
``Do the Right Thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Lee may never compete with Puzo as a literary talent,
``Do the Right Thing'' shared a generosity of spirit with ``The
Godfather'' that cut across ethnic and racial lines. The lesson
here is that whether the subject be blacks or Italian-Americans or
Jews, if the movie maker wants to get away with taking on
incendiary group feelings, the best protection is to make a good
original movie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
