<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7131 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-UNETHICAL-EXPERIM     07-12 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-UNETHICAL-EXPERIMENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE STATE USES PEOPLE AS GUINEA  
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(md) 
 By PHILIP J. HILTS     
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientific experiments in which human subjects are abused are
not new; examples are as old as arrogance and cruelty. In the 13th
century, according to historians, a Mongol commander laying siege
to a port city experimented with heaving his diseased, dead
soldiers over the walls of the besieged town. The result was
victory for the command and the spread of black plague to its first
seaport; the commander's action may indeed have been the key event
in the great bubonic pandemic.
</P>
<P>
   But something different has been produced in this century,
according to John Moreno, director of the Center for Biomedical
Ethics at the University of Virginia, and the author of a book
titled ``Undue Risk,'' to be published this fall by W. H. Freeman
and Co. Modern times have seen the growth of systematic,
state-sponsored programs of unethical experimentation, and they
have occurred in nations as diverse as the United States, Nazi
Germany, China, Japan, Iraq and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno's book traces the history of secret, state-sponsored
experiments in the fields of atomic, chemical and biological
warfare studies from World War II to the present, including the
possibility that governments are now experimenting with what he
calls ``genetic warfare.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreno, who has a Ph.D. in philosophy, was drawn into the
subject when he was telephoned by Dr. Ruth Faden of Johns Hopkins
University and the leader of the President's Advisory Committee on
Human Radiation Experiments, and was asked to become a member.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's task was to reconstruct the story of radiation
experiments on humans carried out in the United States from 1944 to
1974. The investigation, believed to be the most thorough
historical search of its kind ever done, took almost two years, and
plumbed millions of pages of documents, but when it was over in
1995, Moreno found his curiosity had only been piqued. What, he
asked himself, about the other new technologies in modern warfare,
chemical and biological weapons? What experiments had been done
with those? He decided to find out.
</P>
<P>
   What made his and the radiation investigations possible was
President Clinton's decision to declassify the military records of
the secret experiments.
</P>
<P>
   The resultant book is a parade of horribles, but it reveals many
common features in unethical experiments from nation to nation,
experiment to experiment. And while it chronicles familiar cases,
it also describes a few unfamiliar cases, ones that may point to
the abuses of the future.
</P>
<P>
   And it finishes with a discussion of the positive consequences
of unethical experiments _ that ethical standards are being raised.
</P>
<P>
   The committee found that from 1944 to 1974, there were thousands
of experiments in the United States using radiation _ including
everything from injecting plutonium into the bodies of unsuspecting
hospital patients, to marching soldiers onto the sites of atom bomb
tests just after the blasts.
</P>
<P>
   In Iraq in the 1980s, Moreno reports, prisoners and captured
Kurds were tied to stakes and bombarded with chemical and
bacteriological weapons to assess the weapons' effects. The number
of victims is not known, but may be in the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Among the less familiar tales is that of the South African
program called Operation Coast, which was unearthed by that
nation's Truth and Reconciliation Commission hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Coast was a series of experiments in the 1980s in
which biological and chemical weapons were tested _ in one case on
troops from Mozambique _ for use against anti-Apartheid activists.
Moreno writes that the commission found evidence that among the
secret medical experiments was an effort to develop infertility
drugs that would affect blacks but not whites.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno says it was unclear whether such drugs were actually
tried on humans, but the case raises the possibility of adding a
fourth horseman to the atomic, biological and chemical weapons _
``genetic warfare.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Several classes of weapons could result,'' Moreno writes,
``among them microbes genetically engineered to target certain
human populations based on a virus' ability to `recognize' the DNA
variations in specific subgroups.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds that the possibility is credible partly because ``people
from particular ethnic groups or certain geographic origins have
long been noted to be associated with sensitivities to particular
foods and drugs.'' For example, he writes, since ancient Greek
times it has been known that people of African and Middle Eastern
origin often get sick after eating fava beans.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno writes that the Defense Department already has begun
studies to design defenses against ``genetic'' attack.
</P>
<P>
   Human experiments of some kind will always be necessary in
government and military programs, Moreno writes, but what is
necessary for the future is to guard against abuse of humans.
</P>
<P>
   And, he says, one of the things which surprised him most in
doing his research, is that he found the best model for careful,
ethical human experimentation in a United States Army chemical and
biological warfare program.
</P>
<P>
   He discovered a group of medics called ``91 Bravo'' at Fort
Detrick, in Maryland, called the Medical Research Volunteers
(Mervs) whose job as soldiers is simply to serve as subjects in
medical experiments. They give blood, take experimental vaccines
and ingest suspect bacteria, and when they become sick they are
treated on the spot. They receive special training in
experimentation, detailed briefings on each experiment, and have
the option of participating in some trials and not others.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to civilian research on humans, the experiments on
``91 Bravo'' must be reviewed by multiple boards and officials
before proceeding. And the medics themselves sometimes join on the
review committees.
</P>
<P>
   Unethical experimentation will always be with us, Moreno writes,
but if secrecy is limited and good model experimental programs can
be developed, the abuses may be limited.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
