<HEADLINE>
HOW BEES STAY THE COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: England, Australia)   (The Science Times)   
(DW) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flying a plane in crosswinds can be tricky. The pilot has to
compensate for the wind's speed and direction, changing the plane's
heading accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   If it's tough for a plane, imagine what it must be like when a
tiny bumblebee is buffeted by a crosswind. Remarkably, though, bees
are able to stay on course. New research published in Nature
suggests that they don't spend a lot of time assessing wind speed
or figuring out how much they need to turn into it. Rather, they
appear to rely on an optical navigation aid _ images of the ground
flowing across their retinas.
</P>
<P>
   Using radar, the researchers, from the University of Greenwich
in England, tracked bumblebee flights of up to 2,000 feet in
measured windy conditions. The bees adjusted their flying height
depending upon their speed (which, of course, was affected by wind
cpeed). Because the size of the ground area in the bees' view
changes with height, the results suggest that the bees are trying
to keep ground images whizzing by at a constant speed.
</P>
<P>
   The direction in which these images cross the field of view is
important as well. The researchers suggest that the bumblebees,
like some other species of bees, use a ``sun compass'' for
navigation, keeping the direction of the flowing images at a
particular angle relative to the sun. If a bee is blown off course,
it is a simple matter to get back on course by turning until the
image flow is at the intended angle in relation to the sun. As
support for this idea, the researchers note that bees flying over
water tend to drift with the wind, because the featureless water
surface gives no clues to movement as its image moves across the
retina.
THE SECRET LIFE OF ROCKS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sedimentary rocks hold many secrets, not the least of which is
their age. Igneous and metamorphic rocks can be dated through
radioactive decay of isotopes, but sedimentary rocks are formed
through the compaction of eroded grains of other kinds of rocks,
and precise dating is difficult. Scientists often have to rely on
fossils found in the rocks to determine when sedimentation
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a team of Australian researchers has developed a method to
date some kinds of sedimentary rocks, and while the technique does
not involve fossils, it does make use of the decay of organic
matter in a different way.
</P>
<P>
   When sediments settle out of water and begin to compact,
elements and compounds from decaying organic matter in the water
form minerals on the sediments. Among them is xenotime, a crystal
that encrusts grains of zircon in the sediments. Since xenotime
contains a uranium isotope that decays at a known rate into lead,
analyzing the amount of lead and uranium in a sample gives a
measure of how long ago the xenotime was formed, and thus the
sedimentation began.
</P>
<P>
   Using their technique, which they described in a recent issue of
the journal Science, the scientists have measured ancient sandstone
in western Australia and determined it to be 1.704 billion years
old, give or take 7 million years. Previously, the uncertainty in
age had been on the order of about a billion years.
TOO HOT FOR A PLANET  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't taken by the paparazzi, but a photograph released last
year caused a hubbub just the same. Astronomers said the photo,
from the Hubble Space Telescope, was probably the first of a planet
beyond the solar system. In it, a dim object was shown accompanying
a double star system 450 light-years from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   But after further analysis, it appears that the object is not an
extraordinary planet, but more likely a star, and a very ordinary
one at that. According to a report in the magazine Science News,
spectral analysis of the object shows that it does not contain
water vapor, indicating that it is of high temperature _ almost
certainly too high to be a planet. Rather than being 450
light-years away, it is more probably far in the background.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 1717EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7165 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASA-WOMEN-HNS &LR;      07-12 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-WOMEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN WITH SOARING CAREERS SHARE COMMON ROOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMIRA, N.Y. _ Two women who grew up in Elmira, in the back yard
of the National Soaring Museum, will take their dreams to new
heights with NASA's next space flight of the shuttle Columbia,
scheduled for launch on July 20.
</P>
<P>
   Elmira native Eileen Collins, 42, will become NASA's first
female mission commander on the five-day Columbia flight that will
carry the Chandra X-Ray Observatory, an advanced telescope that is
the heaviest payload ever deployed from the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Heidi DeBlock, 37, a physician who works in the surgical
intensive care unit at Albany Medical Center, is a NASA visiting
scientist who will perform blood pressure tests on the shuttle crew
at the Kennedy Space Center in Florida when the Columbia is
scheduled to land on July 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really excited about this mission, especially since Eileen
is making history as the first woman commander,'' DeBlock said.
``It's great to see a woman in that position.''
</P>
<P>
   The dual connection to Elmira, a town of 35,000 people near the
Pennsylvania border, is a natural.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elmira is an aeronautical kind of town,'' said DeBlock, whose
late father, a World War II pilot, was active in the local soaring
club and taught DeBlock to fly a glider.
</P>
<P>
   As girls, DeBlock and Collins were inspired by watching gliders
soar on updrafts along ridges bracketing the Chemung River Valley
in the foothills of the Appalachian Mountains west of Elmira in Big
Flats, home of the National Soaring Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The space shuttle is basically the world's largest glider,''
said Jaye Fish, development director at the National Soaring
Museum. Fish said Collins has donated NASA memorabilia to the
museum, where she helped establish the Eileen Collins Aviation
Camp.
</P>
<P>
   DeBlock, of Niskayuna, N.Y., a mother of three girls, recently
reapplied to become an astronaut after making it to the cut of 300
out of about 3,000 applicants two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to be an astronaut,'' DeBlock said. ``My
dad fostered a love of the stars and flying in me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Elmira childhoods and NASA careers of Collins, an Air Force
lieutenant colonel and mother of a 3-year-old daughter, and DeBlock
have been lately examined in an article researched and written by
eight sixth-graders at Farnsworth Middle School in Guilderland, a
suburb of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Their account, ``Ever Upwards,'' will be published in Space
Launch News, a newsletter that will be distributed at the July 20
Columbia shuttle launch in Cape Canaveral, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The Chandra mission, which has faced delays, will carry an
observatory to an orbit more than one-third of the way to the moon.
The telescope will allow scientists to peer deep into outer space
and to gather unprecedented X-ray images of exploding stars, black
holes and other phenomena as they study the structure and evolution
of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   DeBlock and Collins recalled for the Farnsworth students
memories of sitting on their front porches on warm summer nights in
different neighborhoods of Elmira, staring at the stars and
dreaming of exploring outer space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I was a child, I've dreamed about space,'' Collins told
the sixth-graders.
</P>
<P>
   Collins worked in a pizza parlor, saved her money and took
flying lessons. But she was rejected three times before finally
being accepted at the Air Force Test Pilot Academy. ``If you get
knocked down, just get up and try again,'' Collins told the
youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Elmira, DeBlock didn't know Collins and they've
never met. Both graduated from the same public high school, Elmira
Free Academy, in the city of 35,000. DeBlock's older sister knew
Collins from the Class of '74, though.
</P>
<P>
   Although Elmira today is known as the place where New York
City's subway cars are built, in 1930 it made headlines as the site
of the first nationally sanctioned soaring contest and bills itself
as ``the soaring capital of America.''
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 200 members in the local soaring club,
including one of the largest junior programs in the nation, Fish
said. Youths can fly solo in a glider at age 14.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a ride in a glider is part of the weeklong summer
aviation camp program named for Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eileen's shuttle flight as commander has been delayed many
times, so we've been on the edge of our seats here for about a
year,'' said Fish, who noted that Collins and her family are
frequent visitors to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DeBlock's work begins July 22, when a team of NASA scientists at
the Kennedy Space Center complete several practice runs of a blood
pressure protocol before the scheduled July 24 landing.
</P>
<P>
   DeBlock has conducted cardiovascular research on astronauts
since 1990. She published results of a three-year study in the
American Journal of Cardiology, analyzing how weightlessness in the
zero gravity atmosphere of space alters the working of the heart,
particularly the onset of abnormal heart rhythms (arrhythmias).
</P>
<P>
   DeBlock concluded that short-duration orbits of less than three
weeks and space walks up to six hours were safe, but a lingering
concern for astronauts of any duration in orbit is the shock to the
system during re-entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to understand why astronauts' blood pressure
falls so much when they fly back into Earth's gravitational
force,'' DeBlock said, noting blood pressure can drop from a level
of 120 in space's zero gravity to 60 upon re-entry.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, nearly 30 percent of astronauts suffer ill effects
from the blood-pressure drop upon landing, ranging from dizziness
to fainting.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a dangerous situation,'' DeBlock said. Astronauts
participating in the study will be monitored after they are given
blood pressure medication.
</P>
<P>
   One day, if her dreams come true, DeBlock may be on the
receiving end of the post-flight medical research.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what my chances are this time in reapplying to be
an astronaut,'' DeBlock said. ``But I'm not ready to give up yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
