<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, July 13, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showers and low temperature readings are likely again Tuesday
over much of the Middle Atlantic Seaboard, as a stationary front
drapes over the region. Moist air from the South is being lifted up
and over the front from the Carolinas to New England. As a result,
low clouds and showers will form east of the Appalachians, bringing
some much needed rain to many locations. In addition, the low
clouds will also be very thick, which will tend to keep readings
between ten and fifteen degrees below normal.
</P>
<P>
   The Gulf Coast will experience showers and thunderstorms Tuesday
as a weak, decaying front settles southward. Combined with onshore
flow, numerous storms are likely from the Florida Panhandle to east
Texas. The ce.tral Mississippi Valley to the Great Lakes will
remain under a ridge of high pressure, allowing for a cool morning
followed by a sunny and mild afternoon. The western Plains will
become rather hot as winds from the southwest increase.
</P>
<P>
   Additional showers and thunderstorms are likely in the Southwest
Tuesday as moisture continues to be replenished in the atmosphere
over normally arid regions. Clouds will also be abundant from the
northern Arizona mountains to the Sierra Nevada, as the moisture is
forced to rise up and over the higher terrain. Farther west, the
Central Valley will be very hot once again, with some locations
reaching record maximums as air descends under a strong ridge of
high pressure. The Northwest will continue to be dry, with readings
reaching seasonal levels.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Harmless Storm
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Beatriz churned off the west coast of Mexico on
Monday. Like most of the storms that form in that part of the
world's tropical oceans, it will pass harmlessly into the central
Pacific. A small area near the west coast of Mexico has the highest
birthrate of tropical storms of any place on earth. But the
prevailing winds typically steer storms away from populated regions
into a vast expanse of cooler water that cause the storms to
dissipate. By Wednesday, another disturbance is expected to
strengthen near western Mexico which will be named Tropical Storm
Calvin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
