<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-DELAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELAYS ARE CLOGGING MANY EUROPEAN AIRPORTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Italy, Germany, France, Switzerland, Ireland, Austria, The
Netherlands, Norway)   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ On a recent afternoon, the Lufthansa flight from Cologne,
ordinarily as predictable as the tides, lumbered into Fiumicino
airport outside Rome an hour and a half late. Bedraggled passengers
bumped into others from the Crossair flight from Basel, usually a
reflection of Swiss punctuality, which was 50 minutes late. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every summer, flight delays are about as abundant at European
airports as foreign tourists, but this year, they have reached
crisis proportions. In the first three months of 1999, delays of
more than 15 minutes rose 28.3 percent over the same period in
1998; in May, total delays in the system, calculated on the number
and percentage of landings and takeoffs delayed, soared by 217
percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Karl-Heinz Neumeister, secretary general of the Association of
European Airlines, said that this summer promised to be the worst
on record. Pierre Jeanniot, director of the International Air
Transport Association, warned that unless European governments
tackled the crisis, ``any prospects of growth in European air
transport will be strangled at birth.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American travelers who have had to face crowded European
airports recently know what they're talking about. David Henderson,
spokesman for the Association of European Airlines in Brussels,
said major headaches were caused earlier this year when France and
Switzerland began a two-month readjustment of the air corridors
that cross their border, causing bedlam at regional airports like
the one in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually the changes will help,'' he said. ``But they caused
chaos.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Kosovo crisis, by limiting civilian air space over
many European countries, has caused about 30 percent of this year's
flight delays, according to Atilla Parla, spokesman for
Eurocontrol, the centralized European air traffic control agency in
Brussels, covering 28 countries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the main problem, experts say, is the structure of European
air traffic control systems, which are fragmented by national
boundaries as if, as Jeanniot said, ``they were part of some tiny
medieval fiefdom.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Lambert, a European Union spokeswoman for transportation,
said that in a single aviation market, ``for historic reasons in 15
states you have more than 20 systems at air traffic control
centers.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While individual national systems are linked by Eurocontrol,
technological standards often differ by country. Parla of
Eurocontrol said that the agency was virtually powerless to force
member states to live up to commitments to boost the efficiency of
air traffic control systems or to increase airport capacity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neil Kinnock, the senior European Union transport official,
addressing the crisis in flight delays, warned recently that
``expectations for the near future are dismal, and even greater
difficulties can be anticipated in the medium term.'' He called on
European governments to surrender greater authority to Eurocontrol.
</P>
<P>
   Without singling out culprits, Kinnock said that only a few
European regions, responsible for about 3 percent of total air
traffic, now caused 45 percent of the delays. Jeanniot was more
specific, saying that the crisis was due to a severe lack of air
traffic control capacity in Switzerland, parts of France and
Italy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Neumeister of the Association of European Airlines
said that northern France, southern Germany, the whole of
Switzerland and northern Italy formed, in an arc from the English
Channel to the Adriatic, a kind of ``solid barrier against
efficient operation and good timekeeping.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But national prerogatives are strong and the wheels of European
Union decision-making grind slowly, so no one expects a quick fix.
NATO officials have provided a measure of relief by reopening some
corridors closed by the war in Kosovo, including air space over
Hungary, Bulgaria, Romania and Croatia, according to Eurocontrol. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travelers who would like to avoid some of the worst airports can
find some guidance in a list published last month by the
Association of European Airlines. The group ranked 27 airports
according to delayed flights in the first three months of the year.
Leading the offender list was the new Malpensa airport at Milan,
where 56.3 percent of departures were delayed more than 15 minutes,
with an average delay of more than 45 minutes. Malpensa was
followed by Geneva, Munich, Oslo and Rome.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, two of the worst offenders _ Malpensa and
Oslo-Gardermoen _ are recently opened airports still suffering
teething problems. Since formally opening last October, Malpensa
has been notorious for delays, lost baggage and poor transportation
links. Munich and Rome have felt the effects of Kosovo, and Geneva
was disrupted by the changes earlier this year to French-Swiss air
corridors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the European airports with the best departure records were
Dublin, Athens, Vienna, Duesseldorf and the London airports at
Heathrow and Gatwick. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Malpensa also led the list in delayed arrivals, with 52.8
percent of flights late, and an average delay of almost 45 minutes.
Madrid, Paris-Charles de Gaulle, Istanbul and Lisbon followed.
Among the most punctual for arrivals were Dublin, Vienna,
Copenhagen, Duesseldorf and Amsterdam. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Generally, European officials discount mushrooming European air
traffic, which increases about 7 percent annually, as a cause of
the crisis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The sky is big,'' Henderson said. ``It's simply the way it's
managed.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 1732EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
