<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7199 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-PHYSICAL-ART-2TAK     07-12 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PHYSICAL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOPHISTICATED TESTS ECLIPSE THE ART OF PHYSICAL EXAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.  Graphic  is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By ABIGAIL ZUGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the beginning _ before, that is, the chest X-ray,
the CAT scan, the transesophageal echocardiogram, the
prostate-specific antigen, the thallium stress test and the
gadolinium-enhanced MRI _ was the physical examination. For most of
the last two centuries, it was medicine's most elegant diagnostic
tool, the best way for a doctor to probe what was going on in a
patient's interior.
</P>
<P>
   Blood tests, X-rays and scans now often outdistance a doctor's
hands, eyes and ears. They can locate and define problems a
physical examination can only hint at, sometimes before even the
patient knows there is something wrong. Compared with the precision
of most common tests, many of the maneuvers a doctor performs at
the bedside (``Open your mouth ... breathe in ... breathe out ...
and again ... '') are inexact or even useless.
</P>
<P>
   In some situations, though, the physical may still be
lifesaving. It can be an inexpensive way to identify which patients
need expensive tests. And it forces doctors to touch their
patients, creating a physical bond between them that many feel is
essential to the art of healing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only time that we have an opportunity to literally
touch our patients,'' said Dr. Salvatore Mangione, a pulmonary
specialist at Jefferson Hospital in Philadelphia, who has written a
textbook on the physical examination. ``To relinquish it would be a
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   But now medical educators worry that a generation of young
doctors dazzled by LED displays and computer printouts is turning
away from the hands-on skills that, once forgotten, may never be
retrieved.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, studies have confirmed that the concerns are
well founded. Many American doctors are no longer very skillful at
what is called ``physical diagnosis,'' or the art of interpreting
abnormalities in the physical examination.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have available technology as an alternative,''Mangione
said, ``you're going to rust at the bedside. We now have an entire
generation or generations of teachers and physicians that may be
not very comfortable with that bedside part.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last 50 years, studies have questioned the need for
healthy adults to undergo the ritual of a complete yearly physical
examination. Most of these investigations have concluded that the
tappings and probings, which may take the better part of an hour to
complete, are unnecessary. A comprehensive review published in the
Annals of Internal Medicine 10 years ago concluded that after a
single heart and skin examination, healthy adults under age 60 who
felt well and had no unusual health risks had no need for a doctor
to lay hand or stethoscope upon them save for periodic measurements
of blood pressure and weight, and periodic breast and pelvic
examinations in women.
</P>
<P>
   For children, periodic physical examinations are still
considered important. But for adults, most health policy
organizations, including the Department of Health and Human
Services' influential Preventive Services Task Force, agree that a
complete yearly physical examination is obsolete. In its place,
doctors are encouraged to substitute an entity called the
``periodic health examination'' that, for healthy people between
ages 25 and 64, consists mostly of reminders about health risks
like smoking and driving without seat belts, and screening tests,
tailored to the patient's age and life style, like mammograms, PAP
smears and blood tests for sexually transmitted disease. This is
what many patients experience in their yearly visit to the doctor.
</P>
<P>
   But abolishing the yearly physical may have unexpectedly serious
repercussions, other doctors say. ``I believe in it,'' said Dr.
Michael A. LaCombe, the director of cardiology at Maine General
Medical Center in Augusta and a nationally known medical educator.
``There's a lot of soft stuff involved in a yearly physical that
can never be put into a database or measured with outcomes. There's
an intimacy with a patient, a closeness that evolves into
disclosure that doesn't occur on a questionnaire or with a
perfunctory 15 minute appointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, LaCombe said, when doctors no longer routinely
examine healthy patients, they lose their innate sense of what is
normal in the human body, and become increasingly unable to
distinguish what is abnormal when a patient gets sick.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies confirm that this may well be happening. A 1992
study at Duke University Medical Center in Durham, N.C., one of the
most prestigious places to study internal medicine in the country,
showed that residents there were only about 50 percent accurate in
identifying the heart murmurs and other physical examination
abnormalities that appear when a patient has a damaged heart valve.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, 200 medical students and residents at Philadelphia-area
hospitals were asked to listen to tape recordings of the
characteristic sounds heard through the stethoscope in patients
with a variety of lung diseases. They too scored about 50 percent
overall.
</P>
<P>
   In a paper published in the Archives of Internal Medicine last
month, three experienced Seattle doctors were asked to figure out
if a few dozen patients had pneumonia without looking at the
patients' chest X-rays. Even the best missed a third of the cases.
</P>
<P>
   Even the simple determination of blood pressure is turning into
a lost art. A study from Milwaukee presented at a meeting of the
American Society of Hypertension in New York last month found that
a year after a special course in how to take blood pressure, 95 of
100 medical students were doing it incorrectly.
</P>
<P>
   Educators are startled and unhappy at these trends, particularly
since the physical examination can also be a technique for
effectively controlling health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physical diagnosis can be an enormously powerful and
inexpensive way of sorting out those who need expensive tests from
those who don't,'' said Dr. Robert H. Fletcher, a professor of
ambulatory care and preventive medicine at Harvard Medical School.
``And yet the skills are tending to be de-emphasized, to atrophy in
young physicians because they jump right away to expensive
technology. So when it comes down to being on their own and having
to decide something without the technology, they've lost a lot of
their ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of studies in the last 20 years have tried to figure
out exactly which elements of the physical examination are valuable
and which are relics best supplanted by X-rays and blood tests. A
1992 article in The Journal of the American Medical Association
concluded, for example, that for a patient suspected of having
fluid in the abdomen, one method of tapping on the abdomen would
detect the fluid about 77 percent of the time and was still worth
doing.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for the venerable ``puddle sign,'' on the other hand,
which requires a patient to balance on all fours in bed for several
minutes, while the doctor taps on the belly from underneath, was
uncomfortable for the patient, would find fluid only 45 percent of
the time and should be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some techniques are still a part of what we teach because
nobody ever questioned their validity before,'' said Mangione,
whose textbook of physical diagnosis, unlike most standard texts,
provides editorial commentary on which rituals of the physical
examination should be retained and which, like the puddle sign, can
be retired.
</P>
<P>
   In the examination of the heart, for instance, Mangione's book
suggests, the doctor should still listen for the sounds of a normal
heartbeat. However, listening for a sound called a pericardial
knock, which is sometimes heard in serious infections, is no longer
worthwhile because these conditions have become so rare. Listening
for a sound called a ``tumor plop,'' which can be a sign of a tumor
in the heart, is far less accurate than an ultrasound test.
</P>
<P>
   But even worthwhile maneuvers often now get short shrift from
time-pressured doctors, for whom scribbling out an X-ray slip is
far faster than waiting for clothing to be removed so that a
stethoscope can be judiciously applied to the chest or abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am definitely doing fewer physicals,'' said Dr. Anke Jacobs,
an internist at the Manhattan Veterans Administration Hospital and
four years out of medical school. ``The thoroughness I had when I
started is gone. It would take too long. Doing a good examination
takes time. Once when I wanted to do one I had to wait for 10
minutes just for the nurse to find a gown for the patient to put on
_ and I have only a half hour with each patient, and all the
paperwork for the labs to fill out.''
</P>
<P>
   Another New York internist added: ``It's all for the patients'
psychologic benefit now. They like their lungs and hearts listened
to, but the important decisions are based on lab tests.''
</P>
<P>
   Some medical educators worry that this attitude quickly
percolates down to medical students, who learn the basics of
physical diagnosis in their second year of school. Students meet in
small groups with a preceptor, practice some parts of the
examination on one another, and become familiar with others by
examining willing patients on hospital wards. Examinations of the
breasts and genitalia are generally taught separately in
specialized clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Students invariably start out loving physical diagnosis,
Mangione said, which probes the patient for hints of disease the
way Sherlock Holmes looked for clues. ``But by the time they finish
their second year and start working in the hospital, they get very
rapidly disillusioned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most hospital stays are so short now that patients often spend
most of their time there moving from one test to another.
``Patients are in and out and have so much being done to them while
they're in, that when you lead this great team out to examine the
patient and show them how you do it, half the time the patient is
down in the MRI room,'' Fletcher said.
</P>
<P>
   In parts of the world where technology is less accessible,
skillful physical examinations remain important. ``In Europe they
pay more attention to physical findings,'' said Dr. Jacqueline
Achkar, who received her medical training in Germany and Britain,
and now teaches physical diagnosis to students at New York
University Medical School. ``Here students talk less to the patient
and spend more time in front of the computer. That is what they're
focused on. I say, did you feel the liver, and they tell me what
the blood tests showed. I say, `Was the patient yellow?' and they
say, `I don't know, I have to go back and check.'''
</P>
<P>
   LaCombe, the director of cardiology at Maine General, had a
similar observation. ``Most physicians would admit that few
physicians under 50 know how to do a physical exam,'' he said.
Teaching the subject is now generally considered one of the
thankless chores of medical education in this country, he added,
usually an unpaid labor relegated to junior medical school faculty
members who themselves are uncertain of the techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like `Fahrenheit 451,''' LaCombe said, referring to Ray
Bradbury's science fiction novel about a totalitarian society where
books are burned, but a small cadre of rebels keeps their contents
alive by memorizing them. ``There has got to be a place where we
can keep this thing alive until it gets into vogue again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
