r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-BUFFYFINALE-TEX     07-12 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BUFFYFINALE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MONTHS LATER, THE WB FINALLY AIRS TOO-HOT-TO-HANDLE `BUFFY'
FINALE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Funny how things work out.
</P>
<P>
   Not funny ha-ha.
</P>
<P>
   Funny peculiar.
</P>
<P>
   Funny in a queasy sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   Students are gunned down at a high school, and a television
series based on good vs. evil profits from the bloodstains.
</P>
<P>
   A niche hit from a niche network finally gets star treatment,
front and center.
</P>
<P>
   Postponing the second part of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer's''
two-episode season finale, in which the mayor morphs into a giant
serpent to feed on the Sunnydale Class of '99, was, considering
this spring's tragedy in Colorado, necessary censorship.
</P>
<P>
   But what timing. It set up the drama for a ratings massacre
against summer reruns, while also positioning the WB as The Network
That Cares.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's hour-long episode, titled ``Graduation Day, Part
Two'' and airing at 7 p.m. CDT, brings to a close a season-long
story line, and ties up a number of loose ends dangling from the
first installment, which aired 86 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Just enough time for the Internet to buzz, the media and
industry to contemplate, pontificate and salivate, for ``Buffy'' to
get its first shot at what we call anticipated television.
</P>
<P>
   Is Faith dead? Will Angel die? Will the mayor kill them all?
</P>
<P>
   What was all the fuss about anyway?
</P>
<P>
   The answers are here, played out in the series' complex but
customary way of juggling romance, horror and sarcastic one-liners,
and the violence that's at the core of the show's existence.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of fighting, lots of blood, lots of death in this otherwise
well-crafted episode written by the show's executive producer and
visionary, Joss Whedon. He has set up a rather clever, dramatic
exit for David Boreanaz (Angel, who gets his own series next fall)
and made it clear that the series and its characters are at a
crucial crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   The last time we saw Buffy (Sarah Michelle Gellar), she was
finishing off Faith, trying not to kill her but merely to subdue
her in order to save Angel's life. (He needs to drink the blood of
a slayer in order to survive a poisonous arrow; how she eventually
does this merely caps what has turned out to be television's most
touching, fatalistic love affair.) That's where ``Graduation Day,
Part Two'' starts, and it only accelerates from there.
</P>
<P>
   There's a grand plan to stop the mayor/demon (recurring guest
star Harry Groener in a hilariously scary spoof of a performance),
with most of the school taking part. Students fight back with
arrows, flame throwers, harpoons, axes. The fight scenes are
well-choreographed, the dialogue witty.
</P>
<P>
   At a cost of $1 million, the episode is one of the more
elaborate of the series, what with things blowing up and the number
of people taking part in the climactic scene. Perhaps this explains
why the serpent, at least on the review tape sent to this office,
looked a bit cheesy. Did they run out of money?
</P>
<P>
   Never mind.
</P>
<P>
   Whether ``Graduation Day, Part Two'' should have been
temporarily shelved will be debated for weeks to come. The fuss
will die down, of course, and we'll patiently await a new batch of
episodes and a new direction, considering that the core characters
are now out of high school. (I hope I'm not giving too much away by
saying that Sunnydale High is blown to pieces, which is
apocalyptic, considering that Buffy had something to do with the
destruction of her last place of learning as well.)
</P>
<P>
   What shouldn't be debated is whether ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer'' deserves an Emmy nomination as best drama series along
with the likes of ``The Practice,'' ``Law &AMP; Order'' and the new TV
darling, ``The Sopranos,'' and whether its star, Gellar, should be
competing with Camryn Manheim for best actress.
</P>
<P>
   It won't happen. ``Buffy'' is too much of a niche show, too
young-skewing, too cartoonish, too supernatural, too WB.
</P>
<P>
   My fellow critics say they like it, but the series isn't even
listed on its Television Critics Association Awards ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Funny how that can happen, with a series that's the best-written
on television.
</P>
<P>
   Not funny ha-ha.
</P>
<P>
   Funny in a sad sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 1752EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
