<SLUG> BC-TV-BUFFY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BUFFY, THE VAMPIRE SLAYER': THE DELAYED SEASON FINALE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When last we saw Buffy and her friends, Angel (Buffy's true
love, a good vampire) was on his deathbed, drenched with sweat,
after being struck by a poisoned arrow; Willow and Oz (Buffy's good
pals) were in bed together for the first time, and the mayor of
Sunnydale was eating spiders in preparation for his transformation
into a demon, scheduled for graduation day.
</P>
<P>
   That was in May, and the season finale of WB's ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer'' would have been broadcast the following week, but
the network reconsidered. So soon after the student massacre in
Littleton, Colo., the thinking went, maybe it wouldn't be
completely tasteful to show an episode whose climax consists of a
high school conflagration brought on by students.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two months later, here is Sunnydale High's class of 1999 in
blood-red caps and gowns, ready to prevent the mayor's
transformation. They are motivated not just by civic pride _ to
save their town from being destroyed _ but by the knowledge that
the demon's first act will be to eat them and their graduation
guests. Just to be safe, Buffy persuades her mom to skip the
commencement ceremony and get out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Buffy (Sarah Michelle Gellar), a senior with a
particularly demanding after-school job (saving the world from
evil), has other things to worry about. In the middle of this, she
has to find a way to save the life of Angel (David Boreanaz), even
if he is leaving town to star in his own spinoff this fall. And
certain adults continue to behave with typical idiocy. ``This is a
time of celebration,'' the principal announces at the beginning of
graduation, ``so sit still and be quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffy,'' unbeknown to the vast majority of viewers over 25, is
one of the sharpest, cleverest shows on television, but you
couldn't necessarily tell it from this episode. That's because the
finale turns into an action movie, though that probably won't
disappoint regular viewers of the series; this episode may not
serve up as much witty repartee as the average episode, but there
are enough emotional-wrap-up moments to more than make up for it.
And there is the occasional verbal delight.
</P>
<P>
   Cordelia (Charisma Carpenter): ``I personally don't think it's
possible to come up with a crazier plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Oz (Seth Green): ``We attack the mayor with hummus.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordelia: ``I stand corrected.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was probably a smart move to delay the finale
until now. It's not only the sight of scores of students wielding
swords, baseball bats and bows with flaming arrows; it's that under
the circumstances of the plot and the show's fantasy premise,
they're absolutely justified in resorting to violence. But the
members of the Trenchcoat Mafia may have thought they were battling
demons, too.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION &UR;  &LR; NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BUFFY, THE VAMPIRE SLAYER'
</P>
<P>
   Graduation Day, Part 2
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Tuesday on WB
</P>
<P>
   Created by Joss Whedon; Whedon, David Greenwalt, Sandy Gallin,
Gail Berman, Fran Rubel Kuzui and Kaz Kuzui, executive producers;
Gareth Davies, producer; written and directed by Joss Whedon. A
Mutant Enemy Inc., Kuzui/Sandollar Production in association with
20th Century Fox Television.
</P>
<P>
   With: Sarah Michelle Gellar (Buffy Summers), Nicholas Brendon
(Xander Harris), Anthony Stewart Head (Rupert Giles), Alyson
Hannigan (Willow Rosenberg), Charisma Carpenter (Cordelia Chase),
David Boreanaz (Angel), Seth Green (Oz), Alexis Denisof (Wesley),
Eliza Dushku (Faith), Harry Groener (Mayor) and Armin Shimerman
(Principal Snyder).
</P>
</TEXT>
