<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7219 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSTAND13-COX     07-12 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seeking solutions to suburban sprawl
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In addition to its sensational coverage of the U.S. women's
World Cup victory, Newsweek ($3.50) devotes a sizable chunk of this
issue to Atlanta. In a seven-page report, the magazine examines the
problems of suburban sprawl and traffic congestion. According to
the latest statistics, Atlanta has the longest daily round-trip
commute in the country: 36.5 miles, compared with 29.5 and 20.5 for
Dallas and Los Angeles, respectively. Julie Haley, a 39-year-old
mother of two, moved to a neighborhood of horse farms and trees in
Alpharetta five years ago to escape some of the problems of
overdevelopment. Now, she says, many of the trees have been
bulldozed, ``there's a million shopping centers'' and her kids have
developed asthma, which she blames on auto pollution. One answer,
Newsweek says, may lie with Gov. Roy Barnes' Georgia Regional
Transportation Authority and plans for more mass transit. Others,
such as Republican state Sen. Don Balfour of Gwinnett County,
envisions another solution to hour-and-a-half commutes: more
highways.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Newsweek, the futuristic home of Atlanta architects Mack
Scogin and Merrill Elam is featured in a review of ``The Un-Private
House'' exhibit at the Museum of Modern Art in New York. The
couple's house was designed with a glass wall separating the
bedroom from a second-floor outdoor lap pool.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kudos for Kubrick: The orchestrated hype for ``Eyes Wide
Shut'' has reached fever pitch in the past few weeks, with Tom
Cruise or Nicole Kidman or both on the covers of Time, Rolling
Stone, Harper's Bazaar and Us magazines. The August issue of Vanity
Fair ($3.95) takes a more subtle approach with Michael Herr's
account of his 19-year friendship with ``Eyes Wide Shut'' director
Stanley Kubrick. In his first magazine article in 20 years, Herr,
the author of the critically acclaimed book ``Dispatches,'' says
Kubrick, contrary to popular belief, was not a recluse. He simply
didn't like leaving his British estate. Kubrick spent hours on the
phone, discussing everything from Jung to Kafka. Despite leaving
America to live in England, he still liked many things about this
country: ``Seinfeld,'' ``Roseanne'' and ``The Simpsons,'' to name a
few.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Manly tribute: On the anniversary of Ernest Hemingway's 100th
birthday, P.O.V. ($2.99) pays tribute to Papa as the man who best
represented a macho century. Author Budd Schulberg writes of his
early rivalry with Hemingway (``You could call the man a lot of
things _ but you couldn't call him a coward''), and P.O.V. writer
Bert Sugar recalls the author's advice over a drink in 1956
(``Never delay kissing a pretty girl or opening a bottle of
whiskey'').
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More about Papa: Book ($4.95), a new magazine devoted to
things literary, also allots a large chunk of the July/August issue
to Hemingway. Included are interviews with Hemingway's son Patrick,
who edited the posthumous fictional memoir, ``True at First
Light,'' and Michael Reynolds, whose fifth and final volume on
Hemingway's life has just been published. And, in an interesting
essay, Atlanta teacher Paul Evans says his students are discovering
Hemingway's fiction is as fresh to them as it was to young people
of the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Medical news: Emory University Hospital and Crawford Long
Hospital are listed among the 50 best health care facilities in
U.S. News &AMP; World Report's ($3.50) annual survey. Topping the honor
roll of facilities are Johns Hopkins Hospital, the Mayo Clinic,
Massachusetts General Hospital, Cleveland Clinic and Duke
University Medical Center. ... Time ($3.50) offers some encouraging
news for those concerned about cholesterol and heart disease: Many
of the foods once considered deadly are not so bad at all,
researchers say. Eggs, for example, are OK if eaten in moderation.
Salt is not taboo unless you already have high blood pressure; tea
is better for you than coffee; and onions and garlic can protect
your heart. (Just make sure your mate eats some, too.)
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
