<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-OLAZABAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLAZABAL HOPING FRACTURED HAND WON'T KEEP HIM OUT OF RYDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ Nick Price had the perfect cure for Jose
Maria Olazabal's broken right hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Try kicking the wall next time,'' the practicing non-physician
yelled to the unsuspecting patient Monday as they crossed paths
during their warmup rounds at Carnoustie Golf Club for Thursday's
start of the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   But Olazabal apparently believes in home remedies. Doffing his
cap and bowing in Price's direction, he countered, ``No, I'll use
my head. It's the only part of my body that can handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Observers were getting a kick out of the situation, and Olazabal
certainly was going along with the fun. But he wasn't in such good
humor in his North Carolina hotel room when he threw his infamous
private tantrum last month, punching a wall and breaking his hand
to celebrate the 75 he'd shot that morning in the first round of
the US Open at Pinehurst.
</P>
<P>
   He was fresh off his second Masters triumph _ which capped a
heroic comeback from crippling foot problems that almost had ended
his career and knocked him into decline for several years. So you'd
think he'd have learned to take better care of his extremities.
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't as if this was a rash act of self-destruction.
Olazabal claims he went to lunch right after his round, chewing on
the fact that he'd yielded four shots to par on his last four
holes. Then he went to the practice range. Then the putting green.
Some five hours after the crime, he reached his hotel room and
discovered he'll never be a champion boxer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I did pretty well holding my emotions on the golf
course and on the driving range and on the putting green,'' he
said. ``I was just on my own in the room and I could express myself
freely at that time. That's why it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   If the wall didn't make enough of an impact, the consequences
did. Olazabal couldn't hit a ball for three weeks, thus
jeopardizing his European Ryder Cup chances. Though he's back ahead
of schedule, he doesn't believe the hand will be right for two to
three more weeks. That means his expectations of being a viable
contender in this tournament he cherishes are about the size of a
thumbnail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have the proper preparation for the tournament,'' he
said. ``I'm still not 100 percent fit. It's going to affect my
chances. I'm going to make clear that I'm here to try the best I
can. It is the British Open. I love this tournament in a very
special way and I will do whatever is needed to play in this
tournament. So for me, it's just nice to be here, even though I
know that my chances are not all that great.''
</P>
<P>
   That's for sure. Monday Olazabal played a practice round with
fellow Spaniards Sergio Garcia, Miguel Angel Jiminez, and Miguel
Angel Martin. Two fingers on his right hand were in a splint
because he can't put pressure on the pinkie. That left him
virtually helpless during the inevitable encounters with
Carnoustie's hellacious heather rough. And when they start keeping
score, that will be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot grip the club properly,'' said Olazabal. ``It is
affecting my swing nore than anything else. It is not that it hurts
when I strike the ball. It's just I cannot grip the club
properly.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems a rather exorbitant price to pay for four measly shots,
especially given Olazabal's previous medical ordeal that wasn't of
his own making.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be a little thing for you; it might not be a little
thing for me,'' he said. ``I live the game with a lot of passion,
and it hurt a lot (to falter at the end of the round), and that's
the reason why it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   But he still could find an encouraging sign in his rage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most of the time, it would have happened somewhere on
the golf course, throw clubs or whatever,'' said Olazabal. ``So
that's why I think I'm getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But it would seem healthier to make a public spectacle
of himself rather than a private wreck.
</P>
</TEXT>
