<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-HEARING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE AGREES TO SEPARATE TRIAL FOR CISNEROS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge on Monday agreed to a separate
conspiracy trial for former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros,
clearing the way for prosecutors to eventually drop charges against
two aides indicted with him.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin granted the motion after
prosecutors with Independent Counsel David Barrett's office said
they would drop the case against the two aides, John Rosales and
Sylvia Arce-Garcia, if they remain out of trouble with the law for
six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased that this ordeal has come to an end for me,''
said Rosales, who continues to work at the Department of Housing
and Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ecstatic,'' said Jeff Gans, a lawyer for Rosales. Gans
said the decision by prosecutors would allow ``John to get back to
his normal life.''
</P>
<P>
   Arce-Garcia still works for Cisneros, who is president and chief
operating officer of the Spanish-language network Univision in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sylvia Arce pleaded not guilty as a statement that she should
not have been charged. Now she will be getting the same result,
even if it is taken a little while to get there,'' said her lawyer,
Abbe Lowell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are delighted that the government has seen its way clear to
end this case against Sylvia,'' Lowell said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosales and Arce-Garcia were named in the 21-count indictment on
Dec. 11, 1997, charging them, Cisneros and Linda Jones of Lubbock,
Texas, with conspiracy to defraud the government.
</P>
<P>
   Rosales also was charged with two counts of lying to the FBI and
Internal Revenue Service agents about payments Cisneros made to
Jones, with whom he had an extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   The aides, Cisneros and Jones, pleaded not guilty to the
charges, which are third-degree felonies punishable by up to five
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, 52, was San Antonio mayor from 1981 to 1989 and
housing secretary from 1993 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, he announced he was involved romantically with Jones, a
political fund-raiser known then by her married name, Linda Medlar.
</P>
<P>
   After a separation, Cisneros reconciled with his wife but
continued to pay Jones, who was divorced and unemployed after the
affair. Barrett claims Cisneros tried to hide the extent of those
payments _ which amount to $250,000 _ when he was under
consideration by President Clinton to head HUD.
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin has ordered a Sept. 7 trial.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A pre-trial hearing to determine whether taped telephone
conversations can be used against Cisneros will resume Thursday.
The tapes are considered crucial to Barrett's case against
Cisneros, and Jones is the government's leading witness.
</P>
<P>
   She has pleaded guilty to lying to federal agents, money
laundering and bank fraud for purchasing a home with Cisneros'
payments that were funneled through a sister and brother-in-law.
Jones is serving a 3 1/2-year prison sentence at a prison medical
center in Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said she attempted suicide, became addicted to
prescription medicine and suffered from bouts of depression after
her extramarital affair with Cisneros became public. She has agreed
to testify against Cisneros in exchange for a reduction in her
sentence.
</P>
</TEXT>
