<HEADER>
A7244 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS &LR;      07-12 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION TALKING TO ADDO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did the Revolution revert to form in a 5-2 loss to Los Angeles
in their final game before the All-Star break? Or have they
reinvented themselves as a playoff contender over the first 17
games of the season?
</P>
<P>
   The answers will be provided in the second half of the season,
starting with a July 25 game against D.C. United at Foxboro
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, help could be on the way for the Revolution
defense. Central defender Joseph Addo, captain of Ghana's national
team, is negotiating with the Revolution and could play for them in
an exhibition against Dutch power Ajax July 21. Addo, who attended
James Madison University and has been playing for Ethnikos in
Greece, would provide a physical presence with the experience and
skill to provide the variety the team is lacking. His technical
ability could also bolster the Revolution's possession game.
</P>
<P>
   Addo, 27, was on the verge of being signed by D.C. United in
1997 but failed to come to terms. He was with Sparta Rotterdam
(Holland), FSV Frankfurt (Germany), and Belenenses (Portugal)
before moving to Greece.
</P>
<P>
   The loss to Los Angeles was the Revolution's worst since Walter
Zenga rejoined the team as coach last August. Zenga has rescued the
Revolution as their goalkeeper in several games this season but was
helpless against the Galaxy's late surge.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution lacked midfield possession, especially with Jair
out with a bruised heel, and struggled to contain the Galaxy. They
failed to capitalize on the continued hot streak of Joe-Max Moore,
who scored twice and has 10 goals this season, one less than his
best MLS total, set in 1996. Moore departed Monday for US national
team training camp and will likely be away for the exhibition
against Derby County in Denver today and the Confederations Cup in
Mexico starting July 24.
</P>
<P>
   When Zenga was hired by the Revolution, he pledged to attempt to
prevent such one-sided losses, especially before a home crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``By all indications, the team was on track to do that, until
(Sunday),'' general manager Brian O'Donovan said Monday. ``But we
can't panic with 15 games left. We will take what we have and
figure out what adjustments we need to make. You can't start from
scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some aberrational qualities did exist in the L.A.
game. We had done well in the first half, and the score was 2-2.
Then, a major mistakes leads to 3-2 with 17 minutes left. As a
coach, you have to go for the tie or win by playing more
offensively, and suddenly we were even more exposed at the back.
So, it was not a pounding 5-2 but it was 5-2 nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happens in sports. You are pressing forward and trying to
get some offense after having gifted the other team a goal with
little time remaining. And you either tie it up or win, or you
lose, 4-2 or 5-2. But this team has shown enough resilience and we
have enough talent on the field to do well in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Revolution had 10 points at the halfway point
in the season and were in a stretch in which they would win only
twice in 17 games.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga and assistant coach Giuseppe Galderisi have brought
cohesion to the Revolution this season. But the team still has some
vulnerabilities that fighting spirit and togetherness might not be
able to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be auditioning some players starting Saturday,''
O'Donovan said. ``The idea was to have a nice wing midfield player,
but we also need to look at shoring up our defense, given what
happened the last few games. Walter prided this team on solid
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Two South American players _ Argentina-born Ariel Graziani of
Ecuador and Henry Zambrano of Colombia _ became available to the
MLS after their teams were eliminated from Copa America. Graziani
is a candidate for the Revolution and Zambrano will likely join the
MetroStars.
</P>
</TEXT>
