<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUMOR WEB SITE IS CREATING A STIR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) Do you want to get the lowdown on what it's like to
work for a competitor? Or do you want to know what's really going
on at your own company?
</P>
<P>
   Check out the Web site VaultReports.com for tales, mostly
unsubstantiated, of withdrawn job offers, nasty bosses and cheap
expense account practices.
</P>
<P>
   These are the stories people talk about all the time at work but
usually in hushed tones around the watercooler, said Mark Oldman,
one of the founders of VaultReports.com. Now they're available for
everyone to see on what Oldman likes to think of as an electronic
watercooler. They're not typically the things you find in a shiny
recruiting brochure.
</P>
<P>
   Comments about pay _ who's earning what _ and comparisons of
prestige are the most common topics of discussion, Oldman said.
</P>
<P>
   It's such a job seeker's market that people wonder if they
really have a good deal, he said. They jump on the site to find out
what others are earning and the perks they're getting.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the postings, which can feature raw language, contain
startling information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yow,'' said Cheryl Matherly, director of career services at
Rice University, as she perused the Abbott Laboratories message
board. ``Oh, my. Oh, my gosh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They recruit with us,'' said Matherly, reading the chapter
headings out loud: ``Crappy pay'' and ``New Abbott management slow
to act.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the information doesn't fit what Matherly knows about
the company, but she worries what effect it will have on the
company's ability to recruit.
</P>
<P>
   Word of mouth really shapes the impressions of students,
especially at a small school such as Rice, she said. Matherly said
she has seen small companies without much prestige hire one student
as an intern _ and the student had such a great experience that the
company's reputation on campus soared.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Seff, director of career services for the University of
Houston's business school, said she believes students take the
information with a grain of salt.
</P>
<P>
   It's a really skewed view, and readers don't know if the writer
is just angry, Seff said.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter won't allow its employees access to
the Web site, which is kind of like the Catholic church banning a
book: Suddenly it hits the best-seller list.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the electronic watercooler, Morgan Stanley seems
to have become the most-talked-about company on VaultReports.com's
message board.
</P>
<P>
   Oldman speculates that Morgan Stanley blocked access to the site
because it didn't want its employees gossiping about the legal
brouhaha at the venerable investment banking firm. The firm paid an
informant $10,000 to keep tabs on a former employee, and now
Manhattan's district attorney is investigating.
</P>
<P>
   But Wesley McDade, spokesman for Morgan Stanley in New York,
said the firm restricted access to VaultReports.com before news of
the payout hit the street.
</P>
<P>
   The firm has blocked access to hundreds of Web sites that create
an atmosphere of hostility or intimidation because of their racial
references or sexual explicitness, McDade said. VaultReports.com
allows employees to trade offensive messages without identifying
themselves, he said, and the investment banking firm didn't want to
make other employees feel uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   A cruise through the message board uncovered a few messages
directed at individuals that indeed are sexually explicit.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site of Dilbert, the cartoon character whose experience
with idiot bosses speaks to every worker, also has stirred up
trouble. Several companies, which are listed on the site's
``pointy-haired boss index,'' have banned Dilbert's site.
</P>
<P>
   To keep up with those companies, the site also lists each
company's high and low stock prices for the day, along with charts
detailing their 52-week highs and lows.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco was one of the companies that the Web site recently
listed as having denied employees access to the site. But a call to
the company's Chicago headquarters straightened out that nasty
rumor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What?'' said Jim Fair, spokesman for the company. ``We love
Dilbert.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Fair said, he was sitting in front of his computer
terminal at BP Amoco's headquarters in Chicago looking at
www.Dilbert.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``We publish Dilbert cartoons in our corporate publications; we
send them out to all employees,'' said Fair. ``Dilbert's part of
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   To voice comments, telephone (713) 220-2000 and dial code 1002.
Send e-mail to lm.sixel(a)chron.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
