<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7264 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANCE-PILLOW-REVIEW-A     07-12 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-PILLOW-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACOB'S PILLOW DANCE FESTIVAL: REAL WIND BREEZES IN TO BOLSTER
IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(md) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BECKET, Mass. _ A door flew open with a crash in the midst of a
panel discussion on Saturday afternoon in Blake's Barn at the
Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival. Fresh, sweet wind gusted in from the
green woods and over the audience and panelists, who included the
choreographer Trisha Brown, the jazz composer and trumpet player
Dave Douglas and the painter Terry Winters. It proved to be one of
those defining moments in life and art, for ``Five-Part Weather
Invention,'' a new collaborative work by Ms. Brown, Douglas and
Winters, is just as fresh and sweet and is filled with surprising
gaiety.
</P>
<P>
   One of two festival-commissioned pieces by choreographers named
Brown that were presented last week at the Pillow, ``Five-Part
Weather Invention'' is a wonderfully playful romp that feels as if
it might have provided exuberant release for the three
collaborators as well as its audience. The elements in the piece,
seen on Saturday night, are simple enough. Winters contributed a
large backdrop painted like slats and scrawled across in black,
with a color at the top whose hues reappear in his costumes.
Douglas' vivid and richly changeable score, performed live by his
Charms of the Night Sky ensemble, helps create a sense of five
flowing sections, moving among styles and genres in a way that
sounds both giddy and profoundly serious. At one point the
musicians even erupt in a fit of coughing.
</P>
<P>
   The dancers spill out across the stage with a similar
changeability: full of purpose at one point, falling limply to the
ground at another, feinting and piling in close and wheeling out to
form more regimented ranks. Every part of the body is used in
``Five-Part Weather Invention.'' The one constant in this happy
scrawl of a dance are slippery feet that bound and chatter, hot and
cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five-Part Weather Invention'' was danced to blithe perfection
by Stacy Matthew Spence, Todd Stone, Keith Thompson, Kathleen
Fisher, Brandi Norton and Abigail Yager. The musicians were Douglas
(trumpet), Greg Cohen (double bass), Guy Klucevsek (accordion) and
Mark Feldman (violin). Jennifer Tipton designed the glistening
lighting.
</P>
<P>
   The Trisha Brown Company also performed ``Canto/Pianto,'' a
series of highly stylized, formalistic dances drawn from the recent
production of Monteverdi's ``Orfeo,'' which Ms. Brown directed, and
the signature ``Set and Reset,'' which looked intriguingly
sweet-tempered on the rustic bare stage of the Ted Shawn Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's other featured choreographer was Ronald K. Brown,
who is not related to Ms. Brown, whose Evidence troupe performed on
Sunday afternoon at the Doris Duke Studio Theater. Brown and his
coolly impassioned, hard-dancing performers are all over the map
this summer, reaping the rewards of richly deserved popularity. And
the Pillow audience clearly connected with the three dances on this
program, giving Brown's new ``Water'' a roaring, cheering standing
ovation. Largely white, the audience was clearly on the wavelength
of this proudly black modern-dance choreographer and his
Afro-modern dance vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water'' looks, however, as if it needs to settle into itself a
little more. The overall look of the seven bodies _ battling often,
rising unbeaten yet poised for danger _ creates an unsettled,
discordant mood. So does the poetry of Cheryl Boyce-Taylor, which
serves, with Fahali Igbo's musical score, as accompaniment. Ms.
Boyce-Taylor threads through the piece like a strong but vulnerable
earth mother or worldly goddess, speaking of children endangered by
too little love and respect from family and authority figures.
</P>
<P>
   But the movement, the themes Brown suggests and the themes Ms.
Boyce-Taylor articulates never quite seem to come together in this
strangely distanced piece. Love and hatred are closely twined here.
Dancers in bloodstained white clothes battle then hover anxiously
around the vanquished. Changing to fresh white costumes with a
faintly angelic air, the dancers kneel for benediction, form and
reform in orderly ranks and seem to receive baptism at one point.
</P>
<P>
   But we know these men and women far less well than the roving
men in Brown's teasing, much simpler ``Better Days.'' On the other
hand, the characters in ``Ebony Magazine: To a Village,'' a company
premiere that completed the program, are almost too familiar: lost
souls who seek validation in superficial fashion and material
acquisitions but whom Brown brings home by the end to a sterner and
more enduring sense of self.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water'' was performed by Brown, Taurus Broadhurst, Arcell
Cabuag, Telly Fowler, Diedre N. Dawkins, Celise L. Hicks and
Angelica Patterson. The company also included Pofina Williams. The
program's lighting was by Melody Beal, with costumes by Wunmi
Olaiya, who also composed the music for ``Ebony Magazine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7266 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-CRIME13-COX     07-12 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CRIME13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE CALLS FOR PHOTO LICENSES FOR HANDGUNS
 &HT;    600&AMP;add. With GORE-CRIME-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (p)
politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore took aim at the politically
powerful gun lobby and Republican presidential front-runner George
W. Bush on Monday with an anti-crime initiative that would require
photo licenses for all handgun purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gun lobby is sure to have a fit,'' he said. ``But to me,
it is worth it, and I am sure the decent people of America will
agree _ because too many illegal guns are flooding our communities
and too many precious lives are being lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposal, unveiled at the Boston Police Department, is
not as sweeping as the handgun controls promoted by former Sen.
Bill Bradley of New Jersey, Gore's only rival for the 2000
Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley wants to require registration for every one of the 65
million handguns in the United States. In an op-ed article for The
Washington Post last Friday, he chided the Clinton administration
for not advancing such an idea.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's idea of requiring photo licenses for new handgun owners,
while falling short of outright registration, contrasts sharply
with anything proposed so far by Bush or any of his rivals. The
Republican presidential contest has only one strong gun control
advocate, Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is too easy for a child to get a gun, and there are too
many political leaders who take their marching orders from the gun
lobby,'' Gore said in his fourth major policy speech since becoming
a candidate for president. ``Let's create a family lobby that is
greater and more powerful than the gun lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore did not mention Bush by name, he implicitly
criticized the Texas governor, who, during his tenure, has signed
into law measures that prohibit cities in his state from suing gun
manufacturers and that expand opportunities for private citizens to
carry concealed handguns.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response from Bush's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   National Rifle Association Executive Director Wayne La Pierre,
reacting to Gore's proposal, said, ``What's next? Tattooing a
number on the arms of all law-abiding citizens? It's sure not going
to be the rapists. It's sure not going to be the robbers. It's sure
not going to be the drug dealers and the criminals. ``
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre said Gore ``would have voted against this in a minute''
when he represented Tennessee in the Senate and the House.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Brady, president of Handgun Control Inc., the leading gun
control proponent, said Gore's proposal, coupled with Bradley's
support for handgun registration, means the Democratic presidential
nomination ``will be running on a strong gun safety platform'' next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for Republican presidential hopefuls to let the
American people know where they stand on this critical issue,''
added Brady, the wife of Jim Brady, the former White House press
secretary severely wounded in the assassination attempt on
President Reagan. ``Any presidential candidate who ignores these
concerns fails the test of leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's speech outlined other anti-crime steps, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ A constitutional amendment to protect the rights of victims.
</P>
<P>
   _ More federal money for the nation's court system.
</P>
<P>
   _ Requiring criminals to stay off drugs to get out of jail.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tougher penalties for people who commit crimes in front of
children.
</P>
<P>
   _ A crackdown on criminal exploitation of the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Making it a federal crime to stalk children on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ An end to racial profiling by police.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sharing computerized crime-mapping technology with local
police departments.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Gore also urged Congress to pass administration measures aimed
at hate crimes, another seeming criticism of Bush, who opposed a
similar measure in the Texas legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a killer on the rampage picks Jews, blacks and
Asian-Americans as his victims, I do not understand how some can
still argue that hate crimes are no different from all other
crimes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are different. They are often among the most vicious and
violent crimes, and more serious still is the fact that their very
purpose is to dehumanize and stigmatize, not only to wound the
victim but also to distort the American conscience,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also criticized the Republican-controlled
Senate for failing to confirm 72 nominees to federal judgeships. He
said the Senate ``continues to hold our system of justice hostage''
for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   But the gun control provisions were by far the most
controversial. In addition to photo licenses for handguns, he
called for banning the so-called ``Saturday night special''
handguns and a policy of ``zero tolerance'' toward guns and drugs
in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children cannot reach for their dreams if they are ducking
for cover,'' the vice president said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore has sought to distance himself from President
Clinton in recent weeks, he did not do so Monday. Instead he
credited administration's policies for the current 25-year low in
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That should be just the beginning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7267 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-CRIME13-COX     07-12 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
