<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7272 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-12 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT TOOK A LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. women's soccer team is basking in
well-deserved glory after its thrilling capture of the World Cup.
It is hard to take our eyes off our newest sports heroes _ so
talented, so collegial, so hard-working, so darned decent.
</P>
<P>
   Let's send these wonderful female athletes to Congress. They
could teach its quarreling partisan inhabitants a lot about working
together _ sharing the action and the credit for the greater good
of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, that's a fantasy. Congress is a closed world that plays by
cynical rules. Good sportsmanship does not figure much in the way
its particular game is played.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the team's athletic triumph, something of lasting
significance may have happened after all in the creaky, stratified
culture of law and politics.
</P>
<P>
   The unmistakable crowd appeal of the women's achievement should
be a timely save for the obscure law passed more than a quarter
century ago that made it all possible. Maybe now its foes will give
up trying to do it in. They certainly should.
</P>
<P>
   The 1972 measure, called Title XI, guaranteed equal sporting
opportunities for men and women in public educational institutions
receiving federal funds. It persuaded _ or forced _ colleges and
secondary schools to grudgingly give female athletes similar access
to training and scholarships traditionally offered only to men.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are Title IX babies,'' Women's World Cup president Marla
Messing said of the U.S. team. ``They are reaping the benefits of
the legislation that has enabled them to play soccer their whole
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Let us crow a bit here. Opponents said the law wouldn't work.
They insisted that women didn't want to be jocks, that it was a
waste of good money, that nobody would turn out to see chicks play,
that it was just feminist bellowing.
</P>
<P>
   Not very far-sighted, those guys. To say nothing of missing a
fairness gene somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Yet their latest champion is none other than House Speaker J.
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., who has repeatedly tried _ unsuccessfully _
to undermine enforcement of the law on the grounds that it hurts
men's secondary sports by siphoning off money they would otherwise
have been given.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, college football sponsors tried to talk
Congress into exempting their game from Title IX guidelines but
were denounced as big-bucks bullies and got nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled in 1992 that Title IX allowed sexually
harassed students to sue for monetary damages over the objections
of President George Bush's administration. That accelerated the
pressure for compliance with the law.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert fashions himself a defender of the weaker sports for men
that don't attract the big publicity and money of football,
basketball or baseball. He deplores the declining interest in, and
funding for, college gymnastics and fencing, but as a former
wrestling coach, he really cares about that sport.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1995 speech shortly after Republicans seized control of
both houses of Congress, Hastert pleaded for a weakening of Title
IX to rescue minor male-oriented sports ``that have fallen victim
to an intrusive federal bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   In March of this year he starred at a news conference announcing
formation of a pro-wrestling lobby to ``eliminate the use of quotas
as a way to develop equal opportunity in sports.'' Title IX doesn't
mention quotas. But when politicians use the word, it means they
want to protect the privileges to which their favored establishment
has become accustomed.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert said he was demanding Title IX changes to assure
``fairness'' for men in sports.
</P>
<P>
   Fairness? Fairness? The salaries of the women's winning soccer
team run $25,000 to $40,000 a year, plus their unexpected victory
bonus of about $35,000 apiece. No $5 million contracts for them, as
is common for male stars in major sports. Yet.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert also demanded that Congress' chief investigating agency,
the General Accounting Office (GAO), review sports available to
male and female athletes at 725 schools in the National Collegiate
Athletic Association.
</P>
<P>
   The recently released study noted that in the past 10 years
participation in men's gymnastics was down 56 percent and in men's
wrestling down 33 percent while women's soccer was up 154 percent
and women's golf up 80 percent. Overall, women's participation
increased 16 percent while male participation declined 12 percent,
although the figures varied from sport to sport.
</P>
<P>
   But if Hastert thought the study would show that male sports
need protection from Title IX, he was disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO study carefully drew no conclusion about the reasons for
the shifts in participation. It noted that women still lag
proportionately far behind men, with women representing only 39
percent of all sports participants and men making up 61 percent.
And it suggested that some of the male sports that had suffered did
so because of an inherent lack of interest and economic support
having nothing to do with competition from women's sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some schools have helped justify their decisions to cut men's
sports by blaming Title IX,'' NCAA President Cedric Dempsey
said.``That certainly is not the intent of the law and it is almost
never the only factor.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Hastert is likely to lose on the issue. This is an
era in which both parties are eager to appeal to female voters. It
does not seem like a winning move to pick on the law credited with
opening up opportunities _ previously been available only to men _
to women so they could learn the skills of leadership and teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they hadn't been doing so before, women will be watching
after the World Cup victory.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means may be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7276 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OIL-MERGER-NYT &LR;      07-12 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHLUMBERGER DRILLING UNIT TO BE MERGED WITH TRANSOCEAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Schlumberger Ltd. has agreed to spin off its offshore drilling
unit, Sedco Forex Offshore, and merge it with Transocean Offshore
Inc. to create the world's largest offshore oil drilling company.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies said that the spin off was being spurred by the
high cost and greater technological demands of offshore oil
exploration, where drilling is taking place in ever deeper waters.
The new company would have a market capitalization of $6.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Most major new finds have been in deep water, most recently off
the coast of West Africa and in the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep water is one of the last frontiers of the oil business,''
said Dan Pickering, an analyst of oil service companies for Simmons
&AMP; Co. International.
</P>
<P>
   He said that drilling in deep water was continuing at high
levels despite low crude oil prices last year. Both oil companies
and firms that supply them with exploration and production
equipment underwent major consolidation to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   Thus demand for deep-water rigs is expected to increase quickly
if crude oil prices continue to move upward beyond levels hoped for
by most major oil companies. The recovery has been due to cutbacks
by major oil producing countries and strong world demand.
</P>
<P>
   Pickering added, however, that the spin off by Schlumberger
``was not driven by any type of financial distress.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, rigs that can drill in water from 5,000 to
8,000 feet deep can cost from $250 million to $450 million each and
are becoming more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   J. Michael Talbert, the chairman and chief executive of
Transocean Offshore, which is based in Houston, said that the
merger with the Schlumberger unit ``is advantageous due to the
rising capital costs for new rig construction, the increasing size
and needs of our customers, the expanding geographic diversity of
offshore drilling and the technical challenges posed by the new
deepwater drilling activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Euan Baird, the chairman and chief executive of Schlumberger,
which is based in Paris, said that the company will concentrate on
technology and methods of getting more oil out of the ground and
bringing down the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Schlumberger stockholders would receive
about one newly issued Transocean Sedco Forex share for every five
Schlumberger shares they hold.
</P>
<P>
   The 109 million shares that are to be issued are valued at $3.2
billion, using the closing prices of Transocean stock on July 9.
The companies valued Transocean Sedco Forex shares at about $29
each. The market capitalization of the merged company will be about
$6.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Transocean will also assume about $430 million in Forex Offshore
debt. The merged company, which will employ 7,500 people, will have
75 offshore rigs, the most in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Talbert will become president and chief executive officer of the
merged company. Victor Grijalva, the vice chairman of Schlumberger,
will become chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The board of directors will be made up of five members
designated by Schlumberger and five by Transocean Offshore.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the spinoff, Schlumberger, which has 60,000 employees
and operations in over 100 countries, with revenue last year of
$11.8 billion, is still the largest oil service company in terms of
market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   Sedco Forex Offshore had income of $390 million on revenue of
$1.1 billion last year. Transocean Offshore had sales of $1.09
billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Pickering said that the agreement was structured in a way that
will give Schlumberger a big voice in the running of the merged
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making sure the business in run correctly for their
shareholders,''he said.
</P>
<P>
   Transocean stock gained 93.75 cents Monday to trade at $29.9375,
while Schlumberger rose 62.5 cents to trade at $64.9375, both in
composite New York Stock Exchange trading. Diamond Offshore was up
$1.25 at $31.6253.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
