<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7279 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOOMED-STADIUMS-ART-2     07-12 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOOMED-STADIUMS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE HAILED AS MARVELS, DOMED STADIUMS GIVING WAY TO FRESH AIR AND
SUNSHINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Texas, Minn., Mich., Calif., Mass., Fla., Wis.,
Md.)  (ART ADV: Graphic and photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seattle is about to say hello to Safeco Field, a
brick-facade palace with cedar-lined dugouts, an exquisite turf of
Kentucky bluegrass and ryegrass, and a retractable steel-rail
canopy to insure that the game will go on, rain or shine. At $517
million, the ball park, which opens on Thursday, is the most
expensive in Major League Baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   But the big welcome to (mostly) outdoor baseball here heralds an
inglorious farewell to the hulking concrete mushroom next door
known as the Kingdome, where the Mariners played indoors, on
artificial turf, for 22{ seasons. The dome is scheduled to be
imploded next year, to make way for an open-air football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, baseball's Astros are ditching the Astrodome, which
was hailed as the Eighth Wonder of the World when it opened in
1965. The building, the country's first air-conditioned stadium, is
being abandoned next spring for a new downtown ball park that, like
Seattle's, has a retractable roof.
</P>
<P>
   With football's Oilers having already left town for Nashville,
the Astrodome's future is uncertain. Its major tenants now include
the two-and-a-half-week Houston Livestock and Rodeo Show, an
offshore-oil technology conference and assorted auto shows known as
``dirt events,'' like the demolition derby and ``Monster Truck
Madness.''
</P>
<P>
   These are dark and difficult days for many of America's domed
stadiums, which were once hailed as technological marvels but,
after barely a generation, are increasingly considered obsolete by
fans and owners alike.
</P>
<P>
   In several cases, in places that might be described as
climatically challenged, owners have been able to entice or
strongarm their cities into adopting the vastly more expensive,
have-it-all philosophy embodied in outdoor stadiums with
retractable roofs and bolstered by the go-go economy of the '90s.
These splashy convertible models are already in use in Toronto and
Phoenix, and, in addition to Seattle and Houston, Milwaukee will
open one next year.
</P>
<P>
   Many other cities have already chosen gleaming new outdoor
ballparks that hark back, in design and ambience, to the era of
such venerable stadiums as Fenway Park in Boston, where the
All-Star Game will be played on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   And with the Minnesota Twins lobbying strongly for an outdoor
ballpark to get themselves out of the Metrodome, it is very likely
that just one Major League Baseball team will be left playing
inside a fixed-roof dome within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Even that team, the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, seems to be doing
everything it possibly can to distract fans from the fact that they
are stuck indoors watching a ball game. The stadium's name, the
Thunderdome, was changed to Tropicana Field. The huge Diamondvision
screen broadcasts live shots at night games of the sun setting over
the nearby Gulf Coast. Palm trees are placed throughout, and in a
section of the upper deck known as the beach, fans can order
tropical drinks at a tiki bar or listen to island music.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario is somewhat less bleak for domes as venues for
professional football. Seven of the National Football League's 31
teams still play indoors.
</P>
<P>
   But not a single one has won a Super Bowl, a fact that is a
source of endless speculation for fans (some say it is injuries
from the artificial turf; others contend that the domed teams
collapse when they have to face a team outdoors in January's
playoffs), and nearly all new and proposed football stadiums, like
the one here in Seattle, are of the open-air, real-grass variety.
</P>
<P>
   And, for baseball at least, the verdict is clearly in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There simply aren't any domes out there for baseball that
people are excited about,'' said Andrew Zimbalist, an economics
professor at Smith College who has written several books about the
sports industry. ``For football, there are at least some fans who
like the fact that they don't get snowed on or get cold, and they
never have to worry about the football hitting the ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   But for baseball games, domes just aren't a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more important, said Zimbalist, is that owners so
far have been able to persuade cities and states to foot a hefty
part of the bill for the fancier retractable models.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a few years ago,'' Zimbalist said, ``a stadium would cost
maybe $125 million. Now they're spending that just on the roof.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is possible, of course, that cities will soon shun the
convertibles, not necessarily for reasons of esthetics, but of
cost. Seattle's new baseball Xanadu is a cautionary example: It is
already roughly $100 million over budget, and the Mariners and
local leaders are engaged in a bitter battle over who will pay,
putting something of a damper on Thursday's big opening, at which
the Mariners will play the San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   But fans seem excited, and the new parks do hold out a
best-of-all-worlds scenario: Most of the time, they promise outdoor
baseball under blue or night skies, but if the rain or cold or heat
or humidity or even the mosquitoes come, the roof can slide in over
everyone's head in a matter of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the Kingdome is a fixture of the skyline, few
people seem to lament its passing. This is partly because it was
never considered an object of beauty. Sports Illustrated once
described it as having ``all the ambience of a port-a-john,'' and
Bob Wood, author of ``Dodger Dogs to Fenway Franks'' (McGraw-Hill,
1988), a book about baseball stadiums, called it ``a festering
pimple on one of America's loveliest urban faces.''
</P>
<P>
   It also has had its share of misfortunes. Heavy acoustic tiles
once fell from the ceiling, nearly striking Cal Ripken Jr., the
Baltimore Orioles' modern-day iron man who holds the record for
most consecutive games played.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, feelings about the Astrodome seem to be a bit more
complicated. After all, its opening was an event noted around the
world and literally hailed by city leaders as one of the great
human achievements of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sparkling like a rare jewel on a one-time Houston swamp, the
Astrodome is the Taj Mahal of all stadia from Rome's Colosseum on
down to this day,'' exulted the 262-page book that celebrated the
Astrodome's 1965 opening. Or this, from the opening-day program:
``The searing Texas sun will still beat down, the angry Gulf winds
will still howl, and the tropical rains will still fall, but not on
the spectators in the Astrodome,'' it read. ``They will sit in
almost regal splendor.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The problem these days, of course, is that few people consider
the air-conditioned, artificial-carpeted ambience of a fixed-dome
stadium to be splendid at all. They clearly prefer to watch a game
outdoors _ unless, of course, it is too hot, or too cold, or too
wet, which is where the retractable roofs come in.
</P>
<P>
   The Kingdome is one of five Major League ball parks closed or
closing this year, and it is by far the youngest. With the
Astrodome, the others are Detroit's Tiger Stadium, which opened in
1912, County Stadium in Milwaukee (1953) and Candlestick Park in
San Francisco (1960).
</P>
<P>
   With Safeco's cost cresting above the half-billion dollar mark
(the Kingdome cost $67 million, far less even adjusting for
inflation), it is not clear whether municipalities will continue to
finance convertible stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Many cities are not clamoring for them to begin with because
their climates do not create a need for them; others have resisted
any calls for new stadiums as primarily a ploy by owners for yet
more lucrative luxury boxes. In New York, nearly every indoor,
outdoor and both-ways version of new ball parks for the Yankees and
the Mets has been discussed, including the possibility of a $1
billion, retractable-roof stadium on Manhattan's West Side, but the
issue is far from resolved.
</P>
<P>
   And although the Minnesota Twins now want to move outdoors,
their domed home, known as the Metrodome, was seen as a big factor
in the 1987 World Series. The team lost all three games on the
road, outdoors, to the St. Louis Cardinals, but won all four games
in the dome, with deafening support from the home crowd, to win the
championship.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the main, fans here in Seattle seem excited about the concept
of outdoor baseball on real grass, although one nagging issue has
come up.
</P>
<P>
   What will it mean for the team's star slugger, Ken Griffey Jr.,
who hit more home runs than anyone else in the Kingdome (198),
including, fittingly, the last one in the dome's history, in the
Mariners' last game there on June 27?
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, widely seen as the current player with the best chance
of breaking Hank Aaron's all-time homer record of 755, might not do
as well in an outdoor park with damp air and other weather factors.
Also, the distance down the line to right field, which he favors,
is 326 feet, 14 feet longer than at the Kingdome; on the other
hand, the new fence is shorter in some places.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners actually conducted a series of wind-tunnel tests
and other measurements to try to calculate the new stadium's impact
on their star's homer production. ``But I don't think anyone will
definitely know until we get out here and play ball,'' said Rebecca
Hale, a team spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you this, though,'' she said Monday at the stadium.
``We've got a nice breeze going on right now. And it's blowing
out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
