<HEADER>
A7282 &Cx1f; ttg-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     07-12 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WANT ADS FOUND WANTING  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES    
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune    
 c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trick to writing a classified ad is to get as much
information as possible in the shortest possible space.
Unfortunately, there are times when brevity succeeds at the expense
of meaning, as these ads, brought to my attention courtesy of Diana
Sysinger, demonstrate.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner Special _ Turkey, $2.35; Chicken or Beef $2.25; Children
$2.00.
</P>
<P>
   The ad does not say whether the children come with potatoes and
a vegetable, but at these prices, who cares?
</P>
<P>
   For sale: an antique desk suitable for lady with thick legs and
large drawers.
</P>
<P>
   It may take a while for this item to sell as not too many ladies
like to admit they have thick legs and wear large drawers.
</P>
<P>
   Now is your chance to get your ears pierced and get an extra
pair to take home, too.
</P>
<P>
   I admit to being behind the curve on the latest fashion news,
but when did replaceable ears come into vogue? If it were up to me,
I'd get the extra ears pierced instead of my own. It sounds a lot
less painful.
</P>
<P>
   Wanted: Unmarried girls to pick fresh fruit and produce at
night.
</P>
<P>
   I'm surprised a sleazy ad like this ever made it into the paper.
I bet if the unmarried girls are good at producing at night, no one
will care if the fresh fruit gets picked or not.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what your topcoat is made of, this miracle spray will
make it really repellent.
</P>
<P>
   This may, indeed, be a ``miracle'' spray, but it sounds to me
like you could throw your topcoat at a skunk and achieve the same
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of cleaning yourself? Let me do it.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's very kind of you to offer, but some things a person
just feels more comfortable doing himself.
</P>
<P>
   Dog for sale: Eats anything and is fond of children.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like this dog has been given too many leftovers from the
$2.00 dinner special.
</P>
<P>
   If you think you've seen everything in Paris, visit the Pere
Lachasis Cemetery. It boasts such immortals as Moliere, Jean de la
Fontain and Chopin.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know; if I were immortal, I don't think I'd waste my
time hanging around a cemetery, but you've got to admit it sounds
like pretty interesting company.
</P>
<P>
   Get rid of aunts! Zap does the job in 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives can be a nuisance, sure, but unless Zap is nontoxic,
this seems like a pretty harsh way to treat one's aunts.
</P>
<P>
   We build bodies that last a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Whose lifetime? Mine or yours? The nice thing about a body is
that it lasts exactly a lifetime whether you do any painful
exercises or not.
</P>
<P>
   Man wanted to work in dynamite factory. Must be willing to
travel.
</P>
<P>
   Only once and at a very high rate of speed. Return ticket
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Man to take care of cow that does not smoke or drink.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't realize that tobacco and alcohol dependency was a big
problem with cows, but now that I think of it, they do have a lot
of free time on their hands (hooves?). Instead of standing around
all day smoking and drinking, cows might consider doing some
volunteer work or perhaps enroll in a personal enrichment course at
the local community college.
</P>
<P>
   3-year-old teacher needed for preschool. Experience preferred.
</P>
<P>
   That seems a little young to be teaching preschool, if you ask
me, but I guess it's hard getting help these days. Either way, it's
going to be difficult finding a 3-year-old who's got experience in
anything, unless you count soiling diapers.
</P>
<P>
   Wanted: Preparer of food. Must be dependable, like the food
business, and be willing to get hands dirty.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't sound like a place where I'd care to eat, even if
the children dinner special is only two bucks.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
