<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7283 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-WESTBANK-NYT &LR;      07-12 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-WESTBANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL SUSPENDS FUNDS FOR WEST BANK FACTORY CONSTRUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Taking a step to curb building in Jewish
settlements, a minister in the new government of Prime Minister
Ehud Barak announced Monday that he had suspended financing for
construction of new Israeli factories in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was made by Industry and Trade Minister Ran
Cohen, a member of the leftist Meretz Party. It was the first
concrete move by Barak's government to reduce support for
settlements granted by the administration of Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   The move was a modest one, a far cry from the sweeping building
freeze ordered by the government of Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin
after he took office in 1992, but it was an early indicator of a
change in priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the start of the season in which state money is no
longer burned and wasted in unnecessary places,'' Cohen said in a
radio interview, asserting that spending on settlements had been at
the expense of job creation for 100,000 unemployed people in Israel
proper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here and found that huge parts of the budget of the
Industry and Trade Ministry are going to settlements, and not into
the state of Israel to develop places of work,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said that under his predecessor, Natan Sharansky, the
leader of a Russian immigrant party who supports the settlers, the
ministry had approved investments of $240 million in settlement
factories, of which $73 million were subsidies granted by the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Sharansky also began construction of four new Israeli industrial
zones in the West Bank during his three years in office, a ministry
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen announced that he had suspended approval of investments
totaling $90 million for new factories in settlements, including
$22 million in ministry subsidies. The freeze will remain in force
until the government reviews aid to the settlements, Cohen added.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines of Barak's government call for a review of
assistance to the settlements, equalizing allocations to those
given to communities inside Israel proper. Barak said after a
meeting with Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, on Sunday that
his government would reassess settlement decisions by Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians have pressed Barak to halt settlement activity,
arguing that it prejudices the outcome of planned talks on a
permanent peace agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
