<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7288 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-NEWSPAPER-SALE     07-12 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-NEWSPAPER-SALE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALE OF RUSSIAN NEWSPAPER HAS POLITICAL CIRCLES BUZZING 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Someone not familiar with the average Russian's bent
for intrigue might find it strange that one of Moscow's most
influential newspapers was sold last week to an offshore investment
fund run by two Iranians from a nearly empty Manhattan office.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot is going on with the country's raucous press these
days, much of it unsettling, and Russians who have been fitting the
pieces together do not find such a sale strange at all. They
suspect that the Iranians are a front for one local power broker or
another. An election campaign is beginning, and everyone with
power, from business moguls to the government, is angling to
influence the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Influence has been a synonym for money in some years, but the
consensus this year is that the press _ or, perhaps, the faction
that has the most control over it _ will play a crucial role in
choosing who will lead Russia. The nation will choose a lower house
of parliament this winter and a successor to President Boris
Yeltsin next summer.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, analysts say, dates to early 1996, when a deeply
unpopular Yeltsin appeared destined to lose his re-election
campaign until Russia's information outlets rallied behind him _
and helped pull off a spectacular comeback victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``For everybody involved in this election, 1996 proved that
control of the media _ the support of the media _ is crucial in
Russia,'' said Floriana Fossato, a correspondent and expert on the
Russian press for Radio Free Europe in Moscow, ``in fact,
particularly in Russia. That's why we're seeing this action now.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief difference this time, of course, is that the press is
not about to unite behind Yeltsin or his favored candidate. The
solidarity of 1996 sprang from fears that a Communist victory would
end capitalist reforms and lead to the closing of opposition
newspapers and television stations.
</P>
<P>
   Today Yeltsin is even more unpopular, but his likeliest
successors, by and large, are democrats, if not always
unreconstructed capitalists. Few worry these days about either a
communist victory or a serious crackdown on newspapers or radio and
television stations.
</P>
<P>
   That is not quite the same as saying that the Russian press is
free. Moscow has at least 15 dailies of note, and a scad of
weeklies and bi-weeklies. They flaunt a range of opinion that makes
American newspapers look pinched, and rarely a day goes by without
the flaying of some hapless public official or business power.
</P>
<P>
   But most remain tools of their owners. Moscow is a William
Randolph Hearst kind of town, where press moguls are not squeamish
about ordering up stories to suit their views. Newspapers and
television stations tend to be viewed first as instruments of
power, only later as public servants.
</P>
<P>
   More than once, feuds among oligarchs and officials have been
played out in the press. The most spectacular example occurred this
spring, when an inquiry by Russia's prosecutor general into
high-level corruption was sidetracked by a videotape broadcast on
state-controlled television that showed a man strongly resembling
the prosecutor in bed with two prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the information moguls have that sort of power, it
was not at all surprising that someone decided to snap up
Kommersant, a business-oriented daily said to be millions of
dollars in the red. It does not circulate widely outside Moscow,
but its reputation for independence and accuracy has given it
influence there well beyond its circulation.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's buyers, two 30ish unknowns, paid perhaps $20
million for an 85 percent stake. Although they vigorously deny it,
as does the publisher, few in Moscow believe that Kommersant's new
owners are anything more than fronts for someone seeking an
extended reach in anticipation of a new government. It is unclear,
though, why the buyer would want to be secretive about it.
</P>
<P>
   The denials have not gained credibility with the disclosure that
the remaining 15 percent stake in Kommersant was bought by Boris
Berezovsky, the most flamboyant, contentious and openly ambitious
of Russia's business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that these events are directly connected with
the elections _ the parliamentary elections this winter, and the
presidential elections after that,'' said Misha Berger, editor of
the respected daily Segodnya. ``Kommersant is the act of a group of
private investors or politicians in Russia. Maybe it was a contest
between Berezovsky and Chubais.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to Anatoly Chubais, once Yeltsin's chief
economic adviser, now the chairman of the nation's electricity
monopoly and an enemy of Berezovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Chubais, who remains a backstage adviser to Yeltsin, was widely
reported to be seeking control of Kommersant with the help of a
Moscow bank.
</P>
<P>
   It would take a small book to describe all the political
jockeying among the information barons. But any report would begin
with Berezovsky, an arch-capitalist and onetime Yeltsin ally whose
relations with the Kremlin are said now to be strained.
</P>
<P>
   More than anyone, Berezovsky has been beefing up his information
holdings. He is already the principal force at the Moscow newspaper
Nezavisimaya Gazeta and at Russian Public Television, a nationwide
network that is 51 percent state-owned. And this spring he bought
control of TV6, a popular Moscow station hard hit by last year's
fiscal collapse.
</P>
<P>
   He said at a news conference a month ago that his media holdings
would work to promote liberal economic reforms and to restrain the
Communist Party. Some analysts believe he plans a campaign to try
to end Communist control of the lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky's purchase angered Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov. Through
city entities, the mayor controls a small stake in TV6, a chunk of
a Moscow newspaper, a major publishing house and two thirds of
Center TV, another channel whose content might best be termed
all-Luzhkov, all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov, an early major contender for president and a political
enemy of Berezovsky, complained that TV6 would not cover him fairly
if Berezovsky owned it.
</P>
<P>
   For sheer scope of ambition, however, neither man is likely to
match the Russian government, which experts say has been
conspicuously busy fine-tuning its huge information machine for the
coming elections.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, the country's second state-controlled
television network, RTR, abruptly canceled one of its
longest-running and most popular programs, ``Top Secret,'' which
specialized in political muckraking, sometimes aimed at the
government itself.
</P>
<P>
   Network officials said the program had descended into
``kompromat,'' roughly translated as mudslinging. The program's
executives responded that it was RTR that had aired the videotape
presumably of the nation's chief prosecutor two months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, Igor Shabdurasulov, general director of the
largest state-owned television network, ORT, told a convention of
Russian journalists his views on the campaign. ``We will determine
for ourselves which political parties and movements correspond to
our political understanding,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The government owns 100 of Russia's 550 television stations and
18 percent of the 12,000 registered newspapers and magazines, said
Kim Iskyan, an analyst with MFK Renaissance, a major investment
bank in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the overwhelming majority of broadcasters and print media
outlets controlled by groups that have political power as their
ultimate aim (including the government itself), the media has come
to be a means to the end of power, rather an end in and of
itself,'' Iskyan wrote in a newly issued analysis of the Russian
information business.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Yeltsin signed a decree combining all press
functions, from issuing broadcast licenses to overseeing
communications satellites to forming media policy, into a single
Cabinet agency, headed by a state television official, Mikhail
Lesin, who is known as one of Yeltsin's top image-makers.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin rejected expressions of concern
that the government was forming a propaganda ministry, but allowed
that the agency would ``consolidate all the state's capabilities in
_ pardon the old-fashioned word _ `ideological work.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Friday, Yeltsin's spokesman, Dmitri
Yakushkin, said the ministry was an old idea that Stepashin had
decided to carry out and that its functions would be mainly
technical.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists here note, though, that the new ministry will have
potentially sweeping powers to revoke broadcast licenses and even
to pressure newspapers. But some said the consolidation move could
be a two-edged sword because control of broadcasting, in
particular, had fallen to regional officials, many of whom have
little concept of press freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists here say they hope Stepashin is simply guilty of
infelicitous phrasing stemming from his years of internal security
work. Journalists say they take heart from the fact that Yeltsin
has repeatedly insisted that the press be unfettered even as it
attacked him. At the same time, they are unnerved by his mercurial
personality, and by nagging reports that he is reluctant to cede
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we have to exaggerate the meaning of these
events, but we can't ignore them either,'' said Berger, the editor.
``During the last year Yeltsin has been an even stronger advocate
of freedom of the press. But maybe something changed. We hope it
didn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
