<SLUG> BC-GORE-CRIME-DATA13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With GORE-CRIME. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics
categories.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Here are positions of the leading presidential
candidates on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   Gore _ Supports photo identification for handgun owners, a ban
on cheap handguns known as ``Saturday night specials,'' raising the
minimum age for handgun ownership from 18 to 21, requiring
background checks on gun show sales of handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley _ Advocates handgun registration, mandatory safety
courses for handgun owners, a ban on Saturday night specials,
prohibiting gun dealers from selling in residential neighborhoods,
mandatory trigger locks for guns.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   Bush _ Supports instant background checks at gun shows, except
for unlicensed gun dealers. Signed a bill effectively barring Texas
cities from suing gun makers to recover damages resulting from gun
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Dole _ Supports instant background checks wherever guns are
sold. Calls for increased enforcement of existing laws.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes _ Supports the national instant check system to prevent
felons from purchasing guns. Supports automatic jail time for any
criminal who attempts to buy a gun, and automatic jail time for
anyone possessing a gun in the commission of a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle _ Supports the national instant check system. Calls for
stronger enforcement of laws dealing with gun violence. Says
``overriding issue isn't really gun control, it's self-control.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain _ Supports background checks on gun show sales. Advocates
increased enforcement of existing laws.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
