<SLUG> BC-MANAGED-CARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS VOW TO USE MANAGED CARE AS CAMPAIGN ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Democrats kicking off this week's debate on
a ``bill of rights'' for patients vowed Monday that they would use
any Republican-led defeat of the legislation as a political weapon
in next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats seek, among other things, to give patients
expanded power to sue managed care providers for denial of service.
But the Republicans say such power would lead to a barrage of
lawsuits that would drive up the cost of health care.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Thomas A. Daschle said that if the
Democratic proposals are not approved, the Democrats would use the
defeat as ammunition in their drive to regain the Senate in the
2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we control the Senate, which will happen, as you know,
in 2001, we fully expect to ensure that we have a good debate about
these amendments and put the Senate on record,'' said Daschle,
D-S.D.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle acknowledged that Republicans have a parliamentary
advantage that could allow them to disregard the Democratic bill
and simply vote on the Republican version.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say they have three Republican senators who will
support their bill _ Sens. John H. Chafee, R-R.I., Arlen Specter,
R-Pa., and Peter Fitzgerald, R-Ill. But they say they still need
two more votes to win.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent managed care providers from denying coverage to
patients, the Senate Democrats say Congress needs to hand patients
a bigger legal stick.
</P>
<P>
   They want to change the law to allow a patient to sue managed
care providers in state courts for pain and suffering and punitive
damages _ whatever is allowable under the state's law _ if a
patient was harmed because a treatment was wrongfully denied.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law now bars patients with employer-provided health
insurance from suing the managed care provider for any damages
beyond the cost of the wrongfully denied treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also want to guarantee that a patient's own physician,
rather than an accountant or consultant hired to cut costs, will
get the last word in determining which treatments are medically
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers, business groups and Republican Senate leaders argue
that expanding a patient's right to sue would lead to lawsuits that
would jack up health care costs. This in turn would cause more
people to be uninsured because businesses won't be able to afford
to provide health insurance, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Republicans support a scaled-down approach to help
patients fight back if they think they've been wrongfully denied
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day Monday, both parties held dueling press
conferences and rallies on Capitol Hill in an effort to more
sharply draw the battle lines.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., called the Democratic proposals
``fatally flawed,'' saying they would increase health insurance
premiums by about $30 a month and add 1.8 million people to the
list of the uninsured. More than 40 million Americans now lack
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Nickles, the assistant majority leader, instead promoted GOP tax
provisions aimed at making it easier for Americans to buy health
insurance. They include a provision that would allow the
self-employed to deduct 100 percent of health insurance costs, up
from 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, dismissed the claim of Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., that the Democratic proposals would cost $2 a
month, or the price of a McDonald's Big Mac. Gramm said the cost of
the Democratic proposals ``would buy the McDonald's franchise in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy told a cheering rally of more than 200 people,
including doctors, nurses, and medical researchers, that
Republicans are merely pushing a ``profit protection program'' for
insurers and ``a bill of wrongs'' for patients.
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
judy(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
