<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-SACHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN-SACHS GROUP AGREES TO BUY ELECTRONIC TRADING COMPANY FOR
$531 MILLION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Britain, Germany, France)   By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Goldman Sachs Group Inc. signaled its support Monday
for new ways of trading securities when it announced that it would
buy Hull Group Inc., a leading electronic trading company, for $531
million.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's purchase of Hull, its first major acquisition since
becoming a public company two months ago, is a calculated bet that
people and institutions will increasingly buy and sell securities
electronically rather than in private deals or on traditional
exchange floors. Hull, which is based in Chicago and will operate
as a subsidiary of Goldman, is one of the largest electronic
traders and specializes in derivatives trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at this as a way of getting ahead of the technology
curve, positioning the firm to take advantage of electronic trading
platforms worldwide,'' said Henry M. Paulson Jr., Goldman's chief
executive. ``This will help us move toward better trading
technology on all sides of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other large securities firms, Goldman has invested in new
electronic securities exchanges, known as electronic communications
networks, or ECN's, that match buyers and sellers of stocks outside
traditional exchanges like the New York Stock Exchange or Nasdaq.
Such exchanges help fill buy and sell orders for less money and at
all hours. They have succeeded in taking some business away from
the established exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Goldman is one of the key minority investors in the
trading network Archipelago and also has a stake in Optimark
Technologies. Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and Goldman recently teamed up
with Bernard L. Madoff Investment Securities to develop their own
electronic stock trading system.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hull purchase is by far Goldman's largest investment in
a new trading medium. It will make Goldman one of the world's
largest electronic market makers for derivatives, especially stock
and index options.
</P>
<P>
   Hull had $103.1 million in revenue and $40.6 million in pretax
profits last year. The company derives more than half of its
revenue in Europe, where electronic trading of securities is a step
ahead of the United States, said M. Blair Hull, Hull's founder and
chief executive. It has a substantial market presence on Britain's
FTSE, Germany's DAX and France's CAC exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our presence in Europe will give Goldman a head start in being
an effective participant in those markets,'' said Hull, who will
continue to serve as Hull's top executive after the sale to
Goldman. ``We will also look for synergies in many other areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull had earlier filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission to sell its shares through an initial public offering,
which would have valued the company at $410 million to $474
million. Goldman said it would pay $531 million for Hull in cash
and stock, but it did not provide a breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   David Viniar, Goldman's chief financial officer, told reporters
in a conference call Monday that the acquisition would probably not
affect Goldman's earnings this year but should add to its bottom
line after that.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Goldman rose $1.125, to $68.375.
</P>
</TEXT>
