<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-AUSSIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSSIES KEEP THEIR HOPES UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUPEN FOFARIA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ It was short, but sweet; small, but
significant.
</P>
<P>
   So much has gone wrong for the Australian Davis Cup team the
last two weeks, but there was a glimmer of hope Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Woodforde jumped two steps back and slapped a return that
headed straight to practice partner Andrew Ilie on the other side
of the net. It looked as if Ilie had an easy opportunity to put the
shot away and tie the score, 15-15, in a practice doubles match
against Woodforde and Sandan Stolle.
</P>
<P>
   But with the reflexes of a cheetah, Stolle flailed his racket
and redirected the ball down the right side of the court, inbounds
but out of reach, making it 30-love.
</P>
<P>
   Stolle and Woodforde, who as of Monday were the Aussies' Davis
Cup doubles team, walked away from the net and smiled at each other
as Ilie shouted curse words in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this will work out, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Woodbridge, who together with Woodforde has been an almost
guaranteed win in doubles competition, announced he was withdrawing
from this weekend's Davis Cup quarterfinal at Longwood Cricket
Club, citing a lingering right arm injury and lack of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Australian captain John Newcombe announced Stolle will join
Patrick Rafter, Lleyton Hewitt, and Woodforde as the Australian
Davis Cup Team, take two. But the way things have unfolded for the
Australians, there may be a few more takes to go before Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've changed by 50 percent,'' Newcombe said. ``I think the
favoritism has shifted to (the USA). I think it was a 50-50 call
before, but now they have to be feeling good about their chances.''
</P>
<P>
   If you'd have asked Newcombe in March, he would've told you the
tie, or five-match competition, would have taken place in
Australia. But the International Tennis Federation overruled
Australia's right to choose the site and staged the event at
Longwood _ site of the first-ever Davis Cup 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The site, I guess, was a given,'' Newcombe said. ``We can't be
concerned about that. That's history.''
</P>
<P>
   If you'd have asked Newcombe three weeks ago, he would have told
you his Australians would meet a US team consisting of Jim Courier,
Tim Martin, and Alex O'Brien. That changed when the world's No. 3
singles player, Pete Sampras, decided to join in the fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's been No. 1 in the world six years in a row,''
Newcombe said, ``I'd rather he wasn't here.''
</P>
<P>
   If you'd have asked Newcombe two weeks ago, he would have told
you his four-man squad would be Rafter (the No. 2 singles player in
the world), Mark Philippoussis (one of Australia's top singles
players), and ``the Woodies'' (Australia's leading Davis Cup
doubles team which hasn't lost a Davis Cup match in 5 1/2 years).
</P>
<P>
   That changed 12 days ago, when Philippoussis injured his knee
playing Sampras at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   And if you'd have asked Newcombe Friday, he would have told you
his four-man squad was still evenly matched with the Americans,
since 18-year-old Lleyton Hewitt gives the team a young, aggressive
talent to replace Philippoussis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Lleyton gets his teeth into a match, he's very hard for
anyone to beat,'' Newcombe said.
</P>
<P>
   But that changed Saturday, when Newcombe learned that he had
lost Woodbridge as well as Philippoussis.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a tremendous loss,'' Newcombe said. ``Two very good,
competitive players.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, he could only muster a cynical smile while pondering
what else could go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's maybe not as good as before, but we're lucky we have two
good backups to put in our open spots,'' Newcombe said quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Newcombe said Monday his doubles team, which competes Saturday,
would be Woodforde and Stolle, winners of the '98 US Open doubles
competition. But that can't be set in stone just yet.
</P>
<P>
   Newcombe is considering teams of Rafter and Woodforde (who won
together against Croatia in '96) and Rafter and Stolle (who went
5-0 together at the World Team Cup in May).
</P>
<P>
   Much of the decision will hinge upon how rigorous Rafter's
singles match is Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Todd's withdrawal is a bit of a blow, as we haven't lost
a Davis Cup doubles match in five years,'' Newcombe said. ``I feel
very confident that Pat or Sandon will get the job done with
Mark.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
