peaceful end to demonstrations; witnesses say fresh violence
erupted as club-wielding police clashed with students in Tehran. By
Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-CARE (Washington) _ For the first time since a
health-care revolution began moving patients into managed care, the
Senate opens a high-stakes struggle over how to protect the rights
of patients and regulate the companies that provide health
insurance for most Americans. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICADS-POLITICIANS (Washington) _ Washington Talk column: A
detailed look at some new public service announcements,
guest-starring spouses of congressmen and senators. By David E.
Rosenbaum. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   DOOMED-STADIUMS (Seattle) _ These are dark and difficult days
for many of America's domed stadiums, which were once hailed as
climate-controlled, multi-purpose technological marvels but, after
barely a generation, are increasingly considered obsolete by fans
and owners alike. By Sam Howe Verhovek. 1,700 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SOUTHPOLE (Undated) _ The plight of a woman trapped for the
winter at a South Pole research station, needing treatment for a
lump in her breast, is even more complex than initial reports
suggested. The woman herself is the only medical doctor at the
Amundsen-Scott station in the Antarctic, according to a cancer
expert who was consulted in her case. Therefore, the patient will
have to act as her own doctor, performing a biopsy on herself, and
if the lump is malignant, administering any needed treatment, which
might include chemotherapy. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
