<HEADLINE>
FEDS SMASH SOUTH TEXAS SMUGGLING OPERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal authorities have broken up a 15-year smuggling operation
that specialized in sneaking thousands of undocumented immigrants
past the Border Patrol's main checkpoint for traffic leaving the
Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A two-year undercover operation, known as ``Operation Snake
Pit,'' resulted in a dozen guilty pleas authorities announced
Monday. Among those who pleaded guilty were seven members of a
family in Raymondville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the U.S. Justice Department and the smugglers
agreed to the destruction of two apartment complexes, a motel and a
house _ all in Raymondville _ used as a staging ground for sneaking
people further north.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to bulldoze four places,'' said Rick Aguirre,
head of the U.S. Border Patrol's anti-smuggling operations for the
Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``They smuggled a lot of people; this family was the nucleus,''
Aguirre, said of the operation that was headed by Olga Contreras,
60, and aided by her husband and five children.
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol and the FBI joined forces to take on the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities took notice of the Contreras in January 1997
when more than 350 undocumented immigrants were found, packed like
sardines, into a Raymondville apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
   The immigrants were squeezed into rooms with space heaters and
mattresses. Some had been there for as long as a week.
</P>
<P>
   Raymondville, which has a population of 9,200, is about 28 miles
south of a Border Patrol checkpoint on U.S. 77 and is considered a
``choke point'' for railway, foot and vehicle traffic headed out of
the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The guilty pleas, entered at federal court in Brownsville,
headed off a slew of charges stemming from a February indictment
including harboring aliens, welfare fraud, money laundering and the
possession and sale of counterfeit Social Security cards.
</P>
<P>
   The Rock Courts Motel and Lounge, Los Milagros Apartments and
the other properties are scheduled to be destroyed by the Texas
National Guard in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all looking forward to the opportunity to clean that
area up,'' Don Calvert, a federal prosecutor, said of the
buildings. ``I do not know of any case where it has been done
before.''
</P>
<P>
   The bulldozers will roll after sentencing in which the
defendants face up to 30 months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The Contreras own several pieces of property in Raymondville,
including a grocery story which was used to provide food and
supplies to the would-be immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Contreras organization has been smuggling and harboring
aliens in the Raymondville area for the past 10 to 15 years,''
according to a statement released by the FBI. ``It is believed the
family and their associates are responsible for harboring thousands
of aliens during that time period.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
