<HEADLINE>
STOCK OFFERING BY INSURANCE COMPANY BOOSTS SOUTH AFRICA'S ECONOMY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ A single South African company sold
shares to the public for the first time Monday, and the response
was so big that economists predicted that it could add 1 percent to
the country's faltering economic growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   The company, commonly known as Old Mutual, is the country's
largest insurer _ 7 percent of the population has policies with it
_ and it is one of the five biggest companies in South Africa. Its
chief businesses are life insurance, pension plans, mutual funds,
banking and real estate. But because 20 years of apartheid
sanctions forced local companies to invest only locally, it has
stakes in everything from coal to hotels to clothing chains to oat
cereals.
</P>
<P>
   After mining, insurance is South Africa's biggest economic
powerhouse. For decades, South Africans have held most of their
savings in insurance policies rather than in banks or stocks. The
reason, economists said, is a combination of favorable tax
treatment for insurance and ignorance about the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   As a mutual insurer _ Old Mutual's formal name is the South
African Mutual Life Assurance Society _ it was owned by
policyholders. Today's conversion to stock and the public sale gave
it a market value of about $6.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   About $2 billion of Monday's sale will go directly to the 1
million Old Mutual policyholders who asked the company to sell
their new shares for them. The spending of that windfall, several
economists estimated, could boost the gross domestic product by
between 0.8 percent and 1.2 percent. Another 2.2 million
policyholders held their shares, in effect creating an enormous new
pool of shareholder wealth.
</P>
<P>
   The issue single-handedly tripled the record for volume on the
Johannesburg Stock Exchange; it reached 1 billion shares, up from
304 million. Old Mutual shares trading on the Johannesburg Stock
Exchange closed at 13.10 rand or about $2.13, compared with the
11.25-rand price initially set.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's primary listing was in London, where the
shares closed at 137.5 pence or about $2.15, compared with the
initial price of 120 pence. Buying there was strong; about a third
of the company is now owned by foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been wonderful for us, and I hope all our new
shareholders are as happy as I am,'' Gerritt van Niekerk, the
company's managing director, said after the sale Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The company will use the cash raised to pay for overseas
acquisitions, especially in asset management and private banking,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting government permission to list in London took months of
negotiations, and promises that the business would still be
regulated here.
</P>
<P>
   Because exchange control regulations _ originally instituted to
stop the flight of nervous capital that began after the 1976 Soweto
riots _ had prevented Old Mutual from buying overseas except
through complicated asset swaps, the London listing allows a major
player in South Africa's insulated economy to diversify globally.
Other big South African companies, including Anglo-American PLC,
the conglomerate built on gold mining, and South African Breweries,
the world's fourth-largest brewer, now have their primary listings
in London.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time in a year that a local insurance giant
has converted from policyholder to stockholder ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, the South African National Life Assurance Co.,
better known as Sanlam, did so, although the overall effect was
smaller, for several reasons: Sanlam is half the size of Old
Mutual; it made it harder for policyholders to sell their new
shares, and they sold into a falling market.
</P>
<P>
   Major changes have swept South African companies in the last few
years _ faced with global competition, banks and insurance
companies have merged, mining conglomerates have rearranged
themselves to concentrate on core businesses, brokerage houses have
sought foreign partners and companies like the national airline and
telephone company have imported foreign chief executive officers.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have touted demutualization as a ``black
empowerment'' exercise because many holders of small policies are
black and became shareholders for the first time today.
</P>
<P>
   Demutualization has also had a hidden side effect that delights
the government: South Africa has a serious problem with tax cheats,
and the government has been perusing lists of Sanlam and Old Mutual
policyholders and seizing the share rights of all those in arrears.
Last month, the South African Revenue Service estimated that about
$85 million of Monday's windfall would go into its coffers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
