A7312 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIRELAND-IRA-NYT &LR;      07-12 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-IRA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH PROPOSAL AIMS TO BREAK NORTHERN IRELAND STALEMATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ With only days left before a make-or-break decision on
a new government for Ulster, Britain Monday proposed a measure
aimed at obtaining Protestant support by requiring the Irish
Republican Army to follow an enforceable disarmament timetable.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of when and how the largely Catholic IRA will disarm
has been the main sticking point in carrying out the Northern
Ireland peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The complex measure contained what Prime Minister Tony Blair
called a ``fail-safe mechanism'' with procedures for banishing Sinn
Fein, the IRA's political arm, from the new all-party government if
there were a delay in dismantling the guerrilla arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Protestant politicians have been demanding such assurances
before they will agree to allow the new government in the
conflicted British province to begin operations by naming its
cabinet this week. David Trimble, leader of the Ulster Unionists,
indicated he was still not satisfied and met Monday night with
Blair at 10 Downing St. to press the argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still continuing problems, but also there is still
continuing consultation,'' Trimble said on emerging.
</P>
<P>
   Blair spoke by phone during the day about the continuing
stalemate with President Clinton and with Prime Minister Bertie
Ahern of Ireland, whose government is a co-sponsor of the peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   While politicians tried to nail down the necessary compromises
in London, uniformed members of the Protestant Orange Order were
observing the most important day in their annual marching calendar,
to celebrate long-ago Protestant victories. The marches have often
caused conflict with Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   There were about 20 flute-and-snare-drum parades across Ulster,
including one that attracted 30,000 people to a park ringed with
barbed wire in downtown Belfast across the Lagan River from a large
Catholic neighborhood. The parades went off without major
disruption under the strictest security by police and British
troops yet seen in the annual Protestant marching season.
</P>
<P>
   A 25-foot steel and concrete barrier was erected to block a
bridge to the Lower Ormeau Road community, a Catholic area where
Protestant marches have led to past conflicts. Orange leaders
marched up to it and handed a letter of protest to a Royal Ulster
Constabulary officer.
</P>
<P>
   July 12 is the date on which Orangemen commemorate the victory
of the Protestant King William over the Roman Catholic James II in
the Battle of the Boyne in 1690. In past years, the parades have
led to widespread violence, but this year security was tightened
and the Order urged troublemakers to stay away.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday's march at Drumcree church near Portadown, a
flashpoint for violence the last five years, ended peaceably as did
the one Monday in Belfast. In both cases, Orange grandmasters
delivered letters protesting the government-appointed Parades
Commission's decisions to forbid them to pass directly through
Catholic residential areas.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, whose party is the largest in the province, is the
first minister of the new Northern Ireland Assembly, and he must
decide by Thursday whether to put into action the next critical
step of the accord _ the creation of the 10-member Cabinet. Two of
the seats belong to Sinn Fein, and the Ulster Unionists are
demanding legislative guarantees that if the IRA does not comply
with the disarmament timetable, the Sinn Fein ministers will be
removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   An effort to satisfy that demand produced the last-minute
modifications on disarmament to Monday's House of Commons measure,
which is the vehicle by which authority is to be turned over to the
new Assembly in Belfast from the British Parliament here.
</P>
<P>
   The bill now enters a virtual wind tunnel of legislative action
to meet deadlines set by Blair. It must go through readings and
debate and be passed in the Commons on Tuesday, clear the House of
Lords on Wednesday, obtain Royal Assent on Thursday and be enacted
by the Commons on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday is officially the day that powers are to be ``devolved''
to Belfast. It is the same way that authority was shifted to the
new legislatures in Scotland and Wales on July 1 under Blair's
program to grant regions of Britain the right to govern their own
local affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The moment of truth will come Wednesday night when Trimble meets
with his 110-member executive committee in Belfast to decide
whether to take the risk of entering government with Sinn Fein
under the terms Blair has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   If Trimble refuses to name the new ministers on Thursday, the
whole peace agreement will come under review, though details of how
that would happen have been left deliberately vague. ``I have no
plan B,'' Blair has repeatedly said since setting a series of final
dates for the transfer of power to Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   From the start of negotiations more than two years ago that
produced a peace settlement in April, 1998, Blair has established
deadlines and then let several of them pass inconclusively in the
interests of keeping the fragile proposition standing. This time he
has appeared more frustrated with the lack of progress and less
inclined to consider another postponement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have taken it as far as we possibly can if we
really can't make progress now,'' he said Sunday. ``I have spent
days and weeks in negotiations, and this issue is not going to
change. It is a question of whether people are prepared to take the
gun out of the politics of Northern Ireland and whether, on the
other side, people are prepared to share power. There are just so
many ways you can dress that proposition up.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of Monday's bill, the Cabinet _ along with the
whole assembly and the newly created North-South entities that link
the Belfast and Dublin governments _ would be suspended if the head
of the independent international disarmament commission, Gen. John
de Chastelain of Canada, ruled that the IRA were in default.
</P>
<P>
   ``If no commitment is made to de Chastelain, we will know where
we are,'' said a spokesman for Blair, explaining the assurances
being extended to Trimble. ``People will know where responsibility
lies. We will press the rewind button and be back where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Ulster Unionists were seeking a guarantee that if the
IRA does not meet disarmament goals, Sinn Fein would be expelled
and the government would continue. The language of the bill calls
only for a vote of the parties in the assembly at that point on how
to proceed. Trimble said he would have amendments to the bill on
Tuesday before it begins its hasty passage through the Commons.
</P>
</TEXT>
