<HEADLINE>
DID ROBIN HOOD FROLIC IN THE FOREST GAILY?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Stephen Knight &LR; , professor of English Literature at Cardiff
University in Wales, says  &UR; Robin Hood &LR;  was gay and liked  &UR; Little &LR; 
 &UR; John &LR;  better than Maid Marian, who was fictional anyway.
</P>
<P>
   According to Knight, 14th century ballads about the adventures
of the outlaw and his ``merrie men'' could not ``say outright that
he was gay because of the prevailing moral climate, but they do
contain a great deal of erotic imagery. The green wood itself is a
symbol of virility, and the references to arrows, quivers and
swords make it clear, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Barry Dobson &LR; , professor of medieval history at Cambridge, told
the Times of London that he concurred on the ambiguity of the
relationship between Hood and Little John.
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights advocate &UR; Peter Tatchell  &LR; said, predictably, ``It's
about time school history lessons acknowledged the contribution of
famous homosexuals.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mary Chamberlain &LR;  of the Robin Hood Society said, just as
predictably, ``Robin remains a highly regarded figure the world
over, and children like to play at being Robin Hood. These claims
could do a lot of damage.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JUST SOME NICE OLD-FASHIONED NAMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Children of the Baby Boomers, cherishing antique photographs of
their moms in granny glasses and their dads in tie-dyed T-shirts,
are also blessed with their own birth certificates, bearing those
wonderful names of the '60s and '70s:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Andrew Demcak &LR;  recalls a high school pal, in the '80s, who was
named  &UR; Celestial Fudge &LR; . ``We all called her Celeste,'' he recalls
kindly. &UR; Alexandra de Moya &LR;  says the name on her birth certificate
is  &UR; Utisha Mariposa &LR; . Utisha, she was told, means ``enlightened,''
and mariposa is the Spanish word for butterfly. She recalls school
pals named  &UR; Mao Che &LR; ,  &UR; Bean &LR; ,  &UR; Rain &LR; ,  &UR; Lucky Hippo &LR;  and
 &UR; Agwitch &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Raspberry Wheeler  &LR; (now Jessica), says she has a cousin still
named  &UR; Blueberry &LR; , and went to school with William Saroyan's
granddaughter,  &UR; Strawberry &LR; , who she thinks is now Sara.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Frank Webster &LR;  admits to naming his son  &UR; Moon Shadow &LR; . ``As he
went through his early teens, he often talked about changing his
name to  &UR; Mike &LR; ,'' he writes, but he changed his mind and now is
happy to be known as Moon.
</P>
<P>
   Among the modern practitioners of this ancient hippie
name-giving craft,  &UR; Jeannette Dillon &LR;  gave her son the right to
choose his own middle name and adopt it legally. On July 1, he
became  &UR; Joshua Moctezuma Dillon &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANYTHING TO HELP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Reading recently that  &UR; David Cassel  &LR; had helped in the rescue of
a butterfly caught in the Sierra Club bookstore window,  &UR; David &LR; 
 &UR; Cassell &LR;  (one ``l'' more than the first, but no relation) couldn't
resist a similar call to action the other day.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter discovered a ladybug in the backseat of their car
as he drove to her piano recital in Berkeley, he writes, whereupon
she made a wish. He opened the door to let the ladybug out, and
there was ``a loud crunch as a car ran into my opening door.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Mary Chapin Carpenter  &LR; canceled a concert in Springfield,
Mo., at the last minute on Friday night to fly home to tend to her
sick dog.  &UR; Enoch Morris &LR; , director of the concert hall, said
singers ``are people just like we are, and they have problems in
their personal lives.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tech briefs:  &UR; Paul Levitan  &LR; and  &UR; Jean Yves Charon &LR;  of Galaxy
Desserts in San Rafael have legally trademarked ``Y2KAKE,'' the
name of a chocolate resolution-breaker they'll push for the New
Year. In Boise, Idaho,  &UR; Paul Beckman &LR;  saw a coffee-shop tip jar
labeled www.tips.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ An ad for ABC.com on the back of the latest edition of the
MetroCard _ the New York version of a transit fast pass _ features
a picture of  &UR; Kofi Annan &LR;  and the phrase, ``Got time for a Kofi
break?'' and it's not making the United Nations happy. ``Inasmuch
as this may raise some legal issues,'' said spokesman
 &UR; Manoel de Almeida e Silva &LR; , ``the legal office is looking into the
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   _ As to celebrity narrators of audio tours of museum
exhibitions,  &UR; Tony Reveaux &LR;  recalls  &UR; Orson &LR;   &UR; Welles &LR;  doing the King
Tut tour in 1977. Also, says Reveaux,  &UR; Candice Bergen  &LR; narrated the
recent Picasso show at San Francisco's Legion of Honor, but it was
French actress  &UR; Liz Lebourf &LR;  who did ``Impressionists in Winter.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows that heroin chic is over and supermodels are so
'80s. So what's next in the fashion industry? Would you believe
Shabbat dinners? Oy! Heretofore non-practicing Jews are lighting
candles, saying prayers and snarfing beef brisket on Friday
nights.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; From Glue, a magazine focusing on ``style and action in Los
Angeles.''
