<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7315 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIABETES-KIDS-2000(2T     07-12 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIABETES-KIDS-2000(2TAKES)-1STLD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE CHILDREN CONTRACTING `ADULT' DIABETES
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: FIXES info box at end, DELETES reference to `high insulin
levels' (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLOTTE HUFF 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Amid the routine of childhood sniffles and
earaches, pediatrician John Menchaca began to notice something
unusual several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rough, dark skin was emerging on the back of some of his
patients' necks. The skin change puzzled him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parents would say, `It looks dirty, and I kept scrubbing
and scrubbing it, and it was still there,' '' said Menchaca, a Fort
Worth physician for nearly three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Menchaca now views the skin change as a ``blessing in
disguise.'' When it appears, doctors are learning, the child runs a
greater risk of developing diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Adult-onset diabetes, also known as Type 2 diabetes, is commonly
associated with those older than 45. But more and more it is
showing up in children too young to drive, and medical
professionals blame America's losing battle against obesity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fatter today than we have ever been in the history of
this country,'' said Paul Villas, executive director of the
University of Texas System Texas-Mexico Border Health Coordination
Office in Edinburg, Texas. Villas has been leading efforts to
screen children living along the border for signs of Type 2.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, $44 billion is spent to treat kidney damage,
amputations and other complications related to diabetes, most of it
Type 2.
</P>
<P>
   Development of the disease in childhood will be more costly and
more debilitating, said Dr. William Archer, commissioner of the
Texas Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten or 15 years ago, we didn't even know'' that Type 2 existed
in children, Archer said. ``We are going to have, I believe, an
epidemic of problems with blindness, kidney failure and
amputations.''
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, officials from the Texas state health department
and the Juvenile Diabetes Foundation organized a workshop in the
state capital Austin on children's Type 2. Soon after, several
studies were presented at the American Diabetes Association's
annual meeting that looked into the emerging problem and its
primary cause.
</P>
<P>
   The University of North Texas Health Science Center recently
completed a pilot study assessing weight problems in three
elementary schools in the Fort Worth district. The three schools
were chosen to reflect a cross section of backgrounds; the
percentage of overweight students ranged from 9 percent to 26
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Menchaca and Ximena Urrutia-Rojas, assistant
professor at the UNT Health Science Center, sat down with school
officials to discuss screening at more schools.
</P>
<P>
   But screening, while helpful, is just one part of the solution,
said Jackie Thompson, director of health services for the school
district. The next step, she said, will be to brainstorm with local
public health officials about ways to help overweight students.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just what the (school district) can do to screen the
students,'' she said. ``It's what's going to happen after we screen
the students.''
</P>
<P>
   For Menchaca, who helped with the school obesity study,
prevention of Type 2 has become a crusade. As a diabetic, he is
particularly concerned about Hispanic children, who, with other
minorities, are considered at more genetic risk.
</P>
<P>
   First, Menchaca screened his patients for weight problems.
</P>
<P>
   Then he sent letters to parents of at-risk children. And he paid
for a bilingual dietitian to teach an after-hours nutrition class
in his office waiting room.
</P>
<P>
   One of those letters landed in the mailbox of Lala Reyes of Fort
Worth. She immediately enrolled herself and her 11-year-old
daughter, Kathy, in the classes.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy soon became one of the prize pupils, dropping her dress
size from 18 to 14 in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clothes, they look so big on her,'' Lala Reyes said
proudly.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, physicians were taught that children develop only
Type 1 diabetes. That occurs when the pancreas stops producing
insulin.
</P>
<P>
   Type 2, responsible for more than 90 percent of all diabetes
cases, involves a reduction in insulin. The long-term consequences
are the same if the disease is not controlled through diet,
medication and, sometimes, insulin shots.
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes is the leading cause of kidney failure and newly
diagnosed blindness in adults age 20 to 74. People with the disease
at least double their risk of a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Research is still trying to catch up with what physicians are
seeing in the office.
</P>
<P>
   It's still unclear, for example, exactly how many children might
have Type 2 diabetes or how fast the numbers are increasing.
</P>
<P>
   One 1996 study, conducted in the Cincinnati area, sifted through
12 years of children's medical records.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1992, only 2 percent to 4 percent of all new cases of
diabetes in children were Type 2. By 1994, the percentage had
jumped to 16 percent, researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
