<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7324 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-DRUGS-2TAKES-N     07-12 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-DRUGS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S MEDICARE PROPOSAL CALLS ATTENTION TO PRACTICES OF
PHARMACY MANAGERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Barrett Toan calls himself a silent partner in the
health care system and if President Clinton has his way, there will
be many more like him.
</P>
<P>
   Toan is the president of Express Scripts Inc., which supervises
the filling of 295 million prescriptions a year for 47 million
people with private health insurance. In calling for Medicare
coverage of prescription drugs, Clinton wants to see Express
Scripts and similar companies play the same role for 39 million
older Americans and disabled people.
</P>
<P>
   While such companies, known as pharmacy benefit managers, have
been popular for a decade or so, most consumers have only a vague
idea of the powerful force they exert over which drugs are sold and
which pharmacies sell them.
</P>
<P>
   With the plastic identification cards issued by Express Scripts
and similar companies, a patient can walk into a pharmacy, hand
over $10 and walk out with $70 worth of medicine. The pharmacy
benefit manager negotiates the complex arrangements behind that
transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton would give such companies a great new responsibility,
managing drug benefits for Medicare patients, who use a third of
all drugs prescribed in the United States. But that shift would
also illuminate some practices that have largely escaped public
notice, including the power of pharmacy benefit managers to affect
doctors' decisions and their dealings with drug companies. The
arrangements, which include rebates from the drug companies to the
managers for giving preference to certain drugs, would become much
more visible.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacy benefit managers organize the market for prescription
drugs, securing deep discounts from drug manufacturers and retail
pharmacies for large employers or health plans. They try to
influence doctors' prescribing habits and encourage the use of
lower-cost drugs, including generic substitutes for brand-name
medicines. They strongly recommend certain drugs over others in
each therapeutic category _ antihistamines and treatments for high
cholesterol or high blood pressure, for example.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, pharmacy benefit managers are like health
maintenance organizations: they try to control the cost of care. So
far, they have not engendered widespread hostility among consumers,
as some HMOs have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we could play a useful role in Medicare,'' Toan said
in an interview at his headquarters here. ``We help consumers get
the maximum value for the dollars they spend on pharmaceuticals.
Many elderly patients are paying prices 20 to 25 percent higher
than what our customers pay because they don't get the type of
discounts we can negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   But doctors and pharmacists have expressed concern about the
market power of pharmacy benefit managers. While Express Scripts is
independently owned, some of its chief competitors are owned by
drug companies and drugstores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offices are besieged with faxes and phone calls urging us
to change the drugs we prescribe for patients,'' said Dr. Raymond
Scalettar, a Washington rheumatologist. ``It's very troubling, very
intrusive, and not necessarily in the patients' best interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people are equally troubled by the practice of drug
manufacturers' giving cash rebates to the pharmacy benefit managers
in return for having their products included on the list of
preferred drugs. Pharmacists worry that some drugs may be chosen
more for their rebates than for their efficacy. The terms of rebate
agreements are considered proprietary information and are a
carefully guarded secret.
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns would grow if these companies managed drug
benefits for Medicare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   The president's plan to cover prescription drugs is part of his
proposal to reorganize Medicare to make it more competitive and
financially secure as members of the baby boom generation approach
retirement age. Administration officials see pharmacy benefit
managers as a way to prevent explosive growth in the cost of
Medicare drug benefits without resorting to federal price controls,
which are anathema to drug makers.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, the president's chief economic adviser, who
helped design Clinton's Medicare proposal, said, ``There are no
price controls in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Sperling said, the government would simply get
``reasonable discounts,'' like other health plans that buy large
quantities of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, pharmacy benefit managers handled 1.8 billion
prescriptions last year. Employers, labor unions and private health
plans have increasingly turned to such companies to control drug
spending, which has grown much faster than other health spending in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the General Accounting Office, an investigative arm
of Congress, found that pharmacy benefit managers had reduced the
cost of drug benefits for federal employees by 20 percent to 27
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Drug benefit managers develop networks of retail pharmacies that
may include thousands of drugstores. In return for a large volume
of business, the drugstores must give discounts. Under a typical
arrangement, a drugstore receives the average wholesale price for a
drug, minus 15 percent. The pharmacist also gets a small dispensing
fee, perhaps $2 for each prescription.
</P>
<P>
   Elderly people often pay the highest prices for prescription
drugs because their purchasing power is fragmented. Under Clinton's
proposal, the government would hire a private company in each
region of the country to manage drug benefits for the large numbers
of Medicare patients who are still in the traditional
fee-for-service program.
</P>
<P>
   Howard J. Bedlin, vice president of the National Council on the
Aging, a research and advocacy group, said, ``There's an emerging
consensus that pharmacy benefit managers have an important role to
play in Medicare reform, but you have to build in certain consumer
protections'' to guarantee the confidentiality of patients' records
and to inform consumers of any restrictions on their choice of
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Express Scripts, like other pharmacy benefit managers, reviews
prescriptions before they are filled at retail drugstores across
the country. The pharmacies file claims electronically. Express
Scripts can immediately tell the pharmacist if the customer has
insurance and how much of a co-payment to charge.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Express Scripts has records of other drugs that a
patient has bought. This allows it to tell the pharmacist if the
new drug would duplicate an existing prescription, if it could
cause harmful interactions with other drugs or if a prescription is
being refilled too early. The company at this point could also
notify the pharmacist if another drug or a generic is preferred.
</P>
<P>
   While employers and HMOs praise the work of drug benefit
managers, many doctors and pharmacists have had frustrating
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Edward F. Dillon, co-owner of Grubb's Pharmacy, a century-old
store on Capitol Hill in Washington, said he understood the need to
hold down health costs but had been exasperated by the techniques
of pharmacy benefit managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some cases,'' Dillon said, ``you have a college-age
customer service representative calling a doctor with 30 years of
experience and asking, `What is your medical justification for this
drug?'''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   John M. Rector, general counsel of the National Community
Pharmacists Association, which represents 35,000 independent
pharmacies, said the preferences for certain drugs were often based
on ``back-room deals that the consumer never knows about.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Rector said, a pharmacy benefit manager ``sometimes
tells the pharmacist to dispense a more expensive, inappropriate
brand-name drug because the PBM is getting a rebate or kickback
from the manufacturer.''
</P>
<P>
   But Toan said most of the money from cash rebates was passed on
to the sponsor of a health plan, reducing the overall cost of drug
benefits for patients.
</P>
<P>
   Toan, a former director of the Missouri Social Services
Department, said Express Scripts was ``the nation's largest
independent pharmacy benefit manager.'' PCS Health Systems of
Scottsdale, Ariz., another benefit manager, has been owned since
January by Rite Aid, the drugstore chain. Their biggest competitor,
Merck-Medco Managed Care, is owned by Merck &AMP; Co., the drug
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Express Scripts manages $10 billion a year in drug spending for
its clients, which include Bethlehem Steel and Blue Cross and Blue
Shield of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart L. Bascomb, executive vice president of Express Scripts,
said some drugs would not be affordable for many people without the
discounts obtained by pharmacy benefit managers. The average retail
prescription price of common cholesterol-lowering drugs, for
example, is $100 a month, or $1,200 a year.
</P>
<P>
   In one respect, Medicare is different from other clients of
Express Scripts. Toan, the president of the company, refused to
give details of its contracts with drug manufacturers and
pharmacies. But Congress and the public would probably insist on
knowing the details of any discounts negotiated on behalf of
Medicare patients.
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller general of the United States would want to audit
Medicare's drug spending. Medicare officials would be tempted to
regulate the activities of pharmacy benefit managers to protect
Medicare patients and to save taxpayers' money. Pharmacists would
demand an explanation if they were excluded from the list of
drugstores serving Medicare beneficiaries in a particular region.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the best efforts of drug benefit managers, Toan said,
``Medicare, like commercial health plans, would probably face
double-digit increases in drug costs, in the range of 15 percent a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Clinton's proposal, beneficiaries would have to pay half
of any drug costs covered by Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would serve as a check against unnecessary use of
medicines,'' Toan said. On the other hand, he said, ``a lot of new
medicines will address conditions of the elderly, and that might
keep up a fairly steep increase in drug spending.''
</P>
<P>
   Independent pharmacists complain that they have little
opportunity to negotiate with pharmacy benefit managers because
contracts are offered to them on a ``take it or leave it'' basis.
They say payments are so low that they often lose $5 or more on a
$50 prescription.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Toan said, ``That's our job, to seek the lowest
price we can get for our customers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
