<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7327 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAKISTAN-KASHMIR-425&AMP;     07-12 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-KASHMIR-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTAN MAKES CASE FOR A HALT TO FIGHTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ Castigated by many as a betrayer of the
dream of a liberated Kashmir, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif said
Monday night in a televised speech that _ to the contrary _ he has
helped usher the cause onto the world stage and prudently steered
away from an all-out war.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not aware of the anxiety we passed through during
the past one and a half months,'' he said, explaining why he had
coaxed Pakistani-backed guerrillas to return from mountaintop
redoubts they had seized a few miles inside Indian-controlled
Kashmir. ``This is no secret that the threat of a big war with
India was looming by the way things had deteriorated between India
and Pakistan.''
</P>
<P>
   He added ominously, ``Missiles with nuclear warheads were
directed toward us, and our air force was put on alert.''
</P>
<P>
   The 25-minute speech was the prime minister's first public
statement since he returned from a hastily arranged visit to
Washington on July 4. There he promised President Clinton to take
``concrete steps'' to end the fighting, which had pitted several
hundred well-armed Muslim infiltrators against the Indian air force
and battalions of infantry.
</P>
<P>
   The trip to Washington puzzled and angered many here. Jubilant
news accounts had led them to believe that well-positioned
guerrillas were making easy prey of woefully vulnerable Indians
attempting frontal assaults up steep peaks. The fighting had put
the emotionally charged Kashmir issue onto front pages worldwide,
and then the prime minister seemed to knuckle under to American
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   But with a troubled political opposition, a weakened judiciary
and an intimidated press, there is little on the political horizon
to challenge Sharif. In fact, for all the discontent, even the
nation's usually intrepid Islamic fundamentalists have been unable
to mount anything but relatively muted street protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our decision to give diplomacy another chance, to try it once
again, is not a result of haste, nor has it been taken under
pressure,'' Sharif insisted. ``A sage has said that it takes more
courage to come out of a war than to start a war.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the guerrillas had made the world understand that
``Kashmir is a nuclear flashpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   A withdrawal of the fighters _ known here as the mujahedeen, or
Muslim holy warriors _ began on Saturday. While the pullback may be
a testament to the prime minister's persuasive skills, it also
lends support to consistent Indian accusations that the invaders
were mostly Pakistan army regulars, a view shared by many analysts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mujahedeen organizations have not helped Sharif's credibility.
While he thanked the guerrillas Monday for heeding his plea,
leaders of several of the groups called Sharif a traitor and denied
they were making any retreat at all.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical criticism, Rifaat Hussain, a professor of
international relations in Islamabad, said: ``Nawaz shouldn't have
had such an early loss of nerve. Now he's nowhere. His idea of
defusing the crisis was to run to Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in his speech, Sharif made much of the assurance he
received from Clinton that the president would take a personal
interest in settling the Kashmir situation, a 52-year-old dispute
that has led the nations into two all-out wars. ``An assurance by
the leader of a power like America is not insignificant,'' Sharif
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistanis want the world to compel India to permit a
plebiscite, a vote to which India once committed itself. The vote
would allow the Kashmiris _ most of whom are Muslims _ to choose
whether they want to belong to largely Hindu India or Muslim
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif's speech was quickly assailed by political rivals. The
leading opposition, the Pakistan Peoples Party, called for his
resignation, but the party has called for his resignation before,
and it is a party in disarray. Its leader, the former Prime
Minister Benazir Bhutto, lives abroad. She faces arrest if she
return because she has been convicted of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Democracy is constantly rumored to be endangered in Pakistan,
which has a powerful military that is said to be frustrated by
inept and corrupt civilians at the helm. But military leaders seem
to support Sharif's decision to reduce tensions with India, which
has a numerically superior military and a less-feeble economy.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night the prime minister spoke of resuming the ``Lahore
Declaration process,'' a high-level dialogue that began in February
with a bus trip to Pakistan by India's prime minister, Atal Behari
Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
   But any talks are likely to be heavy with distrust. As Indians
see it, Sharif has proven a duplicitous rogue who pretended to be a
peacemaker while endorsing a plan by his generals to launch an
adventure into Kashmir. To the Pakistanis, Vajpayee is an
opportunist who has used the conflict to whip up a war hysteria to
benefit himself in coming elections.
</P>
<P>
   Their goals concerning the Kashmir dispute are different:
</P>
<P>
   Sharif hopes that the past two months of alarming headlines will
cause the world to recognize the danger of the situation. Vajpayee
welcomes no such attention, and says Kashmir is best kept a
bilateral concern.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more stirring parts of Sharif's speech was his
likening of the Kashmir situation to a volcano, and the mujahedeen
to lava. ``As long as lava boils, it finds its way to the plains,''
he said. ``And the Kashmiri resistance, like that lava, will find
someplace else. And it will never cool off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
