<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7335 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BROPEN-NOTES13-CO     07-12 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BROPEN-NOTES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olazabal can't get a grip on club, game
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ At least Jose Maria Olazabal did not
fracture his sense of humor. Embarrassed by the outburst of anger
at the U.S. Open last month that severely hindered his chances this
week at the Carnoustie Golf Links, the Masters champion Monday was
able to chuckle at his fragmented game.
</P>
<P>
   The last two fingers on his right hand, which he broke when
slamming it into a hotel wall at Pinehurst, N.C., after a
first-round 75, are taped together and he ``cannot really grip the
club properly.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe ``the flight of the ball'' he was producing in
his practice round at Carnoustie, Olazabal, whose driving accuracy
has been suspect, except for the first week of April at Augusta
National, said, ``The flight of the ball is pretty much the same _
sideways with the driver and pretty straight with the irons.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal said that while he received an assurance from his
doctor that playing will not cause further damage to the hand, it
still causes him pain and will not be healed for two to three
weeks. ``I definitely hurt my chances because of the injury,''
Olazabal said, ``but I'm here to try the best I can. It is the
British Open. I love this tournament in a very special way, and I
will do whatever is needed to play in this tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Acutally, Olazabal said, it was commendable that he was able to
restrain himself at Pinehurst until a few hours after the round at
the U.S. Open, where he shot 4-over for the final four holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I did pretty well holding my emotions on the golf
course and on the driving range and on the putting green,'' he
said. ``I was just on my own in the room, and I could express
myself freely at that time. That's why it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal was partnered with Miguel Angel Jimenez in their
practice round and lost a match at the 18th hole against
19-year-old Sergio Garcia and Miguel Angel Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very usual these days,'' Olazabal said.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar fails to qualify
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech's Matt Kuchar shot a round of 3-over 74 Monday at
the Monifieth Links and missed qualifying for the British Open by
eight shots. Kuchar had a 36-hole score of 3-over 145. Among those
making it were Canadian Mike Weir (71-66_137) and American Len
Mattiace (69-68_137).
</P>
<P>
   ``I played well, but I struggled with my putting,'' Kuchar said.
``It was one of those rounds where it just would not go in. I knew
I needed a good score just to qualify.''
</P>
<P>
   The local wildlife caused a change in the playoff plans for
those at 138 who were trying for an alternate spot. Monifeith's
first hole was not used because of a flock of swans on the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Notes
</P>
<P>
   Boosted by his Loch Lomond victory Sunday on the western side of
Scotland, Colin Montgomerie said Monday, ``It would be a dream
scenario to win any major, never mind in Scotland.'' Montgomerie
thinks a winning score of 300 to be highly possible if conditions
turn severely windy. ``If (Monday's breeze) becomes a wind,'' he
said, ``you'll see scores higher than we've ever, ever seen in any
British Open.''. . .
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson, who won here in 1975 with hardly any rough and
baked-out fairways, envisions a winning score ``well over par.''
Watson said, ``If we get the blow they're expecting Thursday, there
may be some real tears out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
