<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-BONUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    World Cup team gets bigger bonus
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Beneath the smiles of U.S. women's soccer players
during a victory parade at Disneyland on Sunday was the
satisfaction that their good deeds would be rewarded with cold hard
cash.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to past wranglings with both the women's and men's
national teams, the U.S. Soccer Federation is increasing its bonus
pool from $250,000 to $1 million for the Americans' win over China
Saturday in the Women's World Cup final.
</P>
<P>
   The 20 players will be paid $50,000 each, on top of salaries
during World Cup preparations that ranged from $25,000 to $45,000.
Earlier, the bonuses has been announced to be roughly $12,500 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the culmination of 25 years of hard work at the grass
roots,'' federation president Bob Contiguglia said. ``We think this
(U.S. win) will increase the interest of soccer and the beauty and
enjoyment of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The federation and Women's World Cup officials decided to
increase the pot after determining that the tournament would earn
as much as $7 million in profits.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. women's players were shocked by the announcement. Before
last year's U.S. Women's Cup, they threatened to boycott over
salaries. They had issued a similar challenge before the 1996
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The federation insisted on paying them a bonus only if they won
the gold medal, but players wanted to be paid for earning any
medal. The difference was moot after the Americans took the gold in
Athens.
</P>
<P>
   The only player unable to cash in is reserve defender Lorrie
Fair, who has a season of eligibility remaining at the University
of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
