<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-INS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUSTOMS FACES BUDGET CRUNCH, CUTS OVERTIME ON BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ Faced with a budget crunch, the Immigration and
Naturalization Service has cut the number of inspectors working
weekends and holidays at already-crowded border crossing points,
officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The reduction, which affects the Texas and New Mexico borders
with Mexico, means travelers crossing border bridges face more
congestion and delays, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The impact was felt here Sunday when three of the nine lanes at
the main international bridge from Nuevo Laredo, Mexico, were
closed, said Gene Garza, port director in Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   With three months left in the government's fiscal year, the INS,
which shares border duties with the Customs Service, has had to cut
overtime pay for inspectors at all ports of entry in Texas and New
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Since overtime pays for much of weekend and holiday shifts,
fewer traffic lanes will be open, forcing vehicles to vie for
whatever number of inspection booths are open.
</P>
<P>
   The problem surfaced Monday when Laredo Mayor Betty Flores
publicly appealed to federal officials for more money to keep all
the lanes open and staffed.
</P>
<P>
   Flores, who spoke at the dedication of a Union Pacific Railroad
inspection facility, caught INS officials by surprise, and most of
those quizzed about what she had said were reluctant to explain the
development or elaborate on the impact.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the mayor's appeal, Mariela Malero, an INS
spokeswoman in Dallas, would only say, ``We continue to work with
headquarters and regional offices to address all the
possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Malero declined comment on what led to the budget crunch or
specifics on its impact, but she said authorities are looking for
ways to make ends meet for the region's 25 ports of entry.
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol, which is part of the INS, won't be affected,
officials said. The immigration service is part of the Justice
Department, while Customs is a branch of the Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second budget crunch for the INS this year.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the agency cut back on everything from overtime to
gasoline due a shortfall caused by a failure to predict rising
rent, phone costs and other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The latest cutbacks went into effect Friday and boosted waiting
time to enter the United States in El Paso as well as Laredo, the
busiest commercial crossing point on the U.S.-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   The typical wait Sunday was 90 minutes as compared with 35
minutes over the July 4 weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Reba, head of the U.S. Customs Service in South Texas,
said her inspectors would continue to work weekend and holiday
shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The INS is short on overtime money,'' Reba said. ``We are
fine, but we cannot make up the difference'' in staffing on the
bridges.
</P>
<P>
   The INS's financial woes come in the wake of a General
Accounting Office report that said bridges and highways along the
U.S.-Mexico border are becoming increasingly congested due to
stepped-up inspections by federal agents hunting drugs and
undocumented immigrants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
