<HEADLINE>
THE `PEONY,' JUST LIKE THE PHOENIX, LIVES ANEW
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036. 
(md) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``A difficult story to tell,'' Du Liniang says in
Scene 48 of ``The Peony Pavilion,'' the classic Chinese opera that
is the centerpiece of the Lincoln Center Festival this summer, as
it was to have been a year ago. And she refers merely to her own
adventures as heroine, in which, restored to mundane reality after
experiencing glorious first love in a dream, she wastes away to her
death only to be resurrected three years later by a return of love
from her dream partner, the young scholar Liu Mengmei.
</P>
<P>
   The tale of Chen Shi-Zheng's complete production of the work,
which was left for dead by bureaucrats in Shanghai last year only
to rise from the ashes, is hardly less wondrous and contorted. And
although Lincoln Center declared and celebrated victory after the
first of the production's six parts had opened the festival on
Wednesday, complete triumph was by no means assured until Saturday
night, when all 19 hours (1 less than advertised) had passed.
</P>
<P>
   For however much the opera may transcend the laws of nature and
the production may finally have eluded the grasp of politicians,
there was still the matter of sheer human frailty. Because of the
great length and difficulty of several roles, and the four months
of intensive rehearsal that were required, the lead actors are
working without understudies.
</P>
<P>
   Qian Yi as Du Liniang, in particular, appears in 20 of the
work's 55 scenes, generally the longer ones, which she typically
dominates. (The number would be 21 but for Chen's injection of
storytelling in a style called Pingtan in two scenes, including one
in which Du Liniang paints a self-portrait; here the scene is
related by an uncostumed narrator rather than acted.) And Ms. Qian,
one of two performers Chen deemed essential to the production and
spirited away from his troupe of last year, the Shanghai Kunqu
Opera Company, developed a thyroid condition during the winter that
sapped her energy and hampered her singing during the early
rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has been corrected by medication, but even now, it
is said, Ms. Qian tires easily. Not that anyone could have guessed
such a thing from her radiant and energetic performance throughout
the six segments. If her lovely voice seemed small at times in the
965-seat La Guardia Concert Hall, especially in her lower register,
she was not alone, and miking was applied widely, though with far
greater subtlety than any done in Broadway theaters.
</P>
<P>
   In another rehearsal mishap, Luo Wen Shuai, a comic actor and
tumbler, ruptured an Achilles tendon, and this left a bigger mark
on the performances, cutting back on their brilliant acrobatics. At
that, however, Luo, with the energy, versatility and sheer feat of
memorization required of all the performers here, plays ``Scholar
Han, Scabby Turtle, Innkeeper, 13 others,'' as the program
laconically reports.
</P>
<P>
   Zhou Ming, the flutist and orchestra leader and the other
performer retained from Shanghai, met with another sort of natural
frailty during rehearsals, when the dry climate at Jacob's Pillow
in the Berkshire Hills of Massachusetts caused many of his bamboo
instruments, long steeped in Shanghai humidity, to crack. They were
repaired and others supplied, and he is putting on a display of
musical refinement and physical stamina as remarkable as Ms.
Qian's, playing all but constantly through the 19 hours, tracing
the melodies of most arias in unison.
</P>
<P>
   Chen gathered the other performers from the United States as
well as from China, where all were born. Compared with the original
Shanghai cast, as glimpsed in rehearsal and in a video of the dress
rehearsal last year, the new cast proved stronger at salient
points. The Liu Mengmei of Wen Yu Hang was sympathetic and
compelling even when the character seemed willfully obtuse or
obstinate; Jia Yong Hong was charming as Du Liniang's maid, Spring
Fragrance (and ``Prostitute, Elder, eight others''), and the
Pingtan storyteller, Hua Meng, was superb.
</P>
<P>
   Other aspects may have been weaker, in part because this company
rehearsed a mere four months (some members less) in contrast to the
eight months in Shanghai. But all of that was incidental to the
magnificent spectacle crossing the stage: a spectacle imagined in
the first place by Tang Xianzu, who wrote ``The Peony Pavilion'' in
1598, and reimagined by Chen.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even so well versed an authority as Su Zheng, who teaches music
and women's studies at Wesleyan University and is a performer and
scholar of Chinese music, expressed her astonishment at finding the
work to be so much more than a love story. ``It is a whole social
critique,'' Ms. Zheng said, ``showing what life, what Ming society
was about.''
</P>
<P>
   She spoke at a daylong symposium, ``Who Owns Culture,'' offered
on Sunday in the Kaplan Penthouse at Lincoln Center in response to
the collapse of the presentation last year, and she was
enlightening on that subject as well. Without defending the actions
of the Shanghai Municipal Bureau of Culture, which at the last
minute denied the Shanghai company permission to leave China, Ms.
Zheng suggested that since most of China's encounters with the West
over the last 150 years have had painful consequences for China,
the authorities there tend to want to control any new relationship.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the symposium, sponsored by the New School as well
as Lincoln Center, was admirably free of self-congratulation on the
center's part and thorough in its attempt to determine what issues
lay behind the fracas. What was said at the time was that Chen's
production was ``pornographic, feudal and superstitious.'' (Such
charges related particularly to Part 2, where _ in Tang Xianzu's
text as well as Chen's production _ the sexually impenetrable
Sister Stone bawdily describes the fiasco of her wedding night, and
where Chen introduces ancient Chinese folk rituals, including the
burning of effigies, into the scene of Du Liniang's death and
funeral.)
</P>
<P>
   Broader political issues may have been at stake as well, with
the naturalized American Chen returning to work in China. Narrower
esthetic ones surely were. The Shanghai culture bureau considers
itself the guardian of kunqu, the most venerable form of Chinese
opera, which grew up in the region around Shanghai and adopted
``The Peony Pavilion'' as its signature work. Chen's production, it
was said, misrepresented kunqu style.
</P>
<P>
   But although he was working with a kunqu company, Chen never
disguised the fact that he was presenting his own interpretation of
the opera, drawing as much on the reconstructionist philosophy of
the Western early-music movement as on the kunqu tradition of
today. Nor was he trying to show what a specific past performance
might have been like.
</P>
<P>
   Chen always said that his goal was to present ``the best of
China,'' old and new: among other things, the splendid costumes,
set and surroundings, all handmade in China. The same generosity of
spirit led him to want to show off other aspects of Chinese
operatic tradition and civilization, like the Pingtan storytelling
and the folk rites along with more contemporary elements.
</P>
<P>
   With all the resources at his disposal, Chen wrestled a work
hardly ever performed in more than isolated excerpts into full,
vivid, blooming life. The end result bears little kinship to most
products of the early-music movement, although it shows, perhaps, a
route Western early-musickers  &UR; should &LR;  have taken. It undoubtedly
offers much to offend purists of whatever stripe, but it spoke
eloquently to at least one nonspecialist admirer of Chinese opera.
</P>
<P>
   Now, finally a reality, the production can look ahead to
repeated performances at Lincoln Center (two parts per day on each
of the next two weekends), in Europe (this fall and perhaps next
summer) and maybe elsewhere. To Chen and his hardy troupe, these
must all look like so many blank pages on which to inscribe new
adventures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
