<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME, SWEET HOME, BUT ONLY FOR BUREAUCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the aftermath of last week's revelation about
the off-limits Crystal Springs Watershed _ that there are eight
homes lived in nearly rent-free by employees and supervisors of the
San Francisco Water Department _ other prominent water agencies
around the Bay Area said such a thing would never be permitted on
their lands.
</P>
<P>
   In the East Bay, there are no homes on watershed lands managed
by the East Bay Municipal Utility District, said the agency's
Charles Hardy. That includes the off-limit gem of the East Bay
hills, Upper San Leandro Reservoir, a jewel of a lake that is
surrounded by 18,600 acres, about half owned by EBMUD.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rangers have their own homes off the property,'' Hardy
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Marin Water District lands, there are also no homes but
rather what are described as ``ranger quarters,'' simple and
primitive compared to the homes in San Francisco. Watershed lands.
There are five ranger quarters over the course of 18,500 acres in
Marin, where there is public access on the watershed lands for
hiking, biking, horseback riding and fishing at lakes from shore.
</P>
<P>
   None of the ranger quarters in Marin even remotely resembles the
beautiful ranch-style homes and cottages set near different lakes
at Crystal Springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ranger quarters are there for public safety,'' said Libby
Pischel of the Marin Water District. ``Having trained staff on site
saves us a tremendous amount of time, things like search-and-rescue
and dealing with fire danger.''
</P>
<P>
   The Crystal Springs Watershed is a 23,000-acre parcel on the
Peninsula, located just south of Sweeney Ridge in San Bruno, where
there are four beautiful lakes and miles of service roads that
could provide a pristine park-like setting for public recreation.
The lakes are Upper and Lower Crystal Springs and San Andreas lake,
which can be seen from Highway 280, and Pilarcitos, tucked in a
canyon on the southeast flank of Montara Mountain, out of public
view.
</P>
<P>
   The route for the Bay Ridge Trail is planned for two existing
service roads from Sweeney Ridge to the junction of highways 92 and
35 but has been stonewalled for years by the Water Department. A
final environmental document that addresses the Bay Ridge Trail at
Crystal Springs will be released later this year, probably in
September, at which time the public will be able to provide
comments.
</P>
<P>
   The lakes could also provide dream-like settings for fishing.
</P>
<P>
   The best comparative example is at Barrett Lake near San Diego,
which was off-limits to the public for 26 years and faced similar
concerns over impacts from use. The lake is now open two days per
week, six months per year, with a reservation service and quota of
anglers drawn by lottery if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing is catch-and-release, no bait is allowed, from boats
equipped with electric motors. The result is simply the best
freshwater fishing for bass and bluegill in the Western United
States.
</P>
<P>
   A similar program could be established at the four lakes at
Crystal Springs. According to a Department of Fish and Game fish
census using nets, the lakes on the off-limits watershed are loaded
with wild rainbow trout that range mostly 14 to 20 inches and
bigger, and scads of bass in the 3-pound class.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Water Department has blocked every attempt to
establish a fishing program or hiking access by a variety of means,
usually by simply ignoring requests. But I predict that at the
least, the Peninsula's 9-mile missing link for the Bay Ridge Trail
will be a go here.
</P>
<P>
   For years, many wondered why the Water Department has been so
adamant in its refusal to grant access.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's clear. The officials didn't want anybody to see their
houses. After all, doesn't it make sense that they just want it all
for themselves?
</P>
</TEXT>
