<HEADLINE>
STOCKS MIXED DESPITE BIG DAY FOR BONDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks were narrowly mixed on light volume Monday,
although the Dow Jones industrial average did edge up to a new
record. The struggle in the stock market came despite a big day in
the bond market, where long-term interest rates fell sharply, with
the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond ending at 5.90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said bonds benefited from a big slide in the Argentine
and Brazilian stock markets. Money flowing out of those markets may
well have sought safe haven in the Treasury market, they said.
</P>
<P>
   But any improvement in interest rates will be short-lived if
reports on producer and consumer prices scheduled for this week are
not friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The producer price data will be an important determinant in
whether bond yields relax further, or are pushed back up,'' said
Thomas Galvin, chief investment strategist at Donaldson Lufkin
Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   The inflation reports, as well as a heavy schedule of corporate
earnings reports expected this week, caused many stock traders to
stay on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern is about earnings, and whether or not
expectations, which are high, will be exceeded,'' said William
Meehan, chief market analyst at Cantor Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many stocks, especially technology shares, have had huge moves
in advance of these reports. Unless a company really blows past the
estimates, I expect we might see some profit-taking when the
numbers are announced.''
</P>
<P>
   Helped by a gain of 1 3/4, to 53 1/2, in International Paper,
which is scheduled to release its second-quarter earnings Tuesday,
the Dow rose 7.28, or 0.1 percent, to 11,200.98, although broader
market measures slipped.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index slipped 4.18 points, or 0.3
percent, to 1,399.10. Declines in General Electric and America
Online shares more than offset gains in technology issues like
Lucent Technologies, Microsoft and MCI/Worldcom.
</P>
<P>
   The NASDAQ composite index fell 2.63 points, or 0.1 percent, to
2,790.44. Big declines in Internet stocks like Yahoo! and
Amazon.com pulled the composite index lower.
</P>
<P>
   Small stocks, however, had a decent day. The Russell 2000 index
of small company shares rose 1.32 points, or 0.3 percent, to
459.30.
</P>
<P>
   Volume was sluggish, 668.8 million shares on the New York Stock
Exchange and 970.9 million shares on the NASDAQ market.
</P>
<P>
   Galvin of Donaldson Lufkin said a report expected from Intel
after the market closes Tuesday would also say a great deal about
how technology shares might fare in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to releasing financial data for the second quarter,
Intel is expected to provide an outlook on the next six months.
</P>
<P>
   Galvin said, ``If Intel says Y2k is not an issue, that will
clearly be a positive,'' for the market. Intel shares slipped 13/16
to 65 7/16 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Amgen Inc., the world's largest biotechnology
company, fell 2 5/16, to 67, but were trading at $72.25 in
after-hours trading on the NASDAQ. Citing ``unusual'' trading in
its stock, on Friday the company said it would report
second-quarter results after the market closed Monday, about 10
days ahead of schedule. Profits rose 24 percent to $268 million, or
50 cents a share in the quarter, surpassing both the 41 cents a
share earned a year earlier and Wall Street expectations for 46
cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Eastman Kodak, a Dow component, gained 2 11/16, to 72 13/16,
after an analyst at Warburg Dillon Read raised his rating on the
photography company to ``buy'' from ``hold.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
