A7349 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-EARNINGS-COX     07-12 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CCE increases expense estimates of European problems
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Enterprises said the massive recall of its
soft drinks because of the European health scare will cost $103
million _ $43 million more than it originally estimated.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based bottler said Monday that the recall involved
17 million cases, instead of the 14 million initially forecast.
</P>
<P>
   That is partially because European consumers had a larger
inventory of products in their homes than anticipated. As a result,
more beverages had to be recalled and destroyed, thus raising the
costs.
</P>
<P>
   President and Chief Executive Henry Schimberg, however, saw a
silver lining.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unexpectedly high level of in-home product inventory
returned speaks to the popularity and penetration of our brands,''
Schimberg said in a statement. ``This popularity gives us
confidence that, as we continue to work closely with our customers
and the government authorities to finalize these issues, we will be
successful in restoring the full faith and confidence of consumers
throughout Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   CCE owns the two plants in Belgium and France that produced the
beverages blamed for nearly 250 illnesses in Belgium last month.
The scare that resulted spread to several other European nations,
which imposed full or partial bans of Coca-Cola products. Those
restrictions have been lifted.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in the one-time charge in CCE's second quarter does
not include the additional impact of the recall on sales, cash
operating profit and earnings per share.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts polled by First Call Corp. estimate the
company will earn 22 cents a share in the quarter, down from 27
cents a year ago. The estimate excludes the effect of the recall's
non-recurring charge, which would amount to a reduction of another
16 cents a share. But insurance may offset some of the costs.
</P>
<P>
   CCE, which is the world's largest soft-drink bottler, is
expected to report second-quarter earnings on July 20. Coca-Cola
Co., which owns 40 percent of CCE, is expected to report its
earnings Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   CCE, which made its announcement after the market closed Monday,
fell 25 cents at $30.75. Coca-Cola ended the day down 56 1/4 cents
at $63.06 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the financial effect of the health scare on both
companies is likely to extend into the third quarter. But Schimberg
said ``the situation will not materially affect financial results
in the year 2000 and beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
