<SLUG> BC-NETWORKS-NAACP-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAACP THREATENS BOYCOTT OVER DEARTH OF BLACK CHARACTERS ON TV 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pointing out that not a single prime-time show among
26 to be introduced on the major broadcast networks this fall has
an ethnic minority character in a leading role, the president of
the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
Monday announced the start of a campaign to pressure both networks
and advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   The president, Kweisi Mfume, said the NAACP would open a
Hollywood office in October to conduct a long-term monitoring and
lobbying campaign of the television and film industries' progress
on integrating both their acting corps and their behind-the-scenes
production staffs.
</P>
<P>
   Mfume said the effort was likely to lead to a call for boycotts
of shows that remain racially segregated and of sponsors who
advertise on the shows. But first, he said, he has asked to meet
with the top executives of the four major networks _ ABC, CBS, Fox
and NBC _ to discuss the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will certainly have conversations with these executives and
with advertising executives,'' Mfume said in an interview after
making his keynote address to the NAACP's 90th annual convention in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as sure as I'm standing here, you can bet it's going to
come down to that,'' he said, referring to a boycott.
</P>
<P>
   In his address before more than 2,500 conventioneers, Mfume also
announced that the organization would file a federal class-action
lawsuit against handgun manufacturers and distributors, seeking
injunctive relief that would, in effect, regulate the marketing of
firearms more tightly.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Mfume and several lawyers involved in the suit said
they would file it by the end of this week in the U.S. District
Court for the Eastern District, in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The four networks issued statements Monday that essentially said
they had room for improvement in addressing the NAACP's concerns,
and would continue to try harder.
</P>
<P>
   The question of how to get broader ethnic representation in
television shows presents programmers with two options: to develop
shows about minority characters, or to include more minority
characters in shows that then become ethnically diverse.
</P>
<P>
   Some advertisers have resisted programs about minority
characters, believing that such programs will not be watched by
affluent white audiences (with exceptions, like ``Cosby'' on CBS).
</P>
<P>
   And some argue that even a ``real-life'' proportion of minority
characters (African-Americans make up 13 percent of the American
population) will rebuff some white viewers. That has not been a
problem with popular dramas like ``NYPD Blue,'' ``ER'' or ``Law and
Order.'' But comedies seem to fall more readily into categories of
white or black appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, cable networks can succeed with much smaller
audiences, and more and more of them are appealing to particular
groups, defined not only by race but by age, class or
special-interest. Broadcast networks are trying to hold onto their
audience share in this fragmenting world and keep advertising
revenue high, which means appealing to upper-middle-class
Americans, who are especially coveted by advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertisers are interested in demographics, but it doesn't
necessarily have to do with race,'' said Doug Alligood, senior vice
president, special markets for BBDO New York, a major advertising
agency. ``They might say a show is too low-rated in the demographic
I want, in terms of education or income level, for example.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he was not including UPN and WB, the relatively new
five-night-a-week networks, Mfume said, ``Because the Big Four are
the Big Four, and if we are successful with them, the others will
get the message real quick.''
</P>
<P>
   WB and UPN recently, and Fox about 10 years ago, have tried to
gain a foothold by appealing to black viewers, who did not find
many shows with black central characters elsewhere on television.
Once successful, they cut back on black shows or, as WB has done,
confine them to one night of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Alligood and Mfume also said programmers are often influenced by
what they find appealing, and most programming and advertising
executives are white. But Mfume pointed out that, in the 1970s and
1980s, there were more multiracial casts, without apparent
advertising repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see slippage now,'' Mfume said, ``and we need to find out
how to make sure it does not keep sliding back.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fox has no prime-time shows, returning or new, with lead
characters who are not white. One new show, a police drama called
``Ryan Caulfield,'' will have a black captain and desk sergeant,
Fox said, and its new science-fiction drama, ``Harsh Realm,'' has a
Hispanic villain.
</P>
<P>
   Fox does have one returning show (not scheduled to resume until
January) about a black family, a cartoon show called ``The PJ's,''
which has been criticized by Spike Lee and others as buffoonish.
</P>
<P>
   CBS has the best record on integrated casts, with nine returning
shows that feature black or other ethnic minority characters in
lead roles, and CBS's made-for-television movies have regularly
featured black or Hispanic themes. A new hospital drama ``City of
Angels,'' coming in January, will have an almost entirely
African-American and Hispanic-American cast.
</P>
<P>
   NBC had just one new show with a non-white main character,
``Third Watch,'' about an overnight police and fire-rescue squad in
New York, and is adding a black main character to its popular
police drama ``Law and Order.''
</P>
<P>
   One of NBC's most touted new shows, ``West Wing,'' is a drama
about the White House under a liberal Democratic administration,
yet its cast is virtually all white.
</P>
<P>
   ABC has one show about a black family, ``The Hughleys'' (they
live in a white suburb); main characters who are black on ``The
Practice,'' and secondary but regular black characters in a handful
of other returning shows. One new show, ``Snoops,'' about four
detectives, includes one black female among the four.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
