<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-GOVERN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR UNVEILS BELFAST GOVERNANCE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ As part of his last ditch effort to save the Northern
Ireland political settlement, British Prime Minister Tony Blair
Monday unveiled the legislation he said will guarantee that neither
pro-British unionists nor Irish republicans can renege on their
obligations under the Good Friday Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as they read the bill, both the Ulster Unionists,
who represent middle-class Protestants in Northern Ireland, and
Sinn Fein, which has links with the Irish Republican Army, said
they wanted it changed, claiming it was slanted toward the other
side.
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop of political brinksmanship, a contentious
Protestant parade passed off peacefully in Belfast Monday in what
British and Irish officials hope was a good omen for the resolution
of a dispute that has stalled the peace process and the return of
local government to Northern Ireland after 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   Marchers from the Orange Order were prevented by the police and
British army from parading through a Catholic neighborhood in south
Belfast to commemorate the day in 1690 when Protestant King William
of Orange defeated the Catholic forces of King James II.
</P>
<P>
   Showcasing its new policy of restrained, token protest for the
second time in eight days, the Orange Order steered 20,000 of its
members to a nearby park to stage a rally. Last week, a similar
token protest was held in Portadown, where the Orange Order was
prevented from marching through a Catholic neighborhood, and where
rioting has flared for the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from more than an hour of talks with Blair at 10
Downing St., Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble said he would
propose amendments to the bill when it is debated in the House of
Commons Tuesday. He said the bill lacked specific language that
would call for Sinn Fein's exclusion from the Northern Ireland
Assembly if the IRA fails to disarm.
</P>
<P>
   But Sinn Fein assembly member Alex Maskey said the bill gives
unionists a veto not included in the Good Friday Agreement of April
1998, which is on the verge of collapse because unionists refuse to
form a local power-sharing government with republicans until the
IRA begins to disarm.
</P>
<P>
   Blair wants to rush legislation through Parliament this week to
ensure that power is transferred from London to the new Northern
Ireland Assembly. But to do that, unionists have to agree to sit in
the 12-person Cabinet with two members of Sinn Fein by Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it broke with tradition this month and openly called
for the IRA to begin disarming, Sinn Fein argues it won its seats
in an election and cannot be excluded from government because of
the IRA's actions.
</P>
<P>
   The unionists, meanwhile, argue that the assembly should not be
dissolved if the IRA fails to live up to its obligation to disarm
under the Good Friday Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The bill unveiled Monday seeks to balance those two positions.
It says the institutions created by the agreement would be
suspended if either the unionists fail to sit in government or the
IRA begins to disarm. But rather than simply suspend the assembly,
the bill calls for a debate to determine what went wrong, and for
the assembly itself to decide whether it will continue if Sinn Fein
is excluded.
</P>
<P>
   That last provision effectively gives the largest Irish
nationalist party, the Social Democratic and Labor Party, the power
to decide whether Sinn Fein could stay and the assembly would
continue if the IRA refuses to disarm. The unionists have been
asking the SDLP and its leader, John Hume, to publicly declare what
it would do if the IRA does not disarm. But Hume, who last year
shared the Nobel Peace Prize with Trimble, has refused to take a
categorical position.
</P>
<P>
   With a huge majority in the House of Commons, Blair plans to
push the bill through the lower chamber Tuesday and get it through
the House of Lords by Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But all that hinges on Trimble's decision, which is expected
Wednesday night. If the unionists accept the plan, the Cabinet
would be named on Thursday, with full powers devolved to Belfast by
Sunday. By next week, the IRA would have been expected to appointed
one of its members to liase with John de Chastelain, a retired
Canadian general in charge of the commission that will oversee the
disarming of paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   The bill says that if de Chastelain decides any of the
paramilitary groups are failing to disarm, he would notify
Secretary of State Mo Mowlam, who would then suspend the assembly,
putting into motion a series of events that would force the
politicians themselves to decide whether to scrap the peace
process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 1954EDT &QL; 
