<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-CARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE BEGINS DEBATE ON MANAGED CARE HEALTH BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With health care protections for millions of
consumers at stake, the Senate Monday opened a critical debate over
patients' rights amid a multimillion-dollar advertising war and a
scramble by both parties to profit from the politically explosive
showdown.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle set off a swirl of medical horror stories,
parliamentary gamesmanship and dueling rallies, as Senate Democrats
pressed the most extensive plan to overhaul the nation's health
care system since President Clinton's failed effort in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the debate is who controls the delivery of
medical care in managed health systems: a patient's doctor or the
patient's insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of both parties cited flaws in the current system, as
the four-day debate unfolded. Yet party leaders agreed on little
else but the title of their competing measures: ``The Patients'
Bill of Rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy, the chief architect of the Democrat
plan, insisted during a flurry of speeches at rallies, news
conferences and his Senate podium that the managed-care system
could be substantially improved for the cost of ``one Big Mac'' a
month for each American worker. But one of Kennedy's leading GOP
critics, Senator Phil Gramm of Texas, said the Democratic proposal
would cost $72 billion, enough ``to buy every McDonald's franchise
in America'' _ assertions Kennedy vehemently denied.
</P>
<P>
   The battle is scheduled to end Thursday when Republican leaders
force a vote on their measure. Until then, Democrats said, they
will offer amendments aimed at forcing senators to cast votes on
such politically explosive issues as whether to broaden the rights
of patients to sue their insurance providers over the quality of
their care.
</P>
<P>
   The votes, in many cases, could be used as ammunition in the
2000 elections. ``The American people deserve to know exactly where
every senator stands on each of these protections,'' said the
Senate minority leader, Thomas A. Daschle.
</P>
<P>
   With extraordinary stakes for a number of special interests,
from insurance companies to trial lawyers, the insurance industry
launched a $9 million ad campaign to try to influence the vote.
Firing back in their own multimillion-dollar effort were the
AFL-CIO and the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The media blitz is the most extensive since last year's Senate
debate over regulating the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton is expected to campaign for the Democratic
plan in a rally Tuesday at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   By nearly every standard, the Democratic measure vastly differs
from the Republican plan to overhaul the health care system.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders, citing concern about rising medical costs, oppose
the Democratic push to broaden the right for patients to sue to
obtain ``medically necessary'' care. Instead, Republicans favor a
plan to establish new consumer protections, including an appeals
process aimed at guaranteeing that patients have access to the
primary care physicians and specialists they need.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP plan also would expand access to emergency rooms,
medications and physicians who are outside a defined network.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say their plan would increase insurance premiums by
less than 1 percent, while the Democratic measure would boost
insurance costs by 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats criticized the GOP proposal for covering only the 48
million Americans who are covered by ``self-funded'' plans, which
are run by employers rather than insurance companies. The
Democratic plan would apply to 161 million Americans, including
those in health maintenance organizations, and state and municipal
health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans assert that federal regulations are not needed for
members of HMOs and state and municipal plans because they already
are regulated by state laws, a position shared by the insurance
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, citing HMOs as a vast source of patient complaints
about access to care, accused GOP leaders of promoting ``a license
for continued HMO abuses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a phony bill, a cynical bill, a minimalist bill, a bill
bought and paid for by the insurance industry,'' Kennedy said on
the Senate floor. He further blasted the measure as ``a bill of
wrongs ... an industry profit protection plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Judd Gregg, a New Hampshire Republican, countered that
the Democratic plan to expand the rights of patients to sue their
insurers is little more than ``a lawyers' annuity plan.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of provisions in the competing measures are similar in
principle, such as improving access for women to Ob-Gyn doctors.
But the Democratic plan would apply to about 50 million more women
than the more limited GOP proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic measure also would require health plans to cover
overnight hospital stays for women who undergo mastectomies and to
pay for routine health care costs associated with clinical trials.
The Republican plan does not address the mastectomy issue and calls
for a study of the clinical trial question.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders said their final package, which is expected to pass
the Senate, will include increased tax deductions for health
insurance costs, an initiative not included in the Democratic plan.
</P>
<P>
   As both sides jockeyed for an edge Monday, they engaged in a
series of complicated procedural ploys that Kennedy, a master of
Senate rules, described as ``parliamentary gymnastics.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, leaders in both parties were uncertain whether
they were actually debating the Democratic or Republican
alternative. ``Let's just say we're debating health care policy,''
said a senior Republican aide.
</P>
<P>
   The first votes on Democratic amendments are likely to occur
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
