<HEADER>
A7355 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUFFY-FINALE13-COX     07-12 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUFFY-FINALE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Buffy' revampeds finale
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally, the finale.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, the WB decided to postpone the highly
anticipated season-ender of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' because it
dealt with high school violence and would have aired right at
graduation time, following the shootings in Littleton and Conyers.
A lot of ``Buffy'' buffs were outraged and flooded the WB with
protest phone calls and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   A lively black market even sprang up on the Internet and at
conventions like Atlanta's DragonCon selling bootlegs copies of the
finale, which had aired in Canada as scheduled. ($20 a copy was the
going rate.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffy'' has garnered such a devoted audience because it takes
ordinary issues of adolescence _ love, sex, friendship, midterms _
and elevates them by overlaying a series of Armageddonish battles
between Good (Buffy and her buds) and Evil (vampires, demons, a
mayor who's scheduled to turn into a 60-foot serpent during
commencement). Although it could be ridiculous, instead ``Buffy''
has much more emotional resonance than more realistic shows.
</P>
<P>
   But the finale was painted into a corner, first by the long wait
(imposed by the WB) and also by depending on computer-generated
special effects. For months, the series has been building up to the
moment when the mayor of Sunnydale turns into the serpent, and when
he finally does, it's obvious that it was done on a TV budget
rather than a feature-film budget. In the summer of the digital
effects in ``The Phantom Menace,'' Mayor Monster looks more like
Mayor McCheesy.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the WB was absolutely correct in not airing this
episode in May. The big dragon, which caught all the flak, wasn't
really the problem; it's how the kids fight the monster, which has
some eerie reverberations of what happened at Columbine High
School.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the climactic battle is not as grand as it might
have been, the ``Buffy'' romantics will still get more than their
fix between our graduating heroine and her forbidden love, the
noble vampire Angel. Angel will be getting a spin-off series in the
fall, so he had to be written out of Buffy's life, but not before
creator Joss Whedon gives them a scene both sexy and sentimental, a
little Rick-and-Ilsa-on-the-runway moment that will have Buffsters
(the ones who didn't pay $20 for a bootleg) all a-swoon.
</P>
<P>
   And so, on to next season. Angel's gone, and Buffy and her
friends have all left high school (boy, have they left high
school), so the show's basic premises are going to undergo a pretty
basic morph. Whedon's a sharp guy who can pull it off, but even if
the worst happens and ``Buffy'' is like the high-school jock who
never lives up the glory of the game-winning touchdown, we'll
always have Sunnydale.
</P>
<P>
   TV REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.''
</P>
<P>
   9?? p.m. on the WB
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
