<HEADLINE>
WHISTLEBLOWERS WARN OF ALASKA PIPELINE DISASTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An environmental disaster worse than the Exxon Valdez oil spill
could happen any day because of corrosion and poor maintenance of
the 800-mile-long Alaskan oil pipeline, warn six employees of the
company, in a detailed, 21-page critique to government officials.
</P>
<P>
   The employees, all with at least 10 years experience who said
they feared retailiation if their names were revealed, allege that
neglect and intimidation of whistleblowers has set the stage for a
rupture of the aging, 22-year-old pipeline that carries crude oil
from Alaska's North Slope to the port at Valdez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be a single gasket, or valve, or wire, or procedure,
or person that will cause the catastrophe,'' wrote the group in
their letter to two members of Congress, Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt, and the lead owner of the pipeline, BP Amoco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a combination of small, perhaps seemingly
inconsequential events and conditions that will lead to the
accident that we're all dreading and powerless to prevent.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1989 Exxon Valdez tanker accident, the worst oil spill in US
history, dumped 10.5 million gallons into Prince William Sound,
killing 250,000 seabirds and costing more than $2 billion to clean
up. But the employees of the pipeline company, called Alyeksa,
believe that a pipeline disaster could be even worse.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest recent leak came in 1996 when 35,000 gallons of oil
escaped, but the whistleblowers said Alyeska habitually neglects
potentially bigger problems, such as a leak from two gas pipelines
that went on for more than a year. They called company
record-keeping ``totally dysfunctional,'' and said managers play
down negative reports to the government.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Joint Pipeline Office, a federal and state
agency that oversees the pipeline, said they are investigating the
charges, but noted they were already familiar with many of the
charges. They said they have issued often-critical reports in
recent years about poor maintenance records and problems with
corrosion of the pipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we think the pipe's unsafe or worn out? Emphatically no,''
said Gary Riemer, deputy pipeline corridor officer at the Joint
Pipeline Office. ``We are trying to look ahead for the next 10, 15,
25 years.'' As a result, he said Alyeska has replaced eight miles
of corroded pipe and inserted miles of sleeving to other pipes.
</P>
<P>
   However, the whistleblowers wrote in their letter that oversight
from the Joint Pipeline Office was ``totally useless.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at BP Amoco, the London-based oil company that owns 50
percent of the pipeline, declined to comment on the letter, saying
they had not reviewed it.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George Miller, D-CA, a longtime critic of pipeline safety
who received the letter, said he was disturbed because Alyeska
officials had recently assured him that they are now more sensitive
to employee concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know why Alyeska employees apparently continue to
fear being sanctioned for signing their names to a letter raising
safety concerns about the pipeline,'' said Miller, who requested a
detailed response from the Joint Pipeline Office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
