<SLUG> BC-MA-MEDCIAL-DEBT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY: MOST TOO POOR TO PAY MEDICAL BILLS ELIGIBLE FOR AID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Most patients whose unpaid medical bills are written
off by hospitals as bad debt are genuinely poor individuals who are
eligible for state medical assistance, a new study reveals.
</P>
<P>
   The study resolves a longstanding debate about the financial
status of ``bad-debt'' patients, said the researchers, and suggests
that many, if not most, of these patients could be enrolled in
free-care programs like Medicaid. This would alleviate the burden
of bad debt on Massachusetts hospitals, which last year amounted to
about $355 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were shocked by the results,'' said Katherine London, a
policy specialist at the Massachusetts Division of Health Care
Finance and Policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The patients were so much poorer than we expected _ the
majority of these patients were below the poverty level,'' said
London.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts provides free care to uninsured and underinsured
patients in several ways. Those who meet low-income qualifications
get treatment at no cost or at reduced rates by hospitals, which
are reimbursed from a state pool at the end of each year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, hospitals are reimbursed for emergency care to
nonpaying patients. However, hospitals must absorb, as bad debt,
unpaid bills for non-emergency treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The study, released Monday and published in the latest issue of
the journal Health Affairs, was done at the behest of a special
commission directed by the state Legislature to scrutinize free
care.
</P>
<P>
   The authors are Joel S. Weissman, an associate professor in
medicine at Massachusetts General Hospital and Harvard Medical
School; Paul Dryfoos, an independent consultant; and London.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest overall message is that when hospitals see these
data, they should realize they can do a better job of enrolling
patients'' in programs for which the hospitals will be repaid _
like the state free-care pool _ or in entitlement programs like
Medicaid, said Weissman.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were previously released to health care providers,
and London said that hospitals already are working harder to screen
patients for Medicaid and free-care eligibility. Along these lines,
hospitals have put up larger and clearer signs to inform patients
about the programs, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hospitals have always argued that they provide more free care
than the government gives them credit for,'' said Andrew Dreyfus, a
spokesman for the Massachusetts Hospital Association. ``This study
shows that a lot of what's written off as bad debt is really free
care,'' for which hospitals should be reimbursed.
</P>
<P>
   But getting people to apply for government programs can be
difficult, Dreyfus said, because of some patients' reluctance to
talk about their incomes, language barriers, and the like.
</P>
<P>
   ``The study tells us that we have a lot of work to do to make
sure we reach every eligible person,'' said Dreyfus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
