A7362 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HISPANICS-     07-12 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HISPANICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEMUNDO APOLOGIZES TO HOUSTON ASTROS OWNER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Telemundo chairman and CEO Roland Hernandez issued a
letter of apology Monday to Houston Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr.
after executives from the local Spanish-language TV station accused
McLane of insensitive remarks about Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, KTMD station manager Marco Camacho reported that
McLane said that Hispanics aren't smart enough to understand
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The story ignited a flurry of controversy in Houston and around
the nation as McLane was compared to then-Cincinnati Reds owner
Marge Schott, who was fined by Major League Baseball and banished
for a year for allegedly using ethnic slurs to refer to blacks and
Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez said he believes that Camacho misunderstood McLane's
comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based upon my inquiry into the matter, and in reliance upon
your representations to me, the outstanding reputation which you
have earned over a long business career, and the high regard in
which you are held by many outstanding individuals in this
country,'' Hernandez wrote McLane, ``I believe that you did not
make any racially motivated comments to our station management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Further, I believe that you and the Houston Astros strongly
support Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please accept my apology, and the apology of Telemundo, for
any difficulties this situation has caused you and your family.''
</P>
<P>
   After receiving the letter, McLane issued a statement praising
Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``His leadership, sincere attitude and integrity made it
possible to right this wrong, and I appreciate his efforts,''
McLane said. ``The untruthful accusations made by their Houston
television station last month have caused great pain and anguish
for me, my family and the Astros organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Camacho declined comment, according to a KTMD spokesperson.
Hernandez said Camacho still maintains that he accurately
interpreted McLane's comments June 3.
</P>
<P>
   But after talking with Camacho, McLane and others in Houston,
Hernandez decided that his Houston station had been in error and
that Camacho misinterpreted the comments.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez said his apology was issued at McLane's request.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez earns $50,000 annually as a director of Wal-Mart, in
which McLane is one of the biggest stockholders. Wal-Mart and
McLane also have close financial ties through a number of
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Securities &AMP; Exchange Commission filings indicate that
Hernandez owned 5,168 shares of Wal-Mart stock March 31. The stock
closed Monday at 47 7/16 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged comments between McLane and KTMD executives came
during McLane's casual conversation with Camacho, two other
Telemundo executives and several other people during a reception
June 3 in Houston. Later that evening, the Houston Advertising
Federation presented McLane its Trailblazer Award for improving
Houston's image with his strong marketing acumen.
</P>
<P>
   Camacho later called his station and had it report that McLane
had made racially motivated comments.
</P>
<P>
   According to the news report, McLane said he does not market to
the Hispanic community because baseball is too complicated for
Hispanics and they don't keep up with the sport because it requires
reading newspapers daily.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said McLane complained that Hispanics buy the
cheaper seats at games and don't buy food at the Houston Astrodome
because they don't like what is served.
</P>
<P>
   The newscast sparked a furor in sectors of Houston's Hispanic
community, which considered a boycott of Astros game.
</P>
<P>
   McLane insisted that he had not put down Hispanics but was
explaining his team's problem attracting new fans.
</P>
<P>
   By June 8, the maelstrom started to die after the Houston
Chronicle reported that two people not associated with the Astros
said they had heard the same conversation and did not believe that
McLane had insulted Hispanics. One observer said she told Camacho
that same night that it would be wrong for his station to air the
report.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath, advertisers threatened to pull commercial
spots from KTMD, the smaller of Houston's two Spanish-language TV
stations. Los Angeles-based Telemundo owns KTMD and six other
Spanish-language TV stations in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On June 11, after several hours of negotiations, Camacho and
McLane issued a joint statement in which Camacho said: ``It is now
clear that Mr. McLane is not biased or insensitive toward the
Hispanic community.''
</P>
<P>
   Camacho added that the two have decided that ``for the good of
the community, we should put this issue behind us and move
forward.'' But Camacho did not specifically retract his statements.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have since given Hispanic leaders a tour of Enron
Field, the team's new field that will open in 2000, and discussed
ways for the club to attract more Hispanic fans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
