<HEADER>
A7364 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      07-12 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: LULL IN FIGHTING
</P>
<P>
   After a weekend of fighting that led President Andres Pastrana
to declare a partial curfew in nearly a third of the country,
government troops and rebel forces kept their distance from each
other. The military claims to have killed more than 200 rebels and
turned back an offensive that began Thursday, but leaders of the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia say they have merely ordered
a break in attacks.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: QUESTIONS ON CAMPAIGN FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   The governing Institutional Revolutionary Party failed to
account fully for $63 million in donations to the 1994 campaign
that brought President Ernesto Zedillo to office, the newspaper
Reforma reported. Based on documents from the agency that oversaw
the vote, the party reported the donations but not the donors. As a
new presidential campaign gets under way, the finances of the last
one are causing controversy because the governing party has blocked
efforts by Congress to examine them.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BELGIUM: COALITION TAKES OFFICE
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 41 years, a coalition government took
office without any members from the Christian Democrats. Guy
Verhofstadt, 46, the new prime minister, will have to try to
balance the interests of Greens, Liberals and Socialists. A food
scare involving dioxins is widely blamed for bringing down the
coalition of Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene last month.
</P>
<P>
   NETHERLANDS: LEGALIZING EUTHANASIA
</P>
<P>
   The government has proposed a change in the law so that doctors
will formally be allowed to end the life of terminally ill patients
or help them in committing suicide. Until now such actions have
remained technically illegal, although in practice these
interventions have been decriminalized since 1993 when Parliament
adopted the stand that they would be tolerated as long as strict
guidelines were met.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: COMPUTER BUG SHORTFALL
</P>
<P>
   The Finance Ministry said its efforts to insulate Russia's
computers against the Year 2000 bug were flagging and were a matter
of growing concern. The government says that although it needs only
$187 million to protect critical systems, even that small sum will
be impossible to find before the New Year, and only a third of
vital computer systems are likely to be Year 2000 compliant _ far
less than the 80 to 85 percent target set only this spring.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   CONGO: U.N. PLEA TO REBELS
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Security Council called on rebel leaders in Congo to
sign the peace accord accepted by other parties to the conflict and
implicitly warned that a peacekeeping force could not be sent there
until they do. Council members ``expressed their dismay'' that the
Congolese Rally for Democracy and the Movement for the Liberation
of the Congo failed to accept the cease-fire plan at a ceremony in
Lusaka, Zambia, and ``strongly urged the rebel leaders to resolve
their differences and sign the agreement as soon as possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
