<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7366 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANDMARK-SHUTDOWN-BOS     07-12 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANDMARK-SHUTDOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANDMARK DECRIES OVERZEALOUSNESS OF BAY STATE REGULATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Customers and officials of Houston-based Landmark
Securities Corp., a nationwide chain of day-trading firms, say they
are launching a campaign to keep the Boston office open after state
regulators moved last week to shut it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're doing is blatantly unfair,'' said Steve McCarthy
of Equity Traders, a company that provides office space and
computer equipment to Landmark in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about us doing anything wrong. This is about
(Massachusetts Secretary of State) Bill Galvin not liking day
trading.''
</P>
<P>
   Galvin's office, which has led the nation in cracking down on
abuses at day-trading firms, filed an administrative complaint
against Landmark last Thursday alleging ``numerous violations'' of
state securities laws. Landmark would be shut down in Boston if it
fails to disprove the allegations at a yet-to-be-scheduled
administrative hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one of Landmark's day-trading customers have now signed a
petition and have sent it to Galvin's office, asking that the
complaint be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely nothing wrong going on in this office,''
said Eric D'Orio, a 27-year-old Landmark customer who signed the
petition. ``If they close this place down, they're taking away my
livelihood. This is how I pay my bills. It infuriates me.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Galvin's office dismissed the petition as
irrelevant and said plans to close the firm will go forward. But
the dispute highlights a growing tension between regulators and
firms that cater to day traders.
</P>
<P>
   Day trading _ which gets its name from the practice of holding
stocks for less than a day _ has become big business across the
country. Firms such as Landmark have sprung up to cater to a
growing number of speculators who trade huge blocks of stock in
transactions that often last only seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Dedicated traders work in boutiques such as Landmark eight hours
a day, five days a week, often performing hundreds of trades a day
in pursuit of profits on miniscule movements in stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   But regulators have warned the practice is little more than
gambling, and that most people don't make the kind of riches
sometimes claimed by the industry. Many inexperienced traders
hoping to tap a vein of stock-market riches have instead found
themselves buried in debt after months of nonstop trading,
regulators have said. Meanwhile, the firms collect large
commissions on the multitude of transactions, whether traders make
money or lose it.
</P>
<P>
   In last week's complaint, Galvin's office alleged Landmark
officials conducted improper loan schemes that funneled cash to
traders running low on funds, enabling them to continue trading and
generating commissions for the firm. The complaint also alleged
that some Landmark officials profited personally from the loans,
which charged ``usurious'' fees.
</P>
<P>
   While regulators have said day traders should be protected from
an industry that in some cases may be exploiting them, McCarthy
said: ``The traders don't want that protection. These guys are here
to to take a risk. It's not the government's business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad they're happy with the treatment they get there,''
Galvin said in an interview after receiving the Landmark petition.
``But it's irrelevant. It doesn't mean they can get away with
violating securities laws. I'm sure there are people who get
usurious loans from loan sharks who are happy, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 2003EDT &QL; 
