u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVIS-SAMPRAS-BOS     07-12 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-SAMPRAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM MEETING TO DETERMINE SAMPRAS' STATUS ON US TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The No. 3 player in the world still insisted Monday
that, barring a teammate's injury, he does not want to be the No. 1
or 2 singles player on the United States Davis Cup squad.
</P>
<P>
   But don't count on Wimbledon men's champion Pete Sampras being
out of that equation when the US lineup is announced by captain Tom
Gullikson before Friday's quarterfinal tie opening matches at
Longwood Cricket Club.
</P>
<P>
   It all depends on the outcome of a team meeting later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Sampras, along with teammates Todd Martin, Jim Courier,
and Alex O'Brien, practiced for the first time as a unit at
Longwood and at nearby Pine Manor College and then, with the Davis
Cup as a prop, met the media at the Westin Copley Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras was not a team member when the US defeated host Great
Britain, 3-2, in the first round in Birmingham, where three of the
four matches went to five sets, including the clincher by Courier
over Greg Rusedski.
</P>
<P>
   But his patriotic juices got to flowing afterward and Sampras
ended a two-year Davis Cup hiatus when he contacted Gullikson about
a doubles spot on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very sensitive being a part of the team,'' Sampras said
Monday. ``What Jim and Todd did in England was an inspiration to
myself. I've had some conversations with Tom and Jim and Todd about
me playing just doubles here and they didn't have a problem with
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the last thing I want to do is jump on the bandwagon. If
Todd or Jim got hurt, then I would play (singles). I think those
guys deserve to play singles and it's their show. I'm just happy to
be part of it. If we get through this tie and I show the commitment
by being here, then I'll play singles in our next round.''
</P>
<P>
   But could that part be expanded sooner than later?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, if that's what a team meeting produces later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete obviously just gave a pretty strong commentary on how he
kind of wanted to come on to the team and it's kind of amazing that
he could be so humble,'' said Gullikson. ``Circumstances do change
and what you heard from Pete was his honest opinion of how things
should work. It's something he truly believes, but unless the other
four guys physically throw him onto the court, I don't know if
he'll play singles here.''
</P>
<P>
   But picture the Red Sox having Ken Griffey in their lineup and
using him as a late-inning defensive replacement. That was a
parallel scenario offered to Gullikson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm not going to force him (Sampras) to play
(singles),'' added Gullikson. ``We're going to have a team
discussion very shortly about the whole thing and just get all the
opinions out on the table. I'm just happy he's back on the team and
where it goes from there, who knows? I'm glad he had a change of
heart and wants to be a part of it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Martin said: ``I've told Tom that I think we should
have our best team out on the court. If I'm not part of that,
that's fine with me. But if Tom feels I should be on the court, I'd
like to be on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Courier, whose game has been jump-started since last fall,
thanks in large part to improved health, said the team discussion
will be held ``in the next few days. We'll sort that out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is to put a competitive team on the playing field and
I think whichever way we go, we'll have a competitive team,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made it very clear to Pete that once you're on the team,
you're on the team . . . We wanted him on the team and there's no
reason for any awkward feelings. It's time to go out and win three
matches before the Australians do, and that's a simple concept.''
</P>
</TEXT>
