<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7375 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALAYSIA-ECON-NYT &LR;      07-12 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA OPENS CYBERJAYA, ITS HIGH-TECH CITY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, Japan, Calif.)   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CYBERJAYA, Malaysia _ When 25 senior executives from technology
companies around the world gathered here last week to tour
Malaysia's Multimedia Super Corridor project, it had all the
appearance of a somewhat dutiful pep rally for a
technology-friendly Southeast Asian leader.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, however, was far from routine _ either in its lush
tropical setting or in the object of the corporate kudos: Mahathir
Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir, the prime minister of Malaysia, has been engaged in
the fight of his life over the last year. As the Asian economic
crisis tore through this normally tranquil country, Mahathir, 73,
imposed widely criticized controls on Malaysia's capital markets,
vilified foreigners for causing Asia's misery, and imprisoned his
popular former deputy, Anwar Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   Many people here feared that the furor would doom Mahathir's
ambitious vision to make Malaysia the technology lodestar of Asia.
The prime minister's actions baffled some members of the panel of
foreign executives that advises him on his flagship project, the
Multimedia Super Corridor, a project that was begun in 1996,
officially opened last Thursday and is expected to take two decades
to complete.
</P>
<P>
   If the three-day meeting to mark the opening did not quite
dispel those fears, it provided a much-needed psychic boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very pleasantly surprised by the amount of progress,
frankly, that has been achieved,'' said Lewis Platt, the chairman
of Hewlett-Packard and one of the executives on the advisory panel.
Platt said he had heard a stream of bad news about Malaysia and the
Super Corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir's grand plan to carve an Asian Silicon Valley out of
vast palm-oil plantations here is not dead _ though it is not
thriving either. While Malaysia has signed up 228 companies to
invest in the Super Corridor, only nine have moved into the
270-square-mile swath of land between Kuala Lumpur and its
futuristic airport. Just one, the accounting firm Arthur Andersen,
is American.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the upbeat remarks of Platt and other executives, most
major foreign companies are still guarded about their commitments.
The slow pace of investment has forced Malaysia to roll back its
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you plan for X number of dollars, and your economy
suddenly shrinks by 6 percent, you have to scale things back,''
said Mohamed Arif Nun, the head of operations at the Multimedia
Development Corp., which runs the venture. ``But it has not
destroyed the integrity of the project.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Malaysia has settled down a bit, Mahathir seems
determined to get things back on track.
</P>
<P>
   In a ceremony inaugurating Cyberjaya, the new city that will be
the heart of the Super Corridor, the prime minister reminded his
visitors that they had 12 months to move their operations into the
area _ or lose a package of tax exemptions and other incentives.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of companies are here now. NTT, the Japanese telephone
giant, just opened a research center, while Alcatel, the French
telecommunications equipment maker, announced plans to open a
facility with 40 engineers. But the big American players _
Hewlett-Packard, IBM, Microsoft and Sun Microsystems among others _
have yet to break ground or even rent office space.
</P>
<P>
   Jaya is a Malay word meaning success, and Cyberjaya's planners
confidently predict that it will someday be home to 240,000 people.
For now, it feels like an ultra-modern ghost town. Roads and
bridges crisscross land that used to be covered by palm trees,
while fiberoptic cable snakes underground.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a new Multimedia University to serve,
Stanford-style, as an academic hothouse for the community. The
school, which opened in May, has 2,600 students and will eventually
enroll 15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Executives here acknowledged that last year's spate of troubles
made the Multimedia Super Corridor a tough sell. Zasmida Abu Samah,
the manager of sales and marketing for Cyberjaya's real estate
developer, said it was difficult to lure new tenants between
January 1998 and last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was very hard,'' she said. ``After January 1998, it
was dead silence. We couldn't get people to call us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zasmida said companies began expressing interest again after
Malaysia was host for the annual meeting of the Asia Pacific
Economic Cooperation forum last November. Although the summit was
rocked by a speech in which Vice President Al Gore rebuked Malaysia
for its suppression of freedoms, it did not degenerate into violent
street protests, as some predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political situation is something we pay close attention
to,'' said Frank Smith, a partner at Ernst &AMP; Young in Singapore.
``But it hasn't been a particularly destabilizing influence on our
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernst &AMP; Young, the accounting and consulting firm, had proposed
to build a regional technology center in Cyberjaya. Although it is
revising the plan, Smith said it still planned to move operations
here. ``We just didn't do it as fast as we planned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir's decision to impose controls on Malaysia's capital
markets last fall was a bigger cause for concern. The move, which
he said was necessary to stabilize Malaysia's currency, the
ringgit, drew harsh criticism. The prime minister aggravated
matters with outbursts against foreign currency traders.
</P>
<P>
   During talks with the executives, Mahathir was questioned about
the policy, according to a panel member. ``He said, `all we did was
fix the currency.''' said this person, who spoke on condition that
he not be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Malaysia can lay all fears to rest, it still faces
formidable rivals. Singapore and Hong Kong are both building
multi-billion-dollar technology parks _ seizing on high-technology
as a ticket out of their own doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps hedging its bets, the Multimedia Development Corp.
announced plans to build a film studio and theme park in Cyberjaya
_ marrying Silicon Valley with Hollywood, according to its
proponents.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the visitors said the all-encompassing nature of the
Multimedia Super Corridor could give it an edge. With plans for
schools, apartments, even golf courses, Cyberjaya is no mere office
park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these other countries are building technology parks to
incubate small companies, which is fine,'' said John Gage, the
chief researcher at Sun Microsystems. ``But Malaysia thinks very,
very differently.''
</P>
<P>
   As he puts a tumultuous year behind him, Mahathir must now hope
that the world will come to share his vaulting vision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
