<SLUG> BC-MA-SENIOR-PHARMACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDIT CITES LOW USE, HIGH COSTS IN SENIOR PHARMACY PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Massachusetts' three-year-old Senior Pharmacy Program,
which the Legislature currently wants to expand, was beset with low
enrollment and excessive management costs during its first 18
months of operation, state auditor A. Joseph DeNucci said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, auditors said, is that the state did not
try hard enough to sign up eligible seniors.
</P>
<P>
   The audit also noted that state officials wildly overestimated
the number of elders Senior Pharmacy could enroll, but spent almost
as much money administering the program as if their projections had
been met.
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal 1997, the program's administrative costs were
$928,313, or 83 percent of its budgeted volume, although the number
of applicants was only 13 percent of the budgeted figure.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Pharmacy is at the center of a current legislative debate
over how to help elders pay the spiraling costs of prescription
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   A House-Senate conference committee is negotiating over budget
bills that would open Senior Pharmacy to a greater number of elders
and increase its benefits. Last week Gov. Paul Cellucci proposed to
replace it with a state-subsidized pharmacy insurance plan
available to all Bay State elders.
</P>
<P>
   State auditors found that the Senior Pharmacy program, designed
in 1996 to help low-income elders pay for prescription drugs, spent
only $9.1 million in fiscal years 1997 and 1998, even though the
Legislature authorized $30 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, 27 percent of the program's expenditures were for
administrative costs. The contractor hired to process Senior
Pharmacy applications, for instance, spent $18 per application in
fiscal 1997, instead of the $3.27 agreed upon in the agency's
contract with the state.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors faulted administrators for not making low-income elders
aware of the program. Senior Pharmacy is currently designed for
those with yearly incomes under $12,360 ($16,590 for a couple). In
addition, administrators did not set target enrollment numbers and
hold contractors accountable for meeting goals, the 22-page audit
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors found a $16,442 mathematical error in state payments to
West Suburban Elder Services, Inc., a nonprofit agency hired to do
Senior Pharmacy enrollment. They also criticized administrators for
granting no-bid contracts totalling $52,445.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson here is that we all have to be realistic about what
can we do that will help people and attract people,'' said Glenn
Briere, a spokesman for DeNucci. ``This just shows that there were
mistakes made in the past that we should learn from.''
</P>
<P>
   Briere added that the audit report is ``not saying that the
state is not able to run this kind of program.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci administration officials defended their management of
Senior Pharmacy, pointing out that the number of elders benefitting
from the program has climbed to nearly 30,000 from the
disappointing first-year enrollment of 16,500. Initially, officials
projected that 60,000 low-income elders would sign up, but they
currently estimate that about 48,000 individuals are eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Despite enrollment growth, the Senior Pharmacy program spent
only $13 million of its $30 million appropriation in fiscal 1999,
which ended July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program is not perfect,'' said Derrek Shulman, a spokesman
for the Executive Office of Elder Affairs, which runs Senior
Pharmacy. ``But any program that starts from scratch as this one
did has problems. We're very proud of how the program is doing and
how it's grown.''
</P>
<P>
   If no changes are made in Senior Pharmacy, state officials
currently project it will enroll about 33,000 elders within the
next year and expend $14.7 million. The program's costs are paid by
an increase in the state cigarette tax earmarked in 1996 for
children's health insurance and Senior Pharmacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
