<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-SEQUENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM TO ACQUIRE SEQUENT COMPUTER SYSTEMS
</HEADLINE>
   (md) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sixteen years ago, 18 engineers and executives left
Intel Corp. to create a new company and a new kind of computer that
would tie together multiple microprocessors, the brains of personal
computers, to achieve power that rivaled conventional minicomputers
and mainframes.
</P>
<P>
   The technology worked, but the company, Sequent Computer
Systems, never really achieved critical mass. On Monday, Sequent
agreed to be acquired by International Business Machines Corp. for
$810 million, or $18 a share in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Sequent will become a subsidiary of IBM, and Sequent's
technology, which allows hundreds of processors to act as one large
computer, will be folded into IBM's server computers, including the
RS 6000 and Netfinity lines.
</P>
<P>
   Sequent shares had traded up in recent weeks as news of the
pending deal leaked, but they closed Monday at $17.281, down .156
cents, in Nasdaq trading. IBM shares closed at 137.8125, up 43.75
cents, on the New York Stock Exchange. Sequent shares had traded as
low at $5.68 in the past 52 weeks as the company's earnings
disappointed Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the deal was an appropriate exit strategy for
Sequent, which despite market-leading technology has struggled to
close sales in competition with far larger rivals. With 1998 sales
of $784.2 million, and 1999 revenue projections not a great deal
higher, Sequent found the $1 billion mark an elusive goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's probably good for both sides,'' said Steven
Milunovich, an analyst with Merrill Lynch. ``Many of us thought
this would have made sense a couple of years ago, but IBM probably
had to get over a bit of not-invented-here attitude. They need a
high-end Intel-based server.''
</P>
<P>
   For IBM, which had earlier partnered with Sequent to create a
new version of the Unix operating system, the acquisition adds to
an already strong selection of high-powered servers. Sequent
frequently won sales bids against Digital Equipment Corp. and
Tandem Computer Corp., both now part of Compaq Computer Corp., as
well as the Hewlett-Packard Co. and Sun Microsystems Inc., all of
which are IBM's major rivals in the server market.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Sequent, the merger addresses the major issues we faced:
size, reach and software availability,'' Casey Powell, Sequent's
founder, chairman and chief executive, said in a telephone
conference call. ``It's been a particular disadvantage to us, a
company that has not yet reached $1 billion in revenues, as we
compete on a daily basis with companies of $40 billion to $50
billion in sales. Now we are part of the largest computer company
in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell will report to Robert M.Stephenson, IBM's senior vice
president and group executive for servers. Stephenson said IBM
would both sell Sequent machines, and fold Sequent's technology,
NUMA, for nonuniform memory access, into its own servers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasingly, customers want servers that can scale quickly to
manage unpredictable workloads or spikes in online traffic,'' he
said. ``NUMA is an elegant solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Sequent has more than 2,500 employees worldwide with 56 sales
offices in North America, Europe and Asia. No layoffs are planned,
and Stephenson said IBM would add more salespeople to its server
group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
