</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEEP-CHEROKEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIMLERCHRYSLER SLOWS PRODUCTION OF JEEPS  
</HEADLINE>
 (md) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ DaimlerChrysler AG is slowing production of the Jeep
Grand Cherokee, a sign that sales of sport utility vehicles may be
growing a little less quickly.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler said Monday that it would eliminate overtime and
shorten shifts at the end of this week at its huge Jefferson North
assembly plant in Detroit. The factory, the sole source of the
Grand Cherokee, will start producing the vehicles at a rate of
294,000 a year, down from a previous annual rate of 354,000, said
Daniel Moore, a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of the Grand Cherokee, which was redesigned for the
current model year, were up 9 percent last month from a year
earlier, and were up 11 percent in the first half of this year from
the same period last year. But the sales still have not met the
company's optimistic forecasts, Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall sales of sport utility vehicles grew 4.2 percent in June
from a year earlier, a strong pace but less brisk than the
segment's 12.3 percent growth rate since the current model year
began last October, according to Morgan &AMP; Co. Inc., a consulting
company in West Olive.
</P>
<P>
   Auto industry officials say that they are not worried. Auto
makers were offering unusually generous discounts a year ago, which
inflated sales in June, 1998, and make the sales since then look
less robust by comparison, said George Pipas, a market analyst at
the Ford Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   Sport utility vehicles ``are still outperforming the industry,
and I would expect them to continue to outperform,'' Pipas said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jefferson North factory will continue to run around the
clock, although with more time for maintenance between shifts. The
three daily shifts will now last seven hours each, with an hour for
maintenance between each shift, Moore said. The shifts have been
lasting seven hours and 48 minutes each; the slower pace of
production was first reported over the weekend by The Detroit Free
Press.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit auto makers are facing much more competition from
foreign rivals, particularly car-like sport utility vehicles being
shipped here from Japan. According to Ward's Automotive Reports, a
weekly trade journal, sport utility vehicle sales by Ford,
DaimlerChrysler and General Motors only rose 1.4 percent in June
from a year earlier, while foreign auto makers' sales of the
vehicles climbed 23.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Jeep Grand Cherokee faces some of the toughest competition,
from such models as the Lexus RX300, which is based on the Toyota
Camry's design.
</P>
<P>
   John Casesa, an auto analyst at Merrill Lynch, said that the
market had changed since DaimlerChrysler decided three years ago to
increase capacity for the new Grand Cherokee. ``There are simply
more alternatives for the consumer today than there were when they
decided on the capacity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sport utility vehicles have faced particularly strong criticism
this summer, with President Clinton calling for tighter limits on
their smog-causing emissions and with environmental groups
demonstrating in large cities to demand tighter regulations. But
Casesa said that it was unclear whether this had affected sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
