<SLUG> BC-CYBER-TRAVEL-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKING THROUGH THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 18)  
(mk) 
 By L.R. SHANNON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you know where you are going and where you want to stay, you
don't need anything more technologically advanced than a hotel's
800 number. If you are more flexible, or less certain, you may be
able to save some money by booking through the Web. There are
almost as many approaches as there are destinations, and this
column touches on just a few. There are still kinks to be worked
out: While airlines and hotels are bracing for electronic bookings,
they are still the exception. Only about 3 percent of independent
travel arrangements are expected to be made online this year,
according to a report issued in May by Jupiter Communications, a
new-media research company based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   With Priceline's service, as almost everybody knows from the
commercials with William Shatner, you enter the price you want to
pay for a room and, if the hotel accepts it, your stay is reserved.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline says it will get back to you within an hour, and if
the accommodations meet your price and date requests, your credit
card is charged immediately. Priceline's Web page guarantees ``that
you'll always stay in a well known, name-brand hotel,'' but there's
a major caveat: You have no choice of hotel (beyond specifying
location and a quality rating of one to five stars) and
reservations cannot be changed or canceled (though the company says
it will try to intervene with the hotel on behalf of the customer
in case of an emergency).
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, the price you propose has to be reasonable, and
Priceline provides a guide giving the usual range of hotel prices
in the destination you choose (1,100 cities, towns and resorts, all
in the United States). There is no point in offering a dollar or
two for a room, and it is certainly not worth the trouble offering
a few dollars less than you would pay if you called the hotel
directly.
</P>
<P>
   Another service, Travelscape.com, offers hotel accommodations in
about 80 cities, mostly in the United States but also in Mexico and
the Bahamas, as well as air and hotel packages. There is no
bidding, but the site guarantees that the rates offered are the
lowest available for the 500 hotels in its system. Travelscape.com
will add another 700 hotels in the next three to four months,
according to Michael Reichartz, a Travelscape.com vice president.
The mix includes a wide variety of both independent establishments
and members of chains, at a range of discounts. ``If there is a
lower rate found for the same dates and hotel booked,
Travelscape.com will refund the difference immediately,'' the site
says. With limitations, the reservations can be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   There are innumerable other services with hotel information and
bookings. They include Travelnow, The Hotel Guide and
Informedtourist.com which links to other booking sites. If you have
a favorite chain of hotels, odds are you can type its name in the
form ``www.nameofchain.com'' and connect to its Web site. I tried
that with Hyatt, Marriott and Ramada, and they all worked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
