s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-ADV18-NYT &LR;      07-12 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVOIDING LONG LINES IN ITALY  
 VANCOUVER FERRY SERVICE  
 REDUCED-PRICE TICKETS IN PARIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 18)  
(mk) 
 By SUZANNE MacNEILLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I will be visiting Rome and Florence and would like some
advice on how to avoid long museum lines. _ Herbert Kelley,
Norfolk, Va.
</P>
<P>
   A. Waiting as long as three hours under the blistering sun (or
pouring rain, for that matter) can be a maddening part of visiting
Italian museums, especially in the busy summer months. But with the
introduction of two reservation services within the past year, it
is now possible to get around the long lines at many museums (but
not, alas, at the Vatican museums).
</P>
<P>
   In Rome, the Phone Reservation and Information Service, (39-06)
328101, allows one to buy tickets to the Borghese Gallery, the
Palazzo Barberini National Gallery of Classical Art, the
archeological site at Ostia Antica, the Spada Gallery, the Corsini
Gallery and the principal monuments in Ravenna and Ferrara. In the
case of the Borghese Gallery and the Palazzo Barberini, the tickets
will be marked with a set time to visit. You can also use the
service to book tickets to the nightly music and dance performances
held at the amphitheater in Ostia Antica.
</P>
<P>
   The service costs about $1 plus the cost of the museum ticket
(between $4.25 and $5.25). Tickets to the Borghese and Barberini
galleries must be picked up at least one hour before the time given
on the ticket; other museum tickets can be picked up at the box
office any time on the booked day. The service operates Monday
through Friday from 9 a.m. to 7 p.m. and Saturday from 9 a.m. to 1
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   In Florence, Firenze Musei, (39-05) 5294883, offers a similar
service for the Uffizi Galleries, the Academy Gallery, the Boboli
Gardens, Vasari's Corridor, which links the Palazzo Vecchio to the
Pitti Palace, the Archeological Museum, the Convent and Museum of
St. Mark, the Bargello Museum, the Semiprecious Stone Workshop, the
Medici Chapels and the Pitti Palace's Silver Museum, Palatina
Gallery and the Gallery of Modern Art. The booking service is
available from 8:30 a.m. to 6:30 p.m. Monday to Friday and from
8:30 a.m. to 12:30 p.m. on Saturday. There is a $1 fee for the
tickets, which can vary from around $2 to $6.50. Set times are
given for all the museums and tickets can be picked up at the
museum's ticket office 15 to 20 minutes before that time.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is Select Italy, a tour operator based in
Wilmette, Ill., and Venice. It offers similar reservation services
at www.selectitaly.com or by calling (847) 853-1661. For example,
the Pitti Palace Pass, valid for the Galleria Palatina, the Museo
deglia Argenti and Boboli Gardens, all in Florence, costs $39.
Reservations for single museums, such as the Borghese Gallery and
the Galleria degli Uffizi are also available, with a $15 service
fee.
</P>
<P>
   If you're planning to see Leonardo da Vinci's ``Last Supper,''
which has been under restoration for more than 20 years, a
reservation is required. Groups of 25 people are admitted into the
refectory of Santa Maria delle Grazie at 15-minute intervals (if
you want to stay longer than 15 minutes you have to pay for another
ticket). Admission is $6.50 plus a $1 booking fee and can be
reserved from 8 a.m. to 8 p.m. by calling (39-02) 89 42 11 46.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver's Fast Ferry
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there high-speed ferry service between Vancouver and
Vancouver Island? _ Leonard Bohman, Fort Myers, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A. Beginning this month, there is such service. BC Ferries'
PacifiCat Explorer, a high-speed catamaran, began operating between
Horseshoe Bay in West Vancouver and Departure Bay in Nanaimo on
Vancouver Island on July 1. The voyage takes an hour and 10 minutes
_ 25 minutes faster than the ride on BC Ferries' other vessels on
that route.
</P>
<P>
   The new catamaran accommodates up to 1,000 passengers and 240
vehicles and travels at speeds of up to 42 mph.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to eight daily departures on conventional ferries,
the Explorer makes three round trips every day except Tuesday and
Wednesdays until July 28; from then until Sept. 12, it will make
three trips daily.
</P>
<P>
   The one-way adult peak-season fare on both the conventional
ferry and the Explorer is about $6.10 and about $3.10 for children
5 to 11 (under 5, free). After Sept. 12, fares drop to $5.80 and
$2.90; winter fares are $5.10 and $2.50 (except between Dec. 16 to
Jan. 2, 2000, when they rise to $5.80 and $3). Cars (excluding
passenger and driver) range from $15.50 to $36, depending on the
size of the vehicle and the season. (These fares have been
converted at $1.46, Canadian, to the U.S. dollar.)
</P>
<P>
   For information: (250) 386-3431 or on the Web at
www.bcferrries.com.
</P>
<P>
   Cheap Tickets in Paris
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there a way to obtain reduced-price tickets to
performances in Paris? _Joanne Olson, Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, at least to some performances. A Paris business called
Le Kiosque Theatre sells tickets at a substantial savings.
Apparently, the two dark red and green kiosks _ one near the Place
de la Madeleine subway station on the west side of the Madeleine
church, the other in front of the main entrance to the Montparnasse
station on Place Raoul Dautry _ are something of a French secret. A
spokeswoman said that only about 5 percent of their tickets are
sold to foreigners. (The clerks, by the way, do speak English.)
</P>
<P>
   Tickets must be purchased on the day of performance. Among the
offerings this summer are: Offenbach's ``Monsieur Choufleuri'' and
``Les Dames des Halles'' at the Theatre Silvia Monfort (tickets
cost $15, compared to $25 at the box office; ``La Folie
d'Isabelle,'' a Comedia del Arte classic performed by the Mysteres
Bouffes company at the Arenes de Montmartre ($8 instead of $11);
and concerts at the Sainte Chapelle on the Ile de Cite ($14 instead
of $23).
</P>
<P>
   Tickets to performances at Paris' principal opera houses _ the
Garnier and the Bastille _ are not sold at the kiosks, although
reduced admission for students, people under 26 or over 60 are
offered at the operas' box offices on the day of performance.
</P>
<P>
   The kiosks are open Tuesday to Saturday, 12:30 p.m. to 8 p.m.
and Sundays from 12:30 to 4 p.m. (closed on Sundays during July and
August). No telephone inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   If you're visiting Paris next year, a ticket to a Thursday
performance at four Paris national theaters _ the Comedie
Francaise, l'Odeon, Le Theatre de Chaillot and Le Theatre de la
Colline _ will cost only $7.75 (instead of $23 to $62).
</P>
</TEXT>
