<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINE STOCK PRICES TUMBLE
</HEADLINE>
  (md) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ The Argentine stock market suffered
its worst session in seven months on Monday, falling 7.7 percent on
concerns that the government deficit is widening and a year-old
recession is deepening.
</P>
<P>
   The broad drop came on the heels of a 4.4 percent decline of the
main stock index on Thursday, the last day of trading before
Friday's Independence Day holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The stock tumble in what was until recently a favorite emerging
market contributed to a selling mood that pulled down stock prices
across Latin America; Brazil's market fell nearly 3 percent and
Mexico's market shed 1.5 percent. The slide in Argentina also
elicited concerns on Wall Street of more potential weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Argentina faces severe challenges as it tries to deal with a
strengthening U.S. dollar, weak agricultural commodity prices and
stagnant global export markets,'' wrote David Malpass, senior
economist at Bear Stearns, in a report Monday. Malpass attributed
the sliding stock prices to ``shortfalls in tax revenues during the
recession and concerns over Congressional inaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about the health of the Argentine economy have grown
since the government revised its economic data a month ago. The
decline in first-quarter output was recalculated, from 2.8 percent
to 3 percent. At the start of the year, the government projected
that the economy would grow this year, but economists now estimate
that the contraction could be as steep as 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The sharp devaluation of the Brazilian real in January has made
Argentine exports increasingly uncompetitive with the country's
largest trading partner, particularly hurting the automotive and
steel industries.
</P>
<P>
   With tax receipts falling sharply, the government has also been
forced to raise the yearly fiscal deficit to $5.1 billion _ nearly
double the number first targeted in negotiations with the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   And unemployment is expected to climb to at least 15 percent in
the next few weeks, almost 3 points higher than last October.
Private forecasters in Argentina have estimated that industrial
production has fallen nearly 13 percent in the last year _ well
above government estimates.
</P>
<P>
   There is a growing impression among investors that President
Carlos Saul Menem is losing his influence in his final months in
office. Last week, he and his congressional supporters were forced
to back down on a new vehicle tax to pay teacher raises when tens
of thousands of truck drivers went on strike across the country.
The retreat suggested to some analysts that the government would
back down on needed tax measures under pressure from other interest
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The two leading presidential candidates have also contributed to
the market's anxiety because they have failed to declare their
economic policies. And both Buenos Aires Gov. Eduardo Duhalde, the
candidate of the ruling Justicialist party, and Buenos Aires Mayor
Fernando de la Rua, of the opposition Alianza party, hurt investor
confidence in recent weeks when they suggested that Argentina will
need some kind of relief from payments on its $130 billion foreign
debt.
</P>
<P>
   During the weekend, Duhalde said he would seek support from Pope
John Paul II for a debt moratorium for struggle countries like
Argentina.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
