<SLUG> BC-FORD-BRAZIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL PROPOSES $700 MILLION IN INCENTIVES FOR FORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (md) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Ford Motor Co. may receive an incentives
package from the government of more than $700 million to install a
car factory in Brazil's impoverished Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed package, reported in Brazilian newspapers Monday,
has created a political controversy over the use of public funds to
spur job creation in some regions over others.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the package, President Fernando Henrique Cardoso is
expected to issue a decree in coming days providing Ford with
federal financing and other incentives such as tax breaks. In
return, Ford has agreed to invest an estimated $1.3 billion to
build a state-of-the-art compact car plant in the relatively poor
state of Bahia, creating 5,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials and Cardoso's office had no comment on the
reported incentives package.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, the effort to lure Ford to the northeast region
of Brazil would be a victory for Antonio Carlos Magalhaes, the
powerful senator from Bahia who is considered the glue that holds
Cardoso's fragile coalition together in Brasilia. Meanwhile,
leading members of the president's own Social Democrat party in the
industrialized south have criticized what they perceive as neglect
on Cardosos part.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unfair competition from a federalist point of view,''
Gov. Mario Covas of Sao Paulo told reporters here. Similar comments
from Covas and others have recently plagued the Cardoso
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Some local news reports cited the possibility of problems with
Argentina and the World Trade Organization if the incentives
granted to Ford are considered too wide-reaching. Yet the
controversy so far seems more related to domestic politics than
international trade differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned but not extremely worried,'' said a senior
diplomat at the Argentine Embassy in Brasilia. ``Brazil is our
largest trading partner and we have mechanisms to resolve these
problems amicably.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford had originally hoped to build the factory in the southern
state of Rio Grande do Sul but abandoned those plans after a
financing dispute with local socialist officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
