A7395 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUBLICADS-POLITICIANS     07-12 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLICADS-POLITICIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS RAISED ABOUT PUBLIC SERVICE ADS FEATURING CONGRESSIONAL
SPOUSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Washington Talk column; ad text follows) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The commercials begin like ordinary 30-second
public service announcements.
</P>
<P>
   On the screen is a familiar scene like a man and woman in an
office or people in a hurry on a busy sidewalk or a couple sitting
at the kitchen table. The actors begin talking to each other about
literacy or drugs or drunken driving or breast cancer. Or in some
cases an offstage narrator talks about the problem.
</P>
<P>
   But 10 seconds before the end of the commercial, an odd thing
happens. The wife of the local congressman or senator appears on
screen. ``Hello, I'm Simone-Marie Meeks,'' one wife says in a
typical example. ``My husband, Congressman Gregory Meeks, and I
urge you to read with your children. Because literacy is a gift for
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeks is a Democrat from New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the woman's face fades away and the narrator says, ``This
message brought to you by the National Association of
Broadcasters.''
</P>
<P>
   These ads, which start in more than 40 states this week, are a
sweet deal all around.
</P>
<P>
   For the television stations, it is an opportunity to give a nod
to public service and a chance to fill empty time for which they
have not sold advertisements. Because the wife and not the
politician is the one on the air, opposing views do not have to be
given equal time.
</P>
<P>
   For the politicians, generally eager to show off their families,
it is an effortless, risk-free way of keeping their names before
the public, a benefit not available to potential challengers.
</P>
<P>
   For the National Association of Broadcasters, one of the most
aggressive and influential trade associations, it is a quiet way of
further ingratiating themselves with lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   And finally the public will benefit if people see the
commercials and take the advice to heart.
</P>
<P>
   As the perks of incumbency go, this is small potatoes. It does
not rank, for example, with the benefits of having offices and a
large staff paid for by taxpayers, of being able to raise campaign
contributions relatively easily or postage-free franked mail.
</P>
<P>
   As political wheeling and dealing by a special interest, it does
not compare in importance with the large sums of unregulated money
that interest groups give to political parties. And it pales next
to the nearly $500,000 the political action committee of the
National Association of Broadcasters gave to congressional
candidates for the 1998 election.
</P>
<P>
   But many people here said it seemed just a little fishy. Andrew
Jay Schwartzman, president of the Media Access Project, a nonprofit
law firm that often challenges the broadcasters in court and in
lobbying battles, said the ads raised ``serious questions about
whether there are not ulterior motives that may not be more
important to the broadcasters than the stated objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Public service commercials serve a purpose when they are made by
recognizable public figures like actors or athletes who might
command attention, Schwartzman said. But he said he doubted that
the wives of politicians would have much positive effect.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcasters have a long legislative agenda. The main
legislation they want from Congress for this year would prohibit
satellite companies from carrying local, over-the-air broadcast
signals. The broadcasters also want measures to increase the number
of stations one company can own and block the expansion of
low-powered radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Bobeck, a spokesman for the broadcasters association,
said the organization had no ulterior motive in working with
congressional wives on public service advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no political agenda here,'' Bobeck said. ``The
individuals choose the issues themselves. Any spouse who wants to
participate can do so.''
</P>
<P>
   And wives who were interviewed said they were only trying to
promote good causes. Mrs. Meeks, for instance, made three
commercials _ on literacy, breast cancer and prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't enjoy doing it at all,'' Mrs. Meeks said. ``It's just
my face on the screen and not my husband's, and it's not
particularly flattering.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said the issues she dealt with were ``especially
important to the people in the 6th Congressional District.''
</P>
<P>
   The project was a joint production of the broadcasters and the
Congressional Club, an organization of congressional spouses. The
wives of 20 senators and more than 60 congressmen agreed to make
commercials. So did a few of their children and the husband of one
congresswoman, Lino Lipinsky, whose wife, Rep. Diana DeGette, is a
Colorado Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The wives of Republicans and Democrats, conservatives and
liberals, freshmen and veterans are participating. The only pattern
seems to be that for some reason, few of the congressional
districts are in big cities. Mrs. Meeks was the only New Yorker who
took part.
</P>
<P>
   The spots were taped recently at a studio here arranged for by
the broadcasters' association and will be transmitted by satellite
to stations in the participants' districts and states beginning
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Those taking part were offered 16 scripts to choose from. Some
of the other issues included drinking during pregnancy, drug abuse,
conflict resolution and the importance of completing school.
</P>
<P>
   Issues that are even remotely controversial like smoking, AIDS
and contraception were avoided.
</P>
<P>
   Bobeck, the broadcasters' spokesman, said similar projects had
been done in every odd-numbered year since 1985. He said the
commercials were not made in election years so ``it doesn't get
mixed up in campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   But many people who have been around Washington and politics for
decades, like Schwartzman and David Cohen, the co-director of the
Advocacy Institute, said they had never heard of the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, whose organization advises and trains people who lobby
for liberal causes and who has long criticized the perks of
incumbency, said it sounded to him like ``audio-visual franking.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   TEXT OF TYPICAL AD FEATURING CONGRESSIONAL SPOUSE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Broadcasters has begun the
Congressional Family Public Service Announcement Project, a series
of commercials, of which this one on alcohol consumption and
pregnancy is representative:
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN The commercial begins with a tight shot of a glass
with a baby crying in the background. Ice cubes drop and liquor
pours into the glass. After the narrator begins speaking, the shot
widens to reveal that the glass is in fact a baby bottle.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT Narrator: You wouldn't dream of feeding your baby
alcohol. But if you're pregnant and you drink, so does your baby.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional family member: Hello I'm ---------. My husband,
Congressman --------- and I want you to have a healthy baby. If
you're pregnant, don't drink alcohol.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
