<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: DISNEY CREATES GO.COM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT with SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eager to assume more direct control over the future of its
assets on the Internet, Walt Disney Co. announced Monday that it
would create a single company combining the Infoseek search service
and portal with Disney's own Internet holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, to be known as Go.com, will merge Disney.com,
Disney's Club Blast, The Disney Store Online and other holdings
with Infoseek, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Disney already owns 42 percent of Infoseek. The deal, which had
been widely expected, is the company's attempt to create an entity
whose stock will provide Disney with a currency for additional
Internet acquisitions. It will also help attract Internet managers
who expect part of their compensation to come in the form of stock
options in an industry where share prices have soared over the last
few years.
</P>
<P>
   Disney and Infoseek are already working closely together, but a
dual management structure is viewed as unwieldy by many in the
industry. The company clearly hopes that creating a more
streamlined operation with its own shares will streamline both
management and dealmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Once the deal is completed, Disney will own 72 percent of the
new company, through a tracking stock, meaning that the assets
continue to be owned by Disney, but the share price effectively
tracks the performance of those assets. Infoseek shareholders will
own the balance, or 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the agreement, Infoseek shareholders will get
1.15 shares of the new company for each of their Infoseek shares.
Since Disney now owns 42 percent of Infoseek, 57 percent, or 35
million of its 62 million shares, are held by others. Those will
become 41 million shares in the new company, leaving roughly 145
million shares of the tracking stock outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Though Disney did not provide much financial data Monday, James
Preissler, an analyst at Paine Webber who follows Infoseek, said,
``If you are a believer in the synergy that Disney brings to the
story, from both a content standpoint as well as a distribution
standpoint, then the deal bolsters that strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street the initial impulse when the deal was announced
was to wonder whether it might fall apart if Infoseek shareholders
believed they were not being paid enough for their assets. There
was precedent for that concern since Lycos shareholders, angry that
USA Networks Inc. was not paying enough of a premium for Lycos,
blocked that merger earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Infoseek shareholders filed seven suits Monday in Delaware
Chancery Court over the buyout.
</P>
<P>
   Disney stock rose 18.7 cents Monday to close at $27.81, while
Infoseek's shares dropped $5.56 to close at $45.93.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Preissler said he thought the deal was likely to go
ahead. ``It fairly values all the assets that are contributed,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Disney said the combined company was expected to have revenues
of $350 million, of which $150 million would come from traditional
sales from the Disney catalog. The balance will come from Internet
operations of the two companies, Disney said.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, when Disney made its initial investment in Infoseek,
Walt Disney's chairman, Michael Eisner, talked about the advantages
of melding Infoseek's Internet capabilities with Disney's marketing
prowess. ``When all the technology is out there, it is the
entertainment value that attracts people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics wondered Monday whether Disney, already a mature
media company, could work well with the faster-moving Internet
operator. Disney's image, certain and safe, has no edge. John
Tinker, who follows Disney for Nationsbanc Montgomery Securities,
said he saw the deal is a creative venture for Disney. But he views
the key challenge as Disney's ability to sublimate its traditional
image within Go.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disney has kind of an image of monitored, safe sex,'' he said.
``On the Internet everyone wants freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner said the company was well aware that: ``You don't want
big corporate brother pushing you to a certain site,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are more subtle moves a marketing company might
make, Eisner continued, such as using jokes on the Go.Com home page
to liven it up a bit and differentiate it from the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts agree that management would pose the most
immediate problem.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Motro, president and chief executive officer of Infoseek,
is leaving the company once the deal is completed. Steve Wadsworth,
president of Disney's Internet operations, is expected to take
over.
</P>
<P>
   If so, he faces a variety of problems at Go.com. Infoseek's
stock has not done as well in recent months as those of its
competitors, and though Go.com's customer base has increased, it is
not rising as fast as Yahoo's, for example. Moreover, the company
failed to meet analysts' first-quarter estimates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
