<SLUG> BC-POPEYES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Yorkers to get chance to love chicken chain
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Popeyes Chicken &AMP; Biscuits announced it is doubling
the chain's number of restaurants in New York City within the next
five years in three separate deals.
</P>
<P>
   Three franchisees will develop 21 new Popeyes restaurants in
Manhattan and Brooklyn. Currently, the chain has 19 restaurants in
the New York City market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The significance is that we've identified New York as a top
growth market,'' said spokesman Scott Hudler. 'We can use that
growth to develop in the outer communities. This is part of a
national effort to expand the Popeyes brand through franchising.''
</P>
<P>
   Popeyes, which offers a quick-service New Orleans-style chicken
concept, is a division of Atlanta-based AFC Enterprises. It also
operates Cajun Kitchen restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Popeyes has 1,325 units, of which 85 percent are franchises. In
1998, the division reported more than $982 million.
</P>
<P>
   It was recently awarded the the Restaurants and Institutions
Choice in Chains Gold Award for customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila M. Poole writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
