<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, JULY 13
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-ASIA-RECOVERY-NYT (moved on Sunday, July 11)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, July 11,
about Asia's recovery from its financial crisis omitted a given
name and title in some copies for a Philippine businessman who
commented on a proposal to have the Government restrict
competition. He was Emmanuel Gonzalez, president of the Hotel,
Resort and Restaurant Association of Cebu, a resort island.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SAUDI-NUKES-NYT (moved on Friday, July 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, July 9,
about a visit by Saudi Arabia's Defense Minister to Pakistani
nuclear and missile sites referred incorrectly to the missile site.
It is a plant near Islamabad that makes Ghauri missiles, named for
a 12th-century Muslim hero; Ghauri is not the place name.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CLINTON-LIBRARY-NYT (moved on Sunday, June 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, June 27,
about the Presidential Library planned for Bill Clinton referred
incorrectly to the Old State House in Little Rock. It was converted
into a museum in 1951 and was not in use as state offices during
Mr. Clinton's terms as Governor of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   SESAMESTREET-BERLITZ-NYT (moved on Sunday, July 11)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, July 11,
about a joint venture to create a global English-language
instruction business using ``Sesame Street'' characters misstated
one executive's estimate of the potential market. Mako Obara,
executive vice president and chief operating officer of Berlitz
International, predicted a potential $4 billion global market for
all children's language instruction ventures, not just for the new
one, a project of his company with Children's Television Workshop.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MINORITY-JOURNALISTS-NYT (moved on Sunday, July 11)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, July 11,
about Unity, the joint convention of minority journalists'
organizations last week in Seattle, misstated the given name of a
former San Diego reporter now at the Ford Foundation. He is Jon
Funabiki, not Ron. The article also misstated the year of the
group's first joint convention and misidentified a short-lived
local section that formerly employed another minority journalist,
at The Los Angeles Times. The meeting was in 1994, not 1995. The
section was City Times, not City Weekly.
</P>
</TEXT>
