<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-LYNCH-RETIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL LYNCH PRESIDENT RESIGNS UNEXPECTEDLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Herbert Allison Jr., the president of Merrill Lynch &AMP;
Co., unexpectedly resigned Monday, extending a period of upheaval
at America's largest brokerage firm and leaving it without an heir
apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Allison's departure, effective by the end of July, appears to be
fallout from the turmoil generated by rapid change at Merrill. The
firm has overhauled its core business of selling stocks to
investors to meet the challenge of Internet-based rivals. It has
also reshuffled the management of its money management and bond
divisions in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Those changes bore the stamp of Allison, 55, widely viewed as a
brainy, detail-oriented No. 2 to David Komansky, Merrill's chairman
and chief executive. But the rapid pace of change made Allison the
target of critics within Merrill's executive ranks and soured his
chances of succeeding Komansky down the road, people who work at
the firm and analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill called the departure a retirement and said that it came
at the behest of Allison, who informed Komansky of his decision
over the weekend. A spokesman for the firm said that Allison's
departure was not the result of an internal power struggle.
</P>
<P>
   The firm said it had no immediate plans to name a successor. But
Komansky said in a statement that two senior executives, Stephen
Hammerman and John Steffens, both vice chairmen, will assume
increased management responsibilities. Half a dozen business
divisions that had reported to Allison will now report directly to
Komansky.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the key strengths of Merrill Lynch is a depth of
management talent unmatched in our industry,'' Komansky said. ``The
seasoned executives leading our business and support groups have
the ability to lead our company, execute our strategy and produce
superior results.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill lost money in the fourth quarter of last year and has
acted aggressively to reshuffle managers and change strategies in
several core areas of its business since then. Its financial
performance so far this year has been solid, however, and Allison's
departure comes as Merrill prepares to announce strong quarterly
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts expect Merrill to announce second-quarter earnings
Tuesday of about 10 percent more than it did in the same period a
year ago, itself a robustly profitable quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of Allison's departure came late in the day
Monday and had no noticeable impact on Merrill's stock, which rose
62.5 cents to $77.875.
</P>
<P>
   Allison, a 28-year Merrill veteran, took up the position of
president at the same time Komansky became chairman in December
1996. At the time, many at Merrill viewed them as an ideal team.
Komansky advanced through Merrill's core brokerage operation and is
viewed as gregarious, the public flag carrier for the firm. Allison
had a reputation as a number cruncher and a hands-on manager who
preferred to operate behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   The formula appeared to work well for a time. But the
relationship between the two men became strained after Merrill hit
a rough patch late last year amid a general slump in financial
markets, several people close to Merrill said. Allison stepped
forward at that time to attack what he perceived as weaknesses in
Merrill's huge bond division, laying off several thousand people
and prompting a stream of voluntary departures. Some outside
analysts later called Allison's moves an overreaction to a
temporary market downturn and blamed him for hurting morale.
</P>
<P>
   Allison has also taken some heat for the weak performance of
Merrill's mutual funds and for some expensive acquisitions Merrill
made abroad to bolster its money management operation, moves that
have dampened its earnings more than some analysts expected.
</P>
<P>
   Another big challenge came this year, when Allison pushed hard
to restructure Merrill's tradition-bound brokerage operation to
meet the challenge of the Internet, a move that was deeply
unpopular with the firm's nearly 15,000 retail brokers. Allison and
Steffens, who heads the brokerage division, battled for months over
how and how fast to incorporate Internet trading into the mix of
services offered to the firm's retail clients, several people who
work at Merrill have said in recent interviews.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Merrill gave clients the choice of doing some or all of
their trading online instead of through their brokers, an offering
that will be phased in during coming months. The move was intended
to stop the flow of clients to rivals like Charles Schwab, which
has moved most of its stock brokerage business online. But the
final strategy was widely viewed within Merrill as a victory for
Steffens over an alternative plan put forward by Allison.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the firm denied that dissension over online
trading had a role in forcing Allison's departure. The spokesman
said that there were discussions before the change took place, but
that after the strategy was set senior executives rallied behind
the plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
