</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CRIME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE CRIME PROPOSAL URGES PHOTO LICENSES FOR NEW HANDGUN OWNERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Vice President Al Gore outlined his plan for
crime-fighting on Monday, essentially delivering two very different
speeches in one: On the one hand, he called for gun control
measures that go beyond anything President Clinton has proposed,
requiring photo licenses for all new handgun owners and banning
cheap handguns.
</P>
<P>
   But he also sounded a number of conservative anti-crime themes,
saying he'd support longer sentences for all crimes committed with
guns, and for those who commit crimes in front of children. He
pledged to work with states that want to stop plea bargaining on
crimes committed with guns. A program he calls ``Stay Clean to Stay
Out'' would send parolees who fail mandatory drug tests back to
jail.
</P>
<P>
   In an address at police headquarters, surrounded by uniformed
officers who made the vice president look unusually loose, Gore
also pledged to push for a federal law establishing ``gang-free
zones'' with curfews on individual gang members, and a ban on
``gang-related clothing.''
</P>
<P>
   After giving Gore a Fenway Park T-shirt for his newborn
grandson, Boston Mayor Tom Menino called the vice president a
``visionary'' and ``friend of American cities'' who with the
president has helped push crime in Boston to its lowest rate since
1971. (Recalling a speech Gore made at a St. Patrick's Day event
two years ago, Menino added, ``They say he's wooden! Huh! I wish I
was as wooden as he was that morning!'')
</P>
<P>
   Recent school shootings have made gun control a major focus in
the campaign, and Gore, one of the original co-sponsors of the
Brady Bill, has a long history of pushing for it. But since the
shootings at Columbine High in Littleton, Colo., this spring, he
has regularly spoken of limits on gun sales as only part of the
solution to youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we give our kids something to believe in?'' he asked the
crowd. ``Then the lure of cheap sensation will not hold sway over
them. Do we model decency and honor to them? Then they will remain
untempted by theft and deceit.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point in the speech, he said, ``Our children cannot
reach for their dreams if they are ducking for cover. A parent
struggles to pass on the right values in a culture that practically
screams out that chaos and cruelty are cool. And a good parent is
undermined in trying to teach the great, simple lessons of right
and wrong, of the rule of law and responsibility, when a burdened
justice system lets criminals off too easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also said he supported ``common sense gun control
measures'' already advocated by the administration, including a
three-day waiting period for gun purchases, a one-gun-a-month limit
and requiring child safety locks on handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley also has announced a gun
control proposal that is similar in many respects but would go even
further, requiring that all handguns be registered. On ``Good
Morning America'' Monday, Gore said he did not necessarily oppose
the idea of registering guns, but felt the licensing idea would
work just as well since background checks would be incorporated.
Aides said Monday that Gore felt licensing for anyone who wanted to
buy a gun would be less cumbersome for ``law-abiding citizens''
than registration of all guns would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``If other measures are needed, we're open to that,'' a Gore
aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who cast a tie-breaking vote in May when the Senate passed
legislation expanding a system of background checks on gun
purchases, was clearly eager to contrast his views on gun control
with those of his Republican competitors, particularly Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, who has signed a ``conceal and carry'' law and
legislation limiting liability for gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some want to enact new protections for gun manufacturers,''
Gore said in the speech. ``I want to pass new protections for
families. Some want more concealed weapons _ but they can't conceal
the fact that they're just doing the NRA's bidding.''
</P>
<P>
   Mindy Tucker, a spokeswoman for Bush, called Gore's reference to
the National Rifle Association ``so irresponsible he ought to be
ashamed.'' Bush supported the law limiting suits against gun
companies, she said, because ``He doesn't believe we should
subcontract the legal process to trial lawyers. He feels people
should be punished for their illegal actions, not manufacturers of
a legal product.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tucker also defended the conceal-and-carry law, saying that
since the governor signed it in 1995, ``many people feel safer,
particularly nurses and other women who work at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, a spokesman for the vice president, said the issue
was an important one for Gore. ``We always like comparisons to
Republicans on this issue,'' he said. ``If the holster fits, wear
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But William Moffitt, incoming president of the National
Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers, denounced the speech,
saying some parts of it sounded too Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``The culture war stuff sounds very much like what you'd hear
from Pat Buchanan,'' Moffitt said. ``And he wants to turn federal
courts into fashion police trying to dictate what people wear? I
don't know how you square chasing people down because of their
clothing with what the constitution says.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
