u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TAXES-HNS &LR;      07-12 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TAXES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS TO MEND TAX DIFFERENCES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as his advisers blasted Republican Party tax
cut proposals, President Clinton on Tuesday met with Congressional
leaders in an effort to bridge differences over taxes, Medicare and
other spending programs.
</P>
<P>
   While the hourlong meeting at the White House produced no
substantial agreements, Republican and Democratic leaders emerged
saying the discussions had been upbeat and that both sides were
eager to work on how to spend up an expected trillion-dollar budget
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Even House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, normally one of
President Clinton's toughest critics, said that he ``was impressed
with the president's enthusiasm'' about dealing with the issues.
</P>
<P>
   Armey was less charitable toward House Minority leader Dick
Gephardt, D-Mo, saying he hoped the president could convince the
Democratic leader to abandon his ``do nothing '' attitude that had
been impeding action in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The outward display of optimism masked differences between
Democrats and Republicans over tax policy that could play out
through the fall and possibly carry over into the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   The House Ways and Means Committee is scheduled Tuesday to take
up an $864 billion tax cut proposal that Democrats have warned
could lead to new deficits and the inability to shore up Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt and Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said
the meeting with their GOP counterparts had not convinced them to
back such a big tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle warned that if the tax cuts were approved and the
surpluses did not materialize, the government would find itself
short of funds.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said he backed modest targeted tax cuts, but that
Democratic lawmakers would not rubber stamp any proposal offered
them by the Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to collapse to their position if we think
their position is wrong headed, '' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said
they had agreed to work on legislation that would guarantee that
surpluses generated by Social Security payroll tax would be
dedicated to shoring up the retirement program.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the president had called
the meeting to discuss with the congressional leaders ``what his
principles are, what he thinks can get done, how we can cut taxes
the right way, how we can pay down the debt and secure this
economic recovery for the next generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, administration officials shot down
Republican tax proposals saying they would rob the government of
funds needed to extend the life of Medicare and pay for essential
domestic and defense programs.
</P>
<P>
   White House National Economic Director Gene Sperling charged
that the Republicans had failed the ``fiscal responsibility test.''
</P>
<P>
   Sperling called it ``puzzling, disturbing and disappointing that
the Republicans now put forward a tax cut plan that leaves zero,
zero, for Medicare over a 10-year period.''
</P>
<P>
   And Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said that ``huge tax
cuts are the wrong way forward because they mean more debt and
because they mean more risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have responded that they have set aside enough money
to save the entitlements and meet basic needs. They accuse the
administration of wanting to use the surplus to fund more
government programs rather than return extra money to the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need more Washington spending,'' said Lott.
</P>
<P>
   The latest debate was triggered by Republican plans to start
moving massive tax cuts through Congress, beginning with an $864
billion tax cut proposal crafted by Ways and Means Chairman Bill
Archer, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Archer plan would cut federal income tax rates by 10
percent, slash the top tax rate on capital gains from 20 percent to
15 percent, eliminate the inheritance and gift taxes, and offer
deductions for individuals purchasing long-term health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the Senate, Finance Committee Chairman William
Roth, R-Del, has proposed a $792 billion tax cutting package, which
would reduce the lowest tax bracket from 15 percent to 14 percent,
reduce the tax penalty on married people, and provide tax
incentives for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton administration officials say they prefer the Roth
plan because it targets middle class citizens, they say both plans
are too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has proposed instead a $250 billion tax package
that officials say would leave enough money to extend the life of
Medicare by 12 years and fund domestic and defense programs.
</P>
<P>
   The president has proposed using $374 billion for Medicare,
including $46 billion to provide a new prescription drug benefit
for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The president's budget would also add $328 billion for other
programs, including $127 billion for beefing up defense.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say the Republicans have provided no
additional money for Medicare and have not spelled out how they
would give out a large tax cut and continue to fund defense and
other programs.
</P>
<P>
   They acknowledge, however, that the Republicans have dealt with
Social Security by ensuring that $1.9 trillion in surplus that
comes from the Social Security payroll tax would be dedicated to
saving that entitlement.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Rushton, an Archer spokesman, said the surplus dedicated to
Social Security is enough to fix Medicare's financial problems as
well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
