<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7428 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLOBE-PUBLISHER-BOS &LR;      07-12 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-PUBLISHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. TIMES CO.   EXECUTIVE NAMED PUBLISHER AT BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In a surprise move that ended 126 years of leadership
of The Boston Globe by the Taylor family, The New York Times Co.
Monday replaced publisher Benjamin B. Taylor with Richard H.
Gilman, senior vice president of operations at the Times.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to remove Taylor, 52, was made by Times publisher
and company chairman Arthur O. Sulzberger Jr. and by Times company
president and CEO Russell T. Lewis, according to Times spokeswoman
Nancy Nielsen. But it was new publisher Gilman, 48, who faced the
Globe editorial staff Monday to explain the dramatic development
that came six years after the Times purchased the Globe for $1.04
billion.
</P>
<P>
   While choosing not to discuss the details of why the Times
acted, Gilman, whose appointment became effective Monday, cited
``differences in approaches to management.'' This led to
speculation that stylistic and corporate cultural differences
between New York and Boston _ at a time when the Globe is
struggling with declining circulation and sagging classified
revenues _ may have played a significant role.
</P>
<P>
   In a noontime meeting with Globe newsroom employees, Gilman
captured the mood of the day by acknowledging that ``this catches a
lot of people, including myself, a little bit by surprise. . . .
Any time there is a dramatic change, and this certainly qualifies
as a dramatic change, it's an emotional moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilman emphasized that ``the citizens of Boston and all of you
are justifiably proud of your newspaper'' and vowed to continue a
major ``investment in the quality of journalism.'' In an interview
later in the day, he also stressed that no further changes were
planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no other shoe to drop here. I'm here by myself. That's
the only change that's on the horizon,'' Gilman said, adding he had
``complete confidence'' in editor Matthew V. Storin and editorial
page editor H.D.S. Greenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been given complete reassurance about our editorial
independence,'' Storin said. ``They have said all the right things
both publicly and privately. But this is business. There are no
guarantees.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who will remain as chairman of the Globe Newspaper
Company Board, said Monday that Gilman's arrival in Boston ``could
be good for the Globe because one of our ongoing challenges is
educating New York about all the good things that are going on at
The Boston Globe.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction from the journalistic community seemed to be a mix of
resignation and concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the bottom line is that even The New York Times, which
operates at a very high standard of journalism, must move to the
same economic and technological impulses that drive the entire
industry,'' said Marvin Kalb, director of Harvard's Joan
Shorenstein Center on Press, Politics and Public Policy. ``We will
have to see what impact this has on the editorial side of the
paper. . . . Will The Boston Globe shrink from being a major
regional paper to a smaller paper?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that strikes me as noteworthy is that these
companies were attracted to each other because the Taylors and
Sulzbergers were members of a shrinking tradition'' of local,
family-run newspaper companies, said Tom Rosenstiel, director of
the Project for Excellence in Journalism. ``It's noteworthy that
under the ownership of The New York Times, that shrinking family
(management) is down by one.''
</P>
<P>
   In a memo distributed to the Globe staff Monday, Gilman singled
out the twin problems of declining newspaper readership and the
erosion of classified advertising as two issues that have surfaced
at the Globe in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's any surprise . . . that we consider Sunday
circulation the single biggest challenge,'' said Taylor. For the
six-month period ending in March, the Sunday Globe's circulation
was 730,420, compared with 751,377 two years earlier, and the paper
is now concentrating its efforts on building up the Sunday numbers.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures released at last month's meeting of Globe
department heads, total classified advertising in 1999 was down 4.5
percent from last year. And an April press release announcing the
Times Co.'s first quarter 1999 earnings pointedly noted that
``performance was strong at The New York Times and the Regional
Newspaper Group, where ad revenues increased 5.4 percent and 6.7
percent, and weak at The Boston Globe, where help wanted
advertising continued to soften.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Taylor told the staff Monday that the Globe's financial
picture is solid, with a ``very real prospect that we will have our
third record year (of earnings) in a row'' and a 25 percent margin.
Newspaper analyst John Morton concurred, saying ``certainly there's
nothing in the performance of The Boston Globe to suggest that any
change was in order. It's the Sulzbergers' own newspaper. They can
do whatever they damn please.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that reality, much of the speculation Monday centered on
what both Taylor and Gilman alluded to as differences in management
technique, with observers suggesting that differences between the
harder-charging New York style and the Taylors' more conservative
bent _ as well as the Times' desire for more centralized control of
the Globe _ may have proved to be a crucial factor in the change of
publishers.
</P>
<P>
   But for many people inside the Globe, Monday was a day to
contemplate the end of the stewardship of the Taylor family, which
built a reputation through the generations for loyal, benevolent
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a morning meeting of department heads that she
characterized as ``very stunned and sad,'' columnist Ellen Goodman
recalled how ``most of us have worked for at least two generations
of Taylors and (how) we've been very lucky to have the family as
publishers.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same meeting, William O. Taylor, who retired in 1997
after 20 years as publisher, noted: ``This is a very sad day for
both Ben and myself as our family winds up a long career managing
this newspaper. I hope the history books will be kind to both of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   At the large noontime gathering, Gilman asked for a round of
applause for Benjamin Taylor, who began his career as a Globe
reporter more than a quarter-century ago. As the staff rose for a
long and emotional standing ovation, Taylor slowly got up from his
seat and waved _ almost reluctantly, shyly _ to those who had
suddenly become his former employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 2102EDT &QL; 
