<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7431 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-TALLAS-BOS     07-12 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-TALLAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS NET TALLAS FOR ANOTHER YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- One down, one to go.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins locked up Rob Tallas with a one-year contract Monday,
leaving Byron Dafoe as their remaining restricted free-agent
goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old Tallas, whom the Bruins dealt to keep on
expansion draft day when they sent center Randy Robitaille to the
Atlanta Thrashers, signed a pact reportedly worth $700,000 plus
incentives.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a significant increase from last year's $625,000
salary, but Tallas said he feels it's consistent with what his
peers around the league are making, and he's very pleased.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Tallas played 17 regular-season games and earned a
7-7-2 record and a 2.61 goals-against average. If Tallas plays 35
games next year, he'll pocket $25,000 and earn $25,000 for every
additional five-game stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``A one-year deal at this time is pretty much fair for both,''
said Jay Fee, Tallas's representative. ``His contract for next year
will be at the upper reaches of backup goalies' salaries. I think
the main thing we were worried about in Boston is that he not start
wasting away here. I've been assured that the plan is to play
Robbie more next year. Get him going earlier, and get him more
routine work than he had last year, and that's really important.
What happens in the double expansion draft next year, I don't know.
Obviously, Boston likes him, and I think he appreciates the fact
that they went through a lot of trouble to try to hang onto him.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the expansion draft, the Bruins lost forward Peter
Ferraro to Atlanta. Then, as part of the agreement not to pick
Tallas, the Thrashers turned around and swapped Ferraro back to the
Bruins for Robitaille.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy,'' said Tallas. ``After talking to Jay and looking
at where I fit in the league, (filing for arbitration) wasn't
necessary at all. I'm right there. There's a chance for me to play
some more games this year, depending on Byron's contract. I'm happy
with that. We talked about a two-year deal, but the best thing for
me right now is a one-year deal with two teams coming back next
year.''
</P>
<P>
   A one-year deal gives Tallas more leverage next summer as two
new teams will be joining the league for the 2000-2001 season. He
feels that by being a free agent again rather than being under
contract, he's left with more options.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they decide they want to keep (he and Dafoe) together for
another couple of years, it's definitely easier because if you're
signed, the other team isn't really taking any risk by picking you
up,'' he said. ``They know what your salary is going to be; they
grab you and go from there. That definitely will have a big part of
it next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas feels as if he is living a charmed life. He is able to
stay in Boston, he received a new contract he believes is fair, and
he feels he'll get more of an opportunity to play next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has worked out,'' he said. ``I always said I'd deal
with it when it comes. I didn't want to stress myself out and worry
about anything. Look what happened. This summer has totally worked
out in my favor. It's not always going to happen this way. There's
going to be adversity, but so far everything has been great. For me
to go in there and even ask for anything higher than I'm getting
right now is ridiculous. I'm loyal to them just as they've been
loyal to me this whole time.''
</P>
<P>
   You can guarantee that Dafoe's negotiations, which started out
very friendly, are not going to go as smoothly as they did for
Tallas. The deadline for filing for arbitration is Thursday. Look
for Dafoe to opt not to file and instead retain the option of
holding out at the start of training camp. That means the Bruins
are going to have their hands full, and Dafoe is going to retain
any leverage he has. Tallas said if the situation results in Dafoe
holding out, he'll be there to take up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to come into camp in shape, and I'll hope for the
best,'' he said. ``I hope I do get more games, but it's up to
(coach Pat Burns). With the way the race was at the end of the year
and Byron playing so well, Byron wanted those games, which made it
difficult for me. This year, depending on Byron's contract, who
knows if he's going to be at camp? If he's not, I'm taking on that
responsibility of being the No. 1 guy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
