</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOURDEFRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAM OF A TOUR-DE-FRANCE WIN IS DEFERRED A YEAR FOR AN INJURED
JULICH  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)   By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LE GRAND BORNAND, France _ The Tour de France took the day off
Monday, and unhappily for Bobby Julich, he was not here. The
Cofidis rider was in Nice, recovering from the injuries he
sustained Sunday in the time trial in Metz that knocked him out of
the race.
</P>
<P>
   His broken ribs and elbow mean that his dream goes unfulfilled
for another year.
</P>
<P>
   It began in 1986, when he was 14, Julich watched on television
as Greg LeMond become the first American to win the Tour de France.
That changed his life, Julich often says. He dropped the other
sports he played at school in Glenwood Springs, Colo., and
concentrated on racing his bicycle.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Julich won his share of races as he grew older, joined the U.S.
national team and then turned professional in 1993. He experienced
some terrible times, too, including the collapse of his first team
and the year he had to spend as an independent rider in the United
States, eating up his savings as he paid his way to races, hoping
for another chance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he wound up riding in his first Tour de France two
years ago. He finished 17th, then vaulted to third last year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned so much last year,'' he said during an interview
this past spring. ``I spent time on the trainer putting the tape of
the Tour de France in, and I learned a lot not only from the Tour
de France but looking at the tape. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a few times when I was nervous and caught up in the
situation. I was second for a couple of weeks and I began thinking,
`I don't have much higher to go but I can really lose a lot.' I was
kind of playing it safe. People can maybe say I wasn't aggressive,
but the situation I was in, I couldn't deal with it like a seasoned
veteran. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times I was sitting there, watching the tape, and
yelling at myself, totally regretting not attacking. That's not
what I want. The next Tour I want to lay it all on the line and
give myself a 100 percent chance of winning.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He was laying it all on the line Sunday in the time trial in
Metz when he came down a hill too rapidly and crashed, breaking
several ribs and his left elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Beforehand, he was confident, saying that he expected ``a great
time trial.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling good, my legs are good, my morale is super,'' he
said. ``Basically I'm arriving at the first time trial unscathed
and very motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the pollen allergies that troubled him in races in June had
got better, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But, as he said months before, sitting in the sunshine in Nice,
where he lives during the season with his wife, Angela, ``Destiny
has been a big part of my career.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Julich added: ``One thing I'm convinced of now, success doesn't
necessarily mean you'll be happy and failure doesn't necessarily
mean you'll be miserable. It's seeing the bright side of the
situation you're in and not thinking too much about the bad things.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest place to be is at the top because you're going to
get knocked off. And the people who get back there are the people
who've learned to deal with failure as much as success.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Julich was happy to talk about a number of topics in bicycle
racing, including drugs. ``I just hope the riders take more
responsibility,'' he said. ``Winning at all costs is not worth it.
There's honor in second, third, fifth, 20th place or even finishing
100th. You don't measure human beings by the number of bicycle
races they've won.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why did winning the Tour de France mean so much to him? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because it's the biggest bicycle race in the world, he said.
``But I'm not in this sport to say that I'm the best at anything,''
he said. ``I'm in this sport because I love it, first of all, and
second, to see what my limits are. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that a lot of people pass their heyday and think, `What
if I would have taken it a little more seriously?' or `What if I
had taken advantage of that opportunity?' or `What if, what if?' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that with me I'll take advantage of it when I can so
that later I won't regret the decisions I'm making.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such an easy sport,'' he said before he got on his
motorbike and went home. ``Do a lot of training, don't get sick,
don't get injured. What was it Eddy Merckx said when somebody asked
him how to become a top rider? `Ride lots.''' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
