A7440 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-SOCCER-BOS &LR;      07-12 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SOCCER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN ON TOP OF THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Besides the victory, the thrill of the Women's World Cup soccer
game was how well it played out in the hearts of fans.
</P>
<P>
   These players have pulled off a nearly chivalrous balance. They
are aggressive athletes but with a gentle love for the game. Their
interviews skip over canned and scripted answers. When goalkeeper
Briana Scurry talked about watching Liu Ying approach a penalty
shot, fans got to see through Scurry's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Liu ``didn't look like she wanted to be there. She didn't have
that confidence. You could see it in the way she walked up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Scurry blocked the shot _ moving the American team toward
victory and taking fans to a universe far away from
multimillion-dollar endorsements and contract disputes.
</P>
<P>
   In this world of pure joy about the game, the word
``confidence'' shakes off its hackneyed shell. It becomes a
crackling term that bundles the virtues of practice, focus, desire,
and hard work.
</P>
<P>
   In this world, Brandi Chastain's game-winning penalty-kick goal
doubles as a compelling psychological contest between Chastain and
the Chinese team's goalie Gao Hong. Gao, Chastain explains, can get
into confidence-shattering staring matches. So without looking at
Gao, Chastain saw what had to be done.
</P>
<P>
   The win also sheds glory on Title IX, the controversial 1972
policy that required gender equity in school and college sports.
Title IX created opportunities for female athletes even when demand
wasn't obvious. It was a leap of public policy faith, an ancestor
of the baseball movie chestnut, ``If you build it, they will
come.''
</P>
<P>
   As more girls and women played sports, more friends and
relatives paid attention. Television cameras followed. Now members
of America's younger generations take female athletes for granted _
blase about the fact that women aren't just televised gymnasts and
tennis players but also soccer and basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   It's a change that promises to grow. The World Cup's new
champions will surely inspire future champions who will renew our
passion for hard-won victories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7441 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GOP-780&AMP;ADD-N     07-12 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GOP-780&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MEETS WITH CONGRESSIONAL REPUBLICANS ON TAX AND SPENDING
MEASURES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Republican leaders warily met
Monday on a broad array of tax and spending proposals that expose
the deep divisions and distrust between the parties.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton back from a week-long tour of impoverished areas
and Congress returning to work after the July 4 recess, talks began
in earnest in the Oval Office late Monday afternoon on matters of
social policy and money that will drive negotiations in Washington
through the fall budget-writing season, and probably well into the
2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton invited Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, House Speaker
Dennis Hastert and House Majority Leader Dick Armey to the White
House to discuss his plans for Medicare and Social Security and to
hear Republican proposals for large tax cuts. The Democratic
leaders of the Senate and House, Tom Daschle and Dick Gephardt,
also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The president told the Republican leaders that he is willing to
work with them to use the bulk of projected federal budget
surpluses of $2.9 trillion over the next 10 years to insure the
solvency of Social Security and Medicare, aides said after the
meeting. But he repeated his view that Republican plans to cut
taxes by $800 billion or more over the next decade would make it
impossible to revamp Medicare or to add billions in new spending
for education, the military and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, the president's chief economic adviser, said the
president expressed willingness to discuss tax cuts of a smaller
magnitude, but only after dealing with what he views as more
pressing priorities. Clinton has said he would be willing to devote
about $250 billion of the estimated surplus over the next decade to
tax breaks intended to spur retirement savings among low- and
middle-income families.
</P>
<P>
   While the atmosphere of the Oval Office meeting was described as
friendly, administration officials earlier in the day described the
Republican tax-cutting plans as a ``shell game'' that threatened to
undermine the economy, consume the estimated surpluses and put the
federal budget back into the red just as a rosy scenario of surplus
is about to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Larry Summers called the tax cuts
``potentially explosive'' if projected surpluses fail to
materialize. Sperling said the Republican proposals were
``puzzling, disappointing and disturbing'' because they leave
nothing for the repair of Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The vehemence of the White House reaction this early in the
process led Republicans to question the president's sincerity when
he says he seeks to put partisanship aside and reach a compromise
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still trying to figure out if he really wants to get
things done _ cooperate on Social Security, Medicare, taxes, even
trade _ or is he going to go the partisan route,'' Lott said in an
interview with the Associated Press. For all the money being put on
the table by the surplus, reaching a deal will not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over how to apportion the excess revenue is about
more than numbers. Republicans support a big tax cut not just
because it would give money back to voters, but because it would
move the money out of Washington, and therefore help their efforts
to reduce the size and influence of the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said their intent is not to block a tax
cut, but to assure continued funding of military, education, health
and environmental programs, while pumping new money into Medicare
and avoiding the risk of renewed budget deficits.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, any compromise would be more complex than finding a
number between $250 billion _ the amount Clinton says is
appropriate for a tax cut over the next decade _ and $864 billion,
the figure in the Republican tax legislation that will be taken up
by the House Ways and Means Committee on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a mistake to think you just look at these numbers
and somehow say, well, can you just split the difference?'' said
Jacob J. Lew, the White House budget director. ``You have to ask,
what do you want to get on defense, what do you want to get on
Medicare, and you have to put first things first.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, the most complicating factors may be the
political judgments made by leaders of both parties about how a
deal, or the lack of one, would play on the campaign trail in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   There are factions within both parties that see an ideological
showdown as the best way of turning out voters on their behalf next
year. And there are both Democrats and Republicans who believe that
they will do better by going to the voters with a record of
accomplishment, even if it means compromise.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If Clinton and the Republican leadership cannot find some common
ground, and if the tax bill that emerges from Congress this month
looks more like the partisan House version than the more
compromise-oriented Senate version, the most likely outcome this
year will be gridlock, said Robert Greenstein, the executive
director of the Center for Budget and Policy Priorities, a
liberal-leaning research organization.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative, Greenstein said, would be ``a feeding frenzy''
of tax cuts and new spending that could return the nation to the
deficits of the 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gridlock here can actually be the responsible policy and
should not be seen as some form of failure,'' Greenstein said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
