<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7443 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MARTINEZ-COX     07-12 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MARTINEZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pedro Martinez: Halfway to 30
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's not just that he is doing this during baseball's
most prolific slugging era, or that he's doing it in the DH league,
or doing it in tiny Fenway Park, where pitchers have labored in
fear for nearly a century.
</P>
<P>
   What is more appealing in Pedro Martinez's quest this summer is
its simplicity: a man of everyday construction (5 feet 11),
throwing harder than he might (97 mph) and demanding some of the
game's greatest hitters to do something about it. Nothing is more
elemental.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I've faced him twice,'' Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. said,
``and he basically says, `Here, hit this.' And I couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston's newest favorite son starts for the American League
tonight in the 70th All-Star Game, catching his breath before
continuing his run at the game's first 30-win season in 31 years.
At 15-3, he leads the majors in victories and ERA (2.10), leads the
AL in strikeouts (184) and innings (132 2/3).
</P>
<P>
   Immune from the malaise that has hit so many star pitchers this
season, Martinez's start has been bettered by only nine players
since the first All-Star game in 1933. The last was Randy Jones'
16-3 first half in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when chicks dig the long ball, one man strives against
the trend. Asked how hard was the decision to make Martinez his
starter, AL manager Joe Torre said, ``Unless I didn't want to come
to town, it was the only choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, 28, easily could have won 18 already. In his three
losses, to the White Sox, Expos and Devil Rays, Boston scored three
runs in support. His 16-strikeout performance against Atlanta on
June 4 still has the Braves shaking their heads. In a surprisingly
strong first half for Boston, he has made all the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pitched 18 games and kept us in the game 18 times,''
manager Jimy Williams said. ``That statement says it all. It tells
you how good he is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have reworked their rotation to give him a break
entering the second half, prompting more questions about the
possibility of Martinez being the first pitcher to win 30 since
Denny McLain in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I'd love it,'' Martinez said. ``But it's not easy.
I've never won 20 in my career. This is the best chance I've had.
But I can only get ready for the next start.''
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, when Tommy Lasorda was sure he could not use
Martinez as a starter, Los Angeles dealt him to Montreal for second
baseman Delino DeShields. Once in Canada, Martinez spent a couple
of years dodging a reputation as a head-hunter, winning a
respectable 38 times in three years but being viewed as a
pedestrian fastballer on a nowhere team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I was going to be the player I am today,'' he
said, ``with all the bad things they said about me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cy Young season of 1997 _ 17-8, 1.90 ERA, 13 complete games,
305 strikeouts _ changed everything, as he was transformed before
the Expos' eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Then-teammate Sean Berry said, ``Well, for one thing, he throws
100 mph.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, 97. And then he throws that great change-up, a killer
change-up, and then he has a slider, too. He knows how to pitch a
little better now than he did back then. He was there physically a
long time ago, and now he's there mentally, too.''
</P>
<P>
   One year after the game's home-run record fell, a pitcher's
pursuit of 30 wins takes its place. And just as Mark McGwire and
Sammy Sosa cautioned against what eventually happened in 1998, the
same advisories are going out to Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be lucky,'' Torre said. ``You have to have the
lead. With the number of people he strikes out, it takes its toll
by late August or September. I think it's going to be very
difficult for him to win 30. Not that he's not capable. We all know
he's the premier pitcher in the league, and there's no question you
have to try like hell just to stay up with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Durability has remained a concern during Martinez's career. He
always has thrown his share of pitches _ his 113.7-pitcher average
leads the AL _ and he has paid a price. After an 11-2 start in
1998, he went 8-5 in the second half. During his career, he is
46-20 (.697) before the break and 38-26 (.594) after it.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers prompted the Red Sox to move him to the back of
the rotation. His two or three innings tonight will be the only
live work he will have between his last start on July 7 and his
next scheduled start against Florida on July 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws a lot of pitches, has a lot of strikeouts; he may
wear down more than the average guy,'' Boston pitching coach Joe
Kerrigan said. ``That's why you really track his number of pitches,
and the number of days he has between starts. I think he'll be OK
in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight will mark Martinez's third All-Star appearance _ he made
the team last year but did not pitch_ but his first since his
ascension to be the game's best. Fenway will be festooned as usual
with flags of the Dominican Republic, a celebration of a pitcher in
the era of the slugger.
</P>
<P>
   Who does Martinez most look forward to facing? ``None of them,''
he said, although the feeling is mutual.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
