<HEADER>
A7445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-WNBA-NYT &LR;      07-12 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WNBA, QUALITY IS UP, BUT THE GATE IS DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JERRY BREWER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The novelty that has covered the Women's National Basketball
Association like a fresh coat of paint is beginning to chip.
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of the star-studded cast from the defunct
American Basketball League, the WNBA entered its third season
finally being able to say that it had the best women's professional
basketball league in the nation _ or world, for that matter. Every
team now has a bona-fide star, and the deeper rosters have meant
faster-paced games.
</P>
<P>
   For Wednesday night's first All-Star Game at Madison Square
Garden, all 18,645 seats are sold. But comparing last season's
final average with the first half of this season, attendance has
decreased 12 percent _ from an average of 10,821 to 9,536.
</P>
<P>
   League officials say they are not panicking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're at the stage where we're really testing our
audience,'' WNBA President Val Ackerman said, ``and separating the
fans who came to watch us because we were new from the fans who
really care about the sport. We may have some fluctuation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Gillom, the Phoenix Mercury's All-Star center, noticed
the drop in attendance during a June 24 game against the Sting at
Charlotte Coliseum. She could hear sections of fans yelling her
name in a modest crowd of 4,514. The place had such little density
that it might have floated in water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It concerned me a lot,'' Gillom said. ``I'm looking for this
league to go up, not take a step back. It's hard to put a finger on
it. The players have definitely made an impression on the fans.
That's why I guess it surprised me.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 franchises that had teams last season, only one _
Sacramento _ has seen its attendance increase this season. The two
expansion teams, Minnesota and Orlando, are averaging 9,703 and
8,631 fans. The previous 10 franchises had averaged 10,334 in their
first seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte is averaging a league-worst 6,139 fans, approaching
the single-season mark for low attendance set by Sacramento's
average of 6,578 last summer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   League officials seem puzzled about why there has been a
decrease. They have their guesses. While Ackerman said the
attendance has tended to increase during the second half of the
season, she said the late-ending NBA season took some of the luster
off the start of the WNBA season. The attention given to Wimbledon
earlier this month and then to the U.S. women's soccer team during
its World Cup run did not directly compete with the WNBA for fans,
Ackerman said, but news media hype definitely swayed that way.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, when the league began, the league had all the
attention. The WNBA originally expected to draw 4,000 to 5,000
fans. The leaguewide average that first season was 9,669.
Expectations have since increased, and the goal is now to average
10,000 fans per game leaguewide, as was done last season. And in
spite of the 12 percent decrease so far, that goal is clearly
within reach this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty point guard Teresa Weatherspoon, whose team is averaging
12,682 fans this season (down from 14,935 last season but second
best in the league), is not alarmed by the attendance figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it's a concern, but I really don't look into the
stands,'' she said. ``Our job is to go out and do the best we can.
The fans usually respond to that.''
</P>
<P>
   WNBA officials like to throw out a comparison to the brother
league, the NBA, to keep attendance in perspective. The NBA did not
average 10,000 fans per game leaguewide until 1975-76, a full 29
years after the league was founded. The WNBA did it in year two.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flat attendance thus far is not to the extent that the sky
is falling,'' said Dean Bonham, the head of the Bonham Group, a
Denver sports marketing firm that specializes in analyzing
financial deals for sports properties. ``The WNBA is not going to
be like any other sports league because it started up unlike any
other start up in history. It's really a joint venture, more than
it is a start up of a major league.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a lot of synergy with the NBA that keeps costs down
and makes them have great promotion and marketing. But most of its
real success will start being measured after Year 3. The people who
will be long-term fans will start to show.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonham suggested that the league should focus on two things:
quality of the product and drawing a fan base of young females.
</P>
<P>
   No one doubts that the ABL players have helped the league as new
stars like Sacramento's Yolanda Griffith, Utah's Natalie Williams,
Charlotte's Dawn Staley and Minnesota's Tonya Edwards have emerged.
</P>
<P>
   About 75 percent of the fans who go to WNBA games are female,
according to league demographic studies. The WNBA's figures also
show that boys and girls ages 7 to 17 make up about 20 percent of
the attendance. And, the league says, there is little overlap with
NBA season ticket-holders. Only about 10 percent of NBA season
ticket-holders are WNBA season ticket-holders.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's not like most of our fans are checking `yes' on the
back of their NBA season tickets to come watch us,'' Ackerman said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the growth of the league lies within its ability to
market its marquee players. While the WNBA has done a tremendous
job of marketing the Washington rookie forward Chamique Holdsclaw
and most of the prime players who have been with the league since
it started, most of the former ABL stars are still unknown
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Only one former ABL player _ Nikki McCray, who bolted a year
before the league folded _ was voted as a starter for the All-Star
Game. Five others were selected as reserves, which means that six
of the 22 All-Stars once played in the rival league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the players from the ABL aren't used to so much hype,
but they are great players with great stories,'' said Maura McHugh,
an assistant coach with Sacramento who used to be the head coach of
the ABL's Long Beach franchise. ``I hope that, in time, people will
really recognize that they are elite players, and people will
realize that there are so many great players to choose from.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one of those players will shine at the first All-Star
game Wednesday night. It is a stage _ national television, a
sellout crowd and a purposeful date on which there is no
major-league baseball _ that could give the league a jolt, the kind
that you would give to a car whose battery has run down
temporarily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
