<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON.COM TO EXPAND SALES OF ELECTRONICS AND TOYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moving to position itself as the Internet's first true
department store, Amazon.com plans to introduce two new divisions
Tuesday, one for consumer electronics and another for toys.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon has grown from just an online bookseller into the largest
Internet retailer by far, with more than 10 million customers. In
addition to books, Amazon already operates sections for music and
videos, as well as an auction site. Analysts estimate its sales
will exceed $1.3 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   Through a gifts section it introduced last year, Amazon has
offered a handful of toys and electronics items. But now it will
offer thousands of products in each category.
</P>
<P>
   So far, neither category has attracted many sales on the
Internet. In 1999, online sales of toys will be $52 million,
according to estimates by Jupiter Communications, the Internet
research firm, and sales of electronics will be $78 million. By
contrast, online book sales will be $1.1 billion, Jupiter
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   In toys, unlike electronics, some prominent online merchants
have emerged. The leader is eToys, which went public earlier this
year and has established a well-known brand and quality reputation.
But its sales in the fiscal year ended in March only amounted to
$30 million. Toys ``R'' Us, the leading toy-store chain, has
fumbled its first online efforts and is now working on a new
initiative in conjunction with Silicon Valley venture capitalists.
Kay-Bee Toys, the chain owned by Consolidated Stores Corp., bought
Brainplay.com, a specialized Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   The electronics field is more fragmented, with a handful of
start-ups, like 800.com, and electronics sections on larger sites,
like Cendant Corp.'s Netmarket. One hurdle to online electronics
sales has been that large manufacturers like Sony have not wanted
many of their products sold online. In part, this has been to
protect their local dealers, but some manufacturers have been
deciding whether to open online stores of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bezos, Amazon's chief executive, said that the company,
which is based in Seattle, had been able to get access to a wide
range of consumer electronics products, but he declined to say how
many items Amazon would carry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can go to a manufacturer and say we bring 10 million
experienced online shoppers and the ability to do a good job
selling your product,'' Bezos said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that in toys, the battle between Amazon and Etoys
will be hard fought. ``In terms of customer service, they are both
singing from the same choir book,'' said Mark Johnson, an analyst
with Jupiter. ``Amazon just has unbelievable scale and a much
larger customer base.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not so long ago skeptics were predicting that Amazon
would wilt in competition with Barnes &AMP; Noble, the much larger
bookseller. That did not happen, and Toby Lenk, chief executive of
eToys, said his company could be the David to slay Amazon's
Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   His company's strength, he said, was its specialization in goods
for children. And eToys has initiated a preemptive strike, opening
its own children's bookstore on Tuesday, with 85,000 titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same rules don't apply when you sell things for kids than
when you sell books,'' Lenk said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Amazon offers a service that lets regular customers
buy items with a single click of the mouse, assuming they have
already entered their shipping address and credit card number. Lenk
said that eToys requires a password for customers to complete
purchases to prevent kids from charging away on their parents'
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Bezos argued that the one-click purchase system would be an
important convenience for customers and would drive impulse
purchases. Customers, he noted, have the option of disabling the
feature. What is more, he said, since Amazon would store and ship
all its products from its network of warehouses around the country,
customers could combine books, toys and electronics in one order
and save on shipping costs.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Amazon's toy store emulates the look of eToys, with lots
of information about toys and suggestions for children, broken out
by age groups. Amazon said that it was spending even more to
develop reviews and other information content about its products.
For example, it said it had hired Dr. Penelope Leach, the noted
pediatrician and author of several well-regarded books on child
rearing, to recommend educational toys.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, for the consumer electronics section, it has hired
editors to write buying guides and individual product reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time, we will do a full Consumer Reports-level of
testing,'' Bezos said. For now, the company does not accept any
money from toy or electronics manufacturers to promote their
products. Eventually, it will charge fees for prominent placement
of positive reviews, as it does with books.
</P>
<P>
   But Bezos said the opinion in the review would be independent of
any fee paid by the manufacturer. And in both categories, readers
will be able to submit their own product reviews and ratings, as
they do with books, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bezos would not say how much these new departments would
contribute to Amazon's sales, but he noted that the company's past
expansions had grown quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We launched music and four months later we were the leading
seller of music online,'' Bezos said. ``And we became the No. 1
seller of videos in 45 days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
