<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7449 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-INTERN-ART-2T     07-12 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-INTERN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM SEEKS REALITY BEHIND FASHION'S CAREFUL MAKEUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036. 
(md) 
 By CATHY HORYN  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Jill Kopelman was a girl of 9 or 10, she would
accompany her father, Arie L. Kopelman, the president of Chanel
Inc., on business trips to Paris, and among the fashion players she
liked to watch were Elizabeth Saltzman and Andre Leon Talley, both
editors at Conde Nast. Little did they know they were helping a
young writer sharpen her eye and ear for the nuances of the fashion
world.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Kopelman, now 25, said shortly before filming began on
``Intern,'' a romantic comedy she and her friend Caroline Doyle
wrote, ``I would sit in the Ritz bar and, like, eavesdrop on their
conversations while my parents talked about taxes or something.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, as extras took their places at Il Cantinori,
the restaurant on East 10th Street, Ms. Saltzman, the fashion
director of Vanity Fair, and Talley, the editor-at-large at Vogue,
were ready for their close-ups. They are playing themselves in the
movie. And so, too, will the designers Tommy Hilfiger, Cynthia
Rowley, John Bartlett and Narciso Rodriguez. Making a cameo
appearance at Il Cantinori was the actress Gwyneth Paltrow. Ms.
Paltrow, who won the Oscar this year for best actress, has been a
close friend of Ms. Doyle's since they were at Spence, the Upper
East Side girls' school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy for her and Jill,'' Ms. Paltrow said, as her hair
was being combed out on the first day of filming. ``They're so
talented, and the script is funny and irreverent. I think this is
the beginning of a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie is about a 23-year-old fashion magazine intern, played
by Dominique Swain, who from the bottom of the heap gets to observe
the narcissism of fashion's upper reaches. The script is mean,
outrageous and darkly funny, and it reflects the writers'
experiences as interns at Harper's Bazaar, Mademoiselle and
Interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``The characters are all based on real editors,'' Ms. Kopelman
said. ``The most hyperbolic scenes are 100 percent true. All the
actors who came in for auditions said: `This is crazy! How did you
think this up?' But it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing a scene in which the movie's heroine, Jocelyn, is
approached by the beauty editor of the fictional magazine Skirt, Ms
Doyle said: ``The editor walks up to Jocelyn and says, `Bob.' And
she says, `No, Jocelyn.' And the editor says, `No, you need a
bob.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Doyle smiled. ``That happened to me. Then the real editor
said: `Look at this picture of Linda Evangelista. You don't know
how many thousands of people would kill for my advice.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Doyle, who was a Russian studies major at Barnard College
and spent three years in Moscow helping to start the Russian
edition of Marie Claire before she decided to leave magazines and
write ``Intern,'' added: ``There's that fine line being an intern
at a fashion magazine. You don't know if you're supposed to be
going to get the dry cleaning of the person you're working for. Or
sending flowers to her friends or buying gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kopelman interjected, ``Or retyping Rolodexes.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its perversity and potential for satire, the fashion
world (and its parallel universe of fashion magazines) has proven
resistant to the comic skills of filmmakers. No director, with the
exception of Stanley Donen, who made the 1957 movie ``Funny Face,''
has been able to do much more than sneer at a few eccentric home
folk _ and Donen had the advantage of working in an era that still
could be amused by a character not unlike Diana Vreeland, who coos
such lines as ``Think pink!''
</P>
<P>
   Woody Allen failed to excite audiences with his 1998 film
``Celebrity,'' and of course, there was the famous letdown of
``Ready to Wear,'' which the director Robert Altman filmed in 1994
during the Paris collections. Altman seemed to have everything
going for him. He had big stars, credentials, the involvement of
the fashion world _ everything that is, except a cliche-free
script.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the only filmmaker who got the fashion world right was
Douglas Keeve, who made ``Unzipped,'' the 1995 documentary about
Isaac Mizrahi. That was in part because Keeve had access to
Mizrahi, and in part because his humor was at right angles to the
fashion industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intern,'' which will also star Peggy Lipton and Joan Rivers
(as a swooning editor), is being made on a shoestring budget of $1
million. Its producers, Galt Niederhoffer and Daniela Soto-Taplin
of Given Films in SoHo, made the 1997 film ``Hurricane Street'' and
later this year will produce the film version of ``Prozac Nation,''
starring Christina Ricci. They don't think of ``Intern'' as
strictly a fashion movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Cinderella story,'' Ms. Soto-Taplin said, referring to
the office romance that blossoms between Ms. Swain's character,
Jocelyn, and Paul, the magazine's token heterosexual male, played
by a newcomer, Ben Pullen. Ms. Niederhoffer added that neither she
nor her partner knew much about fashion and that they decided to
produce the script simply because they were charmed by its language
and array of characters, like a model named Resin whose best friend
is called Aloha.
</P>
<P>
   ``As in Amber and Shalom,'' Ms. Kopelman said with a grin.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The story behind ``Intern'' is every aspiring screenwriter's
dream. Last fall, Ms. Doyle and Ms. Kopelman, who had graduated
from Yale University and was working at Interview, decided to quit
their jobs and write a screenplay, working mostly on the Doyles'
dining room table. Ms. Doyle's mother, Kathleen Doyle, owns William
Doyle Galleries, the the auction house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had just broken my engagement, Ms. Kopelman recalled, and
her mother and father ``were devastated.'' ``Then I announced I was
going to write a screenplay,'' she added. ``My parents are the best
parents, but I think it was just the odds that were speaking to
them. Every busboy across America has a script.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a month they had finished ``Intern.'' It took them
another month to find an agent, although it was Ms. Kopelman who
sent the script to Ms. Niederhoffer, whom she knew through a mutual
friend. The day before Ms. Niederhoffer called to say she wanted to
buy the script, both Ms. Doyle and Ms. Kopelman were offered jobs
with magazines that anyone eager to move out of their parents'
apartments would have accepted. But they declined.
</P>
<P>
   And even though it took just a week to sell the script, with no
strings attached like rewriting, Ms. Kopelman said her parents
remained cautious. ``They didn't want me to get excited,'' she
said. ``They were, like `That's great. We're happy for you, but
don't get your hopes up because these kind of things often don't
get made.' They really didn't believe it until it was in Variety.''
</P>
<P>
   The screenwriters will serve as associate producers of the film.
They were involved with choosing the director, Michael Lange, whose
credits include episodes of ``The X-Files'' and ``The Tracey Ullman
Show,'' and they went to auditions for the cast. Indeed, it is
through their New York connections, both personal and professional,
that Ms. Doyle and Ms. Kopelman have been able to arrange some of
the locations during the four weeks of filming (including the
Chanel offices and the Doyle Galleries). Graydon Carter, the editor
in chief of Vanity Fair, said they could film in his magazine's
offices _ provided they cast his summer intern. ``It seemed a fair
ransom,'' Ms. Kopelman conceded. They helped to entice Jimmy
Hanrahan, who does costumes for MTV, to handle wardrobe. And of
course, they brought in Ms. Saltzman, Ms. Paltrow and Talley.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Talley, who wore a white Fendi mink coat for his scene
at Il Cantinori, needed much enticement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great script,'' Talley told Ms. Kopelman with a
flourish of his hand. ``I'll tell you, I wouldn't have done it if
it wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kopelman beamed. ``Well, we're so psyched,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The young women, no longer novices, have already written their
second script, and have formed their own production company, which
they are calling Skirt Films, after the magazine in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what they plan to do next, Ms. Kopelman laughed and said,
``We want to get a new agent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
