<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COST OF DRINK RECALL RISES FOR COCA-COLA'S BOTTLER
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's bottler, Coca-Cola Enterprises, said that it would
take a $103 million charge against second-quarter earnings to cover
expenses associated with the recall of soft drinks in Europe last
month, about 70 percent more than previously acknowledged. The
charge erases second-quarter earnings for the bottler. Coca-Cola
Enterprises said two weeks ago that the recall involved 14 million
cases of soft drinks and would cost the company $60 million. But
that number ballooned after 17 million cases of products were
returned.
</P>
<P>
   SCHLUMBERGER TO SPIN OFF A UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Schlumberger said that it had agreed to spin off its offshore
drilling unit, Sedco Forex Offshore, and merge it with Transocean
Offshore to create the world's largest offshore oil-drilling
company. Both companies said that the spinoff was spurred by the
high cost and greater technological demands of offshore oil
exploration, where drilling is taking place in ever-deeper waters.
Shares of Schlumberger rose 62.5 cents, to $64.9375.
</P>
<P>
   TOYOTA COULD FACE BILLIONS IN FINES
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department accused Toyota of putting faulty
smog-control computers on 2.2 million vehicles in a lawsuit that
carries the potential for nearly $60 billion in fines.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN SACHS TO BUY HULL GROUP
</P>
<P>
   Signaling its support for new ways of trading securities,
Goldman Sachs Group announces it will buy Hull Group, a leading
electronic trading company, for $531 million.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE DEBATES RIGHTS OF PATIENTS
</P>
<P>
   The Senate opens a high-stakes debate over how to protect the
rights of patients and regulate the companies that provide health
insurance for most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   CUTBACK IN JEEP GRAND CHEROKEES
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler is slowing production of the Jeep Grand Cherokee
to a rate of 294,000 a year, down 60,000, in a sign that sales
growth of sport utility vehicles may be easing.
</P>
<P>
   DOW EDGES UP, BUT NASDAQ SLIPS
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were mixed in light volume. The Dow Jones industrial
average edged up 7.28 points, to 11,200.98, a record. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500-stock index slipped 4.18 points, to 1,399.10, and the
Nasdaq composite fell 2.63 points, to 2,790.44.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices rallied, driving yields to six-week lows. The yield
of the 30-year bond fell to 5.9 percent from 6 percent on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   IBM PLANS TO ACQUIRE SEQUENT
</P>
<P>
   Sequent Computer Systems, which was founded by former Intel
executives and engineers, including Casey Powell, the company's
chairman and chief executive, agreed to be acquired by IBM for $810
million. Sequent was formed to create a new computer that would tie
together multiple microprocessors, but despite market-leading
technology, the company has struggled to increase sales in
competition with larger rivals.
</P>
<P>
   NEW PUBLISHER FOR THE BOSTON GLOBE
</P>
<P>
   A senior executive of The New York Times, Richard Gilman, has
been named the publisher of The Boston Globe, which the Times Co.
owns. He replaces Benjamin Taylor, 52, who will continue as the
chairman of Globe Newspaper Co. Board.
</P>
<P>
   NAACP TO PRESSURE NETWORKS
</P>
<P>
   The president of the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored people announced the start of a campaign to pressure
television networks and advertisers to include more minorities in
prime-time shows.
</P>
<P>
   FTC DOES NOT BACK ONLINE LAW
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission has approved a report recommending
that Congress hold off on legislation to regulate how companies can
collect and use consumer data online.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS PLUMMET 8.7 PERCENT IN ARGENTINA
</P>
<P>
   The Argentine stock market had its worst session in seven
months, falling 8.7 percent on fears that the government deficit
was widening and a recession was deepening.
</P>
</TEXT>
