<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7452 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILITARY-SPENDING-NYT     07-12 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-SPENDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE STOPS FUNDING FOR PURCHASE OF FIRST F-22 FIGHTERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)   By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A House panel dealt a potential death blow Monday
to the Air Force's 21st-century flagship, the F-22 jet fighter,
voting to withhold the $1.8 billion that had been budgeted to buy
the first of the planes.
</P>
<P>
   The House committee that appropriates military money told the
Air Force to rethink or reject the $70 billion program, which is
behind schedule and $1 billion over budget. It ``sent a signal to
the Air Force saying, `We want you to seek a new direction,''' said
the committee chairman, Rep. Jerry Lewis, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force intends the F-22 to be its premier fighter for the
first half of the 21st century, replacing the F-15. But the
unanimous decision by the House Appropriations Committee's defense
subcommittee, which includes some of the most dedicated hawks in
Congress, put the program's future in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has three fighter jets on the drawing board _ the
F-22, the Joint Strike Fighter, and an updated F-18. The
subcommittee said Monday that this may be one plane too many. The
three jets have a combined price of about $350 billion, a sum far
in excess of the entire Pentagon budget for this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not enough money to fund all these three programs,''
said the subcommittee's ranking Democrat, Rep. John Murtha of
Pennsylvania. ``Down the road, the money's not there.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis concurred. ``I do not believe we can afford three lines of
tactical fighters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The F-22 has passed only 5 percent of its flight tests. Its
manufacturers are having trouble connecting the plane's wings to
its body and perfecting the cockpit computers that drive its
navigation and war-fighting systems, government auditors say. But
the Air Force and the main contractor, Lockheed Martin, were set on
building 438 of the fighters, at a cost that independent estimates
have placed at $70 billion and rising.
</P>
<P>
   Congress and the Air Force were on the verge of giving Lockheed
Martin billions to begin building the first 16 planes in 2000 and
2001. But government critics of the program, including the auditors
of the General Accounting Office, called that plan a
``buy-before-you-fly'' boondoggle.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Rodrigues, a senior GAO official, questioned in testimony
before Congress in March whether the Air Force wanted to put
billions into an ``increasing rate of production on an aircraft
we're having trouble producing.'' The House Armed Services
Committee reported in May that it was ``concerned by significant
increases in F-22 budgets'' and ``disturbed by the prospect of
higher costs and increased program risks.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to eliminate financing for the first F-22s, made in
secret Monday morning and officially announced at 4 p.m., shocked
the Air Force and Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are obviously surprised,'' said Tom Burbage, president of
Lockheed Martin Aeronautical Systems in Marietta, Ga., which had
mounted a large and sophisticated advertising program to build
public and political support for the F-22 program. ``We do not
understand the subcommittee's rationale.''
</P>
<P>
   Air Force officers said Monday night that they had just learned
of the move and were trying to gauge its severity. A senior
Pentagon official said ``the Department of Defense was surprised
and disappointed'' by the decision and would work to reverse it.
</P>
<P>
   The House panel left $1.2 billion for F-22 research and
development in its spending bill, giving the program a chance to
continue. But unless the panel rescinds its decision on the $1.8
billion, the first F-22s cannot be built. With criticism coming
from across the political spectrum of the House, the program is in
peril.
</P>
<P>
   The money for the first jets was redirected to other Air Force
programs. Had it been spent to buy the F-22s, members of the
defense appropriations panel said, the $70 billion program could
have gone forward regardless of its technical problems and costs,
driven by a too-late-to-stop-now mentality that has propelled
troubled Pentagon programs in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we wait much longer before we take this step, there'll
never be a chance to get off this track,'' Lewis said. ``You'd
better do it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress rarely kills major military procurement programs
outright, preferring to let them die lingering deaths or have the
Pentagon perform the coup de grace. The last big Air Force fighter
program to be eliminated was the A-12 fighter, shot down by Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney in 1992 after he determined that he had been
deceived about the plane's shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.8 billion for the first F-22s remains in the Senate's
version of the Pentagon spending bill. Once the full House passes
its military spending measure, the two bills must be reconciled.
Lewis and Murtha said they thought the Senate would concur with the
decision to eliminate the money for the F-22s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
