<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7455 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTINGS-COX     07-12 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Bodies were all over the house': 5 adults, 2 children found
dead
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa and Jay Croft
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It could be days before police learn what happened at
3783 Adamsville Drive Monday, the site of Atlanta's worst mass
killing this century.
</P>
<P>
   The case so far depends largely on the accounts of the sole
survivor, an 11-year-old boy who was shot in the elbow and hid in a
closet for eight hours before fleeing to a neighbor's house.
</P>
<P>
   Five adults and two children, ages 9 and 11, were found shot
inside the house on the quiet residential street. Investigators
said the motive was unclear and they had scant details by Monday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bodies were all over the house,'' said Deputy Chief C.B.
Jackson of the Atlanta Police Department. ``We're investigating it
currently as a multiple homicide. The possibility does exist that
one of the persons inside, who is also deceased, is responsible for
all the shootings and that injury to himself was self-inflicted.''
</P>
<P>
   The shooting began about 6 a.m. and did not last long, Jackson
said the boy told police.
</P>
<P>
   Police were called at 2:38 p.m. by Evelyn Broadus, who lives
next to the house where the killings occurred in southwest Atlanta
off Martin Luther King Jr. Drive. The neighborhood is made up of
single-family homes with well-kept yards, and residents described
it as quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Broadus heard a knock at her door in the early afternoon and
found her 11-year-old neighbor, shivering, his arm bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbor Georgia Hall said the boy told her his stepfather had
shot ``everyone in the house.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said: `My stepfather shot my mama, my auntie, my brother,
everyone,' '' Hall said, shaking her head. ``We immediately called
911. We could not believe what had happened. We just called the
police and sat with the boy.''
</P>
<P>
   But when officers arrived, they were kept at bay by a
Rotteweiler and a pit bull, which stood inside the entrance
guarding the bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took investigators almost three hours to get inside,'' said
police spokesman John Quigley. ``The dogs would not let them in.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County Animal Control officials coaxed the dogs out and
put them into two small trucks. Homicide detectives, uniformed
officers and a handful of top brass then spilled into the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you might imagine, there are bodies in a number of rooms,
there is quite a bit of blood,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Officers found at least one weapon in the house, Jackson said.
Family members and friends who flocked to the neighborhood said two
of the adults shot were sisters Dana Briskey and Essie Hugeley. The
women's grandmother, Hattie Mae Hugeley, arrived at the house after
hearing about the killings from her grandson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taking a nap and my grandson ran into the bedroom and
said, `Grandma are you watching the news? I think Dana and Essie
and some of their kids have been murdered,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two women were my granddaughters. This hurts. This hurts
a lot. Those children are my great-grandchildren and they're
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Police would not identify the dead and did not say how they were
related.
</P>
<P>
   No previous mass killing in Atlanta claimed as many victims, at
least as far back as the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as December 1995, two men sprayed bullets into men
playing cards in a ramshackle house, killing four. Brothers Elijah
and Freeman Salahuddin were charged with the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's killing brought back memories of the notorious 1973
Alday family murders in Seminole County, Ga. The family interrupted
a burglary at their mobile home by three escaped Maryland
prisoners. Ned Alday, his brother Aubrey, sons Jerry, Chester and
Jimmy, and Jerry's wife, Mary were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The surviving boy of Monday's shooting was awake, alert and in
good condition, officials at Grady Memorial Hospital said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's interacted fairly well with the physicians and nursing
staff of the emergency department answering questions
appropriately, given the things that he's gone through,'' Dr. Leon
Haley said.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Fuller, who lives two doors down from the boy, described
the him as a smart, happy go-lucky child.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just as sweet as he could be, and God had to be with
him for him to hide,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sisters Jocynta and Kiera Lewis stood outside watching the house
they had visited many times, since Briskey and Essie Hugeley moved
there almost four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   They said the sisters lived there with their children and a man
who had been dating Briskey for about a year. They said Briskey and
Essie Hugeley were close and loving with their children and that
the man was often seen playing and talking with the youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Said 22-year-old Jocynta Lewis, tears streaming down her face:
``What could have set this man off this way?''
</P>
<P>
   Lyda Longa and Jay Croft write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga. Ismail Turay Jr., Stephanie
Reid, Doug Payne and the Atlanta Journal-Constitution News Research
Department contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
