r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WELLS-WELLS_SFCHRON &LR;      07-12 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELLS-WELLS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Wells Exec's Comments Raise SEC Eyebrows  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The Securities and Exchange Commission recently challenged Wells
Fargo about the bank's apparently contradictory statements on job
cuts following its merger with Minnesota's Norwest in November.
<P>
   The bank said the federal watchdog agency queried it after Chief
Operating Officer Leslie Biller told the Minneapolis Star-Tribune
in March that a 5 percent staff cutback described in the bank's
1998 annual report was something ``we don't even think is going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle of a top executive publicly disparaging the bank's
official financial statement prompted the SEC to write in April
asking for an explanation, Wells Fargo spokesman Larry Haeg said.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the agency wanted to know whether Biller's comment
meant that a $280 million charge the bank took for merger-related
severance costs in the fourth quarter of 1998 wasn't warranted. The
SEC is responsible for ensuring the accuracy of public financial
statements.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``They said, `You accrued $280 million for position
eliminations. Have things changed?''' said Haeg.
</P>
<P>
   The bank told the SEC that it believed its job-cut projections
were accurate and the severance charge proper. The agency sent a
letter asking for further clarification in May and has not
contacted the bank since, Haeg said.
</P>
<P>
   SEC spokesman John Heine declined to comment on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   But, speaking generally, Heine said the agency often asks
companies to justify accounting actions if there is evidence they
weren't appropriate. The SEC can force companies to restate
earnings if financial reports already have been issued.
</P>
<P>
   The letters were from the SEC's division of corporation finance,
which supervises accounting practices. Such queries aren't
potentially as serious as inquiries from the agency's enforcement
division, which can result in fines or other sanctions if
violations of securities laws are found.
</P>
<P>
   Biller's comments reflected the bank's eagerness to portray
itself as a friendly employer even as it was slashing about 4,600
of its total of 92,000 full-time positions. The job cuts are
scheduled to take place through 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's Norwest bought Wells Fargo, took its name and made
San Francisco the headquarters of the combined bank. Although the
old Wells Fargo was known as a hard-driving employer, Norwest had a
reputation for pampering its workers.
</P>
<P>
   Since the merger, the bank has stressed finding new jobs for
employees whose positions are scheduled to disappear as duplicate
operations of the two banks are shut.
</P>
<P>
   Before the new Wells Fargo issued its annual report early this
year, the bank had claimed that it didn't know how many positions
it would eliminate as a result of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   The bank has said it was reluctant to disclose a specific number
because it feared doing so would cast a spotlight on the
destruction of jobs rather than on its programs to keep and retrain
displaced workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Les was concerned that a discussion of job elimination would
have a negative effect on morale,'' Haeg said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
