A7459 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOYOTA-POLLUTION-NYT &LR;      07-12 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYOTA-POLLUTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL LAWSUIT ACCUSES TOYOTA OF VIOLATING CLEAN AIR ACT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The federal government sued Toyota on Monday, accusing
it of violating the Clean Air Act by selling 2.2 million cars on
which the ``check engine'' light would not illuminate even when the
vehicles are emitting excessive pollution.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is the latest in a series of similar disputes
pitting the government against automakers and truck makers. In each
case, the government has contended that the vehicles' computer
diagnostic equipment had been programmed to meet federal standards
during laboratory tests, but not during actual driving on the road.
</P>
<P>
   What sets the Toyota case apart is the company's decision to
fight the government in court. In previous cases involving General
Motors in 1995, Honda a year ago and seven manufacturers of
heavy-duty diesel engines last October, the manufacturers chose to
pay fines and take remedial action before litigation began.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota's stance in theory exposes it to large penalties.
Christine Romano, a Justice Department spokeswoman, said that under
the Clean Air Act, Toyota could face a fine of $25,000 to $27,500
for each of 2.2 million vehicles that allegedly failed to comply,
depending on when each vehicle was sold.
</P>
<P>
   But the maximum possible penalty, nearly $60 billion, is
extremely unlikely. The law directs judges to consider a company's
economic gain from pollution, its previous environmental record and
its ability to stay in business if it pays the maximum fine. Toyota
has a fairly good environmental record, its gains from the alleged
pollution are unclear and the maximum fine would equal eight months
of its global sales.
</P>
<P>
   Previous settlements out of court have been much smaller. Honda,
for example, settled a similar dispute a year ago involving 1.7
million Honda and Acura automobiles. To offset any emissions from
vehicles with poorly functioning warning lights, Honda extended the
warranty on all of these vehicles' emissions equipment to 14 years
or 150,000 miles instead of three years or 36,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Honda also paid $10.1 million in federal fines and $2.5 million
in fines to California, which also accused the automaker of
violating state rules. And Honda agreed to pay for $1 million of
federal environmental research and $3.5 million of environmental
research by California. The $17.1 million in payments plus the
warranty costs were considerably less than the company's likely
liability of more than $42.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   California also ordered Toyota last September to come up with a
plan to fix 330,000 vehicles sold there that are among the 2.2
million vehicles involved in the federal case. Toyota refused, and
hearings began Monday before an administrative law judge in
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   In the federal case, Toyota on Friday rejected a federal
settlement offer that included a fine of $75 per car, making the
cost in excess of $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   The current dispute involves vehicles' so-called evaporative
emissions of unburned gasoline, which contributes to smog. Toyota
contends that state and federal rules only require vehicles'
warning lights to meet tests in laboratories. Tiny quantities of
gasoline fumes constantly escape from a vehicle's gas cap and from
joints in the gasoline tank and fuel lines. These losses are
monitored by vehicles in recent model years using systems that
measure the pressure of the gasoline vapor in the system. A warning
light is supposed to go on when the pressure falls while the
ignition is on.
</P>
<P>
   In a complaint filed Monday in the federal court for the
District of Columbia, the Justice Department said that Toyota had
put computer software into its vehicle that caused the engine light
to turn on only when unacceptable evaporative emissions coincided
with a certain pattern of stops and accelerations. This pattern is
used in the test but rarely occurs in the real world, the complaint
said, adding that Toyota did not disclose the existence of the
software to regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The rules do not give regulators the authority to conduct random
checks, as they have done, of whether the vehicles actually perform
in use the way they did in the laboratory, said Joseph Tetherow, a
company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicles, ``only had to meet lab tests,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When California first adopted rules in 1991 regarding the
evaporative emissions and the activation of engine lights, Toyota
developed a system and it passed the state's laboratory tests and
was certified for use, Tetherow said, adding, ``They said it was in
compliance, they gave their approval before we went ahead and put
it in our vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Martin, a spokesman for the California Air Resources
Board, said that, ``in-use compliance has always been a part of the
board's program.'' Regardless of how the administrative law judge
rules, the board can subsequently rule for or against the company,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental regulators contend that without reliable warning
lights, consumers will not know when their vehicles start producing
unacceptable levels of pollution. Carol Browner, the administrator
of the Environmental Protection Agency, said Monday night that,
``Today's action shows this administration's commitment to insure
that companies will not profit from polluting and that the public
health will be protected.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department filed Monday's lawsuit on behalf of the
Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The suit covers most of Toyota's vehicles from the 1996 through
1998 model years. Specifically, it covers Lexus cars as well as
Toyota Camry, Avalon, Corolla, Tercel, and Paseo cars; Sienna
minivans; 4Runner and RAV4 sport utility vehicles; and Tacoma and
T100 pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Tetherow said that none of the vehicles involved posed any
threat to the environment or public safety. If the warning lights
on all of these vehicles failed, the combined annual evaporation of
hydrocarbons from their fuel tanks and engines would be equal to
the painting of two medium-sized houses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clean Air Act allows a maximum penalty of $25,000 per
vehicle sold by Jan. 31, 1997, and $27,500 per vehicle sold after
that. Toyota sold 588,650 vehicles in the 1996 model year with the
contested emissions systems, 857,620 in the 1997 model year and
735,897 in the 1998 model year.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Romano said she did not have the precise number sold
before Jan. 31, 1997 _ when the peak penalty rose _ making it
impossible to calculate precisely the maximum overall penalty
possible in the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
