<HEADER>
A7460 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEMICON-SEMICON_SFCHR     07-12 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEMICON-SEMICON </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Chip Equipment Industry Is Back From the Brink  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
After a devastating 1998, the semiconductor equipment industry _
the companies that make the machines that make chips _ is back on
the growth curve.
<P>
   As equipment-makers and their customers gathered at the Moscone
Center yesterday for the 29th annual Semicon West trade show, the
mood was mostly upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the industry was mired in its sharpest decline in
recent memory, battered by the Asian economic crisis, technological
uncertainties and a glut of unsold chips and PCs. But in recent
months, sales of new equipment have been recovering, and industry
leaders now project continued improvement as chipmakers retool to
accommodate new markets and changes in manufacturing technology.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the trade association that sponsors Semicon West
anticipates so much growth that it's contemplating moving the
sprawling show out of the Bay Area, on the grounds that the region
lacks the exhibit facilities and hotel space that will be required
in future years. The weeklong show, which this year features almost
4,400 booths and is expected to attract some 75,000 attendees, is
already split in two: One segment runs through tomorrow
Wednesday &LR; at the Moscone Center, while a second will be staged in
San Jose tomorrow through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a difference a year makes,'' said Stanley T. Myers,
president of Semiconductor Equipment and Materials International,
the trade group that sponsors the show. According to a survey of
member companies that together account for about 80 percent of the
industry's total sales, revenues for 1999 should be up 9 percent
from over &LR; last year, to a total of $23.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That's still short of industry revenues before last year's
21-percent drop. But companies responding to the survey projected
18.3 percent growth next year, which would bring the total back to
its historic high, and then further growth of 21.8 percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies, however, have yet to benefit from the upturn.
``It's bifurcated recovery,'' said Mark FitzGerald, vice president
of securities research and economics at Merrill Lynch in San
Francisco. ``The companies doing well are those delivering advanced
technology that can help chip manufacturers get their costs down.''
</P>
<P>
   Makers of chips destined for use in PCs are the equipment
manufacturers' largest customers, and pressures growing out of
declining prices and intense competition in the PC market are
``filtering down through the whole food chain,'' FitzGerald said.
</P>
<P>
   These cost pressures are hitting just as the industry is facing
what Myers called ``a materials revolution.'' For nearly 20 years,
most chips have been made with the same basic set of raw materials.
But now, chipmakers are replacing aluminum, the material
traditionally used for the microscopic wires connecting the
millions of transistors on their products, with copper, which
offers better performance.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the industry is moving to a new production process
that reduces the size of on-chip circuits from .25 micron to .18
micron _ about a five-hundredth the width of a human hair. And it's
starting to make its chips out of silicon wafers 12 inches in
diameter, instead of the current 8-inch wafer format.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the hype as well as the new-product announcements at the
show involved copper. Novellus Systems of San Jose took over the
Yerba Buena Center for the Arts for a multimedia extravaganza,
including a nauseating ride on a rocket-ship simulator, designed to
turn showgoers into ``agents of change'' promoting the move to
copper.
</P>
<P>
   KLA-Tencor, a San Jose company that specializes in diagnostic
and yield-improvement tools, also created a 3-D video tour of the
inside of a chip to show how its new electron-beam monitoring
device can detect flaws in copper-based production.
</P>
<P>
   Novellus and others hope the transition to new materials will
help them gain ground on the traditional industry leader, Applied
Materials of Santa Clara, whose 1998 revenues of $4 billion made it
roughly twice as big as the next largest player, Japan's Tokyo
Electron.
</P>
<P>
   James Morgan, Applied's CEO since 1976, insisted his company,
noted for the breadth of its product line, is ready for the
challenge. ``There are seven fundamental processes in chip
production, and we have a lead in most of them,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Semicon West's future in the Bay Area, the trade group is
committed to keeping the show here in 2000 and 2001, but hasn't
made a decision about subsequent years. Myers said the group has
considered sites in Austin, Boston and especially Las Vegas. The
main problem, he said, is the shortage of hotel and exhibit space
here.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco currently ranks 12th in the nation in convention
space, according to Doug Neilson, vice president of the San
Francisco Convention and Visitors Bureau. Moscone West, a new
building scheduled to open in 2003, will add 300,000 square feet to
the center's current 442,00 square feet of exhibit space, he said,
but even that might not be enough for Semicon West, currently the
largest show, in terms of exhibit space, held here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping the other advantages San Francisco offers will
keep them here,'' said Neilson. ``But ultimately the city is never
going to be a place for mega-trade shows _ we just don't have the
space here.''
</P>
<P>
