<HEADER>
A7461 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UGA-DISCRIMINATE-COX     07-12 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGA-DISCRIMINATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UGA reviews racial policies
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin and Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The University of Georgia is reviewing its admissions
policies after a federal judge ruled they stigmatize minority
students and amount to reverse discrimination, UGA President
Michael F. Adams said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge B. Avant Edenfield of Savannah, Ga.,
dismissed a contentious affirmative action lawsuit against the
Board of Regents on a technicality that the student applicant
lacked standing to bring his claims.
</P>
<P>
   But the Regents' legal victory was accompanied by the federal
judge's stinging condemnation of UGA's policies that allow racial
preference in admissions.
</P>
<P>
   Citing ``jaw-dropping'' revelations that UGA's admissions
policies benefit only a handful of minority students, Edenfield
said: ``The court would be remiss if it didn't briefly note what
the record evidence now compels: UGA cannot constitutionally
justify the affirmative use of race in its admissions decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Monday, Adams said UGA, which has 6.2
percent black enrollment, is pleased that Edenfield's ruling last
week did not invalidate current admissions policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, it is clear that the judge is giving the
university advice about an area of the law that is evolving,''
Adams said. ``It is incumbent upon us to work with legal counsel,
the Regents and the university staff to review the institution's
current practices and policies to ensure that they do not
discriminate against anyone, while we continue our efforts
diligently to recruit qualified minority students.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen R. Portch, chancellor of the University System of
Georgia, said, ``Prolonged litigation is not in anyone's best
interest. The judge's views on UGA's admission policies, though,
pose some challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Parks, an Atlanta lawyer representing a student denied
admission to UGA in fall 1997, said he will appeal Edenfield's
dismissal of the lawsuit. If UGA does not change admissions
practices, Parks added, he has other plaintiffs ready to file suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to see if UGA will take Judge Edenfield's language
to heart and amend or fix the program,'' Parks said. ``We have
another whole group of high school seniors who want to apply to UGA
next year and don't want their race or sex taken into consideration
in admissions.''
</P>
<P>
   UGA is the only public campus in Georgia that admits to using
race as an admissions factor. Each of the 34 schools in the
university system has individually crafted admissions policies that
must comply with minimum requirements set by the Board of Regents.
</P>
<P>
   Parks' lawsuit, filed in 1997, attacked UGA admissions policies
as well as those of the state's three historically black public
universities. But rulings by Edenfield, beginning in January, have
whittled away Parks' plaintiffs from the litigation. The judge
ruled that four plaintiffs who sued the historically black schools
lacked standing, as did a white female plaintiff denied admission
to UGA in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Edenfield granted Parks a single victory _ a claim brought by
Kirby Tracy, a white student denied admission to UGA in the fall of
1995. In a decision handed down in January, Edenfield ruled UGA's
previous ``dual-track'' admissions program was unconstitutional and
that Tracy could not compete on equal footing with UGA applicants
``solely on the basis of his skin color.''
</P>
<P>
   In an order issued July 6, Edenfield denied a motion by the
NAACP to reconsider his ruling in favor of Tracy. But he denied
Parks' bid for class-action status, and awarded Tracy $1 in damages
because Tracy has since transferred to UGA.
</P>
<P>
   In response to court decisions nationwide striking down one
affirmative action program after another, UGA in 1995 abandoned its
dual-track program. This now-defunct admissions process put some
black applicants in competition with each other at a lower
standard, without having to compete with non-black candidates.
</P>
<P>
   UGA now allows race to be one of several factors that help
applicants who fall below minimum grades and test scores required
for automatic admission.
</P>
<P>
   But UGA's current policy is more of the same, Edenfield wrote.
``In other words, it's still the same ship; UGA has simply
rearranged the deck chairs,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Green, who lives in Dalton, unsuccessfully sought
admission to UGA in fall 1997. His grades and test scores were too
low to gain automatic admission, but they were high enough to get
him further consideration. His application advanced to the final
stage of the admissions process, where it was read by two UGA
admissions counselors who gave him the lowest possible score. They
later testified they did not consider Green's race when making
their decision. UGA denied Green's application.
</P>
<P>
   Because Green's race was not a factor in the final stage of the
process, and because his race made no difference in the earlier
stages, he ``cannot say that he was prevented, because of his race,
from competing on an equal footing with non-whites,'' Edenfield
wrote. ``This is a huge disappointment for Craig,'' Parks said.
``It is a legally correct decision on the constitutionality of the
admissions process, but it's not a compassionate decision. . . .
It's a tragedy that the young man who chose to take on this system
and had it found unconstitutional does not get the benefit of a UGA
education.'' Green's lawsuit established UGA gave minority
applicants ``an automatic advantage over some whites when competing
for admission,'' all to justify UGA's need for ``diversity'' among
its student population, Edenfield wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But Edenfield said UGA's desire for diversity was ill-defined
and hard to justify.
</P>
<P>
   ``State officials promote exactly what society does not need nor
tolerate: racial stereotyping, where government officials simply
assume that blacks, for example, think one way, and whites
another,'' Edenfield wrote. ``. . . UGA officials evidently
employed racial preferences first and asked questions later.''
</P>
<P>
   Edenfield added that any racial preference in admissions
``stigmatizes'' minority students, ``the vast majority of whom
earned admission without the benefit'' of any racial preference.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also expressed concern that UGA's race-based
admissions preferences achieve only ``an insignificant increase in
'racial diversity' at UGA.''
</P>
<P>
   In his order, Edenfield recited pre-trial testimony from John
Albright, associate director for undergraduate admissions, who was
asked whether black enrollment at UGA would drop if race were not
used as a factor in admissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may,'' Albright answered. ``. . . I would think it would
reduce it by a handful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This jaw-dropping revelation suggests that UGA is willing to
stigmatize its non-white students for the sake of a largely
symbolic racial preference,'' Edenfield wrote. ``This fact alone
should force any reasonable decision-maker to re-examine, if only
on simple practicality grounds, whether such racial preferences can
be justified at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin and Rebecca McCarthy write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga. Ernie Suggs contributed to this
article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
