<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-GILMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GLOBE PUBLISHER BEGAN CAREER IN REPORTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Richard H. Gilman, like Benjamin B. Taylor, the man he
succeeds as publisher of The Boston Globe, began his newspaper
career as a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started my career in newspapering,'' the former New York
Times senior vice president of operations told Globe editorial
staff members Monday, ``as a cub reporter covering the night police
beat while I was going to college.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilman, 48, eventually rose to the position of assistant
managing editor at The Arizona Daily Star, in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a first-rate mind and had a rapid rise here,'' said Steve
Auslander, the Star's executive editor, in a telephone interview
Monday. ``He was well respected.''
</P>
<P>
   Auslander characterized Gilman's newsroom style as having been
``between hard charging and easy going _ a pretty good blend of the
two. If someone had told me (then) he'd be the publisher of a major
metropolitan newspaper, it wouldn't have surprised me at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday, Gilman was happy to dwell on his
journalistic roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The love of newspapering actually began when I was in junior
high school and I produced a mimeographed newspaper about the
school. I delivered newspapers as a kid. I wrote a sports column in
the high school paper and covered school sports as a stringer for
the local paper. I did all those kinds of things. So I had those
newspaper instincts in my blood from a very early age.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilman first worked for the Star while an undergraduate at the
University of Arizona. A government and journalism major, he
graduated in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The summer before his senior year, Gilman, a Detroit native,
worked as a reporter intern at The Detroit News. After graduation,
he returned to the Star. In addition to reporting, Gilman worked as
a copy editor, assistant city editor, and city editor.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman left the paper to attend Harvard Business School. ``There
was a lot of talk about the business side of the business,'' he
recalled Monday. ``I came to the conclusion that if I really wanted
to have a future for myself, I ought to go to business school. It
was always my intention to return to newspapers. But once you get
caught up in that, it's not that easy to jump back over the fence
and return to the news side.'' He earned an MBA in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   During his time at Harvard ``I became a fan of the Globe,''
Gilman said at Monday's staff meeting. ``To me, (Globe
sportswriters) Peter Gammons and Will McDonough walked on water.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilman joined the Times in 1983 as assistant to the vice
president of circulation. He spent the next four years working in
the paper's circulation department, followed by three years in
several production posts. He was named vice president for systems
and technology in 1992 and senior vice president a year later. The
Times' circulation was added to his responsibilities last year.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman and his wife Wendy have a daughter.
</P>
<P>
   A sports fan and history buff, he said he welcomed the return to
Boston. ``My wife and I had been in New York maybe three months
(after getting his Harvard degree) and I remember driving down a
highway and turning to her and saying, `You know, Boston really is
a great city.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
