<SLUG> BC-NJ-WATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY WATER-MAIN LEAK REPAIRED 
</HEADLINE>
  (md) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORADELL, N.J. _ A major water main that began leaking Sunday was
repaired Monday, ending the third water emergency in a decade for
about 750,000 residents of Bergen and Hudson Counties.
</P>
<P>
   The leak, which started about 4 a.m. Sunday, led officials to
ban on all outdoor use of water and to appeal to residents to boil
water for drinking. The leak reduced water pressure to some homes
and apartments in Fort Lee, Tenafly, Englewood Cliffs and Alpine,
touched off a run on bottled water in some stores, and prompted
some worried fire chiefs to summon volunteer firefighters for
stand-by duty.
</P>
<P>
   United Water Resources, the Harrington Park utility that owns
the 78-inch main, reported that repairs were completed by
mid-afternoon Monday, without any of the major supply disruptions
that followed ruptures in the company's mains in March 1989 and
February 1996. The 1996 rupture left between 35,000 and 50,000
customers without water for three days. In the latest break, Sgt.
Dwane Razzetti, deputy coordinator of Bergen County's emergency
management office, said about 20 homes, all in Alpine, lost their
water for brief periods Sunday night and again Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Henning, a spokesman for United Water, said the company
gradually began flowing water through the 78-inch pipe about 4 p.m.
Monday and hopes to return it to full capacity sometime Tuesday.
Henning said a gasket failed at an elbow joint in the pipe on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The water main is the biggest in United Water's distribution
system and carries the bulk of water treated at the company's
purification plant at Oradell Reservoir, Henning said. After it was
shut down, the company relied on two 36-inch pipes that led from
the treatment plant, imported water from the Jersey City water
system and the Passaic Valley Water Commission and used supplies
stored in above-ground tanks throughout Bergen and Hudson Counties,
Henning said.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy demands on water between 7 and 9 p.m. Sunday drained a
tank in Englewood Cliffs, creating the scattered pressure problems
in towns on and near the Palisades, Henning said.
</P>
<P>
   At Engine Company One, one of four fire houses in Fort Lee, one
volunteer fireman, Ralph Porrino, a private investigator, was on
emergency duty. He had planned to spend the day tracking down a
bail jumper. Another volunteer on stand-by, Bill Thompson, who is
retired, gave up a day of fun. ``I'd be up in New Milford in my
sister's pool,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Food Emporium, a 24-hour supermarket in Fort Lee,
customers gobbled up one and two gallon jugs of water as quickly as
clerks put them on shelves. Sales had doubled since Sunday night,
the manager, Jim Vitel, said. ``We're trying to keep up with
demand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Fort Lee dentist, Michael Schneider, turned off the tap water
in his office and filled patients' rinsing cups with Evian water.
``They're getting kind of a kick out of it,'' he said. ``I just
wanted to be on the safe side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
