<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PG&AMP;E-PG&AMP;E </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGE DEBATE OVER PG&AMP;E SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   By Rebecca Smith 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The fate of Pacific Gas and Electric Co.'s crown jewels will be
debated today when a state Senate committee takes up a bill that
would determine under what conditions the company could spin off
its vast hydroelectric system and what impact that transfer would
have on consumers.
<P>
   PG&AMP;E, which has already sold its fossil-fuel plants to other
companies, now wants to transfer its valuable hydropower system to
an unregulated sister company. The San Francisco utility thinks
that it can earn more profits from the system if it is freed from
price regulation.
</P>
<P>
   But in exchange for making that transfer, state Sen. Debra
Bowen, Marina del Rey (Los Angeles County), wants to require that
any new owner meet more-stringent environmental standards and agree
to pricing restrictions to make sure it doesn't abuse its market
power. In addition, Bowen wants to ensure that the system, if it is
transferred, is valued at a price that benefits PG&AMP;E ratepayers.
</P>
<P>
   Those and other conditions are contained in a bill, SB1063, that
will be heard by the Senate Energy, Utilities and Communications
Committee this afternoon. Bowen authored the bill and chairs the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first piece of legislation to emerge from a
three-month debate concerning how _ or whether _ PG&AMP;E should be
allowed to divest its &UR;  &LR; hydropower system.
</P>
<P>
   The future of that system is critically important because its
touches everyone in Northern California who drinks water, uses
electricity or cares about the state's environment.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E's hydroelectric system is the largest under private
ownership in North America and, many believe, the world. The system
consists of 68 powerhouses and 94 dams on 16 river systems that
collectively produce 3,890 megawatts of power _ enough to light 4
million homes.
</P>
<P>
   But its value springs from more than just its electric output.
</P>
<P>
   Hydroelectric power can be ramped up and down more quickly than
any other source of electricity in response to minute-to-minute
fluctuations in demand. This means those 3,890 megawatts of
capacity have unrivaled ability to help stabilize the state's
electric system. As a result, PG&AMP;E's hydropower commands a premium
price over other kinds of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to supplying 15 percent of the state's power,
whoever controls PG&AMP;E's hydroelectric system largely controls the
flow of water out of the Sierra Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 2.6 million acre feet of water that run through PG&AMP;E's
hydroelectric system, the company has rights to sell 200,000 acre
feet for drinking and irrigation. That's enough to flood a
200,000-acre parcel of land with clear mountain water a foot deep.
</P>
<P>
   Those water rights are certain to appreciate as California grows
more densely populated. By 2020, the state is expected to have
added 15 million residents to its current 32 million, creating an
annual deficit of 2.4 million acre feet of water in normal-rainfall
years.
</P>
<P>
   The state is proposing to expand freshwater reservoirs to
provide for the needs of a thirsty state, and it's possible some of
that storage could be added to lands leased from PG&AMP;E, adding to
the value of that land.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, PG&AMP;E's hydropower empire includes 140,000 acres of
forestland surrounding PG&AMP;E generating facilities where generations
of Californians have camped, hiked and picnicked. It appears that
40,000 acres of this land could be carved out and sold to
developers.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen's legislation doesn't grant PG&AMP;E the right to transfer its
hydro system to its unregulated affiliate, such as PG&AMP;E Generating
Co. of Bethesda, Md., but it does establish restrictions that would
apply to any owner:
</P>
<P>
   _The owner would have to follow rules that prevent an operator
from exercising unfair market power in the sale of electricity. It
would not be allowed to sell power &UR;  &LR; for more than $20 per megawatt
hour, nor could it withhold capacity to force prices up.
</P>
<P>
   _It also would be required to craft an environmental plan by
December 31, 2001, showing how it would more speedily meet state
water quality standards. Instead of making improvements as power
projects come up for 30- or 50-year license renewals _ something
that will happen to half of PG&AMP;E's power stations during the next
10 years _ the owner would have to develop an expedited plan to
improve fish habitats by boosting water flows.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Bowen last week, a coalition of environmental
groups said, ``This transition should be used to ... reverse the
degradation'' that began in the 1860s with construction of water
canals and flumes by hydraulic gold miners. Those water diversions
later became part of PG&AMP;E's hydropower system.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most controversial provision of the Bowen bill
concerns how the waterpower system will be valued.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, PG&AMP;E proposed to the state Public Utilities
Commission that appraisers set the value. Ratepayer advocates
pummeled that idea, saying it would be impossible for appraisers to
arrive at a fair value because no comparable system has been
auctioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big problem is finding a value for hydro plants in the West
because they haven't been sold to date,'' said David Wagman,
research director for Resource Data International in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   In the East, sales of hydropower systems that are regarded as
inferior to PG&AMP;E's have sold for an average of $1,000 per megawatt,
Wagman said.
</P>
<P>
   Crude as that measure is, it suggests PG&AMP;E's system would be
worth a minimum of $3.89 billion. The price likely would climb with
recognition of water, real estate and other values.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ratepayers deserve the maximum amount of money, and the only
way you're going to get that is by auctioning the system,'' says
Jim Scarff, an attorney for the PUC's Office of Ratepayer
Advocates.
</P>
<P>
   How the system is valued is of crucial importance to ratepayers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the state's 1996 deregulation law, PG&AMP;E must credit
ratepayers an amount equal to the value of the California
hydroelectric system, to offset billions of dollars of PG&AMP;E debts
that customers are being forced to repay. Most of these debts stem
from PG&AMP;E's Diablo Canyon nuclear plant and from contracts PG&AMP;E
signed to purchase power from high-cost sources such as windmills.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC estimates that ratepayers are still on the hook for
about $4 billion worth of such debts.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Steve Peace, D-El Cajon (San Diego County), has been
trying to negotiate a price that PG&AMP;E Generating Co., the
unregulated affiliate, might pay. In legislative hearings last
spring, Peace said ratepayers should get at least $4 billion for
the hydro system.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E reportedly has balked at paying anything above $3.4
billion, sources said last week, and the discussions appear to have
hit a stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E executives declined to comment for this story, and Peace
could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than pick an arbitrary number, Bowen now proposes that an
interim value be set. If the interim value were high enough _ $3
billion to and  &LR; $3.5 billion _ it's possible that ratepayers could
end their debt repayment as early as April.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, rates could fall by 20 percent for residential
customers and small businesses, and up to 40 percent for large
business and industrial customers.
</P>
<P>
   There is bound to be fierce debate about the Bowen proposal.
Some consumer advocates believe that the state should not rush into
anything and forfeit a once-in-a-century opportunity to completely
re-examine the way land and rivers are used.
</P>
<P>
   Other states are tearing down dams, for example, and restoring
stretches of rivers to their primordial wildness. But there's no
such proposal here nor is there serious policy discussion of any
transfer of the system into public hands.
</P>
<P>
   Nettie Hoge, executive director of the consumer group The
Utility Reform Network, said she favors an interim valuation
because it will end the rate freeze. But she admits that it simply
defers the most vexing questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most difficult questions aren't answered by this
legislation,'' Hoge says. ``Those questions still concern who gets
the hydroelectric system, ultimately, and what should we be doing
for the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
