<HEADER>
A7468 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG_SFC     07-12 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS  &HT;     Keeping Your Finance Data Safe 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: Thanks for your recent tip on how to keep track of the value of
a stock portfolio, using free services available on the Internet.
I'd like to try it, but I'm afraid that someone might break in and
look at my financial data.
<P>
   A: That's possible. I have gone back and forth about security
with various Web site operators, and none has convinced me that any
site is invulnerable to hackers. Most Web sites do all they can to
preserve security, but anything can be broken into. There are some
pretty ingenious hackers out there.
</P>
<P>
   It's also conceivable that the people who operate the Web site
where you store your portfolio data can (and will) peek at your
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   If such things bother you, there's a ploy you might consider.
Try disguising the size of your portfolio by entering sharply
diminished share totals. Suppose, for example, that you hold 100
shares of General Motors, recently worth about $7,000. When you key
in your portfolio data, indicate instead that you hold 10 shares.
It then will appear that you only have $700 worth.
</P>
<P>
   Do that with your other holdings as well, dividing the actual
share totals by 10. When you look at the daily portfolio update,
it's an easy matter to multiply by 10 in your head. Meanwhile, no
one who might take an electronic peek at your portfolio would have
the vaguest idea how much you are worth.
</P>
<P>
   If you happen to be Bill Gates, you might want to divide your
share totals by 100 million, rather than 10, but the same principle
applies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Inside Investors
</P>
<P>
   Q: How does one find out what portion of a public company is
owned by insiders? Also, how do you find out if the insiders are
running the company mainly for their own benefit, at the expense of
other shareholders? I ask this because I invested in a company that
had a large stash of cash, but soon afterward, the insiders
depleted it by giving themselves huge bonuses and the stock price
went down.
</P>
<P>
   A: Get a copy of the latest proxy statement issued by whatever
company interests you. It will tell you how many shares are owned
by each of the directors and principal executives, and it also
lists any other individuals or institutions that own at least 5
percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   The proxy also provides a detailed breakdown of the compensation
paid to the five top officers in the latest fiscal year. If you
skim through the compensation sections of enough proxies, you can
sense which companies have the greediest managements.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't only huge bonuses that can pinch a company's finances.
Huge stock options can dilute a company's earnings per share by
greatly increasing the number of shares outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if an executive owns a large stake in a
company, that can be good for the other shareholders. A major owner
has a compelling incentive to keep the company healthy and the
stock price high.
</P>
<P>
   Proxies normally are sent to shareholders once a year, just
ahead of the annual meeting. You probably can get a copy by calling
the company's investor relations department. Or try searching the
Securities and Exchange Commission's Web site at www.sec.gov.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Choosing an Index Fund
</P>
<P>
   Q: Waterhouse Securities has a mutual fund that duplicates the
performance of the 30 companies in the Dow Jones industrial
average. Would this be a good long-term investment? I don't have a
clue about the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   A: That's OK. You're in good company.
</P>
<P>
   No one can confidently predict the performance of any mutual
fund or other security.
</P>
<P>
   But if the past is any guide, then the Waterhouse Investors Dow
30 Fund (as it is called) should be a good long-term investment. In
the 30-year period ended last month, the Dow industrials posted an
average annual gain of 13 percent, including reinvestment of
dividends.
</P>
<P>
   The Waterhouse fund is a no-load _ which is good. You won't have
to pay an up-front commission to buy the shares.
</P>
<P>
   However, the fund imposes an annual management fee of 0.81
percent of invested assets _ on the high side for index funds,
which are passively managed. The Vanguard Index Trust 500 Fund,
which tracks the performance of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index,
charges a management fee of only 0.18 percent annually. That is a
big advantage, considering that the Dow and the S&AMP;P 500 have turned
in virtually identical performances on balance during the past 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   If the Waterhouse and Vanguard funds both gained exactly 13
percent every year for the next 30 years, someone who invested
$10,000 in each of them today and then stood pat would wind up with
a hefty $315,000 in the Waterhouse fund but an even heftier
$373,000 _ nearly $60,000 more _ in the Vanguard fund.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
