<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7469 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     07-12 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEALING HEADLINES AND HEARTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only constant in life is change, and I'm left numbed and
disoriented from the reconfigurations occurring in our midst in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like it was only a fortnight ago that I was using a
typewriter to pound out these words, but I've now been using a
computer since I was forced, kicking, screaming and complaining,
into making the transition for the 1984 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   I remember there was a time when only Navy guys and Hell's
Angels had tattoos, but now it's become so fashionable among young
people and some not so young to have their bodies festooned with
such skin-scarring graffiti that you're dismissed as a maverick
outcast if you don't have one.
</P>
<P>
   Why, I'm such an old codger that I actually can recall when the
general populace kept its money in low-interest savings accounts in
banks instead of investing it in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   I swear there was a time in America when people communicated
long distance via either mail, or telephone instead of E-mail and
actually conducted their business in person rather than over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   I vaguely can recollect those by-gone days when you could take
kids to the movies without fear of being bombarded with the crass
sexual claptrap and politically correct dung that you find in such
mindless junk as ``Wild Wild West'' and ``Big Daddy.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, if someone told me, say, a year go, or even, say, a week
ago that a bunch of American women soccer players easily would
upstage the 70th All Star game, I would have hooted uproariously
and said, ``Sure, and the next thing you're going to tell me is
that the Women's World Cup championship match is going to get
larger television ratings than the NBA championship finals between
the New York Knicks and San Antonio Spurs!''
</P>
<P>
   Well, I guess times, indeed, are changing dramatically,
especially on the athletic scene.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. ladies actually did generate greater Nielsen TV ratings
in their game with China than the NBA finals managed 13.3 to 11.3
and they actually have commanded more attention the past few days
than baseball's mid-season classic.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have guessed?
</P>
<P>
   Who would have guessed that a bunch of enthusiastic,
bright-eyed, underpaid ladies the $50,000 bonus each will receive
for the team's stirring victory over China doesn't even amount to
one-seventh of what Kevin Brown earns each time he makes a start
for the Dodgers would be earning greater headlines this juncture of
the summer than Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa, Ken Griffey Jr., Pedro
Martinez, Mike Piazza and the rest of baseball's glamorous players?
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought the most popular jocks in America at this
time serenaded by David Letterman, feted by Disneyland, revered by
an entire nation would be a bunch of gals named Michelle Akers, Mia
Hamm, Brandi Chastain, Briana Scurry, Kate Sobrero, Tiffeny
Milbrett, Julie Foudy and the rest of their teammates?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the relative newness of women team sports and the
incredible success enjoyed by the U.S. soccer team has something to
do with this phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, would an entire nation have been glued to its television
sets the ratings in L.A. were a stunning 20.8 had Norway and Brazil
duked it out for the World Cup title Saturday?
</P>
<P>
   No way.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I think it's far more than victories that have propelled
these American ladies to cult status among even many hardened male
sports patrons who in the past dismissed women athletics with
haughty disdain.
</P>
<P>
   It's the strong feeling here that the unparalleled popularity of
Tony DiCiccio's troops is a widespread backlash against so much of
what the public passionately dislikes about modern athletics the
strikes, the lockouts, the high-priced tickets, the loutishness of
its performers, the greediness of its overseers, the general
disregard for the fans.
</P>
<P>
   These soccer players have a charismatic charm about them that
has been beguiling.
</P>
<P>
   You also must understand none have been busted for possession of
dope. None who are married have faced assault charges for roughing
up their husbands. None who are single have run afoul of the law
for beating up their boyfriends. None have been arrested for public
drunkenness, or has any had an unseemly incident in a strip joint.
None refuses to sign autographs. All have been gracious to their
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Brandi Chastain caused quite a stir in a provocatively posed
ad she did for ``Gear'' magazine. And Briana Scurry once streaked
nude around her hometown neighborhood late at night, although no
one was around to see her impromptu 1996 Olympic gold medal
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Listen, girls will be girls, and no one is perfect, not even
these wonderful American soccer champions who play their game with
an uncommon competitive zeal and do so without the finger-pointing,
self-congratulatory mugging that too often stains athletic events
these days.
</P>
<P>
   These ladies have captured a nation because they have come to
epitomize the quintessential essence of sportsmanship, and haven't
been spoiled into becoming conceited, self-important boors like so
many of their male brethren.
</P>
<P>
   This may change in the future when the inevitable huge amounts
of money start rolling in and their perspectives become altered
permanently.
</P>
<P>
   But, for the time being, these American women are clearly at the
top of the athletic ladder, worshiped not only for their vast
accomplishments but also for the exemplary manner in which they
conduct themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
