<HEADER>
A7470 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KASICH-PRESIDENCY-COX     07-12 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KASICH-PRESIDENCY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio's Kasich may bow out of presidential race
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. John Kasich's wild card run for the presidency
might soon fold as sources close to the campaign acknowledged
Monday the Westerville, Ohio Republican has begun a sober
assessment of whether to stay in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Months after joining a passel of Republican candidates seeking
the party's nomination for president in 2000, Kasich hasn't made
discernible gains in either poll results or fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign spokesman Todd Harris deflected questions about whether
an announcement was imminent
</P>
<P>
   In one indication of the campaign's condition, a fund-raising
event scheduled for Monday in Seattle was canceled because of poor
response.
</P>
<P>
   Two sources close to the campaign said the evaluations are now
more intense, a month before the Iowa straw poll, and one of the
two said a decision about whether to withdraw or press ahead could
come soon.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in Kasich's future has grown intense following a
weekend rumor that he was preparing to endorse one of the other GOP
presidential candidates. The speculation hit Washington hard
Monday, bolstered by Kasich's hedging about the rumor when
questioned on the campaign trail Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked directly if he was about to withdraw, Kasich told The
Associated Press in Concord, N.H., ``When we get to the point where
we've made a decision and are going to talk about it, we'll let you
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressure is mounting for all the Republican candidates to
demonstrate their viability in the face of front-runner Gov. George
W. Bush's juggernaut campaign. Two weeks ago campaign finance
totals were tallied and Bush announced that he broke all previous
records by raising more than $36 million in the first six months of
his campaign. He's raised twice as much as Vice President Al Gore,
and his closest money rival in the GOP, Sen. John McCain of
Arizona, has just over $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich's campaign office said he has raised $3 million, but $1.4
million of that was transferred from his congressional campaign
account.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Columbus, Ohio Republicans are waiting to hear
if Kasich will seek a 10th term in Congress after a decision is
made about his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Montgomery writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
