<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7472 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAN-PROTESTS-1STLD-W     07-12 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-PROTESTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRANIAN POLICE MOVE IN TO CRUSH ESCALATING STUDENT PROTEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS 14th graf, As striking ..., to ADD that Khamenei's
predecessor as ayatollah was Khomeini.) 
 (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ The most widespread and sustained protests since
Iran's revolution two decades ago spread throughout the country
Monday, while security police and their vigilante supporters moved
to crush pro-democracy student demonstrators outside Tehran
University.
</P>
<P>
   Students demonstrated in 18 cities and towns, including major
cosmopolitan cities like Tabriz, Shiraz and Isfahan and more
traditional cities like Mashad and Yazd, Iran's official news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Wielding batons and lobbing tear gas canisters, the security
forces emptied Tehran University Monday evening in a campaign to
crush the demonstrations. In Tehran, students who had gathered
inside the gates of the sprawling university complex in the heart
of the capital fainted from tear gas that could be smelled more
than a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Filthy swine! Filthy swine!'' one red-faced student screamed
over and over from inside the cramped quarters of one of the
caged-in vehicles. ``Jerk!'' yelled another. Others yelled
obscenities that are seldom heard in public in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   One woman, wrapped in the all-encompassing black chador, cursed
the clergy with obscenities. A number of people were injured and
received assistance from health personnel in a blood transfusion
truck and passersby.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of injured students were taken to the campus mosque for
treatment, and a parade of ambulances streamed in and out of the
campus as a voice on a loudspeaker called all medical students to
help. Students set a huge bonfire to try to neutralize the tear
gas, one witness said.
</P>
<P>
   The vigilantes, fervent revolutionaries who serve as volunteers
for the regime, carried cables, chains and batons as they emerged
from the government-owned buses that parked near the university,
the witness said. The students had intended to stage an all-night
sit-in, but by midnight, most of them had left the campus.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations _ and the crackdown _ reflect a deep struggle
over the course of Iran's revolution. Students are impatient with
the slow pace of reforms promised by President Mohammed Khatami.
The students are not calling for a change in the Islamic system of
government, rather for a quickening of the movement towards
democracy and the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side are the diehard Islamic revolutionaries, some
of them in positions of power, some of them veterans of Iran's long
war with Iraq, who take their lead from Iran's Supreme leader,
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, and believe that the country's moves
towards democracy are a betrayal of revolutionary purism.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami does not control the police and security forces, who
have enraged and frightened many Iranians by a campaign of
intimidation that included the murders of prominent intellectuals
as well as political attacks on Khatami's allies in the government.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations and the crackdowns do not mean that Iran's
Islamic Republic is in jeopardy. ``We should not assume that this
movement could turn into a revolution,'' said an editorial Monday
in the reformist newspaper, Neshat. ``It's neither nor possible nor
desirable.''
</P>
<P>
   The five days of rage were sparked by the passage by Iran's
parliament of a tough new press law and by the closure of Salam, a
popular left-leaning Islamic newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Security forces and vigilantes stormed a dormitory at Tehran
University on Thursday night and beat students as they slept,
pushing some from second- and third-story windows. Although the
official death toll stood at two, Iran's newspapers, quoting
students, claimed that between five and eight students had died.
</P>
<P>
   As striking as the extent of the protests throughout the country
is the form they are taking. Until now, criticisms of Ayatollah
Khamenei, who is in charge of the armed forces, the security and
intelligence apparatus, and radio and television, were made
privately. Now the criticism of Khamenei, who lacks the religious
credentials of his predecessor, the Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini,
and has resisted any embrace of reform, has burst into the open.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to calm the highly charged atmosphere, Khamenei on
Monday delivered an emotional speech condemning the attack by
security forces on a dormitory last week after the first protests.
He spoke to a hand-picked crowd of thousands in a cavernous hall
reserved solely for his use.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bitter incident has broken my heart,'' he said in the
speech, which was broadcast on both radio and television. He added
that it was un-Islamic to enter the private spaces of individuals.
</P>
<P>
   In a stunning acknowledgment that some of the demonstrators had
turned against him, he added, ``Even if things make you angry and
they condemn me, even if they set fire to my picture, remain
silent. Take no action until the day that the country needs it!''
</P>
<P>
   Men and women in the crowd moaned and wept loudly.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech he said, ``The greatest dream and honor for me is
that I give my life in this honorable, glorious magnificent path''
_ a statement the security forces and the vigilantes may have
interpreted as a message that they should risk their lives instead.
</P>
<P>
   Khamenei also blamed ``enemies,'' including the United States,
for the attack on the dormitory. Over and over, the crowd chanted
``Death to America.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the university, there was no crying for the ayatollah.
When a speaker tried to read the text of Khamenei's speech, the
crowd booed. ``Commander-in-chief resign!'' and ``Down with the
dictator,'' they chanted.
</P>
<P>
   There were posters of President Khatami but none of Ayatollah
Khamenei, whose photographs and portraits dominate public
buildings, shops and landscapes throughout Iran along with those of
his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami called on students to exercise restraint, saying in a
meeting with education officials, ``students should cooperate with
the government and allow law and order to be established in
society.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In another incident Monday, uniformed and plainclothes security
police and anti-riot police protected by shields and helmets
clashed with several hundred student protesters. The police rounded
up dozens of students in Valiasr Square, one of Tehran's busiest
intersections, beating some of them and forcing them into cages
mounted on the back of pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown came after a police car and two police motorcycles
were set on fire, apparently by students, one witness said.
</P>
<P>
   Stone-throwing students smashed storefront windows. Many
shopkeepers pulled down the gates of their stores both to prevent
looting and to get a closer look at the action in the streets.
Police froze traffic just before rush hour. Helicopters kept watch
overhead. Security police roamed among the thousands of people
gathered in the square arresting suspicious-looking young people
and rounding up photographers to prevent them from taking pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day at the university, students stood up on a
makeshift dais near the law school and one after one explained
their views and stated their demands. Among them are the creation
of a national day of mourning in memory of the students who were
killed, the holding of a public trial for the people who ordered
and carried out the dormitory attack, and the return of the bodies
of those killed.
</P>
<P>
   One speaker in a black shirt criticized the lack of
organization. ``We have to have a plan and a leader,'' said the
man, who, like the other speakers, did not identify himself. ``We
have to find out which of our friends have been killed, and who
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Another speaker called for the execution of the perpetrators of
last Thursday's dormitory attack.
</P>
<P>
   A number of student organizers said they believed that the
all-day open microphone was a trap set by infiltrators in their
midst who both tried to provoke the students into more radical
action and ended up being part of Monday night's crackdown. One
speaker said that some in the crowd were offering razor blades to
students who might want to use violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very strange that the students were allowed to speak so
freely,'' he said. ``The whole thing is too suspicious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0404 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7473 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-DISNEY_SFCHRON     07-12 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-DISNEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Disney to Buy Rest of Infoseek 
 &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; Fresh from hitting box-office pay dirt with its ``Tarzan''
animated movie, Walt Disney Co. said yesterday that it will swing
deeper into the jungle of the Internet by acquiring the 57 percent
of Sunnyvale's Infoseek Corp. it doesn't already own.
<P>
   After the deal is completed, probably by the end of the year,
all of Team Mickey's Internet assets will be gathered in a single
operation _ dubbed Go.com _ and a new stock will be created to
track &UR;  &LR; Disney's expanded online assets.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement is intended to make Go.com a more nimble player
than Disney in the fast-moving Internet industry, and to capitalize
on Wall Street's dot-com mania.
</P>
<P>
   Go.com's shares are almost certain to generate interest among
investors, who have steered clear of Disney's stock in recent
months amid earnings disappointments, uncertainties surrounding the
entertainment giant's broadcast properties and sagging sales of
merchandise resulting from Asia's prolonged economic slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will package Disney's Internet assets in a quantifiable
entity,'' said Arthur Hogan, chief market analyst at Jefferies &AMP;
Co. in New York. ``Those assets have been hidden in the overall
stock.''
</P>
<P>
   While financial terms of the deal were kept under wraps,
analysts placed the total market capitalization of Go.com at about
$7 billion. This would value Infoseek at roughly $52 a share, in
line with Friday's close of $51.50.
</P>
<P>
   Infoseek shareholders will receive 1.15 shares of the new Go.com
tracking stock for each share of the portal they hold. The Infoseek
buyout comes as no surprise. Disney signaled that a deal may be
afoot a few weeks ago when it confirmed that it was in talks with
the portal.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies already cooperate in Go Network, which unites
Disney's online resources _ including sites related to its ABC and
ESPN divisions _ with Infoseek's directory services.
</P>
<P>
   The merged company will inherit Go Network's &LR;  go.com  &LR; Web
address.
</P>
<P>
   Disney, which will hold a 72 percent stake in Go.com (with the
remainder held by individual shareholders), expects the combined
businesses to generate about $350 million in pro-forma revenue for
the current fiscal year, with approximately $200 million of that
coming from Internet-related activities and the rest from the
Disney catalog.
</P>
<P>
   There are no estimates as to when Go.com will turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Combining Disney's Internet assets with Infoseek takes our
online strategy to the next level,'' Michael Eisner, Disney's
chairman and chief executive, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Go.com ``will unlock the value and potential of
our combined Internet assets.''
</P>
<P>
   That remains to be seen. While the current Go Network is one of
the top five sites on the Web in terms of traffic, according to
market researcher Media Metrix, its revenues remained flat at $30
million in the latest quarter _ a troubling sign in the
hyper-growth-oriented Internet world.
</P>
<P>
   Infoseek said its own revenues in the quarter ended in April
jumped 105 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Infoseek's share price has steadily risen in recent weeks as
speculation mounted that a buyout by Disney was in the cards. It
closed yesterday down $5.56, or almost 11 percent, at $45.94 as
investors cashed in on the gains.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's stock, meanwhile, edged 19 cents higher to $27.81. The
Mouse House has watched its share price drop by more than 25
percent in the past year as Wall Street analysts have taken an
increasingly downbeat view of the company's near-term prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't seem to be able to do anything right,'' said Steve
Adams, managing director of First Security Van Kasper &AMP; Co. in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Adams, who sees Disney now trading at attractive,
bargain-basement levels, added that ``the moves they're making onto
the Internet are smart. They're starting to position themselves for
long-term value.''
</P>
<P>
   John Ball, Disney senior vice president of corporate
development, admitted that ``our international and consumer-product
devisions have experienced some growth problems.'' But he insisted
that ``if you think ahead two, three, four years, we believe growth
will be reignited.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball also observed that Disney shareholders won't miss out on
whatever growth is experienced by the new Go.com stock. ``People
who hold Disney shares will have a 72-percent interest in Go.com,''
he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   However, this could end up being a liability for the new
concern's shares. With virtually no prospect of Go.com being
purchased by another company, the venture will lack much of the
cachet surrounding most Net firms.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, although many investors will be attracted by the
notion of a stock representing Disney's online properties, there
will be others who are deterred by Go.com being a tracking stock,
as opposed to a ``pure'' Internet investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``These tracking stocks are not the way many people like to play
the Internet,'' said Bill Meehan, chief market analyst at Cantor
Fitzgerald in New York. ``There's no shortage any longer of other
Internet stocks out there.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not yet known who will run the new company, but this much
is sure: It won't be Harry Motro, Infoseek's president and chief
executive. While Motro has agreed to stay on until the acquisition
is complete, he said in an interview that he plans to leave the
company after the deal goes through ``for personal reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was totally my choice,'' Motro stressed, dismissing
rumors that he had been forced out by Disney.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to discuss future career plans. ``There is no other
business interest I have planned,'' Motro said.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's chief financial officer, Thomas Staggs, will head up
the transition leading to the unveiling of Go.com. He has been
overseeing much of the company's Internet efforts since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Some Infoseek shareholders sued Disney in Delaware Chancery
Court yesterday, claiming the buyout shortchanged them. Such
shareholder suits have become commonplace in the Delaware courts
following announcements of large corporate acquisitions, but rarely
halt a purchase.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
