<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7489 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-RECALLCOST-NYT &LR;      07-12 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-RECALLCOST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECALL OF SOFT DRINKS TO COST COKE BOTTLER $103 MILLION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, Belgium, Luxembourg)   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's bottler said Monday that it would take a $103
million charge against second-quarter earnings to cover expenses
associated with the recall of soft drinks in Europe last month,
about 70 percent more than previously acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   The bottler, Coca-Cola Enterprises, said two weeks ago that the
recall involved 14 million cases of soft drinks and would cost the
company $60 million. But that number ballooned to $103 million, or
about 16 cents a diluted share, the company said, after 17 million
cases of products were returned by people living in countries where
Coke products were taken off the shelves in the biggest recall in
Coca-Cola's 113-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The charge erases second-quarter earnings for shareholders of
Coca-Cola Enterprises and leaves little remaining for the full
year. After the crisis occurred, analysts had expected earnings of
about 25 cents a share for the year, but that was before the full
cost of the recall could be calculated.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts now expect the company to earn about 9 cents a share,
said Bill Pecoriello, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola drinks in Belgium and Luxembourg were ordered off
store shelves by the governments of those countries on June 14 and
June 15 after hundreds of people in Belgium reported feeling ill
after drinking Coke and Fanta.
</P>
<P>
   More products were returned in France, where the government
ordered Coke to shut down a plant in Dunkirk that produced cans of
soft drinks that were found to have a strange odor, traced by the
company to a phenol compound that was applied to wood shipping
pallets. Coke products were banned in Belgium and Luxembourg for
more than a week, and factories in France and Belgium were closed
for the same amount of time while government investigators sought
to trace what had caused symptoms like nausea, dizziness and
headaches reported by people who drank the products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The increase in the nonrecurring charge is partially due to
higher product returns as a result of greater-than-anticipated
inventory in consumers' homes,'' Coca-Cola Enterprises said in a
statement. ``In addition, disposal costs increased because of the
larger quantities of product destroyed and the estimated per-case
cost of disposal which reflects the extraordinary quality control
procedures that will be used for product destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the charges would not affect Coca-Cola
Enterprises' earnings for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Asman, a spokeswoman for the bottler, called the situation
``unprecedented'' and added that the company had no idea how many
soft drinks were already in people's homes when the recall began.
Those drinks were brought back to stores and turned over to Coke
executives, who were ordered to destroy them. Some of those drinks
may have been from factories other than the ones under scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is they had people returning their Coca-Cola whether
or not it came from those plants,'' said Emanuel Goldman, a global
consumer-products analyst for Merrill Lynch. ``That's probably what
got them.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the $103 million ``not small potatoes,'' noting that
it was about 6 percent of Coca-Cola Enterprises' overseas volume
for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how much the recall will cost the Coca-Cola Co.
The company is expected to release its second-quarter earnings
before the stock market opens on Thursday. Coca-Cola Enterprises is
scheduled to report earnings on July 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing of this magnitude has ever happened in the Coke
system,'' Ms. Asman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
