<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7490 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     07-12 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FENWAY'S ALL-STAR MONSTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's known as The Green Monster or The Wall, but by any
other name, Fenway Park would smell as sweet. To sluggers.
</P>
<P>
   From the 310-foot mark below the left-field foul pole to the
379-foot mark near center field, it's 37 feet high with an ``All
Star Game `99'' logo in big letters. Above is a 23-foot screen
where Bucky Dent's home run landed for the New York Yankees in the
1978 divisional playoff and where the Boston Red Sox went to die.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway up the light tower in straightaway left field are three
huge Coca-Cola bottles that are as much a target as an
advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   But the real target Tuesday night is the Mass Pike beyond
Lansdowne Street. Nobody has ever hit one that far, but you never
know.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday night's All-Star Game, the fans will be hoping to see
Mark McGwire reach the Massachusetts Turnpike, anywhere from 525
feet to 598 feet away. But whether he does or not, the Green
Monster or The Wall is baseball's All-Star aberration, the most
compelling area of ball park architecture in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about the Green Monster,'' Carlton Fisk was
saying, ``everybody knows where it is.''
</P>
<P>
   And everybody knows that Fisk, then the Red Sox catcher and now
the American League's honorary captain, waved one of Fenway Park's
most famous home runs off the left-field foul pole to square the
1975 World Series with the Cincinnati Reds after six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Wall is really inviting, and we hope the National League
hitters shoot for it; that's when they don't hit it,'' Fisk said.
``I remember Dick Allen going 0-for-7, but then he took his normal
swing and hit one 20 rows deep into the center-field bleachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, those NL hitters, especially the righthanded-swinging
starters with 154 homers this season _ Sammy Sosa, Mark McGwire,
Matt Williams, Jeff Bagwell, Mike Piazza and Jay Bell. McGwire
knows it best from 18 homers in 11 seasons with the Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that Wall is a lot closer than the number says,'' the
Cardinals' first baseman said, alluding to the 310-foot mark. ``I
lost a couple of line drives that would probably have been out in a
normal ball park but hit the Wall. It turns a homer into a
single.''
</P>
<P>
   According to The Boston Globe's videotape study that analyzed
the trajectory of McGwire's record 70 home runs and long fly balls
last season, if he had played all his games in Fenway Park, he
would have hit three more but he would have lost nine for an
overall total of 64.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, the major-league leader this season with 32 for the
Chicago Cubs, hasn't been in Fenway Park since his earlier visits
as a member of the Texas Rangers and the Chicago White Sox, but he
remembered hitting his first big-league homer here off Roger
Clemens, then with the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``From that day on,'' Sosa said, ``I told myself, `I can play
this game.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa played it so well last season, he hit 66 homers, but he'll
always wonder how many he might have hit with half his games in
Fenway Park if the free-agent contract he once signed with the Red
Sox during a labor dispute had not been voided by the
commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I would've played here,'' Sosa said with a smile, ``maybe I
would have hit 72.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza, whose two homers led the Mets to two victories over
the Yankees last weekend, professed not to be thinking about The
Wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very alluring,'' the Mets' catcher said, ``but I think my
strength is gap to gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Life is more difficult for a left-handed slugger in Fenway Park,
although there's a red seat halfway up the bleachers in right field
for the Red Sox's most legendary hitter. Ted Williams lofted a home
run off the straw hat of a fan sitting there in 1946, the same year
he hit two homers in Fenway for the AL in a 12-0 rout in the
All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr., the Mariners' center fielder with 29 homers,
always arrives at Fenway Park with a plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't change my approach in Fenway,'' he said. ``I try to
hit it back up the middle. If it's outside, I try to hit The Wall.
If it's inside, I try to hook it around that pole.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey meant Pesky's Pole down the right-field line that Red
Sox shortstop Johnny Pesky somehow hit for homers.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no nickname for the pole down the left-field line.
The Green Monster wouldn't tolerate any trespassers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
