<SLUG> BC-GORE-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TAKES AIM AGAINST GUN OWNERSHIP RIGHTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore proposed a variety of crime-fighting
ideas Monday aimed partly against gun ownership rights and
indirectly at the Republican presidential campaign of Gov. George
W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking as the Democratic candidate for president, Gore called
for a constitutional amendment guaranteeing rights for crime
victims. They should have official input on the sentencing of the
criminal who wronged them, be notified of the perpetrator's release
from prison and have the right to compensation for the crime, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who delivered his detailed speech at Boston police
headquarters, called for a national law against ``hate crimes,''
more federal funds to hire prosecutors and police officers, and
tougher sentences for crimes against the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   But ``for all the challenges we face in the fight against crime,
there is one that looms over the rest: It is too easy for a child
or criminal to get a gun in America,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government should require states to restrict handgun
sales to buyers who have a special license, including a photo
identification, showing that they have passed a background check
and learned about gun safety, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the government should ban cheap ``junk'' handguns, require
child-proof safety locks on handguns, restrict gun purchases to one
per month and provide grants to help states end plea-bargaining for
criminals who use guns, the vice president said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many political leaders who take their marching
orders from the gun lobby,'' Gore said. ``I call upon you to join
with me to create a family lobby that is greater and more powerful
than the gun lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   A Gore campaign spokesman said the remarks were not intended for
contrast with any other candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore staffers have eagerly acknowledged in the past few
weeks, in response to the shootings at Columbine High School in
Colorado, that Gore is trying to highlight the contrasting gun
ownership policies of Bush, the Republican front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   Bush opposes gun registration and the gun purchasing license
idea, saying that the documentation of law-abiding citizens will
not prevent criminals from using guns.
</P>
<P>
   Bush continues to support tougher sentences for gun violence,
spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said. She contended that the Clinton
administration, which includes Gore, has not adequately prosecuted
gun-related crimes under existing laws.
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican candidate, Elizabeth Dole, said Gore has been
missing from the crime-fighting scene because the federal
government prosecuted few cases involving weapons being carried
into schools.
</P>
<P>
   Dole has proposed some of the most far-reaching gun control
ideas in the Republican field, calling for child-proof safety
locks, among other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is proud of statistics showing crime at its lowest level in
25 years and is proposing new programs to suppress crime further,
spokesman Roger Salazar said. He repeated the statement when asked
why Gore had not broached the ideas earlier as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   In the speech, Gore continued to criticize those ``who want more
concealed weapons'' and ``want to enact new protections for gun
manufacturers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush signed the 1995 law that allowed law-abiding citizens to
carry concealed handguns in Texas as well as a law passed this year
virtually banning lawsuits against gun manufacturers by cities and
other local government agencies. He has said concealed weapons
allow citizens to protect themselves against criminals and that the
lawsuit ban would reduce frivolous lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has also said that gun safety locks should be voluntary and
that gun buyers should have to wait a day _ rather than the
three-day period favored by Gore _ before a background check clears
the way for a sale.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, Gore's competition
for the Democratic nomination, has already called for the
registration of each gun in the nation, a ban on the sale of
``Saturday Night special'' handguns, a ban on gun sales in
residential areas, mandatory safety locks and gun safety training
for every gun owner.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said in the prepared text of his speech that the need for
hate crime legislation was bolstered when a Midwestern racist
recently shot blacks, Asian-Americans and Jews before killing
himself during a police chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``It astonishes me that, just two weeks after the terrible
crimes of hate in Illinois and Indiana, some still deny that hate
crimes merit stiffer punishment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's state Legislature, Bush declined to take sides
over a hate crimes bill for Texas, but also said that laws should
punish deeds instead of thoughts. The bill did not pass.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also addressed issues of crime and race.
</P>
<P>
   He said there should be scholarships to help more minorities
become police officers, prosecutors and public defenders. He also
urged a ban on ``racial profiling'' _ the practice of putting
people under criminal suspicion because of their race.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I am elected president, (the ban) will be the first civil
rights action of the new century,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
