<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BUFFY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WB BLEW IT IN DELAYING `BUFFY' FINALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The WB missed a fabulous opportunity by postponing the season
finale of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Like every ``Buffy'' episode, the delayed finale is dripping
with symbolism. Creator Joss Whedon delights in it, exploring teen
angst on two levels _ one achingly real for any viewer who can
remember the high school experience, the other really aching, but
only for the stunt people and anyone who gets too close to a stray
slayer kick. For the rest, it's a fantasy experience, save for the
inherent allegorical meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of otherworldly meanies do get whacked in the finale,
which airs Tuesday night. A few good guys, too. But violence, while
always a part of ``Buffy,'' is never the message. Tonight's lesson,
for instance, includes a subtle reminder on the importance of
inclusiveness and teamwork. And the marquee exercise _ no surprise
here _ involves the triumph of righteousness over cruelty, hatred
and fear, regardless of cost or loss.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been nice to hear this message on May 25, five
weeks after the horrible shootings at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo. But the brass at The WB thought otherwise, fearing
the network would be viewed as insensitive if it aired the episode,
even though it was the second half of a two-part story that began
the week before.
</P>
<P>
   Without giving away too much detail, Tuesday night's episode is
a sort of Joan of Arc tale for the '90s, in which Buffy (Sarah
Michelle Gellar) leads students in an uprising against the city's
mayor, who chooses the graduation ceremony at Sunnydale High as the
springboard to his transformation into an enormous serpent bent on
world domination, or at least mastery of the greater Sunnydale
metroplex.
</P>
<P>
   The ridiculousness of it all suggests that The WB may be taking
itself too seriously, which is a dangerous development right there.
I mean, come on! The politician as disgusting reptile? How
subversive is that? Rather than questioning the network's motives,
we should be giving it an award for accuracy in entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   And The WB, last time I checked, is all about entertainment. It
doesn't even have a newsmagazine to blur the distinction between
entertainment and information. It exists solely to entertain and,
theoretically, make money for its investors.
</P>
<P>
   By taking the ``Buffy'' finale off the air in May, The WB played
right into the hands of those who want to blame television and the
movies for every act of violence that disrupts our lives. These
people never seem to suggest that the good kids of the world owe
their Eagle Scout behavior to ``Touched by an Angel'' or ``7th
Heaven,'' so the link they make between TV and violence strikes me
as a bit lame. Sure, there's stuff on TV I would never allow a
child to watch, but it usually involves babes in bikinis wielding
automatic weapons. Unfortunately, in the eyes of many who've never
even seen ``Buffy,'' The WB's executive order reduced one of the
best-written, best-acted shows on TV to the level of ``Acapulco
H.E.A.T.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the real shame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
