<SLUG> BC-NY-INSURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE RULING COULD INCREASE HEALTH-CARE PREMIUM COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (md) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Many New Yorkers, already facing increases in health
premiums of more than 10 percent, could face even greater increases
after a ruling by state insurance regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling applies to a popular form of coverage: so-called
point-of-service plans, which generally allow customers to receive
care outside their health maintenance organization's network if
they pay extra.
</P>
<P>
   Under the ruling, insurance companies can no longer offer lower
rates for such plans based on the low health care spending by
employees of some large companies. Independent insurance agents say
the ruling, which affects health plans with 2 million members,
could force up the monthly premium for such plans by $100 to $200
for companies that provide family coverage. The premiums average
$650 a month now, with the employers' share varying widely.
</P>
<P>
   Point-of-service plans usually encourage their members to use
network hospitals and doctors, but the members are permitted to go
to physicians outside the HMO network for an extra charge. The
state has treated them as HMOs, which must offer the same rate to
all customers in New York, except for the portion of services by
non-HMO doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, state regulators allowed the HMOs to offer attractive
deals to big employers to get their business. They based rates on
the number of non-HMO services. But insurance officials say the
companies were inflating the numbers and telling the insurance
department that more members were using non-HMO services than was
actually the case.
</P>
<P>
   The department issued the ruling after receiving complaints from
insurance brokers who said some companies were changing prices in
an inconsistent manner. Members of Oxford Health Plans, which
specializes in point of service, used Oxford doctors 90 percent of
the time and non-network doctors 10 percent, said Charles Henricks,
acting chief of the insurance department health bureau. But in
trying to entice customers with lower rates, Oxford understated how
many of its members were using network doctors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some other big companies used similar sleight of hand to meet
Oxford's prices, Henricks said. Now regulators say that they cannot
do that. Under the new ruling, which takes effect on Feb. 1, 2000,
the point-of-service programs have to offer the same prices to all
comers.
</P>
<P>
   There is a debate about who will benefit. Some industry experts
say premiums for some point of service plans will go up 25 percent
or more. State officials expect the ruling to benefit smaller
groups that were not getting the attractive deals.
</P>
<P>
   The new charges would be on top of double-digit annual increases
already projected for many groups in New York and across the
country as insurance companies push for higher revenues.
</P>
<P>
   But insurance companies say there will be little change in
costs. Oxford says it will rewrite its plans to avoid the ruling,
and several other insurance companies say they are watching closely
to decide what to do. Benefits consultants noted that large
employers can escape the consequences of the ruling by taking
responsibility for insuring their own people, as many already do.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional fee-for-service insurers and self-insured employers
are not subject to the new New York regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Point-of-service plans have about 2 million members in New York
state, including 1 million Oxford members, with the rest shared by
16 other HMOs. They include Cigna Corp., Aetna and United
Healthcare Group. There will be no change for smaller employers
with 2 to 50 workers, which already are charged a rate that does
not reflect their medical histories.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford said Monday it would keep its prices for large employers
substantially unchanged by offering its coverage through an
indemnity unit, Oxford Health Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   While the insurance companies say the ruling should not affect
premiums, several consultants said there could be sharp increases
for some groups.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives said health plans based on indemnity
insurance are usually priced higher than the HMO plans, based on
the expectation that costs would be higher if members and their
doctors could make their own decisions with few restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Travers, a partner in Travers O'Keefe, a Manhattan
insurance agency, said Oxford had handed one large company a 24
percent increase for this year, breaking a promise to limit annual
increases to 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Travers said that after his agency complained to regulators,
Oxford agreed to the 6 percent increase, which he said was $10
million lower than the original increase.
</P>
<P>
   Henricks said regulators noticed discrepancies when took a close
look at Oxford after disclosure of the company's financial
problems. He said Oxford had been losing money on its
point-of-service business, apparently because of the low rates that
it was charging some big employers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
