<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7504 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-CARE-1STLD-WRI     07-12 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-CARE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE OPENS HIGH-STAKES DEBATE OVER REGULATING HMOS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS grafs 4-5 to add summary of differences between Republicans'
and Democrats' version of bill higher in story, recast graf on
floor strategy for clarity; Pickup 6th graf pvs, Republicans
accused ...) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the first time since a health care revolution
began moving patients into managed care more than a decade ago, the
Senate opened a high-stakes debate Monday over how to protect the
rights of patients and regulate the companies that provide health
insurance for most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, the Patients' Bill of Rights Act, is the first
of several politically potent health care issues _ such as an
overhaul of Medicare to include a new prescription drug benefit for
the elderly _ to come to the fore in Congress this session. It
would regulate health maintenance organizations and has broad
implications for doctors, insurance companies, employers and
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   With health care a steady voter concern, the legislation is also
considered so significant for next year's congressional campaigns
that Republicans and Democrats were going to unusual lengths Monday
to frame the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Each side brought in aggrieved citizens to support its version
of the bill. Republicans, whose version provides generally less
regulation than the Democratic version, and would be less
expensive, showcased small-business owners who said that already
they could barely afford health insurance for themselves and their
employees, or could not afford it at all. A man given a platform by
the Democrats told of a son who had died of cancer after an HMO had
refused to pay for a necessary treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The floor strategy was particularly convoluted, as each side
tried to position itself to attack the other's legislation rather
than defend its own. So the bill the Republicans brought to the
floor for debate Monday was an early, more expensive Democratic
version that the minority had superseded. And the Democrats planned
to try to turn that bill into the Republican legislation, through
amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans accused the Democrats of crafting legislation that
would favor lawyers by expanding the right to sue. Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas, said the Democratic bill gives a patient the right to
``choose any lawyer that they could pick out of a phone book.
That's their idea of health care freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats countered that the Republicans were protecting the
profits of health maintenance organizations. ``It is interesting to
hear HMOs and their allies in the Senate weeping crocodile tears
over the cost increases they claim our protections will cause,''
said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., noting that the top 10 HMOs
in the country made $1.5 billion in profits last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cheapest insurance policy is one that pays the fewest
benefits when you get sick,'' Kennedy said, ``and that seems to be
the goal of too many unscrupulous managed care companies.''
</P>
<P>
   As the four-day debate began, an array of powerful interest
groups, from the insurance industry to organized labor to the
American Medical Association, were also waging television and
newspaper advertising campaigns on both sides of the issue,
primarily in the states of swing Republicans, some of them up for
election next year, who are regarded as swing voters on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The health insurance industry announced a one-year, $10.5
million television campaign, featuring doctors, that is intended to
burnish the image of managed care. The AFL-CIO said it was putting
more than $400,000 worth of ads on the air in eight states in favor
of the Democrats' bill. And, acting against the Democrat's bill, a
coalition of businesses and insurance companies continued an
advertising campaign that they said would cost $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The war of the airwaves reflected the awareness that the health
insurance industry's ``Harry and Louise'' ad campaign helped sink
President Clinton's proposal for universal health care coverage in
1994 and that a multimillion dollar campaign by the tobacco
industry last year proved fatal to anti-smoking legislation by
reframing it as a tax increase for smokers instead of as a public
health issue.
</P>
<P>
   The issue before the Senate is how to guarantee patients' access
to medical care. Both versions would give patients easier access to
emergency rooms, and specialists like obstetricians and
pediatricians.
</P>
<P>
   But there are significant differences as well. ``This is a
difference in approach that we think is as profound as anything
that divides Republicans and Democrats,'' said Senate Minority
Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, saying they are acting in deference to the
rights of states, would extend many protections only to the 48
million Americans whose insurance is regulated exclusively by the
federal government, not by the states, although the provision in
their bill guaranteeing a right to appeal a health plan's denial of
treatment would apply to a broader group of 120 million. The
Democrats, in contrast, would cover all 161 million Americans with
private insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats would expand the rights of Americans to sue their
health plans in state court, but the Republicans would not.
Currently most Americans in managed care plans must bring suits
over coverage decisions in federal court, where a patient can
typically collect the value of the care denied but not punitive
damages.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans and Democrats also differ over who decides
whether treatment is medically necessary, with Republicans allowing
insurance companies to make the final judgment and Democrats
granting that decision to doctors, subject to some federal
guidelines. Both bills would allow patients to appeal adverse
decisions _ first to the health plan and then to an independent
panel _ although the details differ.
</P>
<P>
   With regulation of health maintenance organizations a
centerpiece of their legislative agenda, the Democrats for several
years have had the upper hand in this debate. It was their party
that forced the legislation to the floor by tying up the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans and their industry allies Monday sought to turn
the debate away from the Democrats' preferred ground of patient
protection to the question of increased premium costs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To bolster their case, they put an early version of the
Democrats' measure on the Senate floor as the base bill for debate
instead of their own bill. The Congressional Budget Office had
found that that bill would have raised the costs of insurance
premiums by 6.1 percent. The Democrats subsequently altered their
bill so that it would raise premiums by 4.8 percent. The Republican
bill would raise premiums by less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans repeatedly cited the earliest version of the
Democratic bill as they argued that the Democrats would force
people and small businesses to give up health insurance as too
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Democrat bill is fatally flawed,'' said Senate
Majority Whip Don Nickles from Oklahoma, charging that it would
increase health care costs for a family insurance plan by $350.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would add 1.8 million people to the list of the
uninsured,'' he said, ``That is a serious mistake. We don't want to
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The same theme was struck in the ads run by the coalition of
businesses and health insurers in several states represented by
Republican senators. One such 30-second spot featured three
Americans worried about losing their health insurance. ``I gotta
pay more for new government regulations?'' asked one indignant man.
``I can barely afford insurance now.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats charged that the Republicans were inflating the price
of their bill and overstating its effects on the ranks of the
uninsured. They said it would cost an individual an additional $2 a
month in premiums, or as Kennedy put it, ``the cost of a Big Mac.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats sought to portray the Republican bill as
inadequate and their own bill as one that would protect patients
from insurance companies seeking to cut costs by providing inferior
care. ``Theirs is not a bill of rights,'' Daschle said. ``It's a
bill of goods.''
</P>
<P>
   With a 55-45 hold over the Senate, the Republicans are likely to
prevail by week's end. But the days will bring a series of votes on
amendments that both sides want to use to highlight their
differences in the next election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
