<DOCNO> NYT19990712.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7507 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALL-STAR-GAME-NYT     07-12 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALL-STAR-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA, BOSTON'S HERO, LEADS SHORTSTOP PACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The passionate feelings about whether Nomar Garciaparra
would be voted in as the American League's shortstop for the
All-Star Game over Derek Jeter filled this parochial city for
weeks. After Garciaparra squeaked by Jeter, with a late boost from
Internet voters, the dominant question shifted to whether or not
Garciaparra would be healthy enough to play.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra missed Boston's last nine games with a strained left
groin muscle, but he eased the minds of every cab driver, bellhop
and bartender who fretted about the sinewy shortstop's availability
at fabled Fenway Park on Tuesday night by stressing that he would
definitely start. An entire city exhaled.
</P>
<P>
   So Red Sox fans are breathing easily because Garciaparra's
injury will not stop him from starting in this midsummer spectacle
and because the incomparable Pedro Martinez will start against the
National League's Curt Schilling, the former Red Sox minor-leaguer
and current star for the Philadelphia Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless I didn't want to come back to Boston,'' joked Manager
Joe Torre, ``I think that was the only choice.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no debate about Tuesday's starting pitcher for the AL,
because of Martinez's brilliance and because Torre recalled the
ovation the fans gave him when he returned following prostate
cancer surgery here in May and wanted to give them a gift. But
Torre and David Cone continued the ongoing shortstop debate by
respectfully arguing that Jeter, a fellow Yankee, deserved to be
the starter, not Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeter might be the MVP of the league,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   Do not expect this shortstop debate to cease for another decade.
While players discussed Martinez's being halfway to the magical
total of 30 victories and Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire targeting the
Green Monster, they gushed over the shortstops from the American
League. The group is so talented _ with All-Stars Garciaparra,
Jeter and Cleveland's Omar Vizquel _ that Alex Rodriguez, a
wondrous 24-year-old who had 42 homers and 46 steals for Seattle
last season, was not even selected, primarily because he missed
time with an injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are freaks of nature,'' said Barry Larkin, who is
starting at shortstop for the NL. ``It's amazing the things that
they're capable of doing. These guys are a rarity.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin sounded more like a fan than a player who is appearing in
his seventh All-Star Game as he talked of favoring Jeter's defense,
Garciaparra's overall play and Rodriguez's power. What about
Vizquel? Vizquel refused to put himself in the same category as the
terrific trio since he is more renowned for bunting than bashing
baseballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be hard to see guys like this come around in
baseball ever again,'' Vizquel said. ``Guys doing what they're
doing is unreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the consistent Larkin, there is also strength at the
position in the NL with Florida's Alex Gonzalez, an All-Star who
might win the Rookie of the Year Award, and the Mets' Rey Ordonez,
who could be the best defensive player in the majors. But they are
not as formidable as the big three of Nomar, Derek and A-Rod and
the little one named Omar.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're talking shortstop, nowadays you're talking about
some of the very best players in the game,'' said Cal Ripken, the
pioneer for the power-hitting shortstop, who played 14 All-Star
Games at the position. ``It's great to watch and to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone added: ``These guys are MVP-type players who play
shortstop, which is normally a defensive position. I don't know how
that's going to impact future generations, but I know there a lot
of kids who are playing shortstop because of those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra is not 100 percent, but he said that he was capable
of playing and would use the All-Star Game as preparation for the
resumption of the season on Thursday. While Garciaparra was coy as
to how much he plans to play, he might only bat once. Simply seeing
him at his familiar position, even briefly, should satisfy fans who
helped ensure he would be the marquee shortstop for this marquee
game in his own city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's a great time to be a fan of the game,''
Garciaparra said. There's great players all around at every
position in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially shortstop. Jeter admitted he studies box scores to
see how other shortstops have done and claimed it motivates him to
do even better. The Yankee danced like a Rockette when he was asked
to name the best shortstop and playfully decided on his father,
Charles, a former college shortstop. That was not the only time
Jeter behaved like an excitable 12-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're overwhelmed by this whole experience,'' Jeter said.
``You feel like a little kid. You want to run around and get
autographs from everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   It is always interesting to watch All-Stars interact with
All-Stars. There was Jeter peeking over the heads of reporters
gathered around Bernie Williams to get a smile from his teammate,
and Garciaparra's relatives toting a video camera to tape his
unforgettable day, and Ken Griffey Jr. blaming his tardiness on his
3-year-old daughter, who wanted her father to watch cartoons in the
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the chatty Schilling, who called himself
``excited, honored and anxious'' to start the game, even if he said
that watching Martinez dominate hitters has been like watching an
elite major-leaguer subdue Class AAA hitters. But Schilling grinned
and said he planned to throw lots of fastballs and relish his
All-Star experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm as nervous for this game as any game I've ever pitched,''
Schilling explained. ``Because I'm still a fan, I guess. I grew up
watching the All-Star Game. Tomorrow night, it's the only game on
Earth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
