<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7510 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALL-STAR-NOTEBOOK     07-12 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALL-STAR-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ IS STARTING, BUT HE REFUSES TO FORGET A SNUB 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Boston's Pedro Martinez is excited about starting the
All-Star Game at Fenway Park on Tuesday, but the Red Sox pitcher
still harbors animosity toward Cleveland Manager Mike Hargrove for
failing to start him last season. Hargrove picked David Wells, who
was a Yankee then, and Martinez took the choice as a snub.
</P>
<P>
   At last year's All-Star Game break, Martinez was 11-2 with a
2.87 earned run average and had 142 strikeouts and 34 walks in
1251/3 innings. Wells was 11-2 with a 3.75 ERA and had 88
strikeouts and 17 walks in 1121/3 innings. In addition, Wells had
thrown a perfect game for the best team in baseball. While the
statistics favored Martinez, it was not shocking that Hargrove
chose Wells, and it seemed a little drastic for Martinez to hold a
year-long grudge.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a different manager this year,'' Martinez said in
reference to Joe Torre. ``Last year we had a manager who was in
love with David Wells. This year, the manager didn't bring any
excuses like the other guy gives me a better chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who did not pitch in the 1998 All-Star Game, added,
``I'm sure Hargrove knows and realizes what happened after that,''
in an apparent reference to his beating Cleveland in Game 1 of the
division series last year. The Indians won the series.
</P>
<P>
   With a 15-2 record at the break this season, Martinez has
created a stir about possibly becoming the first pitcher in 31
years to win 30 games. Detroit's Denny McLain went 31-6 in 1968,
and Martinez thinks the lofty goal is attainable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get the outings, I don't see why not,'' Martinez said.
``I don't see why it's that difficult if you have 35 starts. It
could happen. I don't know if anyone can do it. I hope it's me.''
</P>
<P>
   Other All-Star pitchers doubted that Martinez could reach 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not in 35 starts,'' Curt Schilling said. ``No way. Just the
fact that you can talk about it as a realistic shot at the All-Star
break is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   David Cone compared winning 30 to Joe DiMaggio's 56-game hitting
streak and said: ``I think he would have to be perfect. He's going
to have to be near perfect to do it, and he's going to need the run
support and some help from his bullpen because he's not going to
throw a complete game each time out.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JACK CURRY
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez `Out of Line'
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez chose not to participate in the All-Star Game if
he was not picked as a starter by the fans, and the Texas
outfielder was criticized by some for not accepting being selected
as a reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Carlton Fisk, the former Red Sox catcher who is the honorary
captain for the American League, spoke harshly about Gonzalez's
decision and called it ``totally out of line.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether that's an attitude or selfishness on his
part, but it is, when you consider what kind of player he is, what
kind of statistics he has on the board at this time and not
allowing the rest of the league or the rest of the world to see his
talents,'' Fisk said. ``I think down the line he may regret that
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa, who played with Gonzalez in Texas, said: ``For me as
a friend and a person, I think the decision he made wasn't a very
good decision. But that's his business. Nothing I can do about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JACK CURRY
</P>
<P>
   Torre's `Shy' Debut
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, manager of the American League All-Star team, Monday
recalled the first time he started in an All-Star Game. It was at
Shea Stadium in New York, he said, in 1964, when he was ``a shy
23-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Drysdale was the starting pitcher, and Torre, who was
catching, wanted to go over the signs with him for his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him what sign he wanted for the spitter,'' Torre
related, ``and he said, `I'll just throw it off my fastball.' I
said OK. It was probably the dumbest thing I've ever done. In the
first inning I wound up going back to say hello to Mayor Wagner
about four times. After that, we had a sign.''
</P>
<P>
   _ MURRAY CHASS
</P>
<P>
   Excited a Million Times Over
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bell was elected to start at second base for the National
League All-Stars, but that role will have to take second place to
the experience he had Sunday. As part of an Arizona Diamondbacks
promotion, a female fan won $1 million because Bell hit a grand
slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to to hit a home run; I tried to hit a home run and
fortunately I did,'' Bell said. ``That was a much bigger highlight
than being here, no question about it. I couldn't have asked for a
better end to the first half than to have someone win $1 million
because I swung a bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell, who had already hit 23 home runs this season, said he knew
the situation when he went to bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was probably more excited about a home run than I ever have
been,'' he said. ``I was excited that this lady won a million
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   _ MURRAY CHASS
</P>
<P>
   Dream Park for Sosa
</P>
<P>
   During the work stoppage of 1994, the Red Sox signed Sammy Sosa,
Kevin Appier and John Wetteland to free agent contracts. But all
three were voided because the signings occurred before baseball
instituted its new policies for the 1995 season.
</P>
<P>
   What would have happened to Sosa if he had come to Boston and
played in friendly Fenway?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I would have hit 72,'' said Sosa, whose 66 homers were
second last year to Mark McGwire's career record of 70.
</P>
<P>
   _ JACK CURRY
</P>
</TEXT>
