<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAYS IN THE SUN FOR THE GIRLS OF SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JERRY BREWER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Their plane from Anaheim, Calif., landed at Newark
International Airport at 4 a.m. Monday, and they slipped into New
York City while it was dozing. By 6 a.m., the U.S. women's soccer
team was leaving its midtown hotel and stepping onto a chartered
bus. Most of the players had not had time to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so tired I can't even give you good quotes right now,''
Kate Sobrero said. ``I'm just so exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   But no one was complaining. A blizzard of morning television
shows awaited the 1999 Women's World Cup champions, news media
attention that they thought was cool.
</P>
<P>
   Much cooler than in 1991, Mia Hamm recalled, when the U.S. team
flew into New York after winning the first women's world
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were thinking we might get a ticker-tape parade,'' Hamm
said. ``Only two people showed up at the airport. This shows the
evolution of our game.''
</P>
<P>
   So 19 women _ every player except Michelle Akers, who has
chronic fatigue syndrome and was still recovering from heat
exhaustion and remained in California _ put on matching outfits
they had picked months ago and hit the town. They wore lavender
shirts, black pants, matching black sandals and cemented smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Weary but still chipper, they hopped on and off their bus for
four hours, stopping for appearances on ``Good Morning America,''
``Today,'' CNN and Fox.
</P>
<P>
   As they traveled, the players interacted with fans, signed
autographs and, especially, talked to little girls. They stopped
midtown traffic when they lifted up their championship trophy and
bopped around singing, ``We Are the Champions.''
</P>
<P>
   With their trademark grace and congeniality, the U.S. team,
which beat China on penalty kicks on Saturday, marched on with
their victory tour. They saved the yawns for commercial breaks, but
as the camera lights turned on, so did their charm.
</P>
<P>
   They were so courteous that some of the players offered to move
to seats in the back of the bus to accommodate the small news media
contingent that traveled with them.
</P>
<P>
   They played with the microphone during a commercial break on
``Good Morning America.'' Jackie Joyner-Kersee stopped by the ABC
set for hugs and praise. Wayne Gretzy called. Vice President Al
Gore saluted them, too.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm did not seem to mind when a ``Today'' show producer looked
down at his scribbled notes and pronounced her first name ``Mian.''
</P>
<P>
   Later at CNN, a worker asked her to spell her name.
</P>
<P>
   ``M-I-A H-A-M-M,'' she said kindly as the rest of the crew
giggled.
</P>
<P>
   Brandi Chastain laughed at and set up countless jokes about her
shirt-tossing, sports bra-bearing celebration moments after her
Cup-winning penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   Here was one exchange as Chastain finished explaining how she
lost her gold medal from the World Cup in Los Angeles on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just lost it in the ruckus after the game,'' she said.
``Somebody's enjoying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her teammate Carla Overbeck quickly responded, ``You should say
it just flew off when you took your shirt off.''
</P>
<P>
   The players scurried to the bus after each show, stopping to
sign as many autographs as time allowed. Once on the bus, they
didn't have much time to relax. Many of the players' cellphones
rang so much that it sounded like a telethon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch us at 8:30 on `Good Morning America,''' one player said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got 17 messages on my cellphone!'' said the team spokesman,
Aaron Heifetz.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday, the team can relax for a few days _ and with more
financial assurance. Each player will now receive a $50,000 bonus
from the U.S. Soccer Federation instead of the original $12,500
they were promised if they won the title. The United States Olympic
Committee said it was giving $6,000 to each player on the team.
</P>
<P>
   A few players planned to leave Monday to go home, but much of
the team will be at Niketown on Fifth Avenue Tuesday at noon for a
rally.
</P>
<P>
   They are scheduled to be on ``The Late Show With David
Letterman'' next Tuesday. A few players are planning to go to the
Women's National Basketball Association All-Star Game Wednesday
night at Madison Square Garden. Some will participate in
Wednesday's LPGA JAL Big Apple Classic Pro-Am in New Rochelle, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing is that we're promoting women's soccer,''
Chastain said. ``It's worth all of this. We're tired, but we're not
complaining. This is such a great time.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what this team does now, Hamm said: ``Rest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 2213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
