</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-IMPACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD CUP MARKETERS MISSED AN OPPORTUNITY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the apparent savvy marketing and luck that vaulted the
U.S. women's soccer team into the public consciousness, one area of
business failed to ignite: the retail sale of licensed merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merchandising was a missed opportunity,'' June McIvor, the
senior vice president and chief operating officer of the Women's
World Cup, said Monday. ``It didn't catch on. Retailers
underestimated what the event was about, and by the time they
understood it, it was too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Selling T-shirts, jerseys, caps, key chains and other
merchandise emblazoned with the official logos and slogans of
events and leagues is a standard sport-business practice.
Short-term ``hot markets'' for the apparel of World Series or Super
Bowl winners often reap millions of dollars in quickie regional
sales.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not happen for the Women's World Cup, which
succeeded only in selling licensed goods at the stadiums where the
games were played.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't keep it in stock at the stadiums,'' she said.
``Even before the first game at Giants Stadium, we were sold out.''
</P>
<P>
   Selling the products at retail proved an unusually hard sell,
however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain the lack of retail acceptance,'' McIvor said.
``It seemed like a perfect product. Manufacturers cut back on
production.'' Among retailers, she said, only the Lady Foot Locker
chain did reasonably well.
</P>
<P>
   Adidas U.S.A., a World Cup sponsor and apparel manufacturer,
generated late sales of T-shirts once the tournament began, but
nearly all came from stadium vendors. Rick Chastain (no relation to
the U.S. player Brandi Chastain), Adidas U.S.A.'s director of event
marketing, said, ``The traditional retail relationship was not as
much as we had hoped.''
</P>
<P>
   At Lady Foot Locker, where 7,000 tournament tickets were given
away in an Adidas promotion, merchandise sold briskly, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Adidas sold a mixture of T-shirts and caps, plus more expensive
custom-made and embroidered jerseys and warm-up suits that were
produced overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain said the lack of a broad-based retail ardor was
understandable because ``the World Cup didn't market itself prior
to the event as much as we had hoped.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to retailers a year ago with our line of goods,'' he
said, ``but we didn't see tremendous outreach in the public of the
event itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The impact of winning may propel stars like Mia Hamm, Brandi
Chastain, Julie Foudy and Briana Scurry to sign more endorsement
deals, especially if they stay with the national team through next
year's Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the World Cup victory translates into the start of a
professional women's league (sometime after next year's Olympics)
or a network frenzy to snare the rights to the 2003 tournament are
uncertainties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Organizing a league takes a lot of heavy lifting,'' said Doug
Logan, the commissioner of Major League Soccer, which was started
after the United States was host to the men's 1994 World Cup in
which the American team had little chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now women's soccer has the attention of the public, but the
public is fickle,'' Logan said, adding that finding talented
players would not be an insurmountable obstacle even if the popular
Americans were dispersed to each team in the league. ``It's a
bigger problem to be playing on a hot Wednesday with the threat of
thunderstorms, and an advance sale of 714 tickets.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The news media's perception of the league is crucial to its
success, Logan said. ``Even if you fill up a small stadium, it's
hard to convince the media that something significant has taken
place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 13.3 overnight Nielsen rating for the U.S.-China World Cup
final on Saturday is no guarantee of network interest in the 2003
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're interested, but a lot depends on if the American women
win the Olympics next year,'' said Howard Katz, the president of
ABC Sports.
</P>
<P>
   But David Hill, chairman of the Fox Sports Group, flatly said he
was not a convert and was not interested in the 2003 event. ``I
don't think Saturday's game will have any lasting impact on U.S. TV
ratings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, leading into Saturday's final, women made up only
34 percent of the World Cup audience on ESPN and 35 percent on
ESPN2, compared with 39 percent for ESPN's Women's National
Basketball Association games and 40 percent for the National
Collegiate Athletic Association women's basketball championship
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men may just be more tuned in to watching sports,'' McIvor
said. ``Watching sports events is a new experience for a lot of
women.''
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of women watching Saturday's final may have been
higher because of the influx of casual viewers enticed by the hype
leading up to the game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
