A7524 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT &LR;      07-12 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KATE SPADE STRIDES INTO SHOES; ATLANTA TO CHELSEA; WHAT VISIONAIRE
BEGAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You might say that Kate Spade's business is principally for the
limbs. She has bags and wallets for those who like to express
themselves by what they carry, and she has added stationery and
colorfully bound organizers, which can make the interior of a pink
sail-cloth tote look as orderly as a Sister Parish room.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ms. Spade, who runs her five-year-old business with her
husband, Andy, is branching into shoes. The first collection,
mainly of leather thongs, crystal-covered sandals and slides in
Life Saver stripes, will arrive in stores in the fall in time for
resort clothes. The shoes are being made under a license to GFW
Group, which also produces private-label shoes for Bergdorf
Goodman. They'll sell for $160 to $250.
</P>
<P>
   What took her so long to come out with shoes to go with her
bags? Ms. Spade laughed. ``I would have loved to have done them
sooner, but we've been growing so much,'' she said. The company,
which started with half a dozen nylon bags, expects to have a
wholesale volume this year of $40 million. Last February, Neiman
Marcus, the Dallas-based retailer, bought a 56 percent stake in
Kate Spade for $33.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Spade and her husband, who is developing an accessories line
for men, called Jack Spade, said they have no plans to design
clothes, though they make a few things like pajamas and scarves.
With accessories driving a lot of designer businesses, who can
fault them for their decision or timing? As Spade said, ``I think
we kind of sneaked in through the back door when everybody was
focused on the runway.''
</P>
<P>
   JEFFREY FROM ATLANTA
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Aug. 2, his birthday, Jeffrey Kalinsky, along with
a rabbi and a throng of friends and family, will cut the ribbon for
Jeffrey, a 12,000-square-foot store on West 14th Street in the
meat-packing district. In a way, Jeffrey is Kalinsky's version of a
Judith Krantz title: ``I'll Take Manhattan in a Pair of Gucci
Pants.'' Kalinsky, whose family has been in the shoe business for
50 years, was a retail buyer in New York before opening a boutique
in Atlanta in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's betting that the popularity of Chelsea (and the offer
of valet parking) will lure the downtown and uptown fashion crowds
to humble 14th Street. Last week, he showed a visitor the space,
which runs like a jetway from 14th Street to 15th Street and is
technically on the ground floor of 450 West 15th Street, which
includes KCD, the fashion public relations firm, and the designer
John Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very, very art gallery and movie set,'' Kalinsky said.
The space will have white walls, a concrete floor and minimalist
furniture by Troy covered in gray Ultrasuede. In the center will be
a shoe salon (with sizes from 4 to 12, AAAA to C widths), and at
the ends will be men's and women's clothes by designers like Jil
Sander, Gucci, Balenciaga, Helmut Lang and Courreges.
</P>
<P>
   Kalinsky says he is paying less for a square foot in Chelsea
than he does in Atlanta. He is buoyant about high-fashion
retailing, despite the demise of stores like Charivari. ``It's like
they said in that movie: `If you build it, they will come,''' he
said. ``I'm a believer.''
</P>
<P>
   VISIONAIRE MEETS THE BIBLE
</P>
<P>
   ``When people first heard about the idea, they wondered if we
were going to be ironic,'' said Cecilia Dean, an editor of
Visionaire, whose 28th number, due out in early August, will be
based on the Bible. ``But it really was about taking the greatest
story ever told and giving it a beautiful and modern
interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   Printed on the glossy cardboard stock used by children's book
publishers and edged in gold, the magazine has the weight and
thickness of an oversize Bible. Inside, on double-page spreads,
artists and photographers like Raymond Meier, David Levinthal and
Mario Sorrenti interpret scenes from biblical books like Exodus and
Revelations. For instance, in an image inspired by Exodus, Andreas
Gursky, a London-based photographer, shows a crowd writhing toward
a celestial light. It was taken at a rave in England.
</P>
<P>
   Visionaire 28, which sells for $150, will be enclosed in a
translucent plastic shell designed by Philippe Starck. The idea,
Ms. Dean said, was to make it look as if it were suspended inside,
with the gold glowing through.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
