<HEADER>
A7527 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-NYT &LR;      07-12 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS COULD SUFFER IF BARROOM BRAWL RESULTS IN SUSPENSION FOR
ELLIOTT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Mass., Washington, D.C., Colo.)   By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If Jumbo Elliott's arrest on misdemeanor charges
stemming from a barroom brawl results in a suspension by the
National Football League, the Jets' chances of continuing their
remarkable surge could be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, 34, the Jets' left tackle and a key member of the
offensive unit, pleaded not guilty to misdemeanor charges Monday in
Long Beach, N.Y., City Court, as did offensive lineman Jason
Fabini, 24, the Jets' top rookie last season, and Matt O'Dwyer, 26,
a former Jet guard now with the Cincinnati Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott and Fabini are scheduled to appear at a hearing on July
26, three days before they are to report for the start of Jets
training camp. O'Dwyer also faces a felony charge of second-degree
assault against two police officers who say he kicked out the
window of a patrol car when placed inside it, sending glass into
their faces. O'Dwyer will have a court appearance on that charge
July 26 in Nassau County Court.
</P>
<P>
   If the Jets have to start the season without Elliott at left
tackle, three-fifths of their offensive line would be new, because
they do not have players at either right or left guard with any NFL
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the units on a team, the offensive line is generally
recognized as the one requiring the most work and the most
familiarity among its individual members. Behind Elliott at left
tackle there is only Kerry Jenkins, whom the Jets acquired as a
free agent several years ago and who did not have one play at
offensive tackle last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets expect to to go into training camp without any guard
who has NFL experience. The club recently lost O'Dwyer to free
agency and dropped left guard Todd Burger.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are coming off one of their best seasons since winning
the Super Bowl in 1969. They finished 12-4 and won the American
Football Conference East Division, getting all the way to the
conference championship game. The line was pivotal in protecting
quarterback Vinny Testaverde, who produced his finest season.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have some difficult games early in the season. They
face a division rival, the New England Patriots, in the opener on
Sept. 12, followed by a Sunday night game at Buffalo. A week after
that the Jets are host to the Washington Redskins, then go to
Denver to face the Broncos, the team that defeated them in the
conference championship game last January and went on to win the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, Fabini and O'Dwyer were arrested about midnight Friday
at Bogart's, a Long Beach restaurant and bar frequented by Jets
players. According to the police, Elliott urinated in a wash basin
in the women's restroom. A woman told the police that Elliott, 6
feet 7 inches and 300 pounds, punched her in the stomach when she
confronted him. According to the police, Elliott then hit a male
patron when he returned from the restroom.
</P>
<P>
   It was Elliott's second run-in with the legal system in 10
months. He is believed to have undergone league-mandated counseling
after being convicted of driving while impaired last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott is likely to be contacted soon by the league's vice
president for player and employee development, Lem Burnham, who
oversees counseling for players charged with violent crimes.
Historically, the league has dealt with alcohol-related incidents
with a fine. There have been no suspensions under the year-old
policy dealing with charges of violent crime, but there have been
fines and mandatory counseling. Once charged with a violent crime,
a player is subject to counseling and discipline by Commissioner
Paul Tagliabue, regardless of whether the player is convicted.
</P>
<P>
   But there are two elements working against Elliott: the possible
involvement with alcohol (although the police did not mention
alcohol) and a charge of assault. So if Elliott is convicted of any
of the charges, a suspension could follow in view of his previous
problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' coach, Bill Parcells, is on vacation, as is his entire
staff, his secretary said Monday, and they were not available for
comment. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
