<HEADER>
A7529 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IBM-FUTURE-COX     07-12 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-FUTURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IBM Corp. interns invent telepathy over the Internet
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A group of IBM Corp. interns sits in a hotel
room on the third floor of the Renaissance Hotel, and, using
lunchtime fajitas and Dr Pepper as creative fuel, they're making
the first neural network translating binary code into synaptic
pulses.
</P>
<P>
   In English: They're inventing telepathy over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   By 2025, according to their business plan, everybody will have
one _ a tiny device worn on the ear that lets you retrieve
information and communicate with others just by thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   They'll call it ``Mindware.''
</P>
<P>
   This is your brain. This is your brain on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (will) become as accepted as the cell phone today,'' says
Chris Simoes, an intern from the University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   But surely there's a downside.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're networked, people could get into your head,'' Simoes
adds.
</P>
<P>
   Any other liabilities? ``It could fry your brain,'' points out
Timothy Weiand, a Tivoli intern from Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, 3,500 IBM interns and engineers got together at IBM
sites around the world for a day of brainstorming.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, home to one of the company's major research sites,
more than 300 summer workers created their own imaginary companies
with unlimited money. The companies were to launch next year and to
continue through 2025, with a global Depression thrown in for fun.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``fantasy startup camp'' for the interns, and a way for IBM
to open its gates to new ideas while putting out feelers for
potential hires.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brainpower of these students is the future of technology
and the future of our company,'' said Alison Barnes, a human
resources staffer for IBM in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Students from about 60 high schools and colleges came up with
ideas for new companies that ranged from the highly probable _
custom music CDs sold on the Web to the highly dubious. One of
Weiand's group's early efforts, for instance, was ``Bubba's Custom
Cow Co.,'' which would genetically engineer meat or dairy cows for
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll create a cow and Fed-Ex it to you,'' he said during
one of the initial pitches. ``Just like you'd say I want a blue car
with leather interior, you can get a brown-spotted cow with leather
exterior.''
</P>
<P>
   They're versed as much on pop culture and science fiction as on
quantum physics and math. When Weiand's and Simoes' group came up
with a brain implant _ the precursor to the telepathic ear device _
one group member asked, ``Is this a 'Johnny Mnemonic' implant or an
implant like in 'The Matrix?''' referring to sci-fi movies with
similar conventions. Derrick Chubbs, an IBM product engineer who
worked as a kind of tech-camp counselor for the students, said much
of the early discussion for the Mindware group veered away from
science and toward how technology will be used by real people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started by talking about what a dream job would be and they
all agreed that they want technology to help them spend more time
with their family and less time working,'' Chubbs said. ``And they
have a social conscience. They say, 'let's not forget everybody.'''
</P>
<P>
   Group Mindware began the day by coming up with ideas for new
companies. As the session went on, the group focused on a single
company idea, product, and marketing strategy. By lunchtime, the
group brainstormed on a name, slogan and future. Then the students
thought ahead to 2010, through the Depression of 2020 and finally
to the company's annual meeting in 2025.
</P>
<P>
   With about 15 other groups, Mindware then presented itself in
true Silicon Valley startup fashion: with a timed two-minute pitch
aimed at conveying what the company had done and what its post-2025
plans were. The premise _ the annual shareholder's meeting of the
future _ brought out a grab-bag of ideas clearly inspired by
today's initial public offering fever and the proliferation of
Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Warning: don't ask your stock broker about these future
IPOs.They don't exist yet.
</P>
<P>
   GlobalTalk introduced a universal language translator, while
E-Grub created an all-in-one food pill that cured global hunger in
2020. SmartHomes allowed users to customize their living rooms with
moveable walls and voice recognition. HouseCall.com eliminated HMOs
with virtual medical consultation and I'm-gonna-take-your-money.com
brought (what else?) online gambling to the masses.
</P>
<P>
   But while one virtual company boasted it made so much money it
caused a global economic collapse, another, the fictitious
Alternavista.com, admitted it had succumbed to hard times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went bankrupt,'' Alternavista's chief executive-for-a-day
announced, to thunderous applause from his virtual shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Omar L. Gallaga writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
