<HEADER>
A7533 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-TROOPERS-NYT &LR;      07-12 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-TROOPERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN PICK TURNS DOWN TROOPER JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Gov. Christie Whitman's attempt to overhaul the
New Jersey State Police suffered a setback Monday when the leading
candidate for the superintendent's position told her he is no
longer interested in the job.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months New Jersey officials have reluctantly concluded
that the state police force has tolerated a culture of racial
discrimination, and they had hoped that Col. Andre Parker of the
Illinois State Police would be the man to transform the department.
Aides to the governor were particularly impressed with how he had
revamped the troubled police force in East St. Louis, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   But when word of Parker's negotiations was leaked to reporters
last month, the governor encountered unexpectedly intense
opposition from legislators, who would have had to approve the
nomination. After a furious lobbying campaign led by state police
supporters, many senators began publicly insisting that the
governor promote someone from within the ranks of the department.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Donald DiFrancesco, who will become acting
governor in January 2001 if Whitman wins her bid for the U.S.
Senate, also complicated the negotiations by refusing to guarantee
that he would allow Parker to serve at least a three-year term.
</P>
<P>
   Had he accepted the job, Parker, 43, would have become the first
black to command the 2,700-member force.
</P>
<P>
   Parker did not return calls for comment, but his letter cited
``personal and professional'' considerations, the governor said. A
leading supporter, the Rev. Reginald T. Jackson, said Parker
withdrew his name because it was clear that legislators were
unwilling to give him enough time or the necessary political
support to effectively reform the state police.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a position he really wanted; he looked forward to the
challenge,'' said Jackson, executive director of the Black
Ministers Council of New Jersey. ``But this process has carried on
so long, it wasn't fair for him to leave the Illinois police
wondering what he was going to do, so he thought it was time to
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said she was disappointed that Parker is no longer a
candidate, but insisted that the state is also talking with several
other qualified candidates, from both inside and outside the force,
and expects to name a nominee soon.
</P>
<P>
   Although she did not criticize legislators, the governor did
indicate that the search was being hampered by her inability to
offer job security beyond next year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got two, two and a half years left on my term,'' she
said. ``To ask somebody to make a career change based on that kind
of career longevity is problematic at best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 2231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
