<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CSUN FOOTBALL FATE IN QUESTIONABLE HANDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cal State Northridge is expected to conclude a
month-long investigation into its football program today.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, we should know if Ron Ponciano stays on for a
second season as head coach or if investigators found probable
cause to either ask him to resign or attempt to oust him.
</P>
<P>
   The belief here is that Ponciano will be asked to step down, as
CSUN offensive coordinator Rob Phenicie was last week.
</P>
<P>
   Phenicie resigned last Wednesday, the first casualty of the
school's internal probe that was prompted by an anonymous letter
detailing possible NCAA-rules infractions. Phenicie had turned down
two jobs during the offseason to stay at Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   To justify ousting Ponciano, investigators must discover he has
broken NCAA rules. To experienced observers, these transgressions
seem minor, the type that at most schools bring a reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   To get around that, CSUN says it operates a zero-tolerance
program. And after being embarrassed by an athletic director, a
basketball coach and an assistant athletic director in the last
eight months, that policy sounds reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   But don't believe it. It goes deeper than wanting to present a
pristine image to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, Ponciano is likely caught in the crossfire of a
campus civil war. At stake is the football program, which some at
the university would like to see disappear. The anonymous letter is
a convenient silver bullet, one they can use to kill the program.
</P>
<P>
   First they ask Ponciano to resign, then they say the program is
out of control, costs too much money and is more trouble than its
worth.
</P>
<P>
   Then they say they have no choice but to discontinue it,
probably after next year.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a clean, efficient murder.
</P>
<P>
   The motive? There are two.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, the school envisions a major fight over the
proposed new football stadium. Chances are that for most of the
next decade, CSUN will be stymied by lawsuits filed by residents
near campus who oppose the project. You don't need a football
stadium if you don't have a football team.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, CSUN hasn't met the requirements of an agreement
with Cal-NOW regarding gender equity. By eliminating football, the
school eliminates the problem.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Ponciano might just be in the wrong place at the
wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   How can this happen, and who is in charge? Good questions. There
is a power vacuum at Northridge, and perhaps that has created the
necessary space for the anti-football group within the
administration to assume control for the moment. Interim president
Luanne Kennedy is expected to make final judgment, but she'll lean
heavily on the investigation team headed by Peter Dinauer.
</P>
<P>
   Dinauer didn't return calls last week, and he's guarded when he
does talk. That's his job; he's an investigator. The question is,
to whom does he answer?
</P>
<P>
   Dick Dull, the new athletic director, is being briefed but is
being kept out of the loop to avoid sullying his image.
</P>
<P>
   If the agenda is to rid CSUN of football, those behind it forgot
one thing. Ponciano won't go softly into the night. The Fourth of
July was last week, but the real fireworks will go off when CSUN
tries to force Ponciano out.
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano has maintained his innocence throughout this whole
messy affair, and that conviction was only strengthened after
investigators presented him with the 20 or so allegations contained
in the anonymous letter. Ponciano said he shot down all but two of
the claims, and he submitted a written explanation on Monday that
he believes will clear those.
</P>
<P>
   He left the five-hour meeting feeling good about his job. But
Ponciano also knows that when somebody wants to get you, they can.
So he's prepared to fight, if that's what it comes to.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it could be Ponciano and Phenicie are actually
guilty. If so, then the university is justified by its course of
action.
</P>
<P>
   We'll reserve final judgement until CSUN discloses its findings.
Some who have seen the allegations say it reads like a sitcom
script. All that's missing is the laugh track.
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano and Phenicie aren't the only victims. An entire
football team anxiously awaits word on its coaches' fate and its
own future.
</P>
<P>
   The San Fernando Valley sits by and watches, wondering if CSUN
will finally do the right thing for the right reasons.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN's history makes us believe otherwise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
