<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-GLOBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMES CO. REPLACES PUBLISHER AT BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The New York Times Co. announced Monday that one of its
key executives had moved to Boston to succeed the publisher of The
Boston Globe, a member of the family that had run that paper for
126 years.
</P>
<P>
   The new publisher, Richard Gilman, headed The Times' circulation
department in New York with the title of senior vice president for
operations. He succeeds Benjamin Taylor, whose family sold The
Globe five and a half years ago to New York Times Co., parent of
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier assignments, Gilman, 48, was responsible for
circulation, production and the development of operations like the
new color printing plant in the New York City borough of Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, 52, will remain chairman of The Globe Newspaper Co.
board. The directors of The Globe Co. advise the management of The
Globe newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   At meetings with top managers and the newsroom staff on Monday,
Gilman and Taylor did not specifically address questions about why
the change was made, people at the meetings said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in his office on Monday, Taylor said that the
hardest question he was asked was, ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not an easy question to answer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The shift in top management at The Globe was effective
immediately. It came several months after Sunday circulation and
the high-margin help-wanted advertising revenue experienced
declines.
</P>
<P>
   It also came a year after newsroom turmoil surrounding the
departure of two columnists: one who acknowledged fabricating
material and another who was accused of plagiarism.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Monday, Arthur Sulzberger Jr., chairman of The
Times Co., said Taylor's ``commitment to the newspaper, service to
the community and dedication to quality journalism are
unquestioned.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same statement, Sulzberger said, ``I know Rich Gilman
will bring vision and leadership in the strongest traditions of The
Globe and will be an outstanding publisher during a time of rapid
change in the news industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilman joined The Times in 1983 and has held his current post
since 1993. He earned an MBA from Harvard Business School and spent
the first 10 years of his career as a reporter and editor at The
Arizona Daily Star in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting with Taylor in the publisher's office here, Gilman said
that all decisions about The Globe's future would be generated
locally. ``Where we go from here _ all that needs to be developed
in Boston,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the newsroom, the prevailing reactions were surprise and
sorrow. ``I wasn't totally surprised that they would make a
significant move, but I didn't expect Ben to be gone,'' said the
newspaper's editor, Matthew Storin.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen McNamara, a local columnist who has worked for The Globe
for about two decades, said: ``It's an especially sad day to me
when the man sitting in the front office is no longer connected to
the city in the way the Taylor family always has been.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of local family control over community newspapers is a
trend that has marked the industry for a generation or more, as
large newspaper chains have bought out newspaper-owning families.
When The Times Co. purchased The Globe in 1993, it agreed to make
no management changes for five years _ a period that ended last
year. Benjamin Taylor's cousin, William Taylor, was publisher at
the time of the sale, and Arthur Sulzberger Jr.'s father, Arthur
Ochs Sulzberger, was chairman and chief executive of The Times Co.
This year, William Taylor announced he was retiring from The Times
Co. board.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of local control is felt particularly hard in this
center of New England, a city whose prickly sense of self and
pugnacious attitude toward New York City are reflected in rivalries
in spheres from sports to scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Lydon, a former writer at both The Times and The
Globe, who is now host of a radio call-in program on WBUR-FM in
Boston, said: ``Boston is a franchise town now, as most American
cities are. We don't own our own village conversation anymore. All
the commercial media in Boston are owned or controlled by distant
emperors.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's reaction to the management change was muted, if
not negative. Times Co. stock closed at $38.75, down 93.75 cents,
or 2.36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Gruneich, a senior managing director at Bear, Stearns who
follows the newspaper industry, described Monday's developments as
``just an evolution in the relationship that the parent company has
with The Boston Globe.'' He added, ``I think that the integration
of The Boston Globe into The New York Times Company will be
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, advertising revenues at The Globe rose to $449 million,
an increase of just 1.8 percent over the previous year, while
valuable help-wanted advertising declined _ as it did in markets
like Los Angeles; San Jose, Calif., and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   In the same year, advertising revenues at The Times in New York
increased by 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter of 1999, advertising revenues at The Globe
were down 2.5 percent from the previous year, while The Times' were
up by 5.44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest concerns at The Globe in recent months has
been the loss of Sunday circulation, which stands at 730,000. It
declined 18,306, or 2.4 percent, between March 31, 1998, and March
31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman said he planned no cutbacks in the news budget. ``The
Globe is a great newspaper,'' he said. ``One of the best in
America. The challenge for us is to find a way to preserve that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
