<SLUG> BC-TEN-GRAF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIREMENT? GRAF LOOKS TO MAHWAH EVENT FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steffi Graf would not say it definitely, but the most successful
women's tennis player of the 1990s strongly indicated Monday that
she would retire from the tour by year's end. But Graf said she
would continue to play a few exhibition tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   One of those exhibition tournaments is the A&AMP;P Tennis Classic in
Mahwah, N.J. She won the event for the first time when she was 14
and for the sixth time last year. This week, at age 30, she will
play there again when she faces Jennifer Capriati on Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Graf arrived Monday from her native Germany. Hours later, she
took the court for the first time since losing the Wimbledon final
10 days ago to Lindsay Davenport. Before the practice, however,
Graf more or less defined her tennis future.
</P>
<P>
   She is scheduled to play several tournaments this year,
including the U.S. Open. Graf previously said that she would no
longer play Wimbledon and the French Open, two of the four Grand
Slam tournaments, and she reiterated that Monday saying it was
unlikely she would change her mind.
</P>
<P>
   But while acknowledging that she would probably retire from the
tour, she also said: ``I'm not going to stop playing tennis for
myself. Tennis will always be a big part of my life. I enjoy it. I
still love it very, very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf has played enough tennis to deserve a long rest. Since she
turned professional at age 13, she has won 107 singles titles on
tour, including 22 Grand Slam events, the second-highest total
ever, and has earned almost $22 million in prize money.
</P>
<P>
   This year, she won the French Open, a notable achievement
because for three years she had been fighting off injuries to her
hamstring, ankle, shoulder, wrist and knee. She is ranked third in
the world behind Davenport and Martina Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good,'' Graf said. ``I have no injuries, but I haven't
been playing. Mentally, I'm not so tired yet. But it's very
demanding traveling to tournaments. And with every day the
questions: `When are you going to retire? When are you going to
retire?' I haven't been able to go out and play matches and enjoy
them.''
</P>
<P>
   If the physical part is still willing, the mental part may not
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always given as much as I have to tennis,'' Graf said.
``If you like it enough, that's the key thing. If it gets to a
point where you realize your mind isn't always 100 percent on the
court, that's different.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to leave the sport when you're on top. That's
never really easy because when you're doing well it's difficult to
stop. The last three years all the injuries I've been having came
very close to making this decision. I feel fortunate I've been able
to do this on my own terms.''
</P>
<P>
   For Graf, retirement will not mean idleness. She owns a sports
management company that represents two junior girls from Germany.
The company has done organizational work for the Federation Cup
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Her tournament schedule this summer and fall includes events in
San Diego and Toronto, the U.S. Open and stops in Europe. She said
she had not decided whether to play in the season-ending tour
championship Nov. 15-21 in Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, she said, will be different. But she added, ``I'm not
going to be disappearing at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
