<SLUG> BC-NY-NASSAU-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND AGENCY DOWNGRADES NASSAU COUNTY BONDS RATING 
</HEADLINE>
  (md) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINEOLA, N.Y. _ A second major bond-rating agency on Monday
downgraded Nassau County's credit to near-junk status, prompting
the county's budget director to accuse Democrats in Albany of
blocking a bailout of Nassau ``for partisan political reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a booming economy and one of the nation's wealthiest
populations, Nassau is confronted with a budget deficit of more
than $200 million after years of growth in spending that was not
matched by tax increases. Its bonds were steeply downgraded by
Standard &AMP; Poor's on June 29. Moody's Investors Service on Monday
lowered Nassau's rating to an equivalent level, Baa2, just two
notches above junk, and threatened another downgrade if the county
does not obtain new sources of revenue soon.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the downgrade, Moody's faulted Nassau for delays
in obtaining state legislative approval for a new 1 percent tax on
property sales. ``It just doesn't seem like a great deal of
progress is being made, or a significant amount of positive
discussions are taking place between the county and the state,''
said Helen Cregger, of Moody's.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Democrats led by Thomas P. DiNapoli, of Great Neck, in
Nassau County, last week demanded that the county give the state
comptroller extensive oversight powers in exchange for such a
bailout. The comptroller, H. Carl McCall, is a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released on Monday evening, Michael Fabiano, the
Nassau County budget director, blamed DiNapoli and his colleagues
for the latest downgrade. ``The county has formulated a fiscal plan
which addresses the issues raised by Moody's,'' Fabiano said.
``Unfortunately, key elements of the plan, which require state
legislative approval, have been blocked by Assembly Democrats for
partisan political reasons. The action announced Monday by Moody's
is not unexpected in view of the State Assembly's failure to act on
the county's fiscal plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Told of Fabiano's statement, DiNapoli said, ``Now's not the time
for a blame game.'' But he quickly added that it was County
Executive Thomas S. Gulotta, a Republican, who was guilty of
inaction, for ignoring the Democrats' call for oversight by the
Comptroller and other reforms. ``We haven't heard back, except that
they feel we're asking for too much,'' he said. ``We give them a
20-page document, and they give a one-sentence response. They're
just not dealing in reality.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to lowering the rating on Nassau's $2.7 billion in
long-term bonds, Moody's lowered Nassau's short-term credit rating
from the highest to the second of three rating levels. Ms. Cregger
said the lower rating would reduce the number of investors bidding
for Nassau's short-term notes and increase the county's costs. The
county expects to borrow a record $430 million in this way to pay
its bills this year.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's also said the county's plan to borrow against
anticipated future income from its share of a nationwide tobacco
settlement by the end of the year seemed ``increasingly remote.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
