<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADCOUNCIL-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: UNSOLD SPACE ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LISA NAPOLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Advertising Council, the nonprofit organization that
produces and distributes public-service announcements, has risen in
the last four months from 23rd to 9th place in rankings of the most
visible advertisers on the Internet, according to Nielsen/Net
Ratings, an Internet measurement service.
</P>
<P>
   That is not because the council has increased its advertising
budget. It has no such budget. As it does in other media, on the
Internet the council relies on the benevolence of Web sites to run
its advertisements in unsold space.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, banner advertisements that the council created on
behalf of nonprofit groups on recycling, drunken driving, crime
prevention and nearly 20 other public-service causes appeared 133
million times on the Web last month. Such messages reached 16.2
percent of all people who surf from home, according to Nielsen/Net
Ratings.
</P>
<P>
   This puts the organization in the ranks of such other highly
visible online advertisers as Microsoft Corp. and Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   The council's increased visibility represents a gesture of good
will on the part of Web publishers. But what does it say about the
medium that so much advertising space is being given away?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another indication that there's a ton of unsold inventory
on the Web, as if we needed any more,'' said Jim Nail, an analyst
who covers Internet advertising for Forrester Research in
Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, 40 percent to 70 percent of the ad space on even the
most highly trafficked Web sites goes unsold, said Rich LeFurgy,
chairman of the Internet Advertising Bureau, an industry trade
organization. For what LeFurgy calls second- or third-tier sites,
the proportion of unsold space is even higher.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation for the unsold space is that the Web offers
practically infinite publishing opportunities. Thus it has
exponentially more advertising capacity than do television, radio
and print media, which have limited space and air time.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctant to have space allotted for advertising appear empty _
the digital equivalent of dead air time in broadcast media _ Web
sites often plug in ads promoting their own services to take up the
space. But a site can use just so many of those ads without looking
tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``So why not plug in some public service, be a good guy?'' Nail
suggested as the reason for the widespread use of the public
service banners. ``When people see that, they say, `Hey, this site
is good.'''
</P>
<P>
   Besides perceiving that the Web site at hand has a social
conscience, the public is also exposed to messages intended to
improve society and public safety and to promote the nonprofit
groups that advocate these causes.
</P>
<P>
   The spirit of mobilizing communities is what propelled the
advertising industry to create the War Advertising Council 57 years
ago. Then, the group's focus was to rally the nation in support of
World War II. One of its first initiatives was a campaign featuring
Rosie the Riveter, the character that motivated women to enter the
work force during the war. Now, the organization is known as both
the Advertising Council and the Ad Council.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the council added an online component to its public
service campaigns. The banners are created by advertising agencies
that volunteer staff time, and are available on the council's Web
site (http://www.adcouncil.org) to anyone who wishes to display
them.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Conlon, president of the Ad Council, likens the increasing
use of council banners online to the early days of television, when
public-service commercials helped fill air time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more stations that went on the air, and the more hours
they programmed, the more space there was to fill,'' she said.
``We're being brought along on the Internet by the phenomenal
growth of the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the council has grown significantly: In 1998,
the group received $1.2 billion in donated space from all media.
Donated space on the Internet soared from $5 million in 1997, based
on cost estimates given the council by the contributing sites, to
$28 million in 1998. That makes the medium an even bigger supporter
of public-service campaigns than newspapers, which contributed
$21.2 million in space in 1998. Even so, the sacrifice is a bit
different: Web publishers have a lot of unsold space to give away,
while traditional media companies often donate space they could
have used for paid advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the National Crime Prevention Council was the
top-ranked media campaign for the Ad Council, receiving $128.1
million in donated media space. Jacqueline Aker, media director for
the National Crime Prevention Council, said the Internet played an
important role in helping her organization achieve its mission of
educating the public about crime prevention, with 5,000 people a
day visiting its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   An anti-crime campaign aimed at teen-agers has received what Ms.
Aker described as exceptional placement online because many
teen-age-themed Web sites are wary of accepting excessive paid
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some sites like the Cartoon Network use our banners all the
time,'' she said. ``The creative makes a big difference, too. Our
banners are really cool.'' They were fashioned by Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi, along with its interactive agency Darwin Digital, both of
which are New York units of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC.
</P>
<P>
   For all the good that such public-service advertisements do,
some people still suggest that the incredible reach the Ad Council
has achieved is a sign of a sluggish climate for advertisers on the
Web. Wenda Millard, a council board member who is executive vice
president of the online advertising network Doubleclick Inc.,
called that view cynical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all inventory on the Internet is going to be valued by
advertisers,'' she said. ``Some of the top sites may be top sites
based on traffic, but it might not all be desirable space. I think
it's very natural that you'll have tons of open space. The barriers
to entry for the Web are so phenomenally low that literally your
grandmother can create a Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Grandma wants to put a public-service ad for the
council-created character Smokey Bear on it, all the better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
