<SLUG> BC-DAILY-NEWS-DRIVERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE AFFIRMS RAISE FOR DAILY NEWS DRIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge Monday upheld a labor arbitrator's
decision to award retroactive wages to members of the drivers'
union at The New York Daily News, a move that could eventually cost
the newspaper tens of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The arbitrator's ruling, issued on March 8, determined that
members of the Newspaper and Mail Deliverers Union should receive a
16.9 percent wage increase retroactive to Jan. 1, 1997, to bring
their pay in line with the wages of drivers at The New York Times.
Because the six other craft unions at The Daily News may be
entitled to any raises won by the drivers' union, the paper
suddenly faces unexpected costs of $18.5 million in 1999 alone,
executives said, a figure that could escalate to millions more in
future years. The Daily News' management appealed, but U.S.
District Judge Thomas Griesa in Manhattan upheld it Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The union represents the 418 drivers who transport more than
700,000 copies of the paper to the five boroughs of the city and
into the suburbs every day.
</P>
<P>
   Mortimer B. Zuckerman, the co-publisher and owner of The Daily
News, did not return phone calls Monday. But Martin D. Krall, the
executive vice president and chief legal officer of The News, said
the newspaper would appeal Griesa's reaffirmation of the
arbitrator's award.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the award issued today confirmed the previous
award,'' he said. ``It gives us a fair amount of time to pay the
retroactive portion. But we are now going to move to the next
phase, and we are going to pursue the case vigorously in federal
court.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute between the drivers' union and Daily News management
arose when drivers contested a 1993 agreement with Zuckerman, who
had just purchased the bankrupt paper. He asked at that time that
The News not be asked to match craft wages at The New York Times.
During wage negotiations in 1997, The News again asked the unions
not to ask for parity with The Times.
</P>
<P>
   Zuckerman now faces a difficult road. An appeal would be heard
by a three-judge panel of the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. It
is unusual for an arbitration case to be overturned by that court,
a lawyer involved in the case said.
</P>
<P>
   Top News officials met with drivers' union leaders last week and
made an offer to settle the dispute, but the union rejected the
offer, a person close to the discussions said Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
