A7547 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-HOMERS-CO     07-12 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-HOMERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Griffey HR king; Mac puts on show
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Someway this city must raze venerable Fenway Park, and
a new method of demolition was recommended Monday night. Let Ken
Griffey Jr. and Mark McGwire homer the thing into a heap.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey homered three times in three swings in the final round,
enough to defeat surprise finalist Jeromy Burnitz and win his third
Home Run Derby. That came in conclusion to a wicked long-ball
display in the earlier rounds that made Fenway look like a playpen.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, launching a record 13 homers in the first round, swung
himself into exhaustion and failed to make the finals. He and
Houston's Jeff Bagwell (1) were eliminated in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sit-and-wait tired. It happens,'' said McGwire, whose
lone contest win came in 1992. ``I probably tried too hard. I was
more relaxed in the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's first-round total surpassed the previous record of 12
hit by Cal Ripken Jr. in 1991. McGwire cleared the light tower with
a 470-foot shot and knocked out six more in eight pitches before
Boston pitcher Pedro Martinez, having had enough, ran to the plate
and made off with his bat.
</P>
<P>
   After retrieving the wood, McGwire connected with four straight
swings that had the entire park standing. His last blast was his
longest, a 482-foot shot to left-center. Those 13 alone outmatched
the entire five-man AL team's 10.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's Sammy Sosa, the major-league leader with 32 home runs,
bowed out in the first round with just one homer. Oakland's John
Jaha was easily the night's least inspired performer, whiffing
twice on consecutive swings in the first round before being
eliminated with just one homer.
</P>
<P>
   The NL out-homered the AL 27-10 in the first round, Griffey the
only AL player to advance to the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
