<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7549 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALLST-DERBY-BOS &LR;      07-12 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLST-DERBY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE SETS DERBY RECORD, BUT GRIFFEY JR. IS THE CHAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Mark McGwire, forever to be remembered for the record
70 home runs he hit in the refular season in 1998, took the art of
the long ball to another level Monday night by pounding out a
record 13 home runs _ in one of his two plate appearances _ in the
All-Star home run-hitting contest at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Big Mac thrilled the packed house in the Back Bay with his 13
bombs, breaking the record of 12 set by Cal Ripken Jr. in '91. The
13 shots, strung together, traveled 5,692 feet _ more than a mile _
each shot averaging 438 feet.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire banged out only three homers in the second round and
failed to advance to the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. and the Milwaukee Brewers' Jeromy
Burnitz met head-to-head in the final and Griffey, last year's
winner, successfully defended his title. Burnitz hit two homers in
his appearance, and then Griffey sent three deep into the night,
ending his stellar performance by flipping his black bat into the
air.
</P>
<P>
   The final brought two lefthanded hitters together, ironic for a
park known to favor righthanded hitters.
</P>
<P>
   With the baker's dozen, McGwire advanced to Round 2 of the
long-ball contest, along with Jeff Bagwell, Burnitz, and Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to McGwire returning for his second tour de force, Griffey
put on a stunning performance of his own. After a slow start, he
finished with 10 homers, sending repeated shots over the bullpens
and into the right-field bleachers. The most impressive of the
shots was No. 5, which Griffey sent soaring to the back of Conig's
Corner in center field.
</P>
<P>
   Fenway was abuzz when Big Mac stepped up again, but he couldn't
get back the form he showed in Round 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably tried a little too hard,'' said McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   The rock band Smashmouth, set up on a stage erected in the Red
Sox bullpen, played a couple of songs in an attempt to get the
crowd jumping before the long-ball contest. Rock music and Fenway
Park are strange bedfellows. For decades, the only tunes heard in
the Fens came from John Kiley's keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado outfielder Larry Walker led off for the National League
and he pounded a pair out of the park. He launched a 385-footer
into the right-field grandstand with his second pitch and later
drilled a 405-footer over the visiting bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN went immediately to its first of many protracted breaks
after Walker's appearance, allowing on-field announcer Sean
McDonough some extra time to get the crowd charged up over the next
hitter, Sox shortstop Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a feeling you might like the guy who's coming up
next,'' said McDonough, as Garciaparra slowly strode to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the Boston lineup for nearly two weeks with an injured
groin, Garciaparra looked comfortable and fluid at the plate. With
his first cut, he sent a liner rocketing into the screen. Two
swings later, he sent a 414-footer over the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look out, Mass. Pike!'' shouted McDonough, as Garciaparra's
second bomb headed into the Back Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra finished with two homers in the opening round, going
0 for 8 after sending his shot to Lansdowne Street.
</P>
<P>
   The first surprise of the night was the outstanding performance
by Burnitz. The 30-year-old lefthanded hitter sent no fewer than
six balls over the fence, the majority into the right-field
grandstand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little nervous,'' Burnitz said after his impressive
outing. The jitters didn't show.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-born Jeff Bagwell, the power-hitter the Sox let get away,
also put on an impressive show, after the A's John Jaha managed to
poke only one out of the park. Bagwell jumped out early with five
homers, the last two soared over the screen. ``Look out, Medford,''
McDonough said after the first of two. But Bagwell got stuck at
five. Sox fans in the sellout crowd had to be wondering the
obvious: How many would Bagwell have hit in a Sox uniform if Lou
Gorman hadn't dealt him for Larry Andersen?
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, hitting seventh on the night, stole the show with his
seemingly endless stream of long bombs over the Wall. They were
prodigious shots, the third hitting off the top of the light tower
in straight-away left. The fourth zoomed over the Coke bottles
strapped halfway up the same tower. On and on he went. San Diego
coach Tim Flannery, the pitcher, tossed in the creampuffs and
McGwire effortlessly ripped them out.
</P>
<P>
   After McGwire's ninth drive cleared the screen _ it was taking
on the proportions of ``The Natural'' at this point _ Sox pitcher
Pedro Martinez shuffled to the batter's box and politely wrested
the bat away from Big Mac. It was Martinez's way of saying,
``Enough!''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't enough. McGwire got the bat back in his hands and
promptly pounded out Nos. 10, 11, 12, and 13. It was big man's tee
ball. No. 13 was the longest of all, a high drive that went just to
the left of the light tower in left-center. It traveled 488 feet.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire hit only four homers in last year's competition and said
he felt he had to make up for that performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim got me in a groove,'' said McGwire, referring to
Flannery's batting practice tosses. ``I broke my bat about halfway
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa, leading the NL with 32 homers, managed to bang out
only one homer. Griffey, who won last year's event, muscled only
three out of the park, two into the bleachers, but it was enough
for him to make it into the second round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
