<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-FISCAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET DELAY MAY CAUSE TAX INCREASES, OFFICIAL SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (md) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The state comptroller, H. Carl McCall, Monday
warned that the protracted state budget stalemate could soon play
havoc with annual property tax bills and would likely result in
unnecessary tax increases in suburbs and small towns.
</P>
<P>
   McCall, a Democrat, said at a news conference that the decision
of the Republican-controlled Senate not to return to Albany until
Tuesday to pass the latest in a series of emergency spending bills
would mean that many state workers will be paid a day later than
usual.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials contended that the Senate had chosen not to
return Monday to avoid a scheduling conflict with a key senator's
fund-raising event. Republican officials denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
   The squabbling came as the Democratic Assembly speaker, Sheldon
Silver, nursing a broken collarbone suffered in a softball game
Sunday, resumed budget negotiations with Gov. George Pataki, a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate majority leader, Joseph Bruno, agreed with McCall's
warning on local school districts, but the governor's office
disputed it.
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday, the budget will be 104 days late, tying the
second-latest ever, in 1996. In 1997, the state budget was 126 days
overdue, a modern record for futility in any state.
</P>
<P>
   Except for New York and a handful of other cities, the state's
nearly 700 school districts assess property taxes that account, on
average, for about 60 percent of their budgets, with the rest
coming from the state. (In the cities, the school systems have no
taxing power, but rely on money from city governments.) By law,
school districts must send out annual tax bills in August.
</P>
<P>
   Districts must obtain voter approval in spring elections for
their budgets, but they do not need voter approval to set tax
rates. As they draft their budgets, districts estimate property tax
rates. If the state provides more money than expected, the tax
bills are lower than those estimates; if the state provides less,
the tax bills are higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those school districts around the state don't have very
definitive information in the next couple of weeks about what they
will receive in state aid for education,'' they will be forced to
guess and to base their tax bills on those guesses, McCall, the
state's chief financial officer, said. The Assembly convened Monday
to pass another batch of two-week emergency spending bills to keep
the government running. This year, as in years past when the budget
ran late, the bills are usually passed on Monday to enable state
workers to receive their twice-monthly paychecks on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate decided, instead, to return on Tuesday this week,
and McCall said that it would be impossible for his office to issue
checks to all state employees by the following day.
</P>
<P>
   John McArdle, a spokesman for the Senate Republicans, said:
``They shouldn't be paid late. He should have plenty of time to
process the checks.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Democratic legislators and some Republican Senate aides,
speaking on the condition of anonymity, said the Senate was
returning a day late because of a fund-raising event for Sen. Dean
Skelos, R- Nassau, who is the deputy majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Bogardus, a spokesman for Skelos, and McArdle denied that
the event had anything to do with the Senate's Tuesday return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
