<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI REMAINS NONCOMMITTAL ON A CANDIDATE FOR THE SENATE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At a time when national Republicans are increasingly
nervous about the party's failure to unite behind an opponent to
run against Hillary Rodham Clinton in the U.S. Senate race from New
York next year, Gov. George E. Pataki is still refusing to go along
with his party's leaders and support Mayor Rudolph Giuliani over
other potential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has said time and again that he doesn't believe
that anyone should be anointed,'' said Zenia Mucha, the governor's
director of communications and his most powerful aide.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mucha made her comments a day after Pataki criticized Mrs.
Clinton's candidacy as ``cockamamie'' in an interview on CNN,
saying that the first lady was running only to get ``national
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same interview, the governor praised Giuliani, with whom
he often fights, as ``an outstanding mayor who would be an
outstanding senator.'' But the governor also said in the interview
that two other possible Republican candidates, Reps. Rick Lazio and
Peter King, both of Long Island, are ``tremendous leaders in
Congress'' and would be ``great candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday in Philadelphia, Republicans at the party's summer
convention had what several officials described as passionate
discussions in closed meetings about whether they should try to
force Lazio out of the race. In the end, they decided to leave the
New York race and possible primary to New Yorkers _ a decision that
clearly pleased Ms. Mucha.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has made it perfectly clear that this is an
election that is 18 months away and that we have a number of
extraordinarily qualified candidates who need to go out there and
make a case to the people as to why they can beat Hillary
Clinton,'' Ms. Mucha said.
</P>
<P>
   She added that ``no one in Washington has ever called the
governor and told him how he should or should not deal with the
current situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But the actions of the governor, who has his own ambitions for
national office, possibly as a vice-presidential candidate, have
puzzled and angered national Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lazio has been actively courting Pataki, who has
never forgiven Giuliani for supporting the incumbent Democrat,
Mario Cuomo, over Pataki in the race for governor in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said Monday that he planned to announce his candidacy for
Senate before Labor Day, and that the only reaction he had to the
Republican consternation over his candidacy in Philadelphia was
``all's well that ends well.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's aides said Monday that he has raised more than $3
million for the race. Giuliani has reported raising $744,000, but
that does not include money not yet reported from a large
fund-raising dinner in May and other recent events.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, meanwhile, are concerned about the enormous
media attention that Mrs. Clinton received on a three-day visit to
New York last week, her first since announcing the formation of a
Senate exploratory committee. ``The television coverage of her has
been like Mother Teresa's visit to New York,'' complained one
leading Republican strategist.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton was in New York City Monday for what her press
secretary, Howard Wolfson, said were private meetings. She was to
meet in the evening with a small group of New Yorkers at a home in
southern Westchester County as part of her summer ``listening
tour,'' which her aides closed to the media. Tuesday, Mrs. Clinton
is to go to Westchester Community College and then Long Island. She
is to be in Long Island again on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Mrs. Clinton is to be in New York City for what
Wolfson called an organizational meeting with a core group of
fund-raisers, among them Alan and Susan Patricof, Patty Kenner,
Roger Altman and Erskine Bowles, the former White House chief of
staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-99 2257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
