<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FENWAY PARK WILL BE ONE OF THE TV STARS DURING ALL-STAR GAME
</HEADLINE>
  (md) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a television stage, Fenway Park, now age 87, is as
recognizable as Ralph Kramden's barren kitchen, the bustling police
station in ``Hill Street Blues'' or the coffee bar in ``Friends.''
Tune in, and you know in an instant exactly where you are.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Monster in left field is Fenway's leading man, but
more of a weathered character actor like Spencer Tracy. The quirky
outfield dimensions, the fans' proximity to the players, the Citgo
sign and the hand-operated scoreboard make up the supporting cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us see Fenway and have certain memories,'' said Mike
Weisman, the producer of Tuesday night's All-Star Game for Fox
Sports. ``We don't have Bank One Ballpark memories. Bank One is a
great stadium, but the All-Star Game at the end of the millennium
wouldn't have the same feel in a modern ball park.''
</P>
<P>
   Fenway is a perennial star, the edifice as matinee idol, much
like Ted Williams or Carl Yastrzemski, Tony Conigliaro or Pedro
Martinez. ``Well, maybe not as much as Ted,'' said the Fox analyst
Tim McCarver.
</P>
<P>
   Purists get weepy about old joints like Fenway, which is the
reason for the opposition to replacing the ancient Boston baseball
gem. There is a charm to watching games at a place that looks as it
did when television first focused on it more than 50 years ago. Had
television been around in 1933, viewers would not have seen the
Green Monster, which was added by the owner Tom Yawkey in 1934.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are amazed, when they come in, to see how high the wall
is and how close it seems,'' said Sean McDonough, a Red Sox
announcer. ``You feel you can reach out and touch it.''
</P>
<P>
   With a capacity of 33,871, Fenway is baseball's smallest ball
park, but it is larger than the late Ebbets Field by more than
2,000 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, makes it nearly perfect for television's
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intimacy works so well for television,'' Weisman said.
``The sound seems to crackle there. The dark green of Fenway looks
so good at night. The field sparkles. It's everything you want in a
ball park.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not everything. Weisman said that Wrigley Field in Chicago
wins the slight nod as the better place for television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrigley has a slight edge because of the ivy and the
bleachers,'' he said. ``Little things like better sight lines and
camera angles.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox will give Fenway, which hasn't been the site of an All-Star
Game since 1961, a star turn. Cameras will be atop the Green
Monster (imagine watching Carlton Fisk's home run in the 1975 World
Series from that angle); footage of Fenway oddities will be on tap
(if a ball rattles into one of its nooks or crannies, a flashback
will be summoned); 3-D graphics of old Fenway and the planned new
one are available, and an estimated 40 baseball legends will walk
in from center field in a ``Field of Dreams'' motif, followed in a
golf cart by Williams, who will toss the first pitch to Fisk from
in front of home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't it be great if Ted tips his cap to the fans?'' said
Weisman, who watched Fisk's home run from an NBC production truck.
</P>
<P>
   That would certainly be memorable given Williams' aversion to
cap tipping. But would such an event eclipse in importance
McCarver's indelible memory of his first trip to Fenway as the St.
Louis Cardinals' catcher for the 1967 World Series?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting blown out in Game 6, and Red Schoendienst
asked Alex Johnson to pinch-hit,'' he said. ``Alex was in the
clubhouse and said he couldn't pinch-hit because he was eating a
bologna sandwich. So Phil Gagliano pinch-hit. Imagine telling that
to your grandchildren.''  &QL; 
When Good Toys Go Bad  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OK, it was defensible during Fox's broadcast of the Yankees-Mets
game Saturday to employ a split screen (or double box) to show
Sammy Sosa's at-bat during the Cubs-White Sox game. After all, who
was more apt to hit a home run, Sosa or the Yankees' Ricky Ledee?
So Ledee homered, but Fox did not shift back to New York's full
screen or restore the audio from Shea Stadium. Thus, Fox remained
in the double box when Jorge Posada followed Ledee with another
home run. A Fox spokesman said there were no technical problems.  &QL; 
World Cup Wrap-Up  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The enormous, unexpected 13.3 overnight rating for the Women's
World Cup final does not obscure the serious deficiencies of ABC's
broadcast. In addition to xenophobically treating the Chinese team
like an afterthought (we learned more about the star Sun Wen from
an Adidas commercial), ABC did not help newcomers understand the
rules of soccer, explain the dimensions of the field or even what
``caps'' are.
</P>
<P>
   The pre-game show was inadequate and the halftime show lacked
analysis (but had those key highlights from the Greater Milwaukee
Open). More important, ABC should have quickly replayed the notable
achievement of the United States goalkeeper Briana Scurry for her
penalty-kick save, which is rarer than any successful penalty kick,
even one as crucial as Brandi Chastain's.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the United States team make the rounds of the morning
talk shows Monday, one was struck by the gushfest on ABC's ``Good
Morning America'' by Robin Roberts (``Whoo Whoo!'' ``You da
women!'') and Charlie Gibson, and the controlled enthusiasm of
Katie Couric during her smart interview with the players on NBC's
``Today'' show. Mark McEwen's taped interview with the team on
``CBS This Morning'' showed intelligence without fawning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
