<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM RIVA, 79, SCENIC DESIGNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Riva, a scenic designer who worked in theater and
television, died on July 3 in Bern, Switzerland. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   Riva's credits included the sets and lighting for a 1950
production of Gian Carlo Menotti's operas ``The Telephone'' and
``The Medium,'' presented in the round at the Arena Theater in the
Hotel Edison in New York. He also did the settings for an opera
production of Leonard Bernstein's ``Trouble in Tahiti,'' broadcast
on NBC in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Maria, the daughter of Marlene
Dietrich; four sons, J. Michael, John Paul and J. David, all of
California, and Peter of New York, and seven grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
