<SLUG> BC-AIRPORTS-SHEAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE ENTERS AIRPORT RADAR DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (md) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House has moved in to try to settle a
dispute between two federal agencies over plans to build a radar
system that would detect deadly wind shear at Kennedy and La
Guardia airports.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration and the U. S. Department of
the Interior have been negotiating fruitlessly for months over the
aviation agency's plan to build the radar system at Floyd Bennett
Field in Brooklyn, which is part of the Gateway National Recreation
Area. The aviation agency contends that it can build the radar
installation _ it resembles a 37-foot ball atop an 82-foot tower _
without the approval of the Interior Department. The Interior
Department, which includes the National Park Service, which in turn
is responsible for Gateway, maintains that it must give its assent,
and will not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a definite recognition here that this can't be
allowed to linger,'' a White House official said. ``People are
working to nail it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of both agencies said the Council for
Environmental Quality, part of the Executive Office of the
President, was reviewing the dispute. A White House official said a
decision was expected soon.
</P>
<P>
   The aviation agency has been trying since the early 90s to build
the radar system in New York, and Kennedy International and La
Guardia Airports are the last major airports in the country not
served by a wind-shear detection radar. The system was invented in
part in response to a crash at Kennedy in 1975 that killed 113
people.
</P>
<P>
   The Floyd Bennett site is the best available for the system,
aviation agency officials say. The agency, which owns a 1.8-acre
parcel there, has promised the Interior Department to use the radar
for only 20 years and then tear it down, but the Interior
Department has remained adamant that it does not want a radar tower
in a national park.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the National Transportation Safety Board, which
has only advisory powers, has called for approval of the Floyd
Bennett site, pointing out that 500 people have died in the last 25
years in accidents caused by wind shear, a sudden shift from a
headwind to a tailwind that can cause a loss of airspeed and knock
a plane out of the sky.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is further complicated by a lawsuit brought against
the aviation agency by several community groups in Brooklyn and
Queens, arguing that the law that established the Gateway National
Recreation Area bars development there without the permission of
the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   The aviation agency has already begun preliminary work at the
site and could build the radar while the suit is pending, unless
the plaintiffs win an injunction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
