<HEADLINE>
EARL FOELL, 69, MONITOR EDITOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y., Calif., N.C.)  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earl Foell, a longtime senior editor of The Christian Science
Monitor with a romantic attachment to precision and clarity, died
on Saturday at the MIT Medical Department Inpatient Unit in
Cambridge, Mass. He was 69 and lived in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Foell (pronounced fell) died after what his wife, Cordelia,
would describe only as a brief illness.
</P>
<P>
   In a career spanning half a century at The Monitor, Foell rose
from copy boy to reporter, foreign correspondent, U.N. bureau chief
and, from 1970 to 1983, successively, managing editor, editor and
editor in chief.
</P>
<P>
   From 1994 to 1999, he was chief editorial writer and editor of
the editorial page. Last month, he was named contributing editor.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Science Monitor, an international daily newspaper
published Monday through Friday, is owned by the Church of Christ,
Scientist, in Boston. Foell was a member of the church, as are
about half of the staff members.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1908 by Mary Baker Eddy, The Monitor was to serve as
an antidote to the practices of yellow journalism rampant at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Each day of the week The Monitor publishes a clearly designated
article consistent with the religious beliefs of Mary Baker Eddy,
but apart from that the religious society exercises no control.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, the publishers ventured into television
programming, but the effort failed, and in 1992 the society
retrenched its media operations. ``We're beyond that now,'' said
Faye Bowers, a spokesperson for The Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Its circulation today is about 80,000, down from more than
200,000 in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   As an editor, Foell was obsessed with comprehensibility. Writing
an appreciation in The Monitor on Monday, a colleague, Roderick
Nordell, said: ``As in E.B. White's advice to writers who see
readers floundering in a swamp, he was always throwing ropes of
clarity. He suffered puns gladly, but no cliche except to turn it
on its head. ''
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Foell became editor of a new publication, World Monitor
Magazine, a monthly magazine published by Christian Science
Publishing Society. He had high hopes for the magazine which, he
said in an opening editorial, would have a global perspective and
``throw a life preserver'' to readers wallowing in `'a vast glut of
information.'' The publication was discontinued in May 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Foell served several terms as a Pulitzer prize juror, most
recently this year. ``I was enormously impressed by the breadth of
his knowledge,'' said Seymour Topping, administrator of the prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Foell, who was born in Houston on Sept. 21, 1929, graduated from
Principia College in Elsah, Ill., in 1949 with a degree in
mathematics, and immediately joined The Monitor staff as a copy
boy.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, he joined the Army but was not sent overseas
because his degree in mathematics was considered an essential
wartime skill on the homefront. In 1953, he was discharged and
returned to The Monitor as a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of years with The Los Angeles Times, he returned
to The Monitor as a senior editor.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Cordelia, Foell is survived by three
sons, David of Manhattan; Jonathan Kane of Alamo, Calif., and
Hayden Treanor of Oakland, Calif; a sister, Ruth Hill of Charlotte,
N.C., and three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
