<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF COURSE, THESE FIVE MISS BRITISH OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hoot Mon! Carnoustie Golf Links here. There has been a wee
misunderstanding I must clear up before I host the British Open
this week. It's the first time since 1975 the ``greatest major of
the four'' _ those are Yank Mark O'Meara's words, not mine _ has
called on me and I'm over the moon.
</P>
<P>
   I want to put on a grand show. It's a terribly personal thing.
I'm on a comeback of sorts after letting myself go to sod three
years ago. I was shaggy and unkempt, but I'm feeling dapper now. My
grooming never has been better.
</P>
<P>
   I want the world to see the resplendent new me. I realize it's
going to be tough, topping Tom Watson's 25-foot birdie on the 72nd
hole in 1975, which delivered him into an 18-hole playoff with
Aussie Jack Newton.
</P>
<P>
   Watson beat Newton by one stroke the following day to win the
first of his five British Opens. I want this year's event to be one
for the ages, as well, and that's why I had to make some difficult
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   A golf tournament can only be as grand as its guest list and,
frankly, some of the U.S. entries reminded me of doddering members
of the Royal and Ancient Golf Club of St. Andrews. They were
dynamic once, but now they're just cantankerous.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, I'm talking about Tom Kite, Ben Crenshaw, John
Daly, Steve Jones and Fred Couples.
</P>
<P>
   You might have heard last week that they all pulled out of the
tournament. Well, I'm here to tell you it didn't exactly happen
like that.
</P>
<P>
   Let them say their bad back couldn't take the trans-Atlantic
plane flight. Let them gripe that it costs too much to come and see
me.
</P>
<P>
   Let them go off on the traffic tie-ups trying to get into my
village or the paucity of decent accommodations near me. Let them
blame their sore shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   They're trying to save face, every last one of them. The truth
is, I rescinded their invitations. Aye, they gave me no choice.
</P>
<P>
   Look at Kite. The guy will be eligible for the British Senior
Open next year and his game is starting to betray his age. He
already has carded three rounds in the 80s in 15 events this year.
If Bay Hill, Torrey Pines Golf Club and Pinehurst No. 2 can
discombobulate him like that, Kite would have been putty in my
fairways (provided he could have found them).
</P>
<P>
   Kites are supposed to be made for the wind, but it would have
been Tom's scores, not his spirits, that soared in the switching
gales that pass for sea breezes in this quaint little city a few
miles north of Dundee.
</P>
<P>
   Trust me, I did him a favor by pulling his entry. I sent him
some nice marmalade from Dundee, just to smooth things over.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw, who succeeded Kite as the U.S. Ryder Cup captain, is a
historian of the game and I respect that. But facts are facts. He
has missed the cut in all 11 events he has entered this year and he
has only one sub-70 round, at Riviera Country Club in the first
round of the Nissan Open.
</P>
<P>
   My rough-strewn links would have unhinged his game but good.
'Tis better, I decided, that he stay at home and ponder who to name
as his two captain's picks for the upcoming Ryder Cup matches in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   As for Daly, no way do I want a guest of mine leaving early and
he already has withdrawn in mid-tournament three times this year. I
hated like heather to exclude him, because Daly did win the British
Open in 1995 in a playoff with Constantino Rocca at my sister
course in St. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   But when I saw the grief Pinehurst's upside-down-Pyrex-bowl
greens gave him and the scurrilous disrespect he showed for the
game by stroking a second putt before the first one had stopped
rolling, my conscience was clear. If you're not going to honor the
game, why bother participating in it?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, I figured Daly, a recovering alcoholic, has worse
hazards to try to steer clear of than my fairway bunker.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a former U.S. Open winner, says he has only one good
shoulder. So what? Tommy Armour had only one eye (he lost his left
one during World War I), but that didn't prevent him from playing
and winning the British Open when I hosted the event in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   Three years removed from his U.S. Open title at Michigan's
Oakland Hills, Jones posted an 82 in the second round at Pinehurst.
If Jones couldn't hack the wind along Tobacco Road, he'd have been
an empty cigarette box swirling in Carnoustie's gray skies.
</P>
<P>
   I would have smoked him. For his health more than mine, I
suggested he stay at home.
</P>
<P>
   Couples, I really wanted to come. In 1995 he was the first
American in 22 years to record back-to-back victories on the PGA
European Tour. In Scotland, where I dwell, that means something.
</P>
<P>
   He has two top-eight finishes to show for his past three trips
to the British Open, which isn't shabby. But I'm the toughest
layout in the British Open rotation. I can break the backs of the
sturdiest souls. I didn't want to be responsible for what might
happen to Couples' degenerative discs.
</P>
<P>
   So I sent him a note. `` `Stay the Course' is on the banner that
greets all my guests,'' it read. ``And if that doesn't stir you,
then just stay away.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
