<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Tuesday, July 13. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
FERTILITY (Phoenix) _ After 16 years of working miracles in the
eyes of infertile Arizonans, Dr. Robert Tamis is retiring and
closing his Phoenix clinic. Do you know where your children are?
The embryos of about 50 donors are stored in 35-liter metal
containers in a stark white room at the clinic. Unless their donors
are located by July 31, they will be destroyed, along with
unclaimed vials of frozen sperm from as many 70 donors. Staffers
started to search in early May for donors whose records are
out-of-date, scanning telephone books and sending out certified
letters to last known addresses. By KARINA BLAND. Story will move
in the ``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TWOCITIES (Phoenix) _ They're all Phoenix kids. Robyn,
Antoinette, Ray, Carson. They're all growing up together in the
same big, bright city. Yet they're worlds apart.``The gangs. They
shoot by my house,'' complains Ray Gamez, 10, who will be a
fifth-grader at J.B Sutton Elementary School in southwest Phoenix.
Jeff Scala, 10, has his worries, too: ``Our next-door neighbor
built this thing really close to the wall, like a ramada. It blocks
the view of the mountain.'' Jeff is a fifth-grader at Copper Canyon
Elementary School in northeast Phoenix. What children encounter
there, day after day, shapes their lives. The two different
Phoenixes don't have clear boundaries. Many children grow up in
areas that contain elements of both. By PAT KOSSAN. Story will move
in the ``A'' category. &QL;
