<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HOLBROOKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MISCHIEF IN THE SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, July 13:
</P>
<P>
   The long-delayed nomination of Richard Holbrooke to be chief
American representative to the United Nations has hit yet another
snag. By now, questions about Holbrooke's ethics and approach to
policy have been thoroughly vetted. The latest problem concerns the
judgment of Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the Senate majority leader,
and his chamber's dubious practice of letting individual senators
freeze a nomination to gain leverage on an unrelated matter.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., Lott has placed a hold
on the Holbrooke nomination to pressure President Clinton to
approve the Republicans' flawed candidate for a seat on the Federal
Election Commission, Bradley Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the pressing business awaiting Holbrooke at the U.N.,
Lott's performance is troubling on two counts. First, by initially
trying to hide his role in blocking Holbrooke, Lott violated the
spirit of a reform measure he negotiated in March with the
Democratic leader, Tom Daschle of S.D. The reform was supposed to
require senators to make their identity known when they put a
nomination on hold. Previously they could do so anonymously.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is right to resist naming Smith, an Ohio law professor,
to the Election Commission. Smith's writings make plain that his
agenda as a commission member would be a further dismantling of
reasonable campaign limits intended to curb the corrupting
influence of big money rather than serious enforcement of current
campaign finance laws. Both the agency and the laws need
strengthening, not further evisceration. In any case, squabbling
over the FEC job should not mean a further delay in Holbrooke's
arrival at the U.N.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
