<HEADER>
A7701 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWOCITIES-AZR &LR;      07-12 1669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWOCITIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX KIDS LIVE IN TWO CITIES, TWO WORLDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT KOSSAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ They're all Phoenix kids.
</P>
<P>
   Robyn, Antoinette, Ray, Carson. They're all growing up together
in the same big, bright city.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they're worlds apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gangs. They shoot by my house,'' complains Ray Gamez, 10,
who will be a fifth-grader at J.B Sutton Elementary School in
southwest Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Scala, 10, has his worries, too: ``Our next-door neighbor
built this thing really close to the wall, like a ramada. It blocks
the view of the mountain.'' Jeff is a fifth-grader at Copper Canyon
Elementary School in northeast Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff and Ray both live in America's fastest-growing big city,
with low unemployment, surging population and a booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the hometown they will all remember.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhoods surrounding Sutton and Copper Canyon schools
reflect the differences that tear Phoenix into two distinct worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Differences that show up next door, across the street, around
the corner.
</P>
<P>
   What children encounter there, day after day, shapes their
lives. Research shows that it can help root them in peace, trust
and stability _ or help shatter their security, destroy their joy
and derail their futures.
</P>
<P>
   The two different Phoenixes don't have clear boundaries. Many
children grow up in areas that contain elements of both. Kids of
all colors struggle to grow up in impoverished, crime-ridden
neighborhoods scattered throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   Copper Canyon is at one extreme, surrounded by airy, multistory
homes with red-tile roofs, manicured, flowery front yards and
mountain views.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton is at the other, surrounded by a far more crowded
neighborhood thick with children who live in apartments and small
houses, some with families struggling to keep them maintained and
others that have surrendered to ruin.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between the neighborhoods also shows up in
statistics. In the past 12 months, for example, police arrested
2,152 adults within a 2-mile radius of Copper Canyon for domestic
violence, violent crimes and property crimes.
</P>
<P>
   For the same area around Sutton, that number is 12,375.
</P>
<P>
   Children arrested for those same offenses _ domestic violence,
violent crimes and property crime _ in the Copper Canyon
neighborhood over the past 12 months total 197.
</P>
<P>
   In the Sutton neighborhood, the total is 932.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are gangs around it,'' Ray says of his street near
Sutton. ``They kill too much and smoke too much.``
</P>
<P>
   The Sutton students will tell you about the neighbors who shoot
off guns _ sometimes into the air, sometimes at each other. Mean
dogs run in their alleys, their homes are violated by break-ins,
their pets killed, their walls smeared with graffiti or damaged
when speeding cars crash into them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There lives some gang members there and drunk people drive
there,'' says Marco Anguiano, 10, complaining about his busy road.
``One time one crashed into a wall _ my wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomas Patino, 10, says his street doesn't have as many cars;
it's the foot traffic that bothers him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They throw stuff. People. Like sodas and cans and coffee,''
explains Tomas. ``It's nasty. If you have grass in the front yard,
it gets messed up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they break into your house and steal stuff. Bikes,
money, jewelry. They take good stuff and it's hard to replace it,''
says Juan Abreo, 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many gang members, and they tag on your wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Cutting to the core, Marco says, ``I don't like nothing about my
street. I stay inside.''
</P>
<P>
   The children up north, in the other Phoenix, have complaints
about their neighborhood, too.
</P>
<P>
   What irritates Copper Canyon student Bryce Sirrine, 11, are
those big hills that stand between him and his dirt bike trails and
force him to get off his bike and walk.
</P>
<P>
   The noise on Bell Road was so intense that 9-year-old Carson
Park's parents had to install a waterfall in their pool to block it
out.
</P>
<P>
   Lizzy Johnson, 11, lives just a block from Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other night there was an accident. I heard the siren and
saw the red and blue lights. That bothered me and I couldn't
sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody denies that even small worries can loom large in any
child's life. But officials like state Superintendent of Public
Instruction Lisa Graham Keegan say they're tired of trying to cope
with the large worries, trying to shape schools for devastated
neighborhoods instead of reshaping neighborhoods into safe,
nurturing places.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't have to come up with a way to teach children who
live in that environment,'' Keegan says. ``We should solve the
problem of bullets flying through back yards.''
</P>
<P>
   People with power and money have to make a ``huge'' shift in
policy, Keegan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you've had a child look you in the eye and say, `I
don't want to die,' you'll never understand,'' Keegan says.
``They'd see these old, old eyes in children. They've (the
children) seen much, much more than you or I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Damian Cuspard is 23 now, an assistant to a Phoenix City Council
member, father of two, a homeowner. He wishes every Phoenix child
could live on peaceful streets with mountain views.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up on West Buckeye Road, a giant of a child who followed
his older brothers into gang life. He lived with streets filled
with crackheads and drug dealers. He was mugged in an alley at age
12; at 13 he saw his first dead man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never really home because you never feel safe,'' Cuspard
recalls. ``When you're in bed and you hear gunshots, how can you
feel safe if one of those bullets hits someone you know, or comes
through and hits someone in your house?''
</P>
<P>
   You stop thinking about the future, Cuspard says, and survive
day to day.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as Mom and Grandma can eat today,'' he says, ``that's
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   John Loredo, 31, also grew up in the meaner Phoenix. Every day,
around the corner or across the street, lurked a decision that
could have changed his life forever, Loredo says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deck is stacked against them,'' says Loredo, now a state
legislator, about the children who live in the other Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   These desperate, violent neighborhoods are filled with good
people and children, he says. ``But the opportunity to deviate from
the straight path is increased by 100 percent over those other
neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   All of Phoenix's children have fears about the streets where
they live. But some are easier to survive than others.
</P>
<P>
   Those who live near Copper Canyon say they fear mostly what
MIGHT happen, and far less about what does.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a really, really huge snake, like 3 feet long,'' Bryce
begins. ``One day it crossed the street and Dad said to watch it
and I didn't hear him and we don't know where it went.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't Bryce's only story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had troublemakers on our street and they egged our cars,
but they only had two eggs, and we thought it was them. But the
next day their house was (toilet-papered).''
</P>
<P>
   For the kids from Sutton, it's not snakes and eggs, it's
burglaries and gunshots.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hear gunshots,'' Antoinette Ordaz, 10, says about what
scares her. She's a talkative little girl who continually adjusts a
tiny shoulder bag. ``Last time it scared me when my grandma's house
got robbed. I thought they'd get my house. They got away because
the police took forever.``
</P>
<P>
   Juan says, ``Nothing scares me, except when they shoot a lot in
the night. Sometimes they do it for fun, but it might hit someone.
They might end up killing someone I know, like my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Children like Juan who live with violence risk becoming numb to
it, reports Michael Kelley, an Arizona State University professor
in child development.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley worked for Issac School District, which includes Sutton,
and saw preschool children come in with ``a gleam of life in their
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Not for long. ``You interview them at 8 or 9 and that gleam is
gone. They build a core or crust around their bodies to survive,''
Kelley says. ``They do become very different human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are beginning to track anti-social behaviors in
children as young as 4 who live in impoverished areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about survival,'' he says, ``not the pursuit of
happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Phoenix children _ in Copper Canyon and Sutton _ remain
alike in many ways. They say their parents make them do homework
before they can play. They have big plans.
</P>
<P>
   At Sutton, Marco wants to be a NASCAR driver or a scientist,
while Tomas is thinking about becoming a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either a teacher, a nurse or an astronaut to go to Mars or the
moon,'' Antoinette says.
</P>
<P>
   The kids at Copper Canyon are a little more detailed in their
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Robyn Keith, 10, expects to have two jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my early life, I'll probably be an engineer,'' she says,
but noted that her family also owns a hardware store. ``So, in my
30s or 40s, I'll probably take over the company with my cousins.''
</P>
<P>
   Lizzy wants to be a news reporter or manage a clothing store or
be a fashion designer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm obsessed with Nordstrom,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   Bryce thinks he'll go into construction contract management,
like his dad. ``If not that, I want to work for a monopoly,'' Bryce
explains. ``Some corporation that has a nice monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   But the neighborhoods' deep differences never disappear, and the
sadness of everyday heartbreak seems to haunt some streets more
than others.
</P>
<P>
   Ray is only 10, but when he talks about his neighborhood he
watches the floor, his arms folded across his chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``My best friend's brother grabbed a little cat I liked so much
and gave it to dogs,'' says Ray.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering his dead pets, his soft voice suddenly fills with
sarcasm: ``Oh, that was so funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray's voice softened again. ``Sometimes they take dogs I like,''
he said. ``I like animals too much.'' &QL; 
Pat Kossan can be reached at (602) 444-8960 or at
pat.kossan(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
